<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Fla., Ga.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   GORE GAINS IN MISSOURI: Thanks in part to postconvention gains
among women, Vice President Al Gore has caught up with Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas in Missouri, a swing state in which he had been
trailing. The results of the poll, conducted last Thursday and
Friday for The Kansas City Star by Mason-Dixon Polling and
Research, found that 45 percent of 621 registered voters favored
Gore and 41 percent favored Bush, a spread that technically left
the race a dead heat because the margin of sampling error was plus
or minus four percentage points. Ralph Nader, the Green Party
nominee, had 2 percent, and Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party had 1
percent. In a Mason-Dixon poll conducted July 6 to 10, before the
Republican and Democratic conventions, Gore trailed Bush by 11
points, 48 percent to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA VOTES AS EXPECTED: There were no surprises in Tuesday's
primaries in Florida that picked Democratic and Republican
candidates to compete for the Senate seat being vacated by Connie
Mack, a Republican who is retiring. As expected, Rep. Bill McCollum
easily won the Republican primary, capturing 82 percent of the
vote, and the state's insurance commissioner, Bill Nelson, coasted
to a win in the Democratic primary, taking 77 percent of the vote.
But the fall contest is expected to be one of the most competitive
in the country. Democrats say Nelson has a real chance because
McCollum, who had been counting on riding Gov. George W. Bush's
coattails, no longer is assured of a good ride.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, in Nevada, former Rep. John Ensign easily won
the Republican primary for an open Senate seat. In the fall, he
will face Ed Bernstein, a millionaire who ran unopposed in the
Democratic primary. The incumbent, Richard Bryan, a Democrat, is
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA RACE HEATS UP: The race for the seat once held by Sen.
Paul Coverdell, the late Republican from Georgia, has been a quiet
affair, with both leading candidates spending more time raising
money than campaigning. Zell Miller, a Democrat, was appointed to
the seat, pending a special election, after Coverdell died in July,
and this week Miller, a former governor, began running the first
television advertisement of the campaign, tying himself to
Coverdell while stepping back from his own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was honored by Governor Barnes when he appointed me to fill
the big shoes of my good friend Senator Coverdell,'' Miller says in
the 30-second advertisement in which he courts some of the
Republican voters who twice elected Coverdell over a Democrat.
``But in November, you get to decide if I should finish the last
four years of his term. I pledge you this: As your senator, I will
serve no single party but rather seven and one-half million
Georgians.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's opponent, former Sen. Mack Mattingly, has a new
campaign mailing that includes an endorsement by Coverdell's widow,
Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   THE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER DEBATE, ANOTHER DISPUTE: As the spat over the
presidential debates plays out, House and Senate Democratic leaders
are churning up their own election year debate controversy on
Capitol Hill. Several months ago, the two leaders _ Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. Thomas Daschle of South Dakota _
challenged Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott to a debate on ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'' on Oct. 15.
The Republicans declined, saying they were too busy and could not
plan that far ahead. Wednesday, Gephardt dashed off a letter to
Hastert, saying he was disappointed that Hastert would not
participate in a discussion of major campaign issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given Governor Bush's refusal to participate in the three
debates proposed by the Commission on Presidential Debates, your
refusal raises questions about whether the leaders of the
Republican Party really want any honest discussion of the issues
this year,'' Gephardt wrote.
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, Hastert's press secretary, said Hastert was busy
doing his job. ``He is a legislator, not a debater,'' Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Westland, Mich.; Dayton, Ohio, and Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY: Portland, Me.; Manchester, N.H., and Burlington,
Vt.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Carbondale, Pa., and New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH LIEBERMAN: Little Rock and Fort Smith, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER: Albuquerque
</P>
</TEXT>
