<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER AND AOL PLAN NO CONCESSIONS TO EUROPEAN REGULATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Despite unusually sharp criticism from
European antitrust regulators, executives of Time Warner and
America Online do not plan to offer any concessions to clear their
proposed merger plans when they meet regulators behind closed doors
here on Thursday, company executives said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the companies will try to refute European arguments
that the merged company would harm competition because of its
enormous size.
</P>
<P>
   That sets the stage for what is likely to be bruising
negotiations over the next several weeks. But despite the U.S.
companies' seemingly hard line, many experts think that they will
have to modify their plan before they receive permission to operate
as a merged company in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission, the administrative arm of the European
Union, has sent the two companies a 45-page statement of
objections, arguing that the merger in its current form would allow
the companies to dominate the online distribution of entertainment
and of music, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who have seen the statement, it warns that
America Online and Time Warner would create a ``dominant position
in the markets for online music delivery, music software, Internet
dial-up access, broadband Internet access and integrated broadband
content.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining their concerns, European regulators here argued
that the two companies would own so many forms of entertainment and
information that America Online would be able to lock customers
into its service. That in turn would give the combined company even
more leverage in acquiring rights to music, videos and online
information services.
</P>
<P>
   European concern has been magnified in Time Warner's separate
plan to merge its music business into a joint venture with EMI
Group of Britain, the big music distributor. In an all-day hearing
Wednesday, also in private, Time Warner and EMI executives tried to
convince officials that the deal would be beneficial despite
reducing the number of major music distributors to four from five.
</P>
<P>
   The battle in Europe is parallel but somewhat different from the
one involving the companies in the United States, where regulators
are also scrutinizing the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, America Online is by far the largest
provider of Internet service. Time Warner is the nation's
second-largest cable company and therefore controls the means to
deliver high-speed Internet service to millions of homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the companies are significantly weaker. AOL Europe
serves only about 10 percent of online subscribers and is no more
than a distant second place in any market. And despite the
Europeans' stated worries about Time Warner's potential control of
broadband Internet access, the company owns no cable television or
other high-speed networks in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy McKiernan, a spokeswoman for America Online, said
Wednesday that the European Commission's objections were nothing
more than ``a normal and predictable part of the process'' and that
AOL would not offer any compromises when it presented it case.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Time Warner and America Online will be
questioned by senior members of the European Commission's merger
task force. Antitrust regulators from each country in the European
Union and representatives of at least a few companies that are
fighting the merger will also take part.
</P>
<P>
   European arguments about the companies' grip on music are likely
to be stronger because worldwide music distribution is already
dominated by a handful of giants, and the combination of a Time
Warner music operation with EMI would concentrate the industry
more.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission has real power. It can block mergers
between companies that generate European sales of more than 250
million euros a year, currently $217 million. On many occasions,
including mergers between two U.S. companies, officials have used
their power to force companies into divestitures or changes in
their practices.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's deadline to reach a final decision on Time
Warner's deal with EMI is Oct. 16, and on its merger with America
Online, Oct. 24. The companies have to submit proposed remedies at
least one month before then.
</P>
</TEXT>
