<SLUG> BC-SMOG-BADAIR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR APPARENT: HOUSTON TAKES L.A. SMOG CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With several weeks to go in the smog season,
Houston blew past Los Angeles this past weekend to once again
clinch America's Smoggiest City pennant, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas gulf city, sweltering under 100-degree temperatures
during a weeklong high pressure system, eked by its L.A. rival over
the Labor Day weekend with two more days of unhealthy levels of
ozone.
</P>
<P>
   And with the smog season ending locally in a few weeks, air
quality experts said Houston might for two years running post the
highest peak smog and most unhealthy ozone days of the year. That
is, if the weather holds out for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a fairly clean year,'' said Joe Cassmassi, senior
meteorologist for the South Coast Air Management District.
``Instead of stagnant sinks, we've had cool breezes.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Houston stunned Los Angeles by stealing its long-held
Smog Cup. But late last month, Los Angeles threatened to take it
back -- with 34 days surpassing national health limits for ozone
compared with Houston's 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of last weekend, they had a higher number of unhealthy
ozone days than L.A.,'' said Sam Atwood, spokesman for the South
Coast Air Management District.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had 36; we had 34 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassmassi and other meteorologists attribute Houston's lead to
its high pressure system and nearby fires that have built a layer
of smog.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, by comparison, coasts toward the end of its smog
season late this month with cool breezes brought on by unstable
atmospheric conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When y'all have been up there lollygagging about with
70-degree highs and 50-degree lows, we have had highs in the
100s,'' said Gene McMullen of the Houston Bureau of Air Quality
Control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some folks claim what we need to do is not have barbecue pits
out here, but if that will help the ozone, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Houston has led Los Angeles with a peak ozone level
day (or highest ozone level) of 206 parts per billion to L.A.'s 184
parts per billion. Levels below 200 ppb are known as ``ozone health
advisory episodes'' and call for joggers and other athletes to
cease outdoor activity.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, an industrial powerhouse that is home to 49 percent of
the nation's petrochemical industry and 25 percent of its gasoline
refining, lags 10 to 20 years behind environmental regulations
imposed by Los Angeles, smog authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, high ozone levels last generally through November.
In Los Angeles, the smog season usually ends in early October. For
that reason, Cassmassi and others predicted Houston would keep its
Smog Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we may have to claim the title again this
year,'' said Dave McCullum, spokesman for the Greater Houston
Partnership, a business advocacy group that oversees the chamber of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it's not something we're proud of -- whether you're
No. 1 or No. 2, there's no honor in being on this list at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the campaign to elect Vice President Al Gore
to the presidency were quick to jump on Houston's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush has implored us to `Look at my record in Texas,' ''
said Peter Ragone, a spokesman for the Gore campaign. ``The record
on Texas is clear: Bush has been ignoring and not enforcing
environmental laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be farther from the truth,'' said Ray Sullivan,
a Bush campaign spokesman from Austin, Texas. ``Under Gov. Bush, we
have reduced air emissions, we've reduced toxic emissions, air and
water are cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud of Gov. Bush's record.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
