<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOCUMENTS INDICATE FIRESTONE KNEW ABOUT DEFECTIVE TIRES
</P>
<P>
   Newly released documents provided additional evidence that
Bridgestone/Firestone and possibly Ford Motor knew about a pattern
of tire failures long before a recall was announced in August.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures came during hearings on Capitol Hill Wednesday
at which lawmakers called for a larger budget for safety regulators
and proposed federal criminal penalties for any future cases in
which companies might be found to have knowingly sold products with
lethal defects.
</P>
<P>
   FTC INVESTIGATES DRUG COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said that it was investigating
whether Bristol-Myers Squibb and American Bioscience colluded to
keep the lower-cost generic version of Bristol's cancer drug,
Taxol, off the market. The Food and Drug Administration gave Ivax,
a generic drug maker, tentative approval last month to sell generic
Taxol. But regulators said they could not let Ivax sell the drug
because of a complex legal agreement between Bristol-Myers and
American Bioscience. The FTC said in court papers that the terms of
the agreement ``raise potential competitive issues.'' Shares of
Ivax rose $7.81, to $39.
</P>
<P>
   NOVELL TO ELIMINATE 900 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Novell, the networking operating system maker, said that it
would eliminate 900 jobs, or about 16 percent of its worldwide work
force, to reduce costs. The company said it would take a pretax
charge of $40 million to $50 million in its fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ SLIDES AGAIN, BUT DOW RISES
</P>
<P>
   A sell-off in semiconductor stocks drove the Nasdaq composite
index down 129.84 points, or 3.1 percent, to 4,013.34. Other
markets fared better, largely because of strength in a handful of
financial stocks and in oil shares. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index fell 14.83 points, or 1 percent, to 1,492.25. The Dow Jones
industrial average advanced 50.03 points, or 0.4 percent, to
11,310.64.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK AGENT LEAVES WILLIAM MORRIS
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gottlieb, one of the most powerful agents in book
publishing, resigned as head of the William Morris agency's New
York literary group to start his own agency and multimedia
management company.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTIVITY UP 5.7 PERCENT IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Productivity, a measure of how much a worker produces for each
hour on the job, grew at a 5.7 percent annual rate from April
through June, up from the 5.3 percent pace originally estimated,
new data showed.
</P>
<P>
   TIME WARNER BUYS AFRICANA.COM
</P>
<P>
   Facing an uncertain climate for Internet startups, the founders
of Africana.com, the Harvard University professors Henry Louis
Gates Jr. and Kwame Anthony Appiah, have sold their venture to Time
Warner. Gates said the deal would help keep the Web site, one of
many seeking a worldwide audience of African descent, alive. ``The
revenue model was slow to develop, let's put it that way,'' he
said. ``I would have become worried about its future by next year
unless there was some dramatic turnaround.'' Terms of the deal were
not announced.
</P>
<P>
   HEINZ ISSUES A PROFIT WARNING
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz said that its second-quarter profit would be lower
than analysts expected, and its shares fell nearly 5 percent, to
$35.44.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE AND U.S. IN TRADE STANDOFF
</P>
<P>
   The European Union and the United States are holding fast in
several trade disputes, their continued standoff threatening a more
punishing confrontation between the two trading blocs, the world's
biggest.
</P>
<P>
   ABC REORGANIZING SALES OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   ABC is reorganizing its sales operations in an effort to
integrate and coordinate the purchase of commercial time and ad
space by marketers across all units of the network's parent, Walt
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER REVIEWING ACCOUNTS
</P>
<P>
   The DaimlerChrysler Group unit of DaimlerChrysler will begin a
review on accounts with billings estimated at $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD TIMES MAY FUEL REGULATION
</P>
<P>
   In the past, bad times might be expected to lead to new
regulations and protectionism as people turn to government as a
source of security. That may no longer be true. In the United
States, new regulations tend to come after prolonged periods of
prosperity. When times are good, restrictions look relatively
cheap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
