r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     09-07 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASS HAPPY AT TULANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Suddenly thrust into the spotlight after the
starting quarterback is sidelined with a separated shoulder, UCLA's
quarterback of the future is working feverishly with the first
team, taking a crash course on running a college football team.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan McCann?
</P>
<P>
   Try J.P. Losman.
</P>
<P>
   Losman, the Bruins' answer to Carson Palmer when he announced
two years ago that he would attend UCLA, will make the first start
of his college career, but it won't be Saturday against Fresno
State.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will be nine days from now when he leads Tulane, the
school for which he now plays, against East Carolina. Losman is
taking over for Patrick Ramsey, who _ like UCLA starter Cory Paus
against Alabama _ suffered a separated throwing shoulder in
Tulane's season opener, a 49-20 loss at 17th-ranked Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got all the tools,'' said Frank Scelfo, Tulane's
quarterbacks coach and the brother of head coach Chris Scelfo.
``He's got great mobility, an excellent arm and he's very
confident. The one thing he hasn't done is been in there and faced
live bullets. Until then, you never really know.''
</P>
<P>
   !ital!Until then, you never really know.
</P>
<P>
   There are no better words to sum up Losman's career.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively unheralded player at an unheralded school, Venice
High, Losman opened everyone's eyes with his arm and athletic
ability at a quarterbacks camp at UCLA the summer before his senior
year.
</P>
<P>
   He committed to UCLA shortly thereafter and as a result UCLA
never pursued one of Southern California's other highly regarded
quarterbacks, Hart's Kyle Boller, who is beginning his second
season as Cal's starting quarterback. UCLA offensive coordinator Al
Borges wanted Losman so badly that he personally recruited him _
the only Bruin quarterback for whom Borges has ever done that.
</P>
<P>
   Losman, eager to replace Cade McNown, graduated from high school
early so he could enroll at UCLA for the spring quarter and be
eligible to participate in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   He not only arrived on campus with the best arm among the five
quarterbacks but also with a cocksure attitude. Losman was cordial
to the others, but it wasn't hard to tell who the outsider was.
Between drills, it looked as if there were two groups _ the
quarterbacks and Losman.
</P>
<P>
   There were jokes made by the other quarterbacks and Borges at
Losman's expense. There were articles taped to his locker intended
to get under his skin.
</P>
<P>
   What might have been an attempt to bring Losman back to earth
was taken as hazing. When it became clear that Losman's inability
to absorb the UCLA playbook had him as the No. 5 quarterback just
before the start of fall camp, he walked into head coach Bob
Toledo's office and announced that he was transferring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of little things that added up,'' said Losman,
who is 6-foot-3, 200 pounds, about 15 pounds more than last season.
``It's nothing personal. I wish them the best of luck, but I had a
lot of questions and doubt in my mind over whether it was going to
be the right place for me. A lot of things didn't fall into place.
I didn't feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who thinks Losman got some bad advice from his former
high school coaches, tried desperately to talk him out of
transferring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't guarantee anybody anything,'' said Toledo, who
confirmed that Losman asked to be the No. 1 or 2 quarterback. ``He
wanted to be the guy. He wanted all this extra attention. He wanted
(Borges) to spend more time with him. Well, there's (NCAA)
restrictions (on hours of practicing) and we've got five
quarterbacks. He wanted the opportunity to compete for the starting
job; he wanted equal reps. This isn't intramurals.''
</P>
<P>
   Borges said Losman set unrealistic expectations for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened, happened,'' he said. ``But if he was
patient and let the natural order of things take place, he could
have been competing for the starting job this season. I'm
empathetic to him. For him to be in high school one day and college
the next, where there's nobody else in his situation, had to be
difficult. But to leave after 15 days of practice is
unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo wasn't the only one who told Losman he was making a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to talk him out of it,'' said his mother, Tricia
Losman, who raised J.P and his sister, Amy, in Venice. ``It was a
blow to us. Jonathan has never not gotten along. I said, 'No way,
you can't leave UCLA. Are you crazy?' He said, 'Mom, if I have to
stand up to all of you, I will. Do you know how hard that is?' At
that point, I really needed to listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he had committed to UCLA, Losman had taken a
recruiting visit to Tulane when Joe Dickenson, an assistant who had
recruited him for Oklahoma and a friend of his high school coach,
Angelo Gasca, was hired by the Green Wave.
</P>
<P>
   When he left UCLA, he chose Tulane over Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane, a school with a previously moribund football program,
was coming off a 12-0 season that showcased quarterback Shaun King,
now with Tampa Bay, and a wide-open, run-and-shoot offense. And
being in New Orleans didn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with the place,'' Losman said. ``I always
remembered that trip. Something happened on that trip that was so
special for me. People say I was crazy. No one (in Los Angeles) has
a clue about Tulane. They don't know where it is, what state it's
in. But I wanted to go some place where I was going to enjoy
myself. Wherever I go, we're going to win. I don't want to make the
same mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while Losman has left UCLA, he hasn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Bruins fan, his bedroom at home still has a UCLA neon
light and a Bruins comforter on the bed. He says he dreams of
playing in the Rose Bowl one day, though he realizes it's not
likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved going to class there,'' said Losman, an honors student
in high school. ``For the first time in my life, I loved going to
class. I was going to the school of my dreams. I got to answer a
bunch of questions wherever I went. Cade was leaving. Hopefully,
I'd be the next Cade McNown. I thought it would be something
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in the Superdome press box during home games last
season, he couldn't help but think about what might have been had
he stayed at UCLA. The Bruins used all four quarterbacks last
season and ended the season with McCann, who was No. 4 at the end
of fall camp, in the lineup against USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Losman said when asked if he followed the Bruins
last season. ``I was going to get my chance even if I didn't play.
I would have had a chance to come back this year and compete. With
the injuries, they might have put me in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to that stuff all the time (at home). People say,
'See, if you stayed, you would have started or you would have
gotten a chance.' But it's not about that. That's not why I left.
It just didn't feel like the right place. You have to go someplace
where you feel comfortable and are happy. A lot of guys who played
college football understand the situation I was in.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Losman _ a year older, a year wiser and a year humbler
from the experience _ takes the reigns of another team. He has 31
plays under his belt, completing 5 of 10 passes for 35 yards. He
didn't throw an interception or a touchdown pass, and he was sacked
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played like someone playing in his first game,'' Scelfo
said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Losman says, he couldn't be happier. His new team and
his new school feel like home. Four years from now, he'll be better
able to look back and see whether he made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, you never really know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
