<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUBLIC MEETINGS ABOUT INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Policy Institute, a Washington-based independent
research organization, plans to hold eight town hall meetings
designed to gather grass-roots information on Internet policies and
will present its findings to the next president after the November
elections. The meetings are being held jointly with eight
universities across the country to get ``outside the Beltway''
views on the Internet, said James L. Barksdale, former president
and chief executive of Netscape Communications and chairman of the
institute, which is nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   WEB ENCRYPTION PATENT INTO PUBLIC DOMAIN
</P>
<P>
   RSA Security said it had placed the RSA public key encryption
algorithm into the public domain, permitting programmers to freely
incorporate the technology into their products. The RSA algorithm _
named after three computer scientists, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir
and Leonard Adelman _ has been widely used for more than a decade
to protect the privacy of digital commerce and communications. The
technology was originally awarded a U.S. patent on Sept. 20, 1983,
and it is due to expire later this month. Known as public key
cryptography, the technology was also pioneered independently by
researchers at Stanford University, and makes it possible for two
people who have never met to exchange information securely.
</P>
<P>
   FBI DEFENDS E-MAIL TAPPING PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the FBI and the Justice Department defended the
Carnivore e-mail surveillance system Wednesday, asserting that the
program is used only after all other investigative methods have
been exhausted. In remarks before the Senate Judiciary Committee,
Kevin DiGregory, deputy assistant attorney general, urged the
continued use of the program ``as criminal activity migrates to the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   PC SALES STRONG IN LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Sales of personal computers in Latin America this year will
increase by 30 percent over 1999, according to International Data
Corp. Laptop sales alone will increase nearly 50 percent over last
year, IDC estimated. PC sales are rising, in part, because of
falling prices and the increasing availability of systems in local
stores, said Alexandra Martinez of IDC. She also said growing
Internet usage was helping to drive sales. America Online-Latin
America, a unit of AOL, which has invested heavily in South America
this year, reported that its fourth-quarter revenues rose 55
percent over the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   PALM FORMS INVESTMENT UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Palm, the maker of the Palm Pilot line of hand-held computers,
is forming a new unit, Palm Ventures, with $50 million to help
develop wireless content companies, mobile systems integrators and
Palm accessory manufacturers that support the Palm operating
system. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
