<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-KENNEDY-AR     09-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-KENNEDY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT KENNEDY, CITING ENVIRONMENT, ENDORSES HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 (With LAZIO-TAX-PLAN) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT13 and NYT36 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert F. Kennedy Jr. endorsed Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Senate candidacy Wednesday, declaring that she would show
leadership on environmental concerns he champions and would
overcome the ``carpetbagger'' tag that also threatened his father's
bid for a Senate seat from New York in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, an environmental lawyer who had considered running for
the seat Clinton is seeking, stood at her side at the 79th Street
Boat Basin in Manhattan and delivered her second endorsement on
environmental issues in two days. On Tuesday, she was endorsed by
the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy credited Clinton with exerting influence on her
husband's administration to take steps to protect the lands around
New York City's upstate drinking water supplies from development, a
battle Kennedy has waged for several years. He said that during a
``seminar'' he conducted for Clinton this year, she had
demonstrated a strong interest in that problem and in such other
issues as cleaning up chemical contamination from the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kennedy acknowledged that Clinton's Republican
opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, had agreed to write a letter to the Army
Corps of Engineers urging further protection of the watershed,
Kennedy faulted him for not taking the initiative on protecting the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy adopted the favored Clinton campaign tactic of linking
Lazio to his former ally, former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who
Kennedy said was vehemently against the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Lazio, Kennedy said: ``You can't point _ and Rick
Lazio can't point _ to a single instance in which he has ever
demonstrated environmental leadership on any environmental issue.
He walked in lockstep with the Gingrich Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also addressed an assertion that Lazio has constantly
repeated: that Clinton is a ``carpetbagger'' who moved here in
January only to establish residency for her Senate bid. The same
charge was leveled against Robert F. Kennedy Sr., who moved from
Massachusetts to New York City in 1964 for a Senate run that he won
by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who was 10 when his father ran, said: ``The passions
against my father were equal to or exceeded what I have seen. This
is the question that was asked about my father: Is somebody who is
not born in this state capable of putting in or offering leadership
to this state? And my answer to that is resoundingly, yes, they
are. New Yorkers come from everywhere. We have the most
cosmopolitan community in North America and maybe one of the most
cosmopolitan in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, a spokesman for Lazio, dismissed Kennedy's
assertions as partisan rhetoric. He said the congressman had a
solid environmental record that included supporting the cleanup of
Long Island Sound and more closely regulating mining practices
believed threatening to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New Yorkers are more impressed by Rick Lazio's real
record on the environment,'' McLagan said, ``than by Mrs. Clinton's
empty promises and partisan endorsements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
