u p BC-LAZIO-TAX-PLAN-NYT     09-07 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-TAX-PLAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S TAX PLAN UNDERGOES SOME DEDUCTIONS OF ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREECE, N.Y. _ With television cameras and photographers crowded
around him, Rep. Rick Lazio settled behind a green plastic picnic
table in the Caracci family back yard here to talk up what he calls
the most dramatic component of his tax cut plan: allowing taxpayers
to deduct their payroll tax from their federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had an extra twelve hundred bucks, what would you do
with it?'' the Suffolk County Republican asked four Rochester area
taxpayers recruited by his campaign for an orchestrated
conversation designed to draw attention to the tax cut that he has
presented as a cornerstone of his campaign against Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax plan Lazio promoted again Wednesday was not
precisely what he first proposed two weeks ago, his aides
acknowledge. The aides have offered some new details on the plan
since then, with the effect being to lower the plan's potential
cost. Those changes occurred as some of Lazio's economic
assumptions were challenged by some independent analysts, and after
Clinton's aides said he underestimated the plan's price tag so he
could distance himself from the $1.3 trillion tax cut proposed by
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The payroll tax deduction that Lazio has proudly highlighted in
his speeches would, in fact, be phased in over 10 years, meaning
that it would be 2011 at the earliest before the four people seated
at the table with Lazio Wednesday would get the $1,200 tax cut he
promised. What is more, in a bit of tax policy that several
independent analysts described as highly unusual and
extraordinarily complicated, the tax deduction, for Social Security
contributions, would only be permitted for taxpayers who, after
computing their gross adjusted income, found themselves in or below
the 28 percent income tax bracket. They would then proceed to
subtract the additional deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Without those provisions, the cost of making the payroll tax
deductible would be $500 billion over 10 years. With these
provisions included, its 10-year cost would be about $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of making the payroll tax deductible has been
considered, but discarded, in Congress, both because it is highly
expensive and because deductions favor taxpayers in upper brackets.
And in Albany, Frank J. Mauro, director of the Fiscal Policy
Institute, a group that studies government finances, contended that
Lazio's proposal, even with its upper-income limit restrictions,
would still benefit wealthier taxpayers because they are
statistically far more likely to itemize deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio made no mention of those restrictive provisions when he
outlined what he described as a ``bold'' idea to the Chamber of
Commerce in Amherst, N.Y., on Aug. 24, and there was no mention of
it in the detailed briefing papers his campaign provided about the
plan that day. ``I propose allowing people to deduct their payroll
taxes on our 1040 forms _ the same way we do our state income taxes
and real estate taxes,'' he said in his speech. ``This pro-family
tax cut will reduce the average two-income family's tax bill by
$1,200.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference afterward, Lazio described his tax plan in
even more generous terms, saying that with other provisions _
including the elimination of the so-called marriage penalty, and an
increase in the amounts families are allowed to contribute to IRA's
_ the average family would save close to $3,000 a year. Bryan W.
Flood, one of Lazio's senior advisers, said that these provisions
were always part of Lazio's plan, though Flood acknowledged that
the candidate did not mention them in his speech, or in appearances
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no intention to mislead,'' Flood said. ``We talked
about about the fact that the payroll tax deduction plan is aimed
at lower- and middle-income voters. In retrospect, I guess, we
could have been more clear about that. But certainly we're talking
about it as a middle-class tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Flood said disputes about numbers aside, Lazio had put forward
the plan as a way to draw one of the sharpest distinctions existing
between the congressman and Clinton: How much of the nation's
surplus should be used for tax cuts. The first lady has offered a
much more modest, and less detailed, tax cut plan that adheres to
the Democratic program that would provide targeted tax cuts for
specific income groups.
</P>
<P>
   Several elements of Lazio's tax cut plan are under fire from
analysts and Democrats, who contend that their costs are
significantly understated. From a political perspective, this is
more than just a bookkeeping dispute because Lazio has gone to some
lengths to distinguish his plan from the $1.3 trillion plan offered
by Bush, putting the cost of his own plan at $776 billion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he put the cost of eliminating the marriage penalty
at $89 billion. But analysts said that figure accounts for just the
five-year cost of the tax cut: the 10-year cost is $293 billion,
according to the bipartisan Congressional Joint Committee on
Taxation. Similarly, Lazio put the cost of repealing part of the
Social Security tax at $56 billion. Flood acknowledged, though,
that that figure was ``several years old''; the joint committee's
estimate is $117 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Flood said that his campaign stood by its estimates, suggesting
the different views represented nothing more than customary
disputes between congressional Democrats and Republicans over
numbers. If Lazio were to accept the congressional figures, the
cost of his plan would clearly jump over $1 trillion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
