<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS CARRY ANGELS TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The box score of the Anaheim Angels-Detroit Tigers
game will show that pitcher Scott Schoeneweis threw eight scoreless
innings. But what he really provided was resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   With the Angels mired in a six-game losing streak and fighting
for their playoff lives, Schoeneweis outdueled Tigers knuckleballer
Steve Sparks to lead the Angels to a 1-0 victory Wednesday night at
Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis gave up only two hits and got ninth-inning help from
Troy Percival, who earned his first save since July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Spiezio's double in the third inning was the key hit,
setting up Mo Vaughn's RBI groundout for the only run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels picked up a game on the AL West-leading Mariners to
close within six games with 23 to play. They still have a pulse
thanks to Schoeneweis, who became the first Angels starter to win a
game since Aug. 25 (Matt Wise vs. the Indians).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted one time to pick us up, instead of them picking me
up,'' Schoeneweis (7-7) said of his teammates. ``And tonight I
picked them up. We scored one run. For us to win, I had to give up
nothing. Thank God I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis gave up a single to Brad Ausmus in the third inning,
but he got a double play and escaped trouble. Through six innings,
he faced the minimum 18 batters. But when he walked Damion Easley
to lead off the seventh, he knew he was in for a tough inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk the leadoff guy, you've got a big job to do,''
said Schoeneweis, who walked two and struck out six. ``It always
seems to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis got one out, but Bobby Higginson followed with a
chopper over Spiezio's head at first base and into right field,
giving the Tigers runners on first and third with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis walked Dean Palmer to load the bases, but he got a
huge out when he struck out Wendell Magee on a 3-2 pitch, a 90-mph
sinker. Deivi Cruz grounded into a force play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   '``I've been in jams like that all year and got out of them,''
Schoeneweis said. ``All that experience helps you in those
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels couldn't do much with Sparks, their teammate of a
year ago. Troy Glaus doubled twice off him and had a third double
in the ninth off Danny Patterson. Glaus said he hit fastballs for
the doubles off Sparks, laying off the knucklers as best he could,
including one that was clocked at 49 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly looking to hit that,'' Glaus said. ``I'll take
it and do my best to hit the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus eventually reached third in every inning he doubled, but
he never scored. In the ninth, he was thrown out in a rundown
between home and third when Bengie Molina missed a squeeze-bunt
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Angels, Schoeneweis was up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a start like that,'' Glaus said. ``We scored one
run. We needed to get picked up tonight and Scott did it. It was
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis argued in the dugout with manager Mike Scioscia
after being told he wouldn't pitch the ninth. But Percival came
through with his 26th save of the season. It was his first save
opportunity since Aug. 4
</P>
<P>
   Percival walked Easley leading off the inning, but he struck out
Palmer to end the game, leaving Easley stranded at third. Although
the save was his first in more than a month, Percival said it
wasn't the most satisfying aspect of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``More satisfying for me was the way I threw the fastball, how I
got it there,'' he said. ``Being able to hit the outside corner was
huge. That's the satisfaction I get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
