<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ FINISHED FOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers fans will no longer have to
endure the frustration and sheer agony of watching left-hander
Carlos Perez pitch in 2000. His season ended Wednesday when an MRI
and CAT scan revealed a bone spur in the back of his pitching
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is scheduled to have surgery next Thursday at Centinela
Hospital Medical Center. Team physician Dr. Frank Jobe said Perez
could be ready to return to the mound for spring training, but much
of that is contingent on Perez's rehab.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie right-hander Luke Prokopec will take Perez's spot in the
rotation and make his first major-league start Tuesday in Arizona.
Prokopec, who went 7-3 with a 2.45 ERA with Double-A San Antonio,
threw three scoreless innings in his major-league debut Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Prokopec was Australia's No. 1 starter for the upcoming Olympics
before being recalled by the Dodgers, and he's fine with the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the minors six year waiting for this
opportunity'' said Prokopec, 22, originally signed as an
outfielder. ``It's a situation where you win either way. You
fulfill a dream of pitching here or you pitch for your country.
Either way, it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   While Prokopec's Dodger career is just beginning, there are now
questions as to whether Perez's is over.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the surgery will do is make it virtually
impossible to trade the already unwanted Perez. He's guaranteed
$7.5 million next season and the Dodgers wanted to move him because
he's been awful the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was 5-8 with a 5.56 ERA this season after going 2-10 with
a 7.43 ERA last year. Add shoulder surgery to the mix, and even if
the Dodgers pick up a portion of the $7.5 million he's owed, moving
him will be a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do the surgery and prepare myself for next spring
training,'' said Perez, who missed the 1996 season after undergoing
shoulder surgery. ``The last time I had surgery, I came back strong
and pitched (206) innings and I still believe that after this
surgery, things are going to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 29, said he felt pain in his left shoulder during his
start last Thursday in Milwaukee, in which he allowed six runs in
two-plus innings. But he felt something pop in his shoulder when he
threw a slider to Pittsburgh's Brian Giles on Tuesday. It was
Perez's last pitch. He left the game having allowed six runs in 3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to work hard and be ready for spring training so I
can do what I did in '97 and '98 _ throw a lot of innings and win a
lot of ballgames,'' Perez said. ``It's hard to pitch when you're
not 100 percent. I never said anything, never complained. If I was
like in Chicago and Milwaukee, I would finish my season like that.
But (Tuesday) night was unbelievable. As soon as I heard my
shoulder pop in the back, I knew something was wrong. I had to shut
it down right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to keep rushing and keep pushing to be 100
percent when I'm not supposed to. I'm going to take my time and
keep working and do my exercises and be ready for spring
training.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Craig Callan, the director of Dodgertown, was
promoted to vice president of spring- training/minor-league
facilities, the club announced. Callan has been active in working
with the Vero Beach, Fla., community to keep the Dodgers
spring-training home in Florida. A 20-year agreement is expected to
be announced soon between the Dodgers and Vero Beach. Callan also
will oversee the Dodgers' operations in the Dominican Republic. . .
. First baseman Eric Karros was given the day off to rest and Jim
Leyritz started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
