<SLUG> BC-FBN-TEXANS-McNAIR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `History-making day' just what McNair hoped it would be &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ For the first time since his beloved South Carolina
Gamecocks failed to win a football game last season, Bob McNair had
trouble sleeping. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The anticipation and excitement building up to what would be
Wednesday's unveiling of his NFL team's name, logo and colors
caused him to spend a restless night at his River Oaks home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, I watched all the television stations to see what
they were saying about today's events,'' McNair said. ``I wanted to
get a sense of how things were being conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer we got to the unveiling, the more the tension
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who paid $700 million to return the NFL to Houston, was
as excited as a child on Christmas morning. He got up at 6:30 a.m.
Wednesday to prepare for what he called a ``history-making day''
for his NFL franchise _ the Houston Texans.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most important days of his life, McNair was king
for a day. Everywhere he went, he introduced himself to people, and
they thanked him for bringing the NFL back to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to be perceived in a favorable light, and I
draw energy from people who treat me that way,'' he said. ``I
really appreciate the fans taking the time to thank me. Shoot, I
want to thank them for helping make all this possible.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at his office in the Pennzoil Building, McNair
looked over his daily schedule of events prepared by Becky Virtue,
the executive assistant who keeps track of him by the hour, and
began to feel the exhilaration of what was in store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been sleeping very well, but I got more excited the closer
we got to Wednesday,'' McNair said. ``There was a little anxiety
about how the nickname, logo and colors would be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this was a one-of-a-kind event, something that'll
never be repeated. A lot of people worked a lot of hours to make it
possible. I can't tell you how proud I am with the way everything
came off. I've got so many people to thank for pulling it off.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McNair and Texans general manager Charley Casserly
went to Enron Field. McNair threw three passes to Casserly to
practice throwing out Wednesday's first pitch to Astros owner
Drayton McLane Jr. McNair used a football instead of a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not have Sonny Jurgensen's arm, but he throws a tighter
spiral than Billy Kilmer,'' Casserly said. ``After his third throw,
I told him this is like when you're on the driving range and you're
supposed to quit while you're ahead, so we did.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at his office Wednesday morning, McNair went
over the details of the day's activities with Virtue and Philip
Burguieres, his close friend and confidant who is the team's vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Bob for 25 years, and this is the culmination of a
childhood dream,'' Burguieres said. ``When Bob was a kid, he said
all he cared about was sports. When he was growing up in South
Carolina, he hitchhiked 20 miles to a high school where he could
play football because the one closest to him didn't have a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's wanted an NFL team for 10 years. In the world of
business and sports, this is the biggest thing that's ever happened
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m., Ryan Reichert, the team's director of security and
McNair's son-in-law, drove McNair to the Astrodome for what was
billed as ``The Big Return.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamey Rootes, the Texans' senior vice president of marketing,
sales and promotions, spearheaded the Astrodome event that featured
Raul Allegre, a former kicker for the University of Texas and
several NFL teams, including the New York Giants and Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Allegre, who owns a sports marketing business in Austin, kicked
ceremonial balls to former players from Houston, Rice and Texas
Southern _ Jason Phillips (Cougars), Hunter Brown (Owls) and
Jarrett Harper (Tigers). The balls were to be used in promotions
for the Texans in Beaumont, Austin and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving the Astrodome, McNair asked Reichert to drive
slowly past the Texans' new stadium that is under construction next
to the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, doesn't that look great?'' McNair said. ``From this
angle, it kind of looks like a battleship.''
</P>
<P>
   When McNair travels in his private jet, he takes off and lands
at Hobby Airport, and his pilots fly over the stadium site each
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get more excited every time I see it,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to his office, McNair went to the site of
Wednesday's unveiling event on Texas Avenue between Bayou Place and
Wortham Center. He got a walk-through on the stage and the football
field that had been set up on Texas Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked around, McNair introduced himself to the workers
and anyone who had come to inspect the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, this is really first-class, isn't it?'' he said. ``I
think this is going to be great. We couldn't have picked a more
beautiful spot. It's fan-friendly with a lot of wide-open space. I
can't wait for tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   After going over last-minute details with Virtue, McNair left
for the Hard Rock Cafe, where everyone scheduled to participate
would check in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to be big, really big,'' he said. ``I
hope everything comes off OK. I've got to look over my speech some
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything came off better than McNair and his staff expected.
When the name, logo and colors were unveiled, the crowd estimated
at 16,000 erupted into a thunderous ovation as fireworks and
confetti filled the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was overwhelmed by the fans' response,'' McNair said as he
received a police escort to Enron Field to throw out the ceremonial
first pitch before the Astros-Marlins game. ``When I looked out
from the stage, all I saw was a sea of humanity. The warm and
enthusiastic reception I've got all day is something I will always
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   At Enron Field, McNair threw a Texans football from the
pitcher's mound to home plate, where it was caught by McLane, who
spiked the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous about the pass,'' McNair said. ``I was afraid I
might throw it at Drayton's feet. I was fortunate to get the ball
to him, and he made a great catch. We may have to consider signing
him as one of our receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   McLane caught the ball so easily that some wondered if he found
some stickum to put on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I didn't need any stickum to catch that ball,'' McLane
said. ``I've been practicing on making that catch. Maybe Bob will
be interested in signing me.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Enron Field, McNair returned to Bayou Place, where
he hosted a private party at the Hard Rock Cafe. After the party,
he entertained team executives, NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue and
league executives at a dinner party at River Oaks Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly was a night to remember,'' he said. ``I know I'll
never forget it. I hope our fans won't, either.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
