<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-2NDLD-WRI     09-07 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU </SLUG>
 - ART-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 WASHINGTON: a problem. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Heather Wilson, R-N.M., challenged Firestone officials
Wednesday on why the tire maker's safety officials did not take
action if the company's financial staff was aware of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you looked at it from a financial point of view and not a
consumer safety point of view?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Crigger responded, ``I'm sorry to say that's the
case.'' &UR;  &LR; Firestone switched production of tires for the Explorer
from Decatur to other fac- tories last January for reasons the
company has never explained.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also gave House investigators Wednesday a copy of an
internal memorandum from March 1999, describing how the company
handled the replacement of problem Firestone tires on Ford
Explorers in Saudi Arabia. On Tuesday, congressional investigators
gave reporters a copy of the memo with one section previously
blacked out by Ford.
</P>
<P>
   That version showed that Firestone officials had been leery of
sending a letter to tire owners in Saudi Arabia for fear that it
might have to inform the U.S. Department of Transportation and that
it might be banned from the Saudi market. ``They feel that the U.S.
DOT will have to be notified of the program, since the same product
is sold in the U.S.,'' the Ford memo stated.
</P>
<P>
   But the complete memo included a section in which the memo's
author, a Ford official named Chuck Seilnacht, mentioned that a
colleague at Ford shared Firestone's worries.
</P>
<P>
   Corey MacGillivray, an official in Ford's general counsel's
office, ``was concerned about the implications,'' as well, the memo
said. ``He was going to check with one of his colleagues to get
more info.''
</P>
<P>
   Firestone's Crigger said that he had been aware of discussion
within the company's legal department of how to handle tire
problems in Saudi Arabia, but was not familiar with the details.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Firestone, Ford sent a letter to owners of Explorers in
Saudi Arabia several months later that they should get new tires,
Nasser pointed out in testimony Wednesday night. Ford also took out
advertisements to promote the tire replacement effort, and covered
the program's expense after Firestone refused to do so on the
grounds that the tires were failing because of customers' misuse.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford did not tell U.S. regulators about the recall after
Firestone officials assured the auto- maker that the tires did not
pose a problem in the United States. Both companies still take that
position: all tires replaced in Saudi Arabia were 16-inch
Wilderness tires, a size that has not been recalled in the United
States, though some plaintiffs' law- yers say they should be.
</P>
<P>
   If Ford and Firestone knew of problems and did nothing, federal
regulators could impose up to $925,000 in fines. But the two
companies and possibly their executives could face criminal charges
by state and local prosecutors, who could accuse them of
culpability in deaths that occurred after the companies clearly
became aware of problems, said Joan Claybrook, who was the
administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
under President Jimmy Carter, and is now the president of Public
Citizen, an advocacy group. A local prosecutor in Indiana tried to
charge Firestone officials with criminal negligence after the
company's huge tire recall in 1978, but was unsuccessful, she said.
</P>
<P>
   If the public comes to perceive Ford and Firestone as culpable,
that could also help lawyers for consumers win larger punitive
damages in lawsuits against the companies. The biggest potential
damage to both companies, however, is that their images could be so
sullied that customers start shying away from their products. Ford
and Firestone both say that their August sales showed little effect
from the recall, but some independent tire dealers say that many
customers are now avoiding Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials repeated Wednesday their contention that they had
asked Firestone repeatedly over the last two years to check the
tires for defects, and had been assured every time that any
problems resulted solely from customers' abuse of the tires.
</P>
<P>
   But senators and representatives were unsympathetic, saying that
Ford had a responsibility to make sure that it put safe tires on
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford, too, when faced with hundreds of complaints of major
tire defects on the Explorer, failed to respond with the sense of
urgency that one would expect when the safety of so many people
rested on its shoulders,'' said Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser announced Thursday night that Ford would set up an
``early warn- ing'' system with the tire industry to identify tire
problems as they L emerge. He also said Ford would tell U.S.
regulators of all for- eign recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers' proposals Wednesday emphasized harsher punishment for
violators of safety rules and closer government monitoring of the
auto industry, with little attention to new safety rules for tires.
A few of the proposals put forward were so far-reaching that even
safety activists spoke against them at the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., proposed that the Transportation
Department assign inspectors to auto factories much as the
Agriculture Department assigns inspectors to chicken processors,
and that automakers be required to forward their quality-control
data to the government. Claybrook said that regulators did not have
the staff necessary for such an ambitious undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said that he planned to introduce
legislation as early as Sept. 7 to establish federal criminal
penalties, possibly enabling a charge such as second-degree
manslaughter, for the executives of companies that knowingly sell
defective products that kill consumers. Automakers lobbied
successfully to defeat a similar measure in 1966, when the nation's
auto regulatory system was set up.
</P>
<P>
   Violations of federal auto safety rules are currently punished
with a fine on the manufacturer of no more than $925,000, plus a
mandatory recall of the defective vehicle, auto part or tire.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Shelby, the Alabama Republican who is the chairman of the
Senate Appropriations subcommittee for transportation, which held
one of Wednesday's hearings, said that he would consider an
immediate increase in the budget of the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, which is part of the Department of
Transportation. The agency's budget was cut almost in half at the
beginning of the Reagan administration, and remains one-third lower
than it was in the Carter administration, after adjusting for
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Auto defects have received little attention on Capitol Hill for
many years. Sue Bailey, the safety agency's administrator, pointed
out that the agency recommended on March 24 that Congress enact
tougher laws, including an increase in the limit on civil penalties
to at least $1 million. But no member of Congress has introduced a
bill with these proposals, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The current session of Congress is scheduled to end Oct. 4, with
only 21 more working days. Bills and budget changes introduced this
late in a session usually have little chance of passing, but Sens.
Specter and Shelby said in interviews that Congress and the nation
were so interested in the tire issue that legislative action was
possible, and even likely.
</P>
<P>
   The tire recall appears to have had fairly little effect on
sales of sport utility vehicles. SUV sales rose 5.1 percent in
August from the level of a year earlier, while the overall auto
market was flat. But all of the growth in sport utility sales
occurred in small car-based models like the Chrysler PT Cruiser,
which the auto industry classifies as sport utilities to qualify
for more lenient regulations that cover light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of larger SUV models like the Ford Explorer, which tend to
be based on pickup truck designs, fell .9 percent in August, partly
because the Explorer itself, the nation's best-selling sport
utility, had a drop of .8 percent. Sales of pickup-based sport
utilities soared in the mid-1990s, but their growth has been
slowing since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., said that he would use the Firestone and
Ford issue to seek quick passage of legislation barring companies
from sealing information relevant to public safety in court
settlements of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for consumers contend that Ford and Firestone have
hidden many documents with such secrecy orders.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Petrauskas, Ford's vice president for safety and
environmental issues, said Ford only sealed the amounts of
settlements and did not seal engineering information.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for consumers said it does not appear that
Bridgestone/Firestone has softened its litigation stance in the
past week, despite the threat of criminal prosecution in Venezuela,
pressure from federal regulators to recall additional tires and
blistering hearings in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened scrutiny ``has had no effect whatsoever,'' said
Bruce Kaster, a lawyer in Ocala, Fla., who has been a leader in
suing Bridgestone/Firestone over tread separation problems.
``There's no indication of any willingness on their part to soften
their position on discovery or settlements or anything else.''
Firestone is only settling cases, he said, ``when they start
getting nervous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
