<HEADER>
A4795 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-H     09-07 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caminiti's future &QL; 
an uncertain one &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ The Astros still were mum on Ken Caminiti's whereabouts
Wednesday, one day after saying he had left the team for personal
reasons and would not return this season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, his voluntary admission into a
substance-dependency program has turned out to be one of the most
talked-about topics in town. The biggest question _ outside those
regarding Caminiti's personal well-being _ is what will be the next
step in his baseball career?
</P>
<P>
   Even before Caminiti's personal problems came to the forefront,
the Astros already were facing a difficult decision regarding
whether to honor his $5.2 million contract for next season or buy
out of the agreement for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, opinion within the organization was split.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Caminiti is one of the most popular players in
recent franchise history, and he was having a big season _ a .303
batting average with 15 homers and 45 RBIs in 59 games _ before a
wrist injury sent him to the disabled list on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Caminiti will celebrate his 38th birthday
during the first month of the 2001 season, and injuries have
limited him to fewer than 140 games each of the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   If, in fact, the Astros were having doubts about bringing
Caminiti back, it's reasonable to assume the personal problems
could work against him.
</P>
<P>
   During spring training, Caminiti hinted at retirement following
the 2000 season. But since the injury, he repeatedly has said he
intends to play next year, even if the Astros decide to pass on the
final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   He also recently brought up the idea of playing in the American
League, where the designated-hitter rule might give his body a
better chance to make it through a full season, not to mention
prolong his career, which began with the Astros in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the Detroit Tigers in mind. Tigers general manager Randy
Smith _ son of Astros president Tal Smith _- is a big fan of
Caminiti's. The Tigers' GM offered Caminiti a three-year, $21
million contract before Caminiti signed a free-agent deal worth
$10.5 million less to return to the Astros after a four-year stint
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Neither confirming nor denying the nature of Caminiti's personal
problems, Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said the veteran third
baseman is in control of his own destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Cammy gets healthy enough physically and mentally,
it's whatever he wants to do,'' Bagwell said. ``No one else will
make that decision but him. Ultimately, it's all going to come down
to Cammy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros must at least prepare for the possibility
of trying to return to their winning ways without Caminiti. Manager
Larry Dierker said veteran Bill Spiers and rookie Chris Truby could
form a productive third-base tandem on what the Astros hope will be
a contending team next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the makeup of the rest of the team,'' Dierker
said. ``But I think that would work. Of course, Cammy brings
something offensively that is far beyond what you're going to get
from Truby and Spiers. But defensively, you'd be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd just have to get the offensive production from somewhere
else. And to be honest, we could probably get by with less offense
because most nights we score enough runs to win. If we had to rob
Peter to pay Paul anywhere, it would probably be offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Truby, an above-average fielder, has been trying to get everyone
to notice his work at the plate. Count Wednesday's performance in a
13-5 win over Florida as another step in the right direction. The
third baseman had three RBIs and came within a double of hitting
for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way I'm going to stick around,'' Truby said.
``If you're going to play third base in the big leagues, you have
to drive in runs and hit for power.''
</P>
<P>
   As for putting a thought in management's mind for next season,
Truby said: ``I'm not the one making the decision, but I can help
the decision. To be honest, I don't really think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, the Astros have quite a bit to think
about with regard to the future at third.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
