<HEADLINE>
CSUN DEFENSE MUST CONTAIN RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Same challenge, different team.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge's football team will be forced to stop the
run again this week _ or at least try. CSUN plays Southwest Texas
State, a team which had two running backs top the 100-yard mark in
a 34-13 win over Midwestern State last week. And it's no secret the
Matadors failed to contain the run in their season opener.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (0-1) surrendered 583 rushing yards in a 55-6 loss to Air
Force. But the Falcons run the option, something CSUN probably
won't see the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite such an amazing offensive performance by Air Force, I
don't consider that indicative of our defense,'' CSUN coach Jeff
Kearin said. ``I really believe the offense put our defense in a
tough spot. . . . We had some bright spots, especially in the
secondary. Overall, I'm relatively pleased with the way we
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's hoping for a better output against the Bobcats, who
got stellar performances from running backs Bronso Sanders and Lee
Davis. They ran for 157 yards on 20 carries (7.6 yards-per-carry
average) and 105 yards on 16 carries (6.5 average), respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some pretty swift running backs,'' CSUN linebacker
Cos Abercrombie said. ``We understand that. Of course (after Air
Force), we have to put the emphasis on the run. That's a lot of
yards for one game. Everybody feels bad about that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hicks out again: Running back Matt Hicks is not expected to
play Saturday. Hicks, who was supposed to make his debut with the
Matadors since transferring from Air Force, is out with the flu. He
missed Tuesday's and Wednesday's practices and isn't expected to
travel to San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed but it happens,'' Kearin said. ``He's sick.
It'll work out OK. He's really close (to playing).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: Defensive back Karalus Doyle (hip) and
defensive end Joseph Roberson (knee) will play Saturday. Defensive
back Sean Atkins (knee) hasn't practiced this week and probably
won't travel to Texas. Atkins bruised his knee against Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   __ They're back: Backup quarterback Mitch Ryerson and receiver
Jason Stone served one-game suspensions for violating school policy
and will be available Saturday. . . . Tight end Cory DiSanti
practiced for the first time Tuesday. DiSanti was waiting for a
summer-class grade to be completed and processed to earn his
Associate of Arts degree.
</P>
<P>
   __ Up in the air: Receiver Ryan Felix _ a transfer from Utah
State _ didn't play Saturday and didn't practice Wednesday. Felix
is trying to clear up academic-eligibility issues from the
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Turn that dial: This will be the first season fans won't be
able to listen to Matadors football games on the radio. CSUN
couldn't raise the $12,000 needed for the KCSN broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Once Matadors coach Jeff Kearin learned the money wasn't raised
through CSUN, he thought about trying to raise it himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were going to have it, I was going to have to raise the
$12,000,'' Kearin said. ``But I had to fight other battles. I'm
sick about it, but that's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0025 </DOCNO>
