<SLUG> BC-MTA-UPDATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTA, UNIONS STILL BARGAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(New version to correct name. Disregard previous version) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
  LOS ANGELES _ MTA rail and bus operators said Wednesday that they
have no plans to strike before Friday as talks continue on wages,
work rules and the proposed Valley transit zone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Metropolitan Transportation Authority and Amalgamated Transit
Union officials said they hope to resume negotiations Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to meet with them any time,'' MTA spokesman Marc
Littman said. ``We are anxious to work something out.''
</P>
<P>
   An official of the ATU, which represents more than 1,800 bus and
train mechanics, said public transportation should be running at
least up until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The unions representing most MTA workers agreed Monday to a
five-day extension in talks, but the ATU rejected the extension,
saying it would consider on a day-to-day basis whether to walk off
the job.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the United Transportation Union and the
Transportation Communications International Union, which represent
about 4,950 bus and train drivers and clerical workers, met with
MTA negotiators. Those talks are expected to resume today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to meet with the UTU and the TCU and continue
to invite the ATU to meet with us,'' MTA spokesman Gary Wosk said.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a projected $438 million operating deficit over the next
10 years, the MTA is attempting to reduce its costs and is trying
to hold the line in negotiations to achieve those savings.
</P>
<P>
   Goldy Norton, spokesman for the UTU, said negotiations bogged
down Wednesday over the MTA's proposal to require drivers to work
four 10-hour days spread over 12 to 13 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said the long days could fatigue drivers and endanger
passengers' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our drivers have the lives of their passengers in their hands
and we believe this is a serious threat to the safety and
well-being of the schoolchildren and others who are dependent on
public transit,'' UTU General Chairman James A. Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Littman said many MTA drivers already work more than 12 hours a
shift and not just four days a week, but five and six days a week,
collecting large amounts of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our operators are paid overtime to work 12-hour shifts
and if the UTU was concerned about driver fatigue and safety then
they would not permit their members to volunteer to work that
overtime,'' Littman said.
</P>
<P>
   The looming strike, which would clog freeways and shut down bus
and train service to the MTA's 450,000 passengers a day, is
worrying riders in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in wheelchairs who are absolutely terrified
of the strike,'' said Van Nuys resident Rick Rofman, a 57-year-old
disabled rider who depends on public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Sylmar resident Bart Reed, a legally blind man who is a member
of the MTA's Passenger Advisory Committee, said the mood on the
buses this week is very somber. ``Every bus was sort of like
waiting for doomsday,'' said Reed, 48.
</P>
<P>
   !end!
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
