<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TEXANS-LOGO-HNS &LR;      09-07 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TEXANS-LOGO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texans' logo development reflects `spirit of achievement'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ Selecting a name, logo and colors for an NFL franchise is
a long, difficult and multifaceted process involving dozens of
people in several states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To start from scratch and end up with the Texans name, the logo
of a bull with elliptical horns, and team colors of battle red,
deep steel blue and liberty white was a challenge for the many
designers and marketers who worked on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a name that was distinctive and timeless and not
faddish, something contemporary and powerful,'' team owner Bob
McNair said. ``We wanted a name with a strong state association,
something that was representative of Texas and unique to Houston
and the NFL. A Texan is authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the spirit of the bull reflects Texas _ bold, proud,
strong, courageous, independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red, white and blue are the colors of our state flag. Our
scheme differs from the state flag in that we're using a darker
blue and a lighter red.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before McNair was awarded his franchise in October 1999,
there were nicknames that interested him, including Texans,
Stallions and Toros. After he paid $700 million for the 32nd
franchise, McNair met with executives from NFL Properties, the
league's marketing arm, to start the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creative process began with a blank sheet of paper,''
McNair said. ``We tried to capture an image that reflects the
spirit of Texas, and that wasn't an easy task, because Texas means
so much to so many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas can mean things like the space industry, oil, energy,
rodeo and real estate. It can be urban, suburban or rural. A Texan
represents the diverse interests of our state. There was a
challenge of blending the old with the new. We wanted something
dynamic that was separate and distinct from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to build on our great heritage by blending the past
with the present and future.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is excited about the name, logo and colors and how the
process played out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entire process has been driven by Mr. McNair and his
image of his team,'' said Dave Goldman, a senior director at NFL
Properties. ``He was going for something bigger than the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept telling us he didn't want a fancy design or something
hyped to sell tickets. He said he wanted something the community
could be proud of, something that represented the best parts of his
city. During the process, we also remained sensitive of NFL
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman met with McNair for the first time two weeks after
Houston got the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Mr. McNair what he wanted his team to represent,''
Goldman said. ``In November, we met with our research group and set
up our first focus group. We asked them what was their image of
Houston, the NFL and Texas and what they expect from their team.
That gave us a starting point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our working catch phrase was spirit of achievement. We met
with focus groups in Houston, Austin, San Antonio, Galveston and
Beaumont. We looked at a lot of different names.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about the finalists, Stallions and Apollos
didn't really capture that spirit of achievement. A Texan is an
all-inclusive name. It's very ambiguous. A stallion is a horse. An
apollo is a spaceship. A Texan can be an awful lot of things, and
that was the challenge. We could design a Texan to be anything, but
we had to create an identity behind the name.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those involved in the process with Goldman were NFL
executives Marty Fitzpatrick, the design director who led the
design team; Dave Kocsis, the senior manager of research who
coordinated the focus groups; and Brian McCarthy, director of
corporate communications, as well as commissioner Paul Tagliabue
and vice presidents Joe Browne and Roger Goodell.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a process taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we looked at every conceivable possibility,'' McNair
said. ``I think we had more than 81,000 suggestions in our (name
the team) contest. We eliminated most of them because we didn't
want to consider anything that generated negative feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dealt with over 40 focus groups and had discussions with
over 500 people in those groups. We asked the focus groups for
their perceptions of Houston, the NFL and Texas. We found Houston
and the state of Texas described with words like dynamic,
forward-thinking, proud, determined, mentally tough. What's been
achieved in Texas is affirmation of that. Texans are people of
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Once McNair decided Texans was his first choice, he contacted
Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt, whose team was originally the Dallas
Texans before it moved to Kansas City. McNair didn't need Hunt's
permission to use the name.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a courtesy, Lamar's the first person I spoke to, and he
said he'd be delighted,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Oilers became the Titans last year, they used the New
York Jets' original name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what's happened in the last two years, the
history and heritage of the NFL has been born again with Titans and
Texans,'' Goldman said. ``Once Mr. McNair decided on the name, we
had to create the logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I've worked with the Buccaneers, Titans and Browns,
among others, and this one was tough because there's no obvious
symbol of a Texan. What image could we design that symbolically
demonstrated the strength and energy of Texas _ that spirit of
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we met with the focus groups, we found out that Texans are
proud of their heritage and tradition, but they don't want to be
typecast. We think the logo is a stylized, modern symbol that's
unique to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Texans, the designers gave McNair some logo and
color possibilities utilizing the Stallions name, which was a
personal favorite because of his love of horses and his involvement
in the horse racing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have taken the easy road and selected Stallions,''
Goldman said. ``A horse would have been the logo. But a horse is a
horse. He said he didn't want to just put a horse on a helmet,
because this is about the Houston community.
</P>
<P>
   ``In mid-August, we rented Giants Stadium for a day for logo and
uniform testing. We wanted to see the logo and colors in daylight
with still photos and video. Mr. McNair wants something unique,
something that'll make people go, `Wow! That's the Houston Texans
uniform.'''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman disputes any claims that the Texans name won't sell
outside Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary goal is to be accepted in the Houston marketplace
and the surrounding communities,'' he said. ``If the team wins, and
fans around the country find the logo attractive, why wouldn't it
catch on? We think it's outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
