<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     09-07 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Davenport proves she's not ready to step aside &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ It was a case study in the ephemeral nature of
self-confidence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams began her U.S. Open quarterfinal Wednesday night
behaving exactly as a defending champion is expected to. There was
a swagger in her step, and her cruise-missile groundstrokes were
equal parts ability and attitude. Hence, the would-be has-been, Ms.
Yesterday's News, Lindsay Davenport, seemed in trouble from the
get-go, facing this buffed, steely-eyed woman-child who exuded a
supreme certainty that she couldn't possibly be beaten by anybody
not named Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to be more specific, anybody not named after the second
planet to the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, having lost her last five matches to Serena _ not to
mention her most recent one to sis in the Wimbledon final _ needed
to stave off three break points, clawing through five deuces in the
process, simply to stay level in the match through two games.
</P>
<P>
   Watching, you couldn't help thinking, ``Poor Lindsay.'' At 24,
her window of opportunity was being slammed down upon her fingers.
Serena, never mind Venus, was only going to grow stronger, smarter
and more polished. As fine a player as Davenport had become,
winning three of the four majors in a two-year period, the Williams
girls already were making her appear gawky and slow, downright
un-athletic by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   As Serena guaranteed later, before stomping out of her
post-mortem in a petulant huff, there will be a
Williams-vs.-Williams Grand Slam final in the future. But what this
evening's result reminded us was that there won't be one until
Lindsay concedes to its inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   She has perhaps played better, if only because she did struggle
with her serve a bit, but she never has played with more tenacity,
with more dogged determination to prove her day isn't done yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was expecting an all-Williams final,'' Davenport
said with a twinkle in her eye, ``but I didn't want that to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Serena talk, nobody wanted it to happen. Alas, she has
yet to learn to handle defeat as gracefully as she plays, and she
showed her brat side Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Serena sniffed, ``no one would want to see an
all-Williams final because everyone doesn't really like us. That's
just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   You assume she didn't mean that exactly as it came out because,
if she did, it likely is the dumbest thing she has ever said. And,
when a reporter pressed her on the remark, it only made her angrier
than she already was about losing. Remember, she is still 18, an
age when it is practically mandated to do and say dumb things.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Serena had shown a measure of courage by surviving five
match points against her serve at the end, but she was pretty much
broken emotionally by then, having sensed the futility of her
mission.
</P>
<P>
   She already had cracked a racket out of frustration, and that
was before she dropped six consecutive games, finding herself being
pummeled at every turn _ 6-4, 6-2 _ by her own grip-it-and-rip-it
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I was getting a good hit on the ball,'' Davenport
said. ``I waswasn't being jerked around. I was able to dictate
where the ball was going.''
</P>
<P>
   As we've learned, Serena much prefers to force the issue, using
her physical strength to bludgeon opponents into whimpering,
shivering submission. But Davenport turned the tables on the kid.
</P>
<P>
   She replied to power with more power. The harder the ball came,
and Serena does give it a nasty whack, that much harder it went
screaming back.
</P>
<P>
   Williams appeared to be surprised by Lindsay's tenacity, saying:
``You know, she should take that attitude toward everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In their most recent meeting in Los Angeles last month,
Davenport had collapsed at 6-5 and serving in the third set. Also,
she had definitely been overpowered by Venus at Wimbledon, although
a sore back and a cold contributed to her demise that day. She
subsequently suffered a foot injury, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great to be able to play 100 percent,'' Davenport
said, ``to finally be able to play full out.''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't had that much freedom on the court physically since
probably a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In private, pre-match family discussions, nonetheless, you
suspect Lindsay's potential for upsetting the Williams' apple cart
here was given short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, in victory, maintained her humility, something Serena
and Venus frequently struggle with. (Yes, Daddy's influence.)
Venus, of course, still lurks, and even if Martina Hingis turns the
elder Williams away, that only means the top-ranked, top-seeded
woman on the WTA Tour will be at the top of her game as well.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the growing perception in many quarters _ making
Serena's paranoia all the harder to fathom _ the WTA does not yet
stand for Williams Tennis Association. Trouncing a Williams in the
quarters only earned Davenport a deserved place in the semis,
against the upstart Russian Elena Dementieva.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big match to get through,'' Lindsay said. ``It felt
like a final. But it was just a quarterfinal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just any quarterfinal, though.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
