<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-LSU-BOOTY-HNS &LR;      09-07 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LSU-BOOTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Booty trades major leagues for LSU football &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RICHARD JUSTICE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BATON ROUGE, La. _ Josh Booty has ended up right where he was
supposed to be from the moment he first stepped onto a football
field: He's LSU's starting quarterback. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as some told him he would be one of baseball's next great
players, and even as he got a huge signing bonus and a World Series
ring from the Florida Marlins, his football dream never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   While some looked at him and saw Brooks Robinson, he always
looked at himself and saw John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved it,'' he said. ``It's what I want to do with
my life. I still think I can play in the NFL _ if it's God's
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he begins an interview by mentioning that the
Marlins are playing in Houston and that his buddy, Florida first
baseman Kevin Millar, homered Tuesday night. He mentions how much
fun it has been to see so many of his minor league teammates play
in the big leagues the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met a lot of great guys,'' he said. ``I'll keep in touch
with those guys for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He just won't play with them. Instead, he'll be starting at
quarterback when LSU hosts Houston here Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In his first appearance of the season, he showed athleticism and
a rocket arm in completing 12 of 15 passes for 291 yards and two
touchdowns while splitting time with Rohan Davey in a victory over
Western Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   New LSU coach Nick Saban said Davey and Booty will continue to
share the position, but Booty clearly is the fan favorite. With
almost every completion, the talk-show phone lines light up from
Lafayette to Opelousas with Tiger faithful who say they have seen a
glimpse of the next Bert Jones or the next Archie Manning.
</P>
<P>
   His life has been like that since he was a schoolboy star at
Shreveport's Evangel High. He led his team to the 1993 state
championship and set national records with 11,700 career passing
yards and 126 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Parade Magazine and USA Today chose him their national player of
the year over fellow Louisiana prep star Peyton Manning of nearby
Newman. Bill Walsh called Booty the best high school quarterback he
had ever seen, and when Booty signed with LSU in 1994, he was given
a simple label: savior.
</P>
<P>
   He still may be LSU's savior, but his path has been a strange
one.
</P>
<P>
   He was also one of the best high school baseball players in the
country and when the Marlins made him the fifth pick of the 1994
draft and offered him a $1.6-million signing bonus, Booty signed.
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't hit. In five minor league seasons, he had a .198
career average with 62 homer runs and 621 strikeouts. Still, he
worked his way up the system and got a September call-up and a
World Series ring in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the 1998 season as the Marlins' starting third baseman
while Bobby Bonilla was injured. When Bonilla got well, Booty
returned to the minors with a respectable .269 career batting
average in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   But he hit just .202 at Class AA Portland and was placed on
waivers after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great kid and has a world of talent,'' said Cincinnati
Reds superscout Gary Hughes, who signed Booty for the Marlins. ``He
played third base as well as anyone I've ever seen. I've seen him
make Brooks Robinson plays. I've seen him go behind the third-base
coach's box to field a ball and throw a guy out.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I don't think he was ever totally committed to baseball,
and he'd probably tell you that now. But I'll always wonder what
would have happened if he'd been totally dedicated to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Booty, now 25, apparently never came close to that kind of
dedication.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins were concerned enough about his love of football to
include a clause preventing him from playing it during the
offseason. Booty didn't play football, but he did the next best
thing. Instead of taking part in winter ball, as the organization
wanted, he returned home right after each season and went to every
high school, college and pro game he could get to.
</P>
<P>
   He discussed retiring from baseball after his second season, but
when the Marlins ordered him to repay the signing bonus, he stayed.
Finally, after the 1998 season, both sides were ready for a
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minor league baseball is a real rough life,'' he said. ``I
don't see anything being any harder. You play 30 to 40 spring
training games, then 140 to 160 games in the regular season. That's
a lot of playing time. That's a lot of travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the friendships I made, but it was difficult being
away from home. I wanted to give it a good chance because I loved
baseball growing up. I loved it as much as football. I didn't want
to just give it one year and move on. I thought playing in the big
leagues might help me. The more I played, the more I missed playing
football and playing with my brother and coming to LSU and
different things. The longer I was away from football, the more I
wanted to be playing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he seems happy. His brother, Abram, is a wide receiver for
the Tigers, and throughout the Bayou there's hope that Saban and
his new staff will escort Booty down the aisle of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Purple and Gold magazine, which covers LSU sports, greeted his
enrollment by calling him ``the Prodigal Son, the Golden Boy and
the Messiah all rolled into one.'' Three other publications
splashed him on their yearbook covers.
</P>
<P>
   He's not like most college students. He lives in an off-campus
apartment, drives a black Corvette and wears a World Series ring.
If the NFL seems like a distant dream to most of his teammates, he
has been close enough to glory to really believe it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought his first season back in football would be
like, Booty smiles and says: ``I envisioned coming here and setting
the world on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Booty started eight games in 1999 _ and threw a
school-record 19 interceptions _ while attempting the third-most
passes in school history. He had some moments _ like throwing three
touchdown passes against Ole Miss _ but he also threw three
interceptions in three straight games and was picked off four times
against Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   He was the most visible player in a terrible season.
</P>
<P>
   LSU alums began to call for coach Gerry DiNardo's head early on,
and when the season began badly, it came undone in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   If Booty was stung by any of this, he doesn't show it. He
remains as instantly likeable and open as he was in the minor
leagues, and if he's inclined to blame someone else for his
problems, he refuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got put in a lot of hard situations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps returning to football and being an instant star after
five years in baseball was asking too much. Now, having dropped 30
pounds, to 215, he seems to be zipping the ball as well as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if last season had lowered his expectations of himself, he
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question. I feel like I can play in the NFL.
Maybe I had to go through something like that to get to where I
need to be. I was thrown into the fire last year. Everything
dominoed. We didn't know if we were going to have a new coach week
to week. We weren't healthy. I tried to do too much. I've tried
(this year) to get back to the basics. I think I've done some of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Louis Williams put it simply: ``He's a completely
different quarterback this year. He was so raw last year. He was
supposed to be all-everything, and he struggled the first year. I
think now the pressure's off a little bit, and he can keep growing
with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
