u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HN     09-07 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truby helps Astros punt Marlins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ The NFL is still two years from returning to Houston, but
you wouldn't have guessed it Wednesday night at Enron Field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During pre-game festivities, owner Drayton McLane Jr. caught a
ceremonial football and spiked it at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the dugout, several Astros tried on a football helmet bearing
the logo of the city's new NFL franchise, the Texans.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the Astros commemorated the occasion by putting
two touchdowns and an extra point on the scoreboard in a 13-5
victory over the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Implementing baseball's version of the run-and-shoot, the Astros
blitzed the Marlins for seven runs in the fifth inning, and
righthander Jose Lima took over from there for his seventh victory
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great game for a lot of different people when you
score that many runs,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more so if your name is Chris Truby.
</P>
<P>
   Truby, the Astros' rookie third baseman, tied a season high with
three hits. He hit a run-scoring triple in the second, a two-run
homer in the fifth, and a single in the eighth. He also was retired
on a long fly to center in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Truby hit only four home runs at Class AAA New Orleans before
his call-up in mid-June, but he has eight homers and 38 RBIs in 58
games with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I'm going to stick around and play third base in
the big leagues is to drive in runs and hit home runs,'' said
Truby, who batted .319 in August.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 4-2, the Astros erupted in the fifth inning, sending 11
batters to the plate. Marlins starter Jesus Sanchez (8-10) failed
to retire any of the six batters he faced and allowed three
consecutive doubles before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros loaded the bases on a pair of walks and an infield
single before Julio Lugo lined an 0-2 pitch into the left-field
corner to tie the game at 4. Lugo has five hits in the last two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell, who had three RBIs to raise his team-leading total
to 113, followed with a two-run ground-rule double that bounced
into the front row of seating at Ruggles Restaurant in center field
an estimated 410 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo followed with an RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Truby unleashed a two-run homer off the top of the
facade in left field against reliever Manny Aybar. As the ball
cleared the Crawford Boxes, Marlins left fielder Cliff Floyd didn't
even bother looking back.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The seven runs tied a season high; the Astros scored seven in
the 10th inning of a 14-8 victory May 7 at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing three runs in fifth, Lima (7-15) clamped down and
held the Marlins to one over his final three innings. He allowed
five runs and seven hits in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Lima improved to 5-0 in six career starts against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitches good against us all the time,'' Marlins third
baseman Mike Lowell said. ``We hit him decent. With five runs you
would figure to be in the game. They just outslugged us. After five
innings it was no contest.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing a club-record 13 straight games, Lima has
resurrected his season, going 6-2 with four no-decisions since July
9.
</P>
<P>
   His only mistakes Wednesday were a pair of walks that prolonged
innings and allowed the Marlins to score in the fourth and fifth
innings _ and a hanging 0-2 slider that Preston Wilson sent over
the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Lima also allowed a pinch homer to Chris Clapinski in the
seventh. He has allowed 42 home runs this season, a club record and
the most in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched pretty well inside,'' Lima said. ``I straightened
myself out after the first couple of innings.''
</P>
<P>
   He also helped himself at the plate, going 1-for-3 with a single
and two runs. ``A knock (hit), a walk and two runs is pretty
impressive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Scott Linebrink pitched a scoreless ninth inning in his
Astros debut.
</P>
<P>
   After the Marlins tied the game at 1 in the fourth inning,
Moises Alou put the Astros back in front in the bottom half of the
inning with his 27th homer _ a solo shot that landed in the
left-center field concourse.
</P>
<P>
   Florida answered with three runs in the fifth. With two outs,
Alex Gonzalez singled to left and Lima walked Floyd before Wilson
drilled a three-run homer to right.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Astros answered _ very loudly _ with seven in the
bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
