<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4808 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-KILLING-2NDL     09-07 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-KILLING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 TEENS ACCUSED OF KILLING FOOD DELIVERYMAN TO AVOID PAYING
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS grafs 11-13 with progress of case, quotes)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW and SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It looked at first like a botched robbery: the owner
of a Chinese takeout place was lured late Friday night to a dark
dead-end street in Queens, where he was jumped and bludgeoned to
death. The killers left him with $600.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators said Wednesday that the real motive was
heartbreakingly mundane: he had been killed by a group of
teen-agers who wanted a free meal.
</P>
<P>
   The five teen-agers, who were all under arrest Wednesday and
scheduled to be arraigned Wednesday night, had no criminal records
and were mostly from solidly middle-class families. Prosecutors
said they were hungry and wanted to eat without paying, so they
used a cell phone to call in their $60 order _ General Tso's
chicken, shrimp egg foo yong, chicken with broccoli and shrimp lo
mein _ to a vacant house on 176th Street in Springfield Gardens,
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   When the deliveryman, Jin-Sheng Liu, 44, arrived shortly before
midnight, he was jumped from behind, covered with a bedsheet and
pummeled to death with repeated head blows from fists and at least
one brick. As police officers converged on the scene, the group _
four boys and a girl, none older than 17 _ fled with a bag of food
to one of the boys' homes to eat, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of days, police, who cracked the case by tracing the
call to the restaurant on the cell phone, began zeroing in on a
group of teen-agers who lived in the neighborhood around the vacant
house at 130-19 176th St. The youngest, a skinny 14-year-old karate
enthusiast named Robert Savage, was arrested Tuesday as he was
riding his bicycle outside his parents' neatly kept home in
Springfield Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   It was Savage, investigators said, who struck the most serious
blows, smashing the skull of Liu with a brick. Liu, the owner of
the Golden Wok at 192-15 Linden Boulevard in St. Albans, Queens,
was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just did something, and it turned out ugly,'' said Robert
Eilam, 20, who lives across the street from Savage. Eilam said that
on Tuesday afternoon, a few hours before Savage was arrested, the
boy had started to cry for no apparent reason. ``He was just acting
as if he were so sorry about something,'' Eilam said.
</P>
<P>
   Savage and the other teen-agers are being prosecuted as adults.
Each faces multiple charges of second-degree murder, robbery and
criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terribly tragic case,'' said Richard A. Brown, the
Queens district attorney, said at a news conference Wednesday.
``Mr. Liu was a hard-working immigrant who leaves behind a wife and
two children. He was killed without provocation and without reason.
It was a shocking crime, which leaves us all shaking our heads and
wondering why these kids would do what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities identified the other teen-agers as James Stone,
16, of 176-31 130th Ave.; Jamel Murphy, 17, of 219-05 131st Ave.;
Darryl Tyson, 17, of 132-07 178th St.; and Stacy Royster, 17, of
257-52 148th Drive. Because of his age, Savage faces a maximum
sentence of nine years to life in prison, prosecutors said. The
other four face up to 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers were arraigned Wednesday night and ordered held
without bail. Later, their lawyers told reporters that detectives
obtained statements improperly, and they disputed the authorities'
account of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, Savage's law- yer, Rudy Hirschheimer, disputed the
prosecution's contention that his client had acknowledged striking
Liu with a brick. ``My client said he didn't hit anyone with a
brick,'' he said, joining with other defense law- yers in
suggesting that a sixth teen-age boy may have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Neville Reed, a lawyer for Tyson, said that police officers re-
peatedly assured Tyson's par- ents that their son did not need a
lawyer during questioning. ``The so- called statement they obtained
from my client was in my opinion in viola- tion of his
constitutional rights to have counsel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Savage, Stone and Tyson either would not comment or
did not respond to messages left at their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family just wants their son home _ that's it,'' said a man
sitting on the front steps of James Stone's home, five doors down
from Robert Savage's home.
</P>
<P>
   A man who would not give his name but identified himself as the
father of Jamel Murphy trembled during a brief interview Wednesday
in front of his house. ``I really don't have any words to describe
how I feel right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he planned to attend his son's arraignment, he replied:
``I'm not going to go, no. For me to go and show support for
something I don't support would be hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   Royster's grandmother, Anastasia Brown, said in an interview
Wednesday that her granddaughter had struggled in recent years with
mental illness that at times made her ``aggressive and out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who raised Royster after the girl's mother died about
eight years ago, said that in recent months Royster had seemed to
get her life back on track. Only last week, Brown said, she signed
up for classes at Queensborough Community College.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investigators described Liu's death as the senseless outcome of
an amateurish scheme. The group had already eaten once on Friday
from another Chinese restaurant, but they decided they wanted
seconds. Only this time, they came up with a plan to avoid paying,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, officials said they told the police, was for Royster
to call the Golden Wok with her cell phone and place an order.
Then, investigators said, Royster was to wait on the front steps of
the vacant house, ideally situated for a robbery across a dead-end
street from thick woods. The teen-agers later told investigators
that they chose Royster to place the order and wait for the
delivery because they figured that she would be perceived as less
of a potential threat, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When the delivery man arrived, the idea was for the boys to jump
out of hiding places in the bushes by the front door, cover him
with the sheet and then flee with the food, investigators said. But
they also were armed with a couple of bricks taken from one of
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the authorities, the plan unfolded as planned about
11 p.m. on Friday when Royster called the Golden Wok. Royster
barely knew most of the boys. She had become involved with the
group through her friendship with Tyson, whom she had known from
high school. She keeps a photograph of Tyson by her bedroom mirror,
not far from her posters of Snoop Doggy Dog and Mariah Carey and
her collection of stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't find a nicer guy,'' Brown said of Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   According to her grandmother, Royster had been at home much of
Friday, listening to CDs _ hip hop and Spanish music _ writing
e-mail messages, watching television. About 5 p.m. she told her
grandmother she was going over to Tyson's house, in Springfield
Gardens several miles away, and said she would not be out late.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that about 9 p.m., she beeped her granddaughter, who
called her back on the cell phone Brown had bought for her a few
months ago. Brown said she told her not to stay out late, but
Royster did not come home until about 2 a.m., and she was agitated
and nervous, staying up until 3:30 a.m. and acting strange ``and
hyper'' the rest of the weekend. She told her grandmother over the
weekend that she had lost her cell phone, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Liu was already dead. Plans for a simple robbery of
food had spiraled out of control, investigators said, when Robert
Savage used one of the bricks to begin hitting Liu. An autopsy
found that he had been struck in the skull at least three times.
</P>
<P>
   Liu had operated the Golden Wok for at least 10 years. It is a
modest storefront operation. There are no tables for dining, and
Liu, a Chinese immigrant who spoke little English, made most of the
deliveries himself. He worked long days side by side with his wife,
a son and a daughter, and they lived in an apartment fashioned from
partitions and bunk beds at the rear of the restaurant, said the
former property manager for the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Golden Wok remained closed and the Liu family
remained in seclusion. ``He was an asset to the community,'' said
Morris Greene, owner of a realty company a few doors down from the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after Liu's death, the teen-agers carried on as if
all were normal. They went to a nearby mall. They rode their
bicycles in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Royster went to her first day of classes at
Queensborough, and while she was at the college a detective showed
up at the house with questions about a call placed to the
restaurant from a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brown, she quickly admitted to calling the
restaurant and then described the attack. Several people who live
in the neighborhood said Royster also returned there and helped
point out some of her alleged accomplices to detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said her granddaughter told detectives that she and Tyson
had waited on the steps, with the other boys in the bushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stacy had nothing to do with that man being killed,'' Brown
said, beginning to cry. ``She's not involved in anything like
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
