<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-OPEN-SAMPRAS-HNS &LR;      09-07 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-SAMPRAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sampras rallies by Krajicek &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By SCOTT KAISER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ It was Wimbledon all over again for Pete Sampras at the
U.S. Open on Wednesday night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Needing a tiebreaker miracle like he had against Patrick Rafter
in the finals earlier this summer, Sampras came through again in
rallying for a 4-6, 7-6 (6), 6-4, 6-2 quarterfinal victory over
nemesis Richard Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was down a set and trailing 4-1 _ with Rafter having two
serves coming up _ in the second-set tiebreaker at Wimbledon, but
battled back en route to his record 13th Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was even more precarious here as he trailed 6-2 in
the second-set tiebreaker and Krajicek possessing the biggest serve
in the game. However, Sampras answered with six straight points to
knot the match and snatch the momentum away from the Dutchman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was finished,'' Sampras admitted. ``I was a little
lucky because I don't know how I pulled (the tiebreaker) out. It's
all kind of a blur. Richard was outplaying me to that point, so it
was a carbon copy of Wimbledon.``
</P>
<P>
   In the tiebreaker, Sampras saved the first set point with a
gutsy drop volley that barely cleared the tape. Krajicek then had
two serves, but Sampras hit a forehand return winner and a backhand
passing shot down the line. Sampras saved his fourth set point with
a slicing volley that Krajicek couldn't handle, then took a 7-6
lead with a big serve. Sampras then completed the improbable rally
with a forehand passing shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really do anything wrong,'' Krajicek said. ``Those
were three great points in a row for him to get back to 6-5. I
guess it was just meant to be for him.``
</P>
<P>
   With his confidence suddenly renewed, Sampras made a break of
Krajicek in the third game of the third set stand up. In the final
set, he broke Krajicek in the third and seventh games en route to
closing out the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``(After the tiebreaker) I raised my game,'' said Sampras, who
is seeking his fifth title here. ``I started slicing my returns and
making him play a few more shots, and Richard might have gotten a
bit down on himself.``
</P>
<P>
   Sampras dug himself into a hole in the first set when he missed
a forehand volley wide at break point in the ninth game of the
first set and Krajicek held his serve at love to close it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate,'' Sampras said. ``He was doing everything a
little bit better than I was and I would have had trouble battling
back from two sets down.``
</P>
<P>
   Sampras will next face young Aussie Lleyton Hewitt, who cruised
past unseeded Arnaud Clement 6-2, 6-4, 6-3. The 19-year-old Hewitt,
seeded ninth, let Clement orchestrate his own defeat as the
Frenchman _ who ousted No. 1 Andre Agassi in the second round _
sprayed shots all over the court. Clement finished the match with
42 unforced errors, 19 more than Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so bad,'' Clement said. ``I was sleeping the first two
sets. I'm not happy.``
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who patterns his game after Swede baseliner Mats
Wilander, had a relatively low 10 winners, but came up with a
surprising 18 aces. The latter was 15 more than Clement and allowed
Hewitt to be broken only once the entire match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two matches (he knocked out No. 7 Thomas Enqvist in
the fourth round) have probably been a lot more mental than
actually technical,'' Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be mentally tough out there in the first couple of
games and try to get that early break, and get the first set under
your belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say I've definitely been hitting the ball a lot better
with each match that I've played.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
