<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY PUBLIC TRANSIT TURNED INTO MAGIC BUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I don't know about all the Muni workers, but at
least one unidentified driver deserves a big raise.
</P>
<P>
   It was last Friday evening and Liz Einbinder was aboard the
45-Union, heading west toward Russian Hill from North Beach, and
she reports:
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we reached Columbus, the bus was nearly full, with
tourists and locals. The driver not only greeted all the passengers
as they boarded, but he led us in a sing-along throughout the
route.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started with Billy Joel's `For the Longest Time,' and then
campfire songs and various popular hits. Everyone on the bus sang
along, including the two big gang-looking dudes in the back row,
who sang beautiful harmony on the Billy Joel song.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when the bus went down the steep hill after Hyde St., the
passengers put their arms in the air as if on a roller coaster, and
oohed and aahed down the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one weird city.
</P>
<P>
   STRANGERS are shooting you full of dangerous radiation as you
walk down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's nothing personal. But according to flyers circulating
in parts of the city, those little remote devices that lock and
unlock your car send out zaps of radiation that cause various aches
and pains, difficult breathing and even limping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand A Recall!'' the flyer demands.
</P>
<P>
   What about garage-door openers, TV remotes, cell phones,
microwaves, high-powered antennas and computers? We are slowly
frying our innards to a crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Is the flyer legit? Don't ask me. I don't use a garage-door
opener because I'm afraid a UFO will be hovering overhead, my
remote will drop the saucer's hatch, and green aliens will splatter
all over my driveway.
</P>
<P>
   But a recall? Never. I think we all agree it's worth a few aches
and pains and death to avoid having to actually insert a key in a
lock or get up from the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if those remote-key devices really were dangerous, Ford
would be recalling them from Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   GOOF DEPT.: Chronicle headline said, ``Raiders, Local Officials
Butt Heads Once Again.''
</P>
<P>
   A typo! As Paul Quihillalt points out, ``Butt Heads'' should
have been ``Buttheads.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG CONTEST: I was in a retail shop recently and the decor
included some lovely photographs of the Golden Gate Bridge. Every
photograph of the Golden Gate Bridge is lovely, or haunting, or
poetic, or inspiring, or moody.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible there has never been an ugly photo of that bridge.
</P>
<P>
   But if you do have a bad photograph of the Golden Gate Bridge,
send it here. I'll get Stanlee Gatti to help me judge. The winner
will get something.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. Bush referred to a New York Times reporter as ``a
major-league a------.'' But as Bob Ryan notes, what does the
Bushster know about the major leagues? When he owned a baseball
team, he traded Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see the Gore ads on  &UR; that  &LR; one,'' Ryan sniffs.
</P>
<P>
   And Lou Bristol heard W deliver a stump speech in which he
declared that there is a gap in this country ``between the poor and
the nonpoor.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Bush family compound, I believe that gap is referred to
as the moat.
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN chuckle at some of these names, but please exercise good
taste:
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the Santa Rosa Junior College farm is a
well-grounded gent named Leonard Diggs (thanks, Paul Franson). ...
From a news story: ``Air travel (with pets) is not going to get
easier,'' says Millie Woolf of the Independent Pet and Animal
Transport Assn. (Yeah, and it's already ruff!). ... The
distinguished chairman of the Stanford Alumni Assn. Board of
Directors is Young J. Boozer III. From a long line of Young
Boozers. (Thanks, David Jensen). ... (Here comes the one you're not
to laugh at:) And Brian Gordon was motoring through a small town in
Washington State when he saw a sign, ``Please don't drink and
drive.'' Next to it, a smaller sign, with a wreath and the words,
``In memory of Terry Skidmore.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T TAKE it personally if you get an information request card
from the city's Department of Elections stating that records show
you were born in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who registered before about 1972 gets that notice.
Before that time, voters were not asked to give their birth year,
so the computer was programmed to list them all as born in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't the mailed notice simply ask for a birth year, thus
avoiding possible confusion and insult? As a department
spokesperson told me, ``I guess every form could have been worded
in a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   Damn right, and sooner or later I'll fix all of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF OLD: The lovely and talented Susan Prather, shining
knight of the homeless in Contra Costa Co., is about to become a
bride at 49. So she went to register for gifts.
</P>
<P>
   At Pottery Barn, the clerk ignored Susan and spoke only to
Susan's 25-year-old stepdaughter-to-be. At the cake place, the
clerk asked Susan, ``Will your daughter be coming in to finalize
the plans?'' And at Crate &AMP; Barrel, the clerk said,  &UR; ``You  &LR; want to
register?''
</P>
<P>
   Susan just laughs. But I hope somebody tips off the preacher.
</P>
<P>
   NAPA WINE &AMP; Crafts Fair on Saturday, and Lotta Dotz says to look
for a lot of instant garage sales, too, and booths selling ``I
survived'' quakeshirts.
</P>
<P>
   I'm skipping the whole event this year. I prefer my wine
stirred, not shaken.
</P>
</TEXT>
