<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CANNIBALISM-ANASAZI-S     09-07 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNIBALISM-ANASAZI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TESTS SHOW CANNIBALISM AMONG ANCIENT ANASAZIS  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mysterious Anasazi people, whose long-abandoned dwellings
dot the harsh desert of the American Southwest, left few remains to
make their culture clear for modern archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes the strongest evidence yet that the Anasazi
practiced cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have found evidence that during a period of severe
drought some 850 years ago, an unknown raiding party swept through
several Anasazi villages in southwest Colorado, killing the
inhabitants, boiling their bones and eating their flesh. In one
case, the archaeological team found ancient human feces that
contained residues of human blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the entire community was extinguished in a single
episode of violence and terroristic cannibalism during a period of
social chaos brought on by the drought,'' says Brian R. Billman, an
archaeologist at the University of North Carolina who has studied
the Anasazi for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the people who settled in the Four Corners region a
thousand or more years ago were the ancestors of today's Hopi and
Zuni tribes, any hint of cannibalism grates on the sensitivity of
those Native Americans. As a result, the findings by Billman and
his colleagues are intensely controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an archaeologist retained by the Hopi tribe has already
quarreled sharply with the report, calling it ``a supposition
rather than a demonstrated fact.'' Kurt E. Dongoske of the Hopi
Tribe's Cultural Preservation Office said the evidence ``is
provocative but as yet unconvincing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dongoske, who dismisses the reports by Billman's group as ``a
smorgasbord of theoretical variables,'' maintains that the
scientists have deliberately ignored other theories suggesting that
the people whose bones were found might have been ritually executed
as witches _ a powerful taboo that still exists among people of the
Pueblos.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the bitter argument between the two rival groups of
scientists reached print recently in the respected journal
``American Antiquity.'' Thursday in the international journal
Nature, Billman's team is publishing what it claims is the first
direct biochemical evidence of cannibalism in prehistoric Anasazi
lands.
</P>
<P>
   In one site, among a small cluster of Anasazi villages on a
mountain slope called Cowboy Wash, near what is now the Colorado
town of Towaoc on the Ute Mountain Indian Reservation, Billman's
team found the remains of a community where three families had
lived centuries ago in pit houses for at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 35 adults and children were systematically butchered
there when all the villages were suddenly abandoned about 1150
A.D., Billman's group said. From the bodies of at least seven men,
women and children in one dwelling, the scientists found cracked
bones where flesh had been stripped, marrow sucked, and the bones
themselves boiled and roasted.
</P>
<P>
   In one ruined dwelling, the group found more than 1,000
fragments of bone that had been smashed into small pieces after the
flesh had been removed and the joints cut.
</P>
<P>
   And in the hearth of one small pit house, the archaeologists
also found a single coprolite, the scientific term for fossil
feces. The feces contains a protein, myoglobin, whose structure is
unique to human heart and muscle tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Marlar, a biochemist at the University of Colorado
Medical School, &LR;  who analyzed the coprolite, found that it contains
no evidence of digested vegetables like corn or beans, which he
said indicates that no other food was available to the invader who
must have defecated into the hearth.
</P>
<P>
   The Anasazi people of the Four Corners region lived a hard life
between about 700 and 1300 A.D. When the rains were good they
cultivated corn and beans and other crops, but the rains were
infrequent, forcing the Anasazi to move often, taking their meager
belongings with them.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboy Wash settlement, Billman said in an interview,
shows every evidence that the people there must have fled abruptly
in terror. They left behind the posts of dwellings, the tools and
ceramic cooking pots and other belongings that they normally would
have carried with them during a search for more fertile land.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows just who raided and terrorized the inhabitants of
Cowboy Wash, nor where they came from or where they went, Billman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what is most striking,'' he said, ``is that we have
captured only a single unique moment in time _ a sudden flareup
that apparently didn't last long, for we find no evidence of any
kind of cannibalism among the Anasazi or their descendants after
about 1200 A.D.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
