<HEADER>
A4816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-OPEN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Davenport ousts defending U.S. Open champ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By SCOTT KAISER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ A backhand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting one from your mom is a bad thing. Having it abandon you
on the tennis court is even worse.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case for defending women's champion Serena Williams
at the U.S. Open on Wednesday night as an ineffective two-hander
proved to be her downfall in a 6-4, 6-2 quarterfinal loss to 1998
champion Lindsay Davenport at Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, normally lethal with groundstrokes from both sides,
committed 17 errors with her backhand and had her five-match
winning streak against Davenport snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really hit my backhand or my forehand well, and I
wasn't serving well,'' Williams said. ``You can't afford to be off
your game against (Davenport), because she has a great all-around
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport didn't serve particularly well (making only 48 percent
of her first serves), but deep returns allowed her to put pressure
on Williams' service game.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth groundstrokes _ which she admitted were the best she's
hit since the Australian Open final _ helped Davenport dictate most
of the points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I did everything that I wanted to,'' said Davenport,
who lost to Williams in last year's final here. ``I'm sure she
didn't think she played well, but I thought I made her not play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The match was on serve in the ninth game of the first set before
Davenport broke through.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had two game points for a 5-4 lead, but Davenport came
up big with her forehand both times and then got the break when
Williams missed a pair of forehands. Williams then fought off a
pair of set points before missing a backhand _ her ninth such miss
to that point _ to give Davenport the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to hit to the same spot a lot of times, and a lot
of times once the first or second ball went there, I just stayed
with it and waited until the court opened up to go to her
forehand,'' said Davenport of her tendency to go to Williams'
backhand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I saw she was missing a few, I'm going to stay with that
game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams then double-faulted twice and missed two backhands,
including an unwise drop-shot attempt from the baseline, as she
squandered two game points and was broken in the first game of the
second set.
</P>
<P>
   After Davenport held, Williams blew three game points in the
third game and was broken again to dig herself into a 0-3 hole.
From that point on, Davenport took care of business, facing only
two break points over the remainder of the match.
</P>
<P>
   After squandering five match points in the seventh game on
Williams' serve, Davenport had two aces to give her match point,
and Williams _ surprise _ netted a backhand return to end the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disappointing that this was only the
quarterfinals, because it felt like a really big match,'' said
Davenport of the meeting between top-five seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Up next for Davenport in Friday's semifinals is unseeded
18-year-old Elena Dementieva, who ousted No. 10 Anke Huber 6-1,
3-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Although not blessed with the same press attention as fellow
Russian Anna Kournikova, the nearly-as-good-looking Dementieva has
shown more mental toughness and desire to improve.
</P>
<P>
   She has steadily climbed in the rankings (624th in 1996, 355th
in '97, 182nd in '98 and 62nd in '99) to the point where she will
crack the top 20 after this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's just amazing, because two years ago I watched
(Williams and Davenport) on TV,'' Dementieva said. ``I didn't think
I could play like I'm playing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her idol, Martina Hingis, Dementieva is a quick, smart
player who picks her spots. That was the case against Huber when
she rallied from a 2-0 deficit in the third set, thanks mostly to
aggressive returns on Huber's weak second serve.
</P>
<P>
   Dementieva won 22 of 35 points off Huber's second serve and
broke the German six times, including three times in the final set.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dementieva) plays smart and simple, maybe not like the other
18-year-olds who just hit the ball (hard),'' Huber said. ``She's a
very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
