<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FAR, FAR AWAY IN WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ This season _ much like the Los Angeles
Galaxy's five-year history _ has been about blown opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   You can add another to the list.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a win to have a mathematical chance to stay in the
Western Division race with Kansas City, the Galaxy's hopes were
dashed when Dallas handed it a 1-0 defeat before a crowd of 11,744
at the Rose Bowl on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the Galaxy folded again, the Wiz stepped up by defeating
New England 1-0 earlier in the evening to claim the West.
</P>
<P>
   While Dallas (13-14-4, 43 points) clinched a playoff berth with
the victory, all the Galaxy has left to play for is home-field
advantage in the first-round of the playoffs _ an unlikely scenario
now.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Chicago defeated Columbus 3-1 to wrap up the
Central Division, which means the Galaxy will face Mamadou Diallo
and the Tampa Bay Mutiny in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutiny (16-12-3, 51 points) leads the Galaxy (14-9-8, 50
points) by a point with one game remaining. For the Galaxy to
wrestle home-field advantage from the Mutiny, it must win Friday at
Colorado and hope that Kansas City wins or draws against the Mutiny
at Tampa Bay on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the way this season has gone for Los Angeles, the chances
seem slim.
</P>
<P>
   A sluggish first half came to life when Burn striker Ariel
Graziani broke loose down the left flank, sending a cross behind
Galaxy defender Greg Vanney for Jorge Rodriguez. The Salvadoran
striker's header found the left netting, beating Galaxy goalkeeper
Kevin Hartman for the game's only goal, in the 37th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy striker Luis Hernandez, quiet most of the night, was
heard when he called Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid and the rest of the
Galaxy subs off the bench in the 60th minute. He was protesting an
apparent trip of Hernandez by Dallas' Antonio Martinez in the
penalty area. However, referee Kevin Stott allowed play to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez nearly evened the score in the 81st minute. He took a
corner kick from Cobi Jones and tried to flick it past Dallas
goalkeeper Matt Jordan, whose quick reflexes preserved the lead.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first game without Galaxy Olympians Danny Califf,
Sasha Victorine and Peter Vagenas. They will all miss the first
round of the MLS playoffs and possibly the second if the U.S.
advances to the second round in Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT &LR;      09-07 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT TAKES OUT SERENA WILLIAMS TO REACH OPEN SEMIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Somewhere in the background of the hype, standing
well out of the swirl of attention, the unassuming Lindsay
Davenport and the mischief-making Martina Hingis were feeling a
little Williams-sister fatigue recently.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, the focus has been on the charismatic sisters
with the colorful style, public appeal and two Grand Slam titles
that, at some point, went through Davenport and Hingis. So there
was an innocent conversation recently, and a little joke between
the two women hidden behind Venus and Serena Williams. One of them
had to crash the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started last year, because I played the first semifinal
against Serena,'' said Davenport, referring to last year's U.S.
Open. ``Martina played Venus. She's like, `Well, you better win.'
So I lost. I saw her in the locker room. She was shaking her head
at me right before she played. Obviously, she won. This time she
said, `You're first again.'''
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was Davenport who was able to creep into the
airtight confidence of Serena Williams with unsettling blasts of
patience. By repeatedly pounding her ground strokes into the same
corners of the court, by luring Williams into gimmick shots as a
way to end the point, Davenport decoded her opponent's hold on her
with a 6-4, 6-2 quarterfinal victory inside a chilly Arthur Ashe
Stadium. Suddenly, the end came to Williams' chance to repeat as
the U.S. Open champion. Abruptly, the all-Williams final many
envisioned was in pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way a lot of people want it,'' Serena Williams said
after her loss. ``I'm sure a lot of people never want to see an
all-Williams final. It's going to happen in the future, inevitably.
Nobody's going to be able to stop it. Unfortunately, I didn't pull
my end up this year. I'm sure in the next Grand Slam I'm going to
do my utmost to make sure it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, no one would want to see an all-Williams final
because everyone doesn't really like us.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been tension in the locker room between the Williams
sisters and some of the other players on the women's Tour. Some see
them as polite, but aloof or arrogant. Some also view the sisters
as a threat to take over the Grand Slam events.
</P>
<P>
   But Davenport proved Wednesday night that she wouldn't be
intimidated. Although she had lost to Serena Williams in their last
five meetings, Davenport didn't flinch. As a result, she will meet
the unseeded Elena Dementieva in the semifinals Friday. The other
semifinal will feature Venus Williams against Hingis. Then, it will
be Hingis' turn to see if she can pull off a victory over a
Williams sister. No doubt, Davenport will be in Hingis' corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get along well,'' Davenport said of Hingis. ``She sides
with me against them. She's fun to joke with. Venus doesn't talk to
me much.''
</P>
<P>
   The silence will probably grow after Wednesday night's outcome.
Davenport was unshakable in her game plan against Serena Williams.
Davenport knew what she had to do. One short ball or mis-hit, one
passive second serve or ill-conceived drop shot, and Williams could
devour it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Williams was the one who covered the court with the
speed of ricochet while Davenport has more of jellyfish-like
languor to her movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get every ball, but if I try my hardest, and
physically I'm a hundred percent, I'm not the slowest thing out
there,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Davenport was vulnerable to the differences in
quickness. A confident Williams scampered toward every driving
ground stroke by Davenport and turned sure winners into amazing
gets. A steady Williams was also putting in her crushing first
serve at 78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment, Davenport looked overwhelmed, acting as if
she just wanted to stay in the point instead of dictating it. In
the second game of the match, Davenport had to fight off three
break points just to keep on serve. Williams had her chances, but
foreshadowed just how impatient she would become in this match.
</P>
<P>
   On her first break point, Williams tried to end a rally by
pulling out a backhand drop shot. After Williams whacked an
over-the-shoulder overhead well out, Davenport exhaled after
holding at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The threat was over, and the momentum turned. Suddenly, Williams
became overeager, and began whipping forehands 2 feet beyond the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   She also started a stream of desperate spinners and drop shots
until she found herself handing Davenport her first and only break
point of the first set in the ninth game.
</P>
<P>
   That was all Davenport needed. She served out the set. Williams
never recovered. In the end, she could only hold Davenport off for
so long. By yelping as she took swipes at the ball, Williams saved
five match points in a thrilling seventh game of the second set
that contained every theatrical version of a point.
</P>
<P>
   There was Williams, flicking her wrist like a short-order cook,
cracking strokes with great angles only to see Davenport answer by
putting balls into the corner of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was, Lindsay just played better than I did,''
Williams said. ``You can't afford to be on anything but your best
game in the quarterfinals of a Grand Slam.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
