<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AWAKES TO STOP KRAJICEK
</HEADLINE>
  (With TEN-USOPEN)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pete Sampras was staring across the net at the one
player who has been able to defuse his atomic serves with his own,
and the one opponent who has been able to emerge from their matches
with barely a scratch over the years.
</P>
<P>
   It was the steel-coated Richard Krajicek. He had taken six of
his last eight matches against Sampras, and put together a
head-to-head record no other active player has approached.
</P>
<P>
   For so long Wednesday night, inside a nervous Arthur Ashe
Stadium, Sampras looked as if he would succumb to Krajicek's
strange hold over him again. Sampras was in trouble after
sleepwalking through the first set, and was about to fall into the
abyss when he found himself down by 2-6 in the second-set
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting outplayed,'' Sampras said. ``I thought it was
going to get away from me. I got lucky. I don't know how I won
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Sampras pulled off a great escape on his way to a 4-6,
7-6 (6), 6-4, 6-2 quarterfinal victory Wednesday night at the U.S.
Open. The fourth-seeded Sampras, who will meet ninth-seeded Lleyton
Hewitt in a semifinal match on Saturday, felt fortunate to advance.
An unflappable Krajicek, who fired 23 aces to just eight by
Sampras, was serving for the set with his gaudy lead in the tie
breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you lose that tiebreaker,'' Krajicek said.
``I didn't do anything really wrong. I think he just did a good
job. There's nothing I can blame on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras recovered, in part, because of a mis-hit off a backhand
return of serve at 3-6 in the tiebreaker that turned into a point
to keep him alive. Sampras also pulled a half-volley out of his
hat, and conjured up a couple of tremendous responses to Krajicek's
powerful serve, including one forehand return that cracked right in
the corner for a winner. Krajicek looked on helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   After a run of five straight points to take the second set,
Sampras was pumping his fists as he walked to the changeover with
new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was meant to be that he would win that set,'' Krajicek
said. ``I guess it was his tiebreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   He was sensing a turnaround. The lethargic demeanor that Sampras
revealed early in the match vanished as the third set unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence rose,'' Sampras said. ``I knew I was back in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third set, Sampras put in 79 percent of his first serves.
In the fourth, he hit a solid 70 percent. There was little Krajicek
could do to force a break of serve when Sampras was pouring on such
force. Other than serving percentage _ and Krajicek was at 58
percent _ the statistics were almost even. Krajicek came up with 46
winners to Sampras' 49. Sampras had 19 unforced errors; Krajick had
16. But when it came to breaks of service, Sampras converted 4 of 6
opportunities while Krajicek was 2 of 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the way I played in the third and fourth set,''
Krajicek said. ``That's what's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he was revived by the second-set tiebreaker, Sampras was
dominant again, putting in 67 percent of his first serves. On match
point, Sampras whipped a service winner that bounded off the frame
of Krajicek's racket.
</P>
<P>
   A relieved Sampras had finally found a way to slip by the one
player who has been his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I needed to make a statement,'' Sampras said.
``It was a big match, and the fans were great. They really got
behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras needed their help, particularly in the second-set
tiebreaker. In some ways, Sampras was in a similar situation
against Patrick Rafter in the Wimbledon final. Once again, he was
down in the second-set tiebreaker, feeling the match slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Wimbledon,'' Sampras said. ``It was a matter of a
point here or there. I thought I was finished. I thought I was
gone. At Wimbledon, I thought I was just a few nails away in the
coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My will is always there, especially for a big match like
today. But I needed a little luck today. I thought it was going to
be a tough battle to come back. He was making me work hard, and he
was outplaying me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd been down two sets to love,'' Sampras said, ``it would
have been a tough hole to get out of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
