<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES PILLAGE DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Los Angeles Dodgers reacquired
right-hander Ismael Valdes in late July, they didn't bring him back
to be a world-beater, or even a pitcher who could provide eight or
nine wins in what they thought was a playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers went back to Valdes because they thought they had a
better chance to win with him starting instead of rookie Eric
Gagne. Well, the playoff race that was supposed to be heated is
frigid. And Valdes isn't having nearly the effect the Dodgers
thought he would.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes allowed four first-inning runs, which carried Pittsburgh
to a 8-3 win against the Dodgers on Wednesday and gave the Pirates
a three-game series sweep at Dodger Stadium. The Pirates outscored
the Dodgers 28-4 in the whitewashing.
</P>
<P>
   And Pittsburgh also kept Valdes winless since his return to the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now is whether Gagne would have provided better
starts, worse starts or merely similar starts to what Valdes has
done.
</P>
<P>
   After yielding five runs on eight hits and two walks in six
innings against Pittsburgh, Valdes' ERA stood at 6.08 since he
returned to the Dodgers. He's 0-3 and has reached the seventh
inning just once in eight starts. He was 2-4 with a 5.37 ERA with
the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne certainly had his problems with the Dodgers, including
having his turn pushed back in the rotation almost regularly. But
he did have some quality starts and was 1-6 with a 5.85 ERA before
being sent to Triple-A Albuquerque after Valdes joined the club.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four July deals in which contending teams acquired
pitchers, Valdes has fared the worst. That says something since
neither Arizona's Curt Schilling, Philadelphia's Andy Ashby nor the
Yankees' Denny Neagle has been dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, after a quick start, is 4-4 with a 3.77 ERA. Ashby is
4-5 with a 4.70 ERA and Neagle is 5-4 with a 5.04 ERA. Of course,
the Dodgers tried to get each of them in a trade but were told
every time they didn't have enough prospects even to be considered
as viable suitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were hoping Valdes would build some momentum coming
off his last start. He allowed one unearned run on three hits in
seven innings against Philadelphia, but, alas, there was no
carryover affect.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the previous night against lefty Carlos Perez, the
Pirates got to Valdes quickly. Adrian Brown led off with a single.
Jason Kendall flied out, but Brian Giles singled and John Vander
Wal made it 1-0 with a double to right. Enrique Wilson followed
with an RBI single to center field and, after Warren Morris walked,
Alex Hernandez singled to left to make it 3-0. Pat Meares'
sacrifice fly made it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The shell-shocked Dodgers, outscored 14-3 in the first two
innings of the series, saw the Pirates increase their lead to 5-0
in the second. Brown led off with a double and scored on Giles'
one-out single.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh lefty Dan Serafini, who was 1-3 with a 6.14 ERA, won
for the first time since Aug. 5. He allowed three runs on four hits
in 6 innings and was hurt by a pair of throwing errors in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers climbed to within 5-2 in the second when Gary
Sheffield scored on third baseman Wilson's wild throw to first.
Chad Kreuter's grounder, which turned into a throwing error by
Meares at shortstop, drove in the second run.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cora's team-leading sixth triple set up Kevin Elster's
pinch-hit RBI single in the seventh to make it 5-3. Tom Goodwin
singled to put two runners on, but Mark Grudzielanek struck out to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh made it 8-3 in the eighth off Dodgers reliever Mike
Fetters, pitching for the first time since Friday. Brown, Kendall
and Giles each had run-scoring singles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
