A4835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      09-07 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS GIVE RIVERA A REST AND PAY THE PRICE
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Boston could sweep this weekend and the New
York Yankees would still be in first place, so Manager Joe Torre
can afford to be judicious and take advantage of the growing
division lead. He began the process of reinstalling second baseman
Chuck Knoblauch into his lineup Wednesday night, and was intent on
resting the closer Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch did OK, making a couple of strong throws and going 0
for 4. But Rivera's temporary replacement bombed: Mike Stanton
emerged from the bullpen for the bottom of the ninth entrusted with
a 2-1 lead, and walked off the field disheartened minutes later, as
Kansas City players celebrated a 3-2 victory around him.
</P>
<P>
   If Knoblauch was Torre's most significant reclamation project
over the last week, he has been replaced by Stanton, whose problems
have lasted the better part of a month. ESPN silently filled the
face of a large-screen television after Wednesday night's game, and
just as Stanton was about to leave the clubhouse, he realized
highlights of the Yankees game were forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton pulled out a folding chair, sat with his forearms rested
against the back, and watched the whole, horrible inning unfold
again, sipping a bottle of water in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had taken a 2-0 lead, on solo home runs by Jeter (in
the fourth) and Paul O'Neill (in the sixth). Orlando Hernandez had
thrown 122 pitches in eight brilliant innings, killing a Kansas
City rally in his last inning by starting a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera pitched two innings Sunday, another inning Monday, and
Torre and the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre were determined to
give him two days off, back-to-back. There's nothing wrong with
Rivera, Torre said, other than being a little tired, and he will be
available to pitch here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Torre wanted to use Stanton again, to give him a
chance to emerge from his funk; Stanton gave up home runs in four
straight outings at the end of last month, then was not used for 10
days until pitching an inning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Stanton struck out the Royals' Carlos Beltran.
Kansas City manager Tony Muser inserted the right-handed-hitting
David McCarty as a pinch-hitter, with a right-handed hitter on
deck. Torre had the option of calling on the right-hander Jeff
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   But he stuck with the left-handed Stanton, who has been more
effective against right-handers, anyway. ``Heck, he got Sweeney and
Dye out last night,'' said Torre, referring to Mike Sweeney and
Jermaine Dye, the Royals' best hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton fell behind McCarty three balls and no strikes before
McCarty singled. Nelson leaned against the bullpen wall, arms
crossed. Carlos Febles ripped a doubled into the left-center-field
gap, and the pinch-runner Luis Ordaz scored the tying run from
first.
</P>
<P>
   With the left-handed-hitting Johnny Damon at the plate, Stanton
remained in the game, and Damon singled through the middle, scoring
Febles and setting off a Royals celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get a whole lot worse,'' Stanton said. ``Joe has the
confidence to send me out there in the ninth, and I fail. There's
no excuse for me going out there and doing that. I let the team
down, I let Duque down.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch played behind Hernandez for seven innings before being
replaced for defense, and somewhere, the Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner was smiling. Most of the owner's criticisms are
calculated _ the ``fat toad'' reference to Hideki Irabu last year
being an exception _ and when he inferred last week that
Knoblauch's elbow pain was fake, his intent was to prod the second
baseman back into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said he didn't need that motivation; he just wants to
play again, and he felt good. ``It was good,'' he said. ``On the
right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was the first position player in the Yankees' lineup
to emerge from the clubhouse in the half-hour before Wednesday
night's game, stretching his legs and going through a series of
sprints to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's notorious throwing jitters, active in June, are
mostly dormant in September, the fault line faded but still in
place. With Damon running from first on a pitch in the first
inning, Rey Sanchez chopped a grounder to second. Knoblauch fielded
the ball cleanly, briefly considered a flip to second before
setting himself, tapping the ball in his glove, stepping with his
left foot and throwing, hard and straight, all in perfect rhythm.
He had a couple of other chances, as well, attempting to finish two
double plays, looking a little awkward but always throwing the ball
straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
