A4837 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-NUDODG-LADN-(SLAN     09-07 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUDODG-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAS VALDES TIPPING HIS PITCHES?
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The cold, hard facts support the case of Los
Angeles Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter and right-handed pitcher
Ismael Valdes. But their revelation that Valdes was tipping off his
pitches in the four-run first inning of Pittsburgh's 8-3 win
Wednesday at Dodger Stadium drew reactions of surprise in the
Pirates clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was better than the atmosphere of confusion in
the Dodgers clubhouse, where the realization of getting pounded in
three games _ by a cumulative 28-4 score _ brought a sense of
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of six consecutive games, Pittsburgh had the
second-worst road record in the National League entering the
series. They're now 28-43 on the road while the Dodgers are 35-33
at home.
</P>
<P>
   The shell-shocked Dodgers were outscored 14-3 in the first two
innings of the series. On Wednesday, they watched Pittsburgh score
four times in the first inning and make it 5-0 when Adrian Brown
led off the second with a double, scoring on Brian Giles' one-out
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been inconsistent in every aspect of the game,'' Dodgers
shortstop Alex Cora said. ``Sometimes it's hard (to fall behind
early), but the same way they score runs, we can do it, too. And we
know we can do it. It's not like we're going to give up because
they score four runs, but it's hard. You look up and it's like,
`Wow, here we go again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers now trail the first-place San Francisco Giants by 10
games in the National League West. The playoff race has forgotten
them.
</P>
<P>
   But after getting pummeled by the Pirates for the third straight
game, the issue of ``paranoia or problem'' was raised after the
game in regards to Valdes tipping pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew what was coming and were taking advantage of it,
especially when he was pitching from behind,'' Dodgers catcher Chad
Kreuter said. ``We were mixing, and we weren't just throwing
fastballs in fastball counts. We were throwing breaking balls and
change-ups, and they were taking good swings at the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter said Valdes was manipulating his glove, which clued
which pitch was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't lie about it. I'd just say nothing,'' Pittsburgh
manager Gene Lamont said. ``I never heard anybody in the dugout say
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then how does one account for what transpired? The Pirates
scored four times in the first inning on five hits and two of the
outs recorded came on balls hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was tipping them, I didn't get it from anybody,'' said
Giles, who went 3 for 5 with two RBI. ``For the most part he
pitched OK, but the few mistakes he made we were able to put in
play and find some holes. Maybe Chad saw something that he did, but
I wasn't aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who is 0-3 with a 6.08 ERA since rejoining the Dodgers
in late July, said once he stopped wiggling his glove and tipping
pitches, the Pirates were unable to do anything against him.
</P>
<P>
   After the first inning, the Pirates managed one run and three
hits. At one point, Valdes retired nine consecutive batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I was making good pitches, but at times it looked
like they knew what was coming,'' Valdes said. ``I made the
adjustment and after the first inning it was tremendous and they
didn't touch me. I felt much better and I got in a nice rhythm.
You're doing your best, but when you know what's coming, it's
easier to hit the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Valdes is tipping his pitches, it would be the
best explanation as to why a guy who had a 61-54 record and a 3.38
ERA entering the season is 2-7 with a 5.64 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
