<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 09:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-CO     09-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Stamp out ``going postal''
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 10, 2000.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All along I knew that Patty the Postal Lady was not a latent
killer. Patty delivers the mail to my house. Often, we chat.
Sometimes about the rock music she has bellowing from the portable
radio in her little truck, sometimes about other things. But I
never envisioned that one troubled day she would show up back at
the post office, automatic weapon in hand, and rat-a-tat-tat a
bunch of co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did I think the same of the guy who subs for her on days
off.
</P>
<P>
   I was relieved to read last week that an independent commission
has determined statistically that postal workers are no more likely
to blow each other away, to sexually harass or to verbally abuse
than do hamburger flippers at McDonald's, stock clerks at Home
Depot or National Football League players. (Wait a second; I'm not
that sure about the NFL guys.)
</P>
<P>
   The study, done by Columbia University's National Center on
Addiction and Substance Abuse, determined that postal workers were
``less angry, aggressive, hostile, depressed and stressed'' than
the average American worker.
</P>
<P>
   There were statistics, such as cab drivers are 150 times more
likely to be killed on the job than postal workers. Somewhat
lacking is that the study didn't say if that meant cabbies were 150
times more likely to be killed on the job by other taxi drivers,
which has been the stereotype of postal workers these days.
</P>
<P>
   Leading to this has been the growing apprehension among the
workers themselves, inasmuch as there have been a reported 26
incidents among them since 1986 in which 54 people were murdered.
It made for big headlines, tough jokes and an awful sense of
insecurity within the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   The expression ``going postal'' has crept into our spoken tongue
to describe someone who has gone berserk, but the study shows that
``going postal'' means little more than slapping a stamp onto an
envelope and dropping it into the blue box.
</P>
<P>
   Will the perception evaporate with this conclusion? Likely not.
There are some observations, statistical or otherwise, that just
fail to go away.
</P>
<P>
   We media types rarely let a provocative label vanish. Possibly
because of a prior relationship, I've always been irked by
newspaper articles and headlines that exclaim that an ex-Marine has
killed someone or otherwise committed a serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   You know, something like: Ex-Marine, 87, Kills Girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The guy likely was a Marine between the ages of 20 and 23, then
became a college student, maybe an insurance salesman, possibly a
school teacher, then a retiree but, for the story and headline
writers, he always will be a Marine. Why? Well, because Marines are
taught to kill; right? And there was a killing. So there always is
that editorial connection. And, besides, it makes for better
reading.
</P>
<P>
   How stimulating is the headline: Ex-insurance salesman, 87,
Kills Girlfriend?
</P>
<P>
   It is astonishing that with all the serial and other prominent
killers this nation has produced, the few unbalanced postal workers
become the model for out-of-control madmen. Why couldn't somebody
be ``going Bundy,'' as in Ted Bundy; or ``going Gacy,'' as in John
Wayne Gacy? (And will unacceptable sexual encounters ever come to
be known as ``going Clinton?'')
</P>
<P>
   Alas, and despite the statistical clearance by the independent
commission, the ``going postal'' expression likely will remain with
us for a while, to be used by stand-up comics, writers and the
young crowd as a synonym for the previous generational depiction,
``going bonkers.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time I ever used that term was in the '70s, to
describe Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini. I didn't even know what
``bonkers'' meant, just that everyone was using the term. I looked
it up. The dictionary defined ``bonkers'' as being an obsolete
military slang adjective to mean ``to bomb,'' also ``crazy, mad.''
To me, that fit Khomeini, so I used it.
</P>
<P>
   Likely something will happen down the road to create another
expression that will replace ``going postal'' as a trendy
definition of a mad act but for the time being, and despite its
statistical clearance, its a painful, unfair part of the lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
