<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There must be a reason most Texans move in August
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   T.S. Eliot wrote that April was the cruelest month. He never
visited Texas in August.
</P>
<P>
   One joke going around is that the devil was thinking about
moving hell to Texas but decided it was too hot.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only month of the year when I entertain fantasies
about returning to New Hampshire. A fellow expatriate from New
England recently returned from several weeks in Vermont. New
England is having the coolest, wettest summer in recent memory.
High temperatures there were barely above our lows. The natives
were complaining about the cool, wet weather.
</P>
<P>
   Come to Texas in August, Yankee folks. Stay a few weeks. You'll
never complain about cool weather in August again.
</P>
<P>
   I will admit winters in New England are worse than the summers
in Texas and last longer. Besides, you can't find decent barbecue
up North. I'm staying put, but upon retirement I guarantee you'll
find me somewhere cool every summer, even if I have to get a paper
route.
</P>
<P>
   Thank the Lord August is over, though the heat wave is still
very much with us. Now that it's September, at least one can see an
end to this madness, though the high on Sept. 1 was somewhere north
of 105 degrees. But soon it will be October, and temperatures will
again be tolerable, though probably not what normal people would
call cool. There is hope, my friends.
</P>
<P>
   My little brother called me a few weeks ago and said it's
payback time. He's building a new house outside of Dallas and sold
his old one, so he had to move his family into an apartment and put
most of their stuff in storage. Call it kin karma. In my younger
years, I leaned on my father, brothers and friends to help with
many moves. Now that hopefully I'm staying put, they're calling in
their chits. Plus, I have two daughters just now entering the
young-adult moving cycle, and I can count on at least one of them
moving annually for the next 10 years or so, until they get settled
and start producing grandbabies.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of all moves made in Texas are made in August. Of
the 30 of so moves I've made, all but a handful were in the summer,
and most of those were in the dog days. It's as if Texans sit
around trying to figure out a way to make their lives even more
miserable. ``I know, let's move 10 tons of stuff while the
temperature is 104 degrees. That'll be fun!''
</P>
<P>
   There was the added dubious benefit of my brother living in
Dallas, which has gone more than two months without rain and is the
second-hottest large city in America, next to Phoenix. Think it's
hot here behind the Pine Curtain, where at least most of the land
isn't covered in concrete or asphalt? Try Dallas. The trees in
Dallas are hoping dogs mistake them for a fire hydrant. It's even
too hot for the fireants, most of whom have migrated to East Texas
for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike me, my brother has never been divorced, and I hope never
will. The only good thing I can attribute to divorce is that it
definitely lightens your load of worldly possessions, especially if
you have a couple decrees under your belt. The upshot of all this
is that my brother has more stuff than several small Third-World
countries. There are boxes upon boxes of stuff, some of which has
remained unpacked for the last several moves. If there is a prize
for most stuff accumulated by one middle-class human being, he's in
the running. I was vigorously expounding the virtues of annual
garage sales to him by the time we had filled a storage unit and an
entire garage with stuff, crammed a three-bedroom apartment full
and still had a pile of possessions left in the old house by the
time darkness fell and exhaustion set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you sell some of this worthless (expletive
deleted)?'' I believe is what I screamed. Sorry. This outburst came
after I had made my fourth trip to the storage building with my
flatbed trailer full of boxes containing such valuable items as my
old slot-car racetrack and old Boy Scout uniforms. Why he has them,
I have no idea, other than my mother had failed to foist them upon
me. I am not much of a sentimentalist.
</P>
<P>
   I survived the move and actually lost a few pounds even while
drinking gallons of water and Gatorade. Now, as the sprinkler runs
at night and keeps the city flush in cash when I pay my water bill,
I doze in the recliner and pretend it's raining when the water hits
the window outside my study. Raining, cold, gray skies and a harsh
northern wind. What a pleasant thought.
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches (Texas)
Daily Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
