<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-FAULT (San Francisco) _ The gentle-looking hills of
Northern California may forever hide the identity of the dark force
a previously unknown earthquake fault that shook Napa County over
the weekend. Experts have yet to identify the exact location of the
fault, and may never be able to if it's buried miles beneath the
surface, said leading quake authority William Ellsworth of the U.S.
Geological Survey. The quake caused more than 70 injuries, mostly
minor, and at least $15 million in damages. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   INSECTICIDE-HUMANS (San Francisco) _ Pesticide Action Network, a
San Francisco-based environmental group, is formally introducing
the first comprehensive online database on the health hazards of
more than 5,100 ingredients in Sevin and other home and garden
pesticides. ``Most people think that if the EPA allows a pesticide
to be sold, it must be safe to use,'' said Susan Kegley, a staff
scientist at the network. ``Unfortunately, that's not true, and
finding out whether a particular pesticide is linked to cancer,
birth defects or other problems can be extremely difficult.'' By
JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   PROP-209 (San Francisco) _ Civil rights groups that hoped to
preserve the remnants of affirmative action after Proposition 209
appear to be headed for disappointment from the California Supreme
Court. The court took up the major unresolved legal question about
the 1996 ballot measure _ whether a government agency can target
minorities and women in recruitment, without promising favorable
treatment in jobs or contracts _ and showed little doubt about the
answer. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   IRANIAN-DEPORT (San Francisco) _ A federal appeals court has
barred the deportation of an Iranian who worked on a clandestine
translation of Salman Rushdie's ``The Satanic Verses,'' then fled
Iran before his colleague was tortured to death. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-CHILDREN (San Francisco) _ Baby boomers have grown up
mocking their parents for staying together ``for the sake of the
children,'' but that may be the healthier alternative to divorce,
if a small but in-depth study is on target. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Some people who are aghast at
bigotry put their righteous indignation on hold when it comes to
dot-commers. In the land of political correctness, it seems to be
all right to say that dot-commers clog the streets and drive up
housing prices and ruin it for REAL Bay Area residents (like us)
even though you would be labeled a racist if you made the same
comments about any ethnic group. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-EMAIL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Teen-agers used to while their time
on the telephone. Nowadays they are wrapped up in instant messages,
or ``IMs.'' Popularized by market leader America Online, they are
the stuff of enthusiastic and lengthy, late-night on-line
conversations that start with ``Hey, what's up?'' _ or SUP _ and
end several hours later. By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   FASH-VAMP (Undated) _ By day, best dressed women this fall will
turn up the heat with deep shades of red, sensual blouses and
fishnet stockings. By evening, they tempt fate with the likes of
plunging necklines and body-hugging liquid satin goddess gowns. So
is the lady a tramp or a vamp? By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   FASH-GOLD (Undated) _ Gold, real or faux, is the hottest trend
for fall and winter. From jeans to jewelry, glittering gold is the
way to go, but don't ditch your silver jewelry yet. By LINDA GILLAN
GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   With: FASH-ACCESSORIES4
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NURSEBETTY-REVIEW (Undated) _ When a traumatic event shocks
her into a psychotic episode, a waitress (Renee Zellweger) goes in
search of the handsome doctor (Greg Kinnear) on her favorite soap
opera, not realizing two hit men (Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock)
are looking for her in ``Nurse Betty.'' By ERIC HARRISON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-OPPORTUNISTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A former safe-cracker
(Christopher Walken) lets his pride and ``friends'' back him into a
corner, and he tries for another score. Cyndi Lauper and Peter
McDonald co-star in ``The Opportunists.'' By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WATCHER-REVIEW (Undated) _ The serial-killer merry-go-round
begins again in the ``Watcher,'' a yarn about an FBI agent (James
Spader) who's burned out after years of chasing serial killers,
only to face yet another (Keanu Reeves). Marisa Tomei and Ernie
Hudson co-star. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CATFISH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Twenty-two years after they
adopt two Vietnamese babies, an American couple finds their world
upset when the kids locate their biological mother and bring her to
the United States. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOYERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ An interview with Bill Moyers about
his documentary miniseries on death in America, ``On Our Own Terms:
Moyers on Dying,'' which begins Sunday on PBS. By MIKE McDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-OLYMPICS (Undated) _ The Olympic Games are television's baby.
But the network of 2000, NBC, isn't much of a parent. The Sydney
Games will be stuck in lockdown, on a rigid schedule. NBC plans to
show nothing live. Instead, the network will present premier events
roughly 17 hours after they have ended. The network insists on
treating this global spectacle as an extension of its entertainment
division. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
