<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4987 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TEENS-EMAIL-HNS &LR;      09-07 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-EMAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHAT'S UP? FOR TEENS, NIGHTS OF INSTANT CYBER CHATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last week, still summer's halcyon days of Britney
Spears, tennis and sleeping in, 14-year-old Caitlin Orlofsky and
her friends caught up on it all, in a conversation punctuated by
LOLs.
</P>
<P>
   The abbreviation, for Laugh Out Loud, also signifies the fun,
busy social lives of teen-agers who straddle the real world and
cyberspace, by sending instant messages in real-time computer
discussions that may make their parents reminisce about the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   IMs _ ``instant messages'' popularized by market leader America
Online _ are the stuff of enthusiastic and lengthy, late-night
on-line conversations that start with ``Hey, what's up?'' _ or SUP
_ and end several hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty addicted to it,'' said Brent Ruhle, 14, of Ballston
Spa, N.Y. ``Most of my friends use it. Since they use it, it's a
lot easier to talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruhle has used AOL instant messaging for about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Orlofsky, alerted by a friend to instant messages about six
months ago, also has become an avid user, filling her ``Buddy
List'' to the maximum, with the screen names of 160 friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy way to stay in touch,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the teen-age pastime _ these long dialogues, they say,
are about the day's events, plans for the week, playing on-line
games or just goofing around _ is Internet growth on par with the
rise of e-mail several years back, analysts have reported.
Approximately 90 million America Online subscribers, as well as
users who can download the AOL's free Instant Messenger, daily send
approximately 650 million instant messages, said AOL spokeswoman
Jane Lennon.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, according to news reports, has repeatedly blocked rival
companies, such as MSN and AT&AMP;T, from letting their customers
access the massive network, citing the privacy and security of AOL
members.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike e-mail, instant messaging allows a quick volley of
real-time conversation. Messages are heralded by dialogue boxes on
the computer screen or by customized sounds, and depending on the
computer, participants can speak through microphones.
</P>
<P>
   While instant messaging has existed since the 1980s, several
recent features have helped propel its word-of-mouth popularity.
</P>
<P>
   AOL in 1996 created the Buddy List, the prepared list of social
groups, like family members or the soccer team, that also alerts
users when the people on their personal list are on line. ``What it
really did was bring an element of community to what was a solitary
on-line experience,'' Lennon said. AOL in 1997 introduced the free
Instant Messenger. The free service is ``an extension of our brand
and it's an enormous value for our existing members,'' Lennon said,
since it widens their on-line circle to non-subscribing friends.
</P>
<P>
   In February, AOL also announced the launch of a mobile service
that will allow subscribers to access the Internet, instant
messaging and e-mail through wireless phones and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   In sending IMs, teen-agers demonstrate the computer dexterity
for which they've become famous, carrying on a chat with up to 20
people, as Orlofsky does, and at other times, doing their homework,
while exchanging messages about weekend plans or talking to their
working parents.
</P>
<P>
   Some caution: Several teen-agers who use instant messaging
demonstrated caution about releasing too much information about
themselves or talking to strangers on line.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin Orlofsky simply finds it more fun to talk to her
friends. Brent Ruhle uses different screen names. He occasionally
receives messages from strangers, who presumably have found him via
a Buddy List feature that seeks out people with similar interests.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Sims, 14, of Ballston Spa, said that at one site he meets
fellow enthusiasts of the on-line game Star Craft, who then gather
around their computers to message each other about results. His
profile, though, is filled with song lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin's parents, Susan and Paul, are mindful of her on-line
conversations and feel the need to double-check how her friendships
are formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always asking her, `How did you meet that kid?''' Susan
Orlofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL does offer a system of controls that allows parents to limit
the sending and receiving of instant messages and e-mail, as well
as access to chats, Lennon said. The free Instant Messenger offers
built-in privacy preferences, such as blocking select messages,
though parents obviously would need to be aware that their child
had downloaded the service.
</P>
<P>
   Other young people have heard their parents' urgings to get off
of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me I spend too much time on it, but I have other
things, like football and stuff, so that I get away from the
computer,'' Brent Ruhle said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Incessant instant messaging may ease as teenagers age.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Potente, now 17, visiting the Orlofskys one afternoon at
their Ballston Spa home, recalls the hours he spent
instant-messaging with some disdain. ``This is how I used to be
talking to people _ about nothingness,'' Potente said of ``What's
up?'' banter. His computer use is now more specific, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhle sees the point. At first, he'd battle his family for
maximum computer time. ``After a while you get bored with it and
realize you've got to go out and do other things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
