<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      09-07 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFRONTING THE WORLD'S PROBLEMS IN THE BACKYARD
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   When Janet and Jim bought their
lovely old house in downtown Santa Rosa, Calif., they were thrilled
to be on a creek. This is an area where Santa Rosa Creek runs free,
not confined to concrete.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful,'' says Janet. ``We were in the middle of
town and we had mallard ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   As well, down by the creek they had large twisted oak trees,
thick bushes and green hollows. Janet and Jim imagined an idyllic
picnic spot and a place for kids to skip rocks and catch pollywogs.
They didn't imagine a homeless encampment.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are strangers living along the creek, at the end of
their property, past their gardens and down the hill. If you had
nowhere to sleep and knew you'd be rousted in a park or chased off
the steps of a storefront, you might covet such a peaceful, pretty
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Janet and Jim provided a tour one afternoon when the place was
empty of people but dotted with bags of food and clothing,
mattresses, pillows, sleeping bags, magazines, an office chair, a
stack of couch cushions.
</P>
<P>
   Janet spots something propped up in a bush and pulls out a
crutch. ``Now this makes me want to cry,'' she says, which shows
how much sympathy is mixed in with frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Janet says her inclination, at one time, would have been to say,
``Poor homeless people. Leave them alone.''
</P>
<P>
   But now she's living the problem and worried about threats to
her child, her dog and her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a liberal,'' she says. ``But when it affects you and your
property the issue goes deeper than your politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you live in the country, like I do, and consider street
people a fact of urban life. But they're not an acceptable fact.
Occasionally street people come too close to those who live in
houses and there are confrontations. Shelters and group homes are
proposed for the homeless, the addicted, the mentally ill, and
people who live in the neighborhood protest.
</P>
<P>
   They're commonly known as NIMBYs _ people who say, ``not in my
back yard,'' regarding a facility they don't want to see move in
next door or down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Janet and Jim literally fit the label, because it is their
personal backyard which has become an unauthorized campground. It
is difficult to tell how many people sleep there, although last
week there appeared to be at least four separate sites scattered in
the trees and bushes. Of course, people don't just sleep there.
They eat there and go to the bathroom there and when the night
cools, they often make fires there.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Janet believe in taking care of the less fortunate. They
donate to the Food Bank. They've given money to people on the
street. But they feel like they've given enough. An incredulous Jim
said one cop even told him they could be liable if one of the
uninvited got hurt on their property.
</P>
<P>
   Janet says, ``I think if the city cannot provide a shelter then
maybe it has to let people sleep on public property.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked a woman who advocates for the homeless what she'd do if
people moved into her yard and she shakes her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dilemma. Sometimes I feel like a hypocrite because
where I personally live it's not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet and Jim have posted ``No Trespassing'' signs, which don't
last long. They have a big dog. They're installing flood lights,
even though they doubt they'll last any longer than the signs.
They've fenced off most of their yard but can't fence all the way
to the creek because the waterline changes dramatically when it
rains.
</P>
<P>
   They call the police when they see trespassers. Officers come by
and look to see if there's any drug use or criminal activity and
usually end up telling the campers to move on. But either the same
ones sneak back or new people discover the spot. Their house has
not been broken into. Nor have they been accosted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lay there imagining all kinds of things,'' says Janet.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's more the threat of what might happen that makes
them uneasy and, yes, resentful. That's gotten worse as their child
became old enough to play outside and have friends over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to train a child so early about watching out for
strangers,'' laments Janet. ``You can't let them go to public parks
or walk to school alone, but at least you consider your backyard a
safe haven.''
</P>
<P>
   The creek stays pretty quiet during the day but around
dinnertime there are voices. Sometimes late at night there is
arguing and cursing. Sometimes there's the smell of marijuana and
wood smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Janet tries to be understanding. ``At first I thought, `There
but for the grace of God go I.' I know people have unforeseen
circumstances and sometimes no place to go. But I hate feeling
uncomfortable in my own home.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple has been tempted to move, but there's an issue, says
Janet. If they listed their house for sale they'd have to disclose
an existing problem in the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
