<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     09-07 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGAL MILESTONE DESTINED FOR THE DOGHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   News item: A group of lawyers has
founded the Great Apes Legal Project in hopes of extending basic
legal protections to primates and, possibly, other animals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prosecutor: Buster Grimes? Would you please take the stand?
</P>
<P>
   Buster: (Sneeze)
</P>
<P>
   Clerk: Do you promise to tell the truth, the whole truth and
nothing but the truth, so help you God?
</P>
<P>
   Buster: (Scratch)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor: Isn't it true, Buster, that your owner has forced
you to eat from a bowl on the floor for the past four years and
compelled you to perform your business in the back yard for all the
world to see without even giving you a magazine to read?
</P>
<P>
   Buster: (Snoring)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor: And isn't it also true, Buster, that your owner has
called you insulting names when you bark at TV doorbells; gives you
only the toughest, gristliest remnants of his steak dinner and will
not share the pillow with you when you sleep in his bed?
</P>
<P>
   (Last accusation brings audible gasp of shock and disbelief from
jury.)
</P>
<P>
   Buster: (Wet snuffling)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor: Have there not also been times, Buster, when your
owner has left you alone in the house and forgotten to turn on the
classical music station you like so much to keep you company? And
that these long afternoons without Debussy and Rachmaninoff
sometimes leave you feeling detached and dislocated with subtle
shadings of ennui?
</P>
<P>
   Buster: (Licking)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor: Buster, would you please tell the court how your
owner addresses these unfulfilled yearnings of the soul, this pit
of existential dread in which he forces you to wallow day after
meaningless day? Does he take you in for counseling? Does he enroll
you in a 12-step program? Does he encourage you to call in to Dr.
Laura?
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen of the jury, it appears that Buster cannot
speak right now. Perhaps the trauma has been too great. Perhaps the
words are too painful to utter. Perhaps it is just a flea. No
matter. As his advocate and counselor, I can answer this question
for him: Buster and his owner play tug-of-war with a sock!
</P>
<P>
   (Loud sobbing from jury box. A woman faints, briefly
interrupting testimony.)
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor: That is right, ladies and gentlemen. The owner's
answer to all problems besetting this poor, mistreated,
emotionally-starved dog is to make him pull on a sock.
</P>
<P>
   And not just any sock, ladies and gentlemen, but a dirty sock.
One that has been on the owner's foot during a five-hour round of
golf in August or while he was mowing the lawn. He invites his dog
to put this fetid thing in his mouth and Buster, a classic
co-dependent, obeys.
</P>
<P>
   What comes next I can hardly bear to describe. The owner tugs on
the sock so hard that Buster is occasionally lifted off his feet.
Buster growls and shakes his head _ ``No! No! Please stop! You are
not addressing my needs!'' _ but Buster's owner pays no heed. The
game continues until the sock is stretched hopelessly out of shape
or Buster's owner grows tired, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Buster's soul is still crying out for help but now he has sock
threads stuck between his teeth, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Something flies out of the jury box and hits Buster's owner in
the back of the head, knocking him unconscious. It is a heavy
refrigerator-magnet with the message ``Dogs Are People, Too.'')
</P>
<P>
   (Recess.)
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
