<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LATIN-MUSIC (New York) _ Turn the dial on your radio three
times these days, and chances are you will tune in to at least one
Latin artist, whether it's Marc Anthony, Jennifer Lopez or Carlos
Santana. New York City has long been a crucible for the
Latin-American music now known as salsa. The city also wins credit,
in many quarters, for transforming big-band mambo. And it lays
claim to Cubop, a fusion of be-bop's brass and Afro-Cuban
percussion. Some music historians even say New York is responsible
for the various dance crazes that went along with Latin music
forms, like the cha-cha in the 1950s and the pachanga a decade
later. By Nina Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-PUPPET-THEATER (New York) _ On Ronnie Burkett's ``Street
of Blood,'' the ambitious, exhaustingly told tale of anger and
intolerance in rural Canada, and Burkett's touring Theater of
Marionettes, based in Alberta. By Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-WOMEN-GUGGENHEIM (New York) _ On ``Amazons of the
Avant-Garde,'' the exhibition of paintings by six Russian women
from around the time of the Russian Revolution, all of whom were
modern painters at a moment of incredible upheaval. By Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   ATWOOD-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ On Margaret Atwood's absorbing
new novel, ``The Blind Assassin,'' which features a story within a
story within a story _ a science-fiction yarn within a hard-boiled
tale of adultery within a larger narrative about familial love and
dissolution. Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (Undated) _ The opening of the French social
season begins on Tuesday, when more than 90,000 international
collectors _ from the Prince of Lichtenstein and the Princess of
Kent to Baroness Philippine de Rothschild and Quentin Tarantino _
are expected to congregate for a two-week extravaganza of openings,
parties and special events connected to the 20th edition of the
Biennale International des Antiquaires, the Super Bowl of antiques
fairs. By Wendy Moonan.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Filmed with unassuming realism,
beautiful to look at even as it refuses any suggestion of
stylishness, ``It All Starts Today,'' the latest film from Bertrand
Tavernier, is a passionate and relentless look at how chronic
unemployment _ with the usual side effects of alcoholism, domestic
abuse and pervasive despair _ menace the lives of children.
Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   SOLAS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Solas,'' a sober Spanish film by
Benito Zambrano, is pointedly antithetical in spirit to the zany,
sexually charged antics of Pedro Almodovar and his imitators. It
quietly tells the story of every mother who has ever watched a
grownup child stumble through life, swallowed her sadness and
disapproval and did what she could to help. Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
