<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-OLYMPICS-HNS &LR;      09-07 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NBC HOLDS THE OLYMPICS HOSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sports writers who went to the Munich Olympics
in 1972 love to tell this story. They were covering the usual
favorites of the Games _ track and field, swimming, boxing. Their
editors, tuned into what the American public was watching back
home, called and ordered up features on the phenomenon of the
Games, a tiny gymnast from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The sportswriters, so close to the action, were baffled. ``Who's
Olga Korbut?'' they asked.
</P>
<P>
   Korbut was television's baby. Before ABC, the Olympic network in
'72, put her on the air, gymnastics wasn't treated as a real sport
in the American media. But then Korbut was beamed into living rooms
around the country, and the audience was utterly smitten. Four
years later, Americans would be equally captivated by a Romanian
teen-ager, Nadia Comaneci.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of the Cold War, Americans cheered for two young
women who learned their back flips behind the Iron Curtain. ABC had
helped the Olympics accomplish their stated, but often elusive,
mission. Watching Korbut on the balance beam brought the world
together.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Games are still, like Korbut, television's baby. But
the network of 2000, NBC, isn't much of a parent. The Sydney Games
will be stuck in lockdown, on a rigid schedule.
</P>
<P>
   NBC plans to show nothing live. Not a dash by Marion Jones, not
a vault by Amy Chow.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of immediacy, in the Internet world, NBC will present
premier events roughly 17 hours after they have ended. The network
insists on treating this global spectacle as an extension of its
entertainment division.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the time-zone difference creates a huge problem. The
marquee events in Sydney will start at about 4 a.m. in the Eastern
United States. But only one thing prevents NBC from showing the
events live and then repeating them in a prime-time broadcast
later. And it isn't concern about compounding America's
sleep-deprivation crisis. The bulk of the audience might choose to
videotape the live version and edit out the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   So even though NBC and its two cable affiliates will be putting
on countless hours of programming from Sydney, viewers will have to
follow the old ritual of covering ears and eyes to avoid news from
the Games before they can get home to see the events on television.
</P>
<P>
   America Online conducted an informal survey of its members and
learned that 75 percent did not want results from the Olympics
before NBC had shown the event. AOL will have try to keep the
results off its main screen.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Olympic motto of ``Faster, stronger, higher'' should
probably give way to one from the TV age: ``Don't tell me. Don't
tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   My newspaper learned just how much TV controls the Olympics and
their audiences after the Nagano Games in 1998. My mailbox was full
of nasty notes, including a memorable mother-daughter missive that
said: ``CBS must want to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   My capital crime was reporting that Tara Lipinski had upset
Michelle Kwan for the women's figure skating gold.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper hit the street several hours before CBS fit the
event into its prime-time schedule, the perfect showcase for
Coca-Cola commercials, if not Lipinski's triple Lutz.
</P>
<P>
   I understood why the letter-writers were upset. In the years
when I didn't cover the Games, I avoided hearing results, too.
</P>
<P>
   But after listening for years to colleagues deride
figure-skating as a nonsport, as something that should be relegated
to the features pages, I believe that the Games must be treated as
breaking news. It's disrespectful to the contestants to do anything
less.
</P>
<P>
   It's also disrespectful to the audience. In this country,
Olympic viewing is heavily female, and the event is packaged
accordingly, with soft-focus features. The assumption seems to be
that women won't appreciate sports as sports. The show has to be
gussied up for them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of NBC's features end up being excellent, but the network
condescends to its viewers by making them watch the Olympic Games
strictly in that through-the-Cuisinart format.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Canadian television will offer live feeds to its
audience, an unnerving prospect for the American network. In border
states, Americans will be able to watch live, and satellite dishes
could allow another end-run around the peacock network.
</P>
<P>
   And some newspapers will have same-day coverage of events,
beating the network's presentation. If this ruins anyone's fun, I
apologize. I am sincerely sorry that NBC has the Olympics in
lockdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
