<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-NURSEBETTY0908     09-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-NURSEBETTY0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frank Capra optimism, philosophic hit men and twists make 'Nurse
Betty' a hit.
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Spunky, sunny Betty Sizemore is a swell
diner waitress, but don't expect much service from her while the
hospital soap opera ``A Reason to Love'' is on the air. Betty
(Renee Zellweger) is fixated on that show and on that dashing
do-gooder, Dr. David Ravell (Greg Kinnear), its leading character.
</P>
<P>
   So it is almost logical _ or as logical as the nutty, yet sweet
``Nurse Betty'' gets _ that when she witnesses the scalping and
killing of her philandering, abusive husband Del (Aaron Eckhart) by
a pair of professional hit men, Betty loses touch with reality and
tumbles down a rabbit hole into the world of soaps. Convinced that
she is Dr. David's ex-fiancee, she treks from Kansas to Los Angeles
to reunite with him, followed by the assassins (Morgan Freeman and
Chris Rock, an inspired pairing), who are after Del's drug stash.
</P>
<P>
   The joys of ``Nurse Betty'' are its yin and yang of abrupt
Quentin Tarantino violence and philosophy-spouting bad guys, mixed
with the innocent optimism of Frank Capra. The surprise is that
this audience-friendly juggling act comes from director Neil
LaBute, previously known for such nasty, misogynistic films as ``In
the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and Neighbors.'' The last
thing you would expect from him is an Oz-like odyssey with such a
radiant, albeit delusional, Dorothy Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those earlier LaBute movies were composed of inert,
talky two-character exchanges, but he demonstrates his assurance
here with complex set-ups, crowd scenes and the glossy sheen made
possible by a higher budget. While it is an easy target to spoof
soap operas, notice what carefree fun LaBute has with these
television sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, this is the first of his films that LaBute did
not write. Much of the credit goes to rookie screenwriters John C.
Richards and James Flamberg, whose frequently inspired plot twists,
tongue-in-cheek dialogue and evident affection for their characters
keep the movie from turning dour.
</P>
<P>
   Never doubt that soap operas are educational, however, for Betty
is able to fake being a nurse just from watching ``A Reason to
Love.'' She demonstrates her triage skills during a hospital
parking lot shoot-out and later caringly ministers to patients on
the sly. When she eventually meets the actor who plays Dr. David,
she relates to him in character, which he takes to be a skilled
improvisational audition. Amused and impressed, he offers her a
chance to be on the soap, which leads her to a sobering collision
with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Zellweger may well be Hollywood's millennial answer to Doris
Day, with wholesome good looks and a gentle comic flair. ``Nurse
Betty,'' a better vehicle for Zellweger than the more mean-spirited
``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' offers her a starring role with both broad
and subtle touches. We need to understand and empathize with Betty
throughout and Zellweger amiably charts those difficult waters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she almost has the movie stolen from her by Rock and
Freeman, as a hot-headed, impatient young gunslinger and his
soft-spoken mentor, whose true relationship is purposely withheld
until late in the tale. Rock projects a street punk mean streak,
while Freeman is old school philosophic. The more he tracks down
Betty, the more he begins to understand her plight and eventually
falls in love with her.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Betty runs on a bit too long and has a few false endings,
but ultimately LaBute and his writers know exactly where they want
to take us. Psychically and geographically, Betty travels far from
Kansas, and those with an affection for the quirky will enjoy
following where she leads us.
</P>
<P>
   NURSE BETTY
</P>
<P>
   3 -1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Violence, language, one sexual situation
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A loopy yarn of a soap opera-addicted waitress,
played by a sunny Renee Zellweger, who leaves Kansas for the Oz of
L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
