<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A SHORT TIME, THE CONCORDE FLEW OUT OF DALLAS/FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: A short time after the Concorde crash, I saw a retired pilot
on television who said he flew the Concorde for Braniff out of
Dallas/Fort Worth Airport. Did I misunderstand, or was this true?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.C., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: On Jan. 12, 1979, two Concorde supersonic jets landed
simultaneously at D/FW Airport to begin one year of service to the
area.
</P>
<P>
   The flights were the result of a deal among Braniff Airways, Air
France and British Airways. The planes flew from London or Paris to
Washington Dulles Airport and then on to Dallas/Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Concordes were ever painted in Braniff colors, although
British Airways did have one ready to go in the paint shop when the
interchange service was abruptly canceled in May 1980,'' Braniff
enthusiast Kristopher Crook writes on his Web site at
members.tripod.com/BIVA_2/BIVA.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was in the Navy in 1945 and got a ticket to the Green
Bay/Philadelphia football game. What was the score?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Green Bay Packers and Philadelphia Eagles played each
other six times in the 1940s, but not in the 1945 season.
</P>
<P>
   The year-by-year results:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 20, 1940: The Packers defeated the Eagles 27-20 in Green
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 29, 1942: The Packers won 7-0 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 5, 1943: The Packers won 38-28 in Philadelphia over the
``Steagles,'' a combined team of Eagles and Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 14, 1944: The Eagles won 38-13 in an exhibition game played
in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 6, 1946: The Packers won 17-7 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 14, 1947: The Eagles won 28-14 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ How can I get in touch with the talk show host Bob
Eubanks?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.L.N., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Eubanks in care of Byway Entertainment, Box 1563,
Palm Springs, CA 92263.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks, 62, was a disc jockey and concert promoter when he
began hosting ``Newlywed Game'' on July 11, 1966. The series
returned in syndication three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He is developing a Web site for newly married couples. ``I've
always wanted to get all the newlyweds in one big room to talk to
each other and to experts about merging their lifestyles,'' he said
in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
