<HEADER>
A5014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-DEFENSE-$ADV10     09-07 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-DEFENSE-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI ARMY RELIES ON U.S. AID - SOME SAY TOO MUCH
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-USAID-$ADV10; ISRAEL-DEFENSE-$ADV10.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 10 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In Israel, national pride comes wrapped in military
might and emblazoned on the T-shirts sold to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``America don't worry,'' quips one T-shirt with a drawing of an
F-16 fighter jet. ``Israel is behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, of course, it is the other way around. U.S. aid to
Israel has been the backbone of this country's defenses for at
least 15 years. More than one-fifth of Israel's approximately $9.3
billion defense budget, including expenditures for nearly half its
equipment each year, comes from America.
</P>
<P>
   But that aid is being criticized, just as Israelis may ask for
billions more. With the encouragement of President Clinton, they
seek money to beef up the army as they offer land in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Most favor the idea, but arms control experts deride the annual
$2 billion military aid package as fueling an arms race in an
already volatile region. And Israelis seem reluctant to pay for
large increases in defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Israeli executives say the reliance on American guns
and planes stunts the growth of their own arms industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaders of defense industries say, 'Enough to U.S. aid,'''
cried a headline in the newspaper Yedioth Ahronoth last month(CQ).
``We don't need its favors.''
</P>
<P>
   They are angry because under terms of the aid agreements, most
of the money must be spent in the United States. The policy, they
say, will cost them thousands of jobs over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time you are trying to help us you are doing us
terrible harm,'' says Abraham Hatzor, chief executive of an Israeli
company that makes bulletproof vests, military tents and other
textiles.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the United States gave Israel more military aid than
usual, $3.12 billion. It was more than the rest of the world
combined received for military aid in the main U.S. aid budget,
according to figures from the U.S. Agency for International
Development (USAID).
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money, $1.2 billion, was a special grant to be given
over three years as Israel implements the 1998 Wye River peace
accords _ under which Israel agreed to give to the Palestinians
land it captured in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
   The long-stated purpose of the military aid is to ensure that
Israel always maintains an edge over its potential enemies. Most
agree Israel has the best fighting force in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's shopping list for American equipment over the last two
years is long and varied. According to a tally kept by the
Federation of American Scientists' Arms Sales Monitoring Project,
Israel has spent billions on everything from F-16 fighters to
Apache helicopters to air-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Israeli officials contend that their military is woefully
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to modernize our air force, modernize the navy and
modernize our vehicles. Some of them, you won't believe this, are
from World War II,'' said Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim
Sneh. ``The point is that Israel faces tremendous military problems
given the environment we live in.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Israelis say U.S. aid is crucial as they try to make
peace with the Palestinians, or Syria. As they give up land, they
need extra military might.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much cheaper to assist Israel to deter war than to assist
Israel when it is at war,'' Israeli Ret. Brig. Gen. Shlomo Brom
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Federation of American Scientists researchers say
increasing the military aid just fuels an arms race that makes the
region more dangerous. They say the aid antagonizes rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to a point where Israel's lead is significant enough
that you don't need to give them more,'' says Tamar Gabelnick,
director of the FAS's Arms Sales Monitoring Project. ``I don't
think it's really credible for them to say we need more weapons. I
see it as a way for them to get as much as possible from the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Israelis themselves seem to show little enthusiasm for spending
more on defense.
</P>
<P>
   A February poll by the Israeli Jaffee Center for Strategic
Studies showed just 28 percent of Israelis willing to pay higher
taxes for more security. (The poll surveyed 1,201 people, and had a
3.1 percent margin of error one way or the other.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, last year, U.S. officials warned Israeli leaders
that proposed defense cuts in Israel would make it harder to ask
for more U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   But, the army is still a popular and nearly omnipresent part of
Israeli life. Service is compulsory for most men and women.
Soldiers patrol the streets with their U.S.-made M-16s, and
casually take them to the malls and restaurants while off duty.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day affords a solemn moment each spring, when sirens
bring the nation to a halt and motorists pull over to stand by
their cars in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Given that sense of pride, it's hard to find detractors of the
army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody asks the questions, 'Do you buy what you need, or do
you just buy because you have the money?''' said Reuven Pedatzur, a
military analyst and former pilot in the Israeli Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Pedatzur has been a lone critic of Israel's Arrow missile
defense project, which has received $820 million in U.S. aid
separate from the annual package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tells me, 'Why are you against it? It's American
money.''' he says. ``When you're talking about American money,
nobody wants to ask the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For information on arms sales to Israel and other countries see
the Federation of American Scientists Arms Sales Monitoring
Project:
</P>
<P>
   www.fas.org/asmp/profiles/index.html
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
