<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-SPORTS-FOOD-0908-COX     09-07 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-FOOD-0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Food is fuel and must be maintained to perform well
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Want to play like the pros? Then model
your diet after theirs. Kick the caffeine, beef up the beef and
consume carbohydrates in moderation.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter whether you're a duffer on the links, or a
cyclist who regularly rides 100 miles _ food is your fuel, and it
must be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet the Olympic athletes competing in the Summer Games
in Sydney will have gone through nutrition training as part of
their preparations.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new emphasis on nutrition and overall fitness
throughout the sports world, according to Randy Myers, fitness
director at PGA National Resort and Spa in Palm Beach Gardens. He
helps big-name golf clients such as Michelle McGann and Bruce
Fleisher.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers are just one group finally tuning in to the role food
plays on their play, Myers said. ``You'll see a lot of our players,
the ones we work with, with a cooler on the links so they can eat
every hour or so during play to keep up their performance level.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies among nutritionists and dietitians have raised awareness
among the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know more than ever,'' said Kathleen Kelly, a Palm
Beach Gardens sports dietitian. ``The guidelines for food groups
have changed, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, there was an emphasis on carbohydrates and keeping a
diet really low-fat. The current guidelines call for at least 20
percent of the diet from protein, and 30 percent from fat. The
other 50 percent is carbs. That's down from 60 to 80 percent some
recommended before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not the high protein of the Atkins-type diets,
but it's more focused on adding proteins,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sports bars, protein drink mixes and lean meats have replaced
huge plates of pasta for many players, who are trying to build
strength or endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Mazzolaof Palm Beach Gardens relies on supplements to
help her kids get the right nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Two are teens and run cross-country. The youngest, 7, is a
swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can scream at them, stand on your head, and they wouldn't
listen. They `don't have time' to eat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They don't eat red meat, which presents extra problems. ``We
stopped eating it for five or seven years, because my husband, who
was also a runner, developed high cholesterol. But the kids were
having problems, not getting enough iron. So we introduced it back
in the diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said ``runner's anemia'' is a common woe among those
athletes. ``Running breaks down the red blood cells and the body
can't replenish them fast enough, so the runner becomes tired,
fatigued all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrestlers who are trying to lose weight to qualify for a
certain weight class also are at risk for health problems because
of their dieting. They eat poorly, taking in too few calories and
not enough essential nutrients.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes should consult their doctors or a dietitian if they're
tired or ``bonk'' _ run out of energy during a workout or game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're eating right or getting the right supplements, that
shouldn't happen,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Awareness is a first step, but eating consistently plays a role,
too, Myers said. ``You have to force yourself to eat breakfast, but
it's important to fuel the body for the rest of the day. Especially
if you're active,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us are in the habit of not eating breakfast or
grabbing something fast, then eating poorly at lunch _ maybe
grabbing some fast food. By the time dinner rolls around, we're
gorging ourselves, because we've starved ourselves all day. We eat
too much, too late.
</P>
<P>
   There's no one set diet for everyone, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Women need more zinc, which they can get from eating shellfish.
Exercise also uses up calcium _ a crucial element for all women,
but especially older ones who are beginning to lose bone mass.
Kelly recommends supplemental calcium for them, but also green
leafy vegetables and dairy products that contain high amounts of
other important nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Magnesium is a concern for all active people; green leafy
vegetables and complex carbohydrates such as whole bran and seeds
and nuts contain this element.
</P>
<P>
   But the single most important part of sports diets should be
water, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   For any athlete or amateur sports enthusiast, it's especially
important in the humid heat of South Florida. At least a quart of
water per hour is recommended; more if the heat index is peaking.
Kelly knows athletic nutrition firsthand; she also is a distance
cycler and is the nutrition coach for a number of triathletes on
Team USA.
</P>
<P>
   She's the diet consultant to Mike Rozingaro, a Jupiter cyclist
who participated in the Olympic trials. The 22-year-old didn't make
it this year, but will continue competing to prepare for turning
pro. ``I try to eat plenty of carbs, but not too close to the race
time. I want to be fueled ahead of time, but not sluggish at the
start of the race. I eat protein for recovery (after the ride), for
my muscles.''Keeping the body consistently nourished with nutrient
packed foods is the basic theory, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's an analogy: Would you put low-octane gas in your car?
Of course not. Our bodies are another type of engine.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Myers puts it, if you eat poorly, you perform poorly.
``It's the old saying: Junk in, junk out.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: jannorris(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   FOOD FOR FUEL
</P>
<P>
   Salmon-pasta salad
</P>
<P>
   Why it's a winner: Canned salmon (along with green, leafy
vegetables and dairy products) contains calcium, which is important
for women athletes. Women also need extra zinc and vitamin D.
</P>
<P>
   Other strengths: The hearts of palm provide magnesium, a
nutrient lost in activity.
</P>
<P>
   Whole-grain cereal
</P>
<P>
   Why it's a winner: A quick and easy breakfast, whole-grain
cereal with low-fat milk provides several nutrients including
protein and iron.
</P>
<P>
   Other strengths: A banana contains potassium and extra
carbohydrates for natural energy.
</P>
<P>
   Creamy soup
</P>
<P>
   Why it's a winner: Some athletes actually try to maintain weight
_ particularly wrestlers. They are at risk for malnutrition.
Low-fat, low-calorie, but high-nutrient foods such as a ``cream of
any vegetable'' soup, is just what the sports doc ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Other strengths: Made by pureeing cooked vegetables with low-fat
chicken or vegetable stock, seasonings and skim or low-fat milk,
it's a tasty way to slim down, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sunflower seeds
</P>
<P>
   Why they're winners: Seeds, nuts and beans of all varieties are
good for an active body, but sunflower seeds are better than most.
They are high not only in protein, but also in magnesium and zinc.
</P>
<P>
   Other strengths: They're portable. Mix shelled ones with prunes
or raisins, dry oat bran cereal and almonds for a trail mix.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Why they're winners: Cookies don't seem as though they figure
into a healthy diet for an active person, but carbohydrates are an
important fuel source. Dietitians recommend extra carbs a half hour
before beginning a workout and every half hour during prolonged
play to avoid ``bonking'' - running out of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Other strengths: Figs, prunes and other dried fruits provide the
diet with fiber. And they're portable!
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   Why it's a winner: It is the single most important nutrient the
body needs during any activity. For high-activity levels in
moderate heat, 32 ounces (1 quart) per hour is recommended. Never
wait until you're thirsty to drink, because by then, it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Other strengths: Water is a natural body cooler, essential in
South Florida heat. Freeze a few bottles and wrap a wet sock around
them for insulation on the go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
