<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CATFISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY FLAVORS, TOO MANY INGREDIENTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dwayne, the hero of this ultra-indie movie, is suffering a bit
of an identity crisis. A Vietnamese-American raised by
African-American adoptive parents, Dwayne (originally named Sap)
struggles with typical familial communication gaps, talks
'hood-speak to his white roommate, acts the professional
businessman at the small bank he manages, and nervously tries to be
himself with his African-American fiancee. And then Dwayne's sister
has to go and track down their birth mother, confusing the poor guy
even more.
</P>
<P>
   As you might be able to tell from the preceding paragraph,
writer-producer-director Chi Muoi Lo, who plays Dwayne/Sap, wants
to say a lot in ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce.'' He winds up trying
to say too much, and the movie lurches from tone to tone _ family
soap opera one minute, oddball comedy the next _ without ever
settling down. It's not without merit, but at times it feels like
the world's weirdest Hallmark Hall of Fame movie.
</P>
<P>
   Hindered by a modest budget, ``Catfish'' features a cast whose
work could charitably be called uneven. It still manages to snag a
couple of good performances, from Paul Winfield as Dwayne's
live-and-let-live adoptive father and ``Love and Basketball's''
Sanaa Lathan as his fiancee, whose confusion grows along with
Dwayne's. But it's hard to embrace because, well, Dwayne is such an
idiot. Sure, the guy's mixed up, but he's unnecessarily callous to
his birth mother, his adoptive parents, his sister and his fiancee,
his roommate (who's confused in a different way) and his roommate's
girlfriend. None of his reactions seems motivated by anything in
Chi's overstuffed screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was a labor of love for Chi, who escaped from Vietnam
at age 6 in 1975 and went on to play small roles in movies such as
``The Relic'' and ``Indecent Proposal.'' The problem with labors of
love, however, is that too often, their creators get too close to
them. A few steps back, and Chi might have been able to untangle
some of snarled story lines; as it is, ``Catfish'' is a watchable
enough first effort, with hints that more solid work is to come.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
