<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5030 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-LOVEANDSEX-TEX     09-07 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVEANDSEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE AND SEX EQUAL BOREDOM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Valerie Breiman's lighthearted look at the perils of modern
romance has all the familiar trappings of a Julia Roberts comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing is, Julia Roberts isn't in it. Apparently, the
script wasn't funny enough to attract the ``real'' pretty woman,
and, sadly, Famke Janssen is no Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Janssen stars as Kate, an unwillingly single writer for a
women's magazine whose disastrous track record with relationships
leaves her ill-equipped to tackle a story on landing the perfect
man.
</P>
<P>
   Her past flings are told in flashbacks: her creepy high school
French teacher, the married guy she fooled around with in college,
and then the real love of her life, a wiseacre artist named Adam
(Jon Favreau).
</P>
<P>
   The relationship blossoms, gets serious, then wilts, leading to
the inevitable string of mutual attempts at making the other person
jealous. But it's not until Kate starts dating an air-headed
action-film star that Adam realizes what he's been missing, by
which point it may be too late. Too bad that, by this point, you
also couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   Favreau manages to breathe some life into the picture, recalling
some of the irrepressible anti-charm he showed off in ``Swingers,''
but it's all in vain. Janssen rarely does anything to merit his
attention (or ours), and you find yourself hoping to see more of
insignificant side characters such as Cheri Oteri as Kate's
conniving co-worker or Ann Magnuson as her surly editor.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the film's screamingly obvious conclusion, ``Love
and Sex'' still manages to blow any hope of an entertaining
denouement, opting instead to give the impression that filmmakers
simply ran out of celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
