<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THINK ABOUT YOURSELF BEFORE JUDGING OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some people who are aghast at bigotry put their
righteous indignation on hold when it comes to dot-commers.
</P>
<P>
   In the land of political correctness, it seems to be all right
to say that dot-commers clog the streets and drive up housing
prices and ruin it for people in the San Francisco area and the
Silicon Valley, even though you would be labeled a racist if you
made the same comments about any ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Get over it.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening is the same sort of thing that can get older
workers into serious career trouble. If you cling to the way things
were instead of the way things are, you will be overcome with
jealousy and bitterness instead of initiative and adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   Think of yourself as a professional golfer who had a pretty good
career going until that Tiger Woods fellow came along. Now you find
yourself playing for second place most of the time. Where do you go
from here?
</P>
<P>
   It might help if you focus on three things:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't underestimate the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for golfers to whine about how tough it is to compete
with Woods, but the smart ones also realize how much better he has
made it for them. Golf is now a hot sport, with bigger prize money,
more endorsement opportunities and greater public attention _
thanks mostly to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the San Francisco area goes through a wave of cost
increases, there is also a current of opportunity. Economic
Darwinism kicks in, and the people who remain are economically
stronger than those who depart.
</P>
<P>
   That means they pay higher taxes, which can lead to better
schools and nicer parks and safer cities. The wealth attracts
high-level entrepreneurs, which is why some of the world's best
businesses, universities and even restaurants are located here.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity has made life here into a rich tapestry, but it also
has a computer-generated flavor to it. A few clicks and keystrokes
and the tapestry changes. But it's never gone; it's just different.
Don't be so preoccupied with the missing parts of the picture that
you overlook everything fresh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lift up your game.
</P>
<P>
   The economic changes invariably offer opportunities for talented
people, but they can lead to disaster for those stuck in the land
of the mental status quo. Just like a lazy golfer, if all you do is
sit and complain, your future will look a lot like Tiger chow.
</P>
<P>
   A fresh challenge can bring out the best _ or the worst _ in
you. It's pretty much up to you to decide.
</P>
<P>
   What do you need to work on? It's probably not as clear-cut as
learning to putt better, but it's not as hard as hitting a 350-yard
drive, either. Think about how you need to grow as a worker so you
can stay in the game. Who is getting ahead and who is getting left
behind?
</P>
<P>
   Talent and adaptability get rewarded. That is true now, and it
was true long before there were opposable thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   _ You have to sacrifice to be No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for anyone who has grabbed a 9-iron to fantasize about
being like Woods, with all the talent in the world. But those
fantasies probably don't include the loss of privacy that comes
from being famous, or the long hours of drills and exercises that
make those Sunday afternoons look so easy.
</P>
<P>
   The dot-commers who have struck it rich usually had to sacrifice
a lot of friendships and personal time to get their financial
reward, and their jobs often aren't as emotionally satisfying as
other people's might be. No job is wonderful all the time. Ask
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   You could well make a perfectly rational decision that the
rewards aren't worth the pain. Maybe it's best to pick up your
clubs and go home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
