<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-DIVORCE-CHILDREN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-CHILDREN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW BOOK SAYS CHILDREN OF DIVORCED COUPLES FACE MORE TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Baby boomers have grown up mocking their parents
for staying together ``for the sake of the children,'' but that may
be the healthier alternative to divorce, according to a study
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by psychologist Judith Wallerstein of Marin County,
Calif., is detailed in the book ``The Unexpected Legacy of Divorce:
A 25-year Landmark Study.'' The researcher followed 93 children of
failed marriages over a 25-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Co-written by San Francisco State Professor Julia Lewis and New
York Times science correspondent Sandra Blakeslee, the book details
findings showing that adult children of divorced parents had far
more trouble establishing intimate relationships in adult years,
were less likely to go to college and more likely to get into
trouble with drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, where divorce was once believed to have the
strongest impact on children at the time of the break-up, the
authors are now saying it has implications that last long into
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The study of the 93 predominantly white children _ whose fathers
were doctors, lawyers and executives _ came from 60 families. They
were compared with 44 children from similar families whose parents
remained married.
</P>
<P>
   The good news in the study is that most of the children of
divorced parents had successful careers, knew how to handle money
and even emerged as adults with character and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But their love lives left a lot to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their first thought in a quarrel was, `I'm out of here.' This
is the nightmare I was waiting for, and here it comes. I might as
well get out,'' Wallerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are plenty of family crises that affect a child _
including the death of a parent at a young age, or alcoholism or
drug abuse _ none has the impact of divorce, Wallerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Children know that parents do not choose to die and believe that
a dysfunctional parent on drugs or alcohol may be ill.
</P>
<P>
   But the divorce is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``With death it's final,'' Blakeslee said. ``But with divorce
he's around, and she's around. With every birthday or graduation,
it's an open wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents who choose divorce ``should know what their children
need and how to put them first, and what they're going to need two,
five and 15 years down the line,'' Blakeslee said. ``It's the long
haul that shapes their experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallerstein said many children of divorce eventually found
personal happiness but not without a lot of pain and many mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Children of divorce were far likely to marry before age 25 _
50 percent, compared with 11 percent for the comparison group.
Nearly 60 percent of the young marriages among children of divorced
parents failed, compared with 25 percent among their peers whose
parents stayed married.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 25 percent of children of divorce used drugs and alcohol
before they were 14, compared with 9 percent in the comparison
group.
</P>
<P>
   One specialist in families questioned the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Wallerstein ``has always viewed divorce through a pretty gloomy
glass,'' said E. Mavis Hetherington, a professor emeritus at the
University of Virginia. ``It's almost as though they have a
terminal disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Hetherington said other research had shown that about 25 percent
of children of divorce had long-term problems with relationships.
That means the other three-fourths are doing well or surviving as
well as anybody can be expected in a nation with a 50 percent
divorce rate.
</P>
<P>
   She did agree, however, that government funding should be spent
on couples having trouble with marriage rather than focusing on
healing wounds after divorce had occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
