<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SHARK-BIOLOGIST-BOS &LR;      09-07 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARK-BIOLOGIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARK RESEARCHER GOES TO EXTREMEMS FOR SOME ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORDON'S GULLY, ATLANTIC OCEAN _ Greg Skomal, Massachusetts'
shark biologist, was 20 miles south of Martha's Vineyard and 20
feet deep the other day, and he was frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   There were not enough sharks milling about.
</P>
<P>
   Despite hours of throwing morsels of bloody fish overboard to
create a mile-long chum road leading to his submerged cage, all
Skomal had attracted were two toothy, somewhat bored-looking blue
sharks to a neighborhood also known to be carved up by makos,
hammerheads, and a great white or two.
</P>
<P>
   Skomal studies shark behavior, often in scuba gear, often from
inside his homebuilt cage.
</P>
<P>
   It is what he did next that perhaps best illustrates Skomal's
mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the safety of his cage, the researcher swam to the
nearby boat to retrieve the meaty remains of a yellowfin tuna
caught and cleaned the day before. Then he descended, swam past the
cage, and disappeared into the murky green world beyond, waving the
large tuna carcass like someone might wave a slab of prime rib to
attract a pack of pit bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's hard to tell who is the more aggressive,'' said
Paul Diodati, director of the state Division of Marine Fisheries,
``Greg or the sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's peak season for the half-dozen sport fish biologists
assigned to monitor and safeguard the state's recreational fish
stocks. With the warmer water of late summer come the bluefin tuna,
marlin, and mako _ and close behind them, a host of hopeful anglers
in pursuit. State officials estimate these anglers are generating
approximately $1 billion annually in economic activity (such as
boats, fuel, hotel rooms, and meals) in their quest to land the big
fish or the big story.
</P>
<P>
   Skomal, 39, who is based in Vineyard Haven, has monitored shark
populations for the past dozen years, entering the profession
during an era when ``Jaws,'' the 1975 Hollywood shark thriller, was
still casting a deadly shadow over sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a time when people continued to think the only good
shark was a dead shark,'' said Skomal, whose sharp, handsome
features and wavy blond hair suggest he is the lad the Beach Boys
left behind. He is single _ or, rather, married to a job that
recently took him to Greenland diving with sharks for the Discovery
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   One of Skomal's duties is touring the docks collecting fish
stories during any of the half-dozen shark-fishing tournaments held
in Massachusetts every year. Competitors used to kill all the
sharks they caught. Now, partly because of Skomal's dockside chats,
competitors voluntarily return all but the largest sharks to the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Skomal measures the health of a species by the catch per boat
hour of fishing effort. Blue and mako shark _ the state's most
abundant game sharks _ posted steady increases in population during
the first half of the 1990s. More recently, the landings have
flattened out, and may even be in decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too early to tell what's going on. There are so
many variables,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear precisely where Skomal developed his passion
for sharks. But it came early, according to his sister Lenore, who
lives in Skomal's hometown of Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the only one in the family who insisted on having an
aquarium in his room. And the designs on the wallpaper? Sharks.
Drawn by Greg with crayons, much to our parents' dismay,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   His affection for the fish led him to earn a bachelor's degree
in zoology at the University of Rhode Island, then onto oceangoing
fishing boats studying the sharks caught by commercial fishermen.
When he was working for the National Marine Fisheries Service, Jack
Casey, now retired and a resident of Narragansett, R.I., was his
boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy would be out on deck in storms, green water up to his
neck, looking at sharks,'' Casey said. ``He wasn't just interested,
he was obsessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Chase, another sport fish biologist who sometimes works
side by side with Skomal, had a similar observation. For example,
during one research trip, Chase was assisting Skomal as he tried to
determine if blue sharks fought to the point of near-fatal
exhaustion when they were caught by rod and reel. The answer lay in
the bloodwork of the fish. Extracting blood from a caught fish was
simple; the problem was comparing the blood to that of an uncaught
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Skomal's solution?
</P>
<P>
   ``He grabbed one of the animals by the tail as it lunged for
bait hung from the boat. Then he figured out where he needed to
hold the thing so it couldn't bend around to bite him as he
withdrew blood,'' Chase said. Actually, that wasn't quite accurate,
Skomal added. It was Chase who worked the needle, once pinning
Skomal's hand to the fish.
</P>
<P>
   All in a day's work. The men determined a fight does not
jeopardize the health of a blue shark. One question answered, but
there are thousands to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know so little about sharks. If I could be granted but one
wish, I would ask: Show me the details in the daily life of a
shark,'' Skomal said.
</P>
<P>
   And so several times a summer, he goes offshore with his shark
cage just to watch sharks, his trip last Monday aboard the No
Doubt, a Hyannis-based sport fishing boat captained by his friend
Chris Gallagher. Loading the cage in the Oak Bluffs harbor was
something of a dockside conversation piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, but I thought there were no sharks on Martha's
Vineyard,'' Mary Moore of Rye, N.Y., shouted to Skomal as he and
crew members muscled the cage aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not on the Vineyard,'' Skomal answered.
</P>
<P>
   This did little to appease Moore, who said her three children,
now grown, have not gone swimming hereabouts since they watched
``Jaws'' filmed 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there have been only three unprovoked fatal shark
attacks recorded in Massachusetts since 1670, according to the
Florida Museum of Natural History, keeper of shark-attack
statistics nationwide. The last Massachusetts fatality occurred in
1936.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, sharks don't like people, Skomal explained hours
later, dressed in scuba gear before jumping into the ocean to
observe sharks, a reporter in pursuit to observe Skomal.
</P>
<P>
   His cage is about the size of a ski-lift gondola. It floats 20
feet below the surface, suspended from three large buoys and
loosely tethered to the boat to keep it from drifting away.
</P>
<P>
   His sister had said that Skomal was not mechanically inclined,
that he had built go-carts in elementary school, shark cages in
college, and there had been nothing in between. Indeed, his cage
this day had several large openings in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were made by film crews. Don't worry. If a shark tries
to get in, just bop it on the nose. Lightly,'' Skomal had said. No
doubt where his priorities lay.
</P>
<P>
   An adult shark brain is roughly the size of half a banana,
devoted entirely to sensory reception and instinct, able to detect
a drop of blood a mile away. But despite all of Skomal's efforts to
bring the animals in, the only large visitor would be a
10-foot-long blue shark. It circled the cage an arm's length away,
its back a striking fluorescent indigo, its eyes the size of silver
dollars, its temperament curious if somewhat bored, its mouth
closed.
</P>
<P>
   No need to bop the shark, although one began to wonder about
Skomal as he swam off after the shark, leaving behind an oily trail
of flayed tuna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
