<HEADLINE>
BULBS FOR SHADE ABOUND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If bulbs could plant themselves (and don't we wish they could),
most would select a sunny site with good drainage and alkaline soil
that reminded them of their mountain homeland in southern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   But what if they're stuck with a shady lot? There are still
possibilities, but it depends . . .
</P>
<P>
   If your shade comes from deciduous trees, your choices are many.
If you have dense, unyielding shade from buildings and evergreens,
on the other hand, your options are fewer. In either case, look at
it as a challenge to explore some of the most interesting
connoisseur bulbs that have recently entered the mainstream of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   While most daffodils will tolerate some shade, (the new
apricot-pink daffodils are better planted in light shade because it
keeps their color from washing out), the large tulips we're all
familiar with will have a hissy fit if they get less than four
hours of full sun a day. Even if you're hooked on tulips, though,
there's a solution. Try the small delicate species tulips such as
chrysantha, clusiana, sylvestris, the sturdy little yellow and
white tarda, and the lovely bronze and yellow batalinii for partial
shade. Many people come to like them better than the big hybrids,
partly because they're longer-lived as well as charming.
</P>
<P>
   If your shade comes from trees, says Jo-Anne Ohms of John
Scheepers, one of the country's most respected bulb companies, test
the soil. ``If you have pine or oak trees, they may help make the
soil acid. Flower bulbs prefer a neutral pH level, so test your
soil and sprinkle lime on top if it's acidic.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the right pH, you have two tactics for selecting
bulbs. One is to pick species that are native to shady woodlands,
not sunny mountain meadows as tulips are. The other is to buy bulbs
that bloom so early that they're almost ready to go dormant by the
time your trees leaf out and cut off the sunshine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Early bloomers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even sun-loving bulbs that bloom in February, March, and early
April can be planted under non-evergreen trees and shrubs. These
early bulbs include crocus, winter aconite (eranthus), snowdrop
(galanthus), pushkinia, and Siberian squill. All are small, ranging
from 3 to 12 inches tall, and should be planted by the dozens to
get an effect.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier bulbs bloom in the spring, the earlier they should
be planted in the fall, so plant these March bulbs as soon as you
can, says Peter de Jager, a fifth-generation bulb dealer in South
Hamilton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to buy your bulbs early, says Keith Hutchins of
Wilson Farms in Lexington, Mass., is that the supply will be
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulb production was down about 40 percent because of bad
weather,'' he says. ``The quality of bulbs I saw this year in the
Netherlands was exceptional, except there's not a lot of them. The
Dutch perennial crop is spectactular because it got warm early and
then it got wet. So you'll be seeing few specials on bulbs and a
lot of specials on perennials.''
</P>
<P>
   If you buy your bulbs before you're ready to plant them, store
them in a cool, dry place (but not the fridge). Prolonged
temperatures over 75 decrease can affect their blooming ability. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Crocus family &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crocuses are the best-known early bulb, a down payment on
spring. The first to bloom here in late February is the lavender
Crocus tommasinianus, which is a great investment because it's a
true species from Bosnia and Croatia rather than a hybrid, and will
seed itself around. Even better, squirrels don't seem to like the
taste. There are several named selections, including Barr's Purple,
Whitewell Purple, and Albus, which is white.
</P>
<P>
   The second crocus to bloom is golden bunch (Crocus ancyrensis),
a traffic-stopping, orange-gold species from Turkey. Don't plant it
with ``tommys.'' Colorwise, it would be like mixing lilacs with
black-eyed Susans.
</P>
<P>
   March brings the snow crocuses. If nature dumps an inch of snow
on these flowers, they just laugh, and continue blooming when it
melts. These are smaller, earlier, and better increasers than the
later Dutch crocuses. There are also dozens of varieties in
interesting color combinations. Dutch crocuses are the largest
crocuses and last to bloom. They're somewhat out of favor now, but
it's interesting to know that common Giant Yellow is one of the
oldest hybrid plants still in commerce, dating back to 1600.
</P>
<P>
   Winter aconite looks like golden buttercups and often blooms in
February. Two kinds are sold. Eranthis hyemalis is the best for
shady or damp sites as it is native to moist woods in Europe, says
Peter Messelaar of the Messelaar Bulbs Co. of Ipswich, Mass. The
rarer Eranthis cilicica likes drier, sunnier sites. It's a good
idea to soak the corms for several hours before planting. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shade-loving squill &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the best bulbs for shade is Siberian squill (Scilla
siberica), which blooms in late March. Eight inches tall, it
produces clusters of downward-facing bells of the most intense blue
and will quickly spread. This is one bulb that prefers shade and
will thrive under trees and bushes. It's quite a sight to see a
blue carpet of Siberian squills under spreading beach trees in
March, as at Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Pushkinia scilloides has the same size and bloom time, but its
flowers are white with stripes of aqua, the rarest of all garden
colors. It, too, will self-seed, though not as densely as Siberian
squill. Pair pushkinia with larger, early, pink or apricot bulbs
such as hyacinths.
</P>
<P>
   Glory-of-the-snow (chionodoxa) blooms in April, well after the
snowstorms of March, so the name is a misnomer, but this is another
bulb that prefers the summer shade of deciduous shrubs and trees to
flat-out sun and which will self-seed. Chionodoxa sardensis has
intense blue flowers while Chionodoxa luciliae has larger paler
blue stars with white centers. There's also a taller pink version
called Pink Giant, which is too close to the color of dead leaves
to be effective in the early garden.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet-smelling hyacinths of April are surprisingly tolerant
of light shade and will linger for years before they gradually
dwindle away. Though many people don't like their squat appearance,
they are worth planting near a doorway or window for their powerful
scent.
</P>
<P>
   For later-blooming flowers, choose woodland bulbs that are used
to coexisting with trees. Most of these like a spot with good
drainage and rich soil that gets some irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   Fritillaria imperialis is the best-known member of its family
because it has the tallest flowers of any early-April-blooming
bulb. It will tolerate light shade, but there are several smaller
relatives that are even more shade-tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   While most spring bulbs are bright and charming, no one would
call fritillaries cheerful. These are bulbs Edward Gorey would have
loved, with pendulous bells in smokey colors and odd patterns. The
guinea hen flower (Fritillaria meleagris), which has checkered
flowers in shades of maroon and cream, is fascinating and easy to
grow. British garden writer Vita Sackville-West proclaimed it
``sinister in its mournful colours of decay.'' Fritillaria
pyrenaica also has checkered bells in shades of brown and red. Even
more gothic is Fritillaria camschatcensis, whose almost black
flowers are native to China, Japan, and Alaska, providing yet more
evidence of an ancient land bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the wood hyacinth (Scilla campanulata) nor the grape
hyacinth (Muscari) are true hyacinths, though the second has a
faint fragrance. Both tolerate a fair amount of deciduous shade.
</P>
<P>
   Other later bulbs to try in dappled light include Allium
aflatunense, golden onion (Allium flavum), golden garlic (Allium
molly), our native Anemone canadensis, Camassia quamash, and
Anemonella thalictriodes. Lilies will tolerate partial shade, too,
but don't plant them because they'll be devastated by lily-leaf
beetles. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     09-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... lily-leaf beetles.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for light, deciduous shade. Suppose your shade is
lovely, dark and deep?
</P>
<P>
   Don't despair. This is where real ingenuity comes in. Some of
the less-common but most-prized bulbs can handle considerable shade
if you plant them in rich soil and keep them watered with average
garden irrigation. You don't want them to be in wet soil. They like
a raised bed, a slight slope, or to be under trees and shrubs that
will suck up excess moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodroot (Sanguinaria canadensis) from our native woodlands has
beautiful leaves and graceful white daisy flowers in April that
will self-seed. Even better is the double form, which looks like
miniature white waterlilies and is considered one of the most
beautiful of all plants, says Baldasarre Mineo, owner of Siskiyou
Rare Plant Nursery in Medford, Ore.: ``It's expensive but
unkillable and will gradually multiply.''
</P>
<P>
   The wood anemone (Anemone nemorosa) is another beautiful daisy.
It likes well-drained shade. ``Try to get one of the blue forms,''
advises Mineo.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice bulb for shade is the dog's-tooth violet
(erythronium), which likes to grow under trees and shrubs.
Erythroniums are miniature lilies, not violets. The unfortunate
name comes from an imagined resemblance of the bulbs to a dog's
tooth. Erythronium americanum grows wild in our local woods and
goes by the pleasanter name trout lily because its beautiful leaves
are mottled like a trout. However, it sends up few flowers, so is
not a great garden subject.
</P>
<P>
   Other erythroniums have been hybridized to create heavier
bloomers with pink, lavender, white, or yellow flowers that often
retain the handsome leaf patterns. ``Pagoda, which is yellow, and
the cream and orange White Beauty are the easiest and most
robust,'' says Mineo.
</P>
<P>
   You could also try Arum italicum. This is a wonderful, underused
plant that is slow to mature. If you give it a few years, though,
it will reward you with white hooded flowers like calla lilies each
spring and brilliant spikes of red berries each fall that have
earned it the common name lords and ladies. (Presumably the fragile
flowers are the ladies and the assertive red berry spikes are the
lords.) The tropical-looking foliage is evergreen and in the
variety ``Pictum'' is fretted with intricate white markings.
</P>
<P>
   Arum is related to our great native Jack-in-the-pulpit (Arisaema
triphyllum), which is also a fine bulb for deeper shade. There are
many other arisaemas that have recently been embraced by
adventurous shade gardeners, including the native green dragon
(Arisaema dracontium), and the prized, hard-to-find Arisaema
candidissimum from the woods of western China, and Arisaema
sikokianum from Japan. This plant looks like a small
Jack-in-the-pulpit that's gone to heaven. The exterior of the
``pulpit' is exquisitely marked brown while the ``jack'' and the
entire inside of the pulpit are a luminous white. If you have
success with it, no gardener will pity you for growing bulbs in
shade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
