<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-GARMENT-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     09-07 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GARMENT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... much fun.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon after Nixon's resignation in 1974, Garment returned to New
York. He resumed practicing law, only to return to public service,
this time as right-hand man at the United Nations to then-US
Ambassador Moynihan. Soon enough, he saw the wisdom of what Fortas
had told him and by 1980 was back inside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Garment specializes in ``political litigation'' (his term). His
clients have included Fiat, Attorney General Edwin Meese III, and
former national security adviser Robert McFarlane. He used to play
in a monthly poker game whose other regulars included two members
of the Supreme Court, Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justice
Antonin Scalia. Garment almost made it a Supreme Court trifecta,
becoming an unofficial campaign manager for Robert Bork during the
judge's unsuccessful confirmation fight in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Garment has slowed down some since then but remains a fixture in
the permanent-Washington firmament. Garment still has ``that
slightly edgy, funny, perspicacious nature,'' says McPherson,
``skillful in all the arts of lawyering.'' At Verner Liipfert, he
rubs shoulders with the likes of former US senators Bob Dole,
George Mitchell, and Lloyd Bentsen. His current big project, one
that's close to fruition, is setting up a national museum of jazz
to be built in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great strength,'' Garment says, ``is putting things
together and taking chances. So it's sort of, splat, and then the
next three months represents an effort to organize splat into a
coherent statement. The story of this book was a long couple of
years of splat here, splat there.''
</P>
<P>
   Much though Sears may not like having been splattered, Garment
is happy with his book and the debate it's stirred up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-seven years later, it's time . . . (to) discuss the
obvious fact that what was journalism is now history,'' Garment
argues. ``They can tell us who it is so we can determine the
contours of this legendary figure who has helped significantly in
shaping modern American history, and modern American journalism,
and modern American politics. . . . (Concealing the identity of
Deep Throat) has the deliberate quality of `If the secret is kept
long enough it will go away.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Garment gives a vigorous nod of his head, secure in the
knowledge that _ so long as he's around, anyway _ the secret of
Deep Throat isn't about to go away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
DEEP THROAT ROLLCALL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to identify Deep Throat, Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein's celebrated source during Watergate, has been a favorite
inside-the-Beltway sport for more than 25 years _ even for those
who contend that Deep Throat was either a composite or outright
fiction (contentions Woodward and Bernstein stoutly deny).
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``In Search of Deep Throat,'' former Nixon aide
Leonard Garment points to John P. Sears, who after serving in the
1968 Nixon campaign and briefly as a White House aide went on to be
Ronald Reagan's campaign manager in 1976 and the early part of
1980. Sears has denied being Deep Throat _ as has Garment, when
it's been suggested he was the source for Woodward and Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, who has said Deep Throat's name will not be revealed
until the latter's death, cleared two candidates of the charge when
they were being considered for posts in the Reagan administration:
Nixon chief of staff Alexander M. Haig Jr. and White House deputy
counsel Fred F. Fielding.
</P>
<P>
   Other leading contenders, all of whom have denied being Deep
Throat, include Nixon speechwriter David Gergen; acting FBI head L.
Patrick Gray; FBI official W. Mark Felt Jr.; US Senator Robert F.
Bennett (R-Utah), who employed Watergate burglar E. Howard Hunt at
his public relations firm; CIA director Richard M. Helms; deputy
CIA director Vernon A. Walters; and White House press secretary
Ronald L. Ziegler.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, one person whom everyone can agree on as Deep
Throat: Hal Holbrook, who memorably played him in the 1976 film
adaptation of Woodward and Bernstein's book ``All the President's
Men.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARK FEENEY &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
A POP CULTURE ICON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deep Throat, journalism's most famous unidentified source, got
his name not from Washington Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein but the paper's managing editor, Howard Simons. The
inspiration was the Linda Lovelace-starring pornographic movie of
the same name, which was then playing in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie version of Woodward and Bernstein's book ``All the
President's Men,'' Deep Throat (played by Hal Holbrook) urges
Woodward (Robert Redford) to ``follow the money.'' It was the most
famous line in the movie, simultaneously defining the Watergate
scandal and _ it turned out _ offering a road map to the future of
US electoral politics. Yet it appears in neither Woodward and
Bernstein's book nor any of their Post articles. It was the
invention of screenwriter William Goldman and helped earn him the
1976 Academy Award for best adapted screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Throat's pop-cultural legacy lives on, most notably on
television's ``The X-Files.'' The series's creator, Chris Carter,
has said Watergate ``ruined me forever as far as my belief in
institutions and in authority of agendas of government.'' The
recurring character known only as Cigarette Smoking Man (William B.
Davis) is an updated, far more sinister version of Deep Throat:
another tobacco addict with dark secrets to tell (or withhold) most
comfortable lurking in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARK FEENEY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
