   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLLS _ Pollster John Zogby's got Gore up six points and
the most recent Texas Poll, to be released Friday, while still
strong for Bush, shows his numbers slipping since the spring.
Privately and publicly, Republicans are worried that Gore's
post-convention bounce is turning into a sustainable lead. We talk
with folks about Bush's problems and what he needs to do to turn
them around. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE _ For the first time, with Friday's shuttle launch,
viewers can e-mail reservations. For $34.50, you get bus ride to
viewing site, ``maximum access'' badge to complex, narrated stops
along space station center, plus IMAX movies. $15, you get bus
transportation and limited access. (Crecente, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE _ WASHINGTON _ The National Pipeline Reform Coalition
of environmental groups, safety advocates and local officials
called for congressional action on stalled legislation to ``put
teeth'' into federal pipeline safety laws. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-STURGEON _ WASHINGTON _The Senate votes Thursday in a
showdown between the recreational and barge industries over the
pallid sturgeon. The outcome could foreshadow the fate of more than
40 disputes between environmental and business interests over
``riders'' in the 11 unfinished appropriation bills. Pallid
sturgeons are primitive, shovel-nosed, toothless, six-foot-long
bottom-suckers that have lived in the Missouri River since the
Jurassic age of the dinosaurs, but began disappearing after dams
tamed most of the river. Upriver forces led by Sen. Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., want to let the Corps of Engineers allow spring floods in
the Missouri in order to make it easier for the endangered fish, as
well as two rare shorebirds (the piping plover and the internal
least tern) to reproduce. Downriver forces led by Sen. Christopher
(Kit) Bond, R-Mo., say the spring floods would endanger jobs in
businesses dependent on barge traffic. (Mollison,, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LIST _ Describing the 3 species at stake and listing a
sample of the 41 other disputed riders.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ The House is expected to vote on
overriding President Clinton's veto of a bill to eliminate the
estate tax. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, U.S. Government
</P>
<P>
   SORORITY-RACISM _ Interviewing president of UGA's Alpha Gamma
Delta chapter, which allegedly rejected an applicant because she
was black. Attempting to find the student who lodged the complaint
of racial discrimination against UGA's Alpha Gamma Delta
chapter,and recording the buzz on campus. (McCarthy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NC-GOV _ Like the candidates in the race to succeed Zell Miller,
Georgia's ``education governor,'' two years ago, the men wanting to
be North Carolina's next governor_ Attorney General Mike Easley,
the Democrat, and former Charlotte mayor Richard Vinroot, the
Republican_are trying to ``out-education'' each other. Easley is
pledging to carry on the tradition of North Carolina's own
education governor, Jim Hunt, while Vinroot says the state's
education progress is vastly overstated and that a voucher program
is needed. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BUSHAIR _ George Bush is fighting to keep Austin, San Antonio
and the Tyler-Longview area from being designated in violation of
the EPA's new smog standard. Environmentalists say Bush's actions
are motivated by the prospect for embarrassment. They say that he
cannot afford to have these metropolitan areas added to a list that
already includes Dallas and Houston, especially in the midst of a
campaign in which he asserts things are getting better. But
monitoring in those cities clearly show that ozone levels there
exceed the tougher new standard. Bush, and several other Republican
governors, counter that EPA's new standards have been struck down
by an appeals court and now await Supreme Court review, and EPA
action should await that ruling. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CHAMBERS-GORE _ Publishing and cable magnate Anne Cox Chambers,
a big Democratic donor, has mended fences with Vice President Gore.
Chambers, who owns the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, will host a
private dinner at her Buckhead mansion for Gore when he visits
Georgia Sept. 8. An early financial backer of Gore's, Chambers
stopped supporting Gore earlier in the 1990s because of his support
of cable regulation. She backed rival Bill Bradley in the primary,
hosting a fundraiser that netted Bradley $225,000. But in April,
Chambers donated $100,000 to the Democratic Party, one of the two
largest individual contributions to the Democrats of anyone in
Georgia. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-GEORGIA _ Vice President Gore campaigns in Georgia
Friday(SEPT 8). But long before there was a political reason for
visiting the Peach state, there was an all-important financial one.
Gore will headline a fund-raiser in Buckhead that could raise
$500,000 to $1 million for the Democratic Party. The scheduling of
the fundraiser is another example of how the quest for money often
drives the quest for votes in the presidential race, even after the
party nominating conventions. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
