<P>
   CONSUMER-CONFIDENCE _ Consumer confidence indexes rebounded in
the third quarter after falling in the second, Kennesaw State U
reported in its latest survey. But sentiment about big ticket
buying remains squishy, so the retail outlook could remain cloudy.
Meanwhile Telecheck reports a 3.8 percent year-over-year gain in
checkwriting nationally, 3.4 percent in the Southeast. (DeGross,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BASS-ARASI _ Tom Arasi, president of the Americas division of
Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts, is resigning after a year to start his own
business. His successor John Sweetwood, comes from a strong
marketing background and many expect him to focus more on that
aspect of he business as well as development in the Latin American
market. Most of the Bass hotels are in the Americas division. Bass
is one of the largest hotel companies in the world. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FEDEX _ United Parcel Service Corp.'s top two rivals _ FedEx
Corp. and the U.S. Postal Service _ are talking about a possible
business alliance. Such a move could dramatically alter the
competitive landscape in the air and ground delivery industry and
put enormous pressure on Sandy Springs-based UPS. Details are
scarce, but industry experts say FedEx wants to turn over many of
its ground deliveries to the Postal Service. In return, FedEx
planes would carry Postal Service next-day shipments. FedEx could
also gain access to 38,000 U.S. post offices. The deal raises legal
questions and UPS can be relied on to fight it vigorously.
(Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   QWEST _ Qwest is cutting 6,500 jobs, restructuring itself to be
more Net centered and has hired a Cox exec to run the new unit.
BellSouth still owns a (small) part of this company. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GM-LAWSUIT _Bill McAleer is a GM employee, formerly a quality
control manager, who is suing GM alleging that the automaker is
allowing thousands of cars to reach customers with missing bolts,
loose fuel lines and other safety hazards. There's a hearing
Thursday in an Atlanta federal court over whether to seal records
and add an age discrimination lawsuit. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
