 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Includes two Deep Throat sidebars)  
 LEONARD GARMENT SAYS HE'S IDENTIFIED DEEP THROAT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the great mystery man of political scandal, the shadowiest
figure in the annals of journalism, the most famous informant of
the Information Age (not to mention the patron saint of parking
garages): Deep Throat, the secret source who helped lead Washington
Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein to the truth about
Watergate in 1972 and 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Only four people know his identity: Woodward, Bernstein, retired
Post executive editor Ben Bradlee, and, of course, Deep Throat
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Garment thinks he can make it five.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``In Search of Deep Throat,'' Garment names
John P. Sears as his man. Sears, a onetime aide to Richard Nixon,
went on to manage two of Ronald Reagan's presidential campaigns.
Currently practicing law in Washington, he has denied he is Deep
Throat. So have Woodward and Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't faze Garment, nor does the fact Sears has
threatened to sue. ``I'm not holding my breath, waiting nervously
for the process server,'' Garment chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more than the threat of a libel suit to make him blink.
As the liberal conscience of the Nixon White House, Garment was
himself long ago accused of being Deep Throat (it was quickly
agreed that no one that gregarious ever could have kept such a
thing secret). He succeeded John Dean as White House counsel, and
some have credited his opposition to destroying the White House
tapes for Nixon's deciding to preserve them.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as notable as the fact of having stood up both for and to
Nixon during Watergate is his having played tenor saxophone behind
Billie Holiday (albeit for only two weeks) in the early '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Leonard Garment is no stranger to great events or
larger-than-life characters. In fact, he cuts a fairly sizable
figure himself. ``I regard him with a measure of awe,'' says
Garment's friend and former colleague US Senator Daniel Patrick
Moynihan (D-N.Y.). ``You wouldn't understand Washington for the
last 30 years if you didn't know about Len Garment.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not so much formidable as irrepressible, a force of rich
and risible nature. Garment is ``the funniest man I know,''
declares Moynihan. ``The puns and jokes just keep coming.'' At the
same time, the senator adds, Garment is ``a man of profound
seriousness leavened with a sense of the irony of life.'' So
striking a blend of amiability and gravitas has helped make him (in
the words of The American Lawyer magazine) ``the consummate
Washington lawyer, as successful, well-connected, and sought-after
as any in town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pulled off the always difficult trick of making people
from all sorts of political factions all like him,'' says author
and former US News &AMP; World Report editor James Fallows, a friend
and onetime neighbor of Garment's. ``It's a combination of inherent
affability and the fact he very obviously has a life outside of
partisan politics: his writing, his music, and a very ill-concealed
sense of humor about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Len is sui generis, a very special kind of character: very,
very politically savvy, yet very irreverent,'' adds David Levy,
director of Washington's Corcoran Gallery of Art and another
Garment friend. ``He has a certain latitude: He's only responsible
to history now, not some administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Garment is 76 (``rounding second and heading for home,'' he
laughs). He has three children: Paul, a musician, and Sara, a
writer, from his first marriage; and Annie, an incoming freshman at
Yale. Garment's first wife, Grace, was a writer who suffered for
many years from depression. She committed suicide in 1976. His
current wife, Suzanne Garment, is an author, former Wall Street
Journal political columnist, and the only 53-year-old in last
spring's graduating class at Georgetown Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Garment has a soft, slightly gravelly voice. In it, one can
still detect the muscular intonations of Flatbush. A self-described
``verbal manic-digressive,'' Garment talks as naturally _ as
inevitably _ as most people breathe. He thrives on the back and
forth, the give and take, of good gab _ and gives as good as he
gets.
</P>
<P>
   With his blocky build and thinning white hair, he bears a strong
resemble to Sparky Anderson, the Hall of Fame baseball manager. Yet
there's also the raffishness of Anderson's most famous player, Pete
Rose. Garment is part authority figure, part authority flouter.
It's easy to imagine him as, say, a high school principal _ solid,
distinguished, learned _ who just for the hell of it runs a bookie
joint on the side. (One can almost hear the student body: ``Yes,
Mr. Garment. No, Mr. Garment. Mr. Garment!'')
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of three boys, he was born on a kitchen table in a
three-room tenement in the Brownsville section of Brooklyn.
Garment's father owned a (what else?) garment factory but went
bankrupt during the Depression. His youngest son developed a taste
for jazz soon thereafter. Father objected. Not mother, though: She
had babysat the young George Gershwin.
</P>
<P>
   A clarinetist, Garment idolized Benny Goodman (four decades
later he would find himself doing legal work for the King of
Swing). He soon graduated to tenor saxophone. Besides backing
Holiday, he briefly held a chair in Woody Herman's orchestra. He
was drafted, got a medical discharge, and picked up his horn again.
Soon he was playing with the likes of Al Cohn, Terry Gibbs, and
another aspiring reed man, one Alan Greenspan. Twenty years later,
Garment bumped into his old saxophone-section mate, now an
economist, and urged him on Nixon. ``Irrational exuberance'' might
be how Federal Reserve chairman Greenspan describes the bull market
of the '90s. But one wonders if he didn't get the phrase from
watching his old pal in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz was a lot of energy and imagination but it was somewhat
disorganized,'' Garment says of his relationship to the music he
still loves. ``I assumed I could put things together, hold them
together, harmonically. But when the harmonic aspect of jazz became
more complicated, with bop, I knew, playing with musicians who were
first-rate, `Get out of town before it's too late and get another
profession.' Then I became a lawyer, of all constricted
professions!''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz had taught Garment how to improvise, a talent he's yet to
lose. It stood him in good stead as an ``ethnic icebreaker,''
making the leap from Brooklyn Law School to a white-shoe Wall
Street firm with the vaguely Dickensian name of Mudge, Rose,
Guthrie, and Alexander. Garment eventually headed the litigation
department and was looking for new worlds to conquer when who
should join the firm in 1963 but Richard Milhous Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Garment was a jokey Jewish extrovert, a Democrat who'd voted for
John F. Kennedy. Nixon was, well, Nixon. Yet it was love at first
sight. In a very real sense, Garment's life has been lived in
Nixon's shadow ever since. (Certainly, few people have written as
acutely about him as Garment has in his 1997 memoir, ``Crazy
Rhythm.'') Can he imagine what his life would have been like had he
never met Nixon?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've avoided thinking about that the way one avoids
thinking about death,'' Garment sighs. ``I was very bored, then he
providentially dropped into 20 Broad St. and became my law partner.
First, it was hilarious . . . then I found myself involved in
politics at the top, organizing a presidential campaign for a very
talented, strange man.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the White House, Nixon gave Garment the catchall title
of special consultant to the president. This made for more
improvisation, assembling a job portfolio from what Garment once
described as ``the distant swamplands of Republican politics'':
arts funding, Native American issues, Southern school
desegregation. It's no coincidence that some of the
administration's most lasting domestic achievements fell in those
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Watergate. In ``Crazy Rhythm,'' Garment explains his
appointment as acting White House counsel this way, ``I was the
last senior White House staffer who (a) had a license to practice
law and (b) was not a potential indictee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the worst patch any president and his staff
ever went through,'' says Harry C. McPherson, a name partner at
Garment's current firm, Verner Liipfert Bernhard McPherson and
Hand. McPherson speaks with some authority on the subject of
embattled presidents: He was special counsel to Lyndon Johnson.
Watergate left Garment eager to leave the nation's capital _ though
former Supreme Court Justice Abe Fortas told him, ``You'll be back.
Washington is just too much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
