<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAVY-TODDLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERWEIGHT GIRL SPARKS CUSTODY FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE _ A half-hour after being told Tuesday that his
3-year-old daughter would remain in foster care, Miguel Regino
somberly watered the lawn in front of his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard,'' said Regino, whose 3-foot-tall, 120-pound
daughter was taken into state custody last month because of her
weight. ``We were just waiting for the baby to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Regino and his wife, Adela Martinez, have been accused by the
state of neglect and failing to follow a prescribed diet for their
daughter. Some doctors have reportedly said the girl ``would surely
die'' if she does not lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   The couple went Children's Court Thursday to seek their
daughter's return. While Regino and his wife still hold out hope,
officials say it is unusual for the state to give full custody so
soon to a family accused of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Tommy Jewell, frustrated with the media frenzy the case
has caused, closed Tuesday's hearing and barred the family and the
lawyers from speaking to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the courtroom, the case of young Anamarie
Martinez-Regino has been monitored by people as far away as
Germany. The case has become the talk of Anamarie's neighborhood,
on radio shows, television news, and the front page of local
newspapers. Nationally, it has stirred debate on ``fat prejudice,''
whether child-neglect cases should remain confidential, and when
the government should forcibly take away a child because of medical
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, candlelight vigils for the family were held in
Albuquerque, Chicago, and San Diego, and a local parent group has
collected hundreds of signatures asking for a federal investigation
into how the state handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Hartz, who heads the state's Children, Youth and
Families Department, emphasized last week that the state was acting
in the best interest of the child. The state says the parents have
not followed a strict diet and have not been able to keep
Anamarie's weight down.
</P>
<P>
   The parents contend the state overstepped its authority when it
took custody of the toddler. The couple say they have done all they
can to help their child overcome a medical problem that doctors
can't explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely frightening case,'' said Leslie Di
Maggio, who chairs the National Association to Advance Fat
Acceptance, which contributed to the family's legal costs.
``Parents of fat children are ashamed, they feel like it's
something they have done. Now, there is the fear on top of it that
their children can be taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the national media attention, Anamarie had quietly
caused a stir in her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the family was friendly and often had friends or
relatives over to visit, but rarely spoke with neighbors since
moving into this lower-middle-class area about six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Anamarie could be seen sitting in a wooden chair in the family's
small, tan, adobe-style home. Sometimes her parents carried her in
a wheelchair. Until recently, she had to use a walker to get
around. Neighbors watched as she played with other children, but
none of them ever thought Anamarie was so young.
</P>
<P>
   From her porch down the street, Carmen Casaus would see the
couple pulling someone out of a car or Regino's truck and placing
the person into a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize she was a child. I thought she was
(Martinez's) mother,'' she said. ``My neighbor said she heard a
baby crying, but I told her that there is no baby over there.''
</P>
<P>
   James Zingelman, who lives a few doors down from the family,
said the couple always waved to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought (Anamarie) was an overweight 8-year-old,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, doctors and social workers have also been curious
and worried about the child.
</P>
<P>
   Anamarie has spent her life in and out of hospitals. Martinez,
an employee at Mesa Airlines, told reporters that 10 to 15 doctors
have treated her daughter and each one has given different advice.
The child has seen nutritionists and pulmonary specialists, and no
one really knows why she is three times heavier than most children
her age.
</P>
<P>
   While the family has said her weight stems from a medical
problem rather than overfeeding, doctors testing the child have
said they found no signs of glandular problems, according to the
Albuquerque Journal, which retrieved an affidavit in the case.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, doctors worried the excess weight
could cause heart damage or death and ordered the parents to keep
Anamarie on a liquid diet. But officials said the parents continued
to feed her solid food. The affidavit suggests that the child's
weight may be the result of Munchausen by Proxy Syndrome, a form of
child abuse in which caregivers make a child sick to gain attention
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 25, the state of New Mexico, which believed the family
wasn't capable of caring for the child, took Anamarie into custody
while she was being examined at Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the parents) love the child and they are trying hard to
get her back,'' said Diane Whiting, a cousin of Martinez. ``She is
a beautiful child. She gets around fast, but right now she needs
her parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Perci C. De Baca, who lives several doors down from Anamarie's
family, shook her head as she watched Regino watering the grass in
the cool evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will keep them in my prayer. I think they need help. The
state should have never taken the child away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Casaus has become far more skeptical of the family down the
street. She looked at her 8-year-old grandson _ thin and full of
energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want my grandson to grow that big,'' she said,
shaking her head. ``If it was me, I would let the state take her,
knowing it's for the betterment of the child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
