<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-SALINGER-ART-2     09-07 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SALINGER-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR DADDY, WITH LOVE AND SQUALOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is an old man now, says the daughter, old and deaf as granite
and more cut off from the world than ever, even from his own
children. Holden Caulfield, his most enduring fictional creation,
fantasized about being a deaf-mute and living in a cabin by the
edge of a forest, passing notes to his deaf-mute spouse. Be careful
what you wish for, the daughter suggests. When fiction becomes your
reality and reality a squalid inconvenience, the line between what
is imagined and what is experienced grows paper-thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I wrestled with in writing this book,'' says
Margaret Salinger, ``was knowing that if I disobeyed him in this
kind of way, there was a good chance he would cut me off like he
cut off everybody else who committed a misdemeanor in his eyes. And
this was not going to be any misdemeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, says Salinger, ``I also realized pretty early on
that this was the death of a wish, not a reality. I'm never going
to have the mommy and daddy I wished for. What I really had to lose
wasn't a whole lot. Even on good terms with him, I never saw my
father much. I miss him, but _ and I don't mean this in a cute way
at all _ I miss my daddy, not my father. There's not a lot there to
miss.''
</P>
<P>
   He, of course, is Jerome David Salinger, now 81, the Howard
Hughes of American letters, who settled in tiny Cornish, N.H.,
nearly 50 years ago and who, having written ``The Catcher in the
Rye,'' the definitive postwar American novel about adolescence and
alienation, plus having also produced a handful of the truly
classic short stories of his literary generation, pulled up the
ladder into the treehouse and vanished inside.
</P>
<P>
   J. D. Salinger has published no new work since 1965. He has
granted almost no interviews in half a century. He has visited
legal punishment upon at least one biographer and has threatened
others with lawsuits or worse. His relationships with a succession
of women much younger than he, including the writer Joyce Maynard,
have raised questions about his Humbert-like obsession with
feminine youth and vulnerability. He has been portrayed by Maynard
and others as an eccentric recluse whose interests include Zen
Buddhism, orgone boxes, Christian Science dogma, Scientology,
homeopathic medicine, speaking in tongues, and drinking urine.
</P>
<P>
   He may have 20 unpublished novels sitting in his desk drawer
somewhere. He may have none. He might set fire to every one of them
before he departs this planet. He might not. Nobody knows, although
a lot of people still purport to care.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Peggy Salinger, 44, a first-time author and hospital
chaplain living in the Boston area, with the most intimate portrait
yet of her father's cloistered _ and apparently not altogether
happy _ existence. ``Dream Catcher: A Memoir'' (Pocket Books) is
not a full-scale Salinger biography, by any means. It is not an
exercise in literary criticism, either, although she draws many
explicit connections between her father's work and what she knows,
directly or indirectly, about his life. Nor is it, as she says with
wrinkled nose, a ``smutty tell-all,'' a veiled reference to
Maynard's kiss-and-tell memoir about life inside the Salinger
boudoir.
</P>
<P>
   It is instead what the book advertises itself to be, an often
brutally honest, first-person account of Life With Father (and
Mother). A reckoning of his life before moving to Cornish and of
the author's life after she grew up and moved away. And yes, Peggy
Salinger is well aware that she will be accused _ as Jonathan
Yardley did in a scalding review in last week's Washington Post _
of invading her father's ``cherished privacy to the point of
disloyalty and exploitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Salinger, arching her eyebrows, ``Disloyalty? There was no
loyalty toward us. Only loyalty toward him, always. To the point of
my having taken a bunch of pills once and wanting to go to the
hospital, but calling ahead so that his name _ his name _ would not
get into the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exploitation?'' she continues, her angular cheekbones frozen
in an expression strikingly similar to early photos of her father.
``That's in the eye of the beholder, really. I certainly do not
labor under the illusion that if I were Peggy MacDonald and had
written a book of similar quality, I'd be getting the same
attention. A lot of people write terrific books no one hears about.
But as my brother'' _ Matt Salinger, a Hollywood actor and producer
_ ``once said, `The name may get you in the door, but boy, you had
better come through.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Let one thing be clear, Salinger goes on to say with convincing
passion. There is a difference between privacy and secrecy, as
there is a difference between parental authority and child abuse.
Between the right to worship freely and to operate a religious
cult, its members walled off like POWs from the rest of society.
Had her father practiced what he preached in his fiction, she
maintains, railing against ``phonies'' and cultural narcissists,
she would not have written this book _ not the same book,
certainly. In that sense, however, J. D. Salinger was a hypocrite.
The ultimate phony. What goes around, come around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had less of a sense of boundaries and privacy, of what you
do or do not say in front of children, than almost anyone I've ever
met,'' says Salinger, with a mixture of resentment and genuine
wonder. What pushed her over the edge, she avers, what drove her to
risk violating his ``cherished privacy'' _ and thus permanently
alienate the father she still claims to love _ was a search for a
level of understanding that she might pass along to her own son. A
search that was touched off, like a brushfire, with a pair of
conversations she had with her parents when she was 37 and
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   During one of those conversations, Salinger writes, her father
advised her to have an abortion. She was stunned, she says. She was
not, after all, some hapless unwed teenager. She was working on her
second postgraduate degree. She had a career going. She had already
been through years of therapy. His solipsism amazed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not make sense of this father I had loved and
worshiped, and who I thought loved me, treating me the way I
wouldn't treat my own worst enemy,'' recalls Salinger, a faraway
look in her eyes. ``So I called my mother and said, `Has he lost
his mind? Has Daddy gone crazy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not the first time that question has been raised, Salinger is
reminded during a recent interview in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I came to it a little late!'' she giggles in reponse.
``Anyway, I called my mother, and there was this long pause on the
other end of the phone. `Peggy,' she said, `he's done this before.
He did it when I was pregnant. With you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her blue eyes light up with sparks. ``In a sense, it was so
outrageous,'' the daughter says, almost hissing now, ``that it gave
me permission to question everything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a world nearly devoid of living people.'' So
begins the 436-page book that is being released this week, after a
campaign of extraordinary secrecy to keep it out of the hands of J.
D. Salinger and his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The book is divided into three sections. Part 1 covers the years
from 1900 to 1955 and includes previously unreported details about
her parents' family histories. Part 2 focuses on life in Cornish
through 1968, when Peggy was dispatched to boarding school around
the time her parents divorced. Part 3, while providing tantalizing
glimpses of her father's monkish existence, mostly follows the
author on her own troublesome path into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The first section will likely interest Salinger scholars the
most. Drawing on interviews with family members, including Doris
Salinger, J. D.'s sister, it delves into Salinger's childhood in
Manhattan, where he grew up the son of a prosperous Jewish food
merchant and Irish-Catholic mother who often passed herself off as
being Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   (Salinger's issues with being half-Jewish, and with
anti-Semitism in general, not only are marbled throughout his
fiction but are distinguishing parts of his psyche, this book and
others about him amply document.)
</P>
<P>
   After military school, he served with the 12th Infantry Regiment
during World War II, landing on Omaha Beach on D-Day with the rest
of the Allied forces. He later suffered an episode of battle
fatigue that put him in the hospital and out of the Army,
eventually. His wartime experiences traumatized Salinger to a
degree that has perhaps been underappreciated up until now, the
book suggests. Saving Private Salinger?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finally read his earlier stories,'' says the daughter,
who did not even pick up ``The Catcher In The Rye'' until she was
in her mid-20s, ``I first recognized the daddy I know and loved.
The soldier I knew, not the writer I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
