<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-SALINGER-2ND &LR;  &UR;      09-07 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SALINGER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... I didn't know.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around the Cornish house, she says, there were Army songs and
Army stories and Army-era films _ not other writers and discussions
of literature and such. His first wife, a mysterious woman named
Sylvia, had been a Nazi party member whom Salinger met when he
arrested her. Sylvia was, according to Peggy, someone who ``hated
Jews as much as he hated Nazis,'' an interesting dynamic, to say
the least. The marriage lasted less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Douglas, wife number two, was 16 when Salinger met her
(he was 31). The daughter of upper-class Brits, Douglas had been
shipped off to America during the war and survived a trans-Atlantic
passage that included witnessing another shipful of children being
sunk by German torpedoes. She was 5 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping out of Radcliffe her senior year to wed Salinger _
Douglas had also been briefly married once before _ she exhibited
symptoms of severe depression as a young bride and mother living in
extreme rural isolation. Her daughter likens Douglas to a college
student who has been recruited for cult membership, and in one
instance to Lady Macbeth. At one point, her mother may have
deliberately set fire to the Cornish house. Earlier, before seeking
psychiatric help, Douglas had flirted with the notion of killing
her daughter and then herself, Salinger writes. At her husband's
urging, she did burn all her personal papers, along with most
bridges to the outside world. Together the couple began exploring
yoga, Eastern religions, and ``alternate realities.'' The most
alternate of these realities, the daughter maintains, was the one
Salinger created for himself and those around him.
</P>
<P>
   While sympathetic to her mother's situation _ a Jungian
therapist, Douglas, who never remarried, lives in California _
Salinger says they are not particularly close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost better to stay crazy, I think,'' she says, ``than
to realize how much you've damaged your kids. But you also can't
make up for what's lost. And I'm not owed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The book's middle section likewise deepens what is known about
Salinger, particularly during his still-productive years as an
author. Margaret Salinger (not Phoebe, as her father wanted to name
her, after Holden Caulfield's younger sister) was born in December
1955. On the one hand, she writes, her father was a doting parent
who made up enchanting bedtime stories and played ball out back
with his kids. During trips to Manhattan, he took her to the Plaza
Hotel (they traveled under assumed names, like CIA operatives) and
to lunch at the Algonquin with Peggy's godfather, New Yorker editor
William Shawn. It was a childhood ``lush with make-believe,'' she
writes, ``a world that dangled between dream and nightmare on a
gossamer thread my parents wove.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, says the daughter, the nightmares frequently
blotted out the sunny days. There were bitter fights waged in front
of the kids. A miscarried fetus that young Peggy found and
innocently flushed down a toilet. Secrets that were kept from
Daddy, support that was bitterly withheld from Mom. A sense early
on, as Salinger describes it, that ``I was the only grown-up in the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The third section may reveal more than most readers care to know
about Peggy Salinger's later life _ though she says she can handle
that criticism, too. The bare-bones facts are these: that after
surviving (no other word seems apt) a harrowing experience at an
Adirondacks boarding school, she graduated from the Cambridge
School of Weston and Brandeis University, received an Oxford
degree, and is currently one internship shy of a Harvard Divinity
School degree. An accomplished skier and onetime college basketball
team captain at Oxford, she also worked as a Boston Edison garage
mechanic for five years, among a variety of jobs she has held. She
sings with the Tanglewood chorus. Like her mother, she has married
twice _ once to her then karate instructor, briefly, and then to
her current husband, Larry, a former Boston Opera Company singer
who does voice-overs for commercials. Unlike her father, Peggy
Salinger did not marry someone 50 years her junior. She says that
his third wife, a nurse, has shown kindness toward his children and
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Maynard, who was roundly condemned for having
spilled secrets about her father in her 1998 memoir, then
auctioning off a batch of letters from him for a princely sum?
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a parent changes your view of a lot of things,'' says
Salinger. ``Say you have an 18-year-old daughter at Yale, and she
meets a 53-year-old man. He seduces her into going up to live with
him. How many parents do you know who would dress her up for the
sacrifice? Or would you go ask the guy, `How attached to your knees
are you?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have little sympathy for older guys, be they Clinton or my
father, who get involved with younger girls who are supposed to
keep their secrets,'' the daughter says. ``If you don't want it
told, keep it zipped. That's how I feel. Joyce has a right to her
story, even if I didn't want to read the icky stuff. But `How dare
she violate his privacy?' That's a bunch of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   In answer to those who question her own motives for publishing
``Dream Catcher,'' Salinger says that without the discipline of
having to meet a publisher's deadline _ and without the financial
support provided by a book contract _ she might never have seen the
project through. The price she has to pay? A father's (so far)
deafening silence. A painful interruption in her relationship with
her brother. And yes, she could have withheld publication until
after her father dies, but ``something felt sneaky about waiting.
It felt like shooting someone in the back. Maybe God or whoever
will judge me, but it felt less wrong somehow _ or more right _ to
do this while he was still alive and able to take the punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   When J. D. Salinger does pass away, says the daughter, she has
no idea what will happen to the stories and novels millions of his
fans await reading. ``The Catcher in the Rye'' continues to sell
thousands of copies a year. Reporters, schoolkids, and middle-aged
adolescents still crouch in the trees outside the Cornish house,
hoping for a glimpse of the famous recluse. There will be an
explosion _ no, a re-explosion _ of interest in all he has written.
Or not written.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Salinger insists her father hasn't figured out that final
chapter of his biography yet, at least as far as she knows. But in
all likelihood, she concedes, it will not be herself and her
brother put in charge of his literary estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I wouldn't be a bad choice, actually,'' she says,
unable to suppress a smile. ``I don't cheat. I don't have this
great anger people imagine I have toward my father. I don't blame
him for anything. I'd probably do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she adds with emphasis, ``It's not a job I want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
