<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE GOES THE OLD NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Like everyone else, I sometimes have trouble getting through
to a favorite online destination. Usually that's cause for
annoyance, weary resignation, or even anger. When it happened to me
the other night, I felt rather sad.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't logged onto the venerable CompuServe online service
since May. During my absence, the credit card that paid for my
subscription had expired, and so I had to phone in and get my
account reinstated. But as I recited the digits on my new card, a
sour, sorry thought came to me: What's the point?
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, a younger, poorer edition of me would
sometimes be cut off from CompuServe for being late about the bill.
In those days it was nearly as bad as having the electricity
switched off. Back then, CompuServe was as close as ordinary people
could get to the Internet. With its teeming, bawdy chatrooms and
sophisticated, orderly discussion forums, a night on CompuServe was
like a walking tour of an unusually exciting city.
</P>
<P>
   These days there are many such towns online, and no longer is
CompuServe anywhere near the best of them. CompuServe's parent
company, America Online Inc., is its toughest competitor. Back when
CompuServe was still an independent company, its officials and
customers would mock the housewives and tow-truck drivers that AOL
signed up by the tens of thousands. They all knew that CompuServe
users were the smart ones _ doctors, lawyers, airline pilots, and,
of course, computer people. These brainy, stable people weren't the
sort who'd drop out after using up their hundred free hours.
Instead, they'd kept coming back year after year, establishing
CompuServe's network of congenial communities.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the CompuServe loyalists remain. Unfortunately, few
newcomers are joining them. In 1998, when it was acquired by AOL,
Compuserve boasted 2 million members. Over three years later,
Compuserve now boasts a staggering . . . 2.8 million members. The
flagship AOL service grew from 11 million to 24 million in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe general manager Audrey Weil prefers to look at the
sunny side, calling her service's growth ``a huge turnaround.''
Weil credits a $400 rebate to computer buyers who sign up for three
years of CompuServe for roping in 1.3 million new subscribers in
the past fiscal year, though she won't say much about the
half-million subscribers who must have fallen away in that period.
And she notes that CompuServe turns a profit for AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no getting around the fact that CompuServe just
doesn't matter any more. If you want chat rooms, the Internet's
awash in them. Free e-mail service is almost as commonplace as
spam. As for the superb forums where CompuServers go for expert
information on hundreds of topics, there are plenty more like them
at every Web portal, not to mention 50,000 or so on the Usenet.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe has tried to enliven its forums by opening them up to
nonmembers. Anyone can now go to forums.compuserve.com, get a free
screen name, and sign on. It's a welcome feature, but it won't give
the newbies much of an incentive to become paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe has even abandoned the elite swagger of old. Weil now
says that the company is targeting ``the new consumer.'' She admits
that new subscribers will spend little time debating the best hard
drive; they'll be too busy reading the latest celebrity gossip.
``We're taking a tack where we see the most growth,'' Weil said.
``The customer that we're getting through rebates is a little bit
different than the traditional, serious CompuServe customer.'' As a
matter of fact, they're targeting AOL customers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I've already got an AOL account. Far from despising that
plebeian service, I think it's earned a place in history as the
company that democratized the Internet. Besides, it provides a
basic set of online services that are accessible from pretty much
any city on earth. I wouldn't dream of letting my AOL account
lapse. But as for CompuServe, I've pretty much abandoned the old
neighborhood, and only 15 years of loyalty keeps me paying the
rent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
