<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS' QUESTIONS ARE AS VARIED AS THE CARS THEY DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bugs that eat oil, breaking 150 miles per hour on a two-lane
road at night, and who was Rat Fink's daddy? More of your mail,
more of my answers:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 82-year-old father, who lives on Cape Cod, bought a brand
new 2000 Volkswagen Golf several months ago. It seems to be burning
an excessive amount of oil. The dealer says it is normal for these
modern cars with ``high tolerance'' engines. The car burned a quart
of oil in the first 1,000 miles. He was told this would continue
and he should put a quart in every 1,000 and at intervals of 6,000
and 20,000 miles it will improve. Does this sound right?
</P>
<P>
   A. Question for the dealer: Where's the oil going? The folks at
Volkswagen tell me the first oil that should go into a new VW is at
the 5,000-mile oil change. High tolerance engines are everywhere
and they don't burn oil like that. Is your father's car smoking?
And what was that dealer smoking? Call me and give me the dealer's
name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You automotive journalists kill me. You'd think you perceive
yourselves as gods descended to Earth. You drive a Porsche at more
than 175 miles per hour (back in June) at a known speed trials test
site and you get a plaque for doing it. Big deal! Try going over
150 miles per hour in a stone-stock 1988 5.0 Mustang on a two-lane
road at night . . . I could have gone faster but my windows were
open.
</P>
<P>
   A. You, sir, are a doofus. You say I have a god-complex because
I drive fast on a desert where I endanger only myself, yet you take
into your hands not only your own life but the lives of anyone you
may encounter by driving probably three times the speed limit on a
back road. And why were your windows open? So you could toss the
empty long-neck beer bottles out as you whizzed along?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm on a hunt for information about a redesigned Ford
Explorer for model year 2002. They are keeping it all very
hush-hush. We aren't necessarily looking for a significantly larger
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's not really all that hush-hush. The Explorer and Mercury
Mountaineer will share a larger platform, offer three rows of seats
and independent rear suspension. For smaller versions of the
Explorer, consider the Sport Trac and the Explorer Sport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the prize for letting you know that the nickname ``Big
Daddy'' referred to the drag racer Don Garlits, not Ed Roth, the
artist and auto designer?
</P>
<P>
   A. Garlits gave us Swamp Rats, Roth gave us Rat Fink, a host of
other characters, and great, radical cars. Countless hours were
spent by countless young boys trying to recreate the drawings of Ed
``Big Daddy'' Roth as they whiled away time in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've ordered a Toyota Tundra V8 Access Cab 4WD but I can't
seem to get a commitment on having one delivered with ABS. I get
the feeling Toyota does not want to provide the ABS option. I am
moving to Vermont and my new home will be located three miles up a
dirt road and has a very steep driveway.
</P>
<P>
   A. Toyota says there should not be a problem getting ABS for
your Tundra. Let me know if this problem persists _ you may have a
dealer playing games with you. One question, though: You mention
tough sledding where you are going to live. ABS is a brake system
and is not going to help you with traction the way a traction
control system would help. It will help you stop, but won't help
you go. And the Tundra does not come with traction control.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I think you transposed numbers in your story about the Dual
Ghia with the Chrysler hemi engine. The 1957-58 hemi was 392 cubic
inches, not 329.
</P>
<P>
   A. You, sir, are no doofus. You are correct and I'll try to type
better in the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is wrong? Column after column dwells on pretensions . .
. trips by you to silly racing strips courtesy of advertisers . . .
absence of emphasis on autos with sound engineering and real
mechanical class. Have you ever heard of principles of parsimony
and minimalism?
</P>
<P>
   A. You, sir . . . . Ah yes, parsimony and minimalism. I found
those once _ in the Yugo. You've probably got one of those babies
parked in your yard in Maine right now and have time to write hate
mail to me because your car won't start. But to the point: I do not
travel anywhere on the tab of advertisers or auto manufacturers. If
I do, I get fired. And no emphasis on sound engineering? Buddy,
there are hundreds of models of great autos being built these days
and if I have failed to review the one you admire, then keep
watching _ I'll get to the Tucker yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. It is my belief that if you encouraged a single driver to buy
a (more powerful, tuned suspension) Roush Ford Expedition by raving
about how nimble and free of dangerous pitch it is, you have done a
great disservice.
</P>
<P>
   A. The point of the Roush review, from the opening sentence, was
that all those folks who drive their SUVs as if they were in a
Roush are jerks. These are the people you need to watch out for _
not the handful who drive the Roush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does Ford plan to offer power seats in the popular Focus?
</P>
<P>
   A. Ford says no. There just isn't enough demand for power seats
in a car in that price range and of that size. They looked at it,
but it ended up way down the list of potential improvements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-07 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ECONOMY PRESSED TO THE LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The unemployment rate ticked up a bit in August. Consumers
aren't spending as freely as they once did. The economy as a whole
seems to be slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you explain the fact that big chunks of the economy
appear to be bursting at the seams, with demand outrunning supply
and prices climbing at a scary rate?
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few examples:
</P>
<P>
   --The price of oil hit $34 dollars a barrel Wednesday on fears
that oil-producing nations will not pump enough oil this winter.
The current price represents a 10-year high. A year ago oil sold
for $18 a barrel; in January 1999 the price was $11.
</P>
<P>
   --Natural gas prices are twice as high as they were a year and a
half ago.
</P>
<P>
   --Parts of the country have experienced sharp spikes in the
price of electricity as utilities scramble to come up with enough
power. In California some customers have seen their bills triple.
Locally, the electric utilities are asking for rate hikes of up to
12 percent this fall.
</P>
<P>
   --The price of air travel has climbed 9.5 percent over the past
year. Planes are full, the skies are congested, and the number of
late flights is at a record high.
</P>
<P>
   --In Boston, the cost of renting an apartment has increased 9
percent in the past year and for two-bedroom apartments, more than
80 percent over the past five years. According to one account,
there were only 150 apartments available for rent this September
citywide, about one-third the usual number. In the regular housing
market the story is much the same: lots of demand, little supply,
and rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressing against the limits is the story of this economy,''
said Fred Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to see why we have come to this point. The
American economy has been growing since 1991, the longest expansion
in the nation's history. More than that, the economy has been
growing much faster than anticipated. The result has been a surge
in demand, which in many cases, has caught people unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   In the new economy, keeping up with growth is not that
difficult. You hire more people; add some servers, routers, and
computers; and bingo, you can handle the increased load.
</P>
<P>
   But in parts of the old economy, life isn't that simple. Supply
doesn't automatically come on line when you snap your fingers. In
fact, it can take years to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the energy business. Because prices were low for so
long, oil and gas companies didn't invest much in finding or
producing new supplies. Inventories for both fuels are at the
lowest level in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   With prices soaring, those companies today have a big incentive
to find more. But it could be several years before supply meets
demand again. In the meantime we can all expect to pay more to
drive our cars and heat our homes.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is even worse in other fields. In California, no
major electric power plants have been built in the past 10 years.
Because of the long lead times involved, no new plants are expected
to come on line before 2002.
</P>
<P>
   On the air travel front, only three new runways were put into
service at the nation's major airports between 1995 and 1999. In
Boston, new apartment buildings, especially ones that cater to the
middle-class, are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the barrier to building new supply is cost. Sometimes
it is lack of space. And sometimes it is a case of ``Not In My Back
Yard.'' Who wants to live next door to an electric power plant or a
new runway? Just ask the residents of East Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers and investors, all of these imbalances raise a
critical question: Are these isolated examples or are they
forerunners of a more general inflation problem that comes when you
push an economy beyond its limits?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they are isolated,'' said Nicholas Perna, an
economic consultant based in Connecticut. Perna isn't forecasting a
big rise in prices, but he suggests that most economists and
investors may be overly optimistic in their inflation projections
for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more upbeat. Mark Zandi, chief economist at
Economy.com, a forecasting firm, points out that big productivity
gains in manufacturing and service have allowed the economy to grow
without creating an inflation problem. Wednesday the government
reported that productivity grew at a whopping 5.7 percent pace in
the second quarter. When productivity is rising, companies can pay
higher wages while keeping their prices flat.
</P>
<P>
   Zandi still worries about the tight labor market, but even
there, there is no evidence yet that a lack of workers is pushing
wages up at a worrisome rate.
</P>
<P>
   We don't pretend to have the answer to the inflation question,
but the bottlenecks in the economy suggest an important and humbing
lesson:
</P>
<P>
   That while we all love to talk about the magic of the new
economy, we all spend a good chunk of our time and money in the old
economy where the rules of the game haven't changed very much.
</P>
<P>
   Keep that in mind when you pay your fuel bill this winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
