<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITEMENT UNDER THE LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is a night-time town, a town of saloon singers
(`` . . . gimme one more for the road . . . '') and heavy swingers.
Since 1975, when the US Open discovered Edison, the most stirring
conflicts usually havebeen staged after dark, under floodlights.
</P>
<P>
   Whether filling the venerable concrete horseshoe at Forest Hills
or the more modern Flushing Meadows canyon lined with blue seats
and called Arthur Ashe Stadium, the crowds are a throwback to the
old days of ballpark title fights at Yankee Stadium and the Polo
Grounds, when the customers were hyped-up with anticipation of
mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was that kind of night at the US Open. You could
feel the excitement. Joe Louis and Max Schmeling weren't going to
reappear, and neither were Rocky Marciano, Sugar Ray Robinson,
Carmen Basilio, or Billy Conn. But it's the same idea in tennis,
man against man _ or woman against woman _ probing for a knockout.
The patrons were primed for heavy-fisted swinging of rackets. Which
they got.
</P>
<P>
   On the card were four nifty bangers, each a major champ: Serena
Williams against Lindsay Davenport and Pete Sampras against Richard
Krajicek in quarterfinal matches. Their credentials were in order:
knockout punchers all.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras may have been afraid of the dark as a child, but no
more. He's a nocturnal werewolf at Flushing Meadows, a perfect 15-0
once the sun goes down, shooting the moon as he did while eclipsing
his leading rival for the title, Richard Krajicek, 4-6, 7-6 (8-6),
6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Counterpunching furiously as he rose from the floor in the
second set at 2-6 down in the tie-breaker, Sampras pushed his
greatness button and soared through six successive points, five of
them winners. That left Krajicek, the Frying Dutchman, burnt out
and ready for the kill that came with one final overhead right from
Sampras _ a service winner _ liberating the witnesses at 1:05 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying as heavyweights in their own division, Williams and
Davenport, a pair of US Open champions, slugged at each other as
though the world was at stake. Their world was, even though it
won't really be decided until the final Saturday. But Williams, who
came in as the reigning champ, won't be there, even if her sister,
Venus, might be.
</P>
<P>
   With a weak backhand poke of a second serve into the net,
Williams yielded. The queen of 1999 was dead, 6-4, 6-2, and the
queen of 1998, Davenport, was standing and beaming and ready to
chase an 18-year-old Russian beauty, Elena Dementieva, out of the
semifinals and out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Was the half moon crowning the crisp, clear evening an omen the
Williams kids' assault on the Open might not be the full-blown
dream of Papa Richard: both Venus and Serena in the title bout? Now
it's up to the Wimbledon titleholder, Venus, to hold up her half
Friday against yet another champ, Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams and Davenport went at each other immediately,
although they were 18 minutes late in starting _ upholding a US
Open tradition of tardiness. Wimbledon administrators, in their
punctuality, often wonder whether clocks have reached the Colonies
yet.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a late crowd, too, knowing there wouldn't be a
knockout in the first minutes such as Muhammad Ali delivered to
Charles (Sonny) Liston at Lewiston, Maine, in 1965. By the time the
Lilac Lady _ Williams in purple shoes and skirt _ and Long Lindsay
were heated up, the audience had expanded to 23,137, and the fans
had forgotten the chill of the evening amid the warmth of the
torrid shotmaking.
</P>
<P>
   It took Davenport 89 minutes to reverse her semifinal loss to
Little Sister Serena of a year ago. Davenport overcame an immediate
crisis the first time she served, ducking three break points, and
was on her way. Despite Williams's superior speed, Davenport had
the edge in footwork, ever in position to drive forehands and
double-barreled backhands to the corners that kept Williams
constantly commuting.
</P>
<P>
   This felt good to the tallest woman ever to hold a major
championship, and 6-foot-3-inch Davenport kept doling out the
punishment. Why not? After all, Williams had pushed her around five
straight times.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport knifed through Williams's serve for a 5-4 lead, and
she was off on a six-game procession that took her to 4-0 in the
second set.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was staggering, missing too many shots, but her
fighting spirit never diminished. Davenport was wary. She could
recall their most recent meeting, a final three weeks ago at
Manhattan Beach, Calif. Davenport had served for that title at 6-5
in the third _ and Williams had permitted her just one more point,
winning in a conclusive tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the 18-year-old Williams fought like a tigress
protecting kittens as she trailed, 1-5. The championship belt was
slipping. But that seventh game _ a 10 minute ordeal _ seemed like
``a title game'' to Davenport. She had Williams on the ropes,
pummeling her, and five times was on the verge of a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Five match points. But Williams bobbed and weaved, escaping each
of them, twice with aces, jabbing and whacking desperately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a game. Seemed like it meant everything,'' Davenport
said. ``But when I lost it, I looked up at the scoreboard and it
was 5-2. Two breaks. I was comfortable.'' And she served it out
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   The Davenport crowd roared delightedly, and the Williams crowd
sighed mournfully at their girl's last shriek as her last shot
stung the net. It was time to go out for a beer and wait for two
more heavyweights: Sampras, shaking the cobwebs of four set points
in his tie-breaker resurrection to flatten Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   You could hear from the ozone the tribute of the bygone Boston
boxing promoter, Sam Silverman: ``That Sampras is the iron, a
double-tough Greek. He takes it on the lug but gets up from the
dead. Let's go eat Chinese and drink some stingers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
