<SLUG> BC-KNOW-NOTHINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVEALING THE KNOW-NOTHINGS' DARK MOTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ The spidery scrawl is faded by the passage of a
century and a half, but there is no mistaking the fearful and
bigoted message. A slogan atop the first page reads, ``Put none but
Americans on Guard.''
</P>
<P>
   What follows in a document just acquired by Boston College is
the oath taken by Boston members of a secretive political
organization known popularly as the Know-Nothing Party. Five pages
of light blue paper, dated Oct. 13, 1854, outline the stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``To defend our Republic Institutions against the encroachments
of the Church of Rome . . . and its ignorant and deluded
followers,'' it reads, ``we are associated on a secret Military
Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Prospective members were then directed to ``raise your right
hand up before the floating flag of your country (and) place your
right foot on the emblem of the Church of Rome,'' then pledge to
``carry out the objects of this Institution,'' including going to
the assistance of ``a comrade attacked by foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   The document, said Boston College historian Thomas H. O'Connor,
``confirms the anti-Catholic nature of the Know-Nothing movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Know-Nothing document was purchased from Stuart Lutz, a
historical document dealer in New Jersey, who brought it to Boston
College's notice earlier this year. He had acquired it in what he
described as ``a big pile of random paper,'' including letters and
other 19th-century documents.
</P>
<P>
   Both O'Connor and Robert K. O'Neill, director of the Burns
rare-book library at Boston College, said their research has failed
to uncover any similar document dealing with the inner affairs of
the Know-Nothing movement.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill described it as a major addition to the Burns Library's
collection of documents relating to the history of the Irish in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While now rating little more than a footnote, when mentioned at
all, the Know-Nothing Party dominated politics in Massachusetts for
a brief period. In 1854, on the heels of victories in Boston and
other cities, it swept the governorship and other state offices,
all congressional seats, and all state Senate seats, and won all
but one state House seat _ and seemed poised to strongly contest
the presidential election of 1856.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a revisionist tendency in recent years, said
O'Connor, to downplay the anti-immigrant and anti-Catholic bias of
the Know-Nothing Party and instead portray it as a progressive
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you read this,'' O'Connor said, referring to the
oath, ``the blatancy of the anti-Catholicism is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Know-Nothing movement developed in the early 1850s, presaged
by locally based nativist movements that triggered such events as
the burning of the Ursuline convent in Charlestown (now Somerville)
in 1834 and the riot on Broad Street between Yankee firefighters
returning from a fire and Irish mourners in a funeral procession.
But the national movement was fueled by the huge wave of Irish
immigration following the famines of the 1840s. Its leaders,
O'Connor said, realized that control of immigration could happen
only on a national level.
</P>
<P>
   Organized officially as the American Party, it acquired its
popular name because members were instructed to answer with a
``don't know'' when asked about its leaders, membership, funds, or
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people wanted to get off the mark quickly,'' O'Connor
said. ``They didn't want to get bogged down by questions about
their membership or finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical Know-Nothing members, writes Babson history professor
John R. Mulkern in his 1990 book, ``The Know-Nothing Party in
Massachusetts,'' were ``Yankee mechanics, factory workers, common
laborers, clerks, small jobbers, tradesmen and struggling
entrepreneurs in the cities and larger towns (who) had to live
cheek by jowl with impoverished foreigners and face daily the
challenge that Irish Catholics posed to the neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there was a political vacuum in the state,
caused by the failure of antislavery Democrats and Whigs to
coalesce into the new Republican Party, as they had in other
states. Despite its political success in Massachusetts, Maryland,
and several other northern states, the Know-Nothing movement
collapsed as quickly as it had arisen.
</P>
<P>
   During the spring of 1856, even as the Know-Nothings were
confidently gearing up for the presidential election, O'Connor
said, ``the slavery issue blew up.'' In May, John Brown and several
of his followers murdered five pro-slavery settlers in Kansas in
retaliation for a raid on Lawrence, Kan., known as the ``Boston
abolition town.'' Then, Massachusetts senator Charles Sumner was
attacked and beaten on the Senate floor by an outraged Southern
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   The slavery issue clearly had the power to destroy the Union,
O'Connor said, and ``divided people along slavery lines, rather
than religious lines.'' The importance of the issue led to the
formation of the Republican Party. The Know-Nothings ran former
president Millard Fillmore for president, but carried only
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Know-Nothing members, O'Connor said, most went into
the Republican Party _ even though its future leader, Abraham
Lincoln, had explicitly refused to join the Know- Nothing Party
when invited to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
