<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND EARNING ALL A'S FOR EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A playoff team may very well have been in action at
Fenway Park Wednesday night, but it's probably not the one people
around here think.
</P>
<P>
   With their 6-4 victory over the Red Sox nicely coupled with
Seattle's loss to the Blue Jays, the Oakland Athletics are just a
game and a half behind the Mariners in the American League West. No
one has a sweeter stretch run schedule. These guys aren't even
discussing the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I talk to the press I tell them we're just focusing
on one thing, and that's the division,'' says manager Art Howe.
``The other thing, people are coming behind you, or alongside you.
They come from all directions. We're not worried about that. This
was a big game for us. Cleveland, who knows? We don't even look at
their scores any more.''
</P>
<P>
   That was one happy bunch of A's who jumped on that plane for the
long ride into the night. They closed out a 4-2 road trip and now
head back home to play Tampa Bay for four. And, as far as we know,
their general manager hasn't said anything lately to rile up the
last-place Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those four games, the A's will also play 15 more
games against teams with losing records. They've already dealt with
the iron. The only games they have left with anyone on the plus
side of the standings are the four with Seattle, and those are four
games they really want to play, since they currently fear nobody.
</P>
<P>
   They're certainly as lovable as any team in the league. They've
got that slow-pitch softball look with the likes of Jason Giambi
and Matt Stairs, who said he fulfilled a long-standing ambition by
curling a third-inning home run around Pesky Pole. They've got some
nice young positional talent in the form of shortstop Miguel
Tejada, third baseman Eric Chavez, and center fielder Terrence
Long, who made the defensive play of the game by leaning into the
Oakland bullpen to take a sure game-tying two-run homer away from
Jason Varitek in the seventh. They have some superb young arms with
pitchers like Tim Hudson, Barry Zito, and Wednesday night's starter
(and winner) Mark Mulder. They have quality veterans like Gil
Heredia, Kevin Appier, and Mike Stanley. They even have the oldest
currently active player in the league (now that Jesse Orosco is on
the disabled list) in 43-year-old reliever Doug Jones.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting mix, but the public image sees them more in
terms of the kids than anything else. Stanley hasn't been with the
team very long, but it's long enough to arrive at the conclusion
that in this case youth is not being wasted on the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts out here with just plain desire,'' he maintains.
``People keep talking about the youth here, and every time
something goes wrong people say, `Oh, they're too young,' but
nobody's more experienced than Seattle and look at the problems
they've had. These pitchers may be young, but there are some great
arms, like that kid tonight. And Barry Zito. And Tim Hudson.
There's a lot of poise on that mound.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to face them,'' decided Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   The kid in question was Mulder, a primo prospect who was the
second player chosen in the 1998 draft. The lefthander has had good
days and bad days in this rookie season (he's 8-10, 5.57), but he
clearly has the raw talent, and this was a quality six innings of
work in a pennant race game. Afterward he stood around and talked
as if he had just won a game in the Pioneer League, or even the
Cape League, where he once performed for the Bourne Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to know what you're doing,'' he shrugged.
``You've got to go after guys, and you've got to be aggressive. It
might be my first year, but that's the way I approach it. I know I
can pitch like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson is 15-6 in his second year. There's no doubt that he can
pitch. And though Zito has only made nine big league starts (3-3,
3.12), he has managers and pitching coaches salivating all over the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Mix these kids in with outstanding young players like Giambi,
Tejada, Chavez, and Long, and you have a very intriguing club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some excellent young pitchers and some excellent
young position players,'' confirms Oakland coach Ken Macha, who
managed in the Red Sox system. ``Tejada is a good player. He's
going to join those other couple or three (shortstops) at the head
of the class pretty soon. Chavez is coming along at third. Terrence
Long has a chance to hit 20 homers and score 100 runs. There are a
lot of good young players here. We have a chance to make the
playoffs this year, and we should do nothing but get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The architect of all this is general manager Billy Beane, who
has done a sensational job of managing his limited resources.
Whatever kind of market a $32 million payroll makes you, that's
what the Oakland A's are. And if that isn't enough to make you root
for the A's, consider that are essentially unloved in their own
backyard. The payroll and the attendance (12th in the league) go
hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Howe basically issued a plea for people to come out and back
them down the stretch. ``It would be nice,'' he sighs. ``It would
show that the fans appreciate the effort these guys have given.
Some fan support would be greatly appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it would be fun to play in a sold-out stadium every
night,'' says Mulder. ``But it's something we've accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Something always seems to get in the way of public acceptance
out there. The fact is that as worthy as the A's are, nothing they
can do will distract people from what's happening across the Bay,
where the first place Giants play before sellout crowds in
everybody's new favorite ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   So that leads us to the ultimate possibility _ a second Bay Area
World Series. Nobody's talking about it, but as you look around
baseball in the year 2000, is it that ludicrous an idea? Who's so
great that the A's and Giants can't dream?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the A's have positioned themslves perfectly to decide
their own fate. ``I see it in everybody's eyes, every day,''
contends Long. Whatever that ``it'' is, one thing it most
definitely isn't is fear. These guys are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan can be reached by e-mail at ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
