<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-CENSUS-ADJUST-$ADV10-     09-07 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-ADJUST-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEGAL FIGHT OVER CENSUS DATA COULD SHAPE POLITICS FOR A DECADE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The battle brewing in a federal courthouse here
could shape America's political landscape for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court's review of a Virginia election law has emerged
as an all-important test case in the politically charged issue of
whether states should redraw their legislative districts next year
using raw census results or statistically adjusted data.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen major U.S. cities and counties, including Miami, Houston
and Los Angeles, have sought to join the legal fight against the
law, passed earlier this year by the Republican-dominated
legislature in the capital, Richmond. The law mandates the use of
raw population numbers on which to base Virginia's political
mapmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Urban areas, with large minority populations traditionally
undercounted by the census, fear the Virginia law will set a
national precedent as states prepare to redraw legislative
boundaries based on the results of the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Four other states with GOP-controlled legislatures _ Alaska,
Arizona, Colorado and Kansas _ have approved similar laws barring
the use of adjusted numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argue that the method, known as sampling, is necessary
to correct the undercount and ensure that federal spending based on
the census reaches the poorer areas that need it most.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say sampling is merely a means of boosting the
census numbers _ and political clout in urban Democratic
strongholds _ with people who may or may not be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sampling is really no more than educated guesswork,'' said
David Botkins, spokesman for Virginia Attorney General Mark Earley.
``Census means count, it does not mean guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Virginia law claim it will discriminate against
minorities, who are traditionally undercounted by the census and
thus will be underrepresented by skewed political boundaries based
on unadjusted population figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This undermines the principle of 'one person, one vote' by
virtually assuring us that voting districts will not be the same
size, and it practically guarantees an undercount of racial
minorities,'' said Kent Willis, executive director of the American
Civil Liberties Union of Virginia, which has joined the suit.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. District Court in Washington
will hear preliminary arguments in the Virginia case on Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court last year upheld a Republican claim that
unadjusted census figures should be used in apportioning the 435
seats in the House of Representatives among the states. But the
ruling seemed to suggest that it was up to the states to determine
whether to use adjusted data or the actual count for redrawing
congressional, state and local district boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Census Bureau plans to release two sets of
numbers next year _ the raw count and the adjusted numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia case is being widely viewed by state officials and
legal scholars as a legal fight that eventually will make its way
to the Supreme Court, giving the high court an opportunity to
clarify its ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Much is at stake. Control of redistricting can determine the
partisan balance in state legislatures and the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   And most experts believe the season of lawsuits regarding
redistricting and the census has only begun. Redistricting
following the 1990 census generated litigation in 41 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming there is no perfectly clear Supreme Court decision,
no booming voice telling states that this is the way to do it, all
the states are vulnerable, no matter what set of data they use,''
said Tim Storey, a redistricting specialist with the Denver-based
National Association of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question isn't if, but when _ will the decision come
early next year before states must do their redistricting, or will
it come afterward when everyone is stuck trying to decide if they
have done the wrong thing or the right thing?'' said Dale Oldham, a
lawyer and redistricting specialist for the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   As part of the 2000 census of America's 120 million households,
the Census Bureau is gathering demographic statistics from 314,000
households to adjust population counts in areas as small as city
blocks. The method, known as sampling, is based on a mathematical
formula regarded by demographers as a reliable way to fine-tune the
census to account for millions of people missed in the traditional
count.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census failed to count about 4 million people, and was
more likely to miss minorities, the poor and children, according to
Census Bureau estimates. About 4.4 percent of all blacks were not
counted and nearly 5 percent of Hispanics were missed, according to
the post-census review.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 2, Census Bureau officials will hold a hearing at the
National Academy of Sciences to review the process their experts
will use to adjust the count. If the Census Bureau and the National
Academy of Sciences find no fault with the scientific methods being
used, the adjusted numbers will be released early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good numbers are critical to a good democracy,'' said Kenneth
Prewitt, director of the Census Bureau, which is not a party in the
Virginia lawsuit. ``It starts with the assumption that it is
impossible to count everyone. The census is an estimate of a true
count, and we believe we should do everything possible to make the
census a better estimate, a better count.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is one of 16 states which must submit changes in its
electoral laws to the Department of Justice for review under the
1965 Voting Rights Act. In effect, the state sued the Justice
Department seeking a federal review of the law barring adjusted
census numbers in an attempt to clarify the issue before the state
lawmakers must begin redrawing boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for Virginia and Virginians to have swift,
timely elections and that they not be delayed by litigation,''
Botkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
