<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOOR DILEMMA: THEY'RE TOO LOOSE OR TOO TIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a frustrating summer, all right _ muggy and humid
and musty one day, dry as a bone the next, and never really
pleasantly hot for summer living.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, doors began to stick. Sometimes interior doors
stick, sometimes exterior doors stick, sometimes they stick at the
same time, making them hard to open or close.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Why did those doors, which worked well enough
last winter, stick in the summer? It's the humidity that did it.
The wood doors absorbed moisture and expanded, making them too big
for their openings.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity and expansion of the wood is the biggest cause of
sticking doors, but before you start trimming them to fit, check to
make sure the hinges are tight.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes hinges work loose, from constant use of the door.
Check the screws; you might have only to tighten them. If they
tighten, you're all set. If they keep turning without tightening,
replace them with larger and longer screws that will tighten.
</P>
<P>
   Or, fill screw holes with wood matches or slivers of wood and
drive in the original screws. Or, buy Mr. Grip _ little barbed
strips of aluminum _ and slip them into the holes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shimming will fix it &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a door will stick only on part of a side, usually the
top or bottom third of the door. To fix this, determine where the
door is sticking. If the top third is sticking, and the hinges are
tight, you can shim behind the bottom hinge, which will bring the
bottom of the door out a little so it won't stick.
</P>
<P>
   Unscrew the hinge leaf on the jamb, not the door, and cut a
piece of cardboard, poster board or mat board to the size of the
hinge leaf and insert it behind the leaf. Drive in the screws and
see what happens. You may have to put a double thickness of
cardboard behind the leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Lubricating with soap, wax or WD-40 will help, but only
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you've done everything and still the doors stick. If they
have swollen due to moisture, wait. In winter, the doors will lose
moisture shrink back to normal, and swing free again without
sticking. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trim as needed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you can't wait 'til the doors shrink, or if they don't shrink
enough, surgery is needed. Trim off the offending edge; it could be
the latch edge, the top or bottom edge or all three. Rarely does
the hinge edge need trimming.
</P>
<P>
   Trim with a plane or Surform plane, a tool with a lot of little
teeth that does a pretty good job. In severe cases, you might have
to saw off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with trimming is that you might take off too much,
and when the door dries out and shrinks, it will be way too small
for its opening. If it is, you can nail on an extra side and top
stop, wood trim that the door butts up against when it is closed.
</P>
<P>
   Trimming of sides and tops can be done with the door in place.
Put a wedge under it so it will hold steady when you are working on
it. To saw an edge, it's best to take the door off its hinges and
put it on a flat surface. The door must be removed to trim the
bottom edge. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seal out the moisture &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We mentioned that a wood door takes on moisture. Once you have
trimmed it, paint all edges and possibly both faces to seal the
door at its dryest, against invasion of moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Use an oil primer and finish with latex finish paint.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the door's finish _ too many coats of paint _ will
make it too big for its opening. Remove the paint by sanding or
stripping. Then refinish.
</P>
<P>
   All this information applies to interior doors, exterior doors,
and wood storms.
</P>
<P>
   If your aluminum or steel storm doors stick, it isn't the doors
that have swollen from moisture, but the frame. You can't trim the
doors, but you can rebuild the frame they sit in.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, the handyman's back wood storm door has
been sticking on and off all summer.
</P>
<P>
   I'll fix it _ some day. At least the front wood storm door is
nice and loose. Too loose? Maybe, but it doesn't stick.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you've solved the problem of sticking doors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
This door won't stay open &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what about a door that is not tight at all, but is too
loose, and won't stay open when it is supposed to? You open it, and
the darned thing closes all by itsef.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a reader wrote about his door. ``I put WD-40 on the
hinges of the door,'' he wrote, ``and now it won't stay open. Any
suggestions you might have would be appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   First, check the hinges to make sure they are tight. They are
likely to be.
</P>
<P>
   OK. The WD-40 made the door run more smoothly on its hinges,
which is good because it can stop squeaks. A down-and-dirty cure is
to remove the hinge pin, place it on a hard surface and whack it
with a hammer. This will bend it slightly so that it will be
tighter in the pin holder when you re-insert it, thus holding the
door open. The trouble with this is that the squeak is likely to
recur.
</P>
<P>
   What happened is this: The door is not vertical; it leans
slightly in its frame. When the door is open, the slant causes it
to close by itself because it is off balance.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate this, open the door to your freezer or
refrigerator; let it go, and it will close by itself. This slanting
is done on purpose so you won't leave the door open longer than
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The slanting of your regular door is not on purpose. But you can
fix it. Shim the top hinge by placing a piece of cardboard under
the leaf of the hinge on the jamb. This will bring the door to
vertical, and presto! It will stay open.
</P>
<P>
   At least it should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-07 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXACTLY HOW MUCH TOE IS TOO MUCH TOE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if we don't already have enough to worry about, now there's
the issue of toe cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never thought much about toe cleavage until I saw it
mentioned in a story in Sunday's New York Times Style section. In
fact, I don't recall hearing the phrase before, although it did set
off a very faint bell. Toe cleavage? Did it come up during the Dick
Morris foot-fetish affair?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the ins and outs of toe cleavage loom large in the
life of Manolo Blahnik, and the lives of his devotees. I may not
have heard of toe cleavage but I've heard of Manolo Blahnik. Who
hasn't?
</P>
<P>
   For years Blahnik's shoes have been the apotheosis of footwear
fashion. Lately you can hardly turn on the TV or pick up a magazine
without finding some celebrity or other singing the praises of
Blahnik's designs. Manolomania is everywhere. The ``Sex and the
City'' girls teeter about Manhattan on his spikes. Jennifer
Anniston wore 4-inch Manolos at her wedding. Joan Rivers, Queen
Latifah, Diana Ross, and Kathie Lee Gifford, among many others, are
on record testifying to the fabulousness of Manolo Blahnik shoes.
Madonna once said that her Manolos are ``as good as sex, and they
last longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to toe cleavage. In the New York Times
story, Blahnik is quoted as saying that toe cleavage is ``a very
important part of the sexuality of the shoe,'' and that the secret
is in showing only ``the first two cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   This pronouncement was taken from a book, ``Manolo Blahnik'' by
Colin McDowell, published this month by Harper Collins and, at $50,
a bargain compared to the price of a pair of Manolo Blahnik shoes,
which start at around $500 and price-wise ascend into the shopping
stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't wait to get my hands on the book to see what other
secrets of toe cleavage it might reveal. Is there, perhaps, a
language of toe cleavage, understood only by shoe connoisseurs and
shoe fetishists? Why are two toe cracks sexier than one? Why draw
the line at two? Why not three?
</P>
<P>
   Blahnik is no ordinary shoe designer and, appropriately,
``Manolo Blahnik'' is no ordinary biography, but what its author
describes as ``a thing of fits, starts and enthusiasms.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by what McDowell writes in the introduction, it was no
simple task to capture the elusive Blahnik persona, although I
can't help wondering if it might have gone more smoothly if the
biographer had assumed a slightly less worshipful posture as he
went about his work. It can't be easy researching and writing an
entire book while on your knees.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell's book is a peculiar treasure, but it doesn't shed any
more light on the toe cleavage issue. I called an expert, Valerie
Steele, chief curator of the museum of the Fashion Institute of
Technology and author of ``Shoes: A Lexicon of Style,'' and
``Fetish: Fashion, Sex and Power.'' Feet, she said, are commonly
seen as analogous to body parts. Toe cleavage evokes breast
cleavage. ``Showing off toe cleavage is way more common than it
used to be,'' she said. ``Shoes that you used to see only on
strippers you now see at the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele said she found it ``interesting'' that Blahnik focused
his attention on the first two toe-cracks, since many other shoe
designers are showing off all the toes. ``It's kind of a `this
little piggy went to market' look,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking through the drawings and photographs of Manolo Blahnik
shoes in the book I noticed that many of the master's own designs
flouted the two toe-crack cleavage dictum and flaunted multiple toe
cleavage, as many as four toe-cracks. What can this mean? The toe
cleavage issue remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      09-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINEGAR WILL BANISH GRASS FROM WALKWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Grass is always growing through the joints of my concrete
walk. Is there a way to keep it from growing back, once it is
removed?
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN GREEN, Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Be happy that you have just a few joints in the concrete
walkway. Pity those who have a brick walk in the sun. Grass and
other weeds really grow between the bricks.
</P>
<P>
   You can pull out the grass and other weeds bodily. To hasten the
removal, kill the greenery with vinegar. Just pour it on each
joint. Vinegar is essentially acid rain, and we know what acid rain
does. It is the least toxic of the treatments available. Bleach,
salt water, and Roundup are three others, much less environmentally
friendly than vinegar, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Treat the joints in mid-spring and again in mid-summer.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone's brick walk is plagued with lots and lots of weeds,
here is one cure and preventative: Pick up the bricks, lay down
agricultural cloth or perforated black plastic, and replace the
bricks. This will keep weeds from growing. It will work for a
while, but eventually the weeds will win out, and you will be back
to the vinegar patrol.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A large part of my walls is covered with Z-Brick, which I
like very much. A small area has to be redone. I have the Z-Brick
to put up, but I don't have any of the mortar-like filler material
used between the bricks. What can I use?
</P>
<P>
   JO HANEGAN, Lynnfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since the Z-Brick is real clay, and the filler material is
cement-based, use Mortar Mix by Sakrete, sold in hardware and
building stores. How you put it between the bricks is important.
You can put up the Z-Brikck itself with a tile adhesive or a
thin-set mortar. Then, to install the Mortar Mix, mix a small
amount with water to make a crumbly, not soupy, mix. Press it in
the joints with a pointing tool (a steel bar made for this
purpose). Compact the mortar and smooth off. And more important,
avoid getting mortar on the face of the brick. If you do, do not
wipe it or smear it, but scrape it off with a trowel, and let the
rest set. Then any time in the future, days or years later, treat
the spilled mortar with muriatic acid. Mix it half-and-half with
water, and always pour the acid into water. The mortar will fizz up
and can be scraped off with a wire brush. Then rinse.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned making up a small batch of mortar. The reason for
this is that being an amateur, you will be slow in your work, and
since mortar sets up in 15 mintues, a larger batch will begin to
harden before you can use it all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new roof is three years old, and there is a leak. The
roofer admits that it is in a valley, where two sloping roofs come
together. He wants to redo the area of about 150 square feet, and
to install an Ice &AMP; Water Shield (a rubberized membrane) before
putting on new shingles. Will that cause problems such as ice dams,
or anything else, that I should be concerned with?
</P>
<P>
   SIDNEY HARRIS, Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The rubberized membrane will help avoid problems such as ice
dams. And be happy that the roofer is willing to do something,
particularly if the leak occurred after three years. Even if he
charges for the work he will do, it should not be that much, and in
my opinion will cure the leak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quarry tile makes a very nice floor, for kitchen, patio,
sunroom, or mudroom. But it has one drawback: It is unglazed and is
susceptible to stains. People try to varnish it to make it stain
resistant and to give it a gloss, but this is not always
satifactory; the varnish usually peels.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman has suggested using Future, the acrylic designed
for sheet-vinyl floors, but this may not be the best way to go,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Burkhart of Wichita, Kan., found a better way.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years,'' she wrote, ``I tried numerous products to make it
(quarry tile) shine, including Future, which you suggested using.
It does not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally called a janitorial supply company, and purchased a
product called Plaza, sold by S.C. Johnson Professional (Johnson
wax). I have used it for four or five years. I wax once a year, and
usually put two coats on. My floor stays shiny the entire year. It
is easy to use, dries to a hard finish, and doesn't scratch easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The directions state, `The product can also be used on
terrazzo, brick, slate, unglazed ceramic, and Mexican tile.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not work for Johnson wax. I am a housekeeper who likes
shiny floors. I found something that works. I thought you might be
interested since it's cheaper than having quarry tile glazed or
having the tile removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Sheryl. I certainly am interested, and so are a lot
of other owners of quarry tile floors who want to keep them shiny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter C. Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or
e-mail him at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
