<HEADLINE>
BUSHNELL'S IRRESISTIBLE `4 BLONDES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALYSSA HAYWOODE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
``4 Blondes'' 
By Candace Bushnell 
Atlantic Monthly Press, 246 pp., $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candace Bushnell is back in fine, blunt form. The author of the
book-turned-hip-television-show ``Sex and the City'' has a new book
out enticingly titled ``4 Blondes.'' Fans, in other words, will get
what they love, the literary dirt on characters who are so
maniacally self-absorbed they're appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The September release seems an odd choice for this book since
it's perfect summer reading _ especially for those who like their
summers to be complicated and catty.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four blondes gets a story of her own that between
them cover sex, drugs (prescription and otherwise), summer homes in
the Hamptons, bad marriages, odd affairs, and raw ambition (sexual
and otherwise). Expensive clothes get plenty of attention: there's
a beaded ivory bustier; a Dolce &AMP; Gabanna coat with a cranberry fur
collar; and shoe shopping at Barney's, Bergdorf's, and Saks, a hunt
that ends with the purchase of a $500 pair of Manolo Blahnik
sandals.
</P>
<P>
   In the first story, ``Nice N' Easy,'' Janey Wilcox, ``enough of
a model to become a lukewarm celebrity,'' knows the secret of
dating rich men, two-thirds of which has to do with being
entertaining company and having no hopes of marriage. True to its
ribald spirit, the book graphically describes the sexual
requirements of the other third.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed with the glitzy surfaces is impressive depth. Situations
and images softly echo F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby.''
Parties and desires are both glimmering and raucous. Social status
is as brutally important as oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   There are also wisps of Edith Wharton's ``The House of Mirth.''
If Wharton's single, financially strapped character, Lily Bart,
stepped into the year 2000, Bushnell seems to be whispering between
the lines of this book, she could easily be facing the same
pressing need to find a husband of means fast. One man advises
Janey to go to London and find a ``titled Englishman'' to marry.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lily, Janey is no victim. She plays the game with her
cynical eyes wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart and a model. What could be better?'' one man asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dumb and a model. The way most men like them,'' Janey says.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no thinly veiled treatises on gender relations
here. What makes the book good is that it's all about the messy
clash of bad ideas, greedy expectations, and power. While readers
love some characters for their nobility, these characters are
attractive because of their huge, human flaws. They know about such
practical alternatives as law school or accounting, but they're in
blind pursuit of glamour _ no matter how misguided this may be.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly striking is the third story, ``Snow Angels,'' which
announces itself as a fictional spin on Princess Diana. A friend of
Cecelia Kelly, princess by marriage of Luxembourg, wants to turn
her into ``America's very own Princess Di,'' blithely brushing
aside the tragic end of Diana's story.
</P>
<P>
   This princess goes through her own version of hell, upset by,
among many things, her distant husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really did believe, when we first got married, that we would
talk about everything honestly but the opposite has occurred: We're
like two people on separate islands with only tin cans and string
as a means of communication.'' And there's ``that photograph in
STAR and the accompanying article that accuses me of being an
anorexic, which I'm NOT, but what I am is so complicated that I
can't begin to explain it to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   What Bushnell mercifully and compelling gives Cecelia is a
``best friend,'' Dianna Moon, who may have killed her husband, and
a narrative that ultimately pulls free, taking a different road
than Princess Diana's story.
</P>
<P>
   To match the frenetic nature of its characters, the book is also
relentlessly up to date. Parties are thrown for Internet sites.
Frank Sinatra is dead. Someone is going to be the next Brad Pitt.
There is a reference to the recent Bruce Willis movie, ``The Sixth
Sense.'' The details create a sharp sense of fragility. They are an
indirect reminder that one day there will be readers wondering who
Sinatra was. It may be that these stories will come to seem
old-fashioned _ except for the realization of how some plots keep
repeating themselves _ much to our delight and consternation.
</P>
<P>
   Life could be a breeze, this book seductively whispers, only in
entertaining fiction it never is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
