<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CH. 5 AND DR. LAURA; A BUSH DIVIDEND? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the deadline for Dr. Laura Schlessinger's national TV debut
at T minus four days and counting, WCVB-TV's refusal thus far to
commit to the program has thrust the Boston station into a national
controversy that is testing the political and economic clout of the
gay community.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in a conference call with journalists, a group of
gay-rights activists _ citing the pullout of a number of major
advertisers from her radio show _ claimed the talk-show host's
attitude toward homosexuality is affecting the bottom line. (The
activists acknowledge they don't have much information about
advertisers for the TV show.)
</P>
<P>
   ``She has really lost millions of dollars in ad revenue because
of her antigay statements,'' said Rhona Berenstein, vice president
of Online Partners/gay.com. ``Being associated with Dr. Laura is
just bad business.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Schubert, the chairman of gfn.com (Gay Financial Network
Inc.), asserted that gay-community protests against Schlessinger
are having an economic impact on companies ``because they don't
want to alienate a market that is clearly very attractive to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, protests are now planned in 27 cities to coincide
with the Monday rollout of Schlessinger's syndicated show.
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves WCVB (Channel 5) perched conspicuously on
the fence. Station officials have been waiting to view a tape they
requested from the show's producer, Paramount, before making up
their minds. But it's safe to say that a decision not to air the
show would not only be a loud political statement, it would
surprise the anti-Schlessinger activists.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Tyler, a national protest leader and cofounder of the
StopDrLaura.com Web site, said Wednesday that she was under the
impression that Channel 5 had ``decided to air'' the program,
adding that stations are ``fairly scared to break ranks'' on the
issue. ``We're not naive about this,'' added Cathy Renna, a
spokeswoman for the Gay &AMP; Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation.
``We're working on the assumption that all the stations are going
to air the show on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, however, Channel 5 officials said they'd made
no decision on the fate of ``Dr. Laura.'' They are expected to
announce one this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like running for president, George W. Bush's unflattering
anatomical reference to The New York Times's Adam Clymer is part of
a family heritage. It was at a memorable 1988 campaign rally in
Indiana that the George Bush-Dan Quayle ticket turned the tables on
journalists who were aggressively questioning Quayle about his
military record. When the crowd heard the questions through the PA
system, they loudly and angrily turned on the reporters,
particularly Ellen Hume of The Wall Street Journal. And in the 1992
campaign, Bush actually adopted the slogan ``Annoy the media,
reelect George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Former network newsman and media analyst Marvin Kalb thinks
George W.'s remarks will find some receptive ears. ``For those
people who don't like the press, who don't like The New York Times,
who don't like reporters whose first name is Adam, it's probably a
good thing he said it,'' says Kalb.
</P>
<P>
   Brookings Institution analyst Stephen Hess goes further,
suggesting Bush's insulting Clymer may even be popular among the
media. ``It does a couple of things,'' he says. ``It's the elitist
press. It's The New York Times. This is something that's probably
cheered in newsrooms across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is subtle and not so subtle racism still a way of life on
television news? Yes, according to a new guidebook on TV journalism
written by former ABC News vice president Av Westin, funded by the
Freedom Forum, and based on the observations of nearly 200
electronic journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In a jarring chapter labeled ``Bias'' Westin quotes some of
those journalists, anonymously, confessing to some damning
realities. ``My bosses have essentially made it clear: `We do not
feature black people,' '' says one. ``A story involving blacks
takes longer to get approved,'' says another. ``And if it is
approved, chances are that it will sit on the shelf a long time
before it gets on the air. No one ever says anything. The message
gets through.'' Another admits that in a lot of his network's file
footage showing arrests, ``all the `perps' are black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it was most disheartening,'' Westin added in an
interview. ``I hadn't realized the degree to which race was an
issue in not scheduling stories or making them sit on the shelves.
It's a dirty little secret.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Metro columnist Leonard Greene's return to the Boston Herald was
brief. After only a few weeks in his old post, Greene _ one of a
handful of African-Americans at the tabloid _ departed in late
August. Managing editor Andrew Gully says Greene, who'd been living
in New York, had problems with lifestyle logistics, and that ``it
was difficult in the end to juggle his home life in New York and
his job up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who could not be reached for comment, signed on to write
twice-monthly op-ed columns for the Herald; his exit poses another
diversity problem for the paper. ``It's pretty darn hard to walk
out there and just decide you're going to find a minority
columnist,'' says Gully. ``Are we looking? Yeah. Do we have an
answer? No.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Jurkowitz covers the media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
