<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORVETTE C5: SPEED, STABILITY WITHOUT THE SHAKE OR STIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The family names Ford, Harley, and Davidson are familiar to all
of us. After all, they are linked to enduring symbols of American
auto culture: the Model T (and the method of its production) and
the Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say Zora-Arkus Duntov? Designer of the Duntov? No. Try
performance-schooled engineer with a bent for racing. He gave us
none other than the Corvette, back in 1955 _ a true American sports
car with the fabled short-block engine.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Vette stands with the ``T'' and the Harley because of its
seamless lineage as a sports car. The Thunderbird might have made
this list had it not become long, bloated, and four-doored in ugly
times of transition. Ford is bringing back the Thunderbird, looking
much like it did in its glory days, and that is a wonderful and
anticipated event.
</P>
<P>
   But the Corvette needs no bringing back. It has rocked steady
down the decades.
</P>
<P>
   So with the promise of soon getting behind the wheel of the 2001
Z06 Corvette _ a beast of a coupe with nearly 400 horsepower _ we
took the latest generation, a 2000 C5 roadster out for a week of
testing for pre-comparison.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the shuddering, hold-on-in-the-corners Corvette of
old. Powered by a 5.7-liter V8 that cranks out 345 horsepower and a
whopping 350 lb.-ft. of torque, its got a rigid construction and a
suspension that withstands what all that power can do to a hurtling
automobile.
</P>
<P>
   But first you need to be securely anchored inside. The long,
low, narrow seats hold you like you are Velcroed to them. They are
so firm at the thigh, with great lateral support on the outside of
the legs and up from waist to shoulders, you feel as if you are
wearing your seat. You may feel as if you've worked a bit to crawl
into them, but once there, the whole inside of the car feels
spacious.
</P>
<P>
   It's got an airplane cockpit feel that is enhanced by the
electronic digital display that pops onto the windshield just above
the dashboard behind the wheel. Roaring straight ahead, it is easy
to keep track of RPMs, speed, and your fuel level.
</P>
<P>
   The C5, introduced in 1997, is the stiffest 'Vette yet. It's got
a strong perimeter frame but its key is a molded center spine
running cockpit to rear that is literally the car's backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Damping this stiffness so you don't get shaken and stirred on
bumps and in corners is a double wishbone suspension system mated
with really big stabilizer bars. The result is minimal lean in
corners, straight ahead acceleration stability, and a sense that
your spine is being pushed firmly back into the seat during hard
acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you pay a bit of a price for stiff stability: there
is a slight corner-to-corner vibration noticeable when you
accelerate through sharp turns on less-than-smooth roads, and even
creased highways give the car a slight tremble. But it's also a
price worth paying for the overall stability in a car with this
much power.
</P>
<P>
   Aiding the suspension in keeping it all under control are ABS,
traction control, and an active handling system. In addition, the
power steering is a variable assist unit that changes touch as it
senses speed.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it's a very stable package (turn it off and you're on
your own in this rear-wheel-drive rocket and that's another
adventure), though I found the active handling system, which cuts
power to wheels when it senses trouble, a bit disconcerting at
first.
</P>
<P>
   Though I almost always prefer standard transmissions, especially
in performance cars, the 4-speed automatic in this test model did a
fine job of popping from gear to gear even as it let the engine do
what I wanted it to do.
</P>
<P>
   And the torque the C5 produces is something you feel from gas
pedal (when you depress it) to the back of your head (as it gets
pushed against the seat during acceleration).
</P>
<P>
   I got 20.7 miles per gallon _ a remarkable figure, I thought _
in a week of less-than-gentle driving.
</P>
<P>
   With its big engine, calculated rumble, and convertible top, the
Corvette is not a quiet car. You can't conduct cell phone business
in it while whisking down the road, but you shouldn't be on the
phone when you're driving this car anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The only ojectionable noise, and I found the body and
appointments to be remarkably squeak-free for a rigid convertible,
came from the hinges in the convertible top when the top was down.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of that top, it may be the easiest-to-use manual
convertible I've encountered. It takes seconds of easy effort to
lower and raise.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Corvette, with optional heads-up display, those great
power leather seats, dual-zone air conditioning, and other
performance goodies, breaks the $50,000 mark, but that puts it in a
unique niche. It's more powerful than almost any other car at that
price _ picking between the 'Vette and a Boxster S, say, is really
a choice of style rather than function.
</P>
<P>
   To match its oomph, you'd have to jump up into the $70,000
range, a jump that may send lots of folks scampering to their Chevy
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The slots behind the seats that extend all the way back into
the high-floored trunk. Great, accessible storage space.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --No one else is building an American competitor as yet, and I
love comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $45,705 &QL; 
Price as tested: $52,379 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 345/350 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 104.5 inches/179.7 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 73.6 inches/47.7 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3.246 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 2 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
