<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-QUAKE-FAULT-HNS &LR;      09-07 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-FAULT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GEOLOGISTS SAY FAULT BEHIND NAPA QUAKE MAY NEVER BE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The gentle-looking hills of Northern California
may forever hide the identity the previously unknown earthquake
fault that shook Napa County last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have yet to identify the exact location of the fault,
and may never be able to if it is buried miles beneath the surface,
William Ellsworth, of the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park,
told an earthquake conference at Stanford University on Wednesday.
``The fault may not come to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 5.2-magnitude quake, which struck near Yountville,
caused more than 70 injuries, mostly minor, and at least $15
million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   One of those shaken awake was geologist David Jackson, who was
visiting Napa County at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the strongest shaking I felt in my life,'' said
Jackson, science director of the Southern California Earthquake
Center in Los Angeles. He spoke during an interview on the opening
day of the three-day ``Third Conference on Tectonic Problems of the
San Andreas Fault System.''
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, which was scheduled before Sunday's quake,
attracted about 50 seismic authorities. They reported their latest
findings and ideas about how the San Andreas Fault generates
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Across California, ``there are so many little faults that we
don't know about,'' including the buried ones, Jackson said.
``There will never be a time when we will have a complete catalog
of faults.''
</P>
<P>
   California is like a pane of cracked glass, a state rippling
with seismic faults. Some are visible on the surface in the form of
long gashes or deformed terrain, such as valleys or elongated
ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Other faults are buried miles underground. These include both
the ``buried thrust'' faults that move up and down, like the
previously unknown one that triggered the damaging Northridge quake
of 1994, and the ``strike-slip'' fault beneath Napa County hit
early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A strike-slip fault is one in which two slabs of crust move
horizontally past each other. The nation's most famous strike-slip
fault is the San Andreas.
</P>
<P>
   The San Andreas, which stretches from the Southern California
desert to far Northern California, separates two giant, slow-moving
slabs of terrestrial crust called the Pacific and North American
plates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5089 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WORKPLACE-INJURY-BOS &LR;      09-07 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-INJURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL TANKER SUIT PROMPTS CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As an immigrant from El Salvador, Rodolfo Arevalo
learned English, raised three children with his childhood
sweetheart, and landed a succession of jobs in sweatshops, textile
mills, and a shoe factory before deciding that trucking would offer
him the best chance at a good living.
</P>
<P>
   His family threw a small celebration the day he earned his
trucking license. But after a short time driving, he found a
better-paying, steadier job as a technician at the Exxon
fuel-loading facility in Everett, just outside Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, 12 days before Christmas in 1993, that Arevalo's
American dream ended. While loading a tanker truck with heating
oil, a bubble of compressed air exploded out of the nozzle. The
recoil effect sent the loading arm crashing into his chest,
catapulting Arevalo off the tanker onto a concrete floor 12 feet
below. The fall fractured his skull and caused massive brain
trauma. He died a few days later at age 36.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the family settled with the company that insured the
Boston engineering firm that had repaired the fuel-loading system
the day of the accident. The $7 million settlement is believed to
be one of the largest ever in a workplace accident in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The case also prompted the oil giant to install safety equipment
for the first time in hundreds of similar facilities across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this case shows that the civil justice system can do a
whole lot better job policing big business than the public sector
does,'' the family's lawyer, Douglas Sheff of Boston, said last
week. ``In a way, it's kind of a David and Goliath story. To some
folks, they may seem powerless. But this shows that an Arevalo
family can be on the same playing field with large entities like
Exxon.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon, protected from a large-damage award by the state's
workers' compensation laws, was not a party in the suit. Instead,
Sheff said, the family sued Boston-based Fraser Engineering, the
company that had made repairs to the fuel-loading system earlier on
the day that Arevalo was fatally injured.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser engineers had failed to close a key valve in the system
before repairing it, allowing air to get inside, an expert hired by
the Arevalo family said. Once repressurized, the fuel system
compressed the bubble like air in a scuba tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about hundreds of thousands of pounds of
force,'' said William Dobson, a mechanical and materials engineer
with Binary Engineering Associates, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Dore Hunter, an attorney for Fraser Engineering, said the
accident was the ``unfortunate'' result of miscommunication between
the Fraser and Exxon engineers, but one that resulted in positive
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right hand didn't know what the left hand was doing,''
Hunter said. ``But they (Exxon) got off their duff and did
something and they did so long before litigation was filed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheff said his research found that it was not uncommon for air
to leak into pressurized systems used to top-load liquids into
tanker trucks. He said similar incidents elsewhere had resulted in
injuries and at least one death.
</P>
<P>
   With the proper safety equipment, however, the compressed air
bubbles are usually not a major problem, Sheff said. Companies can
install ``high-point vents'' that automatically release the air
when it reaches the highest pipe in the system, ``t-diffusers'' at
the nozzle to vent the explosive force sideways, and tie-downs that
anchor the fuel-loading arm to the truck and keep it from recoiling
back toward the operator.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have also installed fall-protection grates to
ensure that if workers get knocked off trucks they don't fall all
the way to the ground, Sheff said. The grates are one of several
safety measures that have now been installed.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon officials did not return telephone calls seeking comment,
but in a deposition filed in the case, a company operations
supervisor said similar changes had been ordered throughout Exxon's
US facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be credited for it,'' Sheff said. ``I am not
trying to slam Exxon. Sometimes it takes a lawsuit to get them
moving on something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the family's engineering expert called it surprising that
safety measures weren't installed earlier, particularly given their
low cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking less than $100 for a t-fitting on a pipe. There
is no reason that I can see why it isn't done more often,'' Dobson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such safety equipment is not required by law and the federal
government does not keep statistics on accidents specifically
related to fuel-loading arms, trucking safety experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the US Occupational Safety and Health
Administration said they track the number of ``falls'' at the
thousands of fuel-loading facilities across the country, but no
distinction is made between a worker knocked off a truck and one
who slips on a stray patch of oil on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Transportation, meanwhile, stopped
collecting data on trucking-related falls and accidents in the
1990s during a government-wide drive to reduce paperwork, said
Cliff Harvison, president of the National Tank Truck Carriers
Association in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   In general, experts say, tanker truck drivers and loaders do not
face above-average danger on the job compared to other workers,
although accidents are more common in the Northeast because the
region has a higher proportion of homes heated with oil and
operators have to work on top of snow- and ice-covered trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Harvison said, fuel-truck loading is becoming generally
less hazardous due to advances in technology. Many newer trucks are
now loaded from a pipe located on the bottom of the tank, rather
than through a hatch on the top, allowing the operator to stand
safely on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1446EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
