<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-07 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS CHECK BOTTOM LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If the Patriots win the Super Bowl this
season, it certainly won't be because they bought their title.
</P>
<P>
   According to union and NFL sources, the Patriots have the
second-lowest payroll, behind only the traditionally cheap Arizona
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, like all NFL teams, are relatively close to the
$62.7 million salary cap. But the dollars spent on payroll are
actual dollars the Patriots are putting toward salaries this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' outlay of $54.29 million is 3.8 percent less than
last season. But they are competing in a division with the Bills
(seventh, $70.657 million), Dolphins (eighth, $70.29 million), Jets
(10th, $69.08 million); the Colts are 16th. Their payrolls have
jumped dramatically: Colts (42 percent), Jets (39.4), Dolphins
(33.2), and Bills (32.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Redskins lead the league, spending more than $87
million on payroll.
</P>
<P>
   On the Patriots, low-priced players are starting at running
back, tight end, defensive back, and on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you of this, the Krafts do everything they can to
put the best possible talent on the field,'' said Patriots chief
operating officer Andy Wasynczuk. ``You have to understand that we
did some of our bigger deals last year and the year before, where
some teams like Washington spent a lot of money on their big deals
this year. That drives the cost of the payroll figure up. We have
those deals in place, but we're still paying the prorated signing
bonus on those deals against the salary cap. Four years ago, we had
young players who weren't making a lot of money. They were
successful and suddenly we have to pay out free agent dollars to
keep them here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who are expecting to play at CMGI Field by 2002 (a
deal that puts almost $8 million a year in their vaults), may also
be gearing up for big deals for Drew Bledsoe and Terry Glenn, both
of whom will enter the final years of their contracts next season.
Contract talks are ongoing with both players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say something is imminent with Drew, but we
intend to keep him here for many years to come,'' said Wasynczuk.
``We've been having ongoing discussions and at some point we'll
reach fruition with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Terry's agent (Jim Gould) a few times and Terry
still has another year left. We're aware of the impact player he is
and our need to tie him up as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offseason was strangely quiet this year, with new
head man Bill Belichick signing mostly minimum-salaried veteran
free agents. The Patriots did have salary-cap considerations
because of huge signing bonuses given to core players, forcing them
to part with a few veterans who would have improved their depth.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe carries a salary-cap number of $8.6 million, one of the
largest in the league. As a result, the team dumped four of its
draft picks and issued incentive-laden contracts whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   When it came down to paring the roster, Belichick cut veterans
Vincent Brisby and Chris Carter and kept lower-salaried players in
their place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to model the San Francisco 49ers where you have
to go in the tank for a few years after years of overspending,''
said Wasynczuk. ``We want to assure our fans that we'll be a
competitive team year after year. What we need to do is develop our
young players so they can complement our older, higher-salaried
players. That's the model we're trying to build here.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to strengthen the offensive line, the Patriots
signed Grant Williams (two years, $2.1 million with a $975,000
signing bonus) and Lance Scott (on injured reserve). They also
drafted Adrian Klemm, who hasn't played a down after knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   They also dumped Ben Coates and his $2.5 million salary in favor
of Eric Bjornson (and his minimum salary) and former draft pick Rod
Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots went to the Super Bowl in 1996, they didn't
have a lot of high-priced players, except for Bledsoe. In the years
that followed, Chris Slade, Willie McGinest, Ty Law, Lawyer Milloy,
Ted Johnson, Max Lane, Todd Rucci, Bruce Armstrong, and Coates all
became wealthy men while driving up the cap numbers. Two years ago,
the Patriots had the third-highest payroll, spending more than $72
million between signing bonuses and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year is going to be difficult in terms of staying under
the cap, but I think we're going to be in a positive position to do
things in free agency next year,'' said Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   There's 15 games to go before any of those decisions have to be
made. The Patriots are not a cheap organization, rather one that is
paying a steep price for not developing draft picks who can play at
a high level. The organization is trying to do that now, but the
price may be a rebuilding year or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
