<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV10-C     09-07 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE 'PEOPLE'S GAMES' SHUT OUT CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (s) sports categories for
release Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    Fixes minor typos.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sports buffs in Europe, Asia, Africa and Latin
America will soon be watching the Olympic Games live from Sydney on
their TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   But in the United States, most fans will be fed only
tape-delayed coverage, sometimes a day after actual events occur.
Only Americans who live near the Canadian border or who own
mega-satellite dishes may escape the real-time ban.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors are at work here. One is the $3.5 billion that NBC
paid for the exclusive U.S. broadcast rights to the Games through
2008. The other is the 15-hour time difference between Sydney and
the Eastern time zone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you're thinking of jumping the bar on as-it-happens
Olympic reporting by watching via a Webcast? You don't need to live
in China to know that the Internet can leap across national
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, as the Games unfold, lots of Web sites _ including
the official one, Olympics.com _ will offer results, schedules and
background data. But they have all been shut out of video streaming
coverage of the events.
</P>
<P>
   There's always the chance that videotaping enthusiasts working
from overseas or folks who bring a digital camera into
the110,000-seat Olympic Stadium will beam unofficial Webcasts. The
Internet isn't known for bowing easily to rulemakers.
</P>
<P>
   To counter that threat, International Olympic Committee, the
beneficiary of those NBC billions, will field a special team to
scan cyberspace for pirated material.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is free to use its own Web site to show the Games, in the
same way that it could forgo heartwarming ``Today'' show blather
from Australia to show some actual events as they happen in (local)
prime-time. But it has no plans to so.
</P>
<P>
   Says Gary Zenkel, who heads the marketing of NBC's Sydney
coverage: ``Right now, the Olympics garners a premium in both
rights fees and ad buys because it is able to attract and sustain
an enormous TV audience. Until that audience and those advertising
dollars are diverted to other (media) platforms, we will not in any
way compromise the value of the exclusivity of TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But the outright Internet ban also delays any such diversion in
favor of tightly produced Olympics, built around mostly U.S.
athletes with star potential.
</P>
<P>
   There's bound to come a time, however, when modern technology
and ancient avarice converge to let the dot-coms into the Games _
although, if the NBC brass has it way, that time may be a long time
in coming.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the British Broadcasting Corp. first instituted the
idea of media rights fees for the equivalent of $3,000. (The
British organizers never cashed their check.)
</P>
<P>
   The first live TV feed came eight years later at the Winter
Games in Cortina D'Ampezzo, Italy. On that occasion, Olympic honcho
Avery Brundage sniffed: ``We ... have done well without TV for 60
years and will do so certainly for the next 60 years, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Come December, the world's top Olympicrats will hold a summit in
their Swiss lair to figure out where ever-expanding cyberspace fits
into what they like to call the ``People's Games.'' But you won't
find a Webcast of that meeting on the Internet either.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0121 </DOCNO>
