<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PIPELINE08-COX     09-07 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFORM GROUP CALLS FOR TOUGHER PIPELINE SAFETY LAWS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing the fate of 12 New Mexico campers who died
last month in a natural gas pipeline explosion, a grassroots
coalition of environmentalists, safety advocates and local
officials pressed Congress on Thursday to pass stalled pipeline
safety legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of interstate pipeline releases are preventable
because they are caused by such factors as corrosion, material
defects or employee errors,'' said Lois Epstein, a member of the
National Pipeline Reform Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pipeline tragedies like the one last month in New Mexico are
inevitable unless Congress ensures that the deficiencies in
standards and enforcement are immediately remedied,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition contends that the approximately 1.2 million miles
of pipelines through which natural gas and such hazardous liquids
as gasoline and crude oil are transported are inadequately
maintained. They accuse the federal Office of Pipeline Safety of
following a pro-industry bias in its regulatory activity.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference in front of the Capitol,
representatives of the coalition said the deaths of 12 members of
three New Mexico families on a camping trip Aug. 19 could have been
prevented by more rigorous federal regulation of the pipeline
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The campers, including five children, died when a natural gas
pipeline operated by El Paso Natural Gas Co. broke and exploded
near Carlsbad, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein, an engineer with the national environmental
organization, Environmental Defense, also released copies of a new
coalition booklet, ``Out of Sight, Out of Mind No More ...,''
containing pipeline safety statistics and accounts of recent
failures.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, the Senate was considering a
pipeline safety act that was introduced following the deaths of two
10-year-old boys and a teenager in a gasoline pipeline explosion in
Bellingham, Wash., last year.
</P>
<P>
   But to Frank King, father of one of the boys, the Senate bill
does not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that is going to protect your safety in that
bill,'' King declared. ``I give it a 2 on a scale of 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Millyn(cq) Dolphin, a burns nurse, described in gruesome detail
the death of a 5-year-old girl for whom she cared during a futile,
55-minute flight from the New Mexico blast site to the University
Medical Center in Lubbock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here because this did not have to happen,'' Dolphin said.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline safety advocates want a law passed that would increase
penalties for pipeline failures, allow citizens to file suits to
force regulatory action, require safety devices and improved
inspection procedures and strengthen the authority of states to
regulate pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.fuelsafewashington.org.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
