<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-POLITICS-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    INTERNET COMING OF AGE IN PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGNS
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic and Republican strategists concur that
in the not-so-distant future presidential debates will be staged on
the World Wide Web, perhaps with online voters posing questions to
the White House contestants.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 2000 race, Al Gore and George Bush have yet to agree
on ground rules for the traditional televised debates, let alone
deal with the uncharted risks of political combat in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the vice president and the Texas governor have
fully integrated the Internet into their campaigns. Each side has
thoroughly revamped its Web site for the general election contest,
with results that are far removed from the novelty items of the
not-so-distant past.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Internet assumes a dynamic role in their quest for
the presidency, their divergent Internet strategies have sparked a
lively debate on which of them makes the best use of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struck by the way the two redesigns reflect what each of
the campaigns chooses to emphasize,'' Tucker Eskew, senior
communications adviser for the Bush campaign, said in a telephone
interview from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our site,'' he added, ``allows for much more intense
personalization, while the Gore site emphasizes the ability to
create (linked) interest group Web sites. Philosophically, Bush
focuses on the individual while the vice president's approach is
mired more in an interest-group style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using our Internet site to rally our supporters and get
our message out aggressively. They don't do that,'' countered Ben
Green, a veteran political webmaster who has served as Gore's
director of Internet operations since last February.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Nashville, where he sometimes
appears on an always-on office webcam, Green asserted that ``one of
the clearest differences between our site and their site is that on
ours ... you can see the campaign actually as it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web address for Gore is: www.algore.com. The Web address for
Bush is: www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Each side claims credit for having scored some notable firsts in
their online duel. Still, visitors to the Gore and Bush sites are
more likely to be struck by how similar they are in their basic
purpose, if not in their individual personality.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns make extensive use of powerful search engines
that are able to find archived issues papers, campaign speeches and
press releases on virtually every topic that has been in the news _
and quite a few that have not.
</P>
<P>
   They also let users customize the Web sites to reflect their
home state, their choice of English or Spanish, and a long laundry
list of specific interests. Both sites adhere to a rigorous privacy
code. Gore and Bush send a ``personalized'' electronic thank you
note to anyone who signs up.
</P>
<P>
   Each site also pushes the digital envelope into the broadband
future by offering extensive audio and video materials. Bush posts
all his campaign ads, including a 30-second spot a supposed
``first'' devoted exclusively to plugging his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   One Bush response to the unique Gore webcam is a ``daily trivia
contest.'' If they answer correctly, visitors can win a Bush coffee
mug.
</P>
<P>
   One difference: The Bush campaign shuns online donations while
the Gore site actively solicits contributions for a ``General
Election Legal &AMP; Accounting Compliance Fund.'' That reflects a
legal loophole in the campaign laws. Otherwise, the campaigns are
now limited to spending $68 million apiece in taxpayer subsidies
which must also cover the cost of their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have so far posted only one of their campaign ads.
But they seem to be ahead in the video streaming race by featuring
frequent ``live'' appearances of Gore and his running mate, Sen.
Joe Lieberman, on the campaign trail. The Bush site counters with a
link to CNN.com, where viewers can watch ``live'' Bush coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps license vendors to sell campaign-related materials
online, beyond the usual buttons and balloons. Goregear.com, for
example, offers $55 rolls of ``Gay &AMP; Lesbian Outreach Lapel
Stickers,'' an item not to be found at georgewbushstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP outlet advertises, at $32.40 a case, 16-ounce plastic
bottles of ``George W. Bush Drinking Water,'' which is said to
``come naturally from underground springs in the heart of
Kentucky's famous Blue Grass region.''
</P>
<P>
   According to PC Data Online, a leading Web site traffic tracking
service, for the week that ended Aug. 19, the official Bush site
attracted 193,000 unique visitors while Gore's attracted 175,000.
Each campaign also currently sends targeted e-mail updates to more
than 200,000 people who have signed up for them.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns continue to devise more strategies to lure even
more ``eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Eskew and Green envision the day when the Internet will
assume a leading role in interactive presidential debates. One
possibility: Users could review an extensive list of issues and
rank those that concern them the most. The candidates would then be
obliged to respond according to these ``votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story can end here. Optional add follows.
</P>
<P>
   Green, Gore's cyberspace guru, noted that ``when Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman are on the campaign trail, the Web site address is on the
podium. So it gets into the local news shots ... and on the
politics page of the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush staffers accuse the Gore camp of copying its new supersite,
which went up first. Said Eskew: ``They followed our lead. We can
cite many examples of Gore following Bush's lead with pale
imitations, such as Social Security reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush site is still in seeming need of some tweaks. A
recent ``personalized'' request on ``MyGeorgeW'' for Bush's views
turned up an apologetic ``sorry, we found nothing'' on Bush's own
list of topics for such subjects as antitrust, biotechnology,
defense modernization, uninsured health care, e-commerce, Medicare,
prescription drugs, the Vietnam war and the Balkans. On the other
hand, ``your interest in Social Security'' yielded links to 98 Bush
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor clearly has extensive views on all those
(unreferenced) matters,'' Eskew said. ``We're going to have to fix
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.algore.com; www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
