<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-XBOX-AR     09-07 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-XBOX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH XBOX, MICROSOFT FIRES SHOT ACROSS SONY'S BOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ This summer, Microsoft executives have been
coyly popping a videotape into a VCR here and showing visitors the
Computer Age equivalent of the blinding power of a race car
dragster on nitro fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The tape reveals a photo-realistic schoolroom where an invisible
hand is poised to drop a table-tennis ball with an X on it. As it
falls, the viewer sees that it is about to land in a sea of 1,024
similar balls, each perched on a hair-trigger mousetrap.
</P>
<P>
   When the ball hits, mayhem ensues; table-tennis balls _ each one
accurately shaded and shadowed _ explode in all directions,
bouncing and ricocheting in concert and then slowly coming to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Rendering such an image in what the digerati call ``real time,''
with all the computing done as the balls collide so that each
collision can be altered on the fly, is today beyond the ability of
all but the most powerful supercomputers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if all goes according to plan, Microsoft hopes to begin
selling a game computer with this kind of computing power for
around $300 in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The machine, called Xbox, is both a technical tour de force by
the world's largest software publisher and a shot fired across the
bow of the giant Sony Corp., which now dominates the $20 billion
videogame industry.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is serving notice that it is intent upon extending its
reach from the office into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also an immense gamble by a company that has vowed to
commit $500 million to elbow its way into a consumer electronics
market governed today by a business model that is anathema to most
of the strategies Microsoft has, until now, pursued in the personal
computer software business. Unlike the PC software business, which
allows some independence, the game industry is based on a model
that requires the payment of royalties by software developers to
device makers, a model that would require Microsoft to depend on
other companies to ensure the success of its product.
</P>
<P>
   Will Microsoft be able to move with impunity into one of the
world's most lucrative consumer electronics markets, or is this an
act of hubris, evidence that the software titan, in its desperate
push for growth, has finally overreached?
</P>
<P>
   While the company's specmanship has been greeted
enthusiastically by those involved with videogames, some analysts
are far from convinced that Microsoft will have an easy road in a
marketplace that is unfamiliar and that is already dominated by
Japanese consumer powerhouses like Sony, Nintendo and Sega
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about Sony's crown jewels,'' said Peter Sealey,
a professor of marketing at the Haas School of Business of the
University of California at Berkeley, where he also serves as
co-director of the Center for Marketing and Technology. ``Their
installed base is enormous and the kids are with them, and
Microsoft's greatest danger is in spreading itself too thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand and demographics may well conspire against Microsoft.
Since July 1998, the penetration of videogame consoles in the
nation's homes has begun to decline, to 35 percent from 37 percent.
The reason, according to the San Francisco-based market research
firm Odyssey, is that the home PC is also increasingly a game
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Until now Microsoft has largely eschewed hardware manufacturing,
preferring to let its hundreds of business partners take the risks
in a market that is known for razor-thin margins and brutal
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Microsoft has long prided itself as being what it calls an
``open systems'' software developer. No licenses are required to
write software that is compatible with Microsoft operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, in the videogame industry, software developers pay
fees to have their programs run on the manufacturer's game systems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has little expertise in the world of the ``razors and
razor blades'' business model, in which game machines are sold
below cost and losses are made up from the profits on hit software
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in the videogame business Microsoft will be
confronted by a hurdle its rivals know well, the same
``applications barrier to entry'' that the judge in the federal
antitrust case against Microsoft cited as being at the core of the
company's software monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tables are turned. When Xbox is shipped next fall,
Microsoft is likely to have only a handful of programs to sell with
its machine _ perhaps 12 to 20 _ while Sony will have hundreds of
titles for it Playstation 2 machine, as well as the thousands of
older Playstation games that will also run on its second-generation
machine.
</P>
<P>
   All of those obstacles are things Microsoft says it has
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the games,'' said Robert Bach, the Microsoft
executive who is leading the development program. ``If you have
great games, you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bach, who was previously the head of the company's Microsoft
Office business, now heads the company's game division. In a recent
interview on Microsoft's campus here, he said that in practical
terms his focus had increasingly been on making sure Xbox reaches
the market successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is counting on the fact that there is nothing
sacrosanct about Sony's lead in the videogame business.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bach pointed out that the dominant videogame
manufacturer had shifted with each new generation going back as far
as the Atari Corp. two decades ago. As the videogame approaches the
next generation this year and next, there is no reason the lead
should not shift again.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one more obstacle just over the horizon: Microsoft
is betting that unlike the personal computer, the videogame-player
market will remain a stable one. While PCs have increased in power
every year, the game platform market has generally remained
unchanged for as long as five years, giving consumer electronics
companies time to recoup their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sony, which has sold more than 73 million Playstations
worldwide and has more than 51 percent of the U.S. market, is
preparing to change the rules of the videogame business, according
to people familiar with the company's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft is making its flashy demonstrations and
releasing specification sheets showing supercomputer performance
next year, Sony has been preparing its own multimillion-dollar
campaign for the October rollout of the Playstation 2, which will
sell for about the same price as Microsoft's entry.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the most powerful videogame player ever introduced,
yet it is also a harbinger that the pace of technological change in
the videogame business is likely to accelerate quickly.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft will take the performance lead in 2001, it will
be with a powerful machine and little software.
</P>
<P>
   Sony could then trump Microsoft with a faster machine in a year
or two that could spell trouble for the software publisher: If the
videogame business becomes more like the PC hardware industry,
Microsoft may find itself locked in a bitter war over profit
margins in which it lacks the comfortable software cushion it
enjoys in the PC business. Sony has not publicly acknowledged that
it plans to speed up the pace but it has quietly sent signals to
its developers.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Sony has been engaging in its own game of
specmanship. This summer, what is almost certainly the world's
fastest graphics supercomputer could be found in a faded one-story
office building on a side street in Mountain View, Calif.,
birthplace of the semiconductor chip.
</P>
<P>
   The site's anonymity underscores the special significance of the
GS-Cube, a prototype Sony videogame computer that is being used by
a low-profile group of Silicon Valley programmers to aid a future
generation of game designers in creating software that is far more
lifelike than today's programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sony used the new machine to offer demonstrations on par with
Microsoft's this year at the annual Siggraph computer graphics
exhibition in New Orleans. One had impact similar to the Xbox
table-tennis ball demonstration: a real-time rendition taken from
the Hollywood movie ``The Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   The GS-Cube is composed of 16 enhanced Sony Playstation 2
computers. When harnessed together they are capable of drawing more
than 200 million polygons a second. That speed is more than 16
times faster than today's Playstation and more than twice as fast
as a Silicon Graphics Reality Engine, a supercomputer that is the
most powerful commercial graphics machine.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly Sony will say only that the system is intended to blur
the line between the videogame world and digital entertainment in
Hollywood. Some developers, however, believe the machine could
become a commercial product as early as 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony is going for rapid change of the platform, while
Microsoft is new to the old world of the stable platform,'' said
Richard Doherty, president of Envisioneering, a computer industry
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bach acknowledges the difference in strategy. The PC business
has historically been a marketplace of incremental change, he said,
while the &QL; 
videogame has followed a more stable ``stair step'' evolution.
</P>
<P>
   It may also signify that Microsoft, which until now has been one
of the principal beneficiaries of Moore's Law _ the observation
about the exponential pace of change in the chip industry _ could
find that it has become the principal victim.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Microsoft will have to lose money on each Xbox it
makes, Michael Jones, the chief executive of Intrinsic Graphics, a
maker of videogame-developer tools in Mountain View, Calif., asked:
``How many Xbox's can Microsoft afford to sell?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-03-00 1620EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
