<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN     09-07 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: SPORTS NEWS WEB SITES RECONSIDER ONLINE SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (EDS: Because of transmission limitations, note spelling of
E(asterisk)Offering in graf 7; it is the company's name and uses a
character symbol) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Labor Day
signals the start of the peak season for sports fans, who can
finally supplement their baseball-only diets with smatterings of
professional football, basketball and hockey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web sites like Viacom's CBSSportsline.com, Disney's ESPN.com and
the News  &UR; Corp. &LR; 's FoxSports.com cheer the coming of autumn, as
well, as fans increasingly flock to their PCs to trade gossip,
scores and injury reports.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, many of those sites also promoted new online stores,
as they figured fans would snap up jerseys, caps and other sporting
goods while checking up on their teams. Forget the fact that those
media companies had almost no experience in retailing: this was
during the high-water mark for e-commerce, when the mere mention of
the term was enough to send an Internet company's stock soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, these so-called ``sports content'' sites
are putting as much distance as they can between themselves and
their e-commerce experiments. They have seen the misery visited on
electronic retailers by investors, and they have seen, first hand,
the reasons Wall Street turned a cold shoulder to Web merchants. It
is costly, difficult work, offering few prospects for profit in the
short term.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say the sports sites are eschewing e-commerce
altogether. Rather, many of them are taking a new approach to
selling goods online, one that gives content sites a way to glean
the benefits of e-commerce while avoiding the headaches such an
effort can cause.
</P>
<P>
   The newest strategy is to place the site's store in the hands of
an outside company. This approach has not only given sports sites a
reliable source of revenue and a way to keep fans on their sites,
but it has also given rise to a new category of behind-the-scenes
e-commerce companies, who, analysts said, may be better positioned
for long-term success than some of the more well-known online
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives the sports content guys an easy way to monetize
their traffic,'' said Shawn Milne, e-commerce analyst for
E(asterisk)Offering, an online investment firm. ``And it lets them
get back to what they do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Milne said the leading company providing such services to
sports-related sites was Global Sports Interactive, which created
and runs the online stores of the Sports Authority and Group
Rallye's Athlete's Foot, among other retailers. More recently, it
has begun to do the same for FoxSports.com, with other sites to
follow, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rubin, the chief executive at Global Sports, says the
company handles all aspects of the store for the clients, including
customer service, order fulfillment and returns. In exchange, it
keeps roughly 92 percent of the site's revenue. ``All of my
partners are making money on e-commerce, while everybody else is
out there spending their brains out on marketing and building the
infrastructure,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the company's success, Rubin said, is that it
operates in a highly fragmented market. ``This is a $50-billion
market, and the biggest retailer is Sports Authority, which has
$1.5 billion in sales,'' he said. ``So there's really no one with
the critical mass to do e-commerce successfully on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, sporting goods stores sell 85 percent
to 90 percent of the same inventory. So instead of many companies
building Web sites, call centers and warehouses filled with the
same 90,000 items, Global Sports operates a central warehouse
carrying those items. It also has a single call center in which
representatives handle each store's customers separately. And the
fact that Global Sports operates anonymously _ customers have no
idea that they are not actually buying from the Web site they are
on _ means that it can avoid the marketing costs that have sunk
other e-commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   But such anonymity also carries a degree of risk for the Web
sites, analysts said. If their customers have problems, the Web
site's reputation suffers, rather than that of Global Sports. Jon
Richmond, who oversees FoxSports.com as president of News Corp.'s
digital media group, said that risk was small.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pretty vigorous about testing and checking their
approach so they maintain quality standards for us,'' Richmond
said. He added that Fox Sports just rolled out its online store
with Global Sports last week, ``so it's a little early still.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the two companies shared information on
customer satisfaction, ``so we'll know what's happening there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Global Sports isn't doing this just for us,'' Richmond
said. ``They're doing it for Kmart, Sports Authority and others
who'll demand that they stay vigilant about things like customer
service and fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   Other behind-the-scenes e-commerce companies have found
increasing demand among sports content sites, as well.
EFanShop.com, for one, recently created a store for MSNBCsports.com
featuring licensed sports goods with the logos of professional and
college teams. Marc Andres, eFanShop's chief executive, said sports
content sites were ideally suited to such impulse purchases as team
jerseys and caps, ``because no one really wakes up in the morning
to say, `I think I'll buy a Chipper Jones jersey,''' he said.
``They do it while they're checking scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Andres said eFanShop relied on distributors or vendors to ship
75 percent of its products directly to consumers, and kept the
other 25 percent in a fulfillment center that is run by SameDay, a
company that specializes in shipping and handling e-commerce
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy White, MSNBC's vice president for business development,
said she was approaching the company's Fan Shop, as it is called,
as an experiment that could lead to stores in other areas of the
site. ``If there's a context for it _ say, a book review, and we
want to give someone the opportunity to buy the book _ we could do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports section of the site is an obvious place to start, she
said. About 20 percent of MSNBC.com's visitors head to the sports
section of the site, and sports merchandise lends itself well to
contextual selling, in which sites offer goods related to the
stories on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The two most-visited sports content sites, CBSSportsline.com and
ESPN.com, have also abandoned their in-house electronic commerce
strategies, but they have taken different paths. In December,
CBSSportsline sold its e-commerce business to MVP.com, which
operates its own online sporting goods store, in addition to stores
of corporate partners. For the right to operate the CBSSportsline
store, MVP.com agreed to pay $120 million in cash over 10 years,
said Michael Levy, CBSSportsline's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com shut down its store in August, and will reopen it in
mid-December. But unlike other sports sites, it will create an
online sports mall where different sporting goods stores will sell
their goods to customers. The general manager of ESPN.com, John
Skipper, would not name the stores that will participate in the
mall, but if the stores include all the leading sporting-goods
stores, that is likely to mean that Global Sports will essentially
be selling goods on ESPN.com's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Skipper said he was relieved to be free of
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good at creating sports content, aggregating a large
audience and working with marketers to sell goods to those
people,'' he said. ``We don't have expertise in figuring out what
jerseys or caps to buy. Retailing is a high-risk business anyway.
You exacerbate that risk by not being good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-03-00 1646EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
