<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-LAND-WARS-NNS &LR;      09-07 2630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAND-WARS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE ON LAND ISSUES HOLDS BOTH THREAT AND PROMISE IN WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
THURSDAY, Sept. 7, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ART ADVISORY: With five photos, of Steve Schrock (NNS7), Hank
Fischer (NNS8), Greg Schildwachter (NNS9), Stuart Krebs (NNS10) and
Bruce Watkins (NNS11) For information about purchasing these
photos, call 202-383-7824.  
 By JIM NESBITT  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELTA, Colo. _ From the thickly forested top of the Uncompahgre
Plateau, you can see the promise of a different way of dealing with
the public land conflicts that have endlessly embroiled the West, a
path that emphasizes collaboration instead of confrontation,
cooperation rather than political conquest.
</P>
<P>
   But if you squint just right, you can also see the threat posed
to that promise by 30 years of warfare over logging, mining,
grazing and endangered species and refusal by combatants on both
sides to believe that there might be a better way than litigation,
legislation and presidential fiat.
</P>
<P>
   Threat and promise dance across the plateau and the valley below
like sunlight and cloud shadow.
</P>
<P>
   To the northeast, in the shade of Grand Mesa, is the site of a
conflict between miners and environmentalists over a massively
expanded coal lease on federal land. It could have been as bitter
as any public land dispute the West has ever seen. Just barely, it
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   To the east, city and county officials, state bureaucrats and
railroad representatives watch a long coal train lumber through
Delta while talking about the best way to spend a mix of state and
mining company money to mitigate the impact of twice as many trains
because of that expanded coal lease.
</P>
<P>
   And on the plateau itself, a state wildlife biologist expresses
surprise and shock that a grass-roots group of citizen activists is
offering him money and manpower to restore elk and mule deer
habitat, instead of castigating him for not catering to its special
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``So often, we're just being told what to do by these groups,''
said Bruce Watkins, a terrestrial biologist with the Colorado
Division of Wildlife. ``For once, we're being asked `What can we
do?' by a group, `How can we help?' That's unheard of. ... It's a
totally different relationship with the public than we're used to
having.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins' praise is directed at a loose-knit outfit of locals
known as the Public Lands Partnership, who have ginned up $700,000
in Ford Foundation money for a pilot restoration project on the
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Composed of ranchers and environmentalists, businessmen and
public officials, the Partnership has been in business since the
mid-1990s and represents a growing movement across the West. Groups
like this are searching for a ``third way'' of negotiating the
region's thorny issues, one that strikes a balance between
preserving nature and supporting the people who live in the small
towns and rural communities that flank the region's vast swaths of
public land.
</P>
<P>
   By offering Watkins a hand of aid instead of a slap of special
interest or scorn, the Partnership has earned the trust and praise
of state and federal land and wildlife managers, a rarity given the
polarized nature of Western land issues. The group also helped
defuse the face-off between miners and greens before it became
another bitter land war. It smoothed the way for public and
railroad officials to start talking about how to solve the coal
train problem with a pot of money, some of it provided by the mines
themselves, instead of blasting each other with blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's good for the environment and what's good for
communities, that's what we're about,'' said Steve Schrock, a
former city manager and current business consultant who helped
found the Partnership. ``The notion that people who live in these
communities are Neanderthals and against the environment is just
crazy. This is no longer the days of 100 years ago when,
admittedly, people came in and overgrazed and cut too much timber
and devastated places with mining.''
</P>
<P>
   The Partnership is part of a loosely linked network of community
groups dubbed the collaborative movement. Sporting a mixed record
of success, they include the Quincy Library Group in California,
the Canyon Country Partnership in Utah, Oregon's Applegate
Partnership and the Henry's Fork Watershed Council in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a million acres of forest ablaze in the
intermountain West this summer, the type of public lands
breakthrough promised by this movement seems more urgent than ever.
This is particularly true on issues like forest restoration, the
need to thin more than 40 million acres of federal timberland
dangerously choked with brush and trees, a prime reason the
wildfires of this ultra-hot and ultra-dry season were so big and
destructive.
</P>
<P>
   But urgency has been offset by suspicion, skepticism and fierce
counterattack from the veterans of Western warfare. Critics are
quick to damn conciliation and compromise as a traitorous sellout,
revealing a deep divide between pragmatists willing to step into
what one activist calls ``the radical center'' and purists tied to
the dynamic of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to get people to realize there's another way to
do this,'' said Roger Schlickeisen, president of the Defenders of
Wildlife, a national preservation group involved in reintroduction
programs for grizzly bears and gray wolves. ``They're so used to
slugging it out head-to-head, no quarter asked or given, that they
view anything else with a great deal of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   And though politicians have paid lip service to the
collaborative movement, much of this rhetoric is contradicted by
government action.
</P>
<P>
   The current bone of contention is President Clinton's roadless
initiative, which seeks to close off millions of acres of Forest
Service land from roads built for logging but used for recreation.
It is the very type of top-down fiat for which the movement is
supposed to provide an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust is a horrible thing to waste,'' said Greg Schildwachter,
head of the Missoula, Mont., office of the Intermountain Forest
Association, a timber industry group, and a participant in a
lengthy and fractured negotiation to close roads in the Flathead
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some Westerners see collaboration as a chance to regain
sovereignty in a policy debate previously dominated by federal land
agencies, national environmental groups and the powerful
associations representing the region's extractive industries _
ranching, logging, mining and farming.
</P>
<P>
   In their view, the West has swapped its historic identity as an
economic colony of Eastern corporate interests for one in which
environmental goals predominate. And they think the environmental
movement has an obligation to help salvage the region's small
economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a social concern,'' said Ed Marston, publisher of High
Country News, an environmentally oriented newspaper based in
Paonia. ``You don't destabilize the society. You don't do conquest.
We're about protecting the Earth, not subjugating a rural
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Practitioners believe that common ground can be found between
traditional enemies, that ranchers and miners can strike a deal
with mountain bikers and environmentalists, that an armistice can
be signed to end the West's war of culture clash and bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business of every victory being temporary and every loss
being permanent just has to change,'' said Stuart Krebs, former
president of the Western Colorado Congress, veteran of the region's
environmental struggles, and now a member of the Public Land
Partnership. ``If you can get the other side to share in the
victory, maybe you'll make it a little more permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who walk this ground have found that it can be a no
man's land of recrimination. Consider the experience of Hank
Fischer, director of the Defenders of Wildlife's Northern Rockies
office.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer is a veteran of the wolf wars and two controversial
sitdowns _ a plan to reintroduce grizzly bears into the
Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness near the Idaho-Montana border and the
proposal to close several Forest Service roads in northwest
Montana's Flathead National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   On the grizzly project, Fischer and another professional
preservationist, Tom France of the Wilderness Foundation, joined
loggers, timber companies and federal land and wildlife managers to
hammer out a deal to get animals on the ground and still allow some
logging.
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of these negotiations was a citizens' management
committee that would make decisions on grizzly bear management. It
was unheard-of power-sharing, answering Westerners' call for a
bigger role in these issues, but it didn't keep Fischer, France and
their partners in the timber industry from being branded sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   On the second collaborative effort, Fischer sat down with timber
interests, hunters, outfitters, campers and recreational vehicle
groups for an agreement that would close 116 miles of Forest
Service roads on two large hunks of the Flathead, protecting
grizzly bear habitat while allowing logging and other forest use.
</P>
<P>
   But after five years, the Forest Service has issued a favorable
decision on only one of the land parcels. The deal also drew fire
from a local preservationist, Keith Hammer of the Swan View
Coalition, who wrote to Fischer's superiors and board members
seeking his removal from his post.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's like to be in the radical center,'' said
Fischer. ``They fight dirty. If you're not with us, you're against
us and animosity develops because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammer, whose group earlier obtained a more sweeping court order
requiring the Forest Service to close roads in the Flathead over
the next 10 years to protect grizzly bear habitat, denies trying to
get Fischer fired, but castigates him for flying false colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who brought this thing together were pretty
well-heeled environmental groups and regional timber outfits _ not
folks just down the road from the forest,'' Hammer said. ``This was
a political deal gone bad _ `We'll help you get road closure for
grizzlies if you help us get some timber out of there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer rejects this characterization. The coalition was no
back-room deal, but an attempt to break the logjam that slows
decisions on public land and endangered species policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've got is neither side getting what they want,'' he
said. ``It's a system that serves no one.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Although Hammer's criticism rankles Fischer and other
participants, the fatal blow to the Flathead coalition came from
within, when two of the collaborative partners, Montanans for
Multiple Use _ representing motorized campers, hunters and other
recreational users _ and the preservationist Montana Wilderness
Association, appealed the agreement to which they were parties.
</P>
<P>
   But Schildwachter, a timber industry participant in Flathead
Common Ground, says it was the Clinton administration's roadless
initiative and the opposition of environmentalists like Hammer that
unraveled the collaborative effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we see our honest effort to negotiate a solution left to
die on the vine while a national roadless initiative is getting the
fast track,'' he said. ``Our guys said, `We're done. We're going
back to the bunkers and we're going to fight this thing out.'''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The chief complaint of environmentalists opposed to the
collaborative movement is that national support for species
preservation and wilderness protection isn't fully represented by
grass-roots groups of locals. They also worry that such groups can
be easily co-opted, and might undercut the hard-won gains of the
past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have been little more than a grab at local control and a
guise for the industry,'' said Bruce Hamilton, national
conservation directorof the Sierra Club. ``If we're talking about a
natural resource, we don't feel it's appropriate to set up a group
of local stakeholders and give them all the power.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   There's more than a hint of elitism and jealous turf-guarding to
these arguments, some collaboration advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd had big, wide vision going into this, we'd probably
realize there are a lot of interests and organizations that benefit
from ongoing and unresolvable controversy,'' said Krebs of the
Public Lands Partnership. ``As long as they can keep those flames
fanned, they can keep dollars rolling in and offices open.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the notion that some environmentalists would
rather maintain ideological purity than strike a deal beneficial to
critters, humans and the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in this argument long enough to know that this is a
theological argument, that anything that has borne the mark of the
hand of man has been fouled and must be left to return to nature,''
said Mary Chapman, Schrock's wife and a fellow at the Center for
the New West, a Denver-based think tank on regional issues.
</P>
<P>
   But zealotry and myth-making aren't limited to
environmentalists, said Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to tell you that environmentalism is seen as a
kind of pantheism as much as anything else, but the rancher also
embraces a mythology, a tradition, and he's just as passionate
about making a living on the land,'' he said. ``Both sides of the
argument have their own vision of what grizzly bears symbolize. It
can be a symbol of government interference in their lives under the
guise of species preservation or it can be a symbol of nature's
wildness.''
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism and mythology make it difficult for combatants to step
down from the battlements. But Fischer and others readily risk the
heretic's brand.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer sees nothing wrong with development of a timber industry
geared toward forest restoration and other ecological goals, making
a living off smaller-diameter timber. Schrock aims to demonstrate
the benefit of selective logging and grazing in his group's pilot
project on the Uncompahgre. Still others have tumbled to the notion
that a ranch or a farm is better for the West than another
subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest heretic of the bunch is Michael Jackson of
the Quincy Logging Group. A firebrand environmental lawyer who took
on the loggers of his Northern California hometown, he is a
principal architect of an agreement that protects 1.2 million acres
of old-growth forest and fragile streamside land in two national
forests while launching a five-year project to thin 2.5 million
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson dares to utter the ultimate blasphemy: that the
cherished natural landscape of the West isn't all that natural,
that it's been so manipulated by man that it needs the hand of man
to restore it to pristine condition.
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration is the only way out of the West's public land
policy quagmire, Jackson and Fischer say. Nothing less than the
future is at stake _ of the region's land, its people and the
environmental movement itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being the brake on the car, we've got to be the
driver,'' said Fischer. ``Instead of just stopping things, we need
to be proactive and put solutions on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson: ``Who shot the dog is no longer important. It's
how do we fix it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
