 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bloodshed on a distant patch of soil, not for the
first time, trampled the best-laid plans of U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had not meant to open the Millennium Summit with talk of
tragedy. Just hours after the murder of three U.N. staff workers in
West Timor, a rosy evocation of peace and light for mankind would
have been tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for any secretary general not to take loss of life
amidst the U.N. family personally. The emotion felt by Annan was
visible in his face as he stood at the podium of the General
Assembly and asked a solemn favor of a hall filled with all the
world's most powerful people _ to rise with him and to observe a
minute of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Those 60 seconds of quiet among so querulous a group was an
exceptional tribute. The prime ministers and the presidents and
other sundry leaders all bowed their heads together. Near the front
of the hall, U.S. President Bill Clinton adopted the pose of
mourning, beside his daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Some way behind, Fidel Castro, similarly looked to his toes, the
grey tangle of his beard resting on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths in West Timor did more than just puncture the mood.
Tony Blair, the British prime minister, was one of those to make
explicit what many in the corridors were already observing _ that
what happened overnight on Indonesian territory was one more vivid
reminder of the inadequacy of the current arrangements for U.N.
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Blair or any of the other leaders had needed this
latest atrocity to drive the point home.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping activities in the last weeks, months and years have
supplied Annan and his organization with enough humiliation and
catastrophe already.
</P>
<P>
   The worst has been in Sierra Leone, where 500 U.N. blue helmets
were taken hostage in July and where even now six British soldiers
are being held in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Reform is always a sluggish business at the United Nations _
expansion of the Security Council has been on the agenda for years
_ but the will to make peacekeeping work better seems suddenly to
be congealing.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Annan published a report written by a panel of
experts that called for more money, more troops and coherent
planning as part of an overhaul of U.N. peacekeeping missions
around the world for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   More controversially, the panel also stressed that the world
body has to drop its neutrality and distinguish between aggressor
and victim. It failed to do this before the 1994 genocide in Rwanda
and the massacre of Moslems in Srebrenica a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson seems clear: if humans are being abused inside a
state's borders, then sensitivities about sovereignty should be
ignored. The United Nations should hesitate less to interfere and
to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer good enough to organize blue-helmet operations
as if they were still largely geared to marking and agreed
cease-fire lines between two states that have conceded to a U.N.
presence,'' Blair said Wednesday, taking up the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical case now is fast-moving and volatile. The
appalling attack on U.N. staff in West Timor is demonstrating this
vividly.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, making what was effectively a farewell
appearance before his world peers, was similarly candid saying that
it was time for the United Nations in future cases to ``take a
side, not merely to stand between the sides or on the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   It was thus also time, the president said, to give peacekeeping
operations new methods and new muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, the United Nations has been called into
situations where brave people seek reconciliation but where the
enemies seek to undermine it,'' Clinton said, citing U.N.
peacekeeping operations in East Timor and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in both cases, the U.N. did not have the tools to finish
the job. We must provide those tools, with peacekeepers who can be
rapidly deployed with the right training and equipment, missions
well-defined and well-led, with the necessary civilian police.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair went further. In a burst of enthusiasm _ many in the room
might consider it impractical idealism _ the prime minister urged
fellow leaders to implement the findings of the August report
within twelve months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a new contract between the U.N. and its members,''
he explained. ``The U.N. must alter radically its planning,
intelligence and analysis, and develop a far more substantial
professional military staff. When the moment comes, a field
headquarters must be ready to move, with an operational
communications system up and running immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom has already offered to establish a training
school for U.N. blue helmets somewhere in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, however, has always found it easier to offer
encouragement to the United Nations _ and there is no reason to
doubt his personal commitment to the U.N. ideal _ than to deliver
any material help, thanks to hostility to the body among
Republicans on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   No delegates here can listen to a U.S. president without
recalling the $1.7 billion that Washington owes the U.N. in back
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those in our country or elsewhere who think we can do without
the U.N. misread history or misunderstand the future,'' Clinton
noted wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   His administration, however, is increasing pressure on other
U.N. members to accept that currently the U.S. is expected to
shoulder too much of the U.N. budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things come with a price tag, and all nations,
including the United States, must pay it,'' Clinton said. But he
went on: ``These prices must be fairly apportioned and the U.N.
structure of finances must be fairly reformed so the organization
can do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   t was left to Annan to remind these most powerful of individuals
on the planet that the responsibility that they and the U.N. share
together was the upholding of the welfare of all the world's
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look to you to protect them from the great dangers of our
time,'' he said. ``Let us not disappoint them.'' &QL; 
