</P>
<P>
   Those 60 seconds of quiet among so querulous a group was an
exceptional tribute. The prime ministers and the presidents and
other sundry leaders all bowed their heads together. Near the front
of the hall, U.S. President Bill Clinton adopted the pose of
mourning, beside his daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Some way behind, Fidel Castro, similarly looked to his toes, the
grey tangle of his beard resting on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths in West Timor did more than just puncture the mood.
Tony Blair, the British prime minister, was one of those to make
explicit what many in the corridors were already observing _ that
