<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG WEB PORTALS LOSE INFLUENCE TO SITES WITH GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Internet companies try to find more efficient ways to acquire
customers, a subtle shift is taking place in the balance of power
between retailers and the major Web portals they have relied on to
send them business.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas portals like Yahoo, AOL.com and the Microsoft Network
once held almost singular sway over where their users went to buy
flowers, music or other goods, recent data indicate that this
influence _ though still significant _ is being challenged by
shifting Internet traffic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   A study to be released this week by the Internet audience
measurement service Nielsen/NetRatings confirms this trend, finding
that the portals are losing their dominant position as the source
of traffic for e-commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the portals were the top source of referrals for 54
percent of all e-commerce sites, the study found, compared with 46
percent of e-commerce sites today. The leading referral site,
Yahoo, was the top source of traffic for 30 percent of e-commerce
sites last July, but only 18 percent of Internet retailers this
summer. The data for the survey was based on 809 sites tracked by
Nielsen/NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Kaldor, vice president for e-commerce for
Nielsen/NetRatings, said retailers were seeking out partnerships
with types of Internet companies other than portals. Moreover, the
study found a new category of sites is gaining influence in the
referral arena: sweepstakes and lottery sites, like Iwon.com,
Freelotto.com and Gamesville.com, in part because those sites offer
partners an alternative business model.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, less than 1 percent of referral traffic
to e-commerce sites came from sweepstakes or game sites in July
1999, but by July 2000, that figure was nearly 8 percent. Kaldor
said these sites were gaining influence partly because they
generally offered partners a ``pay per click'' advertising model,
in which a retailer pays the referring site only for customers who
click on a link to the retailer's site, at a rate of about 40 cents
a referral.
</P>
<P>
   Kaldor acknowledged that there were drawbacks to relying on
sweepstakes sites to refer customers. Users of lottery sites tend
be in lower income brackets, and it is not clear whether visitors
referred from these sites _ who sometimes earn points for clicking
on retailers' links _ ever become long-term customers.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Kaldor said the sweepstakes sites bear watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the trend continues,'' he said, ``they do pose a serious
threat to the traditional portals.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUSAN STELLIN
</P>
<P>
   Personal Online Advice on Selecting a College
</P>
<P>
   Live, one-on-one college advisory services, offered until now
primarily offline, became available on the Internet last Friday
through a new Web site, PureAdvice.com. It is offering tools and
services to help high school students identify and apply to
colleges appropriate for them and apply for and obtain financial
aid.
</P>
<P>
   Some information, like extensive data on all the colleges in the
United States, and a calculator that estimates the total expense of
going to college, is free.
</P>
<P>
   But live, one-on-one counseling sessions with experienced
guidance counselors, financial aid experts and former college
admissions officials involve fees that start at $75 for a 45-minute
session. Included in this fee is a written report summarizing the
session, which is sent to the student and to the student's guidance
counselor, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   PureAdvice.com's president, Steven Ehrlich, said 140 advisers
from across the country, each with a minimum of five years'
experience, conduct the online sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In-school guidance counselors are often overburdened.
PureAdvice will help change that, giving students, their parents
and guidance counselors the tools and personalized attention they
deserve,'' Ehrlich said.
</P>
<P>
   PureAdvice also receives fees for referring visitors to vendors
_ like student loan providers _ that are listed on its site.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company has formed a partnership with U.S. News
&AMP; World Report to provide its counseling services on the portion of
the magazine's Web site that carries its annual college survey.
Ehrlich said U.S. News &AMP; World Report would receive a fee for each
referral to PureAdvice.com.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Achieva.com, a three-year-old, San Mateo, Calif.,
company that also helps high school students with the college
admissions process, appeared undaunted by the East Coast start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Feuling, Achieva.com's vice president for marketing, said
his company's $295 online college program ``takes you through
everything, not just college selection and the financial aid
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We help you with test preparation, developing an
extra-curricular resume, with an application strategy.'' The
company also offers live counseling, but not online. He said more
than half Achieva's income was derived from sales directly to
school systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE L. LEVERE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-03-00 1720EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
