<HEADLINE>
U.N. SUMMIT...U.S. OPEN...N.Y. MADNESS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 450-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As if the U.N. Millennium summit were not enough, New
York is also trying to accommodate the U.S. Open Tennis Tournament,
happening across the East River in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top players are finding the convergence most
unfortunate. None are more aggravated than Nicolas Kiefer of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer, who has advanced to the quarterfinals, arrived at
Flushing Meadow on Monday complaining of fatigue after an almost
sleepless weekend at the United Nations Plaza Hotel, just across
from U.N. headquarters itself.
</P>
<P>
   The worst was one Sunday night, when twice the entire hotel was
awakened by security alarms and bomb threats. How was he to know
that Yasser Arafat and Iran's Mohammad Khatami were to be his
fellow guests?
</P>
<P>
   Seeking more serene surroundings, Kiefer decamped to the Waldorf
Astoria a few blocks away. In all likelihood, this was a bad
decision. Arafat decided to do exactly the same.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, you could argue that the Waldorf is seeing more
diplomatic activity during the Millennium Summit than the meeting
chambers at the United Nations itself.
</P>
<P>
   That is because another guest in the august hostelry, right
there on Park Avenue, is Ehud Barak, prime minister of Israel. On
Wednesday, President Bill Clinton spent hours shuttling between the
suites of the two gentlemen in one more vain effort to coax a peace
treaty out of them. British Prime Minister Tony Blair stopped by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For observers down in the lobby, watching the back and forth
might be much like watching the journey of the ball at a Flushing
Meadow tennis court, but in very slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, of course, has reason to feel disgruntled with the
endless disruption that the summit is bringing to New York.
</P>
<P>
   At least once you have conquered the street closures,
circumnavigated the different crowds of protestors without taking a
single of their leaflets and made it through the metal detectors
into the building itself, you can expect then to go about your
business unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
   Not so if you are a journalist whose office is anywhere near the
Trusteeship Council, where portraits of all the leaders are being
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get in. I can't answer my phone. I can't even get my
computer,'' raged one American reporter Thursday, who has been a
resident correspondent inside the U.N. building for years.
</P>
<P>
   Without so much as a by-your-leave, security agents inside the
building had rushed about on Tuesday night, changing the locks on
the doors to the offices just above the Council hall.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind _ they have promised to restore the old locks when
the summit is all over. And when my colleague will have no need to
open his computer. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
