<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-OLY-IBM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLED IN ATLANTA, IBM ENTERS ITS FINAL OLYMPIC GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the computer system IBM built to report results at the 1996
Summer Olympics in Atlanta malfunctioned, the proud computing giant
learned the hard way what it was like to stumble with the whole
world watching.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Summer Olympics set to begin this month in Sydney,
Australia, and IBM's 40-year run as a technology supplier for the
Olympics set to end in December, Big Blue is pushing hard to make
sure it brings home some public relations gold.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which decided two years ago to end its involvement in the
Games, intends to use television and the Internet to widely
advertise its role as the 2000 Olympics' chief provider and
integrator of information technology. The centerpiece of the
campaign will be the official Olympic Games site it has set up to
handle a projected 6 billion user visits during the games, 10 times
the traffic during the 1998 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is also setting up Internet stations called Surf Shacks in
Sydney. Athletes in the Olympic Village will be able to go online
with more than 60 IBM personal computers; the public's Surf Shack,
on a barge docked in Sydney's harbor, will also show off IBM's
voice-recognition technology.
</P>
<P>
   The most crucial audience, though, may be the 1,000 or so major
customers IBM will entertain in Sydney. The visitors, including
executives from telecommunications, transportation, finance, health
care and computer services companies, will be shown the full range
of IBM's Olympics products and services at an executive briefing
center. The hoped-for payoff is the chance to discuss problems in
their businesses that IBM might solve for them. ``It's very
strategic marketing,'' said Elizabeth Primrose-Smith, the IBM vice
president in charge of sports sponsorships. ``We've found it's very
helpful for them to see us in action.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology challenge in Sydney is akin to creating a huge,
transitory multinational business almost from scratch under the
pressure of immovable deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials said that the Sydney Olympic Committee would
spend more than $100 million on information technology and
communications and receive donated goods and services from IBM and
others worth several times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to building the official Web site and systems that
handle scoring, link results to background data about the athletes
and the events, and distribute results, IBM is involved in such
diverse activities as accreditation, accommodations and management
of the athletes' medical records.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is not doing all the work itself. The accreditation system,
for example, has been subcontracted to the Sema Group, a
British-French technology services company. But IBM is the overall
systems integrator, and its Tivoli products will manage the entire
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The company has deployed about 850 computer technicians, who,
among other things, have written 12.4 million lines of code, and
who weeded out 4,000 bugs in the first six months of the year.
On-site equipment testing began last September.
</P>
<P>
   The work is winning praise from some technology managers who had
a front-row seat on the Atlanta problems. ``It's my impression
they've got everything right this time,'' said Klaus Sprick, vice
president for technology at Deutsche Press-Agentur, a German news
agency that found IBM's data feeds ``totally unreliable'' in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's Atlanta humiliation was magnified because the system that
failed was the one delivering scores, times and other results to
the news media, so the problem was widely reported. The news
agencies and newspapers that had paid for the data service were
furious. Ridicule was heaped atop the anger when reports spread
that some information passed along included nonsense like tied
final scores in basketball and boxers listed as 2 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Though IBM's corporate pride suffered, the company's quarterly
earnings, issued during the Games, beat expectations and IBM's
shares jumped.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said its market researchers found that potential customers
did not seem put off, either.
</P>
<P>
   Both IBM and the International Olympic Committee say that the
problems in Atlanta had nothing to do with IBM's decision to end
its association after the Sydney games. IBM had been an Olympic
sponsor and technology supplier since 1960, but its role had
steadily expanded since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, when it came time to negotiate life after Sydney, IBM
was basking in praise for its successful role in the 1998 Winter
Games in Nagano, Japan, and wondering how much longer it wanted to
spend ever-increasing amounts on the Games. Though IBM issues no
accounting of its Olympics spending, analysts estimated that it
invested about $100 million in Nagano. Because the Summer Games are
bigger, it was certain to end up with much higher expenses for
Sydney _ perhaps double, the analysts said. If it was to continue,
it wanted more cash from the local organizing committees to offset
the costs.
</P>
<P>
   But the IOC felt that putting so much of the technology in IBM's
hands was leading to needlessly expensive technical solutions. It
also wanted to handle sponsorship of Internet-related products and
services separately from the rest of information technology so that
it could raise more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them the Internet isn't available exclusively at any
price,'' said Michael R. Payne, the committee's marketing director,
adding that the two sides disagreed over whether the Internet was a
medium or a product category that should be covered by the
information technology contract. ``We would love to have IBM
involved in some aspects as part of a consortium, as in Barcelona''
in 1992, he added, ``but they're saying that's not in their
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The man on the spot in Sydney is Thomas E. Furey, who has worked
at IBM for 37 years and who got his first Olympics challenge soon
after Atlanta when he was assigned to investigate why things had
gone so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One problem was that the Atlanta Operating Committee's
technology staff had run the project, making it hard for IBM and
other technology vendors to deal directly with the sports
organizations and other end users. It did not help that IBM's own
services group, which did much of the project management work for
the Atlanta committee, was at the time independent from the rest of
IBM, Furey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Games also came as the industry was moving from mainframe to
PC-based computing and lacked many of the tools, like Tivoli, that
were later developed to manage distributed computing systems where
processing jobs are spread over many smaller computers supported by
larger servers.
</P>
<P>
   Given the job of overseeing Nagano and then Sydney, Furey
insisted that IBM get more control over the deployment of
technology and more time for testing. ``We also lowered the
threshold of risk,'' he said. ``We didn't use any bleeding-edge
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trumpeting new products, IBM marketers are
emphasizing that many of the Internet applications being deployed
at Sydney are already being used by customers in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   After IBM announced its withdrawal from Olympic sponsorship, the
IOC signed up Sema to take on, through 2008, the bulk of the
software and systems work IBM is doing in Sydney. Gateway will
replace IBM as hardware vendor for the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work for the 2004 Summer Games in Athens will not be
parceled out until after an IOC meeting in December, Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we read and hear about the IOC's future
direction, our role probably will prove unique,'' Craig A. Lowder,
an IBM spokesman, said. ``No single company has ever been
responsible for as much technology as we have at Sydney, and it
doesn't look like any one will be again soon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-03-00 1725EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-EB-MUSIC-TRIAL-NY     09-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-EB-MUSIC-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MP3 AWAITS DAMAGES RULING AND RAISES A THORNY ISSUE IN TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet music start-up MP3.com has been on the losing side
of a legal battle with the record industry ever since a federal
judge decided in April that it had violated the copyrights of the
major record companies by creating a central database of CDs to
allow users to listen to music from their own collections on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Jed Rakoff is set to rule this week on
whether MP3.com willfully broke the law or started the service in
good faith. Based on that decision, the damages he awards Universal
Music Group _ the only one of the five major companies that has not
reached a settlement with the company _ could range from $200 to
$750,000 a compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what happens in this round, MP3.com hopes to turn
the tables on Universal, a unit of the Seagram Co., in the final
phase of the trial, which will determine how many of the 4,740 of
Universal's copyrights in question the company will actually pay
damages on.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief that centers on perhaps the touchiest copyright issue
in the music industry today, one that has nothing to do with the
Internet, MP3.com's lawyers dispute the validity of nearly all of
Universal's sound recording copyright registrations because the
company designated them ``works for hire,'' a concept that, they
argue, has no legal basis, and that remains a subject of contention
between artists and record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright experts said that the argument could fail to have an
impact on how much MP3.com has to pay. But even so, the music
industry might be the worse for having aired in court a question to
which it has so far preferred to avoid obtaining a clear yes-or-no
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view at the end of the day most sound recordings don't
qualify as work-for-hire,'' said Peter Jaszi, a law professor at
American University. ``And that's something that recording
companies would like to avoid having too many courts say too
authoritatively. I don't know that this is a knock-out argument for
MP3, but from a tactical standpoint it raises the stakes in an
interesting way.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``work-for-hire'' terminology is the subject of a storied
battle between music artists and record labels dating to 1978, when
the federal copyright law was revised to set the term of a
copyright grant at 35 years, after which the rights revert back to
their original author. The legislation also identified nine
categories of works, including audio-visual works and ``works for
hire,'' for which the authors would never recapture the copyright.
</P>
<P>
   The record companies, which would like to control their
copyrights for as long as possible, have argued that sound
recordings fall under the work-for-hire category. But musicians
contend that they are not ``hired'' by a record label, and that
they are more like book authors, whose right to regain the rights
to their works is not disputed.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy reached its highest pitch late last year, when
the Recording Industry Association of America, a trade group
representing the major record companies, succeeded in lobbying
Congress to add sound recordings to the categories of works whose
original authors could never reclaim their copyright. The group
argued that it was merely a technical correction to the existing
work-for-hire provision, and it was passed without hearings as part
of a budget bill on Nov. 25, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But after a surge of protest from outraged artists, Congress is
expected in the next few weeks to pass legislation rolling back the
statute to its original form, with language agreed on by the
recording industry trade group and several groups representing
artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming this legislation passes, and I have to think it will
pass, we're back to the argument of whether sound recordings are
works made for hire,'' said Jay Cooper, a Los Angeles music lawyer
who represents a large group of artists. ``And I don't think they
want that decision out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-03-00 1741EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH21-SFCHRON &LR;      09-07 1911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH21-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
TECH 21: EBOOKS NOT YET A GOOD READ &HT;    By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   I didn't get to spend a lot of time at last week's Seybold San
Francisco publishing trade show, but you didn't have to be there
long to realize that the event marked the ascent of e-books into
the high-tech world's ever-expanding pantheon of Next Big Things.
</P>
<P>
   As my colleague Kelly Zito reported, the show produced a flurry
of e-book-related announcements, with Microsoft and Adobe cutting
deals right and left to line up support for their rival formats.
Meanwhile, scores of smaller players tiptoed warily across the
stage, hoping to position themselves to share in the expected
bonanza _ and avoid getting crushed as the giants wrestle.
</P>
<P>
   Even book publishers finally seem to be taking the technology
seriously, in the wake of Stephen King's success with ``Riding the
Bullet,'' a 66-page e-book that racked up half a million orders
when it was offered online for $2.50 back in March.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst the buzz, though, I had to wonder how many of the people
touting this technology have actually read a book of any
substantial length in electronic form. My guess: not many.
</P>
<P>
   E-FANTASIES: Actually, I'm a big believer in e-books. As my
family can testify, for years one of my favorite fantasies has been
of a world where people will have only one or two ``newspapers,'' a
couple of ``magazines'' and perhaps three or four ``books'' of
different sizes and shapes _ in the course of their whole
lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   These of course would be permanent electronic devices. Only the
content would change: Every morning _ or every hour _ the day's
news from our favorite source would appear in our permanent
newspaper, and we could load up the books and magazines at will
with any title we wanted to check out.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine the advantages of phasing out dead-tree
publication: Millions of acres of forest would be spared. Landfills
would get a new lease on life. (Paper of one sort or another
reportedly constitutes 35 or 40 percent of what we put there now;
I'm not saying all that would disappear, but publications have to
be a big chunk of it.) The flow of deadly dioxins from paper mills
and other poisons from toxic inks would diminish. Colleges could
pack more kids into their dorms, and crowded apartments would
suddenly seem roomy, as bookshelves become superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all that with the benefits e-books already offer, like
instant searching and hypertext navigation, and it certainly does
add up to a Big Thing. I'm convinced it will happen, and the world
will be a better place for it. And I don't doubt that it will
create vast opportunities _ as well as risks _ for companies in the
hardware, software and publishing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   What I don't think is that much of this is going to happen soon,
or that the transition will proceed very far with anything
resembling today's e-book reading devices _ either software readers
on PCs and handheld organizers or specialized products such as the
Rocket eBook (www.rocketbook.com) or the Softbook Reader.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that these products are still immature, though
that's certainly true, or that the resolution of today's screens,
even with software enhancements such as Microsoft's ClearType, is
still far short of what we take for granted with ink on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Even with more polished products and better displays, I think
e-books are destined for a pretty limited role for years to come.
Sure, some folks will buy them and use them, but mostly, I predict,
for documents that aren't readily available on paper _ either
because (like King's story) they have yet to appear on paper or
because they're out of print.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, I'll bet most people will end up printing out such
documents, at least if they're more than a few pages long, and
reading them on paper. (I'd love to know how many people actually
read King's story on screen.)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some tech-savvy business travelers may get into reading the
latest management guru's advice or a hot novel in-flight on their
laptops. Electronic encyclopedias have already all but displaced
the old-fashioned kind, and dictionaries and other reference works
are probably destined for the same fate. And technicians crawling
around ships, planes, power plants and other complex systems will
undoubtedly adopt dedicated devices to carry the mountains of
documentation they need into the field; some have done so already.
</P>
<P>
   But most people, when given a choice, will continue to prefer
ink on paper to glowing pixels under glass. It's not that I'm
sentimental about the touch or smell of books, as some people
apparently are.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental issue is purely pragmatic: After centuries of
evolution not only in paper production and printing but also in
design, we've arrived at paper-based forms that are supremely well
adapted to the task of displaying information.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we continue to use more and more of the stuff, even
though technology boosters have been predicting its disappearance
for decades. (``The Social Life of Information,'' a recent book by
John Seely Brown, chief scientist at Xerox, and Paul Duguid of the
University of California at Berkeley, includes an interesting
discussion of these issues.)
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the way they discussed the e-book market at Seybold,
Adobe and its partners seem to share the view that paper's place is
secure for now. In that sense I think their perspective is a lot
more realistic than that espoused by Microsoft, which doesn't even
allow printing from its new Microsoft Reader program
(www.microsoft.com/reader).
</P>
<P>
   PAPER 2.0: If I'm right about the continuing appeal of paper,
what will it take to make my vision of reusable, dead-tree-free
books and periodicals a reality?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, I think, involves an emerging set of technologies
known variously as digital paper, electronic paper or electronic
ink. The basic idea _ I'm glossing over the details and the
differences among the various research teams headed in this general
direction _ is to laminate a layer of ultrafine circuitry onto
paper or paperlike plastic film. Then the material would be coated
with millions of microscopic beads. These beads might be black and
white, or contrasting colors, on opposite hemispheres, or they
might have white particles suspended in a dark liquid. Either way,
the color of each tiny bead can be switched by applying an
electrical charge through the circuitry embedded into the material.
</P>
<P>
   The result is something that looks and handles a lot like paper,
except that it can be digitally ``typeset,'' on the fly, to
resolutions comparable to those of ink on paper. Individual sheets
could be bound together into groups resembling newspapers,
magazines and books.
</P>
<P>
   To load content into one, one might stick it into a virtual
printer or insert a little memory module _ perhaps something like a
Sony Memory Stick _ into the spine, or perhaps just pass a wand
across it. Or maybe it could all be done wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like pie in the sky, but I don't think so. Some
of the nation's top technologists have been working hard at it for
several years, particularly at Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center _
the fabled Xerox PARC _ and a Massachusetts company called E Ink, a
spin-off of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's almost
equally celebrated Media Lab. Both of these teams last year paired
off with another technology powerhouse to develop the physical
media for their projects: Xerox with 3M, E Ink with Lucent
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   (Disclosure: As I perused the E Ink Web site, I discovered that
one of its investors is the Hearst Corp., The Chronicle's new owner
_ alongside IBM, Motorola, the McClatchy Newspapers and others.)
</P>
<P>
   The Xerox team gives an overview of its technology at
www.parc.xerox.com/dhl/projects/gyricon. E Ink has much more on its
site (www.eink.com), including a Flash animation and a bibliography
of published articles about the company and the technology. Among
the listings is an excellent history and overview of both
companies' work in this area at www.eink.com/company/wsj000104.htm.
</P>
<P>
   How far away are real products based on this research? E Ink has
already deployed its technology in experimental form, not in books
but in signs at selected J.C. Penney stores and in sandwich-board
signs for a Yahoo promotional campaign in New York City. The
company's Web site says, ``By the year 2003, we envision electronic
books that can display volumes of information as easily as flipping
a page, and permanent newspapers that update themselves daily via
wireless broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that may be overly optimistic _ I remember the
company's founder, Joseph Jacobson, saying something very similar
several years ago. There's also the question of price _ even if
it's available in 2003, it might still be prohibitively expensive
for years after that. When I asked John Seely Brown, Xerox's chief
scientist and until recently director of Xerox PARC, in an
interview last week how long it would be before my fantasy might
come true, he replied, ``Realistically, about a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   I won't hold either Brown or E Ink to their predictions _ after
all, we're talking about truly cutting-edge technology here. But
I'm pretty well persuaded that one or both of them _ and maybe a
dark horse or two, too _ will deliver the goods before the 21st
century is out of its adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, e-books will be a really big thing.
</P>
<P>
   JUST SO YOU KNOW: If you've paid close attention to media
coverage of lastweek's Emulex stock-manipulation scam, you may have
noticed some inconsistencies about what the Costa Mesa company
actually does. Early accounts generally described it as a
manufacturer of fiber-optic networking gear.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable why it was described that way, considering
all the enormous publicity actual fiber-optic networking players
like JDS Uniphase of San Jose and Cerent of Petaluma have garnered
in recent months. But it's not quite accurate.
</P>
<P>
   What the company actually does is manufacture cards and chips
that connect computers to storage devices _ hard drives _ via a
high-performance interface called Fibre Channel. It is, in effect,
a top-of-the-line, server-grade alternative to the ATA or SCSI
interfaces used on desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it has nothing much in common with the
optical-fiber communications gear that the likes of JDS Uniphase
and Cerent (now part of Cisco) make. In fact, unlike fiber-optic
communications, Fibre Channel usually doesn't involve glass fiber
cabling at all _ despite its name, it's usually run over copper
wire.
</P>
<P>
   If you're curious about it, you can learn more at
www.fibrechannel.com; Sun Microsystems also has a white paper
comparing Fibre Channel to other storage interfaces at
www.sun.com/storage/white-papers/fccomp.html.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, one could argue, the distinction I'm making is
beginning to erode, because the future of data storage may be not
inside individual PCs or servers, but in drives and drive farms
sitting out on the network. In another example of the technology
industry's knack for clear and catchy names, one of the two main
implementations of this approach is called NAS, for
networked-attached storage, and the other is known as SAN, for
storage-area networks. But those are topics for another day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-03-00 2247EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
