<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-PLAYGEAR0905-COX </SLUG>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    On the edge of practicality
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Perhaps you're a gadget glutton, or maybe your
trash bin overfloweth with disposable income . . . Either way,
there's something very novel, overpriced and niche-market
functional waiting for you in Sharp's Internet Viewcam ($700;
www.sharp-usa.com), a digital minicam that requires no tape stock,
merely a removable, many-megabyte (four to 32) ``SmartMedia''
memory card and four AA batteries. It weighs in at a respectable
5.2 ounces at roughly the size of a hockey puck. Utilizing
relatively new ``MPEG-4'' digital video compression, this unit
targets the amateur or frugal Webmaster hoping to place thin,
middling-grade streaming motion pictures (or stills) of the
family's last camping trip on the Web or directly into
manageable-sized e-mail messages. Playback on the PC is exclusively
suited to Windows Media Player, a dangerous assumption on Sharp's
part Still, this is certainly a gadget that'll get your gizmo
going.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   TAKING YOUR GAME TO ANOTHER DIMENSION
</P>
<P>
   Bring your PC monitor to ``life,'' virtually, with VR Joy 2000
($70; www.vrstandard.com), a 3-D glasses bundle complete with
adapters and tweak software ``VR Caddy,'' which will turn any
DirectX or OpenGL graphics _ think games _ into simulated
three-dimensional extravaganzas, regardless of 3-D acceleration
programming or lack thereof. Creepy in that ViewMaster Viewer kind
of way, this stunning VR Standard peripheral has an edge over
similar products on the market as it is compatible with ``most''
VGA graphics cards (as opposed to units such as Elsa's 3-D
``Revelator,'' which works best with Elsa's cards and not so great
with everyone else's). The Joy2000's Line Blanker Controller Port
allows users to view ``stereoscopic'' images on the Internet
without additional hardware or software for the 3-D effect. In
fast-paced games such as Unreal Tournament or the bundled, complete
version of Systems Shock II, that effect is uncanny to the point of
distraction, but slower, more fluidly paced games are simply a joy
to play. There's also great viewing potential for your favorite Web
sites or screen saver. Bringing us that much closer to the virtual
reality of ``The Lawnmower Man,'' this is the fully immersive
technology of the day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Omar L. Gallaga
</P>
