<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-WORKGEAR0905-COX </SLUG>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    It's your turn to play Big Brother
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Sad but true: Paranoia is going out of style. The world really
is becoming a treacherous place, and genuine security is getting
harder and harder to come by (OK, maybe paranoia is still somewhat
fashionable). Fortunately, Angel Watch Systems offers numerous
devices to keep tabs on that which is tabable. Its Wall Clock Cam
for example ($240; www.angelwatch.com) contains a high-quality,
wide-angle pinhole camera within its covertly homely face. Suited
to just about any room in which one would expect a nondescript
timekeeper, the Wall Clock Cam offers discreet remote viewing
and/or recording through a standard monitor and/or VCR. The Angel
Watch product line includes innumerable other spy devices such as
the Clock Radio Cam, the Pencil Sharpener Cam or the Thermostat
Cam. And hey, even if your paranoia isn't real, the various units
function normally, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   EFFICIENT? COUNT ON IT
</P>
<P>
   The Hewlett-Packard HP12C Financial Calculator ($70;
www.hewlettpackard.com) hasn't changed much since the 1980s but,
like the mouse trap, it's simply too efficient at what it does to
warrant an overhaul. Boasting some 120 functions, the likes of
which only number crunchers can truly appreciate, this calculator
does it all, as far as numbers go anyway. Pardon my Greek, but the
HP12C is nuts on Statistical Analysis (cumulative, standard
deviation/mean/weighted mean, forecasting, correlation coefficient,
yadda yadda yadda); stuffed with business/finance features and
digitally cognizant of TVM (number nerd jargon for Time Value of
Money), making it expedient with loans, savings, leasing,
amortization, interest-rate conversions, bond price and yield,
depreciation methods and whatnot. Perhaps I'm not the most apt
reviewer to review this functional numeric chewer and spitter, but
the financier in my family swears by it. So do millions of other
proud professionals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   TEST MARKET MARVEL
</P>
<P>
   The latest Internet-enabled Palm clearly demonstrates why
wireless Internet is the future of personal data assistants. The
Palm Vx (www.palm.com; $399) with OmniSky modem (www.omnisky.com;
$299, with $150 rebate for customers who sign up for at least six
months of wireless Internet service) offers quick and easy Net
access to well-known portals such as Yahoo, Excite and Go.com, and
browsing to non-graphic-intensive Web sites. It also supports up to
six POP3 e-mail accounts, a valuable tool for the business
traveler. By comparison, the Palm VII only gives you a ``palm.net''
address and no Web browsing. The OmniSky modem uses AT&AMP;T's wireless
network, offering access in 3,000 metropolitan areas; Atlanta is
the only notable exception. The Internet service is $39.95 a month
for unlimited usage. My favorite feature of this Palm-modem combo,
available now only in Austin and Seattle as test markets, is the
detachable modem, so if you want to Palm sans Internet, you're
holding a svelte 3.9-ounce machine. With the modem, the setup is
about twice as thick and weighs 8.5 ounces, still sleek by any
measure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert W. Gee
</P>
