u a BC-CPT-TECH-UFC-REVIEW09     09-07 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-UFC-REVIEW0905-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Realistic fighting title rewards player finesse
 &HT;    By Troy Oxford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Ultimate Fighting Championship'' by Crave
Entertainment generated a lot of buzz at this year's Electronic
Entertainment Expo. The fighting simulator, based on the
pay-per-view event, featured outstanding visuals and game play.
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated title finally hit stores Wednesday, and
Dreamcast owners should be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   If you have been disappointed by the clunky graphics, clumsy
control and lack of depth of many boxing and wrestling games,
``Ultimate Fighting Championship'' will slap a smile on your face.
</P>
<P>
   Just like its namesake, ``Ultimate Fighting Championship''
showcases a rich variety of competitors and fighting styles around
the globe. Wrestling, boxing, submission fighting, sumo, jiu-jitsu
and kickboxing are just a few disciplines of the 22 initial
fighters. With this assortment, you can see some interesting
matches. The heavyweight, Andre Roberts, has some devastating
punches, but if he is taken to the mat by a Brazilian jiu-jitsu
fighter, his probability of winning is slim.
</P>
<P>
   You'll get a chance to compete and observe the extensive array
of styles and moves with six different fighting modes. The training
mode is a great starting point to learn the fighting systems and
various attacks of the characters. From there you can move on to
UFC mode and pummel your way to the championship belt. If you want
to develop your own custom fighter, you can check out the career
mode. In this mode, you can choose your fighter's build,
appearance, discipline and list of moves to be used against
competitors in other modes.
</P>
<P>
   A feature that sets it apart from other sports/fighting titles
is the realistic graphics and character animation. Once the
competitors strut through the crowded arena, you know you are in
for a visual treat. Character models are very smooth and lifelike.
The faces are scanned from the actual fighters and mapped to 3-D
models, creating a high degree of realism. Other authentic details
such as tatoos and natural skin tones distinguish each character.
</P>
<P>
   The animation complements the graphic realism nicely.
Motion-capture techniques were used to create the animations, and
it's evident there was a lot of fine-tuning applied to get the
motions just right. Movements are very fluid and don't have that
sluggish feel typical of so many wrestling games. There is also a
good sense of impact when a punch or kick connects.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath all of the realistic visuals is the true heart of this
game _ the fighting system. Offense and defense are very balanced.
Button-mashing players may get lucky at other fighting games, but
if they don't conserve their energy and block properly, one swift
uppercut will send them to the floor. Learning how to counter and
defend properly is just as important as tackling and striking.
</P>
<P>
   As good as this game is, it may not be for everyone. This is not
a typical 3-D fighting game. There aren't any ninjas, projectile
attacks or supercharged lightning punch combos. Games like ``Soul
Calibur'' and ``Dead or Alive 2'' are good choices for that type of
fighting experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimate Fighting Championship'' is a realistic fighting
simulation, and if that's what you're looking for, then this is by
far your best bet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-04-00 1424EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
