<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-ORTIZ-INTERVIEW0905-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Fighter likes Sega game's close reflection of himself
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tito ``Bad Boy'' Ortiz is the reigning Ultimate
Fighting middleweight champion. He also is a video game junkie.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz praised Crave Entertainment's newest title, ``Ultimate
Fighting Championship'' for the Sega Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the best fighting games I ever played,'' Ortiz
said over the telephone from Huntington Beach, Calif. ``I play lots
of video games, and it is tremendous how (Crave) can put everything
from the sport of UFC into the video game. They both look identical
to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, 25, is one of the most recognizable faces in the console
title, which also includes such big names as Frank Shamrock, ``Big
Daddy'' Gary Goodridge, Mark ``The Hammer'' Coleman and Maurice
Smith. UFC legends such as Ken Shamrock, Tank Abbott and Dan Severn
disappointingly have been left out.
</P>
<P>
   In the video game, Ortiz looks just like he does in real life:
bleached-blond hair and muscular upper body with his trademark
tattoos on both arms and skinny legs. Ortiz's fighting style is
both submission and wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each character in the game, including myself, is accurately
(depicted),'' Ortiz said. ``All of my punches and kicks are exactly
the same. It's like, `Whoa ... I'm watching myself on TV in a video
game.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz says his character is the best fighter in the game. At the
E3Expo last May in Los Angeles, Ortiz squared off with Frank
Shamrock in five matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won four of them and let Shamrock beat me in one just to be
nice,'' said Ortiz, with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of UFC's stars, Ortiz thinks the video game will
heavily increase the popularity and understanding of the sport. UFC
is sanctioned in only eight states. Ortiz says once people play the
video game, they will realize UFC does not deserve its ``outlaw''
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are just not educated on the sport because
when it first came out, it was a real bloody,'' Ortiz said. ``Now
it's totally different; UFC has gone through an evolution. The
fighters are so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all about punching and kicking anymore. You have to
use techniques. It's just not the no-holds-barred, bloody sport it
used to be. I train eight hours a day for my bouts, and I am a
professional athlete. This game should give our sport a lot of good
PR.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz is a former college wrestler who attracted the attention
of the UFC after being a sparring partner with Abbott. His most
memorable bout was at UFC XXII, when he took the still-undefeated
Frank Shamrock nearly to the distance. Ortiz charged Shamrock, who
unloaded three powerful elbow strikes to end the fight with 11
seconds remaining in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-04-00 1425EDT &QL;
</P>
