<SLUG> BC-MUDDLE-OVER-NUCLEAR-WASTE-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH IN MUDDLE OVER NUCLEAR WASTE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF SEPT. 11, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ROB EDWARDS  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist/RBI Magazines Ltd.  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arguments over whether to store or reprocess nuclear waste have
been thrown into confusion following a change of heart by the
British Atomic Energy Authority (AEA).
</P>
<P>
   In April, the AEA said the costs of both options were
``comparable'' if plutonium is defined as waste. Now New Scientist
has learned that a confidential draft of the report, completed in
January, concluded that storage ``has a large advantage'' because
it is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The government is considering whether to reprocess or store 25
tons of plutonium fuel from a defunct reactor run by the AEA at
Dounreay in Scotland. The April report was part of a public
consultation.
</P>
<P>
   The draft was obtained from the Scottish Environment Protection
Agency by lawyers acting for the group Nuclear Free Local
Authorities. Jamie Woolley, legal adviser to the group, is now
calling on the government not to agree to funding for reprocessing
at Dounreay until it has studied the earlier, draft report. ``It
looks like the AEA has attempted to suppress a conclusion that it
doesn't like,'' he claims.
</P>
<P>
   The AEA denies this. It says the conclusion was altered because
the draft underestimated the cost of treating spent fuel before it
was stored.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
