<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-INSECTICIDE-HUMANS-HN     09-07 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSECTICIDE-HUMANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DATABASE TO PROVIDE INFORMATION ON PESTICIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Pesticide Action Network, a San
Francisco-based environmental group, on Thursday introduced the
first comprehensive on-line database on the health hazards of more
than 5,100 ingredients in Sevin and other home and garden
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think that if the EPA allows a pesticide to be
sold, it must be safe to use,'' said Susan Kegley, coordinator of
the project and staff scientist at Pesticide Action Network.
``Unfortunately, that's not true, and finding out whether a
particular pesticide is linked to cancer, birth defects or other
problems can be extremely difficult. That's why our new database is
so important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pesticide Action Network's new site (www.pesticideinfo.org)
supplies information on whether a pesticide is a carcinogen,
affects reproduction or human development, or causes other harm to
health. The database tells which chemicals pollute ground water or
kill aquatic life.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for the information include the World Health
Organization, National Institutes of Health, National Toxicology
Program and the Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   A quick look at the brand name Sevin identifies it as carbaryl,
a class of neurotoxic compounds. The EPA considers it a possible
carcinogen, and some scientists suspect it of being a chemical that
can disrupt the endocrine system, which produces hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Sevin can disable an enzyme, cholinesterase, which affects the
transmission of nerve impulses. Exposure may cause neurological
damage in developing fetuses and infants.
</P>
<P>
   Sevin has been used to help eradicate the glassy-winged
sharpshooter, a bug that leaves behind a virus that attacks plants
and has already infested crops in San Diego, Riverside, San
Bernardino, Orange, Los Angeles, Kern, Ventura, Santa Barbara
counties and parts of Sacramento, San Luis Obispo, Tulare and
Fresno counties.
</P>
<P>
   There the state Department of Food and Agriculture approved
spraying Sevin around houses in some of these counties. Dursban, or
chlorpyrifos, has been sprayed near Porterville on commercial
nursery stock.
</P>
<P>
   In cases like this, as with spraying in New York's Central Park
to fight the West Nile virus, Kegley said, the public can use the
new database to develop informed opinions on government decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
