<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PETGUARDIAN0908-COX     09-07 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETGUARDIAN0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Animal experts say humans will always be in charge, but being
the family dog nowadays isn't such a bad gig
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - Anything outside of pampering a dog these days
seems almost uncivilized.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans, we treat our furry friends like royalty. They're
groomed and bathed at special salons, fed premium food and given
Christmas gifts. They sleep in our beds and spend their days at pet
day care while we slave away at work.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, city leaders in Boulder, Colo., recently passed a law
naming pet ``owners'' as pet ``guardians.'' But are all these
things really necessary to give Fido and Fluffy a good life?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my clients has a dog that goes to the beauty shop every
Friday to be groomed,'' said Marilyn Harkness, owner of pet-sitting
business in Waco. ``He has a standing appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Most pet owners consider their cats and dogs to be part of the
family, according to the American Animal Hospitals Association. But
let's be honest _ some are treated even better.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time Buster was told he had to finish his
plate before dessert? Don't think dogs get dessert? Hundreds of
bakeries catering to pet palates have opened across the country
during the last few years. Now, Fido can kick the monotony of Alpo,
Alpo, Alpo. Want to see that tail wag? Let him sink those K-9s into
some wheat germ bonbons covered with crushed peanuts or carrot
cupcakes or cinnamon and carob biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   All this pampering and primping of our four-legged friends has
some people wondering, though, exactly who owns whom _ who's
holding the leash and who's being led by it.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Woodbury, public-relations manager for the animal
hospitals association, said pets will always be at the beck and
call of their human masters. No matter how easy a dog's life may
seem, pets will always be property.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't always so bad, he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all that (pampering) reinforces the high value people
place on their pets,'' Woodbury said. ``There is a very serious
bond there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boulder law, which passed in July, emphasizes the status of
pets as living beings _ not simply property and is designed to curb
the abuse and neglect of animals. But councilman Gordon Riggle, the
lone opponent of the measure, said he sees the change as simply a
feel-good move with no legal consequences, and that, he added, is a
bad way to legislate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people call it the leading edge,'' Riggle said. ``Others
call it over the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   But in most cases, there's absolutely no problem convincing
people to pay special attention to their pets _ excuse us, those
other living beings in the house who have a lot of hair.
</P>
<P>
   One third of ``guardians'' talk to their furry companions on the
phone when they're away from home, according to animal hospitals
association studies. Nearly two-thirds say caring for their pet
fulfills a need for parenting. Health insurance for dogs and cats
is a booming business.
</P>
<P>
   Showering pets with all this humanity wasn't always the norm,
experts say. Back in the old days, back before we could talk to
Fido through the answering machine, he was around for more
practical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to look at pets in a utilitarian view,'' said H.
Richard Adams, dean of the Texas A&AMP;M School of Veterinary Medicine.
``They were used to work or protect property. Now, they're viewed
more as companions. That's why people value them so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Woodbury said there are no definitive studies that
suggest today's pampered dog is a happier, more well-adjusted
creature.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the reality is, most dogs like to stink. Just ask local
groomers and dog ``guardians.'' A few minutes after Fido gets
through with his bath, you can usually find him rubbing his face
and hairy body in the yard, which, upon closer inspection, often
includes things we'd rather not print in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a pampered dog is one that sleeps in bed with you,''
said Shirlene Miller, owner of Tidy Tails Dog Grooming &AMP; Boarding.
``That's another reason to bathe them and keep them clean. But that
can be hard to do. One dog (after we bathed it), ran across some
dead frogs and rubbed against them.''
</P>
<P>
   D.J. Ortman, director of the Waco Humane Society Animal Shelter,
believes dogs should be treated like dogs, not humans. Even with
that view, she admits, some pets seem almost like children. Many
dogs who have to go through surgery at her clinic are calm until
their guardians show up and start showering them with sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't start whining until they see their owner come in,''
Ortman said. ``They enjoy the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said dogs who are groomed even seem to ``primp'' when
they first get home. But concluding that the clean, well-shaven dog
really feels like a sexier beast may not be the case, experts say.
The dog likely knows that he or she will be showered with affection
and may prance around looking for the next round of petting.
</P>
<P>
   Ortman has seen dogs with diamond earrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pets do what their owners do because they want the
attention,'' Ortman said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that your dog won't get into eating sirloin
steak every night. But Buster probably doesn't care about watching
the Animal Planet with you. When you talk to him and pet him while
you're in front of the TV, now that's what he's looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's taking proper care of your pet and providing for its
welfare,'' Adams said. ``Then there's pampering.''
</P>
<P>
   Caring for your dog includes feeding it things that help teeth
stay strong. Diamond-studded earrings are not necessary (and don't
do much to impress the other dogs, experts say). Showering your dog
with affection and spending time together on long walks is a
healthy routine for owner and pet. Talking to them through the
answering machine is optional.
</P>
<P>
   Getting your pet vaccinated and having periodic checkups is
necessary. Letting them sleep in bed with you is not. Providing a
healthy diet for your pet is necessary. Feeding him table scraps is
not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, feeding a dog human food (or letting him have too much
specialty pet foods) can lead to obesity, a common problem these
days with dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'm a firm proponent of the human/animal bond, it comes
with responsibility,'' Adams said. ``Owners have to look out for
the health and well-being of their pets and that doesn't mean
letting the dog do whatever it wants. Most dogs would like to run
free through the neighborhood without a leash, but that's not safe
for the dog. They would like to eat a lot of the foods we eat, but
that's not good for them either.''
</P>
<P>
   What about owners who insist their dogs stay inside where it's
air conditioned? Aren't dogs simply domesticated descendents of
wolves who have to deal with things like heat waves and cold
fronts?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at what the dogs are bred for,'' Ortman said.
``Some dogs would go crazy inside. They like being outside. But
poodles are different. They've been bred to be house dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said pampering doesn't just come in the home. It's on the
road, too. Many pet owners take their significant four-legged
others on cross-country vacations. While some dogs adjust well to
being in a car, owners should watch to be sure the dog isn't overly
stressed.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you won't have to worry about, though, is finding a
place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are special hotels that will accept pets,'' Miller said.
``More and more are beginning to do it. They have to, because pets
are such a big part of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: sobrien(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
