<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REVIEW-ASUNDER0908-CO     09-07 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ASUNDER0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Asunder' is a noble effort, undermined by creaky story
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - About the only time you hear the word ``asunder''
is at weddings: ``What God therefore has joined together, let no
man put asunder'' _ Matthew 19:6. But the word carries a sense of
the chaotic. A marriage put asunder doesn't just come apart; it
explodes, flinging shrapnel that rips through souls.
</P>
<P>
   That's what director Tim Reid's film ``Asunder'' attempts to
depict: an emotional explosion that rips through two couples who
initially appear to have everything.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Asunder'' has its moments, its laborious pacing, uneven
acting and often weak dialogue make it only average.
</P>
<P>
   Asunder starts with two couples at a carnival. Michael (Michael
Beach) and Lauren (Debbi Morgan) apparently have some tension
between them, but Michael's best friend Chance (Blair Underwood)
and his very pregnant wife, Roberta (Marva Hicks), are obviously
ecstatic to be together. Before the first scene is over, however,
Roberta and Chance fall from a Ferris wheel in a freak accident.
Chance escapes with minor injuries, but Roberta and the baby die.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving trio comes together after the tragedy, at first
offering one another support. But past betrayals, guilt and
jealousy will never let them heal.
</P>
<P>
   The first hour of ``Asunder'' plays like a soap opera _ Lauren
is overwrought because she and Chance had an affair before
Roberta's death; Michael is guilt-ridden because it was his idea to
ride the Ferris wheel, and he's dissatisfied because Lauren won't
have his baby; Chance puts his dead wife and child out of his mind
by becoming obsessed with Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   But the last half of the movie slips from soap to slash as
Chance's obsession turns violent. Unfortunately, Underwood is never
quite credible either as grieving husband or knife-wielding psycho,
and his failings rob much of the movie's emotional impact.
</P>
<P>
   Debbi Morgan, on the other hand, is stellar. Her sex appeal has
always been undeniable, but in ``Asunder'' she shows range and
depth in a role that requires her to be sarcastic, anxious,
heartbroken, alluring and terror-stricken in rapid succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asunder'' is the first feature from New Millenium Studios,
which was founded by Tim Reid, television actor turned
producer/director. The film had a red-carpet premiere in Dayton
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Reid has said he's interested in making movies for mature,
black, middle-class audiences to give them alternatives to the
teen-oriented fare he says mainstream Hollywood produces for the
black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asunder,'' is essentially a typical Hollywood movie about
troubled, affluent suburbanites with black performers slipped into
roles whites would usually play. Race never becomes an issue, and
aside from a few ``hip'' verbal exchanges between Michael and
Chance, the ethnicity of the characters is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   It's refreshing to see black characters running businesses and
hiring waiters to serve guests at a Christmas party in their home.
It's too bad, however, there wasn't a better script to go along
with the fancy clothes and the nice sets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SERVINGS-0908-COX     09-07 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERVINGS-0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumers face the daily dilemma of up-sizing their meals or
thinking about portion control
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - At 42, LuAnn Soliah isn't a kid anymore, but she
plays one at fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   But to avoid any disputes about her age qualifications when she
orders happy meals and kids club specials, Soliah usually goes
through the drive-through.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go inside, sometimes they won't let you order off the
children's menu unless you're under 12,'' the Baylor University
nutrition professor said. ``If you go through the drive-through
they usually think it's for someone else. Sometimes they look at me
and ask if I want the toy.''
</P>
<P>
   Soliah isn't trying to save money by going with small orders.
And, for the record, she usually turns down the complimentary toys.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah, like millions of Americans, is trying to eat healthily.
But paying attention to nutrition in today's eat-out era doesn't
just mean watching what she eats. It means watching how much she
eats.
</P>
<P>
   Portion sizes at fast-food and sit-down restaurants are getting
bigger and bigger, Soliah and other nutritionists warn. Most
vending machines offer 20-ounce bottles of soda, instead of the
12-ounce size. Whataburger offers a 44-ounce drink, more fit for
snorkeling in than drinking. There's the Bacon Ultimate
Cheeseburger at Jack in the Box _ with two thick and juicy pieces
of meat, of course. Burger King recently added a super-size option
to its kids meal, calling them Big Kids Meals. And at most pizza
joints, the term ``small'' is blasphemy. Entry-level pizzas at
Domino's are ``medium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, you're not going to want to go back to a
place that serves small portions,'' said Janelle Walter, a
professor in the Baylor department of family/consumer science.
``The servings are large so you'll come back.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``portion distortion,'' as nutritionists call it, has
customers financially satisfied but nutritionally bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are at a restaurant and get a plate that has two big
pieces of chicken-fried steak, they'll do their best to eat it all,
even though it's more than they need,'' Walter said. ``When I'm at
restaurants, a lot of times I wish I could get something off the
senior citizens menu because it's usually the right amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Eating a colossally-huge, extra-jumbo order of french fries, for
instance, isn't what our bodies need, Walter and Soliah say. The
worst part for the health of the average drive-through addict is
that it's usually the less healthy parts of take-out meals _ like
fries and calorie-filled soft drinks _ that are up-sized,
nutritionists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is more Americans are eating out as part of their
normal lifestyle,'' said Kathryn Cortes, a dietitian at Providence
Health Center in Waco. ``And (restaurants) aren't offering extra
large salads or servings of vegetables. Actually, vegetables are
one of the most expensive items.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortes and Soliah said the problem with all this is that the
biggest portions are marketed as the best deals. In fact, 40
percent of adults say they feel like restaurants encourage people
to order the largest-size portions, according to a study by the
National Restaurant Association. Convenience stores often sell
their 44-ounce thirst-quenching, mega drinks for less than smaller
sizes, practically forcing customers to drown themselves in the
carbonated drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was wrong with a 12-ounce drink?'' Soliah said. ``Now,
you get their huge drinks. You don't want or need that much to
quench your thirst. But it's such a good deal, you end up buying
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The health problem comes when people then feel compelled to
finish their meal because they've paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pay for it, we feel obligated to eat it,'' Soliah said.
``That interferes with our effort to keep our weight under
control.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Health Statistics estimated that the
percentage of adults 20 to 74 who were obese increased 24 percent
in the 1960s to more than 33 percent in the late 1980s. By 1994,
the share of overweight adults climbed to 35 percent. Kids are 30
percent heavier than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the problem continues to get worse, recent studies suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at epidemic levels,'' Soliah said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the ``go large'' phenomenon comes from consumer demands,
but some is a natural outgrowth of more competition in the
restaurant industry. As Americans eat out more, more restaurants
open their doors to meet the demand. In turn, they fight for
business, offering ``platters'' _ not plates _ of food for less
than the eatery next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a competitive angle,'' said Alison Hovanec, a spokeswoman
with the Texas Restaurant Association. ``Restaurants have had to
diversify their concepts and watch prices and portions to keep up
with the guy next door. They have to be different. A lot of them do
that by offering more food for your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mike Mount, a spokesman with the National Restaurant
Association, admits that going lean may mean steering away from the
bulk of a restaurant's menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wants a small portion, they can get an appetizer
or order a children's-size meal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail sobrien(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
