<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5173 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-SPORTS-RECIPES0907-CO     09-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-RECIPES0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Athlete's diet can include soup, pork chops
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following recipes have benefits specific to an athlete's
needs. A varied diet is important to everyone, however.
</P>
<P>
   Three-mushroom garlic soup
</P>
<P>
   1 fourteen-ounce can vegetable or beef broth (low-sodium)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dried mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced fresh button mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced fresh shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon snipped fresh thyme or marjoram (or 1 teaspoon
dried, crushed thyme or marjoram)
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups fat-free milk
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup nonfat dry milk powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry sherry (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, bring broth to boiling. Add dried
mushrooms; remove from heat. Let stand for 10 minutes. Drain,
reserving broth. Chop mushrooms; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, cook onion and garlic in hot butter or
margarine until tender. Carefully stir in reserved broth, chopped
dried mushrooms, button mushrooms, shiitake mushrooms herbs and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to boiling; reduce heat. Simmer, covered, for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, stir together the milk, milk powder, and cornstarch;
stir into mixture in saucepan. Stir in carrot. Cook and stir until
thickened and bubbly. Cook and stir for 2 minutes more. If desired,
stir in sherry.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 main-dish servings, or 6 first-course servings.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1 1/2 cup serving: 193 calories, 3 g. fat, 8 mg.
cholesterol, 36 g. carbohydrates, 12 g. protein. Daily values: 70
percent vitamin A, 14 percent vitamin C, 28 percent calcium, 12
percent iron.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   This is a great dinner casserole, but also could be eaten for
breakfast. Assemble it the night before eating, and keep it in the
fridge. Bake it as instructed.
</P>
<P>
   Egg and potato casserole
</P>
<P>
   nonstick spray coating
</P>
<P>
   2 cups frozen loose-pack diced hash brown potatoes with onions
and peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen cut broccoli or asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup finely chopped Canadian-style bacon or lean ham (2
ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup evaporated fat-free milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 eight-ounce cartons refrigerated or frozen egg product, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded reduced-fat cheddar cheese (2 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon snipped fresh basil or 1/2 teaspoon dried basil,
crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt, optional
</P>
<P>
   Spray a 2-quart baking dish with nonstick coating. Arrange hash
browns and broccoli or asparagus in the bottom of the dish; top
with Canadian bacon or ham. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, gradually stir milk into flour. Stir in egg
product, half of the cheese, basil, black pepper, and salt, if
desired. Pour egg mixture over vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 350(degrees) oven for 40 to 45 minutes or until a
knife inserted near center comes out clean. Sprinkle with remaining
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Let stand 5 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 188 calories, 5 g. fat, 11 mg. cholesterol, 373 mg.
sodium, 18 g. carbohydrates, 17 g. protein. Daily values: 23%
vitamin A, 25% vitamin C, 13% calcium, 17% iron.
</P>
<P>
   (Above recipes from ``Better Homes and Gardens Food for Health
and Healing,'' Merideth Books, 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Salmon pasta salad
</P>
<P>
   1 eight-ounce box bow-tie pasta
</P>
<P>
   1 small can (4 ounces) pink salmon, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lentils, cooked and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 fourteen-ounce can hearts of palm, drained, sliced into
circles
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon finely minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   For dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup bottled low-fat citrus vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon low sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta according to package directions for salad use. Rinse
under cold water and drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Place pasta in large bowl. Drain salmon and flake with fork. Add
to pasta. Add remaining ingredients, tossing well to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Mix vinaigrette and soy sauce; pour over all and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 215 calories, 15 g. protein, 5.9 g. fat, 26 g.
carbohydrates, 21 mg. cholesterol, 493 mg. sodium, 5.2 mg. iron,
2.9% vitamin A.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary apple pork chops
</P>
<P>
   4 six-ounce pork chops
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple juice concentrate
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Place pork chops in a shallow glass or ceramic container and
cover with rosemary, apple juice concentrate, and garlic. Cover and
refrigerate 4 hours or overnight, turning occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Take chops from refrigerator, remove as much of the marinade as
possible and place in a small saucepan. Bring to a boil over high
heat and cook 2 minutes. Remove; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare grill or broiler. Place chops on a rack and cook for
about 5 minutes on each side, or until chops are done as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with cooked marinade.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 385 calories, 35.7 g. protein, 19.7 g. fat, 16 mg.
calcium, 1.51 mg. iron, 104 mg. sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Mashed sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 medium-size sweet potatoes, scrubbed or peeled, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and finely chopped or pressed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh ginger root or more, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons yogurt cheese (made from yogurt drained overnight
through cheesecloth) 3/4 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons skim milk
</P>
<P>
   Boil sweet potatoes, garlic and ginger in a medium-size saucepan
on medium-high heat for about 20 minutes or until potatoes are
tender. Drain and mash well with a fork or electric beater. (Note:
Do not use a food processor or blender; it makes the potatoes
rubbery.)
</P>
<P>
   Add remaining ingredients. If needed, reheat over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 102 calories, 2.84 g. protein, 22.1 g.
carbohydrates, 0.4 g. fat, 1.32 mg. cholesterol, 70.4 mg. calcium,
0.4 mg. iron, 422 mg. sodium.
</P>
<P>
   (The above two recipes are from ``The Diet Workshop's Recipes
for Healthy Living'' by Lois L. Lindauer and Sally Sampson,
Doubleday, 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
