<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5174 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-YACHT-TRUMPY0908-COX     09-07 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-TRUMPY0908-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Say 'Trumpy' to a yachtsman, and you may as well say
'perfection.'
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Reid
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Down at Cracker Boy Boat Works, the trio
of old wooden yachts stands out among the dozens of fiberglass
craft like gold doubloons in a fountain full of coppers.
</P>
<P>
   Their teak decks and mahogany trim drink in the blazing white
light of noon and convert it to a soft, rich shellacked glow. Their
old prows jut, strong chins, out toward the sea, as if in defiant
challenge. They are in rough shape, undergoing restoration, but
still, they are as graceful as old violins.
</P>
<P>
   They are Trumpy motor yachts, genteel, rugged, elegant even in
decrepitude.
</P>
<P>
   They were not simply handmade; they were handcrafted, each out
of 50 tons of lumber, a shipwright's dream and a house carpenter's
nightmare because there's hardly a straight line to be found
anywhere on board.
</P>
<P>
   Steam-bent ribs, molded planks, rough-cut keels, laminated
fittings, smooth railings, flawless decks _ yellow pine, white oak,
chestnut curled and planed, caulked and doweled, rubbed and buffed
into perfect symmetry, perfect balance.
</P>
<P>
   John Trumpy built them about 40 years ago in his boat yard, the
Mathis Yacht Building Co., Camden, N.J. He built the 104-foot yacht
Sequoia for Philadelphian Richard Cadwalader in 1925. It was bought
by the Department of Commerce in 1931, and by 1933, FDR was
cruising down the Potomac on it and the Sequoia has been known as
the presidential yacht ever since. He built boats for a Who's Who
of old American money: Scripps, Bingham, Deering, Chrysler. And new
money: the Vernon Savings and Loan yacht was repossessed by the
U.S. government. And he built minesweepers, cutters and sub chasers
for the government. Wood could take the pounding of Coast Guard
rescue work, and it's the only way to build a minesweeper: Magnetic
mines detonate in proximity to steel hulls.
</P>
<P>
   And otherwise staid minds detonate in proximity to old Trumpy
boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to check your brains at the door when you buy one,
like at a horse auction,'' says Trumpy boat owner John Regan of
Palm Beach. ``I suppose you could buy one for the status, but you
really should buy one because you love it. A wooden boat demands
much but gives back more.''
</P>
<P>
   John Trumpy was Johan Trumpy when he emigrated from Norway to
the U.S. in 1902. The Trumpy family had built boats in Norway for
two generations, and a branch of the family built boats in New York
City. The family hailed originally from Switzerland, where
oceangoing boats are something to read about, dream about. Johan
wanted to go where the action was. So he went to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His boats are not the Rolls-Royces of yachts; they are the
Dusenbergs. They were custom-built, all 366 private boats the
Trumpy yard sent down the ways from 1910 to the early 1970s. Only
90 are left. Many are derelicts, the nautical equivalent of the
banker who goes bust and ends up smoking cigar stubs under a
bridge, but only the finest Cuban cigar stubs. Even a derelict
Trumpy boat says wealth, even if it's former wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Like all rare slices of Americana, Trumpy boats have their
followers. Anybody with enough money can buy a yacht, but only a
lover of wooden boats, like Regan, will seek out and buy a Trumpy.
Most likely the boat will need work. Most likely the new owner will
call Jim Mooresdown at Cracker Boy in Riviera Beach, Fla., even if
the new owner is a Dutch merchant who lives in Tanzania, as is the
case with the owner of one of the Trumpys Jim Moores is restoring.
There just aren't a lot of places on the planet where a Trumpy can
get respect.
</P>
<P>
   They get love from Moores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the original craftsmanship,'' says Moores. He's
standing next to the concrete and wood blocks that support an
82-foot Trumpy, high and dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longleaf yellow pine sub-planking, fitted tight, perfect,'' he
says. ``And look along the keel. See how the entire stern is made
to help the boat ride up, push through the water. Look at the
curvature, bow to stern. And then remember: It's all wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Moores is in his mid-40s, flaxen hair, youthful face. Looks like
a Viking after a shave and a haircut. Knows his boats like Vikings
knew theirs. He rode into West Palm Beach 20 years ago, in a
pickup, with his tools and $400. From Lubec, Maine, literally a
stone's throw from New Brunswick, across a piece of the North
Atlantic that freezes for too many months each year.
</P>
<P>
   Up in Lubec, in his youth, Moores built small fishing boats for
Canadian fishermen. And he built dories, the classical fishing
trawler of the American fishing fleet. A good dory gets steadier in
the water as you load it with fish. A dory filled to the gunwales
with cod is as steady a boat as floats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Canadian dollar went south in the late '70s; so did the
fishing industry. So did I,'' says Moores. ``I came here to start a
business, but look around. Lots of boats in Florida, lots of boat
yards. But not a lot of people who know wooden boats. But then
again, not a lot of wooden boats anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   So he grew up in Maine, in a seafaring, boat-building family
perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana, actually,'' he says. ``But my family ran lumber mills
from Oregon to the Midwest. We know wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if the boat-building Trumpy family can come from
Switzerland, the boat-restoring Moores might as well hail from
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody at the Cracker Boy boat yard has that lean, sea-salty
look from laboring under a hot sun. Moores, too. But he and his
seven colleagues _ including his 19-year old son, Andre _ wear lots
of sawdust in their hair. Sawdust from sanding, sanding, sanding.
Wooden boat restoration requires lots of sanding.
</P>
<P>
   The tips of mahogany dowels litter the ground, the whine of
electric sanders litters the air. Tools and blueprints are
scattered about. A cube of first-growth yellow pine lies in a
corner. It's all that's left of a beam Moores found in a demolished
warehouse in West Palm Beach. Only a guy who knows wood could spot
a treasure like that in a pile of dust-encrusted rubble.
First-growth wood is long gone from Florida, the South. Moores
milled the beam into a spar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can use the original materials _ white oak, yellow pine
_ that's the best,'' he says. ``But the forests ... Well, the
forests are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Moores is surveying Andre's handiwork. Andre is under the hull
but not out of the sun. He's hot, he's sanding, he's sweating and
he's smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an apprentice, starting like I started,'' says Moores.
``At the bottom. The keel, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Up on deck, finish work is being done by Richard Rasmusson's
crew. Rasmusson's company installs new baths, dining rooms, beveled
mirrors, mahogany-front fridges, entire bedroom suites. He is known
as the master of custom finish work. His railing joints meet
without so much as a shadow, his hand-made cabin doors snap closed
with authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to spend a million restoring a boat to hear it
rattle,'' says Rasmusson.
</P>
<P>
   And they don't want to spend a million for a leaky hull. So
Moores' crew caulks and planes until an oiled razor blade couldn't
fit between the planks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find a Trumpy for maybe $200,000,'' says Moores.
``Figure a million to restore it. Not repair. Restore. You don't
fix a Trumpy with fiberglass, or mix wood helter-skelter in the
hull. You rebuild them. One nail, one dowel at a time. And when
you're done, you have a boat that costs as much, more maybe, than a
Hatteras. But when you motor down the Intracoastal, people will
look. And they'll look until you're out of sight.''
</P>
<P>
   You can get lost in the Cracker Boy yard. Lots of boats. But if
you ask for Jim Moores, everyone in the yard will direct you thus:
He's down over there with those three Trumpys.
</P>
<P>
   And when you ask, how do I tell a Trumpy from the rest, the
yardmen will say: You'll know.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: paulreid(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
