r e BC-FILM-THEWATCHER-TEX     09-07 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THEWATCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT FOR THOSE THREADBARE SERIAL-KILLER CLICHES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hackneyed serial killer thriller ``The Watcher'' commits a
crime even worse than being irrepressibly dull ... it allows star
Keanu Reeves to speak.
</P>
<P>
   And all the elocution lessons his ``Matrix'' money could buy
would still be incapable of draining the Val-speak from his voice.
Reeves stars as a voyeuristic lady-killer with a penchant for
stalking his victims, then strangling them with piano wire.
</P>
<P>
   James Spader _ whose gravelly, emotionless tone and
overdependence upon prescription medication makes him seem like the
more ideal sort to play the story's homicidal creep _ is the FBI
agent whose obsession with the case forced him to abandon LA for
Chicago. Reeves follows, of course, escalating their cat-and-mouse
game by Fed-Exing pictures of his intended victims.
</P>
<P>
   Spader is reluctantly drawn back into the investigation, making
desperate attempts to find the nameless faces in an uncaring city
conditioned to pay as little attention as possible. There are some
clumsy attempts to make a point about how we go through life
without really seeing each other, how one person can be lost in sea
of forgotten souls. How apropos, considering how quickly this
substandard thriller will be forgotten in a seemingly endless ocean
of serial-killer flicks.
</P>
<P>
   First-time director Joe Charbanic got his start in music videos,
which explains the annoying overuse of grainy film stocks, artsy
flashbacks and jump cuts. Yet in all of its attempts to be visually
striking (which, incidentally, it is not), ``The Watcher'' fails to
build even the slightest shred of suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar-winner Marisa Tomei slums it as Spader's shrink and an
obvious victim-in-waiting, but she's given no other practical
purpose for being there. It's not about her, after all. But
considering that the film relies so heavily on the chemistry
between its two leads, you'd think they might have looked for more
explosive ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Watcher''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joe Charbanic
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Keanu Reeves, James Spader, Marisa Tomei
</P>
<P>
   Length: 93 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, strong language and adult subject matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7691, or e-mail:
tcamp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
