<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-BETTY-SPI &LR;      09-07 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BETTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART AND SWEET, `NURSE BETTY' IS JUST WHAT THE DOCTOR ORDERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: A-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renee Zellweger's fresh-scrubbed looks and Midwest innocence won
her acclaim in ``Jerry Maguire'' but have been ill-used since. That
is, until she landed the lead in ``Nurse Betty,'' a delightfully
comic crime fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   In a contemporary take on ``The Wizard of Oz,'' Zellweger's
Betty Sizemore is a Dorothy in a small-town Kansas coffee shop.
She's perky, pretty and sweetly sociable, but a numbing marriage to
a philandering used car salesman (Aaron Eckhart) and fizzled dreams
have left her with a glazed-over smile for too much of her
existence.
</P>
<P>
   Her only relief is escape into a soap opera fantasy where she
imagines herself the true love of sensitive, haunted,
oh-so-handsome young Dr. David Ravell, played by cocky actor George
McCord (Greg Kinnear).
</P>
<P>
   The tornado that whooshes through her life arrives in the form
of two hit men _ deliberate, precise pro Charlie (Morgan Freeman)
and his smart-mouth, excitable protege Wesley (Chris Rock) _ who
literally scalp her scamming husband during an interrogation gone
terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The shock sends her spinning over the rainbow and onto the road
to Los Angeles in her husband's Buick (which just happens to hold
the contraband the hit men seek) as Nurse Betty, Dr. Ravell's
long-lost love who's coming back to reclaim her beau.
</P>
<P>
   She has two determined gunmen behind her, a flabbergasted soap
star convinced she's method-acting an elaborate audition (``Your
dedication scares me,'' he says after a couple of dates ``in
character''), and the luck of an innocent keeping her safe from
harm in the dangerous Oz of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Director Neil LaBute (``In the Company of Men''), working from a
script by first-time film scribes John C. Richards and James
Flamberg, shakes his sour vision of predatory human relations for
an altogether more generous portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Eckhart plays a smarmy, misanthropic creep and Kinnear
fine-tunes his now patented narcissistic jerk to smug perfection,
but LaBute turns true-hearted naif Betty into more than simply a
little lost innocent. The film could easily have descended into a
mean-spirited lampoon of a woman who confuses an escapist TV serial
for real life, but it's smarter and sharper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring Betty's journey is Freeman's philosophical Charlie, a
clear-headed career criminal who idealizes his target as a
combination homespun innocent, sophisticated aesthete and cunning
nemesis. Laconic, quiet, with a world-weary air effortlessly about
him, Freeman has never been better.
</P>
<P>
   When he erupts with, ``She could never fall in love with a soap
opera character,'' little realizing that he unwittingly has
himself, the joke gives way to the aching sincerity in his face. Is
there any difference between his romantic fantasy and hers?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's little satirical sting to the film,
rather surprising from the usually cutting LaBute, and he lets a
few glib twists drop with a thud, but those are minor caveats. He
pulls the farce and the violence and the fantasies together with a
deft touch and a sweetness rare in American films _ especially his.
</P>
<P>
   NURSE BETTY
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Neil LaBute
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: John C. Richards and James Flamberg
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Renee Zellweger, Morgan Freeman, Chris Rock, Greg Kinnear,
Aaron Eckhart
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 109 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R for strong violence, pervasive language and a scene of
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5229 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-LOVEANDSEX-SPI &LR;      09-07 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVEANDSEX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANSSEN BREAKS FANS' HEARTS AGAIN DOING A FINE JOB IN AN INFERIOR
FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've always maintained Famke Janssen can do no wrong _ except in
choosing her films.
</P>
<P>
   While she racked up hits in ``GoldenEye'' and ``X-Men'' and sank
her fangs into some clever genre exercises (``The House on Haunted
Hill,'' ``The Faculty'') with vamping glee, she remains most
notable as the best thing in many a self-indulgent American
independent production.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: ``Love and Sex,'' yet another in a seemingly
endless stream of indie romantic comedies. Apparently an
autobiographical peek into the dating travails of writer/director
Valerie Breiman, it confirms what many of us suspected for so long:
Hollywood writers really do live sitcom lives, minus the laugh
track. Imagine ``Sex in the City'' with an insecure heroine, no
sexy friends and none of the steamy sex.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine scribe Kate Wells (Janssen) muses over her romantic
history for an article about dating and the single woman in the
city. In flashbacks, we tour from her first high school affair
(it's both embarrassing and unsettling to watch Janssen play an
underage teen with a squeaky, shrieky voice between the sheets with
her French teacher) to her last lover, a dim hunk with a Robert
DeNiro-obsession. But the bulk of her remembrance revolves around
flippant artist Adam (Jon Favreau, the teddy bear single of
``Swingers'').
</P>
<P>
   Janssen gives passion and purpose to an often glib and whiny
role. She doesn't try to hide her model's figure, but rather
carries herself with a gangly awkwardness that broadcasts
insecurity, which explains her string of hopeless boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Favreau keeps his charm in low gear, sneaking up on us with
clever banter that feels more like a challenge than a pickup line.
He delivers Adam's ``I'm just a horny, self-indulgent guy'' lines
with a gentleness and a deprecating humor that belies the pose.
</P>
<P>
   Kate and Adam break up, embark on elaborate jealousy gambits and
obsess endlessly over one another while trying to remain ``just
friends,'' but it plays out like some grotesque sitcom. Appealing
as they are, Janssen and Favreau don't throw off sparks or even a
slow simmer. If they're made for each other, it's solely because
they're the only interesting people in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love and Sex'' is sprinkled with witty lines and convincingly
cuddly moments, and anchored by performers intent on turning their
neurosis-riddled roles into dimensional characters, but Breiman
brings nothing new or insightful or even all that clever, for that
matter, to the familiar questions of love and sex she churns up.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE AND SEX
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Valerie Breiman
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Famke Janssen, Jon Favreau, Noah Emmerich, Cheri Oteri,
Ann Magnuson
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 82 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: No rating, features sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
