<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-HUMANRIGHTS-$A     09-07 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-HUMANRIGHTS-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN A NEW ERA, MEXICANS EXAMINE THE ``DISAPPEARED'' AND OTHER
ABUSES
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 10 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Rosario Ibarra applauded when Mexican police last
month arrested an Argentine here who is suspected of kidnapping and
``disappearing'' scores of dissidents during Argentina's military
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aug. 24 arrest also rekindled Ibarra's 25-year-old cry
for a serious investigation into Mexico's own prolonged repression
against dissidents - including Ibarra's 21-year-old son, Jesus, a
student who was kidnapped by armed men in Monterrey on April 18,
1975 and has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a key moment for us, for the family of the disappeared
here,'' said Ibarra, 73, one of Mexico's premier human rights
figures, who has relentlessly criticized Mexico's ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the PRI, for years.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the PRI was finally defeated in an election that will
end its 71-year lock on this country's powerful presidency. On Dec.
1, when president-elect Vicente Fox takes over, many families of
the disappeared hope he will investigate successive PRI
governments' reported use of torture, killings, secret detentions
and disappearances of political foes.
</P>
<P>
   During a televised campaign debate, Fox paid tribute to Ibarra's
``perseverance'' and ``struggle for the disappeared'' and made an
emotional appeal to Mexicans to end ``PRI authoritarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibarra and others say some of those responsible or knowledgeable
about human rights abuses are still prominent figures in the PRI,
the government, private business or in the military. Two Army
generals arrested Aug. 31 on drug-trafficking charges have also
been implicated in human rights abuses by former detainees and
families of Mexico's disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything the system did here, it did because they thought
they were untouchable,'' Ibarra said. ``I hope there's justice in
this country, and that (Fox) will do what the PRI didn't do during
so many years of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fox takes office he is expected to recommend Congress set
up a ``transparency commission'' that could probe the fate of the
disappeared and other human rights abuses as well as corruption and
theft of public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If society has proof of abuses, then I think investigations
will happen,'' said Fox aide Adolfo Aguilar Zinser.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who'd like a probe is Victor Pineda, 23, who was
only one year old when his father, a teacher and community
organizer also named Victor, was detained by soldiers in Juchitan,
Oaxaca, on July 11, 1978. His family has never been able to find
out what happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine the trauma this causes children,'' Pineda
said, sitting by his mother during a recent gathering of relatives
of the disappeared at Ibarra's home. ``But now the dirty inner
workings of the government are being revealed. There are people who
know what happened and they continue to walk the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   During her long, frustrating quest to find her son, Ibarra
founded the Eureka Group, which contends there are at least 448
unlawfully detained people still missing. The group forced the
release of about 1,500 political prisoners in the 1980s, some of
whom had vanished for as long as nine years, Ibarra said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the disappeared were rounded up during a wave of violent
repression through the 1970s, following the infamous Oct. 2, 1968
massacre of hundreds of youths protesting for more democracy prior
to the Olympic Games in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, disappeared in the 1980s or 1990s. Army Lt.
Miguel Orlando Munoz was 25 when he disappeared in May 8, 1993 in
Juarez, a city steeped in corruption and collusion between the
Mexican military and powerful drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz's family claims they've been repeatedly lied to and
stonewalled by the military, which they believe is hiding
information about Munoz's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the PRI's defeat, two recent scandals here
sparked new demands to investigate the disappeared and other
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   In August Mexican police arrested a prominent Argentine
businessman who the government had hired to direct a
car-registration program here. Former Argentine military officer
Ricardo Cavallo is being held for possible extradition to Spain to
face charges of atrocities committed against Spanish citizens and
others during Argentina's 1976-1983 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s and 1980s, Mexico's PRI governments _ which
professed a leftist tradition _ welcomed refugees from Argentina
and Chile, where right-wing military regimes killed thousands. At
the same time, however, the PRI was violently cracking down on its
own mostly leftist opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mexican dissidents armed themselves in response to
escalating repression. ``They didn't do that because of simple
adventurism. Remember what happened on Oct. 2,'' said Ibarra, who
still cries when she talks about her son, a medical student who,
unknown to her, was a sympathizer of a dissident organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they broke the law, then sentence them. That's what
justice is for,'' Ibarra said. ``What happened was the reverse. The
government broke its own laws and became a terrorist. It violated
the constitution, tortured, kidnapped and set up clandestine
jails.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Solomon of New York-based Human Rights Watch, agreed. His
organization, like Amnesty International, has compiled reports of
disappearances and unlawful detentions from the 1970s up to
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, Mexico legitimately laid claim to being a
refuge for the politically oppressed. But it's not an excuse for
its own excesses,'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico for a long time didn't get the scrutiny it deserved,''
he added, in contrast to South American regimes. ``The government
took advantage of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, according to a 1999 U.S. State Department report
recognizing a pattern of abuses, has had ``limited success'' in
improving its justice system: ``A culture of abuse continues to
pervade the security forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's long history of impunity was also spotlighted recently
with the arrest last month of two Army generals, one active duty
and the other recently retired, who are accused of protecting
Juarez-based drug traffickers. Ibarra and others believe these same
generals either participated in kidnapping dissidents or have
information about their fate.
</P>
<P>
   Octaviano Santiago, who is now a left-wing opposition legislator
in Guerrero state, said in April 1978 he was arrested and tortured
during a secret interrogation by one of the generals, Mario Acosta
Chaparro. At that time Acosta Chaparro held a lower rank, said
Santiago, who spoke by telephone from Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acosta Chaparro told me he had detained certain people,''
Santiago said, reciting six names. ``Those people never appeared
again. I'm willing to testify about this in any court of law that
calls me. This is the most important opportunity we have to find
out what happened to our people. (Acosta Chaparro) is a living
crime file. So among the sea of bitterness, this gives me a spark
of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Matilde Gonzalez, whose 23-year-old son, Jesus, disappeared in
1974, said the other general, Francisco Quiroz Hermosillo, had a
reputation as a military officer who offered to sell information
about disappeared people.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said that in 1976 a neighbor passed her a message from
Hermosillo, who was an acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighbor said if I could pay 250,000 pesos (about
US$20,000) and buy a gold ring to give to his wife, Hermosillo
would provide some information. But I didn't have that kind of
money,'' said Gonzalez, 74, who has participated in hunger strikes,
marches, and visited prisons and filed multiple legal appeals in
vain over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico the Army has been untouchable,'' added Concepcion
Avila, Gonzalez's daughter. ``We've been waiting for a moment like
this, just like people in Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.amnesty.org
</P>
<P>
   www.humanrightswatch.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
