<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ George W. Bush, battling concern by
some Republicans that his campaign is faltering, flanks himself
with military leaders in the Persian Gulf War who back his pledge
to equip America's armed forces with billions of dollars worth of
new high-tech equipment. Al Gore, buoyed by a new poll showing him
with a 6 percentage point edge over Bush, expects to receive an
endorsement from the 1.5-million-member Teamsters union that long
favored Republicans. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Detroit) _ Confronted by polls showing he is trailing or
tied with Al Gore, George W. Bush says he now considers himself the
underdog and, in a slap at his Democratic opponent, jokes that he
needs to be more of an ``alpha male.'' By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Scranton, Pa.) _ Vice President Al Gore, once criticized
for being too aggressive and distant on the campaign trail, has
been more mellow and more accessible lately. The kinder, gentler
Gore may be linked to the polls showing that he is overtaking his
rival for the presidency. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Washington) _ Reform Party hopeful Patrick
Buchanan announces he will try to block rival John Hagelin's effort
to win $12.6 million in federal election funds. Buchanan says he
will file a lawsuit challenging his opponent's claim to be the
party's nominee in 10 states. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-DEATHS (Washington) _ The Justice Department is considering
whether to investigate the Ford Motor Co. and Bridgestone/Firestone
Inc. over their handling of apparently defective Firestone tires
that were used on some Ford models. Meanwhile, Congress is weighing
legislation that would require companies to immediately report
recalls that occur in other countries. By JENNIFER HOYT.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-TRIBUTE (Washington) _ A political action committee
supporting House Republicans who led the impeachment case against
President Clinton cancels a tribute to former Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr. With some of Clinton's House prosecutors facing
tough election battles this November, Republicans are questioning
the wisdom of placing an emphasis on what was a losing issue for
them in the polls. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX (Washington) _ The House fails to override President
Clinton's veto of the estate tax repeal, giving Republicans what
they say is a potent political issue for the campaign trail. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UN-SUMMIT (United Nations) _ World leaders turn from the
ceremony of the Millennium Summit to problems facing the United
Nations, including peacekeeping operations and end to conflicts in
several regions of the globe. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
