   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING (Houston) _ Sen. Charles Hagel, R-Neb., a global
warming skeptic and chief critic of the Kyoto accords, addresses a
conference at Rice University's Baker Institute on Public Policy.
By TODD ACKERMAN and BILL DAWSON.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ Ground teams are back on
schedule, overcoming storm delays as they prepare the shuttle
Atlantis and a crew of seven for a mission to the international
space station. The shuttle is to lift off Friday morning. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Al Gore's vow to fight for a minimum
wage increase prompted big cheers at the Democratic National
Convention, second only to promises to protect abortion rights and
overhaul the health care system. The minimum wage issue is so
popular that congressional Republicans dare not oppose it outright.
Instead they are loading it up with tax breaks for business. George
W. Bush has his own zinger. He wants to give states the right to
ignore the minimum wage if they want. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-TRAINER (Washington) _ It was originally billed by the
Pentagon as a low-risk, relatively low-cost program to equip the
armed forces with a simple training aircraft for novice pilots. But
now the project is expected to significantly exceed cost estimates
_ by as much as $750 million with taxpayers footing most of the
bill. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
