<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SPINALTAP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS SPINAL TAP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a little weird to write about a movie that will appear on
VH1 between the time I finish typing this review and the time the
review hits print _ not to mention a movie that will be released on
DVD four days after it opens in theaters. But in the world of
Spinal Tap, where amplifier volume goes to 11 instead of 10 and
Stonehenge is a foot-and-a-half tall, somehow, it makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, why bother to see this reissue of Rob Reiner's
mock-rock-doc in a theater? The obvious answer _ that all
theatrical films should be seen on the big screen _ doesn't
necessarily apply here, especially because video editions and the
upcoming DVD will have extra scenes. Nothing much has been done to
this 16th-anniversary reissue; although it looks sharp, the sound
isn't exactly state-of-the-art stereo. The best answer is that the
movie gains from having an audience; it's a communal experience,
with so many good lines and bits that the laughter often covers
them up.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, the movie is a fake documentary about the
world's loudest hair-metal band, and Reiner and co-writers Michael
McKean, Christopher Guest and Harry Shearer _ who play the core of
the band _ deftly pierce many rock cliches and pomposities. There's
a germ of a plot, as guitarist/singer David St. Hubbins' (McKean)
control-freak girlfriend drives a band-threatening wedge between
him and his longtime musical partner, Nigel Tufnel (Guest). But
mostly it's a series of amusing-to-gutbusting sketches as
chronicled by Marty Di Bergi, the Scorsesean filmmaker portrayed by
Reiner. In 1984, many of these scenes looked a little absurd _ now,
after we've lived through the excesses of Poison, Cinderella, Skid
Row and others, they look eerily prescient while managing to not be
dated.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner the director gets the movie over with quick, and that's
part of what makes it work; some bits are a little too slow, but
the movie as a whole is so brief that it never wears out its
welcome. ``Spinal Tap'' doesn't work for everyone, but those who do
connect with it will find that it leaves them hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Spinal Tap''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 82 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
