<HEADER>
A5242 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-NURSEBETTY-TEX     09-07 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NURSEBETTY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOSAGE IS JUST RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Nurse Betty'' begins, Betty (Renee Zellweger) is a
waitress at a small-town Kansas diner who's so enthralled by her
favorite soap opera that she's become adept at refilling coffee
cups behind her back, so that she won't have to pull her eyes from
the TV screen. But when something bad happens to her scummy
husband, the quirky Betty really goes off the deep end. And we're
off on the road in this enjoyably twisted comedy of self-delusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' is a change of pace for director Neil LaBute,
who appears to have decided _ after the misanthropy of his first
two movies, ``In the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and
Neighbors'' _ that nice people do exist, after all. Of course, he
didn't write ``Nurse Betty''; John C. Richards and James Flamberg
did the darkly witty screenplay, which won the screenwriting award
at the Cannes Film Festival. But LaBute's sensibilities still come
through _ as in the jarringly violent scene in which Betty
witnesses two hit men (Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock) murdering her
husband over some lost cocaine. It's a graphic scene, and it
switches something off inside Betty.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that should be switches something on _ somehow, through
one of those psychological oddities that movies love so much, Betty
becomes convinced that a doctor character on her soap, ``A Reason
to Love,'' is her ex-fiance. Before her husband's body is cold, she
sets off to LA to reunite with the doctor, with the killers, the
town sheriff and a reporter in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time this year that Zellweger has been
involved in a plot like this _ she was on the run in ``Me Myself &AMP;
Irene,'' which also featured a character whose psyche was
traumatically snapped. But ``Nurse Betty'' puts her in the driver's
seat, and the movie is better for it. So's Zellweger. In ``Me
Myself &AMP; Irene,'' as in a lot of her other movies, the Texas native
was reduced to a reactive role; here, she drops her trademark
squint and screwed-up pout to give a wide-eyed, charmingly
ingenuous performance. Others react to her, and many of the movie's
best moments occur when it dawns on the people Betty meets that not
all of her spark plugs are firing.
</P>
<P>
   But Betty isn't the only person who's deluded. Freeman, who has
a weary gravity as the more patient of the two killers, plays a guy
who develops a crush on his vision of Betty as he begins to believe
that she's the angel who will pull him out of his moral sewer. And
the actor (Greg Kinnear) who plays the soap-opera doctor is so
flattered by Betty's attention that he mistakes her for a
particularly talented method actress and tries to get her a part on
the soap.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnear's character is the movie's biggest problem; although
Kinnear is fine, LaBute and the screenwriters fail to make his
character so convincingly self-absorbed or so stupid that he can't
see through Betty right away. And things threaten to unravel toward
the end, as the filmmakers try too hard to tie up some loose ends,
and some of the actors _ including Zellweger, who's otherwise at
her best _ lose confidence in their performances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, although ``Nurse Betty'' isn't as provocative as LaBute's
earlier movies, it's a big leap for him as a director; maybe having
somebody else write it, or putting it on the road, forced him to
make a movie that doesn't look as stage-influenced as ``Company''
and ``Friends'' did. He usually jacks up his actors, but here he
gets Rock to tone down his shrillness while also eliciting an
acidly funny performance from him. LaBute also puts to good use his
talent for eclectic casting, sprinkling in amusing turns from Aaron
Eckhart as Betty's husband, Crispin Glover as the driven reporter,
and Pruitt Taylor Vince as the cantankerous sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of ``Nurse Betty,'' though, is Richards' and
Flamberg's nutty screenplay, which makes up for its road-comedy
derivativeness with a smattering of ``The Wizard of Oz'' references
and an increasing rarity: humor that relies on dialogue, situations
and performances. Along the way, ``Nurse Betty'' makes some points
about celebrity, romance, regret and independence. If you're sick
of sophomoric comedy, it could be a cure for what ails you.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Nurse Betty''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Neil LaBute
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Renee Zellweger, Morgan Freeman, Chris Rock
</P>
<P>
   Length: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, sexual situations and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
