<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-IRANIAN-DEPORT-HNS &LR;      09-07 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRANIAN-DEPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT BARS OUSTER OF IRANIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal appeals court has barred the
deportation of an Iranian MAN who worked on a clandestine
translation of Salman Rushdie's ``The Satanic Verses,'' then fled
Iran before his colleague was tortured to death.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. immigration authorities decided Abbas Zahedi was lying
about the reasons he left Iran and ordered him deported. But the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco said Wednesday
that Zahedi's evidence, including an order that he report to court
to face prosecution, showed he was eligible for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is highly likely that if Zahedi were to return to Iran, he
at the very least would be imprisoned, and at the worst tortured or
executed for distribution of `The Satanic Verses,''' Judge Betty
Fletcher said in the 3-0 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Zahedi, who entered the United States from Canada in 1996, now
lives in Los Angeles with his wife, a U.S. citizen, and two of his
children who also managed to leave Iran, said his lawyer, Michele
Carney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Satanic Verses,'' Rushdie's 1988 novel, includes dream
sequences in which the prophet Muhammad praises pre-Islamic
goddesses and in which prostitutes take the names of his wives.
Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini issued a fatwa, or death
decree, shortly before his own death in 1989, condemning Rushdie
and anyone involved in publishing or translating the book.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's current government disavowed the fatwa in 1998, but some
hard-line clerics have insisted it is still binding, and a private
organization continues to offer a reward for Rushdie's death.
Translators and distributors of the book have been murdered in
several countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zahedi, who ran an auto parts store and an electronics store in
Tehran, testified at his asylum hearing that he became interested
in the book in the mid-1990s and wondered what the government was
trying to hide. He said he located a copy in Turkey in early 1996,
took it home and asked a friend named Moshen, a political
dissident, to translate it into the Iranian language of Farsi so he
could distribute it.
</P>
<P>
   Zahedi said he made copies of each chapter Moshen had translated
and had given them to 20 to 25 people before security forces
arrested Moshen in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that he fled the country the same day authorities
tried to serve a summons ordering him to appear in court. His
daughter was later interrogated and his mother was threatened. He
later learned Moshen had died under torture.
</P>
<P>
   An immigration judge said she did not believe Zahedi's testimony
because he was vague or inconsistent about such details as when he
learned of Moshen's arrest and who got copies of the books. She
also said documents presented by Zahedi about his impending
prosecution were unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court said inconsistencies in his testimony
appeared to be due to problems with a translator and were not
crucial to Zahedi's story. The immigration judge failed to say why
she rejected Zahedi's documents, which are consistent with State
Department reports about Iran, the court said.
</P>
</TEXT>
