<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-AIRLINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE AIRLINE GETS APPROVAL TO SELL SMALL STAKE TO TAIWANESE
AIRLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China Eastern Airlines said Thursday that it
had received preliminary approval to sell a 25 percent stake in its
tiny cargo subsidiary to China Airlines of Taiwan, a first step in
a what would be a landmark in cross-strait cooperation if Taiwan's
government allowed the deal to go through.
</P>
<P>
   While Taiwanese companies have invested heavily in joint
ventures with state-owned enterprises on the mainland and even
invested directly in some state-owned companies, there has yet been
no Taiwanese investment in China's air carriers, which were only
recently opened to limited foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Though Taiwanese companies have invested as much as $40 billion
in mainland ventures, Taiwan's government has resisted the trend,
fearing that the island's economy could grow too dependent on the
mainland and in turn weaken Taipei's ability to govern the island
free from Beijing's interference. Taiwan maintains a ban on direct
trade and transportation links with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   China Airlines has acknowledged that is in talks to buy a stake
in Shanghai-based China Cargo Airlines, a unit of the mainland's
state-owned China Eastern Airlines, but said it has not yet asked
Taipei for approval of any deal.
</P>
<P>
   China Airlines would need approval from the Ministry of
Transportation and Communications and Economic Ministry's
Investment Commission to proceed with such an investment.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Civil Aviation Administration of China, the
mainland's aviation regulator, has approved the share sale, any
deal would require still higher approvals from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed deal, China Airlines would buy a 25 percent
stake in the cargo carrier, diluting China Eastern's stake to 65
percent and that of another Chinese state company, China Ocean
Shipping (Group) Co., to 10 percent. China Cargo, which is the
nation's only all-cargo carrier but has just three planes, is now
70 percent owned by China Eastern and 30 percent owned by Cosco.
</P>
<P>
   Both China Eastern and China Airlines have said that financial
details and the timing of the stake sale have yet to be decided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
