u l BC-FASH-GOLD-HNS &LR;      09-07 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASH-GOLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNERS GO FOR THE GLOW 
WITH PHOTOS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
HOUSTON _ The '80s glitz and glamour are on the way back.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fall and winter 2000, designers have turned up the wattage,
illuminating clothing from outerwear to underwear with the glow of
metallic fabrics, laces and leathers.
</P>
<P>
   This is one area of high fashion that includes crossover from
street fashion, especially the new rage of glam rock, as the trend
is tagged in Women's Wear Daily _ or pimp fashion, as the kids know
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold is big,'' said Evelyn Gorman, owner of the hip Mix
boutique. ``I think this whole gold thing can certainly be seen in
Madonna's new video.''
</P>
<P>
   In that video, for her latest single, ``Music,'' Madonna rides
in the back of a limousine, decked out as a parody of a rap star
with gold top, gold pants, gold cowboy hat and heaps of gold
necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry counter delights
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest fashion change in metallics will come in
jewelry, a category that has turned from silver to gold almost
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Gold hoop earrings, especially the larger ones reminiscent of
the original ``Charlie's Angels,'' have flown out of Cotton Club
stores, owner Lisa Spain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so many years everything was silver. Now everything is
turning gold,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the gold is real or faux is not important, said Roz
Pactor, vice president/fashion director for Foley's department
stores. ``It's the look of gold that is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman believes the trend to gold jewelry will be accepted very
rapidly and grow, ``but no one will throw their silver jewelry
away. And if they're smart, they will combine the two.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold as fabric
</P>
<P>
   At the Cotton Club, Spain is carrying gold leather and pleather,
gold snake and crocodile and even gold denim, the latter with a
painted-over finish.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Reich, owner of Wink boutique, is another who is replacing
the bohemian look of embellished jeans with gold-sheen jeans of
denim with Lurex threads.
</P>
<P>
   Metallic-finished garments need not be heavy in look or feel.
Some silk charmeuse this fall has a metallic look, even though it
is extremely soft, said El Matha Wilder, owner of Etui boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Metallic accessories include little evening bags, belts and
other leathers with a slight metallic bronzing.
</P>
<P>
   At Mix, an everyday shoulder bag by Mayle is of gold leather
with gold leather fringe.
</P>
<P>
   With the return of blouses, adding a metallic-finish belt can
take a silk blouse and wool skirt from the office into evening.
</P>
<P>
   Investing in gold
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, this is merely the beginning of a retro trend that
will hang on for at least several years, so an investment in a gold
leather jacket, skirt or pants might not be as radical as it seems.
Gold, like python, may even achieve the status of a basic for a
season or two.
</P>
<P>
   Metallic-finished clothing does double duty, dressing up all the
basics in your closet for both day and evening. A black turtleneck
and skirt, for example, goes to luncheons, dinner or the theater
with the addition of a metallic leather jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Metallics also complement the rich spice colors of fall and
winter. For those who still believe that metallics should appear
only after dark, this season's evening clothes are heavily into
gold, silver, bronze and copper.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's, for example, is stocking up on gold metallic separates,
said Christina Kerford, public relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   At Esther Wolf, owner Fred McCann said gold brocade is one of
the choices he believes will be popular for evening. As with an
all-over beaded garment, his customers might once have thought of
gold brocade as an evening-only, but now he believes both beaded
and gold brocade separates will show up at fall and winter
luncheons.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing,'' McCann said, ``these clothes have longevity.
They can go to different places, out to lunch and also to dinner.
Today's women don't necessarily buy for a special occasion, and
most want something in which they will be noticed. And, yes, they
want to look more feminine, younger and even sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
