<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-IVOR-AUSTRALIAN-STARS     09-07 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-AUSTRALIAN-STARS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S LATEST CRAZE: DOWN-UNDER WONDERS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Heath Ledger in
a scene from ``The Patriot'' and Adam Garcia in a scene from
``Bootmen.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 c.2000 Ivor Davis 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    While the world may be watching the Australian Olympics this
fall, thousands of miles away millions of moviegoers have something
else to watch: a slew of good-looking Australian hunks who are
currently captivating Hollywood.
 &HT;    Heath Ledger stared at us from the cover of August's Vanity
Fair, blonde and gorgeous in a tight, white tank top, his bare
midriff revealing well-toned abs, his thumbs dug deep into his
manly blue jeans.
 &HT;    Hugh Jackman took his stand on the cover of a July issue of
Entertainment Weekly _ tall, dark and handsome, his arm clasping
the bare shoulder of his dazzling blonde co-star, Rebecca
Romijn-Stamos.
 &HT;    Ledger and Jackman may not exactly be household names or icons
in the league of Tom Cruise, Brad Pitt or Leonardo DiCaprio. But
they embody the new breed of cover boy, the attractive vanguard of
the new invasion of lads from Oz _ Australian faces that have
Hollywood in a lather.
 &HT;    Even before playing Mel Gibson's son in ``The Patriot,'' many
had declared Ledger to be the heir apparent to Gibson's crown as
Hollywood's favorite Aussie. As for Jackman, he may have started
the year as an unknown, but after playing bad boy Wolverine, a
hirsute hero with razor-sharp metal claws, in this summer's smash
hit ``X-Men,'' he's catapulted onto sexiest-man lists across
America.
 &HT;    Not long ago it was the chaps from the United Kingdom who
commanded the covers, intense, moody actors such as Ralph Fiennes,
Daniel Day-Lewis and Ewan McGregor. But suddenly their Aussie mates
are making them look tired and bland _ yesterday's news.
 &HT;    The Australians are the new flavor of the month, in short. We
haven't even mentioned the most successful of them all, the
Australian sex symbol du jour _ although he was actually born in
New Zealand _ ``Gladiator's'' Russell Crowe, who has recently
finished shooting ``Proof of Life'' opposite Meg Ryan, with whom
he's also enjoying a much-publicized off-screen romance as well.
 &HT;    Of course this is not Hollywood's first love affair with the
cream of the Down Under acting crop: Errol Flynn, a legendary
swashbuckler on and off the screen, was a giant in Filmtown during
the 1930s and 1940s. Peter Finch won an Oscar for his role in
``Network'' (1976), but had already held the attention of many of
the town's most beautiful women long before. Rod Taylor was also no
slouch in the romance department, and more recently Paul Hogan
became the darling of Hollywood during the ``Crocodile Dundee''
1980s.
 &HT;    Gibson ranks as the biggest of them all today, commanding $25
million a picture. He may demand a footnote, of course: He was
actually born in the United States, but as a boy was taken to
Australia by his father, who worried that his sons would be drafted
and sent to Vietnam.
 &HT;    Gibson, star of the ultraviolent ``Mad Max'' futuristic capers,
made a fortune playing a flamboyant cop in the escapist ``Lethal
Weapon'' series, but now is taken seriously as a triple threat _ as
an actor whose name alone can sell a picture and as a
producer/director who won an Oscar for ``Braveheart'' (1995. He'll
be back again in December's ``What Women Want,'' playing a ladies'
man who suddenly becomes able to read women's minds.
 &HT;    When it comes to the heavyweight acting department, this
generation's Peter Finch is Geoffrey Rush, best known for his
Oscar-winning turn as pianist David Helfgott in ``Shine'' (1996).
Rush, who will next be seen in ``Quills'' in December, has added
thespian voltage to such Hollywood films as ``Elizabeth'' (1998)
and ``Shakespeare in Love'' (1998), and is never less than
wonderful.
 &HT;    Then there's Guy Pearce, who with his countryman Crowe scored
big in ``L.A. Confidential'' (1997), and is due to open next year
in the independent film ``Memento.''
 &HT;    And they keep coming. Adam Garcia of Sydney, on screen in the
current ``Coyote Ugly,'' seems a combination of Tyrone Power and a
young Mel Gibson. His star vehicle is the Australian-made picture
``Bootmen,'' based on the international stage hit ``Tap Dogs'' and
opening on Oct. 6, in which he plays a steelworker who turns his
back on the assembly line to become a dashing tap dancer in work
boots.
 &HT;    Word is that the smoldering-eyed Garcia will become a fully
fledged sex symbol once American audiences check him out in
``Bootmen.'' For an early peek, however, they can spot the
26-year-old dancing a featured role in the opening ceremonies of
the Sydney Olympics.
 &HT;    Of course, while Australian men may be taking Hollywood by
storm, their female counterparts are no slouches, either. Cate
Blanchett, Nicole Kidman, Judy Davis, Rachel Griffiths and Toni
Collette have all shown admirable combinations of beauty and
talent.
 &HT;    But right now it's the rugged male wonders from Down Under who
are garnering most of the attention, bidding fair to eclipse Brad
Pitt, Leonardo DiCaprio and other home-grown hunks in the
heartthrob stakes.
 &HT;    The serious money is on the 21-year-old Ledger, who became an
overnight sensation _ at least to those who'd missed him in ''10
Things I Hate About You'' (1999) _ as a zealous, hot-tempered young
soldier in the blood-soaked Revolutionary War epic ``The Patriot.''
 &HT;    ``I really like the kid, he's far more mature than his age,'' an
admiring Mel Gibson says. ``He was measured and deliberate about
his work. I remember what I was like when I was his age _ God, I
don't think I was capable of some of the more subtle things he did
in our film. I look at guys like Heath and say, `Why wasn't I so
smart when I was that young?'''
 &HT;    Ledger, a native of Perth, has been deluged with offers since
finishing ``The Patriot.'' He recently completed a medieval romp in
``The Knight's Tale,'' and is already off in Morocco, shooting the
latest version of ``The Four Feathers.''
 &HT;    ``Once every 50 years a guy like that comes along,'' says Brian
Helgeland, director of ``The Knight's Tale.'' ``When Heath smiles,
it's Errol Flynn.''
 &HT;    At 31, Australian Jackman is the mature counterpart to Ledger's
bright young kid.
 &HT;    ``He's talented, bright, sweet, charming and gracious,''
Jackman's ``X-Men'' co-star Romijn-Stamos says. ``And he's sexy as
hell.''
 &HT;    Jackman was playing Curly in the British National Theater
revival of the musical ``Oklahoma'' _ he previously played Norma
Desmond's boy toy Joe Gillis in Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``Sunset
Boulevard'' _ when ``X-Men'' came up. The road to Professor
Xavier's School wasn't smooth: The role originally went to Scotsman
Dougray Scott, only to fall to also-ran Jackman when Scott had to
withdraw after delays in his previous film, ``Mission: Impossible
2,'' but once in, Jackman made the plum role of ``mutant sex
symbol'' his own.
 &HT;    Next up for the Melbourne native is a more traditional
leading-man role, as Ashley Judd's romantic interest in the comedy
``Animal Husbandry.''
 &HT;    Like Jackman, Garcia first scored big on the stage, winning
London's prestigious Olivier Award as best actor in a musical for
his role as Tony Manero in the London stage version of ``Saturday
Night Fever,'' pulling off the seemingly impossible task of
measuring up to John Travolta's career-making turn in the 1977
movie. Next month he'll begin shooting on Penny Marshall's ``Riding
in Cars with Boys,'' cast _ believe it or not _ as Drew Barrymore's
20-year-old son.
 &HT;    So why is Hollywood going head over heels for the men from the
antipodes? One studio chief, who requested anonymity because he's
maneuvering to sign as many of the new lads as he can, says it all
boils down to salt-of-the-earth, uncomplicated manliness.
 &HT;    ``The guys are natural, blunt and so down-to-earth,'' he says.
``There's no pretense about them, and that's the appeal. They are
all real men, in a world where real men are in short supply.''
 &HT;     c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
