<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALWORLD-PEDRO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PEDRO'S LESSONS: `Real World' Roommate's Death
Inspires  Cartoonist's Book  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)  
 By SAM WHITING  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Judd Winick lived with Pedro Zamora for just six
months, but he's been living with his story for the six years
since.
</P>
<P>
   Cast in MTV's ``The Real World, San Francisco,'' in 1994, Winick
was just looking for free rent and a chance to be on television and
get his cartoons noticed. He didn't know how real ``The Real
World'' would turn out to be until a roommate on the show, Zamora,
developed AIDS symptoms. Three months after the show wrapped,
Winick was at Zamora's side when he died, just hours after the last
episode was shown.
</P>
<P>
   It made the national news, and made a mission for Winick, who is
now an AIDS educator and fund-raiser for the National Pedro Zamora
Project _ a job that peaks this month with the publication of
``Pedro and Me: Friendship, Loss, and What I Learned'' (Henry Holt;
$15).
</P>
<P>
   Written and illustrated in comic-book style by Winick, the
180-page paperback is a quick read and is aimed at people in their
early teens to early 20s. Winick creates the story's tension by
contrasting his safe childhood mowing lawns on Long Island with
that of Zamora, who came from Cuba in the Mariel boatlift and faced
bigger dangers once he got to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The book parallels the lives of Winick and Zamora, who were 24
and 22 when they met at ``The Real World'' house at the foot of the
Lombard curlicue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to write about the everyman's perspective, which
was me,'' Winick says. ``Regular guy getting to know someone who
has AIDS and what that is like.''
</P>
<P>
   That segment of the book, titled ``Six Months Below the
Crookedest Street in the World,'' is just one chapter out of five,
but it's the one that got the book published.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its ninth season, ``The Real World'' was the pioneer for
all the reality shows that are now copycatted to the level of
annoyance. The concept is to take seven strangers in their early
20s and throw them together in a house paid for and decorated by
the producers.
</P>
<P>
   Each season the cast is culled from 30,000 applicants, each of
whom thinks the show will launch him or her into TV or film
stardom. It hasn't yet, and at best cast members get an appearance
or two before going back from whence they came.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 63 people who have been cast, Winick, 30, has probably
lived off ``The Real World'' the longest. As a direct result of the
show he has found a cause, a career, a first book, a fiancee and a
home in San Francisco. He lives in a flat in the Upper Haight with
fellow ``Real World'' veteran Pam Ling, a magenta-haired physician
who works in various city clinics that treat AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs will be the first ``The Real World'' wedding between cast
members who met on move-in day, and would make good footage for an
MTV special report. Maybe even a commemorative album to go with
``The Real World: The Ultimate Insider's Guide,'' published in 1997
by MTV Books. ``Pedro and Me'' is packaged in the same glossy red
binding, and is the same size, so they fit together on a bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   Or on either arm of an easy chair for reference during the
constantly regurgitated ``Real World'' marathons. Next month, the
first four seasons of ``The Real World'' go into national
syndication, locally on KNTV (Channel 11) in San Jose. Watching it
while reading Winick's book should enhance the power of Zamora's
performance in hiding his sickness from the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to prove that you can live with it,'' says Winick,
who put in a good performance of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the book he admits that his biggest fear on the show was
being boring, and he went to great lengths to avoid that.
</P>
<P>
   One episode he is a fresh-faced mama's boy who'd never been to
San Francisco. The next he's an ultra-hip artiste in a goatee and
vest at the televised wedding of Zamora and Sean Sasser.
</P>
<P>
   Winick raised a toast, as if they would live happily ever after.
But he knew the truth after nursing Zamora through night sweats and
bouts with shingles and pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lied to the cameras,'' says Winick, who uses the book to
puncture that lie, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Writing and illustrating the book took two years. Some days were
tougher than others, as when he drew Zamora's face covered with
shingles, or with the skin pulled back from his cheekbones in AIDS'
death grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Pedro, I think it's the last time I'll be telling
the story,'' he says. He's about had enough of ``The Real World''
too, and an omen arrived this summer when the house was badly
damaged by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Winick went by afterward, ``trying to put some closure on it,''
and got what he came for. The fire, as it turned out, had started
in the room he shared with Zamora, right next to his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put any kind of bizarre irony you want on it,'' he says.
``I've moved on from it, and now the house itself has moved on from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
