<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ATWOOD-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-07 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWOOD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BLIND ASSASSIN': THREE STORIES WOVEN INTO A SUSPENSEFUL
DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end of review) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Storytelling has long been a favorite hobby of many of Margaret
Atwood's characters. For some, it's a way to distance themselves
from painful memories while mythologizing mundane triumphs and
travails; for others, it's a means of discovering their own
identities, a way of connecting the dots in their lives, of turning
random points of light into something resembling a starry
constellation.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood's absorbing new novel, ``The Blind Assassin,'' features a
story within a story within a story _ a science-fiction yarn within
a hard-boiled tale of adultery within a larger narrative about
familial love and dissolution. The novel is largely unencumbered by
the feminist ideology that weighed down such earlier Atwood novels
as ``The Edible Woman'' and ``The Handmaid's Tale,'' and for the
most part it is also shorn of those books' satiric social vision.
In fact, of all the author's books to date, ``The Blind Assassin''
is most purely a work of entertainment _ an expertly rendered
Daphne du Maurieresque tale that showcases Atwood's narrative
powers and her ardent love of the Gothic.
</P>
<P>
   To build suspense and create a narrative hall of mirrors, Atwood
deftly cuts back and forth among three plot lines. The first
chronicles the day-to-day life of an elderly woman named Iris Chase
as she tries to come to terms with the many losses she has suffered
over the years, including the suicide of her sister, the suicide of
her husband and the apparently accidental death of her daughter.
The second plot line concerns the events that led to Iris' marriage
in the 1930s to a wealthy industrialist named Richard Griffen and
her estrangement from her sister Laura. The third, which apparently
consists of chapters from a potboiler Laura wrote, recounts the
furtive affair of a well-to-do woman and her ne'er-do-well
boyfriend, who meet in grungy, borrowed apartments and seedy hotels
under the constant threat of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Writing with uncommon authority and ease, Atwood conjures up the
lives of the Canadian gentry in a small town just north of the U.S.
border. She introduces us to the eccentric Chase family (they built
a fortune in the button business) and she traces the reverberating
effects that World War I would have on its members, in particular
Iris and Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Laura is three years younger than Iris, and from the start she
is a strange, watchful child, high-strung, inquisitive and
single-mindedly literal. When told that God is everywhere she frets
about his exact location, wondering if He were in the sun, in the
moon, in the kitchen. ``She developed the ability,'' Iris recalls,
``to subtract herself in the blink of an eye _ one minute she'd be
focused on you, the next she'd be elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   After their mother dies in childbirth, the sisters must cope
with their father's sullen withdrawal into an alcoholic stupor and
the arrival of a sadistic tutor who has been entrusted with their
education. Though Iris resents having to be responsible for her
dreamy, wayward sister, it soon becomes clear that the two girls
are alter egos of sorts _ doppelgaengers and soul mates, like so
many of the paired heroines in Atwood's novels, from Cordelia and
Elaine in ``Cat's Eye'' to Zenia and her adversaries in ``The
Robber Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   As teen-agers, Laura and Iris find common cause in befriending a
charismatic young man named Alex Thomas, who is visiting their
small town. When Alex falls under police suspicion for being a
Communist and a labor agitator, the sisters hide him in the family
attic. Both soon become enamored of this sardonic and slightly
sinister man _ a development that will have serious repercussions
not only for them but also for successive generations of their
family.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what ensues in ``The Blind Assassin'' is
unapologetically melodramatic: In addition to several suicides in
the Chase family, there are intimations of child abuse and
intra-family adultery, not to mention loads of scheming,
manipulation and intrigue. Atwood grounds these events in carefully
observed social and emotional detail, even as she sends up her more
sensationalistic impulses in the extracts from Laura's novelette
(also called ``The Blind Assassin''), which features passages from
a pulp fiction story written by its hero. That story, set on a
planet far, far away, depicts a bloody, class-riven society that
sacrifices its young to propitiate ancient gods, and a chilling
assassination plot involving a blind killer.
</P>
<P>
   Compelling in its lurid way as ``The Blind Assassin'' the
novelette may be, it pales in comparison to the virtuosic
storytelling on display in ``The Blind Assassin'' the novel.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BLIND ASSASSIN'
</P>
<P>
   By Margaret Atwood
</P>
<P>
   521 pages. Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
