<SLUG> BC-FILM-WATCHER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEANU REEVES AS A SERIAL KILLER? IT'S A MOST UNEXCELLENT
ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: D  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the climactic moment of Hollywood's latest serial-killer
thriller, ``The Watcher,'' Keanu Reeves cocks his head audaciously
toward the camera and says in his inimitable, faux-serious style,
``How about that for deja vu?'' It's a perfect mini-review.
</P>
<P>
   This thing is a compendium of scenes from earlier entries in the
overworked genre. It's grindingly mediocre, in a way that probably
would have sent it straight to video were Reeves' name not on the
marquee.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves himself appears to be on board as a favor to the
first-time director, Joe Charbanic, who shot most of the videos of
the star's rock band, Dogstar. Reeves looks bloated and unhealthy
and walks through the part as if he's still worn-out from making
``The Matrix'' sequels.
</P>
<P>
   His character is an habitual psychotic killer of young, lonely
women: a fiend who tortures them over a long period of time while
uttering pithy one-liners, then strangles them with piano-wire.
He's also a bit of a police buff who knows procedures and never
leaves incriminating evidence.
</P>
<P>
   And he's particularly fixated on the young FBI agent (James
Spader) who's been on his trail for the past three years: a man so
stressed by it all that he's become a pill-popping basket case who
has to make visits to a lady shrink (Marisa Tomei).
</P>
<P>
   Do you think we're working to a big scene in which the killer
kidnaps this beautiful and sympathetic heroine and, as bait for a
one-on-one with the hero, has her bound and gagged in his secret
lair _ which, naturally, is aglow with maybe a hundred, carefully
arranged candles?
</P>
<P>
   We have to see endless scenes of other young women being
stalked, beaten, abused, tortured, strangled and set on fire, and
of the hero frantically racing to get to them. How about that for
deja vu?
</P>
<P>
   Director Charbanic goes for an arty, MTV-style with
exploding-cuts and much grainy video footage injected for
flashbacks. It's lively but fails to disguise the fact that his
script is a dud and his career in videos has taught him little
about the art of narrative storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   THE WATCHER
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Joe Charbanic
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS: David Elliot, Clay Ayers
</P>
<P>
   CAST: James Spader, Keanu Reeves, Marisa Tomei
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R, for violence
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
