<HEADER>
A5274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      09-07 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Caan And the Kids
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the bad guys in the picture he's like a good guy,''
said James Caan, talking about his role as a veteran troubleshooter
for a mob lawyer in ``The Way of the Gun.'' ``If there's anybody
who has any kind of moral backbone, it's him, because he's caught
in a dilemma between serving his boss and taking care of his boss'
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   The good bad guy has been a Caan specialty since he played Sonny
Corleone in Francis Ford Coppola's 1972 classic ``The Godfather.''
As an actor he has always been willing to blend his immense, almost
boyish charm with a sense of contained violence, suggesting
something darker behind the bright smile and accommodating patter.
``You see that this guy has been through the wars,'' said Caan.
``And yet he's just really calm and cool. He's done all the
footwork.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Way of the Gun,'' which opens nationally Friday, Caan's
character goes up against two punks, played by Ryan Phillippe and
Benicio Del Toro, who kidnap a young woman (Juliette Lewis) without
realizing that she is serving as a surrogate mother for the mob
lawyer (Scott Wilson) and his wife (Kristin Lehman). The action
builds to a shootout that recalls the films of Sam Peckinpah, for
whom Caan made ``The Killer Elite.'' ``Sam definitely would have
done this picture,'' said Caan, speaking by phone from his home in
Utah. ``It's his kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer-director of ``The Way of the Gun'' is Christopher
McQuarrie, whose screenplay for ``The Usual Suspects'' won an Oscar
in 1996. ``I'm a big fan of his writing,'' Caan said. ``There was a
great 14-page scene, which is basically why I did the movie,
between this character of mine and Benicio. A very long scene in a
diner, where he's talking about how people today want to be
criminals but don't want to commit a crime, they just like the
title.''
</P>
<P>
   With the vagaries of filmmaking, the scene did not make the
final cut. But Caan, who will be back next month in ``The Yards,''
carries no grudges. ``I really enjoyed working with the kids. I
call them all kids now, because I'm ancient. God, I just turned 60.
I can't even think of that. But I'm still playing basketball with
the 25-year-olds, so I just refuse to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   LaButian Undertones
</P>
<P>
   It's been four years since ``In the Company of Men,'' but Neil
LaBute still hasn't learned to play his role as America's Most
Controversial Filmmaker. He's still the shambling Midwestern nice
guy he has always been, even after further heating up the war
between the sexes with ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' and ``Bash,''
his collection of one-act plays that was recently shown on cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   Recently LaBute took two days off from preproduction in London
on his latest project, an adaptation of A.S. Byatt's novel
``Possession'' that will star Gwyneth Paltrow, to visit New York on
behalf of ``Nurse Betty,'' a romantic comedy with some dark
LaButian undertones that opens nationally Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For LaBute, who has always written his own films, two
adaptations in a row seem like a dramatic departure. ``What it is
more than anything is opportunity. Of those first two films, one
was generated strictly out of my backyard, and then the other one
came off of people seeing that. `Nurse Betty' came directly out of
working on `Friends and Neighbors,' because Steve Golin produced
that, and he had the script and said, `What do you think of this?'
I read it, and I didn't have the time to intellectualize career
choices. I told him I liked it and that I couldn't imagine me doing
it, and that's probably a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the theater I directed other people's material, so why
shouldn't I direct someone else's script? It was very freeing in
many respects not to be so close to something. I could immediately
be an audience member, and say, `This is good; this needs some
work,' and not feel that pang of, `I just gave birth to this, be
kind.'''
</P>
<P>
   Written by John Richards and James Flamberg, ``Nurse Betty'' is
the story of a small-town waitress, played by Renee Zellweger, who
witnesses the brutal murder of her drug-dealing husband and,
traumatized, retreats into a fantasy in which she believes herself
engaged to her favorite soap-opera character, a handsome, heroic
doctor played by Greg Kinnear. She sets out for Los Angeles,
pursued by the two hitmen she had observed, played by Morgan
Freeman and Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent every weekend and every day before we shot working on
the dialogue,'' said LaBute. ``But character-wise, plot-wise, it's
very much what the guys wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the only thing that sprang from me as a complete idea
was Morgan and Chris going to the Grand Canyon at night,'' said
LaBute, referring to the scene in which Freeman's character reveals
that he has fallen in love with the woman he's chasing. ``The idea
was that she would imagine something transformative happening to
her at the Grand Canyon and then have these guys physically be
there and have something similar happen to them. I'm a person who
loves to continually thread things back into the hole. That's just
the way my mind works.''
</P>
<P>
   Depardieu Fils
</P>
<P>
   In France the actor Gerard Depardieu seems well on his way to
establishing an acting dynasty, like the Carradines or the
Bridgeses in the United States. Both Depardieu's daughter, Julie,
and his son, Guillaume, have embarked on successful acting careers,
and they both appeared with their father in the hugely successful
French mini-series ``The Count of Monte Cristo.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillaume, 29, is also the star of Leos Carax's grand, dreamlike
adaptation of Herman Melville's 1852 novel ``Pierre, or the
Ambiguities.'' Titled ``Pola X,'' it opens in New York Friday, two
years after its release in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierre was a difficult character to play,'' Guillaume
Depardieu said over coffee in a West Side hotel, ``He's someone who
descends further and further, marginalizing himself, looking for
the truth, and finally he destroys himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The character is a spoiled son of the haute bourgeoisie who
drops out of his comfortable life to become a professional starving
poet, while he carries on a passionate affair with a strange young
woman from the East (Katerina Golubeva), who may or may not be his
half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   Does Pierre become a great artist as a result of encountering
all of this brutal reality? ``Perhaps not,'' said Depardieu. But
why then has he gone through it? ``That, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, Guillaume is delicate-looking, a slender
young man with a self-described ``face of an angel,'' something he
resents. ``I would like to play villains,'' he said. ``But no one
will cast me with this mug.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
