   SCI-MAYA-PALACE (Undated) _ In a remote jungle of Guatemala,
among the remains of a little-known ancient city with a name
meaning ``place of serpents,'' archaeologists have uncovered one of
the largest and most splendid palaces of Maya kings ever
discovered. Its more than 170 high-ceiling rooms were built around
11 courtyards and spread over an area greater than two football
fields. By John Noble Wilford.
