<HEADLINE>
`THE WAY OF THE GUN' SHOOTS ITSELF IN THE FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The multi-Oscar-winning 1995 thriller ``The Usual Suspects'' was
the summation of a distinct brand of hip, funny, ultra-violent,
endlessly meandering, neo-noir crime drama that was, in many ways,
the signature American independent film of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the Gun,'' the first directorial effort of
``Suspects'' screenwriter (and Seattle resident) Christopher
McQuarrie, is another edgy, hard-boiled crime drama that is very
much in this Tarantino-esque tradition, with all of the adjectives
above applying.
</P>
<P>
   But, somehow, the material seems agonizingly stale and the movie
just doesn't have the same kind of power to carry us away. It may
be that the casting spark or the directing touch is missing _ or,
more likely, it may just be that the time for this particular kind
of movie has come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is the story of two wandering, low-life-scum
criminals _ Parker (Ryan Phillippe) and Longbaugh (Benicio Del
Toro) _ who kidnap a young woman in an advanced state of pregnancy
(Juliette Lewis) who is acting as a surrogate mother for a wealthy
Southwestern couple.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly turns out, however, that the father-to-be (Scott
Wilson) is a mob boss of sorts, and the kidnap situation is soon
further complicated by the conflicting interests of what seems an
army of characters around him _ advisers, bodyguards and family
members.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, McQuarrie has a gift for hard-edged dialogue and
colorful characters. As in ``The Usual Suspects,'' he's also not a
bit afraid to construct a swift-moving, complex narrative that
constantly challenges his audience to keep up and often borders on
the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after a promising opening, this film loses our interest
fast. Without a dominating character or performance or visual style
to keep us focused, it soon becomes a tedious bloodbath populated
by uniformly unsympathetic (and unbelievable) characters.
</P>
<P>
   Also like ``Suspects,'' this movie works to a ``big-surprise''
ending in terms of one of its character relationships. But,
intentionally or unintentionally, the revelation is telegraphed
early in the movie, and anyone who hasn't figured it out before the
climax doesn't belong at an R-rated movie in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   THE WAY OF THE GUN
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Christopher McQuarrie
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Ryan Phillippe, Benicio Del Toro, Juliette Lewis, James
Caan, Scott Wilson
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 119 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R, for violence
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BETTY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-07 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NURSE BETTY': FRAGILE: HANDLE WITH DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' takes the most hackneyed dramatic ploy of soap
opera, a case of amnesia, and spins it into an irresistibly heady
mixture of sadness and hilarity. At its giddiest peaks the movie,
directed by Neil LaBute, produces that shivery feeling when your
heart melts but at the same moment you want to burst out laughing.
This whimsical rose-colored fairy tale with tragic undercurrents
suggests a contemporary ``Wizard of Oz'' for grown-ups. It is
easily the finest American comedy since David Russell's ``Flirting
With Disaster,'' another road movie that never ran out of
poignantly funny surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The event that whirls an innocent apple-cheeked waitress and
nursing-school dropout from the American heartland into a state of
enchanted forgetfulness is more traumatic than any tornado. When
Betty Sizemore (Renee Zellweger) accidentally witnesses the grisly
murder of her husband, Del (Aaron Eckhart), by two hit men in the
living room of her home, she instantly erases it from her mind.
Deciding to leave her life in Fair Oaks, Kan., behind, she flees
the past in a 1997 Buick LeSabre borrowed from her dead husband's
used-car dealership.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow brick road she travels, without a scarecrow, tin man
or cowardly lion for company, is the great American highway leading
west to our own Emerald City, the Hollywood dream factory. That
factory has nourished Betty's fondest daydreams of living happily
ever after with a handsome modern-day prince. And the goal of this
not-terribly-bright, open-hearted young woman who dreams of getting
her nursing degree because she wants to ``help people'' is nothing
less than good old-fashioned romantic salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant and terrifying murder sequence at the beginning of
the film establishes its deliberately bipolar mood and lays out its
vision of modern America as a land of colliding, television-fed
dreams of romance and upward mobility. But instead of glibly
condemning the trash-television culture that has seeped into the
deepest crevices of American life, ``Nurse Betty'' accepts that
culture, recognizing both the necessity and the foolishness of
manufactured dreams from which there is no longer any practical
escape. Without them, it implies, there is no hope at all.
</P>
<P>
   As that murder sequence begins, Betty's no-good husband is being
terrorized by two thugs while his wife in the next room is riveted
to a videotape of that afternoon's episode of her favorite soap
opera, ``A Reason to Love.'' Betty is so enamored of its young
hero, Dr. David Ravell (Greg Kinnear), a gifted surgeon in a Los
Angeles hospital, that her colleagues at the diner where she works
have recently given her a birthday present of a life-size cutout of
this dreamboat. As Ravell rebuffs the advances of the soap opera's
designated vixen, who turns right around and accuses him of sexual
assault, Betty's heart is in her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Just then she is distracted by strange noises coming from the
living room and nervously peeks through a crack in the door in time
to witness the two killers (Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock) shoot
her husband dead. As the movie cuts between the television show and
the murder, the soap opera seems strangely more real than the
fantastic, inexplicable violence erupting only a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging stunned but strangely cheerful, in a state diagnosed as
``post-traumatic stress'' (the word amnesia is never used), Betty
embraces the fantasy that David Ravell is the sweetheart she jilted
six years ago to marry Del. The time has come, she decides, for her
to go to Los Angeles for their reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In a story that takes many wonderful twists and turns toward a
bittersweet ending that strikes a perfect balance between tragedy
and a dizzy kind of bliss, fantasy eventually overtakes reality.
And for a brief, magical time Betty's traumatic delusion that
Ravell and his fictional world actually exist becomes real. Or half
real. (Among other things, ``Nurse Betty'' is about the power of
fiercely held fantasies to involve others.)
</P>
<P>
   As Betty arrives in Los Angeles, lands herself a job at a
hospital through astounding luck, then meets and charms the actor
who plays Ravell, the movie cuts back to the killers tracking her
down along with the stash of drugs she is unwittingly carrying in
the trunk of the car. Charlie ( Freeman), the older of the two, may
be a professional hit man, but he is also a remarkably erudite and
soft-spoken introvert who describes himself with bitter
self-contempt as ``a garbage man of the human condition.''
Freeman's mixture of animal cunning and resigned sad-eyed wisdom
finds the essence of Charlie's tortured soul.
</P>
<P>
   His accomplice and protege, Wesley ( Rock), is an angry,
hotheaded sociopath whose first reaction in tense situations is to
explode. He is the one major character in the movie without a
dream. Applying the same hysterical, blazing-eyed sarcasm to Wesley
that he brings to his stand-up comedy, Rock conveys a glowering,
chaotic nihilism.
</P>
<P>
   As the pair, helped by some snapshots of Betty, follow clues to
her whereabouts, Charlie nurtures his own sudsy fantasy of Betty as
a holy innocent, the romantic embodiment of everything he is not.
And in one of the film's riskiest moments, he falls into a dreamy
slow dance with the imaginary Betty at the edge of the Grand Canyon
in the middle of the night. (The soundtrack injects just the right
note of gentle mockery by playing Della Reese's overblown 1959 hit
``Don't You Know?'' in the background.)
</P>
<P>
   But the film's most enchanted sequence is the sustained romantic
pas de deux of Betty and her dream lover, who, despite massive
evidence to the contrary, she insists on believing is really Ravell
and not a vain young actor named George McCord. Flattered and
intrigued, George, in turn, nurtures his own fantasy that Betty,
far from being mentally disturbed, is really an ambitious,
dedicated Method actor who is so determined to be cast in the show
that she never goes out of character. As the tension escalates over
when and how the parallel bubble will finally burst, the screenplay
by John Richards (who wrote the story) and James Flamberg attains a
sublime comic delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   None of it would work if Zellweger's Betty weren't such a
perfectly blended mixture of sweetness, innocence and stubborn
determination tinged with a streak of petulance. Utterly likable
but never saccharine, flighty but not dumb, Betty is a contemporary
grown-up Dorothy Gale skipping down the yellow brick highway to
meet the wonderful wizard.
</P>
<P>
   What more appropriate guise for his millennial incarnation than
as a vain, self-centered actor who dreams of directing the show in
which he's a star? Kinnear, in his richest screen performance,
locates both the slippery charm and the nasty snub-nosed narcissism
of his Ken Doll character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' is as much a triumph for LaBute as it is for its
cast, because its success is so dependent on its sustaining a
precarious balance between humor and pathos, realism and fantasy.
Compared with his vicious examinations of yuppie sexual cruelty,
``In the Co. of Men'' and ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' which
went for the jugular, ``Nurse Betty'' is almost warm and fuzzy. Yet
the director gives the film enough of a misanthropic edge to hold
sentimentality at bay.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of violent flashes in the murder sequence are so
(literally) hair-raising that you wonder for a second if the movie
can recover. But it does. And the emotional payoff is enormous.
``Nurse Betty'' says it's OK to wallow in suds, that dreaming is
only human. And without dreams to guide us in the land of a
thousand and one beckoning television wizards, we would never leave
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Nurse Betty'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has scenes of extreme
violence and some profanity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NURSE BETTY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Neil LaBute; written by John Richards and James
Flamberg, based on a story by Richards; director of photography,
Jean Yves Escoffier; edited by Joel Plotch and Steven Weisberg;
music by Rolfe Kent; production designer, Charles Breen; produced
by Gail Mutrux and Steve Golin; released by USA Films. Running
time: 112 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Morgan Freeman (Charlie), Renee Zellweger (Betty), Chris
Rock (Wesley), Greg Kinnear (Dr. David Ravell), Aaron Eckhart
(Del), Tia Texada (Rosa), Crispin Glover (Roy), Pruitt Taylor Vince
(Ballard) and Allison Janney (Lyla). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
