<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WENT TO CONEY ISLAND .. ': LOST YOUTH, LOST FRIEND, LOST CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Went to Coney Island on a Mission From God ... Back by 5'' is,
thank goodness, not as gawkily clever as its title, but it is an
odd mixture of boyish high spirits and grown-up melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   It begins like an art-house episode of ``The Wonder Years,''
with an adult male voice-over recalling bygone days of youth as
snippets from pop songs mark the passing of the decades. In
bleached-out flashbacks to the old neighborhood, three friends _
Daniel, Stan and Richie _ progress from ``It's a Beautiful
Morning'' to ``Hot Child in the City'' to ``I'll Stop the World,''
as their clothes and haircuts change accordingly. The best of these
moments is a cringe-inducingly authentic garage-band cover of Adam
and the Ants' unforgettable (though not for lack of trying) hit
``Ant Music.''
</P>
<P>
   As the movie follows Daniel (Jon Cryer) and Stan (Rick Stear) on
their search for their lost chum, who they believe is homeless and
mentally ill, the flashbacks sketch their own slide from youthful
optimism to the misery and frustration of their 30s. Daniel works
at a jewelry store that's a small step up from a pawnshop, and
Stan, who limps as a result of a botched operation in childhood,
drinks, gambles and taxes the patience of his longtime girlfriend,
Gabby (Ione Skye). As the two friends wander through the desolate
winter landscape of Coney Island, we learn about the sexual
confusion and family tragedy that led to Richie's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Went to Coney Island'' is structured more like a play than a
movie. Its scenes _ Daniel and Stan's encounters with the eccentric
loners who populate the Boardwalk in the off-season _ seem talky
and stagy, and its action moves backward, toward a reckoning with
the past. Its cinematic interest is largely a result of Adam
Beckman's photography, with its artful overexposures and spare
wide-angle compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Cryer collaborated on the screenplay with the director, Richard
Schenkman. A few years back, the two of them made a quirky,
unassuming comedy called ``The Pompatus of Love,'' about the
romantic struggles of a group of young men in New York. This new
film is more ambitious, but its better moments are distinguished by
the scruffy egghead humor that made their earlier effort a pleasant
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The banter between Cryer and Stear flows easily and believably
and is often quite funny. But the script seems hamstrung between
smart-alecky self-consciousness _ a Skee-Ball parlor operator who
talks like a snide graduate student; a waitress who hands over a
menu with the comment ``It's as thick as `The Fountainhead''' _ and
heart-wrenching naturalism.
</P>
<P>
   Richie's story is too weighted with pain to comport with the
student-film surrealism that surrounds it, and Rafael Baez, as the
adult Richie, seems to belong in a different movie. A subplot
involving Stan's gambling debts and a thuggish deli owner seems
pasted in out of a dozen other ``Mean Streets'' knockoffs. But the
filmmakers' earnestness and intelligence ultimately work at cross
purposes, and ``Went to Coney Island'' never quite comes to
dramatic or comic life.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: This film is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes sexual references and
profanity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WENT TO CONEY ISLAND ON A MISSION FROM GOD ... BE BACK BY 5'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Schenkman; written and produced by Jon Cryer
and Schenkman; director of photography, Adam Beckman; edited by
Richard LaBrie; music by Midge Ure; production designer, Bill
Stabile; released by Phaedra Cinema. Running time: 94 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jon Cryer (Daniel), Rick Stear (Stan), Rafael Baez
(Richie), Ione Skye (Gabby), Frank Whaley (Skee-Ball Weasel), Peter
Gerety (Maurice) and Akili Prince (Julie).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
