<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TODAY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-07 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TODAY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT ALL STARTS TODAY' TOUGH LESSONS FOR A DEDICATED EDUCATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It All Starts Today'' follows a year in the life of Daniel
(Philippe Torreton), the director of a preschool in a depressed
former coal-mining region of France. The son of a miner, Daniel
fills his journals with meditations on nature and history that
provide, as they are read on the soundtrack, a kind of poetic
counterpoint to, and relief from, the misery and deprivation that
dominate Daniel's professional life, and much of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed with unassuming realism, beautiful to look at even as it
refuses any suggestion of stylishness, this latest film from
Bertrand Tavernier is a passionate and relentless look at how
chronic unemployment _ with the usual side effects of alcoholism,
domestic abuse and pervasive despair _ menace the lives of
children. In spirit it's a bit like some of Jonathan Kozol's recent
books, which celebrate the resilience and innate goodness of
children even as they decry the way society has failed to protect
them.
</P>
<P>
   Tavernier takes us into the squalid housing projects in which
many of Daniel's students live and records the bureaucratic
boilerplate that, in the mouths of well-meaning but self-protective
functionaries and politicians, reduces young lives to jargon and
statistics. But he also illuminates the warmth and safety of the
school, watching Daniel and his colleagues sing songs, tell stories
and supervise art projects and playground games.
</P>
<P>
   In scene after scene ``It All Starts Today'' uncovers the
contrast between the world the teachers try to create for their
pupils and the world in which these children must grow up. In the
course of an ordinary day Daniel must deal with a boy who refuses
to talk, parents who can't afford minuscule contributions to the
school's activity fund, and a drunken mother who collapses on the
playground and then, overcome with shame, runs away, abandoning
both her 5-year-old daughter and her infant son to Daniel's care.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel addresses each crisis the only way he can, by a series of
improvised stopgap measures that seem woefully inadequate to
address the social catastrophe unfolding around him. He is
constantly at loggerheads with the local child welfare office, at
one point barring its staff members from the school. The elected
officials are no better, alternately complaining of budget
constraints and boasting about their accomplishments and
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The movie charts both Daniel's frustrations _ his humiliation by
an inspector who finds fault with his pedagogical techniques, the
trashing of his school by teen-age vandals _ and his minor
victories. He manages to harangue the authorities into providing
legally mandated medical examinations for the children and rescues
one young boy from an abusive home. He also tries to live a normal,
decent life: To find time for his girlfriend, Valeria (Maria
Pitaressi), to bond with her suspicious 12-year-old son, Remi
(Lambert Marchal), and to help his aging parents.
</P>
<P>
   Tavernier _ who is still perhaps best known in this country for
``Round Midnight,'' his portrait of the sentimental bond between an
African-American jazz musician and an adoring French fan _ has
ventured into the kind of politically explicit drama often
associated with British filmmakers like Ken Loach and Mike Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   But on close inspection ``It All Starts Today'' can't be
dismissed _ or celebrated _ as a programmatically leftist film. If
it takes up traditionally leftist concerns _ the persistence of
social inequality, the plight of the poor _ it also implicitly
takes account of the European left's defeat. In this film the
French working class, once the proud standard-bearer of radical
tradition, survives as a demoralized underclass stripped of its
historical identity and its vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor who responds to Daniel's plea for more money with a
cynical tirade is a member of the Communist Party. Early on, a
politician stands in front of a mural of 19th-century strikers and
announces that the region must move beyond its claim to fame as the
setting of Zola's ``Germinal'' and stake its future on tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel's class consciousness at times seems downright quaint _
he's the only member of the school staff who belongs to the union _
and the parents of his charges hardly regard him as one of them.
When he complains to his own mother about her coffee, her tart
reply is, ``That's miner's coffee, not teacher's coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the politics of ``It all Starts Today'' might even
be called conservative, since it laments the breakdown of families
and communities and the corrosive effects of popular culture on
social cohesion and national morale. ``We're in Texas,'' says Samia
(Nadia Kaci), the pediatric nurse who becomes Daniel's chief ally,
marveling at a classroom full of children named Wendy, Kevin,
Clayton and Jimmy. ``No, we're on `The Young and the Restless,'''
Daniel replies.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of confecting an ideological soap opera or a
feel-good do-gooder melodrama, Tavernier has pulled off an
emotionally rich and remarkably restrained piece of storytelling.
Torreton, a member of the Comedie Francaise, is a marvelous actor,
compact and reserved, with a gentleness and sorrowful intelligence
that prevent his performance from becoming an exercise in
saintliness. His tough, unshowy goodness is one of the film's
consolations, though not its point.
</P>
<P>
   Tavernier strikes very few false notes. (One comes when Daniel
and his girlfriend, after an especially depressing visit to the
home of one of his students, make love in his car, as though to
remind us that this is, after all, a French film.) ``It All Starts
Today'' strikes a difficult and necessary moral balance, refusing
to succumb to hopelessness but also refusing to rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IT ALL STARTS TODAY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bertrand Tavernier; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Dominique Sampiero, Tiffany Tavernier and Bertrand
Tavernier; director of photography, Alain Choquart; edited by
Sophie Brunet and Sophie Mandonnet; music by Louis Sclavis;
produced by Alain Sarde and Frederic Bourboulon; released by
Independent Artists Group. Running time: 117 minutes. This film is
not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Philippe Torreton (Daniel), Maria Pitarresi (Valeria),
Nadia Kaci (Samia), Veronique Ataly ( Lienard), Nathalie Becue
(Cathy), Emmanuelle Bercot (Tievaux), Francoise Bette ( Delacourt)
Lambert Marchal (Remi).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
