<SLUG> BC-WATCHER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WATCHER': STALKED BY A SERIAL KILLER, HE PURSUES TALK
THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night last spring, fighting insomnia in a North Carolina
hotel room, I spent a few hours flipping back and forth between
``The Matrix'' and ``Devil's Advocate,'' which were showing on
competing cable stations. After a while they began to run together
into a single montage of Keanu Reeves dressed in black clothes,
furrowing his smooth brow in bewilderment as he grappled with one
metaphysical conundrum after another.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Watcher,'' a damp, morose bit of gristle directed by
Joe Charbanic, Reeves, once again dressed in black, looks jowly and
fatigued, perhaps because this time out the role of metaphysical
conundrum has been assigned to him. Playing a sicko whose metier is
the strangulation of young women, Reeves conveys his villainy by
enunciating every syllable with exquisite care and inflecting his
utterances with the fastidious sarcasm of a surfer James Mason.
Unfortunately, bewilderment comes more naturally to him than
diabolical intelligence, and his line readings, aiming for a
mixture of suavity and creepiness, just sound silly.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not even Sir Anthony Hopkins himself could do much
with the lines Reeves is required to deliver: ``We need each other,
we define each other, we're yin and yang,'' he declares at a
climactic moment, adapting Tom Cruise's tearful speech from ``Jerry
Maguire'' to a darker purpose. The role of yin _ an FBI agent named
Jack Campbell _ is played by James Spader. As any moviegoer knows,
homicidal maniacs and the law enforcement officers who pursue them
are joined together by deep and mysterious psychic bonds. ``The
Watcher'' pushes this convention to an extreme by making Jack's
torment the killer's explicit motive.
</P>
<P>
   And Jack is plenty tormented. This we know because he staggers
home to a messy apartment, stares into his empty refrigerator and
takes a lot of pills. He also sees a therapist (Marisa Tomei), who
keeps a copy of Psychology Today on her office coffee table.
``Maybe you're just afraid,'' she speculates, after Jack haltingly
tries to explain how being stalked by a murderous lunatic makes him
feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's talk about that,'' the good doctor suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not. Like ``The Cell,'' the season's other serial-killer
picture, ``The Watcher'' is the feature-directing debut of a
filmmaker whose previous work consists mostly of music videos and
it is similarly crammed with MTV-style visual effects. The
murderer's point of view is registered in grainy hand-held video,
and Jack's inner turmoil reaches us through smeary, cut-up
flashbacks. The soundtrack swells with spooky techno effects, angel
choirs and echoey bits of remembered dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   All of this moody posturing is evidence of the film's aspiration
to be taken as what its production notes solemnly call _ daring to
invoke the name of Hitchcock _ a ``psychological thriller.'' But
it's about as thrilling as it is psychologically insightful. There
are some big explosions and a straight-to-video car chase, at the
end of which Jack and the entire Chicago police force seem to give
up, as though the film had kept rolling after the director shouted
``Cut!'' This is one of those movies in which the forces of law and
order are at once omnipotent _ commanding extraordinary resources
of technology and manpower, all of which can be summoned by
snapping open a cell phone _ and utterly incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as easy as you think,'' Jack muses about his job, but
watching him let the killer slip through his fingers again and
again, you wonder how hard it could be.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the movie Jack crashes through his apartment, grabs a
hypodermic needle and jabs it into a big purple bruise just below
his bellybutton. ``I'm self-injecting migraine medication,'' he
tells his worried shrink. By the end of ``The Watcher'' you'll need
your own prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Watcher'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes several brutal
killings and a lot of tense FBI-agent-under-pressure swearing.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATCHER'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Joe Charbanic; written by David Elliot and Clay
Ayers, based on a story by Darcy Meyers and David Elliot; director
of photography, Michael Chapman; edited by Richard Nord; music by
Marco Baltrami; production designers, Brian Eatwell and Maria Caso;
produced by Christopher Eberts, Elliot Lewitt, Jeff Rice and Nile
Niami; released by Universal Pictures. Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: James Spader (Campbell), Marisa Tomei (Polly), Keanu
Reeves (Griffin), Ernie Hudson (Ibby) and Chris Ellis (Hollis).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
