u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-07 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS ANTIQUE DEALERS ARE TOASTING THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, France)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention, jet setters: get to Paris next week (if you can find
a hotel room). The opening of the French social season begins on
Tuesday, when more than 90,000 international collectors _ from the
the Prince of Lichtenstein and the Princess of Kent to Baroness
Philippine de Rothschild and Quentin Tarantino _ are expected to
congregate for a two-week extravaganza of openings, parties and
special events connected to the 20th edition of the Biennale
International des Antiquaires, the Super Bowl of antiques fairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As antiques dealers, we are experiencing a fantastic era,''
said Claude Blaizot, president of the National Antiques Dealers
Syndicate in France. ``We are witnessing Paris' comeback on the big
chessboard, which the international art market represents.''
</P>
<P>
   The fair opens on Wednesday evening with a black-tie benefit for
the Foundation for Paris Hospitals. Bernadette Chirac, wife of
President Jacques Chirac of France, will welcome 800 guests to the
dinner, which has been sold out since Aug. 1. Isabelle Adjani,
Catherine Deneuve, Hubert Guerrand-Hermes and Dennis and Terry
Stanfill are among the R.S.V.Ps.
</P>
<P>
   Attending charity events is not considered particularly chic in
Paris, but people clamor to attend this one because they are given
the first crack at the Biennale. After dinner there is a private
viewing and shopping is allowed. The people viewing is pretty good,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities resume on Thursday night with a
by-invitation-only opening cocktail party given under the patronage
of . Some 4,000 people attend, dressed to kill in their fall 2000
``robes de cocktail.''
</P>
<P>
   The Biennale setting is far more elaborate than any of the
American antiques fairs. The 116 dealers create stylish stands with
wallpaper, damask or paneling on the walls, and marble or oak
floors, whether they are selling Chinese pots or midcentury modern
pieces. (The cost of the decor comes in addition to the booth
rental fee, which is several hundred dollars a square meter.)
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 10 percent of the dealers spend more than $250,000 on
decoration,'' said Herve Aaron, a Paris dealer who is a longtime
participant. ``We've been working on our booth since July in a
warehouse near Roissy, where we did a mock-up of the space, which
will be hexagonal with an 18th-century parquet de Versailles floor
and Regence wood paneling on loan from a famous chateau.''
</P>
<P>
   He is trying to create a dazzling background for, among other
things, a rare Louis XV white lacquered commode signed by
Antoine-Mathieu Criard. ``He was one of the three most famous
cabinetmakers for lacquer during the reign of Louis XV,'' Aaron
said. ``And white is very unusual for lacquer in France.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Grange, a top Paris decorator, is designing the booth
for Pierre Passebon, owner of Galerie de Passage. Francois-Joseph
Graf has created settings for the pre-Colombian pots of Galerie
Mermoz, the 18th-century furniture and objets d'art offered by the
dealer Jacques Perrin, and the 20th-century specialist Robert
Vallois.
</P>
<P>
   The dealers are making a huge effort this year, partly as a
pre-emptive move to win clients' loyalties before Christie's and
Sotheby's start conducting sales in Paris. After years of dallying,
the French Parliament this year finally passed legislation to allow
foreign auction houses to operate in France, and the two houses are
expected to be in business by the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The art and antiques business is good in Paris. The French
auction houses reported that turnover increased 19.5 percent in the
first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more competition there is, the more clients there will
be,'' Blaizot said.
</P>
<P>
   The Biennale is held every other September in the Carrousel du
Louvre, an underground space next to the Pyramid at the Louvre
Museum. This year's collection opens to the public next Friday and
runs through Oct. 1. To maintain its attraction to regular
attendees _ who include Leon Black, Henry Kravis and Ronald Lauder
_ the French dealers' organization has added 23 new dealers and
organized a special Paris trip for American museum curators and
their trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Houston Museum of Fine Arts,
the Los Angeles County Museum of Art and the Fine Arts Museums of
San Francisco are among those sending curators. They will be given
a private luncheon in the French Senate in the Luxembourg Palace, a
superb Louis XIII building; a dinner at Malmaison, the house
Napoleon built for Josephine; a tour of the 18th-century hotel
particulier of and Michel David-Weill; and cocktails with Felix
Rohatyn, U &UR; . &LR; S &UR; . &LR;  ambassador to France, at the American Embassy,
which is in a former Rothschild house.
</P>
<P>
   The Biennale is all about discoveries, and rediscoveries. This
year Modernism buffs may want to see Galerie Olivier Watelet, with
furniture by Jacques Quinet displayed in a booth with gold-leaf
walls and bronze floor panels. Even experts in midcentury modern
French furniture cannot often identify the work of this
20th-century Parisian interior architect and designer, though he is
the subject of a new biography.
</P>
<P>
   Quinet (1918-1992) was the son of a taxi fleet owner in Caen,
France, a city in Normandy that was leveled in World War II.
Trained by the Jesuits, he seems to have been a precocious student.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war he went to Paris to work for an architect,
Antoine Charpentier. At 21 he set up an office of his own. When
World War II broke out, he was drafted into the French air force,
then released when the government capitulated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 he reopened his office in Paris. He spent his days
getting to know the skilled cabinetmakers and artisans in the
Faubourg St. Antoine, near the place de la Bastille. Despite
shortages of fine materials, be began to design bureaus in amaranth
wood, tables with bronze legs and chairs in white oak covered in
petit-point upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Claude, admired as a hostess, invited clients and
friends to soirees in their home. Soon Quinet was working for the
directors of companies like Larousse, Evian, Air France, Dassault
and Krema, a maker of sweets. He designed the interiors of planes,
trains and ocean liners. He did several pieces of furniture for the
residence of General Eisenhower at Marnes-la-Coquette.
</P>
<P>
   His furniture style was stripped down but elegantly
neoclassical, with bronze ornament and supports. He also used
lacquer regularly. He is ripe for discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The other great surprise in the Biennale is the booth of
Vallois, who is showing a room full of museum-quality Eileen Gray
furniture. It is a collection that he sold in 1971 and has
reassembled for the fair.
</P>
<P>
   There are 15 pieces in the collection: furniture, rugs,
lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the surprise?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is for sale.'' Vallois said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
