<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GUN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-07 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WAY OF THE GUN': A NOIR STORY OF GUNS ALWAYS AT THE READY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For someone who doesn't have much truck with the schematic
approach of those blustering screenwriting teachers who've become
legends in Los Angeles, Christopher McQuarrie writes scripts that
are meticulously worked out and lovingly hand-polished; they glow
with pride.
</P>
<P>
   He won an Academy Award for best screenplay for the stylish
sleight-of-hand of ``The Usual Suspects,'' perhaps the most
arbitrarily plotted crime film ever made; you bet that Kevin Spacey
is Keyser Soze only because he is having so much fun with the
performance. In McQuarrie's new script, ``The Way of the Gun,'' the
action is compartmentalized and the twists come in on a schedule,
something the New York subway system should aspire to. Each note is
struck to hang in the air for several beats. The movie may feel
redundant, but it is stylish and intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the Gun'' feels like a more violent and grim
version of a Coen brothers film; it could be Quentin Tarantino's
``Raising Arizona.'' Its lead characters are small-time criminals
who tend to speak in ambitious and hilariously orotund turns of
phrase, and it's a film noir built around the feelings adults have
about babies, climaxing with a childbirth and a lengthy gunfight
and standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The, um, heroes go by the names Parker (Ryan Phillippe) and
Longbaugh (Benicio Del Toro) _ the real-life surnames of Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid _ and they've ended up pursuing a
criminal career of ultraviolence (the way of the gun) because what
else could they do? When they visit a sperm bank in an attempt to
contribute to the future and make a few bucks at the same time,
their responses to the standard questions are so garishly outre
that it's surprising they don't set off fire alarms. Their options?
``Petty crime and minimum wage,'' Parker says.
</P>
<P>
   While at the sperm bank, Parker and Longbaugh hatch a plan to
kidnap Robin (Juliette Lewis), a young woman doing surrogate mother
duty for a wealthy couple, Hale Chidduck (Scott Wilson) and his
much younger wife, Francesca (Kristin Lehmann). The forlorn Robin
is about to give birth. ``I don't mind if it stays in there
forever,'' she drawls.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Longbaugh flee with Robin, pursued by a pair of
beautifully dressed security guards (Taye Diggs and Nicky Katt) and
Joe Sarno (James Caan), Chidduck's special envoy and a fellow given
to language as grandiloquent as his prey. ``I can promise you a day
of reckoning that you will not live long enough to never forget,''
he snarls, and he uses the word adjudicator so much you suspect he
gets a royalty every time he says it.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie's dialogue _ lines like ``Karma's only justice without
satisfaction'' _ is self-conscious and baroque: Rococo puffs. The
characters' quirks seem to be carved in stone and placed in
platinum settings. Despite the deliberateness of his conception _
at one point, during a shootout in a car chase, the characters push
their sedans forward with their feet _ McQuarrie, making his
directorial debut, does have an authentic, if somewhat offbeat,
taste for inflating the nihilism of noir. He has a strong feeling
for the genre, and the gunfights _ which are louder than the Dolby
trailers _ are staged with an undeniable morality, and the
characters imbued with a sense of inevitability. They know what's
going to happen to them, and proceed anyway, as if finding honor
lying under the wheels of an oncoming Fate.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie understands how to direct actors, and he gets what he
wants from them. Lewis, a mom-to-be with a face that suggest an
infant's, is an interesting choice for the role. Robin represents
hope and the future and is most unwilling to change, but it's hard
to tell if she is meant to be determined or childishly stubborn.
Lewis makes her both, with a rapt delivery that is surprisingly
loud; her dreamy foghorn of a voice has a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe is the real surprise. His angel-boy face is hidden
under wiry scrubs of facial hair, and he uses a runty voice as if
he had studied the Dustin Hoffman or Al Pacino of the 1970s. (He
sounds particularly like the Pacino of ``Serpico,'' speaking as if
he burned the roof of his mouth.) Del Toro, whose turn in
``Suspects'' was so freaky it was like watching a live action Dick
Tracy villain, is more understated here. He is a mesmerized soldier
of fortune, simultaneously out of it and wary. He's even dressed
like a revisionist western hero.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``The Usual Suspects,'' ``The Way of the Gun'' is not
intentionally vague. (In the earlier film, there may have been a
tiny clue; during the invasion of the ship in the movie's climax,
Spacey's Verbal Kint recognizes the language of the sailors, which
was also Soze's native tongue.) And this picture remains true to
its own internal logic. All the pieces fit snugly together.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie is smart about moviemaking in ways that show his
respect for the genre, and he doesn't force the material on
audiences. He knows that part of the enjoyment they will get is in
knowing they've seen movies like this before that weren't so direct
and intense. He uses a few pop songs, but the score is mostly
simple, with scenes highlighted by oboe and timpani.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting that entertaining pointedness, one of the best scenes
takes place when Parker hands his hostage a sandwich and she tears
into it. ``It's from a gas station,'' he says patronizingly. ``It's
still good,'' she responds, dealing with what's right in front of
her. That's the strength of ``The Way of the Gun.'' It's a song
you've heard before, but each chord is hit with extraordinary
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Way of the Gun'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes numerous gun
battles, a long torture scene and a bloody childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WAY OF THE GUN'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Christopher McQuarrie; director of
photography, Dick Pope; edited by Stephen Semel; music by Joe
Kraemer; production designer, Maia Javan; produced by Kenneth
Kokin; released by Artisan Entertainment. Running time: 120
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ryan Phillippe (Parker), Benicio Del Toro (Longbaugh),
Juliette Lewis (Robin), Taye Diggs (Jeffers), Nicky Katt (Obecks),
Scott Wilson (Hale Chidduck), James Caan (Joe Sarno) and Kristin
Lehmann (Francesca Chidduck). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
