u e BC-CLOUDS-FILM-REVIEW-NY     09-07 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOUDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLOUDS': SPELLING OUT BIG IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shot in limpid black and white, studded with symbols and
contemplative vistas of sea and sky, ``Clouds'' is a small movie
with large pretensions. It concerns a young physicist named Robert
St. John, who, to work out a radical new cosmology (``It may
subvert basic models'' he tells a colleague), takes a leave from
his teaching post and sets himself up in a quiet town on the
Northern California coast. There Robert (Michael Patrick Gaffney)
meets a painstakingly selected cast of eccentrics: a chatty, pious
landlady, a profane and cynical artist and a mysterious woman who
claims to have known the scientist in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Robert's past is revisited through dreamlike flashbacks,
sometimes accompanied by voiceover. These moments suggest that in
his quest for knowledge of the world, Robert has neglected the
experience of it. He's so obsessed with meaning that he's lost any
sense of who he is. Luckily, it all comes right in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are not the zero and the world the same?'' Robert asks us.
``The suffering and the love? Reality and I are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, no. ``Clouds,'' written and directed by Don Thompson,
is so eager to impel our contemplation of its big ideas (whatever
they may be) that it neglects to give its story much in the way of
interest or credibility. The dialogue consists of long
philosophical stretches of argument interrupted by sudden bursts of
inexplicable emotions. Thompson creates an illusion of enigmatic
seriousness by ploddingly spelling out themes _ art versus science,
truth versus illusion _ then smudging them with bits of contrived
surreal humor and artsy incongruity.
</P>
<P>
   All this is in the service of something so lofty it can't be
explained. Robert deflects inquiries into his cosmological project,
warning his artist friend that it's too mystical for him to grasp
and telling his colleague that his theory may be ``beyond
coherence, even mathematical coherence.'' This may be the movie's
truest assessment of itself, unless that comes a bit later, when a
character who seems to be Robert's ex-girlfriend tells him he's
``about the most intelligent dumb person I've ever met.''
``Clouds'' is about the dumbest intelligent movie I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CLOUDS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Don Thompson; director of photography,
Gary Lindsay; edited by Lindsay; music by Nawang Khechog;
production designer, Gordon Halloran; produced by Thompson and
Lindsay; released by In Pictures, NextPix and Pacific Grove
Productions. Running time: 95 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Michael Patrick Gaffney (Robert St. John), Jennifer Jordan
Day (Beatrice), Richard Barrows (Tab), Rob Nilsson (Frank) and
Patricia Ann Rubens ( Martin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SOLAS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-07 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOLAS': A MOTHER'S SELFLESS LOVE AND DIGNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the good things that can come with age, if we're lucky,
is a growing capacity to feel and to give our unconditional love.
Benito Zambrano's quietly moving film ``Solas'' explores this gift
with a depth and subtlety that remind you, indirectly, of why the
movies are so infatuated with violence. It's so much easier to
portray anger on the screen (it's a short-cut to feeling) than to
evoke the kind of watchful, selfless devotion that radiates from
the film's central character who is identified only as Mother
(Maria Galiana). Because it's the kind of feeling that affects
things only gradually, it is almost impossible to portray on the
screen without some sentimental amplification.
</P>
<P>
   But Galiana's still, intensely concentrated portrait of a woman
who changes people's lives through small acts of kindness shows
that great screen acting doesn't necessarily rely on
psychologically revealing dialogue. This sober Spanish film, so
pointedly antithetical in spirit to the zany, sexually charged
antics of Pedro Almodovar and his imitators, has few frills. No
heavenly choirs or misty-eyed close-ups are trotted out to push our
emotional buttons. Except for Antonio Meliveo's discreetly
melancholy score, the movie is almost as plain as its central
character.
</P>
<P>
   A stout weather-beaten woman of around 70 who moves slowly and
rarely cracks a smile, Galiana projects the earthy solidity of
someone who despite coming from humble circumstances and being
illiterate is at home in the world because she doesn't expect much
of life. In one of her few remarks about herself, she gravely
professes to have a clear conscience. Those words, along with her
simple acts of thoughtfulness suggest that she is devoutly
religious, although she keeps most of her feelings to herself.
</P>
<P>
   She has made a rare journey into the city (the movie was filmed
in Seville) to be with her husband (Paco De Osca) while he recovers
from surgery. Hour after hour, she sits patiently at his bedside
lost in her thoughts while crocheting. When he addresses her, he
turns out to be a bitter old tyrant who baits his wife by claiming
to detect the smell of a man on her. Having endured his cruelty for
years, she seems almost impervious. But eventually we learn that he
used to be an abusive drunk who gambled, womanized and physically
abused his wife and his daughter, Maria (Ana Fernandez), with whom
she is staying.
</P>
<P>
   Wiry, nervous, and consumed with rage, Maria is definitely her
father's child, although she hates him for refusing to pay for any
higher education. Furious that she has to earn a living doing
menial labor (she works for a cleaning service), she loathes her
bosses, looks down on her co-workers, drinks heavily and fantasizes
about winning the lottery. When a friendly neighborhood bartender
who fancies her isn't looking, she blithely steals his liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Maria's nearly hopeless life reaches a crossroads when she
becomes pregnant by her boyfriend Juan (Juan Fernandez), a burly
truck driver who uses her for sex and refuses to accompany her to
an abortion clinic when she pleads with him to go.
</P>
<P>
   While visiting, her mother takes in the whole sad picture of
Maria's life without comment and bit by bit she begins to brighten
it up. She shops for food. She cooks, places flowers in Maria's
bleak apartment and installs a chair she has found on the street.
By chance, she also meets her daughter's downstairs neighbor
(Carlos Alvarez-Novoa), a lonely old man whose only friend is his
loyal dog, Achilles. The two strike up a courtly friendship, and
she gives him simple, healthful meals.
</P>
<P>
   One day when she is going home from the hospital, Achilles
signals that there's trouble. She enters the apartment to find him
stricken with diarrhea, and despite his protestations insists on
cleaning him up.
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship has only lasted a matter of days before it's
time for her to leave and take her husband home. But before
departing, she introduces Maria to the neighbor. The introduction
proves profoundly life-changing for the two neighbors, who had
never spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solas,'' which opens Friday at the Lincoln Plaza in Manhattan,
eventually makes a bold narrative leap that is not entirely
convincing. Its final scenes are a bit two patly sentimental for
comfort. But Galiana's quietly monumental performance is one for
the ages. She is every mother who ever watched a grown-up child
stumble through life, swallowed her sadness and disapproval and did
what she could to help.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SOLAS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Benito Zambrano; in Spanish, with
English subtitles; director of photography, Tote Trenas; edited by
Fernando Pardo; music by Antonio Meliveo; production designer, Lala
Obrero; produced by Antonio P. Perez; released by Samuel Goldwyn
Films-Fireworks Pictures. Running time: 98 minutes. This film is
not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Maria Galiana (Mother), Ana Fernandez (Maria), Paco De
Osca (Father), Carlos Alvarez-Novoa (Neighbor), Juan Fernandez
(Juan) and Antonio Dechent (Doctor).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PROP-209-HNS &LR;      09-07 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROP-209-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT APPEARS READY TO STRIKE DOWN MINORITY OUTREACH PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Civil rights groups who hoped to preserve the
remnants of affirmative action after Proposition 209 outlawed it
appear to be headed for disappointment from the California Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court on Wednesday took up the major unresolved legal
question about the 1996 ballot measure: whether a government agency
can target minorities and women in recruitment, without promising
favorable treatment in jobs or contracts. The court showed little
doubt about the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plain language of (209) specifically prohibits that kind
of program,'' Justice Joyce Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Kathryn Mickle Werdegar, like Kennard a generally
moderate voice on the court, cited a report by the state's
nonpartisan legislative analyst saying contractors ``would no
longer need to show good-faith efforts'' to use minority and female
subcontractors under Proposition 209.
</P>
<P>
   The case could affect scores of city and county government
programs that make special efforts to inform, recruit and train
minorities and women. A ruling is due within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 209 prohibited preferences based on race or sex in
state and local contracting, employment and education. The measure
was upheld by federal courts, but the state's high court must
determine its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Before the court was a challenge to a San Jose ordinance, which
requires contractors, on city construction contracts over $50,000,
to contact at least four subcontractors owned by minorities or
women, negotiate with them and accept their bids or state
legitimate reasons for rejection. It does not give minority-owned
companies a built-in edge in bidding or set quotas or goals for
their hiring.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, which has an ordinance like the one in San Jose,
filed arguments on behalf of Oakland, Berkeley, Albany, Hayward,
the counties of Alameda and Marin, and other local governments
seeking to preserve ``outreach'' to underrepresented groups.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Browne, the lawyer for a white male contractor who
challenged San Jose's ordinance, said it was designed ``to provide
a competitive advantage to minority- and women-owned businesses''
by requiring contractors to make special efforts to recruit them.
</P>
<P>
   A local government is free to reach out to all potential
applicants as long as its measures are strictly neutral by race and
sex, said Browne, of the Pacific Legal Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Ronald George appeared to agree, suggesting that
outreach remains legal if it ``goes out to all groups.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers representing San Jose said the ordinance was
justified by a study it conducted in 1990 that found minorities
were underrepresented in city contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to equalize the position of minorities and women in
the bidding process,'' said San Jose's lawyer, former City Attorney
Joan Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that ``contracting opportunities exist largely
for white males,'' said state Attorney General Bill Lockyer, who
argued in support of the ordinance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EUROPE-GASPRICES-0908     09-07 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-GASPRICES-0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH 'PETROL' PRICES IN EUROPE FUELING RISING TEMPERS, TENSIONS
 &HT;    With chart attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ If rising prices at the pump are annoying Americans,
they're infuriating Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Already paying the highest prices in Europe, Britons awoke
Thursday to headlines suggesting new taxes could drive the cost of
gasoline to the psychologically important level of 5 pounds _ or
about US$7.60 _ a gallon. Already, the price of unleaded gasoline
is the equivalent of about US$5.25 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Howard, a dentist who lives in suburban Surrey,
wondered Thursday afternoon if the increases would ever stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs me 50 quid (more than US$75) to fill my car,'' he
said, pulling the nozzle from his Toyota sport utility vehicle at a
service station. ``I can clean a few more teeth to come up with the
money, but one has to worry about how average working people can
keep up with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices in Europe already are far above those in the United
States, mostly because of higher taxes. In Britain, for example,
more than two-thirds of the price per gallon is tax. The British
government has been slowly raising taxes on fuels, and retailers,
also pressed by rising crude oil prices, say they have no choice
but to push prices up even higher.
</P>
<P>
   In France, gasoline is cheaper, but the tension is higher. Over
the past few weeks, rising fuel prices have spawned a series of
demonstrations focused largely on blocking travel between Britain
and France.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, French truckers stepped up their five-day blockade
of the nation's fuel depots. They prevented deliveries to thousands
of service stations, which were quickly running out of gas.
Thousands of English tourists are trapped in France, unable to find
enough fuel for their journeys home.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, taxi drivers want to be allowed to raise fares to
offset fuel costs, and expressed their concerns with ``Operation
Escargot'' by driving at a snail's pace through the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In Calais Thursday, farmers atop tractors blocked access roads
to the Channel Tunnel, which connects France and Britain. Farmers
scuffled briefly with riot police when the security forces barred
protesters from closing the freight entrance to the tunnel, which
allows travel under the English Channel. A dozen tractors later cut
off the access road to the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Later, frustrated British vacationers caught in a three-hour
traffic jam caused by the farmers retaliated with their own
roadblock to protest what they perceived as preferential treatment
by French police. The Britons decided to block the French highway
leading to the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   John Hazell, a retired Essex financial adviser who had been on a
day-trip to see Impressionist painter Claude Monet's garden near
Rouen, told reporters that French police were letting their
countrymen through while making the Britons wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to get home,'' Hazell said. ``We are fighting a
combination of the farmers and the French police, who are on the
same team.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of aviation fuel shortages, some passenger flights have
been cancelled or rerouted in Lyon. The airports in the western
French cities of Nantes and Rennes ran out of fuel, and the Nice
airport on the Riviera is expected to run dry by Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The government has ordered many service stations to conserve
fuel for police, hospital and emergency vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has been losing his patience
with the truckers and said their strike had ``inflicted a major
handicap on the French economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Socialist premier, faced with a widening barrage of strike
threats, said an offer of a 15 percent tax cut on their diesel fuel
was the government's final offer. The truckers demanded 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The protestors seemed to have been inspired by last week's
success of French fishermen, who blocked ports until they won a tax
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders, environmentalists and editorialists have
criticized Jospin for giving in to pressure and spawning even more
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, wary of the escalating protests, is urging
OPEC leaders to lower prices and will seek to influence the major
petroleum-producing states during meetings this weekend in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
