<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Sept. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy, cool weather will linger over the much of the southern
Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys Friday as high pressure on the
East Coast continues to circulate moist air into the Southeast.
Periods of rain and some thunder will occur near the Gulf Coast,
especially over central and eastern sections. Drier air and some
sun will cover the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer air will spread from the Ohio Valley into the Northeast.
A weak cool front will be accompanied by a narrow band of clouds
and a few light showers as it approaches the southern Great Lakes.
Meanwhile, a few thunderstorms will occur near the Ohio River as
humidity increases.
</P>
<P>
   Another surge of very cool air will reach the Northwest attended
by coastal and mountain showers. By Saturday, snow showers are
expected in the higher elevations of the northern Cascades and
Bitterroots.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HISTORIC DROUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City has joined a growing list of places in the
southern Plains that have set records for uninterrupted dryness.
Thursday was the 40th consecutive day without rain. The statewide
average rainfall for Oklahoma in August was only 0.13 inches, the
lowest since records began in 1895. The previous August record was
set in 1936 at the peak of the Dust Bowl years. The drought this
year has been especially severe from Kansas to Texas, however the
Dust Bowl droughts spanned several years in the 1930s and covered
most of the Plains.
</P>
</TEXT>
