<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5316 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-CAMPUS-$ADV10-CO     09-07 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CAMPUS-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUN FINDS AN ASYLUM FROM CRAZY SILICON VALLEY REAL ESTATE PRICES
 &HT;    830&AMP;add. With TECH-LIST. For release Sunday, Sept. 10
 &HT;    By BOB KEEFE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ When Sun Microsystems Inc. started looking
for space for a new office and corporate headquarters here four
years ago, it faced the same problems as any company trying to
expand in crowded Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Developable land is scarce. Real estate prices are among the
highest in the world. And in environmentally conscious California,
getting regulatory approval for new projects isn't usually easy.
</P>
<P>
   Sun's approach, however, was anything but typical.
</P>
<P>
   When the state put an abandoned 112-year-old former mental
hospital, decrepit and choked by weeds, up for sale as surplus
land, the computer giant bid on the site and won.
</P>
<P>
   Sun got the entire 82-acre site once known as the Agnews Insane
Asylum, complete with about 100 buildings, for about $621,000 an
acre _ cheap for commercial property in the heart of Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But the story behind the rise of Sun's newest campus, which
officially opened Aug. 23, goes far beyond the palatable price tag
and unusual history. It is a story rife with controversy, despite
seemingly good intentions by Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the office park for the first time and it's hard knowing
where you are. It has the feel of a college campus, the appearance
of a turn-of-the-century town and the flavor of high-tech that is
inescapable in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Next to corporate meeting rooms, community ballet recitals and
public concerts are held in a refurbished auditorium where the rich
wood stage and high ceilings still echo performances of another
time.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is a new homeless shelter. Nearby, developers
are building low-income apartments _ something badly needed in
expensive Santa Clara _ and single-family houses.
</P>
<P>
   And smack in the middle of the corporate campus, between
buildings where Sun will have its world headquarters next year, a
15-acre city park _ the third largest in Santa Clara _ attracts
kids on scooters and picnicking families.
</P>
<P>
   All of it was paid for or prompted by Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like something that's not supposed to happen,'' said a
giddy Larry Wolfe. As director of the City of Santa Clara's parks
department, Wolfe worked extensively with Sun on the newly named
Agnews Historic Park. ``I don't know of anything that has been done
like this anywhere before.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe is right. There hasn't been a project quite like Sun's
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   But in cities where space is often at a premium _ especially in
high-tech, high-growth communities _ more and more technology
companies are taking unique approaches to their new digs.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, for instance, Internet company CarrierPoint Inc.
recently moved into the 60-year-old Siemens-Westinghouse building,
in part because company executives hope the retrofitted office
space near Georgia Tech will help attract new talent.
</P>
<P>
   And near Dayton, Ohio, local officials are trying to redevelop
the aging former Mound nuclear weapons plant, with its existing
high-speed data network and Cold War-era backup power supply, into
a 60-acre ``Smart Park'' for Internet and telecommunications
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Often, like Sun, companies are partnering with local governments
to get projects done more quickly in tough-to-develop areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, for example, Computer Sciences Corp. is
teaming up with the city to redevelop a seven-block section of
downtown into an office campus and a new City Hall. Intel Corp.
also is working closely with Austin officials to build a new design
center downtown after environmental groups objected to the
semiconductor giant's earlier plans to build over the sensitive
Barton Springs aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Clara, where space is so tight that the former mental
hospital was one of the last large developable pieces of land
anywhere, Sun saw a unique opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go looking for land these days and it becomes a matter of
what can business use, what can the public use,'' said Sun
spokeswoman Diane Carlini. ``At some point, there's only so much
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun, best known for developing the Java technology used in
Internet design and for its Unix-based servers, had another motive
in redeveloping the old hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For high-tech companies in Silicon Valley, about the only
problem worse than finding good real estate is finding good
workers.
</P>
<P>
   After Sun officials determined that a high concentration of
their employees live within two miles of the abandoned hospital,
the company decided to try and buy it. At the same time, they
figured, working at the unique location could be an added
attraction for new employees.
</P>
<P>
   When a second phase is completed and Sun's headquarters moves
from nearby Palo Alto next year, about 3,600 employees will work at
the Santa Clara campus. Currently, almost 2,000 work there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, we have to find ways to differentiate ourselves
in a very hotly contested labor market,'' said Bill Agnello, senior
vice president of workplace resources at Sun. ``We think that
employees and potential employees will respond well.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In all, Sun spent about $250 million, or about $250 per square
foot of space, developing the campus, according to Agnello. That's
about the going rate for new space in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had other opportunities that would have been less risky,
less time-consuming, less expensive, but we felt this was the best
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a hospital that was falling apart and that the state
had closed it many years earlier,'' he said. ``The state didn't
have the rehabilitation dollars for it; the (nearby) residents
hated it. We were able to utilize it and still provide for open
space for the public.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that didn't make it easy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sun's plans for the Agnews campus became the focal
point of one of the most contentious development battles ever in
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of the historical significance of the hospital
buildings, which were placed on the National Register of Historic
Places a few years ago, and environmental and traffic concerns, the
Santa Clara planning department initially rejected Sun's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the city council narrowly approved it a few months
later, leading some preservationists to file suit in an attempt to
derail the development. That suit failed, but it didn't stop
opponents from gathering enough signatures to put the plan to a
referendum, which Sun won in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite praises for the project today, some are still bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a very tragic thing that happened,'' said
attorney Susan Brandt-Hawley, whose law firm led the unsuccessful
legal battle. ``They said they couldn't restore (all) the
buildings, so they sacrificed historic resources of national
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandt-Hawley, whose Northern California law firm specializes in
historical preservation cases, said she wouldn't be surprised to
see more bitter fights over historic buildings as space gets harder
to find and cash-laden tech companies continue to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things going on in California right now,'' she
explained. ``Space is becoming limited, and finally we're an old
enough state that we've started to have 100-year-old buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun did save and renovate four of the buildings at the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Like the auditorium, the refurbished former director's mansion
harkens back to a different age, with its warm sitting parlor and
wide wooden staircase that leads to rooms with a bird's-eye view of
the rest of the campus. Today, community groups can use the
building, completed in 1912, for meetings and other events.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the campus is a soaring clock tower that's
still being renovated. Depending on where you stand, the clock's
giant face peeks out between the 450 or so mature trees that Sun
kept on the site. The clock tower is near the only building that
Sun renovated that isn't open to the public, the hospital's former
administration building, which Sun uses for office space.
</P>
<P>
   Sun officials said they wanted to preserve more buildings, but
said the others were too decrepit to convert to modern offices.
They haven't completely disappeared, however. Roof tiles from some
of the old buildings were used on eight new buildings that Sun has
constructed so far.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the development's controversy, Sun officials say they
did the best they could to blend corporate with community when
developing the new campus. And, they say, they'd do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, it was a matter of ``How do we make everybody as
happy as we can,'' said Carlini, the Sun spokeswoman. ``This is
what came about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe's e-mail address is bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
