<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-     09-07 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. REMOVES ALL AID WORKERS FROM WEST TIMOR AFTER ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. high commissioner for refugees, Sadako
Ogata, on Thursday pulled the agency's remaining relief workers out
of West Timor, following Wednesday's attack on a U.N. refugee
office in Atambua that left three international staff members dead.
</P>
<P>
   Ogata said she was withdrawing the relief workers because of the
likelihood of continuing harassment by self-styled militiamen
opposed to independence for neighboring East Timor. The decision
leaves tens of thousands of refugees, who had fled similarly bloody
attacks a year ago in the eastern part of the island, without
assistance from the U.N. refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-nine agency employees, all but two of them Indonesian,
left Atambua Thursday, in a convoy escorted by Indonesian soldiers,
for Batugade, a border town in East Timor, where they were flown by
helicopter to the capital Dili. The group included two workers who
had survived Wednesday's attack _ a Fijian security officer and a
Japanese human rights official working for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said 70 other employees of the United Nations and
other international organizations were flown out of Kupang, the
main town in West Timor, to Denpasar in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the three slain refugee workers were carried by a
separate helicopter to Dili, where their coffins were draped with
U.N. flags and driven to a morgue operated by the U.N. mission in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general's special representative for East Timor,
Sergio Vieira de Mello, and other U.N. officials held an airport
ceremony to honor the dead workers, who came from Puerto Rico,
Ethiopia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the first time I put flowers on coffins or body
bags of U.N. staff, but it is particularly difficult when the
murder is so brutally senseless,'' Vieira de Mello said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about sheer murder of humanitarian staff who
were there to protect the victims of similarly senseless violence
carried out by the same people in East Timor last year,'' the
special representative said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan and other leaders gathered for a
summit meeting here demanded that President Abdurrahman Wahid of
Indonesia take real steps to control the militias, which are
actually lawless gangs that are suspected of getting weapons and
covert support from the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, who is attending the summit meeting, blamed the latest
rampage on militiamen grieving for their murdered leader, but also
suggested that the timing of the attack may have been meant to
embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   A Brazilian tourist in Atambua who was severely injured in the
rampage was evacuated on Wednesday to a hospital in Dili, where her
condition was upgraded on Thursday to stable.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian police reported finding a fourth unidentified
body after the attack, which was thought to be that of a worker for
another aid organization.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Eckhard, a spokesman for Annan, said on Thursday that all
the U.N. employees been accounted for. Eckhard, at a briefing for
reporters, also confirmed that the organization's relief operation
in West Timor was now shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going back until Indonesia demonstrates that it can
get these militias under control, and the threat posed by the
militias has been eliminated,'' Eckhard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
