<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-GUN0908-COX     09-07 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GUN0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Usual Suspects' writer Christopher McQuarrie returns with `Way
of the Gun.'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Christopher McQuarrie wrote one of the most
celebrated movie scripts of the 1990s. ``The Usual Suspects''
stands at the summit of postmodern hip with Quentin Tarantino's
``Pulp Fiction'' and Charlie Kaufman's ``Being John Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   Released in 1995, ``Suspects'' was a crime thriller propelled by
whiplash twists, popping dialogue, and a mystery with a maddening
conundrum _ the elusive Keyser Soze _ at its core.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie's screenplay became a minor sensation, earning almost
as many awards, including an Oscar, as cultish admirers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood works in curious ways. Getting from that peak to
the 31-year-old writer's directorial debut, ``The Way of the Gun,''
, has been a journey through frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 'Suspects' on it was this downward slide. I really
thought that once (the Oscar) happened I'd be given this great leg
up,'' says McQuarrie. ``You go to the studios and tell them your
ideas, but they want to make their movie. ... The harder I tried to
make something that I thought was right ... `` He trails off into
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie, round and ruddy, has delivered this jeremiad before,
you can tell. It tires him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually it becomes about trying to get anything made just
so you can make it your way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Things got rough. When 20th Century Fox asked him to take a pass
at a crime script, McQuarrie pitched his ideas. ``But they insisted
on me making the characters good and sympathetic. You have to make
it OK that the characters are murdering thieves. And that so
offends me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I told them, 'You guys figure out how much money you're
willing to risk on my movie. I will not take a salary. I will not
take back-end fees. I will live on crafts services. I will cast
whoever you want. Just let me tell this story the way I think it
should be told.' And they said no.''
</P>
<P>
   Defeated, McQuarrie left the meeting and had coffee with actor
and friend Benicio Del Toro. ``I said, 'I quit. I'm out of this
business,''' McQuarrie recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro told him to make another crime film, but the writer
feared being branded ``the crime guy.'' Del Toro persisted: If you
want to make a movie your way, you first have to make the movie
they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Benicio that if I ever made a crime film again I would
make it in such a way that no one would ask me to make another
one,'' says McQuarrie. ``I would make a film about criminals and I
would not pull any punches.''
</P>
<P>
   He brainstormed with Del Toro and borrowed a true story his wife
told him about a rich couple who hired bodyguards to watch the
surrogate mother carrying their child.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Way of the Gun,'' a gritty and bloody kidnapping
caper with noirish overtones. Del Toro and Ryan Phillip-- e star as
fatalistic criminals who kidnap a pregnant woman (Juliette Lewis),
unaware of her links to the mob. Their troubles thicken. Guns are
pulled. Men die. A baby is born.
</P>
<P>
   Laced with the plot corkscrews and piquant dialogue that are
McQuarrie's forte, the drama is directed with economy and
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But if there ever was glamo-- r attached to directing for
McQuarrie, it vanished apace. Some days were dark indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask myself why anyone would want to do this for a living.
It is the worst job,'' he says. ``But I will say the fear of
writing, of facing the blank page is infinitely worse ...
</P>
<P>
   With directing, you get up in the morning and that's what you
do. Love it or hate, you don't think about how to get out of it.
You've got to get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of ``The Usual Suspects'' have wondered if director Bryan
Singer and McQuarrie will collaborate again. The high school chums
first teamed for 1993's ``Public Access,'' and McQuarrie was one of
11 writers on Singer's ``X-Men.'' When asked, McQuarrie offers a
suspiciously coy ``I don't know.'' Asked if they're still friends,
he says the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie's currently putting the final touches on his script
for ``The Green Hornet,'' about which he's enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't have a director for it I'm thinking about
throwing my hat in the ring,'' he says. ``It's a superhero movie
without the suspension of disbelief. It would great if the
executives in charge get it.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Chris Garcia at cgarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SHELTER0908-COX     09-07 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELTER0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Shelter' keeps its relevance, power
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - When baby boomers pointed to Woodstock '99's
sordid news footage as proof that Generation X had gone awry, X-ers
immediately reminded boomers of ``Gimme Shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the tragic Altamont Speedway concert of 1969, and
similar to the recent documentary ``Message to Love: The Isle of
Wight Festival,'' this 1970 film was a nail in the coffin of the
'60s free-love era. Released soon after the original ``Woodstock'',
it provided an emphatic counterpoint to that better-known
documentary's images of happy hippies changing the world. In
``Gimme Shelter,'' they can't even change chords without somebody
getting punched.
</P>
<P>
   How fitting that the 30th anniversary re-release of ``Gimme
Shelter'' _ which culminates in a stabbing death some 10 yards from
where the Rolling Stones are performing _ comes a year after the
fiery and violent Woodstock '99 and only two months after nine fans
were crushed to death at a Pearl Jam concert in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll tragedies are nothing new. The revamped, 35 mm
version of ``Shelter'' reminds us of this fact, while also offering
insight into why such debacles happen: namely, out of greed and
arrogance, neither strangers to the music business today.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, filmmakers David and Albert Maysles, with co-director
Charlotte Zwerin, set out to document the Stones' first U.S. tour
in about four years. At that point, Altamont was just an idea.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the first 25 minutes of the film are mostly generic concert
footage. There are also scenes of the ``Sticky Fingers'' sessions
at the Muscle Shoals studio in Alabama. For avid fans (and perhaps
only avid fans), this is great stuff. It's the start of what is
generally considered the Stones best period, marked by a darker,
more Americanized sound and by their arrival as a stadium act.
</P>
<P>
   These elements all come into play at Altamont, which makes up
the rest of ``Gimme Shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   From the go, the concert is a volcano of trouble. Hoping to give
a massive free concert in San Francisco as they did a few months
earlier in London (without any violence), the Stones are bounced
from two sites before settling on a speedway in nearby Altamont
that's hurting for business. This is two days before the event.
</P>
<P>
   It can be done, assure concert organizers, including lawyer
Melvin Belli (who represented Jack Ruby) and Michael Lang, the
smiley, can-do co-producer of the original Woodstock. Lang's
presence eerily ties Altamont to Woodstock '99, where his calm
nature similarly did nothing to help matters.
</P>
<P>
   Altamont's biggest mistake soon becomes obvious: The Hell's
Angels are brought in as a last-ditch, low-cost security team. Just
when it seems things can't get any stupider, organizers opt to pay
the bikers with beer.
</P>
<P>
   When Gram Parsons' timid Flying Burrito Brothers take the stage
to open the show, the Angels are plainly buzzing for a fight. Of
course, they get it _ with the crowd, stagehands, even Jefferson
Airplane singer Marty Balin, in one of the movie's most memorable
scenes. The next segment shows the Grateful Dead high-tailing it
out of there without performing. It's the only sign of intelligence
in ``Shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels aren't the only ones to blame, though. Fans are seen
getting wasted and wild the night before the concert. On the
morning of the show, Mick Jagger gets punched by a fan while
walking to his trailer.
</P>
<P>
   The violence builds to the tragic stabbing of Meredith Hunter by
an Angel _ caught on film and rerun several times, like the
Zapruder footage in ``JFK.'' The clip shows Hunter carrying a gun.
It doesn't, however, support the (unproven) charges that the Angels
initiated the confrontation because the victim was black and his
girlfriend was white.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's message is nonetheless clearly written on Jagger's
face as he watches the stabbing footage in postproduction: This
concert spawned this death, and neither should have happened.
Unfortunately, the lesson of how tragic a poorly produced concert
can be is one still being learned.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Chris Riemenschneider at
criemenschneider(at)statesman.com or 4453607.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
