<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5327 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      09-07 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SETS CAMPAIGN'S SIGHTS ON WASHINGTON MILITARY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story will be replaced by a longer version with a new
lede, BUSH-CAMPAIGN by Alison Mitchell datelined Dayton, Ohio, and
scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT11 and 12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday accused the Clinton-Gore
administration of failing to maintain the military power of the
United States and said he would change how the country uses and
deploys force.
</P>
<P>
   In an address in Dayton, Ohio, Bush, the Republican presidential
nominee, said he would modernize the military to protect the United
States and its allies from emerging threats. He said America's
armed forces were poorly paid and poorly housed, and that he would
improve conditions.
</P>
<P>
   He said that improving the pay and living conditions of fighting
men and women was necessary to improving morale and the readiness
of the military to fight and keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for new leadership in Washington, D.C., that will
rebuild the morale of the United States military,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With retired Gen. Colin Powell at his side, Bush said he would
rebuild the strength of the military. Bush said there were
disturbing signs of military weakness, including low numbers of
recruits, needed replacement parts and low military pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will rebuild the military power of the United States in
order to keep the peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized President Clinton's use of military
peacekeepers. Although he did not specifically criticize any
individual peacekeeping missions in Haiti or Kosovo. But Bush
suggested he would find a different way to exert U.S. military
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission of the United States military is to be able to
fight and win war and therefore prevent war from happening in the
first place,'' Bush said. ``The mission of the United States
military is not to try to solve all the difficult and diplomatic
questions this country faces. We must be peacemakers not
peacekeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would redefine how war is fought. He said
modernizing the military was necessary to prepare for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our military of the future must be easier to move, harder to
find, more lethal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke on similar themes earlier in the day in an address to
veterans in Detroit. There, he said he would transform the military
from a force made to fight Cold War-era battles into an
organization that could fight ever more technically sophisticated
battles.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Detroit, Powell contended the Clinton administration
is unwilling either to modernize the military and improve current
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is we have to invest in readiness; we have to buy
the equipment we need in the future,'' Powell said. ``We have to
plan for the transformation of the armed forces in the 21st
century.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush's vice presidential nominee, Dick Cheney, also speaking
about military issues Thursday at a campaign stop at a Portland,
Maine, company that makes valves for submarines. ``Is the U.S.
military better off than it was eight years ago? I don't think
so,'' said Cheney, a former secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bush has been emphasizing the military, an issue he
believes gives him an edge on Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic presidential nominee. On Wednesday, Bush spoke to
veterans in Milwaukee, saying that the United States must dominate
the skies and the seas in order to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Gore have argued Bush and Powell have overstated
the problems of the U.S. military, which on the basis of size,
training and technology is overwhelmingly superior to any other
fighting force in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign has argued their economic plan would actually
spend billions more of the surplus on improving the military. Gore
has said Bush would dedicate much of that money to tax cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
