<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FABRIC-BACTERIA-NYTSF     09-07 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FABRIC-BACTERIA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS DISPOSE OF FABRIC-COVERED FURNITURE  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY E'LOUISE ONDASH  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Naugahyde may not be your notion of tasteful interior design,
but it may be one way to prevent bacteria from spreading in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Fabric-covered furniture helps transmit vancomycin-resistant
enterococci (VRE) _ culprits notorious for causing infections in
hospital patients, according to new research. The bacteria's
capsule-like coating apparently helps them survive a long time
within fabrics, which become breeding grounds for the critters.
</P>
<P>
   Better to have furniture covered with nonporous material like
vinyl that can be wiped down easily with disinfectant, say the
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 percent of the enterococci in intensive care units are
VRE, meaning they're resistant to the antibiotic vancomycin,
commonly used to treat bacterial infections, says the study, which
is reported in the August issue of the American Journal of
Infection Control.
</P>
<P>
   ``These organisms are hardy,'' says lead study author Dr. Gary
Noskin, associate professor of medicine at Northwestern University
Medical School. ``They can survive for a long time on environmental
surfaces such as countertops, bed rails, telephone receivers and
privacy curtains. They're all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Noskin says most people who carry VRE don't develop
infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``VRE don't cause problems in normally healthy people. They
aren't jumping off the beds and chairs and making people sick, but
they can be a problem for people with weakened immune systems,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bill Jarvis, chief of the infections and prevention branch
of the Hospitals Infection Program at the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention (CDC), says the study is not the first of
its kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The missing link in the study is how the bacteria is
transmitted _ and what is the likelihood that a patient with severe
underlying disease will contract it,'' Jarvis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study does highlight, though, the importance of
disinfecting patients' rooms [when they leave] and that
disinfectant must be applied so that it has contact with the
organism or it won't work,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital infection control is essential, but don't get
sidetracked, says Marissa Miller, a veterinarian and director of
the antimicrobial-resistance program at the National Institute of
Allergy and Infectious Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to focus on what the most important issues are, and
it's not replacing all the fabric-covered furniture in hospitals.
If we diagnose resistant infections rapidly and prescribe the
appropriate antibiotic, we'll have the greatest impact,'' Miller
says.
</P>
<P>
   Carpeting in hospitals also has fallen out of favor with some
infection-control experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carpeting is a filthy thing that harbors infection,'' says Dr.
Philip Tierno, a microbiology and immunology expert at New York
University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hospital is not a home. It's an institution to give medical
care. We're not fooling the patients. It they are afraid of
surgery, a little carpeting isn't going to make them less afraid,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Washing hands is still a highly effective way to control
infection, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands are still the most lethal weapons in the hospital. In at
least six or seven studies, it's been shown that about 50 percent
of all people don't wash their hands, and hospital workers mirror
what the general population does,'' Tierno says.
</P>
<P>
   Noskin says the most important message of the study is that
``hospitals are, by and large, very safe places for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However, there are some resistant bacteria on surfaces. Even
with fabric-covered furniture, you can prevent patients from
getting VRE just by covering the furniture with a sheet. And, when
it comes time to replace furniture, replace it with something easy
to clean,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
