<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5334 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-MAYANRIVIERA-1000(4Ta     09-07 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYANRIVIERA-1000(4Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESORTS FOR FOLKS WHO WOULD RATHER SPEND TIME IN A HAMMOCK THAN AT
A DISCO
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanied by RIVIERA-IF YOU GO)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TANKAH, Mexico _ Shaleh Clark, late of Palestine, Texas, invites
us behind the modest bar at the Tankah Inn, the five-room B&AMP;B her
family opened three years ago on this gorgeous stretch of beach on
the Gulf of Mexico, and explains the house rules.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant doubles as the family's living room and the
guests' lounge area, and here's the menu, but if we want something
else, they'll make it, as long as they have it. Beer is in the big
cooler on the right side under the bar, Cokes in the one on the
left. Go ahead and help yourself; just put your bottle caps in the
glass schooner marked with your name, and we'll count them up at
the end and charge you then. Downstairs, there's a sea kayak and
snorkeling equipment if we want to go looking for the manta rays
that prowl just offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there will be electricity, but not right now. If we want
a really hot shower, we'd best take it between 6 p.m., when the
generator comes on, and midnight, when it shuts off again.
</P>
<P>
   We are only about 75 miles south of Cancun, but it might as well
be a million.
</P>
<P>
   This is what we had been hoping to find when we went to what has
been collectively dubbed the Riviera Maya, an 80-mile stretch of
resorts and villages on the Yucatan coast all the way from the
southern tip of Cancun, to the north, to Tulum, on the southern
end.
</P>
<P>
   Named for the indigenous people who lived on this land a
thousand years before the Spaniards showed up, the region is
probably the hottest tourism area in Mexico right now. Prized for
its white-sand beaches, sunny weather and clear, turquoise water,
the equal of any in the Caribbean, it is also becoming known for
its all-inclusive luxury resorts, which are popping up all along
the coast.
</P>
<P>
   If Cancun is at one extreme of Mexican beach resorts, with all
its five-star hotels like the Ritz-Carlton, chain restaurants like
TGIFridays and nightclubs that charge $20 to get in, we were
looking for the other. When we set off for a four-day drive along
the Riviera Maya, we were looking for a more laid-back Mexico _
where there are only a couple of thatch-roofed restaurants to
choose from, nightly entertainment consists of watching the stars
with a drink in hand, and, if your timing is right, you just might
have a half-mile-long stretch of white-sand beach to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE: TULUM
</P>
<P>
   The man who shows us a room in one of the thatched-roof cabanas
at Piedra Escondida, an eight-room resort on the beach south of
Tulum, is sweating heavily, a sign we probably should have taken as
an omen. But the room is clean and cute, decorated with colorful
Mexican textiles and ceramic tiles, and has a big private bath.
Plus, the owner is willing to take $60 a night, down from the $75
originally quoted and less than the $80 to $100 charged by similar
places down the road. There seems to be a nice breeze if you open
both windows. We take it.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hours earlier, my friend Chris and I had landed in
Cancun, climbed into a rented Nissan Sentra, and set off for Tulum,
generally recognized as the southern tip of the Riviera. Even
stopping for a slow lunch _ quesadillas, chips, juice, delivered by
a shy 12-year-old boy who charged us $8 _ at a tiny deserted
restaurant on a beach called, as best we could determine,
Xcalacoco, we'd made the 80-plus miles in under three hours.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the scheme to build up the Mayan Riviera, the
coastline road between Cancun and Tulum has been greatly improved
over the past several years. Now it is excellent _ four-lane
divided all the way to Playa del Carmen, about a 45-minute drive
from Cancun, and a wide, smooth two-lane with broad shoulders from
there south to Tulum. The driving is easy, once you figure out that
locals consider the shoulders an equal driving opportunity, and
that you shouldn't panic when a taxi decides to pass you despite
there being a car heading in the opposite direction not 30 feet
away. (Everybody always moves over in time; in four days we did not
see a single fender-bender, a record I dare you to match in
Dallas-Fort Worth.)
</P>
<P>
   Most people know Tulum as an archaeological site; it is a minor
Mayan city, originally known as Zama, the culture's word for dawn,
largely abandoned about 400 years ago. The ruins of Tulum have
become perhaps the culture's best-known symbol, by virtue of their
breathtaking setting on cliffs overlooking the gulf and its easy
access to Cancun. But Tulum is also a small modern village, with
little hotels, restaurants and shops, and, on a separate road that
goes down to the beach, a string of small resorts.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   The farther along the road you drive, the more rustic these
resorts get, down to the dirt-floor-and-hammock cabanas that
backpackers discovered a generation ago. We end up on the more
upscale end of things, as, other than exploring the ruins, best
done in the cool early morning before the buses arrive from Cancun
and Playa del Carmen, there's not a lot to do here, and we want a
nice setting in which not to do it.
</P>
<P>
   You can walk along the beach and watch European and Mexican kids
play in the surf; browse the three or four shops selling hammocks,
silver jewelry and pottery; buy bottled water and snacks at the
small food market; or settle in with a book on one of the hammocks
strung between palm trees. There are no discos, no American chain
restaurants, no minimalls.
</P>
<P>
   The resort's lights flicker on just before sunset, as promised,
when the generator kicks in. (There is no electricity on this
stretch of coast; for miles, everyone relies on generators.) We
head to the resort's tiny restaurant for an early dinner, where
we're delighted to see that, because its owners are from the Amalfi
coast of Italy, it serves Italian food. A basket of chips with
fresh salsa, heavy on the lime and cilantro, and two dishes of
perfectly cooked pasta, one with an unusual and delicious sauce of
avocado and cream, and several icy Sols, goes for well under $20.
</P>
<P>
   With the sea breeze wafting through the open windows of the
dining room, and against the background chatter of our fellow
guests, a mix of German and French tourists, it's a perfect
evening. Like them, we decide to retire early; the lights go off
around 10 p.m. anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the room, getting ready for bed, we congratulate
ourselves on finding this spot, for getting out of the Cancun rut.
</P>
<P>
   Then we realize the first problem in paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The breeze has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   We lie in our beds trying not to move, so as not to exert
ourselves and sweat even more. Tomorrow, maybe we'll look for a
room with a fan.
</P>
<P>
   DAY TWO: TANKAH
</P>
<P>
   Casa Cenote, a thatch-roofed, open-air restaurant overlooking
the water and heralded by the guidebooks as an undiscovered gem,
has managed to be discovered today not only by us but by a large
family from Georgia, several day-trippers from up the road, and
assorted other tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But its location, on the northern end of a gently arcing bay
that most people call Tankah (also spelled Tank-ha or Tancah) has
enthralled us. The beach is wide and white; the surf is blue and
gentle. And except for the 20 diners at this restaurant, the place
is practically deserted. We'd planned to find a condo tonight in
Akumal, a 30-year-old diving resort about five miles north, but
instead we decide we'd rather try for one of the homes or small
inns that have sprung up in recent years on the road to Casa
Cenote.
</P>
<P>
   We get lucky on the third stop. The Clarks, who opened their inn
and its attached dive shop about three years ago, have a room for
$65, breakfast included. We also get free use of snorkeling
equipment and a sea kayak, and access to the breezy second-floor
patio, open to the sea and the Clarks' meticulously planted
beachfront garden. (Edged in conch shells, it's in the shape of a
large state of Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   And the spotless room, with cool tile floors, a large bathroom
and a tiny patio, has a ceiling fan! (Though, as we learn to our
regret later, it's not of much use after the generator shuts down.)
</P>
<P>
   We have the beach pretty much to ourselves all afternoon, as we
carefully collect perfectly preserved pieces of coral that we end
up throwing back onto the beach. That night, we luck into a party;
some local divers had gone lobster hunting the night before, and
the Clarks invite us to join them all as they cook up their catch.
We eat dinner late, a feast of fresh lobster, rice, baked potatoes
and garlic bread, and are regaled with stories of life along the
Mexican coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to see why I'm here?'' one of the divers, a Florida
transplant, asks suddenly. ``Come with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He leads us outside, up a rickety ladder and onto the roof of
the inn.
</P>
<P>
   At first it's pitch black, so dark we can't see as we pick our
way over to the edge. But as our eyes adjust to the darkness, we
see dozens of brilliant stars; so many, you can't begin to count
them. We can hear the waves hitting the beach below and virtually
nothing else. The breeze is almost chilly, and smells just barely
of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   This is why I'm here. What else do you need, he asks
rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Tankah, too, is changing. Ten years ago, there was almost
nothing here; now, like dozens of little inlets along this coast,
with names like Paamul, Kantenah and Chemuyil, Tankah is a hot
commodity. When Chris and I kayak into the bay the next morning to
go snorkeling at the coral reef a half-mile offshore, we see huge
cranes rising from the jungle at both ends of the beach. More
development. We wonder: How long before Tankah is a full-on resort?
</P>
<P>
   DAY THREE: PLAYA DEL CARMEN
</P>
<P>
   In the tiny hut that serves as the Hotel El Faro reception area,
Menudo is checking in right in front of us.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, not really. But the group of five well-to-do Mexican
teen-agers _ wearing silver wraparound shades, gelled Ricky Martin
haircuts and many FUBU logos, all carrying color-coordinated
cellphones _ is our first indication that Playa has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Even six or seven years ago, this one-time fishing village was
so laid-back that pigs and dogs were nearly as common on the beach
as tourists. Simple hotel rooms a block from the beach went for $25
a night and were largely filled with American backpackers and
Europeans settling in for long stays; fresh lobster and shrimp
dinners in the open-air restaurants cost less than $10.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
