<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5338 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-MAYANRIVIERA-3rdTake-     09-07 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYANRIVIERA-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 TANKAH, Mexico: less than $10. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But now, fueled by a huge building boom that in just two or
three years has added a McDonald's, a Gap store, and a bunch of
upscale shops, restaurants, hotels and coffee bars, Playa, as it's
called, has become a trendy destination.
</P>
<P>
   Playa, in fact, is said to be to be the fastest-growing city in
all of Mexico. It sure looks like it. There is construction on
virtually every block; help-wanted signs seeking gardeners or cooks
or maids are posted at the entry to a number of hotels and
restaurants, an unusual sight in a country with a traditionally
high unemployment rate. And on the main drag of the tourist zone,
Fifth Avenue, vendors hawking ankle bracelets and silver crosses
and Talavera pottery have grown noticeably more aggressive,
probably a direct response to the scads of cruise ship passengers
and day-trippers from Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs Playa is trying to limit its growth. For
one thing, there is a palm-tree ordinance; hotels cannot be taller
than a palm tree, limiting them to about 3 stories.
</P>
<P>
   For another, most of the new hotels are not mega-resorts but
boutique properties like the 5-year-old El Faro, a sleek, modern
hotel with marble baths in the 28 guest rooms, all built around an
old lighthouse and a gorgeous free-form pool just off the beach.
Owner Bernd Durrmeier plans to add a parking garage, plus 40 or
more condos and rooms, within the next few years, but he plans to
keep as much of his landscaped grounds as possible, and he says
other business owners are trying to keep the development tasteful,
not garish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get the city to preserve what we have,'' he
says. ``Playa is one of a kind. It's more comparable to places in
Europe, little villages that have grown up along the coast, where
you can stroll to shops and restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   And, once we're over the initial shock of its growth, and the
sheer number of sun-lovers on the beach, we realize he's right.
Some of the most recent development has been in an area called
``Uptown,'' the end of Fifth Avenue farthest from the dock where
passengers disembark from cruise ships and ferries from Cozumel.
Unlike that end, called ``Downtown'' and crammed with rowdy
restaurant/bars like Senor Frogs, fast-food outlets like Domino's
and Burger King, and cheap souvenir shops, Uptown is largely made
up of upscale clothing boutiques, coffee bars and restaurants with
sophisticated menus.
</P>
<P>
   We gravitate toward that end of town, flipping a coin among
several stylish restaurants and choosing one called Xas for dinner.
Its dimly lit decor and its menu of Asian-Mediterranean dishes,
like a quesadilla stuffed with oyster mushrooms and teriyaki
chicken, would not be out of place in Deep Ellum. It is the best
meal of our trip, and even with drinks, we still spend less than
$30. We stroll happily down the half-dozen blocks back to the
hotel, past quiet restaurants and bars less than half-full. Despite
our fears, we realize, Playa is not Cancun. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   DAY FOUR: CANCUN
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a deserted restaurant right before the dinner hour,
sipping a Negro Modelo, Chris looks over my shoulder in terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look outside, look outside,'' she says. ``There's a whole
bunch of pirates, and they're coming in here!''
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere else, I would have cut her off from the beer; here, I
merely looked at where she was pointing with mild interest.
</P>
<P>
   In Cancun, few bars or restaurants seem content to merely sell
food and drink. Everybody has to have a shtick _ waiters who wear
fake plastic butts under their aprons and pretend to flash you
while they serve the quesadillas, or who dress up like matadors, or
who carry motorcycle helmets that they slip on the heads of
unsuspecting guests, then slam shots of tequila against them and
pour them down said guest's throat.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in this case, who pretend to be pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Chris said, there was a gaggle of them _ some of them on
stilts _ headed our way. Another waiter, who apparently hadn't
gotten the theme and was dressed like a 1930s-era gangster, had
already tried to get us to ``loosen up'' by sneaking up behind
Chris and poking her in the side. We looked at each other, downed
our beers and headed back to our hotel. We'd spent 45 minutes in
Cancun's party zone, about 30 minutes more than our limit.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
