<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5339 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-MAYANRIVIERA-4thTake-     09-07 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYANRIVIERA-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 TANKAH, Mexico: than our limit. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In our defense, forced fun isn't our idea of entertainment. In
Cancun's defense, it is the choice of a lot of people. With more
than 24,000 hotel rooms, all of them built within the past three
decades, it is Mexico's most popular beach resort, drawing more
than 2 million visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them come here because, as has often been noted, Cancun
is a place that could be anywhere. The beautiful coastline has been
built wall-to-wall with modern conveniences, malls and a Hard Rock
Cafe and McDonald's and Pizza Huts. You don't need to know a lick
of Spanish; you don't need to carry any money besides U.S.
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Mexico's finest hotels are here, including an
extravagant Ritz-Carlton, the beautiful-people boutique hotel Casa
Turquesa, Mexican chains like the Camino Real and a number of
all-inclusive resorts, from whose well-planned grounds guests never
have to venture.
</P>
<P>
   We avoid those, checking into a more unusual option, the Villas
Tacul, a small complex of casitas once used to house visiting
government officials and dignitaries. Turned over to private use a
decade ago, the lobby and the low-slung hotel rooms are decorated
not like a glitzy hotel but more like a gracious Mexican home, with
blue Talavera pottery lamps and planters, heavy carved wooden doors
and furniture, and silver-framed mirrors. There is a small
restaurant, a pool, tennis courts and a playground on the lush
grounds, but no disco, no loud bar, no American chain restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms, like many in Cancun, open up right to the beach,
which is where we are most comfortable in this town. Before our
ill-advised venture into the pirate bar, we'd spent a couple hours
baking under a thatched palapa, watching kids dig in the sand and
adventurous types zip past on personal watercraft, and occasionally
cooling off in the bathtub-warm surf.
</P>
<P>
   We see a lot of tourists as we walk down the beach that
afternoon, and most of them seem quite happy, pleased with their
visit to Mexico's most famous coast.
</P>
<P>
   We're happy for a different reason: Now, we know the Riviera
Maya offers alternatives, a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
