<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-DEADOFFICIAL-0     09-07 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEADOFFICIAL-0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN OFFICIAL CAUGHT IN INTERNATIONAL SCANDAL FOUND DEAD
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In the midst of a scandal involving an associate
who is a suspected Argentine torturer, a high-ranking Mexican
commerce official has been found with his throat slashed in an
apparent suicide, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ramos Tercero, 45, a deputy commerce secretary, reportedly
said in a note that he didn't have ``the energy to defend myself
today or in the coming years as if I were a criminal or a
gangster.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos was found dead Wednesday night near his car, which
contained six suicide notes and was parked along a highway in
Mexico state, officials said. An economist with a doctorate from
Stanford University, Ramos was a government official responsible
for a troubled national car-registration program here that was
plunged into an international scandal last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 24, Mexican police detained the director of the program,
an Argentine businessman contracted by commerce officials last
year. Ricardo Cavallo is being held for possible extradition to
Spain, where a judge has implicated him in dozens of kidnappings,
acts of torture and killings while a Naval officer during
Argentina's 1976-1983 military regime.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials like Ramos were forced to defend the car
registration program, which the federal government enacted to help
reduce the high rate of car theft in Mexico. Prior to Cavallo's
arrest, the program, known here as ``Renave,'' was already under
attack, with numerous state governors and others questioning its
high fees and the government's decision to hire a private firm to
run the program.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Cavallo is also being linked in Spain to car theft
and the kidnappings of 16 babies of Argentine political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a clean man. I'm a good man,'' Ramos reportedly said in a
lengthy and hostile note authorities said was left for Reforma
newspaper. Reforma first revealed suspicions about Cavallo's past
and has covered the program's other problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico City newspaper posted the contents of what it said
was all six letters on its Internet Website.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos said the concession given to Cavallo's firm was done
``with total transparency'' and in strict accordance with the law.
He blamed himself for some errors in making sure the program had
credibility, but he said it was ``professional and clean'' and was
in no way ``an instrument to commit crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos also accused Reforma of publishing false accusations and
subjecting him to ``harsh scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When will you pay?'' Ramos wrote. ``My dream is that this
grotesque episode will inspire in Mexicans a decision to make the
media responsible under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Commerce Secretary Herminio Blanco, Ramos said he
had worked ``to the limit of my capacity and my strength.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the climate of hysteria that's been generated,'' he wrote.
``I have no doubt that my errors and omissions will be presented to
public opinion as intolerable crimes . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   Ramos asked his wife to forgive him in a letter written to her
and his four children. He said the registration project ``was
dead'' although the company had acted properly. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive me for what I'm going to do, but it is the best that I
can do under these circumstances,'' Ramos wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, in New York to attend the
United Nations Millennium Summit, expressed condolences to Ramos'
family and called him ``an honorable man with a firm calling to
public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, Mexico's president-elect, called for a thorough
investigation into Ramos' death, along with other Mexican
opposition legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is behind this has to be confirmed,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos was found with his jugular vein slashed, holding a razor
in his hand, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   reforma.com.mx
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
