A5346 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-RIVIERA-IFYOUGO-TEX     09-07 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVIERA-IFYOUGO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO TO THE MAYAN REVIERA ...
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: Most flights from Dallas/Fort Worth land at the
international airport in Cancun. From there, cabs can be hired to
almost any point on the Riviera Maya; examples of fares are about
$40 one way to Playa del Carmen, $60 to Tulum. An alternative,
especially if you are headed to Playa del Carmen, is to fly into
Cozumel and take the ferry (about $10 one way) from Cancun to
Playa.
</P>
<P>
   PLANNING: U.S. citizens can get into Mexico with a driver's
license and birth certificate, but a passport makes things easier.
</P>
<P>
   STAYING THERE: In Tulum, Piedra Escondida offers eight rooms
with private bath, no fans or a/c, starting from $65, off season.
For information, check out www.hotelstulum.com. No credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   In Tankah, Tankah Inn guest house offers five rooms with private
baths and ceiling fans, at rates starting from $65, off season. For
reservations, e-mail the owners at tankahdiveinn &LR; lycos.com. No
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   In Playa del Carmen, Hotel El Faro has 28 rooms with a/c and
private baths, from $120, off season. Information,
www.hotelelfaro.com; reservations, www.mexicoboutiquehotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   In Cancun, Villas Tacul has 23 villas with rooms and suites,
from $145. www.mexicoboutiquehotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   What to do: The archaelogical site at Tulum is open daily, from
about 7 a.m. to dusk. Admission about $3; parking about $2; guides
are available for an extra fee. Plan on at least one hour to see
the site; it's recommended to arrive early to avoid the heat and
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of ``ecological'' parks along the coast
between Cancun and Tulum, offering manicured beaches, restaurants,
snorkeling spots, marine life, and often a Disney-like atmosphere.
The most popular seems to be Xcaret, which advertises a dolphin
swim program, an underground river ride, horseback riding and an
evening program including a re-creation of a Mayan ball game called
Ulama and a folklorico performance. Admission from $52, including
bus transportation. Information: www.xcaretcancun.com.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The Mexican Tourism Board operates a toll-free
line, (800) 44MEXICO, but it has operated only sporadically over
the past several months, and did not appear to work last week.
There is also a Mexico tourism office in Houston; (713) 772-2581.
</P>
<P>
   Cancun Convention and Visitors Bureau, www.gocancun.com or (800)
CANCUN8.
</P>
<P>
   Good background information is available in the ``Yucatan
Peninsula Handbook'' (Moon Publications; $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, try www.mayanriviera.com for information about
Playa del Carmen, Tulum and points in between.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites www.locogringo.com and www.xaac.com/playaboard
also offer information about these areas, plus Akumal, Tankah and
more. Both sites have good message boards where travelers can post
questions and comments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
