<P>
   NFL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DAVIS-ANDERSON _ Within a two-week period last season, the
Falcons lost Jamal Anderson and the Broncos lost Terrell Davis to
serious knee injuries. They spent the next 9-11 months in grueling
rehab. They talked on a regular basis and Sunday they will meet on
the same field as they both try to return to form, although Davis
sprained an ankle in the opener. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-SC-GA _ The much improved South Carolina Gamecocks seem
prepared to play Georgia. (Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-IRISH-HUSKERS _ A look at the Notre Dame-Nebraska matchup
this Saturday. (Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HUSKIES _ Washington QB Marques Tuiasosopo
</P>
<P>
   is the latest in a long line of Samoan relatives who starred in
college and the NFL. (Capozzi, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS
</P>
<P>
   TEN-US-OPEN _ Coverage of the U.S. Open. (Holcomb, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-OPEN-STODA _ Column from the U.S. Open,
</P>
<P>
   advancing Hingis-Venus. (Stoda, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-AMERICANS _ More than 600 athletes will march into Olympic
Stadium in Sydney under the American flag. Two dozen of those
athletes were born outside the U.S. , but moved here to live, train
and further their athletic careers. (Tierney, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OTHER
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-FOOD _ Want to play like the pros? Then model your diet
after theirs. Kick the caffeine, beef up the beef and consume
carbohydrates in moderation. And it doesn't matter whether you're a
duffer on the links, or a cyclist who regularly rides 100 miles _
food is your fuel, and it must be maintained. WITH ART. (Norris,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-RECIPES _ Recipes that have benefits specific to an
athlete's needs. A varied diet is important to everyone. (Norris,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in lifestyle (l) category
</P>
<P>
   E-SPORTS _ A daily column featuring the most useful Web sites
and live online events affecting Sports fans. Today: (Greene,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This is the CoxNet INSIDE NASCAR page for the week. The
layout will be available Thursday before 3 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET INSIDE NASCAR 0908: SAFETY ON THE TRACK -- All it took to
get safety back to the forefront was for the Winston Cup points
leader to hit the wall with a stuck throttle. Bobby Labonte hit the
wall in his primary car on the Friday before last week's race at
Darlington. Drivers who normally shy away from talking about safety
are calling on NASCAR to make changes to cars and to the track at
New Hampshire where Adam Petty and Kenny Irwin died in crashes
earlier this year. Winston Cup returns to New Hampshire in two
weeks. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
