<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ESTATE-TAX08-COX     09-07 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE UPHOLDS ESTATE TAX VETO, BUT GOP CLAIMS IT AS CAMPAIGN
ISSUE
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a vote fraught with political overtones, the
House failed Thursday to override President Clinton's veto of a
bill to phase out the federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   The 274-157 vote fell 14 short of the two-thirds of those
present required to override a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and House Democrats invoked party unity to protect the
president's record of only two veto overrides since Republicans
took control in 1995, and none during the current Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen Democrats who had supported phasing out the tax when
the bill was first approved by the House switched their votes
Thursday to support Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On the final vote, 155 Democrats sided with Clinton, along with
one Republican and one independent. Voting to override were 53
Democrats, 220 Republicans and one independent.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said they planned to wait until the next
Congress _ when they hope Gov. George W. Bush of Texas will be
president _ to try again.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders also indicated they expected the estate tax to be a
major campaign issue this fall, particularly for those Democrats
who switched their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this will be part of the campaign. We'll let the
American people decide by their own votes,'' said Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas. ``If the American people really want this tax
relief, we'll have a Republican Congress with a Republican
president who will sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax vote was the first of two showcase tax votes
scheduled this month. Next week, the House will try to override
Clinton's veto of the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' which causes
some married couples to pay higher income taxes than they would if
they were single and filed separately.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the vote, calling the repeal bill ``a huge tax
cut for the most well-off Americans'' that threatened the nation's
economic health and critical government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that the estate tax repeal would benefit only 2
percent of the wealthiest taxpayers while jeopardizing the
projected federal surplus and efforts to shore up Medicare and
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have reduced government revenues by $105 billion
over the next 10 years, and $50 billion a year when fully
implemented in 2011. A Democratic alternative would cost $22
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans portrayed Thursday's vote as a referendum on what
Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., called an ``unfair, immoral and
unsound tax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The death tax penalizes families who have worked hard and
saved all their lives,'' said Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas. ``We don't
need a toll booth on the way to Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats responded that Republicans were engaged in a
``political ploy'' by pushing a bill they knew would not become law
while ignoring the Democratic alternative, which they said would
eliminate the estate tax on family farms and businesses worth up to
$4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., asked Republican lawmakers to
support the veto and then work on a compromise tax bill in the
waning days of the session.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still time for us to work together on this and other
matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP lawmakers complained that the Democratic plan, which
relied on raising the limit on a tax exemption, was too complex for
most taxpayers to use. They said the only way to overcome that
hurdle would be to eliminate the tax entirely.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said Republicans would not ``play games'' with the estate
tax and said Democrats were not serious about wanting to lower
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president doesn't want tax relief, he wants to keep this
money in Washington so he can spend it, and (Vice President Al)
Gore is the same way,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. House of Representatives: www.house.gov
</P>
<P>
   Estate tax opponents: www.deathtax.com
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
