</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0908-COX     09-07 2512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH BACKS OFF ON DEBATE STANCE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush backed down Thursday from his refusal to
participate in more than one formal presidential debate, and said
he now is willing to negotiate the question with Al Gore. ``I want
there to be debates. . . . As to what they look like and where they
are, it'll be worked out in due course,'' Bush said. Earlier, Bush
had said he'd participate in only one of the three debates proposed
by the nonpartisan debates commission, and he wanted to add more
informal debates on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and CNN's ``Larry King
Live.'' Gore said he'd appear at the latter two, but only after
Bush commits to all three commission debates. Asked today if he
might agree to more than one commission debate, Bush said, ``Yeah.
. . . We'll work it out. . . . I made a serious attempt to find
some interesting formats.''
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY AND POLITICAL REINFORCEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by retired generals Colin Powell and Norman Schwarzkopf,
George W. Bush promised a ``culture of innovation'' in modernizing
the military through investment in technology. Powell likened
problems in the military to a spreading cancer that Bush could
cure. Readiness and enlistments have dropped, he said, and the
Democrats have failed to prepare the military for post-Cold War
challenges. ``Our enemies start noticing (and) before you know it
you're on a path downward,'' Powell told hundreds of veterans today
at Wright State University in Dayton, Ohio. ``That little cancer
starts to break out in the body of the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: TOO SOON TO JUMP OUT OF FOXHOLE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, reacting to supporters' concerns, said Thursday
he would try to energize his campaign by ``putting faces to
policy'' in events featuring everyday Americans. But he also said
some backers seemed to be getting too jittery too soon after Al
Gore's comeback in recent polls. ``That's Washington,'' said Bush.
``That's the place where you find people getting ready to jump out
of the foxholes before the first shot is fired.'' Bush campaign
officials liken the rising nervousness among party leaders to fears
expressed last winter after Bush lost the New Hampshire primary to
John McCain. They suggest this current angst, too, will pass.
</P>
<P>
   GORE: BUSH'S PROMISES TOO EXPENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has followed up his 191-page budget blueprint with a New
York Times ad today attacking his rival's tax and spending plans.
Gore argues that George W. Bush's proposed tax cuts would enrich
the wealthy, use up the surplus and push the budget back into
deficit. ``Does it matter if the numbers all add up?'' the new ad
says. Gore argues that tax cuts pushed by Bush would cost the
Treasury $1.3 trillion over 10 years, or $1.6 trillion including
lost interest. In addition, Gore says, new spending pushed by Bush
would drain an additional $474 billion. Plus, says Gore, the
missile defense program pushed by Bush would register ``at a
minimum of $150 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: GORE'S PROMISES TOO EXPENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush opened a new line of attack against Al Gore,
accusing his rival of making so many promises in this campaign that
he would eat through the entire $4.6 trillion federal surplus
projected for the next decade. Bush dismissed the new economic plan
that Gore announced as an emblem of big government ``overcharging
the working people. If I might summarize it for you, it says keep
sending all your money to Washington, and I'll be glad to spend it
for you,'' Bush shouted at an airport rally in Indianapolis. ``And
spend it he can. This man knows how to spend that money.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE UP BY 6 IN LATEST POLL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore leads George W. Bush by 6 percentage points, according
to a new Reuters/Zogby poll released Thursday. The poll of 1,001
likely voters conducted for Reuters on Monday through Wednesday by
independent pollster John Zogby showed Gore leading Bush by 46
percent to 40 percent. Green Party candidate Ralph Nader polled 5
percent and the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan scored 2 percent. Seven
percent were undecided. In a two-man matchup. Gore led 49-43
percent. Gore's lead was still near the edge of the poll's
statistical margin of error of 3.2 percent, but the survey
confirmed that Gore has kept the bounce he received from last
month's Democratic convention and added to it.
</P>
<P>
   GORE EXPECTING TEAMSTERS' NOD
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore expects to receive the highly coveted presidential
endorsement of the Teamsters today, and the considerable
get-out-the-vote manpower that comes with it. The Teamsters,
because of the union's fierce opposition to Gore's free-trade
advocacy, which George W. Bush shares, have been a holdout while
other major unions endorsed the vice president long ago. Teamsters
head James P. Hoffa has flirted with the idea of endorsing Bush,
and the union has backed Republicans in the past: Ronald Reagan in
1980 and 1984, and ex-President Bush in 1988. The Teamsters jumped
to Bill Clinton in 1992 but abstained from endorsing in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVITY RISES AS POLL STANDING DROPS
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign for the White House intensifies, George W.
Bush's upbeat messages are being replaced by hard-hitting digs at
his Democratic opposition. Republicans in key states welcomed the
change in tactics, saying swing voters care whether Al Gore is
being straight with them. They also hope the new focus on Gore's
credibility will help Bush regain the lead from Gore. ``Most
campaigns would like to have the luxury of staying positive, but in
order to stay positive you've got to stay significantly ahead in
the polls,'' said Tom Slade, former chairman of the Florida
Republican Party. ``In races that get close _ and this one
obviously has _ the knives are going to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   APOLOGIES TO DISABLED REPORTER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign has apologized to a disabled reporter denied
access to a Gore campaign stop in Michigan over the weekend. The
General Motors plant Gore visited and the buses transporting media
members to the site were inaccessible by wheelchair. While Flint
Journal reporter Chad Swiatecki, 22, was able to cover an earlier
stop made by Gore, arrangements had to be made by the newspaper to
send another reporter to the second stop. ``I got angry when the
state campaign director tried to smooth things over,'' said
Swiatecki. ``But he really wasn't sympathetic or apologetic about
what happened. The only response I got was, `We've never run into
this before.' `` Swiatecki said he has since received a call from
Kim Ruby, a Gore spokeswoman, who apologized to him for the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   UNCERTAIN DEBATE SCHEDULE COSTLY
</P>
<P>
   The costs of preparing for a presidential debate are mounting,
even though it is increasingly uncertain whether the event will
take place on Oct. 3. University of Massachusetts officials are
about to sign a contract for electrical work that will cost between
$120,000 and $165,000. And unless the Commission on Presidential
Debates pulls the plug _ which it said it doesn't want to do _ the
university will soon face having to sign a contract to complete the
production work needed to accommodate the press and nationally
televise a debate. That is expected to cost between $250,000 and
$400,000. All that would come on top of $250,000 the university has
already laid out for infrastructure improvements and other
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER DEBATE, ANOTHER DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   As the spat over the presidential debates plays out, House and
Senate Democratic leaders are churning up their own election year
debate controversy on Capitol Hill. Several months ago, the two
leaders _ Rep. Dick Gephardt and Sen. Tom Daschle _ challenged
House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
to a debate on ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'' Oct. 15. The
Republicans declined, saying they were too busy and couldn't plan
that far ahead. This week, Gephardt dashed off a letter to Hastert,
saying he was disappointed that Hastert would not participate in a
discussion of major campaign issues. John Feehery, Hastert's press
secretary, said the speaker was busy doing his job. ``He is a
legislator, not a debater,'' Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN FIGHTING FOR PLACE AT DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   As the Bush-Gore sparring over debates continued, Reform Party
hopeful Pat Buchanan's legal fight to be included in the debates
made its way to a federal courtroom in Washington. Buchanan's
lawyers asked District Court Judge Richard Roberts to essentially
reverse a Federal Election Commission ruling and mandate Buchanan's
participation in any debates run by the bipartisan debates
commission. Under commission rules, participants must garner an
average of 15 percent popular support in five major polls. Buchanan
lawyer John Duffy argued in part that the commission is not
``non-partisan,'' but rather a bipartisan group protecting the
interests of the major parties.
</P>
<P>
   CHASING THE FEDERAL FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential hopeful John Hagelin has filed papers
with federal election officials laying claim to $12.6 million
reserved for the party's nominee. Hagelin officials said the forms,
filed Friday with the Federal Election Commission, reflect that he
is on the ballot in 11 states as the party's candidate for
president. Election law requires a ``minor party'' candidate
seeking federal funding to certify they are on the ballot in at
least 10 states. The FEC has 10 days after all the necessary papers
are filed to issue a ruling. Pat Buchanan, who also claims the
party nomination, filed similar documents a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   NADER: STILL UNSAFE AT ANY SPEED
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, who wrote the 1965 book ``Unsafe at Any Speed''
that criticized automakers for putting profits ahead of safety,
showed up at a congressional hearing on defective Firestone tires,
but didn't address the lawmakers. Instead, the Green Party's
presidential nominee spoke to reporters in the hallway outside,
saying not much has changed in the past 35 years. Nader said he is
convinced that Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. and Ford Motor Co., which
uses the recalled tires as standard equipment on its vehicles,
covered up defects that led to deaths and injuries. He called for a
change in the law so company executives can be criminally charged
for withholding such information.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN CLEARED TO SEEK TWO OFFICES
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Elections Enforcement Commission confirmed that
Joe Lieberman can run simultaneously for the vice presidency and
re-election to the Senate. The panel's general counsel, Jeffrey
Garfield, rejected the complaint of Fairfield University politics
professor John Orman, who said Lieberman's re-election campaign was
``frivolous'' and ``irresponsibly self-indulgent'' and urged that
he be eliminated from the Senate ballot. If elected to both
offices, Lieberman would have to resign from the Senate to serve as
vice president, and Republican Gov. John Rowland would appoint a
replacement to serve until the next statewide election in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY CONTRASTS THE TAX CUT PLANS
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, in a speech before the Chamber of Commerce in
Wilmington, Del., drew a distinction between who would benefit
under Al Gore's tax cut plan and who would get relief under George
W. Bush's proposal. ``Al Gore will give tax relief if you have
solar panels on your roof or if you drive a battery powered
automobile,'' Cheney said during a 45 minute talk _ among the
longest he's given in five weeks of campaigning. Families with a
mother who stays home with the children get nothing, he asserted.
``You ought to have a tax system that doesn't discriminate one way
or another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS ENDS UP WITH BIGGER SURPLUS
</P>
<P>
   Texas ended its fiscal year with $45 million more in the bank
than July estimates showed, pushing its surplus to $1.45 billion,
the state comptroller said. The state's budget became a
presidential campaign issue in July when a legislative report
projected that $610 million in cost overruns in some programs would
cut into the surplus. Some Texas Democrats blamed the overruns on a
$1.7 billion tax cut that Gov. George W. Bush advocated and signed
into law in 1998. Legislators said the newly announced surplus
would more than cover any excess spending. The state ended its
fiscal year Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   JERSEY AGAIN OVERSHADOWED BY NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   The Hillary Clinton-Rick Lazio battle so dominates the focus of
voters throughout northern New Jersey that it could become a key
factor in the contest for the Senate seat of retiring Democrat
Frank Lautenberg. Turn on any television in north Jersey and it's
hard to miss the barrage of ads drawing attention to the nationally
watched New York Senate race. After a summer-long run of ads, vast
numbers of New Jersey residents have been captivated by the
high-profile campaign so much so, in fact, that the home-state
contest between Democrat financier Jon Corzine and Republican Rep.
Bob Franks has been registering barely a mention at dinner tables
and cocktail parties north of Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   NO LOITERING NEAR BUSH RANCH
</P>
<P>
   It will harder to get a long look at George W. Bush's new Texas
ranch. McLennan County commissioners have restricted traffic near
the 1,600-acre spread, banning parking or even stopping along about
three miles of roadway. The restrictions came at the request of the
Secret Service, which was concerned about media and tourists
impeding traffic in the rural area near Waco. ``It's a public
safety issue,'' said County Commissioner Ray Meadows. Commissioners
also are considering establishing a 40-mph speed limit in the area,
which has no posted speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   GORE TAKES THE MOUND, BUT DOESN'T GET SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore thought about hiding behind his Secret Service agents,
but was soon enough strutting his stuff in a charmed outing with
the Detroit Tigers. ``A lot better than a lot of broken-down former
pitchers that I've seen,'' Anaheim Angels pitcher Tim Belcher said
as Gore threw batting practice for the Tigers an hour before the
two teams met. Even hitter Robert Fick, after getting whacked in
the hip by Gore's lone wild pitch, was impressed: ``He's definitely
not making (a fool) out of himself.'' Autograph seekers mobbed the
rookie star on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   A HARLEY, NOT A TANK
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman, a senator normally known for quiet demeanor,
donned a motorcycle helmet and took a quick spin on the back of a
Harley-Davidson. Lieberman spent some time answering questions from
workers on a motorcycle assembly line in Kansas City, Mo. Then,
with his motorcade waiting, the jeans-clad Lieberman got on the
back of a green Harley driven by an employee and waved to reporters
and employees as they circled the parking lot. He later
acknowledged that ``there was some pressure'' not to ride by aides
who feared a repetition of the ridicule Michael Dukakis got when he
put on a helmet and rode in a tank during his presidential campaign
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
