<HEADER>
A5351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CANADA-PUPPET-THEATER     09-07 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PUPPET-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESUS MAY PULL THE STRINGS, BUT THIS MARIONETTE HAS OTHER IDEAS
</HEADLINE>
  By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there any relationship so intimate as that between a puppet
and its master? Whether controlled by hand, strings or sticks,
puppets are famous for providing bolder alter egos for those who
manipulate them. ``My Puppet, Myself'' could easily be a subtitle
for everything from the cheery television shows of Shari Lewis to
those homicidal ventriloquist movies that show up every decade or
so.
</P>
<P>
   As portraits of divided selves, however, these are all quite
mild compared to the spectacle presented toward the end of Ronnie
Burkett's ``Street of Blood,'' the ambitious, exhaustingly told
tale of anger and intolerance in rural Canada, now at the New York
Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   In that scene, Burkett, the puppeteer, is Jesus Christ; the
marionette at the end of the strings he is pulling is a movie star
who suggests a cross between Katharine Hepburn and the demented
Norma Desmond. She is also a vampire, and she craves a taste of
Jesus' blood. ``Let me know your pain,'' says the gnarled,
bespangled creature, less than half Burkett's size, as she hungrily
crawls up his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Before you cry ``Sacrilege!'' on the one hand or ``Far out!'' on
the other, you should know that ``Street of Blood,'' part of the
Henson International Festival of Puppet Theater, has a heart as
pious and platitudinous as that of its narrator, an apple-cheeked,
gray-haired farmer's wife who describes herself as ``a silly old
biddy in a Sears housedress.''
</P>
<P>
   That one-person encounter between Jesus and the Hollywood
Antichrist is bizarre enough to make you sit up in your seat for a
moment and consider just what makes Burkett tick. The odds are also
that during the more than two hours leading up to that scene, you
have found yourself slumping toward the floor more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett is a obviously a man of high-reaching ideas, many
talents and amazing stamina; his touring Theater of Marionettes,
based in Alberta, has previously considered subjects like the
Holocaust. He has created all the puppets in this 14-character
play, as well as their many elaborate costumes and the show's set;
and he pulls the strings and provides the voices for every one of
them, visibly assisted by only his stage manager, Terri Gillis.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he has written a script that addresses the
theological implications of AIDS, the destructiveness of the gay
anger bred by homophobia and the dangers of identifying with the
heroines of old movies. Unfortunately, this is all presented with a
patient, smiling preachiness, an attitude one associates with
aspiringly groovy ministers hoping to recruit young congregation
members. The marionettes wind up seeming like little more than a
lure, the candy coating on the pill.
</P>
<P>
   The show is centered on the relationship between the gentle,
good Edna Rural and Eden, her defiantly gay son, who grew up
idolizing one Esme Massengill, star of stage, screen and
bloodsucking. Both Esme and Jesus show up for a showdown in the
little town of Turnip Corners, battling for the souls of the
conflicted Rurals. Though Edna has a few reprimands for Jesus for
neglecting his flock, it's not hard to predict who will win.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute drag queens for puppets and take away the Christian
angle, and ``Street of Blood'' starts to look awfully familiar,
like Charles Busch's ``Vampire Lesbians of Sodom'' stripped of its
wicked irony. Mercifully, there are the puppets, and if you focus
on them instead of what they're saying, ``Street of Blood'' is
easier to take.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the finely detailed appearances of the
marionettes that astonishes; it is also Burkett's ability to endow
them with such physical eloquence. A seemingly simple twitch of the
strings, and these characters deliver gestures and assume postures
more expressively human than much of what's offered by live actors
in Broadway musicals these days.
</P>
<P>
   The overture for ``Street of Blood'' is ostensibly provided by a
sextet called the Turnip Corners Ladies Orchestrale. How each of
these musicians simulates playing her instrument, from piano to
clarinet, is a wonder. Even more so is how each commands the stage
with her own character-defining walk. Burkett's marionettes are
clearly talented performers. Now if only they could find the right
script. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STREET OF BLOOD'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created and performed by Ronnie Burkett; music and sound by
Cathy Nosaty; lighting by Bill Williams; marionette, sets and
costumes by Burkett; production stage manager, Terri Gillis. The
Rink-A-Dink Inc. production of Ronnie Burkett Theater of
Marionettes. Part of the Henson International Festival of Puppet
Theater. At the New York Theater Workshop in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
