<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN ADAPTS WELL TO HIS CAMPAIGN ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ On a day the Democrats devoted to trumpeting
their economic goals, Vice President Al Gore, speaking in
Cleveland, never mentioned the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But in a speech on the same topic Wednesday, here at Southwest
Missouri State University, Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, spoke in dire terms of the economic plans of Gov. George
W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee. Bush's proposals
would ``send us back down the drain of deficits, rising interest
rates and rising unemployment,'' he said, and would ``cause tremors
across the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has adopted the traditional role of the No. 2, taking
the lead in attacking the opposition, allowing Gore to remain, if
not above the fray, then less deeply mired in it. At every stop,
Lieberman vows not to make personal attacks on Bush and his running
mate, Dick Cheney, and so far he has not. But he has not hesitated
to tear into their policies and strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running around signing a book of blank checks drawn on an
account that his tax cuts have already depleted,'' Lieberman said
Wednesday of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, he lit into Bush much more strongly than Gore
did for refusing to take part in two of the three debates proposed
by a bipartisan commission, stopping just short of accusing Bush of
being afraid to debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Governor Bush is making an end run around the
established rules of presidential debates,'' he said. ``It's like
one of the teams in the Super Bowl, a few weeks before the Super
Bowl, saying, `I don't want to play in that city, I don't want to
play by those rules, and I don't want to play in front of so many
people.'''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic campaign officials acknowledge the difference between
Lieberman's approach and Gore's, but say it is not a result of any
grand strategy. ``It's what they're comfortable with,'' one aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGNING HIGH ON A HOG
</P>
<P>
   This is how politicians are different from ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two weeks, Medicare has been front and center in
the national campaign. There have been days when the Democrats,
especially, have talked about little else. So it must have come as
a bit of a surprise to Lieberman when he took questions Wednesday
from workers at a Harley-Davidson motorcycle factory in Kansas
City, Mo., and the first query, from a young man, was this: ``I
notice none of you guys who are running are talking about
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary mortals might have grown agitated, but Lieberman
resisted the temptation. Instead, he gently corrected the
misimpression and reiterated the points he and Vice President Gore
have made dozens of times in dozens of places.
</P>
<P>
   The senator seemed a bit out of place on the factory floor, a
situation he either missed or gamely ignored. Harley workers, it
turns out, look a lot like Harley riders, with a sizable quotient
of black T-shirts over jeans, beards, ponytails, sunglasses worn
indoors, and people who generally looked like they might be
auditioning for ZZ Top.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, in jeans and a blue dress shirt, took it all in
stride, and even went for a spin around the parking lot on the back
of a hog driven by a company employee _ while wearing a helmet, of
course. When it was noted that Michael Dukakis' image suffered when
he was seen wearing a helmet _ in his case, while driving a tank _
during the 1988 presidential campaign, Lieberman said: ``It was
another act of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a new fantasy,'' he told a reporter. ``I want to buy a
Harley-Davidson.''
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING TO GRIN AND BEAR IT
</P>
<P>
   When Vice President Gore picked Lieberman as his running mate,
the focus _ both in the media and in the senator's own comments _
was on his being the first Jew to be nominated by a major party for
national office.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Lieberman has shifted somewhat away from the topic, but
others raise it so often that he could not drop it completely if he
wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   At the motorcycle plant, a woman asked him how, if he became
president, his religion would influence the selection of Supreme
Court justices. (He said his Judaism ``doesn't specifically relate
to these kinds of decisions.'') On Monday, Sen. Richard Durbin,
introducing Lieberman at a union hall in Peoria, Ill., said the
Democrats had ``been the first to open the door of opportunity,''
citing John F. Kennedy, Geraldine Ferraro, ``and now, Joe
Lieberman, the first Jewish American to be nominated.''
</P>
<P>
   This theme has also led to some of the campaign's more awkward
moments. At a rally in Claymont, Del., late last month, Sen. Joseph
Biden pointed into the audience and said to Lieberman: ``Joe, you
see that woman over there? She's Jewish, you're Jewish, we're
Catholic. But I say no purgatory for her. Straight to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator's smile never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   EVOKING AN UNPOPULAR WAR
</P>
<P>
   At every stop, Lieberman mentions that Gore ``volunteered for
service in Vietnam.'' It seems an odd tribute, given that both Gore
and Lieberman opposed U.S. involvement in the war, as did tens of
millions of other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But the line always draws hearty applause. And this mostly from
crowds of Democrats, people who, presumably, would be less inclined
than Republicans to view the war favorably. It is, if nothing else,
a sign of America's continued ambivalence about the war, three
decades later.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schmidt, a 49-year-old construction worker who heard
Lieberman speak at a Labor Day festival in Detroit on Monday, said
he was opposed to the war when it was under way and has not changed
his views. But he cheered loudly at the mention of Gore's tour in
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``He served his country, and you've got to respect that,'' said
Schmidt, who escaped the draft by having a high lottery number.
``If he didn't go, someone else would have went, like me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
