<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MEDIA-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TYCOON VOWS TO KEEP KREMLIN FROM GAINING CONTROL OF TV
NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's most flamboyant tycoon aggravated a standoff
with President Vladimir Putin late Thursday by announcing, as
promised, that he is giving away his dominant stake in the nation's
largest television network rather than surrender it to Kremlin
control.
</P>
<P>
   Or almost, anyway. The tycoon, Boris Berezovsky, said at a news
conference that he was putting his shares in the network, ORT, in
trust for the next four years, splitting control among a host of
national journalistic and cultural figures. If their stewardship is
successful, he said, he will give them a 20 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   But Berezovsky did not define success, or specify how the
network's new stewards, a group he is still choosing, would manage
the empire.
</P>
<P>
   That left outsiders still wondering whether Berezovsky was just
parrying in a continuing power struggle with Putin or sincerely
working to prevent a government takeover of Russia's free press, or
both.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky offered another reason. ``I am tired, tired, tired,''
he said at a news conference. ``It seems to me that alone, I simply
cannot carry any longer this load called ORT.''
</P>
<P>
   ORT _ the initials stand for Russian Public Television _ is
nominally government-run. But nobody doubts that Berezovsky, who
controls at least 49 percent of its shares, really pulls its
strings.
</P>
<P>
   In parliamentary elections last winter, he wielded it as a club
on behalf of friends within the Kremlin who were promoting Putin as
the successor to President Boris Yeltsin. With ORT's help, Putin's
Unity Party destroyed its opposition, setting the stage for
Yeltsin's surprise resignation and the spring election of Putin to
a full four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin and Berezovsky have since parted ways. Berezovsky, who
himself gained election to parliament, abruptly quit the
legislature this spring to organize a political opposition to the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has opened his own attack against Berezovsky and other
tycoons, focusing government investigators on their business
empires in what seems to be a campaign of intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how much of a role Putin's ill-concealed
contempt for the news media plays in that campaign. Days after his
inauguration as president in May, masked police raided the offices
of one often-critical press baron, Vladimir Gusinsky, and shortly
afterward jailed him. A criminal investigation later was abruptly
dropped amid rumors, strongly denied, that Gusinsky had cut a deal
with the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Putin has cast the Kremlin's actions as an attempt
to free Russia from the grip of rapacious monopolists. In
particular, he has suggested that Russia's news media are not truly
free because they speak for the rich instead of the ordinary
people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Putin has yet to say whether he thinks the government is better
qualified to run the news media in the name of ordinary people.
When the government's proposed budget for the next fiscal year was
released this week, for the first time there was a ``top secret''
classification stamped on all expenditures involving the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   The public has no love for Berezovsky or other media titans. Any
number of Russian commentators charge that the tycoons amassed
their fortunes through shady deals at the expense of ordinary
Russians, and that they use their media holdings mostly to protect
their own interests.
</P>
<P>
   For Berezovsky, the last straw appears to have been a demand by
the Kremlin this month that he hand over his stake in ORT or suffer
Gusinsky's fate.
</P>
<P>
   At his briefing on Thursday, Berezovsky listed 14 men and women
who he said had accepted his offer to be ORT trustees, and another
nine who apparently had yet to respond. They include some of the
best known and most respected figures in Russian journalism, from
newspaper editors and columnists to authors and television anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky said none of the trustees would be financially
responsible for the network, which is reported to have lost money.
And he said he was considering a similar plan for his other media
holdings, which include Moscow's most powerful business daily
newspaper, Kommersant, and a stake in a popular Moscow television
channel, TV6.
</P>
<P>
   While some dismissed the move as a public-relations ploy,
Berezovsky said he was acting to prevent Putin from further
consolidating control over Russian politics and society.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin already controls one major network, RTR. Control of
Gusinsky's NTV network is in some doubt, leaving ORT as the only
network with national reach that is outside the Kremlin's control.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has neither confirmed nor denied that it has issued
an ultimatum to Berezovsky. One official said the government had no
objection to Berezovsky's plan to distribute his shares in ORT,
providing it was not a sham deal to cover his continued control.
</P>
</TEXT>
