<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-ANNAPOLIS-TRAVEL-ART-     09-07 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNAPOLIS-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CRAB GETS A SALUTE WITH THE NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 6,7,8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD RUDA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. _ For such a small town, Annapolis (pop. 33,000)
has an astonishing array of personalities.
</P>
<P>
   To military types and sports fans, Annapolis is the U.S. Naval
Academy. To architecture lovers, it is a charming 18th-century town
built on a late 17th-century Baroque street plan. To history buffs,
it has been the capital of Maryland for 300 years and was briefly
the capital of the United States. To recreational boaters, it is
among the premier sailing centers on the Eastern Seaboard, its
waterfront thronged with pleasure craft. And to just about anyone,
it is a perfect place to savor Maryland's singular contribution to
Western civilization, the steamed hard-shelled crab.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all for weekend visitors, Annapolis' numerous
attractions are within a 15-minute walk of one another. Like many
tourists, I was drawn to Annapolis by its 18th-century buildings
and by the Naval Academy, a fascinating and surprisingly
visitor-friendly place. Because Annapolis' Colonial homes and
gardens are open longer on Saturdays than on Sundays, I toured them
first, then the Naval Academy, ending my visit at the historic
State House.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting Colonial houses in Annapolis are a product
of its ``golden age'' in the 1760s and 1770s, a period whose spirit
was neatly captured by Jonathan Boucher, the rector of St. Anne's
Church in town at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the genteelest town in North America, and many of its
inhabitants were highly respectable, as to station, fortune and
education,'' he later wrote. There was ``hardly a town in England
so desirable to live in as Annapolis then was,'' he added. ``It was
the seat of government, and the residence of the governor, and all
the great officers of state, as well as of the most eminent
lawyers, physicians and families of opulence and note.''
</P>
<P>
   I walked to the intersection of Maryland Avenue and King George
Street and was magically transported to Boucher's Annapolis. Before
me were two of the grandest mansions of that golden age: The
Hammond-Harwood House and the Chase-Lloyd House. Both completed in
1774, they reflect the genius of William Buckland (1734-74), who
immigrated to Virginia from England as an indentured servant in
1755 but ultimately became one of the Colonies' most distinguished
architects.
</P>
<P>
   The Hammond-Harwood House is a classic example of the five-part
Anglo-Palladian brick mansion popular in America before the
Revolution. Other late Colonial houses may be larger or more
ornate, but none, I think, is more perfect. The Maryland Avenue
facade of the house exemplifies the qualities of
Anglo-Palladianism: Balance, elegance, coolness, understatement
and, above all, flawless proportions. The exquisite front door,
writes G.E. Kidder Smith in his ``Source Book of American
Architecture,'' ranks ``as one of the finest in U.S. Georgian
architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckland's manifold gifts are equally evident inside. The rooms
of the Hammond-Harwood House are not only flawlessly proportioned,
but also, because Buckland had apprenticed in England as a joiner,
contain superbly decorated woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Revolutionary War, Samuel Chase was a young,
ambitious Annapolis lawyer and land speculator. The historian
Norman Risjord called him ``an ardent patriot'' whose ``political
philosophy always seemed to coincide with his own interests.''
Chase later signed the Declaration of Independence and served with
great distinction on the Supreme Court, even though he is best
known today as the only member ever to be impeached. (He was
readily acquitted of the politically motivated charges against
him.)
</P>
<P>
   Chase began building his Annapolis town house in 1769. The
towering three-story mansion he planned was intended to proclaim
his ascendance from humble origins to Maryland's professional
elite.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Chase (but luckily for today's tourists), he
soon ran out of money. Remarkably, he married a woman of modest
means and sold the unfinished house, then a brick shell, to one of
the wealthiest men in Maryland, Edward Lloyd IV. In December 1771,
Lloyd contracted with Buckland to complete it.
</P>
<P>
   The parts of the Chase-Lloyd House designed by Buckland and open
to visitors are a stunning progression of essays in Anglo-Palladian
design. The Palladian front door opens into a front entrance hall
graced by a screen of Ionic columns inspired by one of Palladio's
drawings of Roman baths. Beyond the screen is a majestic
double-cantilevered stair. An oversize Palladian window looking out
on the garden dominates the landing. The stair culminates at the
second-floor hall with its finely decorated plaster ceiling and two
niches flanking a pedimented door.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL MATERIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On Prince George Street, one block south of Maryland Avenue, is
the William Paca House and Garden. Paca (pronounced PAY-cah) was a
contemporary of Chase and, like him, a lawyer and Patriot leader
who signed the Declaration of Independence. Unlike Chase, Paca had
the good sense to marry one of the wealthiest women in the Colony,
Mary Chew. Four days later he bought a prime double lot in the
center of Annapolis, with ample room for a huge house and an
expansive garden.
</P>
<P>
   Paca's house, an imposing five-part brick mansion of 1765 he
probably designed himself, is well worth visiting. The principal
attraction here, however, is the superb two-acre Paca garden.
</P>
<P>
   Due to the vicissitudes of time _ the house served for many
years as the entry to a large hotel and the garden as a parking lot
_ the garden of today is only partly a restoration of Paca's
showplace. The upper half is a conjectural formal garden consisting
of four parterres: Elegant compositions of roses, mixed flowers,
hollies and topiaries. The lower half is a reconstruction, based on
historical evidence, of the ``natural'' portion of Paca's garden.
The sophisticated Paca had combined the French formalism that still
dominated garden design in the Colonies with the naturalism then in
vogue in England.
</P>
<P>
   The garden is full of lovely plantings, outbuildings and
decorative elements, like the charming summerhouse and a
Chinese-style bridge over a pond. Urns copied from the garden of
the poet Alexander Pope at Twickenham, near London, are a splendid
touch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; END OPTIONAL MATERIAL &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday I turned from Annapolis' golden age to the sights,
sounds, history and beauty of the Naval Academy. It was founded
here in 1845 and has occupied a magnificent site on the Severn
River almost uninterruptedly ever since. (During the Civil War it
was moved to Newport, R.I., to put it beyond the reach of
Secessionists in southern Maryland and Virginia; in 1865 it was
nearly relocated to Perth Amboy.)
</P>
<P>
   The academy is the undergraduate professional college of the
Navy, with a 4,000-member Brigade of Midshipmen. During the
academic year midshipmen study at the Annapolis campus, but summers
after the first year are spent at sea and in other off-campus
training. Upon graduation, each becomes an officer in the Navy or
Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   I began my visit at the excellent visitors' center, where I saw
an enticing film about the academy and exhibits about its history,
the life of midshipmen, and famous graduates. I then strolled into
the central part of the academy's campus, the Yard.
</P>
<P>
   The Flagg buildings are in three main groups. The first contains
Bancroft Hall (an immense building, repeatedly enlarged, that is
still the academy's only dormitory), Memorial Hall (a majestic
pavilion that is reached by the grand entrance and ceremonial
stairway of Bancroft Hall) and Dahlgren and MacDonough Halls, which
Flagg designed to be the academy's armory and boathouse. Directly
across the Yard is what remains of Flagg's academic grouping, the
main component of which is Mahan Hall, once the library, with a
striking facade and clock tower.
</P>
<P>
   Flagg's finest building at the academy is the chapel. Based on
Jules Hardouin-Mansard's Dome des Invalides in Paris, the burial
place of Napoleon, the chapel is a beautiful building inside and
out, despite a competent but distorting addition of 1940 by Paul
Philippe Cret. (Because of the addition, the best view of the
Chapel's exterior is from the intersection of Porter and Buchanan
Roads, a hundred feet to the south.)
</P>
<P>
   Several of the buildings in the Yard are open to visitors. The
most interesting ones, architecturally speaking, are the work of
Ernest Flagg (1857-1947), a brilliant, dedicated and protean New
York City architect who was (among other things) one of America's
greatest practitioners in the Beaux-Arts style.
</P>
<P>
   Beaux-Arts architecture was a turn-of-the-century movement
centered on the Ecole des Beaux-Arts in Paris, where Flagg was an
outstanding student in the 1880s. Flagg's buildings at the Naval
Academy, constructed between 1899 and 1908, instantly made me a
convert. They show in the best light the hallmarks of the
Beaux-Arts style: Intense rationality, clarity, monumentality,
meticulous use of decorative elements, and the dramatic and
purposeful ordering of interior spaces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The interior of the chapel holds much Tiffany stained glass on
historical themes as well as a magnificent dome. In the chapel's
crypt are the remains and fascinating memorabilia of John Paul
Jones, Revolutionary War hero and ``father of the United States
Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   My last stop at the Naval Academy is a great place for children:
The Academy Museum. The main floor offers a wonderful jumble of old
photographs, ship paintings, swords, medals and memorabilia of the
academy and of early naval heroes as well as a modern exhibition on
the Navy's history from the Spanish-American War of 1898 to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   The basement houses the academy's trove of 17th- and
18th-century English wooden ship models, one of the two largest
collections in the world. (The other is in the National Maritime
Museum in Greenwich, England.) The models are both precious
artifacts and works of breathtaking craftsmanship. One of the most
remarkable models in the collection is that of the Grafton,
completed in 1679, which may once have belonged to my all-time
hero, Samuel Pepys, when he was Secretary to the Admiralty in the
1680s.
</P>
<P>
   My final destination was Annapolis' most historic structure and
best-known landmark, the Maryland State House in State Circle. The
oldest part of the building, dating from the 1770s, contains a
restoration of the Old Maryland Senate Chamber, which served as the
seat of Congress (and hence as the capitol of the United States)
from November 1783 to August 1784.
</P>
<P>
   In this room Gen. George Washington, in a poignant and tearful
ceremony, tendered his resignation as commander in chief of the
American Army on Dec. 23, 1783. (Ever the showman, George then
gleefully scampered off to enjoy Christmas dinner with Martha at
Mount Vernon.)
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, Congress ratified the Treaty of Paris here,
formally ending the Revolutionary War and making the United States
a genuinely independent nation _ though only after the ailing
delegate from South Carolina was transported from his sickbed to
produce the requisite quorum of 9 (out of 13) states.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious and endearing feature of the old State House is
the huge white dome constructed in 1785-88 to the plans of the
architect Joseph Clark. Said to be the largest wooden dome in the
country, this structure has dominated the Annapolis skyline ever
since, thanks to two remarkable characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   First, Clark wildly overreacted to critics who felt that an
earlier cupola on the State House roof had been too small to convey
the new state's dignity. As an astute observer wrote of Clark's
design in 1789, ``There is a disproportion between the dome and the
body of the building which must hurt the eye of every spectator.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally striking, in a random stroke of genius Clark modeled the
dome on the Schlossturm, or castle tower, of the palace of
Karlsruhe, Germany. How did an epitome of German High Baroque wind
up as the crowning feature of Maryland's State House? Clark most
likely saw an engraving of the Karlsruhe Schlossturm in the
Annapolis book and print shop owned by his brother, Stephen.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's State House dome was an immediate sensation, both
because of its highly distinctive style _ nothing like it ever
existed in Britain, for example _ and because of the wonderful
views from its observation deck. I stood on the State House
grounds, heartily agreeing with the dome's many early admirers,
Thomas Jefferson, James Madison and Charles Willson Peale among
them. After all, why shouldn't the centerpiece of one of our finest
Colonial towns, which is still conspicuously grounded on a
300-year-old Baroque town plan, be a German Baroque marvel?
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   HAMMOND-HARWOOD HOUSE, 19 Maryland Ave. (410) 269-1714;
www.annapolis.net/hammondharwood. Mondays through Saturdays, 10
a.m. to 4 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 4 p.m. Last tour begins at 3 p.m.
Admission: $5; $3, ages 6 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-LLOYD HOUSE, 22 Maryland Ave., (410) 263-2723. Mondays
through Saturdays, 2 to 4 p.m. Admission: $2.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM PACA HOUSE AND GARDEN, 186 Prince George St., (800)
603-4020; (410) 263-5553, www.annapolis.org. Mondays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 4 p.m. Admission: $7
for house and garden; $5 for house only; $4 for garden only;
half-price for ages 6 to 18. Acoustiguide garden tour is $2.
</P>
<P>
   NAVAL ACADEMY, www.usna.edu. The grounds are open daily and
there is no charge to visit buildings open to the public. The
visitors' center is at the end of King George Street, (410)
263-6933, www.navyonline.com; some free parking is available.
Center hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Daily guided tours (schedule
varies): $6; $5 for the elderly; $4 for ages 6 to 12; The Academy
Museum, (410) 293-2108, www.usna.edu/Museum, is open Mondays
through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. The
Academy Chapel and John Paul Jones Crypt are open Mondays through
Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   STATE HOUSE, State Circle, (410) 974-3400. Hours: Daily, 9 a.m.
to 5 p.m. Free guided tours at 11 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. What to Read
</P>
<P>
   ``ANNAPOLIS: A WALK THROUGH HISTORY,'' by Elizabeth B. Anderson,
Tidewater Publishers, $9.95. A guide to many 18th- and 19th-century
buildings that combines history, architecture and anecdote, with
excellent maps and beautiful photographs by M.E. Warren.
</P>
<P>
   ``BUILDERS OF ANNAPOLIS: CHARACTER AND ENTERPRISE IN A COLONIAL
CAPITAL,'' by Norman K. Risjord, Maryland Historical Society,
$18.95. A highly readable account of 18th-century Annapolis,
related in a series of sketches about residents who shaped the
town's fabric and its politics, by a first-rate historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE UNITED STATES NAVAL ACADEMY CHAPEL,'' by Margaret C. King
and Randolph W. King. An informative, well-illustrated booklet
about Ernest Flagg's Chapel, his other work at the Naval Academy
and the John Paul Jones crypt. Available at the Academy Museum ($4)
and the Academy Visitor Center ($6).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE U.S. NAVAL ACADEMY, AN ILLUSTRATED HISTORY,'' by Jack
Sweetman and Thomas J. Cutler, Naval Institute Press, $39.95. A
detailed and scholarly history of the academy from its founding to
the present, with many interesting and amusing illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   RESERVATIONS: Hotel rooms in downtown Annapolis are scarce,
especially on weekends, when rates are higher; also during special
events, like Naval Academy Homecoming (Sept. 28-Oct. 1), the
Sailboat Show (Oct. 5-9) and the Powerboat Show (Oct. 12-16).
Information: Annapolis Accommodations at (410) 280-0900; (800)
715-1000 or www.StayAnnapolis.com. The historic district has many
bed and breakfasts. Information: Annapolis Bed and Breakfast
Association at (410) 263-6124 or www.annapolisbandb.com.
</P>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS MARRIOTT WATERFRONT, 80 Compromise St., (410)
268-7555; (800) 336-0072. A 150-room hotel on the waterfront at the
foot of Main Street. Double rooms from $249 on weekends and $229 on
weekdays and slower weekends.
</P>
<P>
   LOEW'S ANNAPOLIS HOTEL, 126 West St. at Lafayette Avenue, (410)
263-7777; (800) 526-2593. Five blocks west of the State House, with
217 rooms. Double rooms from $189 on weekends and $129 on weekdays
and slower weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   MIKE'S RESTAURANT AND CRAB HOUSE, 3030 Old Riva Road, Riva, Md.,
on the South River just south of the Riva Bridge, about three miles
from downtown Annapolis, (410) 956-2784. A full menu in addition to
excellent steamed blue crabs and other crab dishes; live music on
Friday and Saturday nights. Indoor and outdoor seating.
</P>
<P>
   CANTLER'S RIVERSIDE INN, 458 Forest Beach Road, on Mill Creek
two miles east of Old Severn River Bridge (Route 450), about three
miles from downtown Annapolis, (410) 757-1311. A well-known tourist
attraction, offering excellent steamed, hard-shelled blue crabs.
Indoor and outdoor seating.
</P>
<P>
   McGARVEY'S SALOON AND OYSTER BAR, 8 Market Space, at the City
Dock, (410) 263-5700. A friendly place much frequented by locals,
McGarvey's serves soups, salads, burgers, fresh fish and steak.
Tranquil and airy back room with a 75-year-old tree growing through
the floor; noisy, crowded bar in front. Entrees $6 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   PICCOLA ROMA, 200 Main St., (410) 268-7898. A convenient,
popular Italian restaurant serving lunch Mondays through Fridays
and dinners daily. Lunch, $12 to $25; dinner, $25 to $40.
</P>
<P>
   AROMI D'ITALIA, 8 Dock St., at the City Dock, (410) 263-1300.
Soups, salads, interesting Italian sandwiches, pizza, pastry and
excellent homemade ice cream. Open daily for lunch and dinner;
$6-12.
</P>
