<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-07 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A MEASURE THAT MIGHT ACTUALLY PASS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Vice President Al Gore vowed during his
acceptance speech to raise the minimum wage, the Democratic
National Convention delegates erupted in rafter-rattling cheers
matched in decibels only by the huzzahs for his promises to protect
abortion rights and reform health care.
</P>
<P>
   For roughly 60 years, the minimum wage issue has come up
regularly and has been mostly symbolic. The proposed increase is
merely $1 an hour. As the lowest wages rise, however, higher wages
tend to follow to adjust to the improved pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   But the symbol is powerful. In the world's most prosperous
economy, the salary floor for the nation's lowest-paid employees is
currently only $5.15 an hour, or about $10,700 for full-time work.
</P>
<P>
   This is a disgrace, a piddling sum that members of Congress _
who just hiked their own annual salaries to $145,500 with generous
side benefits _ can justify only if they are cruel, stupid or in
the pocket of cheapo big business.
</P>
<P>
   (Not surprisingly, that group includes the meanie Texas twins,
House Majority Leader Dick Armey and Republican whip Tom DeLay.
Armey wants to repeal the concept of a minimum wage altogether, and
DeLay was recently voiced anger at House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert
for suggesting a compromise plan to get the bill passed.)
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the Democratic minority in Congress are
overwhelmingly behind a minimum wage increase. But for decades,
Republicans have automatically resisted such hikes on the grounds
that small businesses can't survive if forced to share their
profits with lowly laborers instead of using the money to pave over
a new parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   But this time Republicans up for re-election did not dare oppose
the proposal outright. Both the House and Senate passed measures
raising the limit $1 over varying periods of time but compensating
businesses by giving them big tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Sensible Republicans up for re-election are pressuring their
leaders to do the right thing politically and economically. They
want to seem at least mildly concerned about narrowing the vast
income gap between corporate executives and their unskilled
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is this little problem of the lame duck president. He
doesn't want to be fleeced, particularly in an election year
important to his legacy. He has threatened to veto the GOP
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's compromise would provide $76 billion in tax cuts for
small businesses over 10 years to help companies pay ``the costs of
this wage increase.'' It was a psychological breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. What are these supposed costs? An Economic Policy
Institute (EPI) study of the last minimum wage hike in 1996 _
opposed by then-Speaker Newt Gingrich until the Republicans sank in
the polls that election year _ shows that the predicted devastating
loss to corporate America never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Job growth continued at a remarkable pace. The threatened
inflation driven by wage increases did not happen. Some restaurants
raised menu prices, but labor costs were only part of the reason.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 increase raised the wages of almost 10 million workers,
of whom about 71 percent were adults and 58 percent were women. The
EPI reports that four different tests have failed to prove any
substantial loss of jobs directly due to the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage hike is likely to pass this fall because both
parties know it is a popular issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a big Gore issue, his rival, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, has been mostly silent on the subject. It's not a winner for
him. He needs an antidote to his huge across-the-board tax cut
proposal that would benefit the rich proportionately more than the
middle class or poor.
</P>
<P>
   But he supports undercutting the minimum wage by demanding that
states be allowed to opt out of any increase if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   There are already escape clauses for the states. Six, including
Bush's Texas, have lower minimum wage levels for local jobs to
which federal standards do not apply. Texas has a minimum wage of
$3.35 an hour for uncovered workers, including seasonal and farm
laborers. Seven other states have no local minimum wage level at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The federal minimum wage, which covers most workers for large
companies paid by the hour, began at 25 cents an hour in 1938. A
North Carolina reader reminds me that in those long-ago days, 25
cents paid for a haircut, five candy bars, six cups of coffee, two
bottles of beer or five hot dogs. Members of Congress were
considered overpaid at $10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Today a stamp is 33 cents, and an order of french fries is
$1.19. If you can find him, a plain old barber will still give a
male a cut for $10 but women can pay $65 for a real do-up.
</P>
<P>
   The current minimum wage is no longer the single support system
for low-income families. We now have supplemental federal programs
like food stamps to help out. But it is still important for a
country of enormous wealth to demonstrate that its leaders do think
about the least fortunate. It might even be called compassionate
conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
