<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-07 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH VOWS DEFENSE MODERNIZATION AMID GOP CONCERNS OVER HIS
CAMPAIGN  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush, moving to address some Republican worries that
his campaign is faltering, flanked himself with military heroes of
the Persian Gulf War on Thursday as he pledged to equip America's
armed forces with billions of dollars worth of new high-tech gear.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a fresh national survey showing Vice President Al
Gore leading by 6 percentage points and buffeted by allies' public
criticism of his campaign, Bush declared himself the underdog and
vowed to change his style.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would hold more town hall-style meetings with voters
and make fewer set-piece campaign speeches. He also indicated
greater flexibility on the timing and format of campaign debates
with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be able to meet with people more often in less
formal settings,'' Bush told reporters on the campaign trail in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes, responding to GOP criticism of
the Bush campaign, said: ``We're listening'' because those comments
are ``well intentioned. Republicans want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby International poll released Thursday showed Gore
leading Bush 49 percent to 43 percent in a two-way race. Zogby's
poll had a margin of error of 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another survey released Thursday, the CNN-USA TODAY poll, showed
Gore leading Bush 47 percent to 44 percent among likely voters. The
survey had a margin of error of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, declaring that he is the ``underdog'' in the contest,
urged supporters to have ``no illusions'' about the difficulty of
achieving victory on Nov. 7. Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said Gore
has ``recaptured some of the mantle of incumbency, adding that Bush
has always ``liked being the challenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had been leading Gore by more than 10 percentage points
going into the Republican convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby survey showed Gore had doubled his 3- percentage point
edge over Bush to 6 percentage points in just 18 days.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gore challenged Bush's federal budget arithmetic in a
newspaper ad, fleshed out plans to create 10 million new high tech
jobs by 2010 and won the endorsement of the 1.5-million member
Teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bush had sought the endorsement of the union that
had supported Republican presidential candidates before backing.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters said they plan to spend $9 million to support
candidates, including Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters' spokesman Bret Caldwell said members backed Gore in
part because of his ``populist message'' since the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Even before results of the new Zogby poll were released, some
prominent Republicans had voiced varying degrees of concern over
the Bush campaign. They included Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge;
Michigan Gov. John Engler; campaign consultant Charles Black;
former education secretary William Bennett; House Budget Committee
Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio; and Reps. Fred Upton, R-Mich.; and
Gil Gutknecht, R-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Bush worked to retake the momentum by signaling willingness to
end a stalemate over campaign debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be worked out,'' Bush said. ``I want there to be
debates. The more who watch, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's flexibility contrasted with earlier insistence that he
would only participate in two interview-style 60-minute TV
appearances and a lone 90-minute debate hosted by the bipartisan
Commission on Presidential Debates that has sponsored every
campaign debate since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has sought three formal debates with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also sought to rebuild momentum by focusing for a second
day in a row on national security _ a tried-and-true issue for the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to representatives of the 1.9-million member Veterans
of Foreign Wars meeting in Detroit, Bush shifted away from
allegations that the Clinton-Gore administration had permitted the
nation's military preparedness to deteriorate and focused instead
on the steps he hopes to take to transform the armed forces from a
lumbering Cold War-era force to a rapid deployment force.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Bush promised a blue ribbon military task force to
map modernization that would ``redefine how war is fought and won
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was joined during stops in Ohio by two retired military
officers who helped his father, President George Bush, prosecute
the 43-day Persian Gulf War in 1991 _ retired Gen. Colin Powell,
who served as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and retired
Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf, the battlefield commander.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the second-term governor of Texas, left it to his running
mate, former defense secretary Dick Cheney, to flesh out the
Bush-Cheney plan for Pentagon modernization.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Portland, Maine, Cheney sharpened his criticism of
the Clinton-Gore administration by drawing from a letter written to
the White House last March by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., that
challenged the 30 percent reduction in the Pentagon's research and
development funding over the last six years. Lieberman is now
Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lack of planning for the future may represent the path of
least resistance _ but it is by far the path of greatest risk,''
Cheney quoted Lieberman's letter as saying. Cheney added: ``Sen.
Lieberman was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney promised a total $20 billion boost over the next five
years to the Pentagon's annual $34.3 billion research and
development budget for new weapons. Cheney vowed as well to earmark
at least 20 percent of the Pentagon's annual $61.8 billion for
weapons ``that propel America generations ahead in military
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign questioned Bush's budget commitment to
transforming U.S. armed forces. Gore has promised to devote $100
billion of the projected 10-year, $4.6 trillion federal budget
surplus to increase defense spending compared to $45 billion
promised by Bush, Gore aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush talks tough on defense but that is all it is _ talk,''
said Gore spokeswoman Kym Spell.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
