<P>
   MORE WEBCASTS: The success of college football's first live
webcast has brought the inevitable next wave to the Internet.
Foxsports.com's Sept. 2 Webcast of the Nebraska-San Jose State game
had more than 200,000 video streams, and now Multicast Media and
DMB Sports Entertainment Group, Inc. have signed an international
satellite distribution agreement that will deliver broadband
subscribers continuous sports content, including live netcasts of
football games, from 12 mostly western U.S. universities. The site
is still under construction
</P>
<P>
   www.multicastisp.com
</P>
<P>
   IN THE HOUSE: Houseofboxing.com is co-promoting TVKO's Saturday
pay-per-view of the light heavyweight title fight between world
champion Roy Jones Jr. and Eric Harding. HOB is producing exclusive
video footage of interviews with both fighters and the press
conference for its Web site, where cable television and satellite
subscribers also can order the fight.
</P>
<P>
   www.houseofboxing.com
</P>
<P>
   FREE PASS: More on major league baseball's Internet move to
www.mlb.com: Baseball is not making any payments to Morgan, Lewis &AMP;
Bockis LLP, the law firm that registered the domain name in 1994
and launched its site two years later, other than covering the
costs of switching its Web site. The firm, fourth-largest in the
United States with more than 1,000 lawyers in 12 offices,
represented baseball in its negotiations with the players'
association in 1990 and 1994-95. It had refused to relinquish the
site, forcing baseball to use www.majorleaguebaseball.com. The firm
will now switch to www.morganlewis.com.
</P>
<P>
   www.mlb.com
</P>
