<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SENATE-STURGEON08-COX     09-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-STURGEON08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE REPUBLICANS WIN A ROUND IN MISSOURI RIVER FIGHT
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flexing their majority muscles in the first of many
showdowns over environmental policy, Senate Republicans voted
Thursday to keep the federal government from raising the flow of
the Missouri River in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, other big shippers and barge owners along the lower
part of the river applauded the result, which would keep the flow
of the 2,300-mile-long river smooth all year around.
Environmentalists who favored varying the flow split, with some
lamenting their loss and others glad that the Republicans failed to
obtain a veto-proof majority.
</P>
<P>
   By a margin of 52-45, largely along partisan lines, the Senate
voted to ban the Army Corps of Engineers from trying to help save
the pallid sturgeon and two rare shore birds by raising the level
of the Missouri in the spring and lowering it in the summer about
once every three years.
</P>
<P>
   Voting Thursday to defend the ban were 51 Republicans and Sen.
Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark. On the losing side were 43 Democrats and
Sens. Lincoln Chafee, R-R.I., and Bill Roth, R-Del. Three senators
missed the vote.
</P>
<P>
   That display of unity strengthened the bargaining power of
leaders in both parties for the tough negotiations that will settle
end-of-session disputes over several issues, including more than
three dozen environmental clauses in unfinished appropriation
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service says that varying the flow of
the Missouri would help create sand bars where the piping plover
and interior least tern can raise hatchlings, and would stimulate
breeding by the pallid sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The sturgeon, a 6-foot-long, toothless, bottom-sucking primitive
that has been swimming in the Missouri since the Jurassic age of
dinosaurs, have been breeding less often since the once-wild
Missouri was tamed by reservoirs and dams.
</P>
<P>
   During a passionate, fact-packed three-hour debate, the ban was
defended by its author, Sen. Christopher (Kit) Bond, R-Mo., whose
downriver farmers fear wet fields and believe that year-round barge
service will help keep down railroad shipping rates. The attack on
the ban was led by Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, whose upriver recreational businesses make more money from
fishing and boating by tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, almost all senators ignored the arguments and
simply closed ranks behind their party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   That partisan pattern infuriated Tom Searchinger, an attorney in
the Washington office of Environmental Defense, an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't vote on the merits in a case where the Army
Corps of Engineers says the economic benefits of the change will
more than match any economic losses, how can we ever expect them to
enforce the Endangered Species Act?'' he exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   However, other environmentalists were delighted that Bond fell
far short of rounding up the 67 votes that would be needed to
override a veto threat issued by Clinton at Daschle's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this puts us in an excellent position to rip this
provision out in the conference committee, because the president is
going to have a tremendous amount of leverage,'' said Mary Beth
Beetham, director of legislative affairs in the Washington office
of Defenders of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Jason Schechter said, ``The
president has no intention of letting this language ever become
law. If that takes a veto, there will be a veto.''
</P>
<P>
   But Searchinger said, ``There's always abundant risk when a
whole lot of items get thrown into a messy pile on the (bargaining)
table at the end of a session, as to what will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Army Corps of Engineers Missouri River Draft Biological Opinion:
www.nwd.usace.army.mil/
</P>
<P>
   American Waterways Operators: www.americanwaterways.com
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Wildlife:
www.defenders.org/wildlife/riders/riders.html.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
