<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-2TAKES-NYT     09-07 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ON OUR OWN TERMS': THE MANY LAYERS OF DYING  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Va., Kan., Mo.)  (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In America, a nation of strivers, people want to believe that
everything is subject to improvement, even dying. While death
remains (presumably) a constant, the act of dying has become more
complex. Medical advances have prolonged life, but often in an
undesirable form, forcing doctors to reconsider their roles and
obligations. Terminally ill patients may think they want to take
control of their mortality with physician-assisted suicide, then
find they are afraid.
</P>
<P>
   So dying remains a mystery, subject to legal, medical,
theological, emotional and economic considerations. No one wants to
think about it, but eventually everyone must. To help, Bill Moyers
has provided an extraordinary guide with ``On Our Own Terms,'' his
panoramic and often profoundly moving vision of how we die in
America today.
</P>
<P>
   In this four-part, six-hour PBS series, Moyers and his crew
cover a lot of physical as well as emotional ground, featuring
doctors and patients from all over the country, in all kinds of
financial and family circumstances, uncovering heart-wrenching and
sometimes surprising stories of fortitude and fragility,
indifference and love.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the intimate case studies Moyers presents offer
the intense emotionalism of great drama, he always aims to
instruct. So in addition to the six hours presented on television,
PBS has produced elaborate amplification at www.pbs.org, making
this program a vivid illustration of how television and the
Internet are becoming increasingly linked. Throughout the program,
references to corresponding links on the PBS Web site appear
onscreen. The Web site offers comprehensive information on both
practical and intangible matters, including financial planning
advice for terminally ill patients, various treatment alternatives
and on ``taking a spiritual inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the new genre of hospital documentaries like ABC's
excellent series ``Hopkins: 24/7,'' Moyers and his producers don't
try to mimic the fast-paced style of prime-time television dramas _
though these cameras also follow patients into conferences with
their doctors and into their homes. Often the cameras stop to show
pictures of the patients before, when they were happy and whole,
and these ordinary snapshots take on layers of poignancy and
meaning. Viewers meet people who face death with humor as well as
resoluteness, like the retired math teacher who refers to each
weekly gathering with her children and grandchildren as ``the last
supper.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyers isn't afraid to linger, to acknowledge the knotted layers
of his subject. Introducing the third episode, ``A Death of One's
Own,'' which deals with assisted suicide, Moyers notes that the
subject is often sensationalized by the media and pointedly
observes that in this program ``Dr. Kevorkian is not heard from.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Moyers is an unobtrusive but steady presence,
introducing each episode and then occasionally appearing on camera
to ask a gently leading question. (``Is it hard to have to focus on
him all the time?'' he asks a dying man's wife.)
</P>
<P>
   The producers have assembled a remarkable array of subjects,
people whose obsession with death _ whether personal or
professional _ provokes multifarious thoughts about it. They found
Thomas Lynch, the Michigan undertaker who is also an author on the
subject, a homespun poet and philosopher, and a smart, sensitive
doctor specializing in palliative care at Mount Sinai Hospital in
Manhattan. She requires her medical students to read Tolstoy's
``Death of Ivan Ilyich,'' about a man who is dying without anyone's
acknowledging that his death is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The undertaker from Michigan wonders why so many people ask for
funerals without flowers, but when Diana, Princess of Wales, died,
strangers offered flowers in abundance. A doctor in
Charlottesville, Va., tries to convince a group of medical students
that to stop giving a patient food and air through tubes isn't
killing him, just letting him die. In New York City, a young man's
family, refusing to acknowledge that their son is dying, wants to
reduce his pain medication so he can be alert enough to fight the
disease that will kill him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The series falters only in the last episode, ``A Time to
Change,'' which becomes preachy as it poses important questions
about the financial challenges of providing good end-of-life care
to everyone. In part because many of the patients featured here are
too far gone to make a connection, some of the immediacy of the
earlier episodes is diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The series shines with its individual portraits, some of which
have the resonance of good literature. In ``A Death of One's Own,''
Jim Witcher, a veterinarian in Louisiana, and his wife, Susie, are
living their lifelong dream of owning a horse farm in retirement _
a dream fulfilled except that he is dying of Lou Gehrig's disease,
a creeping paralysis that will steadily destroy every function. He
wants to be put to sleep before he dies a miserable death, the way
he often relieved the suffering of animals when he was in practice,
but assisted suicide is illegal in Louisiana and against his
family's religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   His wife sympathizes enormously but can't promise him she'll
fulfill his wishes. It's too much for her to be both a grieving
wife and an ethicist. So she does what she is able, caring for him
at home because, she says, clearly loving, she can't bear the
thought of a stranger ``wiping his bottom.'' It is wrenching to
watch her struggle to hoist her husband from his wheelchair onto a
plastic chair for his shower, then bathe him with the same strong
hands she uses to soap and rinse their horses.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode, ``Living With Dying,'' begins with Bill
Bartholome, a pediatrician in Kansas City, an articulate observer
of his own dying. It reveals no secrets to say that Bartholome dies
at the end of the program. That's the point of his presence.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But first, he engages the audience with his matter-of-factness,
which transmits deep intelligence and bravery. When he received his
diagnosis, it seemed appropriate to him that he should be stricken.
``Why not have it be somebody who can deal with it?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Bartholome possesses the mixed blessing of being able to
diagnose his illness (esophageal cancer) and to monitor its
progress. After initially experiencing ``a kind of grief I had
never known,'' he says, he determined to live with vibrancy as ``a
terminal person.'' He does not want to kill himself as he nears
death; nor does he want to prolong his life. He just wants to die
at home, with his wife present, as comfortably as possible.
</P>
<P>
   For him, this is a personal decision, though Moyers demonstrates
that Bartholome is part of a wider movement to humanize the dying
process. Hospitals like Mount Sinai have established palliative
care units whose focus is not on curing patients but on easing
their pain, though patients still may request medical treatment
beyond painkillers. Then there are hospices, where the emphasis is
strictly on comfort, not cure.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers meets with Bartholome and his wife over a period of
months, and the patient is visibly losing ground, dropping 20
pounds in less than a month. By the end this tall man weighs 154
pounds, a shadow of the hearty 216-pound fellow seen in a snapshot,
happily holding a freshly caught fish.
</P>
<P>
   He writes a journal about his experience and confesses in one
interview that he is in pain, but decided not to take his
medication that day so he could think clearly. ``I want to be
master of ceremonies at this thing,'' he says of his death. Perhaps
we dare not ask for anything more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL; 
`ON OUR OWN TERMS: MOYERS ON DYING &QL; 
Living With Dying'  &QL; 
At 9 p.m, ET Sunday on PBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First in a four-part series continuing through Wednesday. Bill
Moyers and Judith Davidson Moyers, executive editors; Elena Mannes,
series producer; Gail Pellett and Mannes, producers; Alison Amron,
Donna Marino, Nobuko Oganesoff and Sharon Sachs, editors; Gail
Ablow, William Brangham and Paco de Onis, field producers; Felice
Firestone, director of production. Produced by Public Affairs
Television. Deborah Rubinstein, director of special projects.
Moyers and Judy Doctoroff O'Neill, executive producers.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
