<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-DEBT-2TAKES(TRI     09-07 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DEBT-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S BANKING SYSTEM TOTTERING AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ First, there was the failure of Sogo Co., a lumbering
department store chain that was crushed this summer by its $17
billion in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a construction company, Inoue Kogyo, was rescued from a
similar fate when its banks forgave $136 million in debt; Hazama,
another construction company, may receive similar treatment for
about $1 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the central bank moved to raise interest rates,
if only fractionally.
</P>
<P>
   Any one of those events increased the strain on Japan's rickety
banking system. The question now is whether their combined effect
will be lethal, forcing the government to intervene as it did two
years ago when the financial system came close to collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has spent 25 trillion yen in tax money, or $238
billion at current exchange rates, on its overhaul of the financial
system, of $666 billion allocated for that purpose in 1998. Even
more has been spent to prop up banks and other financial
institutions indirectly, through credit-guarantee programs and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are standing at the same divide where we were standing two
years ago, when we recapitalized the banks,'' said Yasuhisa
Shiozaki, a youngish legislator from the governing Liberal
Democratic Party who has been a rather lonely advocate of painful
financial restructuring. ``We can either recapitalize the banks
again, or we can just let them go bust.''
</P>
<P>
   Shiozaki is perhaps the boldest of a growing group of
politicians, economists and government officials who think that
Japan never entirely repaired its banking system after many banks
stumbled into crisis in autumn 1997, falling victim to profligate
lending policies and social pressure to maintain relationships,
whatever the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials at the watchdog Financial Supervisory Agency
have recently been telling reporters and analysts that three or
four more of the country's big banks should have been nationalized
in 1998, along with the ones that were _ Long-Term Credit Bank and
Nippon Credit Bank. But politicians, they say, would not sanction
such radical surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Shiozaki doubts that the government has the will for a second
round of refinancing in the wake of Sogo's failure, when a plan to
spend close to $1 billion to waive debt and keep the company afloat
was swamped in an outcry of public disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling-party politicians quickly scrapped the plan, and Sogo
failed, blowing away the fig leaf that covered Japan's
supposedly-resolved bad-debt problems. ``What we found out with
Sogo and afterward is that the essential and fundamental problems
of the Japanese economy were still there or perhaps even worse,''
Shiozaki said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although a second injection of public money into the banking
system may be unlikely, the government has proven itself adroit at
devising bank rescue programs in disguise. A decision to postpone a
deposit-insurance program that would limit government protection to
about $95,000 a depositor, rather than the unlimited protection in
place since 1996, was aimed at protecting the regional banks and
local lenders that would likely see their customers flee for
bigger, sounder institutions if the plan were to start in March
2001 as originally intended.
</P>
<P>
   And the government's $285 billion credit-guarantee program for
small and midsized enterprises is as much about supporting banks as
about helping struggling mom-and-pop businesses. Takatomo Nakagawa,
a researcher at Teikoku Data Bank, remarked: ``The companies using
this program were, in many cases, using the money especially to pay
back existing bank loans, not only for the operations of the
company. The money was used for the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As of March, the major banks had more than $40 billion reserved
against bad debts, but James P. Fiorillo, senior banking analyst at
ING Barings in Tokyo, estimates that those reserves would cover
only about 2.5 percent of their potential problem loans. He doubts
that all bad debt has been properly classified and that real estate
collateral has been properly valued.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are more optimistic. Statistics show that the big
banks have enough reserves to cover 25 percent of the roughly $188
billion in bad debts held at the end of March.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the fall of 1998, the government enacted sweeping financial
reform legislation aimed at setting the banking system, which had
nearly collapsed within the preceding year, back on its feet. In
exchange for an infusion of public money totaling 8 trillion yen,
or $76 billion, the banks were forced into a wholesale
re-evaluation of their loan portfolios, urged to consolidate, and
exhorted to focus on profitability rather than the relationships
that determined past business decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The government spent an additional 6.8 trillion yen, or $64.2
billion, rehabilitating the two major banks it nationalized, Nippon
Credit Bank and Long-Term Credit Bank. ``I think people forget how
much has been accomplished in less than two years,'' said Yoshimasa
Hayashi, a young member of the upper house of Parliament. ``The
commitment to financial reform continues to be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   While an impressive wave of consolidation in the last two years
has cut the ranks of Japan's biggest banks in half to 10, it has
yet to produce obvious efficiencies. Nor has consolidation
noticeably changed the type of business banks here do or the way in
which they do it.
</P>
<P>
   The banks have yet to incur the costs of bringing their outmoded
technology up to date; meanwhile nimbler new financial institutions
that have linked their fortunes to the Internet are plowing new
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' bread-and-butter lending business remains in a
prolonged slump. Borrowers are either desperately working to reduce
their debts or are increasingly relying on the capital markets for
their borrowing needs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the banks are struggling with negative forces over
which they _ and the government _ have little or no control.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, credit ratings agencies are warning that
bankruptcies, already ratcheting up every month, are likely to hit
a high this year as bigger and bigger debtors throw in the towel.
Bankruptcies rose 21 percent in July compared to the same month
last year, according to Teikoku Databank, a private research
company, and the total debt owed by the companies that folded
tripled to a high of $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see an avalanche of new bad debts into the system, the
banks do not appear to have enough resources to cope comfortably
with the problem,'' Fiorillo said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wave of bankruptcies is forcing banks to sell off shares
they hold to raise money to cover losses, which is, along with
sales by foreigners, contributing to a drop in stock prices that
further erodes the remaining value of their investment portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   ING Barings estimates that the more than 7 trillion yen in
profits that Japanese banks boasted last year when the stock market
staged a mini-recovery had, as of July, turned into roughly 500
billion yen in losses with the market's fall.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, the agency charged with overhauling the financial
system, the Financial Reconstruction Commission, has been buffeted
by a series of scandals that have created a revolving door in its
leadership and undermined its power and credibility. In the last 10
months, the commission has had four chiefs, two of whom were forced
to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head of the organization has been changed too frequently
and that is not good,'' said Hakuo Yanagisawa, the member of
Parliament who served for one year as the commission's first chief
before he was replaced in a routine cabinet shuffle. To critics,
all this suggests that the government is going to have to find some
way to overcome popular resistance to injecting more money into the
banking system. ``Public funds are going to be used, either through
the Deposit Insurance Corp. or by letting banks go bust or
injecting more capital into them,'' Shiozaki said.
</P>
<P>
   But others say Shiozaki and his like are alarmists. ``The
problems emerging now are more or less within the scope of what we
anticipated,'' Yanagisawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa is still accorded a great deal of respect, both
within Japan and without, and is credited with forcing the
consolidation that has reconfigured the landscape of Japanese
banking. Bankers feared him, reformers praised him and politicians
respected him.
</P>
<P>
   It was during his tenure that Long-Term Credit Bank, once the
flagship of the Japanese banking system, was sold off to a group of
foreigners led by Ripplewood Holdings LLC, a private equity firm
based in New York. That move has had big repercussions. Long-Term
Credit, now known as Shinsei Bank, refused to participate in a debt
restructuring plan for Sogo. Ripplewood seemed well aware when it
bought Long-Term Credit that many of its loans were basically
irrecoverable. It demanded that the government promise to make the
bank whole on any loans that fell in value by 20 percent or more
for three years after the sale _ even though the government had
supposedly transferred all bad loans from the bank to the Deposit
Insurance Corp. long before Ripplewood came on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians are now arguing that the government agreed to
that provision because it also knew that a good portion of
Long-Term Credit's loan portfolio was suspect but could not win
political sanction to pull the plug on well-connected companies
like Sogo, Daiei, Kumagai Gumi and the Saison group, which have
strong ties to leaders of the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshimi Watanabe, a Liberal Democrat in the lower house of
Parliament, believes that this failure to thoroughly weed out bad
debts and consign them to the Deposit Insurance Corp. was a basic
flaw in the whole bank rescue program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original evaluation of those loans was totally wrong,'' he
said. ``The banking bureau at the Ministry of Finance was claiming
these loans were `grey' loans, not bad loans, but in fact these
loans were to companies that had a high probability of going
bankrupt or were effectively bankrupt already.''
</P>
<P>
   Yanagisawa conceded that some of the assumptions made when the
Financial Reconstruction Commission was established have since
proven faulty. ``We had hoped that those companies would have made
strenuous efforts to restructure themselves in the period before
their loans were transferred to Shinsei,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the government's economic forecasts had been too
rosy, thus skewing its projections about corporate recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But Yanagisawa argues that today's problems are largely ones of
perception, not asset quality. ``There is no one who can explain to
the Japanese public that these problems are within the bounds of
what we had anticipated,'' he said. ``Government authorities had
envisaged this scenario.''
</P>
</TEXT>
