<HEADER>
A5384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKETS-NORRIS-COLUMN     09-07 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: CORPORATE BONDS ARE AN OVERLOOKED BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which market do you believe?
</P>
<P>
   A look at the U.S. equity market shows a generally positive
picture. Valuations are high, and indexes of major stocks are near
record levels. Clearly, productivity and profits are expected to
stay high for the indefinite future.
</P>
<P>
   But in the credit markets, the outlook appears much bleaker.
There, money is becoming harder to find, and the price is
expensive. Lower-quality borrowers always have to pay more than
safe ones, but this year the spreads have widened significantly.
That would be expected if people feared a recession, but then one
would also expect to see the stock market doing much worse than it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the explanation for this split is simple supply and
demand. The government is buying back Treasury bonds, so yields on
those securities may have been pushed lower than they otherwise
would be. But companies are borrowing at a rapid pace even though
investors are not particularly interested in buying bonds, and that
is driving up yields. Money has been coming out of junk bond mutual
funds this year, while it has poured into stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those bonds have been sold to foreign investors, who
these days are buying about a third of the corporate debt issued.
Bob Prince, the research director at Bridgewater Associates, a
money management firm, argues that higher rates have been needed to
lure overseas buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the widening spreads meant that borrowers paid
more, but credit to companies that willing to pay the tab did not
really seem restricted. The banks have been willing lenders, but
there are now scattered signs that they are growing more cautious.
Since late last year, more and more banks have been telling the
Federal Reserve that they are tightening credit standards. The
default rate on junk bonds has been creeping up, even as the
economy hums along with rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   This fall may prove to be the testing time for capital markets.
Wall Street is gearing up for another big dose of initial public
offerings, and Europeans _ who have provided a lot of the capital
to finance U.S. markets _ need to raise a lot of money to finance
wireless telephone licenses that have fetched amazing bids at
government auctions in Europe. If investors don't put up enough
capital, stocks could suffer far more than bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, something can be said for buying what others
don't want. Just now, that is debt. Corporate bonds won't do well
if the economy goes belly up, and they will not perform as well as
stocks if corporate profits keep booming for years and years. But
within that range of economic outcomes is a middle ground that
favors bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Fridson, Merrill Lynch's junk bond guru, reports that the
spreads of junk bond yields over Treasuries are now far higher than
his economic model would forecast _ higher, in fact, than at any
time in the past save for a brief period in 1998-99 after the
Russian default and Asian crisis, when investors feared a worldwide
recession. Fridson adds, however, that he sees nothing on the
horizon that would produce a sharp narrowing of spreads.
</P>
<P>
   Prince, the Bridgewater analyst, calculates that the divergence
between the pricing of stocks and of corporate bonds ``is near a
40-year high'' because the bond market has priced in plenty of risk
of economic disappointment while the stock market sees little risk.
</P>
<P>
   The message is clear: Corporate bonds are a better buy than
stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
