u s BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT &LR;      09-07 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 2 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   New England (0-1) vs. Jets (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   These teams meet for the fourth straight season in a prime-time
game, this one on Monday night, when both teams' fans and peers
will get an up-close look at the continued rivalry. It runs deep,
from management to coaches to players. The Patriots seek to heal
their offense. It was squashed last week vs. Tampa Bay and the
offensive line, in particular, was tossed around by the Buccaneers.
The Jets feel good, rightly so, about winning on the road, at Green
Bay, and about protecting their lead in the closing seconds. The
matchup of the Patriots' defense against the Jets' offense decides
this game. Give the Patriots' defense the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Patriots, 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (0-1) vs. Cincinnati (0-0)
</P>
<P>
   A brand new stadium will be christened, a stadium named after
the team's founder, Paul Brown. It is a beauty. It sparkles in
downtown Cincinnati and is nestled near the Ohio River. And the
Bengals get to play their longtime rival, their Ohio brethren, the
Browns, in the first-ever game there. Watch quarterback Akili Smith
to rookie receiver Peter Warrick. This is the start of something
special.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Bengals, 27-17.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (1-0) vs. Baltimore (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Tony Banks is 7-4 as the Ravens' starter and his
team has won five of its last six games. They are 7-0 when back
Priest Holmes rushes for 100 or more yards. Ravens' receiver Quadry
Ismail has produced four 100-yard receiving game in his last 6
games. How does a guy get faster as he gets older? Actually, it's
that the Ravens utilize Ismail and feature him, as opposed to him
being a complementary player as he was in Minnesota. Baltimore can
produce a 2-0 record for the first time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Ravens, 26-24.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (0-1) vs. Tennessee (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Against Buffalo, The Titans are a strong team, but they have a
weakness _ not enough big plays downfield. Nearly everything the
Titans get on offense comes in a grinding running game and in its
short passing game. Receiver Carl Pickens is supposed to help free
this offense. Playing against Kansas City instead of Buffalo will
help. The Chiefs allowed 386 yards of offense in losing to
Indianapolis last Sunday. Tennessee might not match that but should
get plenty of yardage in this victory.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Titans, 24-10.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (0-1) vs. Tampa Bay (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Cade McNown threw for 290 yards and two touchdowns against the
Vikings but surprisingly ran 10 times for 87 yards and a touchdown.
For the Bears to reach the playoffs, however, it will be with
McNown's arm instead of his legs. Same way, if he is to beat Tampa
Bay, but that does not look likely. Tampa Bay has not allowed
Chicago to score 20 points in their last 8 meetings. It has not
allowed Chicago to score an offensive touchdown in the last 10
quarters they have played against each other. And Tampa Bay has
beaten Chicago in five straight meetings. Make it six. Prediction:
Buccaneers, 23-6.
</P>
<P>
   Giants (1-0) vs. Philadelphia (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Both the Giants and Eagles are off to fast starts on the ground.
The Giants' leader is Tiki Barber, who is averaging 11.1 yards per
carry. Philadelphia's leader is Duece Staley, who gained 201
rushing yards vs. Dallas. In beating Dallas, Philadelphia not only
scored 41 points on the road but also exuded excitement and
confidence. If both teams' running attacks are neutralized, the
game will come down to the arms of Philadelphia quarterback Donovon
McNabb and Giants' quarterback Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Giants, 19-17.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (0-1) vs. Buffalo (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay offense sank against the Jets and now plays the
defense that led the entire league a season ago. That is a bad
combination. Brett Favre says he is ready to throw it short and
long against Buffalo, that his arm is still sore, but sound. By the
time the Buffalo defense is finished chasing and hitting him, Favre
will have more pain than simply in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Bills, 23-9.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (1-0) vs. Minnesota (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   The key attraction here is the Miami defense and cornerbacks
Patrick Surtain and Sam Madison against Vikings receivers Randy
Moss and Cris Carter. Intriguing, too, is the matchup of Miami's
stout defensive front against Minnesota's big offensive line and
speedy back Robert Smith. But Miami must also focus on offense.
Against Seattle, quarterback Jay Fiedler made enough good plays and
running back Lamar Smith (27 carries, 145 rushing yards) ran
rampant on natural grass. Can both accomplish that against
Minnesota on artificial turf inside a dome? Minnesota's offense
will do enough, but the Vikings win this game on defense with
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Vikings, 21-6.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (1-0) vs. Indianapolis (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Since the Raiders have never played in the RCA Dome, they are in
for a treat. Well, more like a scare _ because the fans there whoop
it up, making it nearly impossible for visitors to hear the signal
calls. Just as scary is the Colts' offense, which is shifty and
speedy at receiver (Marvin Harrison), cool and calm at quarterback
(Peyton Manning) and bullish yet stylish at tailback (Edgerrin
James).
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Colts, 26-17.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES:
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (1-0) vs. Seattle (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks performed miserably against Miami last week and
quarterback Jon Kitna was the focal point, throwing four
interceptions and fumbling. Mike Holmgren, Seattle's coach,
believes Kitna can only improve. Seattle's defense possesses the
personnel to run with the Rams. That's the start in the making of
an upset. And Seattle will be focused, and prepared to answer all
the critics after their listless opening game. And after all of
that drama against Denver on Monday night, the Rams are ripe for an
upset.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Seahawks, 30-28.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (0-1) vs. San Francisco (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   These teams let the ball fly when they meet. Last year, there
were 15 touchdowns scored in their two games and 8 of them were for
20 or more yards. San Francisco has won seven consecutive home
openers but figures to struggle with the Panthers. Panthers back
Tim Biakabutuka averaged 5.9 yards per carry last week against
Washington and can match that against the 49ers' defense. Though
49ers quarterback Jeff Garcia currently leads the league with three
touchdown passes, look for Panthers' quarterback Steve Beuerlein to
make the bigger, longer, more decisive throws.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Panthers, 28-20.
</P>
<P>
   Washington (1-0) vs. Detroit (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are headed in positive directions. Washington
continues to mesh a galaxy of stars; Detroit hopes to get its main
man back _ quarterback Charlie Batch. He has made a speedy recovery
from a knee injury sustained during the preseason and is expected
to play on Sunday. That makes the game more fun for Detroit. Watch
Detroit kick returner Desmond Howard. He used to be a Redskin, but
they gave up on him; he will be ready for Washington. The
difference in this game is quarterback Brad Johnson against a
suspect secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Redskins, 27-23.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (1-0) vs. Denver (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves makes his return to Mile High Stadium. Reeves coached
the Broncos from 1981 through 1992. Good thing he has receiver
Shawn Jefferson on his side. Jefferson gained a career-high 148
yards against the Rams Monday night. That is because New England
always tried to balance him with receiver Terry Glenn, whereas the
Falcons will let him fly. Jefferson will make a mark in this game,
too. But not as much as the Broncos' balanced attack on the ground
and in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Broncos, 30-24.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (0-1) vs. San Diego (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams fought hard in their losses last week _ the Saints by
4 points to Detroit and the Chargers by 3 points to the Raiders _
but both also showed that they are short in manpower. Neither is
playoff-bound. Neither has enough speed. Neither starting
quarterback (Jeff Blake for New Orleans, Ryan Leaf for San Diego)
is consistent. Neither defense sacks the quarterback enough.
Neither makes enough big plays. They deserve each other.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Chargers, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (0-1) vs. Arizona (0-1)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dallas gained 167 yards and allowed 425 against
Philadelphia last week. And quarterback Jake Plummer's passing
yardage (318) was nearly twice as much as Dallas' total offense.
Troy Aikman sits this one out, recovering from a concussion.
Randall Cunningham will start and will give the Dallas offense a
different look, one with more mobility and with more deep passing
strikes. There is no way the Cardinals should lose this game. They
are at home, have played well against Dallas in recent seasons and
don't have to face Aikman or new receiver Joe Galloway, out for the
year with to a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Cardinals, 27-21.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
