<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILITARY-TRAINER-$ADV     09-07 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-TRAINER-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COSTS OF NEW MILITARY TRAINER PLANE FLY HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon's new trainer aircraft is expected to
shoot past its estimated cost by some $753 million, 19 percent
above its original price tag, with the U.S. taxpayer footing most
of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The initial cost for the Joint Primary Aircraft Training System
(JPATS) had been $3.9 billion for a fleet of 740 propeller-powered
aircraft with two seats, one for the student pilot and the other
for an instructor. But according to internal Pentagon budget
documents, the price is expected to surge as manufacturer Raytheon
Aircraft Co., of Wichita, Kans., grapples with design snafus,
increased material costs and poor prospects for foreign sales.
</P>
<P>
   The cost growth in the program has raised eyebrows in the
Pentagon where JPATS is competing for scarce funding against such
high-priority weapons as the Air Force F-22 fighter and the Navy
F/A-18 Super Hornet jet.
</P>
<P>
   The cost spike is all the more disconcerting for Pentagon
officials because JPATS had been designated by the military as a
model for cost-effective purchasing in a culture that is notorious
for cost-overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kaminski, then the Pentagon's top procurement officials,
told Congress in 1997 that purchasing programs like JPATS would
prove that military items could be acquired faster and cheaper
through the use of commercial products and commercial practices.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force and Navy plan to use the JPATS aircraft to train
student pilots in the fundamentals of flying. The JPATS aircraft
would replace the Air Force's T-37B and the Navy's T-34C primary
trainer aircraft. Air Force student pilots will begin training on
the plane next June while the Navy is scheduled to begin training
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Air Force is flying 11 JPATS aircraft from
Randolph Air Force Base in San Antonio. The 11 represent the first
of 454 airplanes that the service hopes to buy. The Navy plans to
buy 328 planes.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminski's enthusiasm was based on the fact that JPATS was
designed as a cousin of an existing aircraft _ the Swiss-made
Pilatus PC-9 commercial aircraft _ and therefore would require only
limited modifications. Those modifications include improved
ejection seats, a pressurized cockpit, an elevated rear instructor
seat, and flexibility to accommodate a wider range of male and
female pilots. The plane also boasts design improvements to protect
against ``birdstrikes'' where birds hit the propeller blades,
causing the plane to stall.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan estimated the cost per aircraft at about $5
million. Now, however, estimates by the Air Force and civilians in
the Office of the Secretary of Defense put the cost at about $6
million each. Some Pentagon officials believe that the aircraft
will cost up to $6.5 million each. The price includes the cost of
ground-based simulators as well.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, an Air Force F-16 fighter jet costs about $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   The JPATS cost overrun isn't among the military's worst
financial miscalculations. For example, the Pentagon estimates that
production costs alone for the Air Force F-22 jet will balloon by
some $8 billion, or 20 percent, over its $37 billion cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy A-12 attack jet was canceled for incurring over $1
billion in projected overruns. And a new Army and Marine Corps
howitzer is overrunning its $31 million development budget by $6.6
million, a 21 percent boost.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the JPATS cost growth, about $230 million, reflects the
fact that the armed services have decided to buy 41 more aircraft.
In addition, the military has opted to stretch out the program by
buying fewer of the planes annually over a longer period, creating
inefficiencies on the factory floor.
</P>
<P>
   But blame for the remainder of the overrun on JPATS _ about $525
million worth and possibly more _ is being laid at the feet of
Raytheon and higher manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Col. Ronald Joseph, the JPATS program manager, said
that ``the aviation market is booming and commercial costs are
increasing. There are some inefficiencies from the company. All the
things combined over a period of time add up to more program
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, who declined to discuss how much more the program will
cost the Pentagon, said the military is girding for a
``correction'' in the price, meaning that the Pentagon will end up
paying more.
</P>
<P>
   David Riemer, Raytheon Aircraft's vice president for government
business, blamed the lack of foreign sales for the higher cost of
each airplane. ``When we forecast the aircraft's price to the U.S.
government, we had a significant volume of (projected)
international sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But those sales haven't materialized due to several factors: a
competitive trainer market and lingering economic problems in Asia
and Latin America that squelched orders from those regions.
</P>
<P>
   The company's rosy assumption was that initial orders from other
countries for the aircraft would top 200 aircraft. But at present,
only 69 are on order: 45 planes from Greece and 24 from Canada. And
prospects don't look that good for many more in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shop floor is not as efficient, indirect expenses aren't
spread over as many airplanes,'' Riemer explained.
</P>
<P>
   One Air Force official who asked not to be named said that some
in the Pentagon are questioning whether the military should pay for
the company's mistake in pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why we should have to eat their pricing problem,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also has had difficulty modifying the commercial
aircraft design for military use. For example, when test pilots
flew the plane in steep dives or tight turns, the plane's propeller
blade on the Pratt &AMP; Whitney Canada_manufactuered engine would bend
and hit part of the aircraft. This sparked a six-month delay in the
project as engineers sought to correct the problem. Joseph said
that problem has been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the problem of sauna conditions in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by the Pentagon's top weapons tester,
``cockpit temperatures near 100 degrees farenheight have been
recorded'' in the JPATS, a situation that prevents the plane from
being used during warm days.
</P>
<P>
   These design setbacks will force Raytheon to absorb at least $36
million in overruns and possibly more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5390 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-NNS &LR;      09-07 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE SHUTTLE OBSOLESCENCE POSTPONED AS REPLACEMENT VEHICLES LAG 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
THURSDAY, Sept. 7, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 By BRETT DAVIS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's main space vehicle for the next decade or
two, or longer, will likely be about 123 feet long. It will have a
tall tail and stubby wings, and will use a massive external fuel
tank and twin booster rockets to help it get into space.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably look a lot like the space shuttle, in other
words. That's because it may very well be the space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Although NASA and aerospace industry companies have spent years
thinking about a cheaper, less complicated alternative to the
shuttle, no successor is ready to go just yet. For at least the
next dozen years, and maybe long after that, NASA will continue to
rely on a vehicle that had its origin in the Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people feel the shuttle will be operating for at
least the next two decades,'' said Jack King, spokesman for United
Space Alliance, the private consortium that now handles shuttle
launch preparation and maintenance for the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of our orbiters is built for at least 100 flights,
and we're only about a quarter of the way through the lifetime,''
King said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after Discovery returns from a flight scheduled for
October (the 100th flight for the shuttle program), it will be the
veteran among the four-vehicle fleet with 28 flights. Endeavour,
the newest shuttle, which replaced Challenger after it was
destroyed in a 1986 explosion, has flown only 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officially plans to fly the shuttle fleet through at least
2012, using it to build the International Space Station through
2006 and help maintain it after that.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Atlantis is slated to lift off Friday for the
station, to install equipment and supplies for the first residents,
who are scheduled to move in in November.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, who analyzes space and defense issues for the
Federation of American Scientists, said NASA will fly the shuttle
``until the next time it blows up. I think that's the real
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The shuttles flying today have progressed since the Columbia
orbiter first took to space in 1981. NASA has tinkered with shuttle
hardware all along as new orbiters were built, but the Challenger
explosion resulted in hundreds of changes across the fleet to
increase safety, from redesigned rocket boosters to more powerful
flight control computers.
</P>
<P>
   More improvements are on the way, some $2.2 billion worth to
both the shuttles and the ground support systems. NASA will spend
the next five years building a stronger external tank, improving
the shuttles' engines to allow them to detect problems before they
happen, and moving to a ``smart cockpit'' that will automate more
tasks now handled by astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   The planned improvements may be the largest modification ever
for the shuttle fleet, the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, said in a report released last week.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said the improvements may be a little too optimistic,
and that NASA may not be able to get them done on time and within
budget. NASA needs to focus on getting them done by 2005 if it's
serious about moving to another vehicle by 2012, NASA's current
plan, the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala., is in charge
of the fourth major overhaul of the shuttle engines, one of the
major upgrades in the works. According to NASA, the shuttles'
engines operate at greater temperature and pressure extremes than
do any other machines.
</P>
<P>
   One of the planned changes is called the Advanced Health
Monitoring System, which uses an optical and vibration system to
track engine performance. If it detects trouble, it can shut an
engine down before the problem gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We currently use temperature to determine if there's a
problem, but a better way to do that is to monitor vibration,''
said Randy Humphries Jr., the propulsion upgrades manager for the
shuttle at Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The optical system analyzes the plume coming out of the engines
to see if there's a problem such as engine parts breaking loose,
Humphries said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall workers are also moving to a new welding system for the
external tank that will make it stronger, and changes to the rocket
boosters to make their solid fuel less prone to cracking during
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA plans to fly the shuttle to at least 2010, 2012,''
Humphries said. ``We have to do the supportability items to keep it
flying the next 10 or 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Space Flight Center is also in charge of managing the
X-33 program, which is intended to lead to a commercially built
vehicle called VentureStar that could one day perform many tasks
handled by the shuttle or even replace it entirely.
</P>
<P>
   But that program's development has been more of a challenge than
NASA and lead contractor Lockheed Martin expected. Manufacturing
delays have put its future in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   NASA had hoped to settle on a shuttle successor by 2005, with
the idea it would be ready to fly about five years later. Pike said
that date is ``vaporware,'' a computer industry term for software
or hardware that is announced but arrives late or never.
</P>
<P>
   NASA had been cutting back on the resources it was spending on
the shuttle after it handed over launch preparation and maintenance
work to United Space Alliance a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That cutback has been reversing after reviews showed that NASA
workers in shuttle-related safety and upgrade jobs and oversight
jobs were being overstressed and overworked.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, in fact, the shuttle is going to be
busier than ever as it makes more than three dozen flights to build
the space station.
</P>
<P>
   King said even if VentureStar does eventually show up, it won't
necessarily put the shuttle out of business. The shuttle was
designed as a do-everything workhorse, and VentureStar initially
will probably be just a cargo carrier.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle allows astronauts to float in space and wrangle with
wayward satellites or space telescopes that need updating.
VentureStar probably won't allow that, King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have the capabilities that the space shuttle has in
many areas, such as assembly and disassembly in orbit,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has good reasons to want to move away from the shuttle.
It's a big, complex, expensive vehicle. In fact, NASA touts it as
being the most complex machine ever built.
</P>
<P>
   It has more than 2.5 million parts, including 230 miles of wire
and more than 27,000 insulating tiles and thermal blankets to
protect it from the heat of re-entry.
</P>
<P>
   All that means it's expensive to fly. NASA Administrator Dan
Goldin has repeatedly complained that the high cost of flying
payloads to space, some $10,000 per pound, is stifling progress in
space flight.
</P>
<P>
   Such a complex vehicle also requires a horde of technicians to
keep it ready. King said United Space Alliance has 3,850 workers
who process the shuttle after each flight and get it ready for the
next one. According to the GAO, that requires 1.2 million separate
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not fly very often, it's very expensive and is of
uncertain reliability,'' said Pike of the Federation of American
Scientists. ``On the other hand, we have two decades of experience
with the shuttle and it's a known quantity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
