<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTALSERVICE-FEDEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTAL SERVICE AND FEDEX CONSIDER FORMING PARTNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service and FedEx Corp. are discussing a
partnership that would help the service increase revenue while
giving FedEx a low-cost way to reach millions of residential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Postmaster General William Henderson said Thursday that
executives from both organizations had been meeting in Washington
and Memphis, where FedEx is based, and that the outline of a deal
could be ready to be presented to the service's 11-member board as
early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic that we can reach some agreement,'' he said.
``We think there are big opportunities for the Postal Service and
FedEx.''
</P>
<P>
   FedEx also confirmed that the two sides were talking, but a
spokesman declined to provide any details.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said that the alliance could enable the Postal Service
to take advantage of FedEx's extensive air network while letting
FedEx piggyback on the Postal Service's network of mail carriers.
For example, mail carriers could pick up returns for FedEx's
catalog clients on their regular rounds, saving FedEx the expense
of having to visit thousands of homes.
</P>
<P>
   A partnership between the post office and FedEx could be a blow
to United Parcel Service, which is the industry leader, delivering
12 million packages a day. FedEx delivers 3.3 million shipments a
day. It dominates the overnight segment of the market and has been
trying to expand its less speedy ground-delivery service.
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson said that the post office would not make an
exclusive agreement with FedEx on any service accept a contract to
provide air transportation. ``In terms of access or use of the
postal service or leveraging our assets, we are open to negotiating
with anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may blunt some of the opposition to a deal but also make it
less attractive for FedEx. ``If they are saying, `We would like to
strike a deal with FedEx, UPS, DHL and anybody else who is
interested,' said Norman Black, a UPS spokesman, ``yes, we would
seriously look at what they are proposing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that it did not appear that that was what the Postal
Service was doing based on reports of the talks, which appeared
Thursday in The Washington Post and The Wall Street Journal. ``You
are left with the impression that they would use taxpayer-paid
employees to favor one competitor over another,'' Black said. ``And
we don't believe that Congress and the United States Postal Rate
Commission would find that proper.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of an $800 million shortfall in revenue, the post office
is expected to lose $300 million in the fiscal year ending this
month, its first loss since 1994. During the heavy mailing seasons
each fall and winter, the service makes substantial profits that
are whittled away when mail volume drops in the spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said that he was looking for ways to increase revenue
and offset the fixed costs of the Postal Service's vast delivery
network by, in effect, renting it out to companies like FedEx.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of FedEx fell 45 cents Thursday, to $39.82, on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
