<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-OVERHAUL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QWEST TO CUT 12,800 JOBS AND INCREASE CAPITAL SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Qwest Communications, a fast-growing provider of
telecommunications services, said Thursday that it would cut nearly
13,000 jobs and increase capital spending in an effort to heighten
efficiency after its $44 billion acquisition of U S West.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is based in Denver, will lay off 11,000 staff
employees, more than 15 percent of its work force, and 1,800
contractors, although it was not clear which geographic regions
would be hardest hit by the layoffs. The cuts will mainly affect
nonunion and middle-management positions, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest's capital expenditures will amount to $9 billion this year
and $9.5 billion in 2001, figures that surpass Wall Street
estimates by as much as $1.5 billion. The company expects revenue
of $18.8 billion to $19.1 billion this year and $21.3 billion to
$21.7 billion next year. The revenue estimates are only marginally
better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Though investors are usually enamored of companies that trim
their work forces to cut costs, traders were apparently shaken by
concern that Qwest's unexpected growth in capital spending would
not correspond to a healthy increase in cash flow. The stock fell
$2.06, or 4 percent, to $49.44 in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, Qwest, which has largely focused on fast-growing
areas like Web-hosting and high-speed Internet access, had escaped
the malaise that has gripped investor sentiment in the
telecommunications industry in recent months because the company is
considered to have less exposure to the squeeze in revenue from
traditional long-distance operations.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest, with 71,000 employees, operates a data and voice network
spanning more than 150 cities in the United States and Mexico. In
addition, the company gained about 25 million local phone service
customers in 14 states after buying U S West.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the drop Thursday, Qwest shares have risen 13.4
percent this year, compared with declines of 42.4 percent in
WorldCom and 40 percent in AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest
telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Qwest took the market by surprise with a barrage of
announcements that investors need time to analyze,'' said Brian
Hayward, who manages the $3.6 billion Invesco Telecommunications
Fund in Denver. ``We're in wait-and-see mode, where the best stock
in its peer group is coming under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the combination of Qwest, a company that is at the
forefront of the changes washing over the telecommunications
industry, with U S West, a slower-growing company that was
considered something of a laggard even when compared with its Baby
Bell counterparts, was not expected to be completed without
glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digesting U S West is not a simple task,'' said Jeffrey Kagan,
an independent telecommunications analyst. ``Qwest is still intent
on being disruptive to its competitors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
