<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-HNS &LR;      09-07 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUCHANAN ATTEMPTS TO BLOCK RIVAL'S CLAIM TO $12.6 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reform Party hopeful Patrick Buchanan announced
Thursday that he will try to block the effort of his rival, John
Hagelin, to win $12.6 million in federal election funds.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he will file a lawsuit challenging Hagelin's claim
to be the party's nominee in 11 states.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission _ which will decide who gets the
money _ requires that any candidate applying for the funds must be
on the ballot in at least 10 states as the party's nominee.
Buchanan, a former Republican, submitted his list of states on Aug.
25 while Hagelin, a physicist from Fairfield, Iowa, who is also the
presidential candidate for the Natural Law Party, turned in his
list last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan officials disputed four of Hagelin's states _
Arizona, Idaho, Utah and Wyoming _ saying they already had
certified Buchanan as the party nominee. In addition, they said, a
fifth state, Tennessee, has agreed to put both candidates on the
ballot, which would make it ineligible for FEC consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Buchanan, who heads her brother's campaign, said Thursday
that ``John Hagelin is a fraud scheming to deceive the FEC.'' She
charged that he ``has no claim, no standing, and no right to the
Reform Party's election funds.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to the decision Wednesday by Wyoming's secretary of
state that Patrick Buchanan will be on the ballot there as the
Reform Party's candidate. Hagelin is to appear under the Natural
Law Party banner, disqualifying him from appearing on another part
of the ballot there.
</P>
<P>
   The other six states claimed by Hagelin are Colorado, Illinois,
New Mexico, Ohio, Oregon and Washington. Hagelin spokesman Robert
Roth said he was ``confident that the courts and the FEC will
ultimately decide in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed by Buchanan claim he has the Reform Party ballot
line in Alaska, Arizona, Delaware, Idaho, Maryland, New Jersey, New
Mexico, South Dakota, Utah and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   FEC officials could not be reached for comment, but a public
hearing on the case is scheduled for Tuesday, with a decision
expected within a few days. However, the loser may ask for another
hearing, which would delay a final decision by 15 days. The hearing
is expected to focus on whether both men followed the Reform
Party's nominating rules during its convention in Long Beach,
Calif., last month. Roth said Hagelin attorneys will offer evidence
of massive vote fraud by Buchanan. They will claim that he sent
about 500,000 primary ballots to people on his Republican donor
list, asking them to vote for him in the Reform Party's mail-in
primary and that the vast majority of these people did not request
the ballots, which party rules require.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said that a random check of 14 Buchanan primary voters in
Iowa found that 12 had not asked for the ballots. If FEC officials
look carefully into the matter, Roth said, ``there is no way they
could give the money to Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan officials deny any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   At the Reform Party Convention, Buchanan won 49,529 votes while
Hagelin got 28,539. At a rump convention Hagelin won.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hagelin filed a claim in a California Superior Court
in Long Beach asking a judge to declare him the sole nominee for
that state's Reform Party. The action came one day after Buchanan
filed an identical claim.
</P>
<P>
   The filings represent the first time that a court has been asked
to decide which candidate will represent the party for a particular
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision in the California could be extremely important in
swaying other states and perhaps even the FEC,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing in that case is scheduled to begin Wednesday with a
decision expected within a week.The Reform Party's nominee is
entitled to the federal money because Ross Perot, the movement's
candidate in 1996, received 8 percent of the presidential vote,
exceeding the commission's 5 percent requirement.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
