<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRITISH INTEREST RATE UNCHANGED
</P>
<P>
   With signs that economic growth is easing, the Bank of England
left its benchmark interest rate unchanged at 6 percent for the
seventh consecutive month. The decision had little impact on
foreign exchange markets, where the British pound has slipped by 6
percent against the dollar in the last three months. The bank's
decision coincided with data suggesting that car sales are falling,
a housing boom is cooling and both retail prices and wage increases
are slowing. The combination left inflation in July at an
annualized 2.2 percent, below the government's target of 2.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERMARKET ACQUISITION
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch supermarket retailer Royal Ahold NV is to expand its
operations in Spain with the purchase of the Superdiplo chain of
food and general merchandise stores for 1.2 billion euros ($1
billion) worth of shares. Once it is complete, the purchase will
add hundreds of stores to Ahold's operations in Spain and is
expected to generate sales of about 2 billion euros, Ahold said.
The company also will assume 153 million euros in Superdiplo debt.
At the news, Ahold's share prices lost as much as 5 percent of
their value on the Amsterdam stock exchange. The retailer is active
in the United States, Europe, Latin America and Asia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INVENSYS SHARES FALL
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Invensys PLC fell 36 percent, their largest drop since
the company was created through a merger 18 months ago, after the
company warned that first half profit would fall below last year's
levels. Invensys, a British industrial equipment maker, said it
would cut as many as 3,000 jobs in the United States and Mexico and
accelerate a reorganization plan. The cuts would be in addition to
1,000 jobs that are expected to be eliminated as a result of
Invensys' $747 million purchase of Baan NV, a Dutch software maker
that has been losing money. Invensys attributed the shortfall to a
drop in U.S. business, sluggish oil and gas spending and an
accounting change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE ACQUISITION
</P>
<P>
   Abbey National PLC has agreed to buy Scottish Provident, an
Edinburgh-based life insurance company, for 1.8 billion pounds
(about $2.6 billion) in an effort to diversify as competition
erodes profits in its core mortgage lending business. The new
company will be the largest life insurer in Britain. Abbey National
said it expected the purchase to enhance earnings within the first
year, and to generate (PS)93 million in cost savings within two
years. The Scottish Provident brand will be retained. ``The
transaction delivers on our stated strategy of significantly
diversifying our business,'' said Ian Harley, Abbey National's
chief executive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELLULAR PHONE SPINOFF
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican telecommunications giant Telefonos de Mexico said
that it would create a spinoff company called America Movil which
will undertake all of Telmex's foreign investments, principally in
Latin American cellular phone services. Telmex's cellular phone
subsidiary, Telcel, which controls 70 percent of the national
market, will become part of America Movil, which will take over
Telmex's existing wireless services in Brazil, Puerto Rico and
Guatemala. The Telmex president, Carlos Slim Domit, Latin America's
richest man, said that the separation would give his cell phone
businesses more independence and flexibility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-LANGUAGE TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TV Azteca, the world's second-largest Spanish-language
broadcaster, has joined with Pappas Telecasting of the United
States to create a new television network called Azteca America
Inc., which aims to capture 25 percent of the total U.S. television
market within five years. TV Azteca and Pappas, which will control
20 and 80 percent of the network, respectively, hope to reach 130
million Spanish-speaking viewers in North America by the start of
next year. Azteca America's principal competitor in the rapidly
growing Hispanic market in the United States is Univision, which is
part owned by the largest Spanish-language network in the world,
Televisa of Mexico. The majority of the new network's programming
will come from TV Azteca's Mexican studios although some shows will
be produced locally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IMPERIAL BANK PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Canada's second-largest bank, Canadian Imperial Bank of
Commerce, reported third-quarter operating profit of 380 million
Canadian dollars ($256 million), or 93 Canadian cents a share,
higher than the 86 cents consensus forecast by analysts surveyed by
FirstCall/Thomson Financial. With after-tax gains from selling a
portion of its investment in Global Crossing Ltd., a
telecommunications company, and some real estate assets, the bank's
total profit was 601 million Canadian dollars ($406 million). Like
most other big Canadian banks, CIBC's profit for the quarter ended
July 31 was higher than a year earlier, but lower than in the
previous quarter because of weaker financial markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
