<SLUG> BC-ABC-KOPPEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOPPEL SIGNS DEAL TO CONTINUE ON `NIGHTLINE' FOR 5 MORE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ted Koppel, the anchor of ABC News' ``Nightline''
since it made its debut in 1980, has agreed to stay with the
program for the next five years, though he will appear as the
anchor less frequently, executives announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under a five-year contract with ABC News that he signed
Thursday, Koppel will be the anchor three nights a week starting in
January. He had previously been under contract to anchor the
program, which is shown Mondays through Fridays at 11:35 p.m., four
nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   Koppel has also agreed to be the host of six special, weeklong
``Nightline'' series a year and, when important news breaks, to
anchor prime-time editions of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightline'' has been a strong ratings performer for two
decades, though it has shown some weakness recently. With an
average of 4.4 million people tuning in each night, its audience is
down about 9 percent compared with this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Koppel, 60, had been telegraphing a desire for a
diminished role with ``Nightline'' in order to pursue opportunities
on the Internet and at the same time prepare to make way for a
successor. He said Thursday that he believed the new contract would
allow him to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying that I believe that a prudent thing to do is
to have a transition period that is so long and so gradual and so
smooth that when it finally happens, the public won't even notice
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has assigned Tom Sievers, the ``Nightline'' senior field
producer, to oversee the program on a daily basis. He will report
to Tom Bettag, the executive producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
