<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Sept. 8 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT (United Nations) _ Ledeall of the summit:
As 15 heads of government meet as the U.N. Security Council,
President Clinton pleads for a broader definition of ``security''
that would include human rights, concern for the poor, etc. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-MIDEAST (United Nations) _ Mideast developments from the
U.N. meetings. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Dayton, Ohio) _ Fighting to regain his footing
after weeks of setbacks and missteps, Gov. George W. Bush on
Thursday said he was reshaping his campaign to show him in more
settings interacting with voters, and he pulled out the Gulf War
heroes of his father's administration to endorse him on the stump.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT11,12.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-LAWYER (Undated) _ Edward D. Fagan, once a
little-known personal injury lawyer from New Jersey, is likely to
earn millions of dollars in legal fees for pursuing his audacious
idea to sue European banks in the theft of money 50 years ago from
those who died in the Holocaust. As he recast himself as a ``human
rights'' lawyer, Fagan left neglected personal-injury clients in
his wake, abandoning their claims or not returning their phone
calls for years, according to court papers and interviews. One
former client recently won a malpractice judgment against Fagan and
ethics officials in New Jersey filed a misconduct complaint against
him last month on behalf of another client. Fagan, so at ease with
using the emotional force of the Holocaust as a weapon, also
ignored for months scores of plaintive calls and letters from aging
Nazi-era survivors anxious about whether their claims had been
received, according to a paralegal who worked last year for him. By
Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT32.
</P>
<P>
   (Editors, a report prepared in conjunction with this article
will be televised Friday night on the ABC News program ``20/20.''
It is broadcast under an agreement between The New York Times and
ABC News.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS (New York) _ A profile of the witness behind
the construction industry mob arrests announced on Tuesday. He's a
street tough from the Bronx who married into the mob at its highest
level in New Jersey, came to work the rackets in Manhattan, and who
ultimately quit as the pressure grew to be too much and he feared
for his life. By C.J. Chivers.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAYA-PALACE (Undated) _ In a remote jungle of Guatemala,
among the remains of a little-known ancient city with a name
meaning ``place of serpents,'' archaeologists have uncovered one of
the largest and most splendid palaces of Maya kings ever
discovered. Its more than 170 high-ceiling rooms were built around
11 courtyards and spread over an area greater than two football
fields. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT27,28,29,30.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-SAFETY (Washington) _ What available data could and could
not have showed about problems with Firestone tires. By Matthew L.
Wald and Josh Barbanel.
</P>
