<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5409 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-SEASON-HIGHLIGHTS-     09-07 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-HIGHLIGHTS-$ADV10-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE TV SEASON: KEN BURNS, NAPOLEON AND PLENTY OF
PSEUDO `SEX' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(Eds.: Time, channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 &HT;     By BILL CARTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   September
</P>
<P>
   ``ON OUR OWN TERMS: MOYERS ON DYING'' _ Not a title calculated
to drive ratings, that's for sure. Four 90-minute reports on
end-of-life journeys, with those on the road as well as their loved
ones and caregivers. PBS, starting Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``GIRLFRIENDS'' _ A series whose name may be the most-used word
in comedies with mainly black casts. It's built on the
relationships among four young black women _ and yes, that is the
same number as ``Sex and the City.'' UPN, Mondays at 9:30, starting
Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``ONE DAY IN SEPTEMBER'' _ The Oscar-winning documentary about
the attack on Israeli athletes at the 1972 Munich Olympics comes to
television. It covers the events from the hostage-taking through
the futile negotiations to the violent conclusion. It includes an
interview with the only surviving Arab terrorist, Jamal al-Gashey,
who has been in hiding for 28 years. HBO, Sept. 11 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``TWO-MINUTE DRILL'' _ What does Michael Davies, the production
mastermind behind ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' do for an
encore? He does a sports quiz show, with Kenny Mayne as host and
with three contestants showing off their arcane knowledge in an
effort to win cash prizes that escalate _ but slowly. And only up
to $200,000, not a million. As a producer put it: ``Hey, we're
cable.'' Then again, how much should you get for knowing things
like who has the Kansas City Royals' season record for home runs?
(OK, I know, it's Steve Balboni, 36.) ESPN, Mondays at 7, starting
Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE ELIAN GONZALEZ STORY'' _ And the winner in the latest rush
to make a ripped-from-the-headlines movie is: Fox Family Channel,
which beat out CBS, whose movie of the same title is not yet
scheduled. Here a child actor named Alec Roberts plays Elian, with
Esai Morales as his father and Laura Elena Harring as Marisleysis
Gonzalez. The events should be rather familiar. Fox Family, Sept.
17 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``FEAR'' _ ``Blair Witch'' meets ``Survivor.'' Young contestants
compete to survive in a setting with a horrifying background while
they are constantly harassed and scared out of their wits. They all
have cameras attached to their vests. MTV, Sept. 21 at 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``DIRECT EFFECT'' _ An effort to link online fascination with
video fascination: Viewers vote online for the next video they want
to see, mixed in with the usual guests and live performances. It
sounds a bit like Total Online Request Live. The host is the
one-named Teck, of ``Real World'' fame. MTV, starting Sept. 25 at
5:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN MASTERS: CLINT EASTWOOD'' _ One of the most reliably
fascinating PBS series takes a look at the now esteemed actor and
director as he hits 70. PBS, Sept. 27 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   October
</P>
<P>
   ``JACKASS'' _ An off-beat show with silly pranks and antics
performed by Johnny Knoxville, exploring the underground world of
skateboarders. MTV, starting Oct. 1 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``DEADLINE'' _ Nobody in television makes better crime dramas
than Dick Wolf of ``Law and Order,'' but here he is trying a
hybrid: Crime and journalism. Oliver Platt plays a famous
of-the-street columnist for a New York tabloid; he also teaches
journalism, and he and his team of young students investigate
crimes on the side. The cast includes such familiar names as Bebe
Neuwirth, Lili Taylor and Tom Conti. NBC, Mondays at 9, starting
Oct 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``FRONTLINE: THE CHOICE'' _ In what is now something of a
tradition, the documentary series takes a close look at the men
running for president. Reported by Peter Boyer, the program
promises to avoid pundits and stick to friends, mentors and
historians. PBS, Oct. 2 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``TUCKER'' _ In television, no good show goes unparroted. In
this case, ``Malcolm in the Middle'' seems the obvious inspiration,
though this is clearly a less-inspired version. A teen-age boy
finds his life in disarray after his parents' divorce, and he and
his mother are forced to move in with his strident aunt and her
slug of a son. Katey Sagal (``Married With Children'') is the aunt,
while Eli Marienthal (``American Pie'') plays Tucker. NBC, Mondays
at 8:30, starting Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``YES, DEAR'' _ A comedy less notable for its premise _ two
couples who are close friends differ about approaches to being
parents _ than its cast, which features not one, but two former
stars of famously failed ``must see'' Thursday-night comedies on
NBC: Mike O'Malley of ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' and Anthony Clark
of ``Boston Common.'' CBS, Mondays at 8:30, starting Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``BUILDING BIG'' _ A five-hour look at some of the most
spectacular structures in the world, including the Channel tunnel,
the Golden Gate Bridge and the Toronto Skydome. The host is the
author and illustrator David Macaulay (``The Way Things Work'').
PBS, starting Oct. 3 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``DARK ANGEL'' _ This is the first creative work undertaken by
James Cameron since ``Titanic,'' and while not quite as ambitious,
it is a highly polished piece of science fiction entertainment with
a young star, Jessica Alba (``Can't Hardly Wait''), who commands
the screen. She plays a superwoman type who has escaped a genetic
experiment in a post-apocalyptic future, when the world's economic
system has collapsed, and teams with a streaming-video journalist
to expose the bad guys. Among her other amazing talents, Alba
manages to support lips that look like they're been stung by a
whole hive of bees. Fox, Tuesdays at 9, starting Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GEENA DAVIS SHOW'' _ Truly a star vehicle, this show wants
to be ``Sex and the City'' crossed with a family comedy, a tall
order. But then Geena Davis is a  &UR; really &LR;  tall actress. She plays a
Manhattan career woman who marries a divorced guy (Peter Horton of
``Thirtysomething'') with kids, making her an instant mom. It's a
well-positioned show that will do well if it's well executed. ABC,
Tuesdays at 9:30, starting Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``GIDEON'S CROSSING'' _ The season's most serious drama, with
the estimable Andre Braugher of ``Homicide'' moving into medicine
at a teaching hospital that takes on desperate cases. It's heavy
going, especially with many patients facing terminal illnesses, but
Braugher has big acting shoulders. Reuben Blades co-stars. ABC,
Wednesdays at 10, starting Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``TITANS'' _ The season's standout in terms of sheer silliness,
the latest soap opera from Aaron Spelling seems unsure itself
whether its hilarious hokiness is intentional. It's about the usual
stuff: The members of a rich, venal family scheme to ruin one
another, mainly through sex. Yasmine Bleeth has the juicy vixen
role, though her supposedly venomous lines draw mostly laughs. But
Spelling has mined this territory successfully before. Victoria
Principal of ``Dallas'' makes a comeback as an older-generation
vixen. NBC, Wednesdays at 8, starting Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``GILMORE GIRLS'' _ A gentle, quirky multigenerational drama
with a light touch about a mother and her daughter in a Connecticut
town. Lauren Graham stars as the mom, with Alexis Blendel as the
other Gilmore girl. WB, Thursdays at 8, starting Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``C.S.I.'' _ A crime drama with a heavy emphasis on forensic
science, this hour has a number of things going for it, including a
reasonably intelligent approach and a cast headed by Marg
Helgenberger (``China Beach'') and William Petersen (``The Rat
Pack''). The producer is Jerry Bruckheimer, who usually blows
things up in the movies. CBS, Fridays at 9, starting Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``FREAKYLINKS'' _ Inevitably, we have a show about a Web site.
This one has ties to the makers of ``The Blair Witch Project'' and
tries to make a similarly scary name for itself. A team of young
hunters of the paranormal traces strange links to the death of a
team member's brother. There is, of course, a real Web site to feed
the hoped-for frenzy of interest. Fox, Fridays at 9, starting Oct.
6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``THE FUGITIVE'' _ What's it been? Forty years? It's actually
been 37 since the original series made its debut, and it's already
been updated once as a movie, but the old chase is back. Dr.
Richard Kimble, convicted of murdering his wife, runs from Lt.
Gerard, while simultaneously seeking the one-armed man who did the
deed. Tim Daly gets the David Janssen/Harrison Ford part, with
Mykelti Williamson stepping in for Barry Morse/Tommy Lee Jones. In
case anybody's still wondering, Dr. Kimble didn't do it. CBS,
Fridays at 8, starting Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``MADIGAN MEN'' _ Another show with roots in ``Sex and the
City.'' This one would like to take a look at the male side, as
long as that means men with Irish roots who share a Manhattan
apartment and spout cute Irish aphorisms. Gabriel Byrne, a true
potential television star, is the newly single man with a teen-age
son and a dad from the old sod, played by Roy Dotrice, who also
played opposite Byrne on Broadway in ``Moon for the Misbegotten.''
ABC, Fridays at 9:30, starting Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE TROUBLE WITH NORMAL'' _ What does that title mean? No,
there is no character named Normal; instead, there are two paranoid
characters who think their neighbor is spying on them. Jon Cryer,
who has had numerous shots in television comedies in the past,
plays the neighbor who is equally paranoid and actually  &UR; is &LR;  spying
on them. They all go to a therapist. Many people have paranoid
tendencies, which perhaps sets up a sizable audience, but do people
who are paranoid find paranoia funny? ABC, Fridays at 8:30,
starting Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DISTRICT'' _ A crime drama that aims to be edgy, but may
be asking for trouble: A white police chief, played by Craig T.
Nelson, moves to Washington to clean up a town where black leaders
have failed. Some genuinely gripping moments could get lost in the
potential controversy. CBS, Saturdays at 10, starting Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``STAGE ON SCREEN: THE MAN WHO CAME TO DINNER'' _ A live
performance of the current Broadway production of the Kaufman and
Hart play, with Nathan Lane and Jean Smart. PBS, Oct. 7 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``THAT'S LIFE'' _ Another show looking to duplicate the ``you
can go home again'' premise of ``Providence,'' this quirky-funny
hour has some nice character work from Heather Paige Kent (``Stark
Raving Mad'') as a woman in her 30s who dumps her fiance and goes
back to college, and from Paul Sorvino and Ellen Burstyn as her
parents. CBS, Saturdays at 8, starting Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``ED'' _ The one new NBC series that seems to be getting an
affectionate response, this gentle, likable hourlong comedy is not
big on laughs but it works because of its sweet characters. Tom
Cavanaugh (``Providence'') reacts to the misfortune of losing his
job and his wife (to the mailman) in the same day by fleeing to his
hometown, a recurring theme this season. There he essentially
resurrects his adolescence, reuniting with high school friends and
even chasing the unattainable girl from those years. To accomplish
that, he buys a local bowling alley, where he also dispenses legal
advice. Even though it's from two of David Letterman's longtime
writers, Rob Burnett and John Beckerman, it's a show that could
give warm and fuzzy a good name. NBC, Sundays at 8, starting Oct.
8.
</P>
<P>
   ``HYPE'' _ A cast of newcomers tries to bring the sketch comedy
formula up to date in a weekly series of fast-paced parodies of
youth-oriented movies and music. WB, still sticking to the recipe
that built the Fox network, tries to re-create the magic of ``In
Living Color.'' WB, Sundays at 9, starting Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``NIKKI'' _ Looking for new venues and new characters, Bruce
Helford, the creator of ``The Drew Carey Show,'' goes all the way
to Las Vegas to build a comedy around a dancer on the Strip, played
by Nikki Cox of ``Norm,'' who is married to a big lug who wants to
be a wrestler. WB, Sundays at 9:30, starting Oct 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``OLIVER TWIST'' _ The big ``Masterpiece Theater'' effort of the
season, a three-part adaptation of the Dickens book with Robert
Lindsay, Julie Walters and Michael Kitchen. PBS, starting Oct. 8 at
9.
</P>
<P>
   ``BETTE'' _ The most anticipated new comedy of the season, with
Bette Midler playing a version of herself, in the throwback style
of ``Burns and Allen'' or ``The Jack Benny Program.'' Actors play
the other members of her family, as well as her manager and
accompanist, but the show is all about Midler, with a lot of her
brand of broad comedy mixed with regular bursts of music. That has
always been a winning formula for her, and it should be here, too.
CBS, Wednesdays at 8, starting Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``WELCOME TO NEW YORK'' _ A comedy with most of the conventions
intact _ a fish out of water shines in a new work environment _ but
in this case the writing makes it exceed the preconceptions. Jim
Gaffigan plays an Indiana guy brought in to be a weather reporter
for a television show in New York by the brassy producer, played by
Christine Baranski. Watch for an unusual clash between Gaffigan's
character and the entrenched anchorman, played by Rocky Carroll.
CBS, Wednesday at 8:30 starting Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``CURSED'' _ For how many years now has NBC tried to make
comedies hits by slotting them in the ideal location, Thursdays at
9? So many that the title of this one seems all too apt. Steven
Weber (``Wings'') plays a man whose comfortable life falls apart
after a bad date, when the woman puts a curse on him. Yeah, and
then what happens? That's the part that nobody seems to know. NBC,
Thursdays at 9:30, starting Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``CURB YOUR ENTHUSIASM'' _ One of the wildest and most promising
new series of the season. It is the creation of Larry David, the
comic mind behind many of the greatest episodes of ``Seinfeld,''
and is improvised from basic story lines. David plays himself as a
stand-up comic surrounded by dysfunctional, loony friends. It
sounds like ``Seinfeld,'' but it's much different _ after all, it's
on cable. HBO, starting Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: THE ROCKEFELLERS'' _ A two-part biography
of the rich American family, from the early days of Standard Oil to
the current generation. From producers who previously chronicled
the Kennedy family and Ronald Reagan. PBS, starting Oct. 16 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``SPIDERGAMES'' _ The first original daytime soap opera on
cable, about a family investigating the murder of the most hated
man in town. Everyone is a suspect and an heir to his video-game
empire. MTV, starting Oct. 16 at 4:30, repeating at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE FEARING MIND'' _ Here's the concept: Stephen King and his
New England family in a sitcom. A horror novelist named Bill
Fearing has real-life horrors, including a mother-in-law who said
she had one month to live five years ago _ and other wacky stuff
like that. The British actor Harry Van Gorkum, whose name sounds
like a Stephen King character, stars, with Susan Gibney. Fox
Family, starting Oct. 20 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``BOSTON PUBLIC'' _ A drama about life in a high school would
not sound too promising if it were not coming from David E. Kelley,
who has made ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice'' into two of the
best series of the last five years. Here the challenge is making
daily high school life dramatic and funny, and it's a bit of a
stretch. A plot in which a teacher fired a gun in a classroom drew
instant protest, and Kelly promised changes. As usual, his writing
is of a high quality and so is much of the acting, led by Chi
McBride as an intense principal. Fox, Mondays at 8, starting Oct.
23.
</P>
<P>
   ``HATE.COM: EXTREMISTS ON THE INTERNET'' _ A documentary about
how hatemongers have used the Web to find new recruits, spread
their messages and in some instances even set up hate crimes. HBO,
Oct. 23 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MICHAEL RICHARDS SHOW'' _ Here is NBC's great comedy hope,
the first new series starring a ``Seinfeld'' grad. And what's
happened? It has been one stumble after another, not unlike the
ones that used to afflict Kramer. Except that those were funny. The
original pilot was totally scrapped. No one knows much about the
new one except that Richards is still playing a bumbling detective.
He does have co-stars now, including Tim Meadows (``Saturday Night
Live'') and William Devane (``The Hollow Man''). NBC, Tuesdays at
8, starting Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``FREEDOM'' _ More apocalypse mongering from the producer Joel
Silver, who hit it big with ``The Matrix.'' Much about this one is
``Matrix''-like, including the premise of a resistance unit
fighting an evil military elite that has taken over humanity. UPN,
Fridays at 8, starting Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``LEVEL NINE'' _ Crime fighting goes totally cyber in this hour
about a secret group created to fight Internet villains, like
hackers who blackmail airlines by threatening to crash airplanes.
Created by John Sacret Young (``China Beach''). UPN, Fridays at 9,
starting Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``FALLING IN LOVE AGAIN'' _ Valerie Bertinelli, who was once in
every other TV movie, returns to play a romantic role in another
generation: Now she's the mom with the teen-age children. The kids
plot to bring Valerie and Jeffrey Nadling, who plays the dad, back
together in a story that is set on a tourist ranch in the wilds of
Alaska. CBS in October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``SECOND HONEYMOON'' _ Roma Downey and Tim Matheson star in
another movie about a couple that just can't seem to break up. Here
the soon-to-be-divorced pair get a surprise 20th-anniversary gift
from the family: A tropical vacation. It works wonders. CBS in
October.
</P>
<P>
   November
</P>
<P>
   ``NORMAL, OHIO'' _ A troubled comedy that still has a great
asset, John Goodman, as star. Goodman plays a father who happens to
be gay; he moves back to his hometown and comedy is meant to ensue.
But this is an all-new premise _ a first pilot was totally remade _
so the result is harder to predict than usual. Fox, Wednesdays at
8, starting Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE STREET'' _ The true heir to ``Sex and the City,'' because
it comes from the same creator, Darren Star. This hour is full of
similar steamy touches as it traces the overheated lives, both
professional and social, of a group of young Wall Street brokers
who are on the make _ in more ways than one. The clothes, the music
and the moves are all designed to reveal the male side of the
sexual play featured in Star's HBO hit. Adam Goldberg (``Saving
Private Ryan'') and Tom Everett Scott (``That Thing You Do'') are
among the big, talented, attractive cast. Fox, Wednesdays at 9,
starting Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``JACQUELINE BOUVIER KENNEDY ONASSIS'' _ Yet another Kennedy
family mini-series, of which so many already exist that they could
fill their own cable channel. This one promises the whole story of
Jackie, in four hours, based on the biography by Donald Spoto.
Joanna Whalley, who has one other high-profile television role on
her resume (``Scarlett''), here will try to impersonate perhaps the
most famous woman of the 20th century. CBS, starting Nov. 5 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``NAPOLEON'' _ A four-hour documentary biography of the French
general and emperor, directed by David Grubin, whose previous films
for PBS include ``F.D.R.,'' ``L.B.J.'' and ``Truman'' in the
``American Experience'' series. PBS, Nov. 8 and Nov. 15, at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN TRAGEDY: THE UNCENSORED STORY OF THE SIMPSON
DEFENSE'' _ Destined to be one of the most talked-about projects of
the season, for better or worse, this adaptation of the Lawrence
Schiller book has already been threatened with an injunction by new
lawyers for O.J. Simpson. It is an account of his defense strategy
and the cast of characters includes those familiar names Johnnie
Cochran (Ving Rhames), Robert Shapiro (Ron Silver), F. Lee Bailey
(Christopher Plummer) and Barry Scheck (Bruno Kirby). Told over
four hours _ if no restraining order is issued _ by a production
team led by Barry Levinson and Tom Fontana. CBS, Nov. 12 and Nov.
15 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: RETURN WITH HONOR'' _ A
two-and-a-half-hour account of the sufferings and ultimate
victories of a group of American airmen shot down in Vietnam and
subjected to years of torture before their release. It includes
film from the Vietnamese government archives. Introduced by Tom
Hanks. PBS, Nov. 13 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   `DAG'' _ David Alan Grier is a talented, funny guy, but this is
his third try at sitcom success and it's not the charm. Here he
plays a bumbling Secret Service agent banished to cover the
president's wife (Delta Burke, who may look too much like a certain
young lady in a beret for some people's comfort). The idea is to
make the comedy extremely broad, but that will require generating a
lot more laughs than the pilot did. NBC, Tuesdays at 9:30, starting
Nov. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``NOVA: HITLER'S LOST SUB'' _ About the 1991 discovery of a
sunken World War II U-boat, found only 60 miles off the coast of
New Jersey, with its unexploded torpedoes and the bodies of its
crew still aboard. The documentary follows the efforts of the diver
John Chatterton and his crew to identify and explore the boat, a
quest that cost three more lives. PBS, Nov. 14 at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``LOOKING FOR LOST BIRD'' _ A story of a woman, adopted as an
infant, who searches for her biological parents, discovers they
were Navajo and seeks to learn of their culture. Mercedes Ruehl is
the star, with Jamey Sheridan as her husband. CBS, Nov. 19 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MOVING OF SOPHIA MYLES'' _ Della Reese of ``Touched by an
Angel'' plays yet another heartwarming role: The widow of a
cherished pastor who duels with an evil real estate maven played by
Rue McLanahan. CBS, Nov. 26 at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``FOR LOVE OR COUNTRY: THE ARTURO SANDOVAL STORY'' _ The story
of the brilliant Cuban trumpet player Arturo Sandoval, who refused
to defect after the Castro takeover because of his love for a
woman, but later did so, with the help of Dizzy Gillespie. Andy
Garcia stars in a cast that includes Gloria Estefan and Charles S.
Dutton. HBO in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``GROWING PAINS: THE REUNION'' _ At first glance this seems like
a project conjured up solely to get Leonardo DiCaprio into a
television movie. But he didn't show up for this reunion, of
course, so fans of the series will have to satisfied with Alan
Thicke, who did. ABC in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``IN THE BEGINNING'' _ Religious stories have been unexpected
hits in recent years, so why not go right to basics. It's the
familar roster, including Adam and Eve, Abraham, Isaac, Joseph and
Moses, with a lot of special effects to enhance the telling. Among
the interesting casting choices: Martin Landau as Abraham, and
Billy Campbell of ``Once and Again'' as Moses. NBC in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``IN HIS LIFE: THE JOHN LENNON STORY'' _ A lot of Lennon's early
professional life was covered in the feature film ``Backbeat,'' and
that R-rated material seems unlikely for a network television
movie. This one includes a bit of his troubled childhood, but
shifts quickly to his efforts to form a skiffle band, his meeting
with a mate named Paul, and so on. NBC in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MIRACLE WORKER'' _ Yet another version of the famous play,
which has already been a television special and a movie. Now it's
back to television, almost solely as a vehicle for Hallie Kate
Eisenberg, who in her ubiquitous Pepsi commercials has not
demonstrated quite the acting depth that this part has pulled out
of the likes of Patti Duke. ABC in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``UNFORGETTABLE: THE NATALIE COLE STORY'' _ A television movie
biography of the singer, who endured several rises and falls before
her hit ``duet'' with her dead father. NBC in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``WIDOWS'' _ Three women with extremely different backgrounds
come together after their husbands are killed trying to pull off an
art heist. Over four hours, on two days, they team up to search out
the killer. Mercedes Ruehl is the middle-class housewife, Brooke
Shields is the low-rent actress and Rosie Perez is the used-car
saleswoman. Lynda LaPlante, the creator of the great ``Prime
Suspect'' series, also created the original of this story, which
was a hit in England. ABC in November.
</P>
<P>
   December
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CHRIS ISAAK SHOW'' _ The singer-songwriter plays himself
in a semi-fictional story about a lead singer for a band who is
very much like Chris Isaak. The musicians are real; many of the
backup characters are not. The show has as much music as comedy.
Showtime, starting in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``QUEER AS FOLK'' _ In Britain, this brutally frank drama about
gay life was a sensation. Rather than simply import it, Showtime
decided to make an American version. Pittsburgh steps in to
approximate blue-collar Manchester, and Hal Sparks, who was once
the host of ``Talk Soup,'' stars as Michael, who is secretly in
love with his childhood friend, a drug-addled advertising
executive. The show is steeped in character complications, some
comedic, some heart-tugging, all fiercely realistic. Showtime,
starting in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``SANTA WHO?'' _ The old guy crashes in New York, of all places,
days before Christmas and suffers amnesia. Panicked elves have to
hunt him down. Santa falls in with a Christmas-hating reporter and,
of course, he lands a job as a department store St. Nick. Will
Santa recover his memory in time to save Christmas? Leslie Nielsen,
who already has the hair, if not the girth, stars with Tommy
Davidson of ``Booty Call.'' ABC in December.
</P>
<P>
   January
</P>
<P>
   ``JAZZ'' _ Potentially the outstanding program of the television
season, the latest series from the much-decorated historical
documentarian Ken Burns examines the roots, glories and influences
of the one true American art form, with an emphasis on the role of
race, in 10 parts over 19 hours. PBS, starting Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``BREAKING NEWS'' _ ABC tried to turn sports news into comedy
with ``Sports Night.'' This effort turns to real news in a series
about a 24-hour news channel where the cranky reporters never go to
sleep. It stars Tim Matheson and Rowena King. TNT, starting in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``NERO WOLFE'' _ The rotund, brilliant detective who never
leaves his New York townhouse comes to television, a long while
after he became famous as a descendant of Sherlock Holmes. Rex
Stout created the character and gave him lots of odd puzzles that
he and his legman partner, Archie Goodwin, could solve. Last
season's television movie inspired this series, which A&AMP;E hopes
will snatch up the crowd that loved its Poirot adventures. Maury
Chaykin is the portly, orchid-loving Wolfe, with Timothy Hutton
doing the hard labor as Archie. Hutton also did the hard labor of
writing and directing. A&AMP;E, starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``OZ'' _ A special mid-season edition of the summer hit, serving
as the sub for ``The Sopranos,'' which put its third-season
premiere off until March. So Tom Fontana stepped in with eight new
episodes of his riveting, often brutal prison series. HBO, Sundays
at 9, starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   March
</P>
<P>
   ``101 CENTRE STREET'' A New York night court is the focus of
this series created by the film director Sidney Lumet. The show
will be fictional, but Lumet will try to make it look real by
shooting entirely with handheld video cameras. A&AMP;E, starting in
March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
