<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SHARP-DRIVING0908-COX     09-07 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aerodynamics don't just benefit NASCAR drivers
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Back sometime in the '60s, I recall someone commenting
that a Lotus Europa, or maybe it was an Elan, was so
aerodynamically perfect that you could drive it 100 mph in the rain
and never have to turn on the windshield wipers.
</P>
<P>
   My first thought was why would anyone be going 100 mph in the
rain?
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who were driving in the '60s, the vehicles we
were cruising around in were about as aerodynamic as a brick, and
the windshield wipers were doing well to maintain contact with the
windshield at 55 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It only took 30-something years for the light bulb to come on.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, I was traveling down I-85 from Charlotte,
N.C. to Atlanta in a new Chevrolet Monte Carlo. My husband was
following in another vehicle. I barely noticed that it had begun to
rain. All of sudden, the sky opened up, but my visibility was
perfect. I thought I was imagining things as I watched perfect
little beadlets of water dissipate oh-so-symmetrically across the
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The story about the Lotus crawled out of the cobwebs of my
memory.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that Chevrolet had gone to great lengths to produce an
aerodynamically ``clean'' vehicle. As with most consumers, the
coefficient of drag numbers mean little to me.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the company go to all this trouble? It's pretty
well-accepted that the Monte Carlo is produced for one main
purpose: NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   My husband, Bob _ who for 25 years worked in the engine shops of
the NASCAR teams of Richard Petty, Richard Childress and Darrell
Waltrip _ has long said that the cheapest horsepower you can find
is aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving home, I could hardly wait to show off my newfound
marvel. Bob was a bit uneasy about driving around in the rain with
the wipers off (I did switch them back on when we were stopped for
traffic lights) but had to agree that it was an impressive
demonstration. For the record, we were not traveling 100 mph; the
Monte Carlo cleaned its own windshield quite nicely at 45 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, we both noted that there was little or no road
film or dirt buildup on the side of the Monte Carlo, another
indicator of an aerodynamically ``clean'' vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of good aerodynamics is to reduce drag. That
means to keep the air from ``clinging'' to the vehicle, except
where you want it. Manufacturers spend hundreds of thousands of
dollars doing research in wind tunnels trying to find out just what
we observed going down the road. The water didn't lie on the
windshield, nor did it cling to the side panels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NASCAR Monte Carlos are similar, but not identical, to
the Monte Carlo you will find in the showroom. Except for the
grilles, all the NASCAR race-car bodies _ Chevrolet, Pontiac and
Ford _ are pretty much identical to each other.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll just have to appreciate Chevrolet's _ and other
automakers' _ efforts to improve aerodynamics if not just for the
savings on wiper blades, then for the 28 miles per gallon that a
slick car can get on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
