A5420 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-THE-MECHANIC0908-COX     09-07 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old refrain: Good help is hard to find
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is something I'd hoped would never have to be
written. It's a story about the decline of a reputable auto repair
shop that my mother had entrusted with the mechanical health of her
pet '81 Oldsmobile for over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   My story starts this past summer while I was out West visiting
Mom. We took her car into the shop for an oil change and checkup
before driving it from her home to California. While the car was
being worked on, I chatted with the shop foreman, a man whom I've
respected and trusted to oversee the care of the Olds.
</P>
<P>
   The checkup noted that two of the tires were getting marginal
and the rear brakes were more than half worn. We left for our trip,
confident the Olds was in sound shape.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember if it was the small puddle of oil, the pinging
of the engine or the lack of air conditioning in 100-degree weather
that alerted me to the fact that maybe they had missed a few things
at the shop.
</P>
<P>
   However, when we returned, I went back to the shop and spoke
with the foreman. He answered with two statements that I hear
echoed throughout the auto repair industry.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has to hire mechanics out of the same shallow pool as
every other shop attempting to keep its doors open. Competence and
conscientiousness have become rare traits.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he has become reluctant to even mention needed repairs,
as it tends to scare customers away. People perceive that they are
being ripped off when additional services are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Mom needed to drive the Olds across the country when she moved
here. She made an appointment to have the car completely gone over
before the 2,500-mile trip. I gave her a list of things that needed
to be examined in addition to whatever the inspection revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the repairs, which included valve cover gaskets, a
CV axle, brakes, A/C service, wheel alignment and new tires _ along
with a much needed major tuneup _ exceeded the value of the car,
but Mom gladly paid for the assurance that her baby was in tiptop
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later I got the phone call.
</P>
<P>
   She told me that the car lacked the power it had before and she
smelled gasoline. I responded with, ``Take it back, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Mom, her two dogs and my daughter made it
across the United States without a noticeable mechanical mishap,
except for poor gas mileage. The bad news is I opened the hood.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel dripped from an over-tightened fitting that damaged the
carburetor. Several of the original 20-year-old vacuum lines were
cracked and split, as was a more obvious coolant hose. A thorough
test of the air conditioning system disclosed the need for it to be
reserviced properly. And although the repair order stated the
battery was serviced, it sported a layer of grime and green, fuzzy
terminals.
</P>
<P>
   Mom's car is a testament to the plague that threatens the auto
repair industry. Several automotive industry studies have
determined we have an aging work force of mechanics (averaging
between 42 to 50), with virtually no new blood on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   I used to say, ``How much will you be willing to spend to get
your vehicle repaired?'' I'm beginning believe that no amount of
money will be able to purchase a commodity that is becoming
extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
