<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-OVERRIDE-HNS &LR;      09-07 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERRIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    House fails to override Clinton veto of estate tax bill
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By DAVID IVANOVICH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-led House failed Thursday to
override President Clinton's veto of a $105 billion bill to repeal
the federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   And Republican lawmakers don't plan to try to reach a compromise
with the White House on the issue before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 274 to 157 Thursday to overturn the presidential
veto, 11 votes shy of the two-thirds majority needed.
</P>
<P>
   When the House passed the original bill in June, 65 Democrats
joined with the Republican majority to do away with federal estate,
gift and generation-skipping transfer taxes by 2010. On Thursday,
13 Democrats switched their votes to help sustain the president's
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend the House members who voted today to reject the
majority's flawed estate tax bill,'' Clinton said in a written
statement after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I support estate tax relief that addresses family farms,
small businesses and principal residences, the approach taken by
the majority in Congress is part of a $2 trillion tax plan that
would take us back to the days of deficits, high interest rates and
fiscal irresponsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans promised to remind voters which Democrats changed
their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the ones people ought to focus on when they express
their outrage,'' argued House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar
Land.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats countered that Republicans could have reached a
compromise agreement with them that would have provided some
reduction in estate taxes starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were serious, they would have worked with us,'' argued
Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But DeLay said the White House does not want to provide estate
tax relief this year.
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax, or ``death tax'' as Republicans have come to
call it, was first added to the tax code in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   The tax code currently excludes the first $675,000 from taxation
for most estates and $1.3 million for family-owned farms, ranches
and small businesses. And by 2006, the exclusion for most estates
will climb to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue the estate tax borders on the macabre. ``We say
death as an event should not trigger a tax,'' said House Ways and
Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Houston. ``The death tax
has given purgatory a new meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   They argue that the provision taxes wealth that has already been
taxed.
</P>
<P>
   The repeal effort was supported by numerous business groups,
from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce to the Air Conditioning
Contractors of America.
</P>
<P>
   The White House contended the Republican-backed bill was
targeted toward a small group of wealthy Americans and would cost
too much.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials estimated the measure would cost
government coffers an additional $750 billion in the second decade,
with more than half the benefits going to about 3,000 families a
year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 _ the last year for which the Internal Revenue Service
has data _ less than 2 percent of the families inheriting estates
had to pay an estate tax _ fewer than 43,000 estates in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that the tax affects many more people than
those numbers would suggest, since many families sell their
businesses rather than incur the hefty estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich don't pay these taxes,'' DeLay said. ``It's people
like me, when I used to be in the pest control business.'' (DeLay
sold his business three years ago, incurring a capital gains tax).
</P>
<P>
   Democrats favor a proposal that would raise the exclusion for
family farms and closely held businesses to $2 million and allow
any portion of that exclusion not used when the first spouse dies
to be added to the estate of the surviving spouse.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
