<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-STARR-TRIBUTE-HNS &LR;      09-07 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-TRIBUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IMPEACHMENT PROSECUTORS' FUND GROUP PUTS OFF TRIBUTE TO STARR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (FILED in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A political action committee raising campaign funds
for the House Republican impeachment prosecution team has postponed
a tribute to former Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr scheduled for
Oct. 4, the PAC's director said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Roney, the House Managers PAC director, attributed the
decision to scheduling difficulties. He said the Oct. 4 date would
conflict with the end of the legislative session on Capitol Hill
and the desire of House members to resume campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But Roney acknowledged that the event ``was turning out to be a
little too political.''
</P>
<P>
   Roney and Rep. Chris Cannon, R-Utah, one of 13 House Republicans
who served as prosecutors (also called managers) in last year's
Senate trial of President Clinton, decided to pull the plug after
the event piqued media interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was our blind ignorance, but we didn't think it would
be described as being political,'' Roney said. ``Even though it was
a fundraiser, we didn't want it to be viewed as political _ as a
lot of media were beginning to portray it.'' The managers group did
not want to put Starr in the midst of another political
controversy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The event might be rescheduled for some time after Congress
adjourns next month, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The PAC has raised $70,000 to $80,000, ostensibly for the
re-election of the 11 managers running for re-election to the
House, as well as one _ Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla. _ running for a
vacant U.S. Senate seat. The 13th manager, Rep. Charles Canady,
R-Fla, is not seeking another term.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12, only McCollum and Rep. Jim Rogan, R-Calif., are in
tight election battles. McCollum is neck-and-neck with popular
Florida insurance commissioner Bill Nelson. Rogan is battling
California state Sen. Adam Schiff in a contest that could become
one of the most expensive House races ever. Rogan and Schiff
together have raised $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, the impeachment of President Clinton in 1998
and the failed Senate bid to remove him from office in 1999 have
always been a double-edged sword.
</P>
<P>
   In polls would-be voters rank ``moral values'' high on the list
of significant issues, and most prefer Republicans on issues
relating to these values.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Republican presidential candidate George
W. Bush regularly tells audiences that if he wins the election,
he'll swear to uphold the honor and dignity of the office of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, polls taken during the impeachment effort
showed that while voters disapproved of President Clinton's
personal conduct in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal, they opposed
removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a professor of government at the University of
Virginia, said people ``don't like what (Clinton) did, but they
want to forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans such as Rogan cannot back away from their role in
the matter either, Sabato said, adding, ``When politicians show
fear, they're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign, Rogan stresses issues of local concern in his
Southern California district encompassing Pasadena, Glendale and
Burbank. He talks about impeachment only when a questioner brings
it up at a meeting, his press spokesman Jason Roe said.
</P>
<P>
   The district is undergoing rapid demographic change, with
Hispanics, Asians and Armenians _ who tend to prefer Democrats _
gradually replacing Republican-leaning Anglo voters.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic congressional candidates, including Schiff, have
tried using impeachment to their own advantage. They have accused
Republicans of being consumed with scandal and investigations at
the expense of bread-and-butter issues such as saving Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican strategists view the impeachment imbroglio as a
nonstarter. ``It's not in our interest to keep talking about
Clinton and Monica,'' said one senior Republican official, who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Starr now teaches law at George Mason University in Northern
Virginia and volunteers as an instructor at a high school in
Washington's predominantly black Anacostia section.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
