<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: `KANE' WARS; NEW RELEASES AND POPULAR RENTALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Battle of Egos Over `Kane'
</P>
<P>
   Famous for gathering the Hollywood elite at San Simeon, his
California estate, the press baron William Randolph Hearst was once
asked why he didn't devote himself fully to movies rather than
journalism. ``He said: `You can crush a man with journalism, but
not with motion pictures.' That was his answer,'' Douglas Fairbanks
Jr. says in the documentary ``The Battle Over Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   Released on tape this week by WGBH Boston Video, the 1996
Academy Award-nominated film depicts two gifted egomaniacs in the
process of discovering that, whether by movie or newspaper, those
most damaged could include themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Thomas Lennon and Michael Epstein, the
film, made by WGBH and shown on PBS's ``American Experience,''
skillfully interweaves the gigantic personalities of both Hearst
and Orson Welles, the 24-year-old whose 1941 film starring himself
as the Hearst-like Charles Foster Kane still defines Hearst in the
minds of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time ever, the methods Hearst had used to lay
bare the lives of others had been used on him,'' a commentator says
in the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Being portrayed ultimately as a brooding, isolated wreck, which
he never was, bothered Hearst, but he was primarily incensed over
Welles' depiction of his companion, the actress Marion Davies, as a
featherbrained drunk. Hearst tried to suppress the film by branding
Welles as a communist and a homosexual, among other things. Then he
tried to have the movie destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Welles didn't scare easily, or at all. In 1938 his radio
broadcast ``War of the Worlds'' and its invading Martians panicked
the country and left Welles, then 22, wondering if the fallout
would destroy his career. ``It was the only time I worked with
Orson that I saw him slightly afraid,'' one associate says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the furor greatly bolstered Welles' reputation and
landed him in Hollywood with a large contract. ``Citizen Kane'' was
his first film. ``He always lived phenomenally dangerously,''
Lennon said in an interview. ``Flying into controversy was Welles'
method.''
</P>
<P>
   But the portrayal of Davies was a mistake. In the documentary
Fairbanks calls her a delight, ``full of wit, humor, a glorious
gal.'' Welles, speaking in the film in 1982, three years before his
death, says the depiction was ``something of a dirty trick.''
</P>
<P>
   In the documentary, Herman Mankiewicz, the co-screenwriter of
``Citizen Kane,'' is labeled as Welles' partner in mischief. ``I
think they thought they could get away with it,'' says William
Alland, a Welles colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they realized how touchy the old man was and
this was Hollywood and there would be hell to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   But even that would be all right. ``If Hearst sued that would be
great,'' Alland continues. ``The film would be news everywhere.
They'd drive the old man crazy, turn the town on its ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Welles' career never fully recovered from Hearst's onslaught,
which had lasting repercussions at the studios. Lennon said that
his own film was criticized for implying that ``Citizen Kane''
essentially finished Welles. ``His career wasn't over by 25,'' he
said, ``but it was limited in a way that haunted him for the rest
of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `MISSION TO MARS'
</P>
<P>
   Washed out of a mission to Mars for psychiatric reasons, Jim
McConnell (Gary Sinise) gets his chance later when the astronauts
run into problems with a huge human face they find embedded in the
red planet. The commander of a rescue attempt figures he needs a
man of McConnell's experience along. Brian De Palma's film reaches
for the great unexplainable out there, but, Elvis Mitchell wrote in
The New York Times, ``it has been a long time since such a
grandiloquent souffle of majesty and silliness refused to rise on
the big screen.''
</P>
<P>
   2000. Touchstone. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 113 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG. Release date: Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `EAST IS EAST'
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, George Khan (Om Puri), the Pakistani owner of an
English fish-and-chips shop, battles to justify his traditionalist
and often brutal ways with a brood of seven children. Rebellion
turns George into a raging patriarch, but Damien O'Donnell's film
shies away from religious and cultural complexities in what becomes
basically a sitcom. When George's rage blows the film apart,
``O'Donnell's attempts to restore its tone of easygoing farce seem
awkward, even insensitive'' (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   2000. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `THE QUARRY'
</P>
<P>
   In remote South African landscapes, tortured souls with generic
names like the Man and the Woman face daunting human and political
issues. After murdering a clergyman who made advances toward him,
the Man (John Lynch) takes up the minister's duties in a small
village, where he boards in the house of the Woman (Sylvia Esau).
The Woman, who is black, is having an affair with a white
policeman, who subsequently arrests a poor black man for the
killing. For all its susceptibility to symbolic interpretations of
God, justice and race, Marion Hansel's film is a ``first-rate
venture into mystery and suspense'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   2000. First Run. $79.95. 112 minutes. No rating. Release date:
Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   `STIFF UPPER LIPS'
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sinyor's film struggles with what appears to be a long
overdue and surefire idea: a sendup of Jane Austen, Merchant-Ivory
style dramas set among the English upper classes. It's 1908, and
Aunt Agnes (Prunella Scales) is desperate to marry off her niece
Emily (Georgina Cates) to the pompous Cedric (Robert Portal).
Lower-class blokes take a hand, but as the film ``stumbles along,
its humor is so scattershot, its tone so wobbly and its casting so
uneven, that the movie never coheres'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 85 minutes. No rating.
Release date: Sept. 12. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   AND KEEP IN MIND
</P>
<P>
   Video's current top three renters, ``Erin Brockovich,'' ``The
Cider House Rules'' and ``Reindeer Games,'' played on thousands of
theater screens. Here are a few examples from Video Business
magazine's list of best renters among films that played on 475
screens or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   `TITUS': Julie Taymor's film turns Shakespeare's bloody tale
into a fluid time-traveling fantasia of violence and revenge that
has the look of a sophisticated video game. 1999. Fox. $104.16;
DVD, $34.98. 160 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY': A best renter since April, Kimberly Pierce's
film stars Hilary Swank as Teena Brandon, a lanky high school girl
who turns her name around and becomes a boy in the small town of
Falls City, Neb. 1999. Fox. $104.16; DVD, $34.98. R.
</P>
<P>
   `GUN SHY': Ever since the federal agent Charlie Mayo (Liam
Neeson) was tortured face down in a pile of watermelon, he has been
trying to get his nerve back. 2000. Hollywood. $104.16; DVD,
$29.99. 102 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `THE STRAIGHT STORY': The elderly Alvin Straight (Richard
Farnsworth) decides to drive his lawn mower from Iowa to Wisconsin
to see his estranged brother (Harry Dean Stanton). Directed by
David Lynch, believe it or not. 1999. Disney. $104.16. 111 minutes.
Closed captioned. G.
</P>
<P>
   `HOLY SMOKE': The headstrong Ruth Barron (Kate Winslet) proves
more than a match for the ``cult exiter'' (Harvey Keitel) hired by
her family to break her away from her Indian guru. 1999. Miramax.
$104.16; DVD, $29.99. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `MANSFIELD PARK': Treated like a poor relation, Fanny Price
(Frances O'Connor) makes her mark on the estate of the pompous
slave trader Sir Thomas Bertram (Harold Pinter). 1999. Miramax.
$104.16; DVD, $29.99. 110 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL;
</P>
