<SLUG> BC-WORKER-CARCERAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER STALKED REFUGEE WORKER SLAIN IN TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He studied journalism and law, but those who knew Carlos
Caceres understood that he had loftier plans in mind, like changing
the world by trying to help clashing cultures understand each
other.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the 33-year-old United Nations refugee worker, who
grew up amid different cultures in Puerto Rico and Florida, died
while working in one of the world's deadliest culture clashes in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Caceres and two other UN workers, who were stationed in West
Timor, which remains under Indonesian rule, were mutilated and
burned on Wednesday by an angry mob of militiamen opposed to
independence for neighboring East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Danger lurked all around him, including death threats, Caceres
recently told friends and relatives. Only a few hours before the
attack, Caceres told a friend via email that he and his colleagues
in the remote West Timor town of Atambua were warned of the
approaching mob, but he continued working on behalf of Indonesian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Militiamen armed with homemade weapons and semiautomatic guns
attacked the UN compound chasing away nine local policemen on
guard, according to information provided to the UN Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Tipton, one of Caceres's journalism professors at the
University of Florida, said that when heard the news Thursday about
his former student, his ``stomach turned.'' But he wasn't surprised
to find out where Caceres was or what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time talking about how different cultures
get along,'' Tipton said in a telephone interview Thursday from his
campus office in Gainesville. ``He always seemed interested in ways
of bringing people together instead of focusing on their
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Caceres's interest in divided cultures may have come from his
own upbringing, which was spent in Puerto Rico until his family
moved to Miami in the mid-1970s. Tipton said he and Caceres spoke
often about the interaction between Miami's Hispanic and
non-Hispanic cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he wouldn't go into journalism,'' added Tipton, who
also wrote one of Caceres's recommendation letters to Cornell
University Law School. ``There was a soft-spoken, almost fragile
quality to him, but it was clear to me he had a strong sense of
social responsibility to help change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Caceres's relatives demanded answers from UN and
Indonesian officials about the attack, like why the workers were
allowed to stay there despite the constant threats they received
from militia members.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have got him out of there,'' the victim's father,
Gregorio Caceres, said from his home in Jacksonville. ``One of the
questions I have for the United Nations _ and I spoke to them
(Thursday) ... I asked: He knew he was in danger and he told me he
was going to be evacuated. What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Caceres had worked for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees
since 1987. Having also attended Oxford University in Britain,
Caceres held three doctorates and spoke five languages. He had been
in Prague for the United Nations and then in Moscow for two years
before being posted in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In recent notes he sent to his family, Caceres described
receiving death threats and hinted that he was not getting much
help.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Caceres told his family, he came down with dengue
fever, but continued his work helping refugees trying to escape
bloody fighting in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Caceres's sister, Elba, a Miami resident, got an email a month
ago from him saying the Indonesia-backed militias ``by the way,
hate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, she said she couldn't understand why her brother would
endure so much to help people so far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what made him decide that he so wanted to help
others that he traveled thousands and thousands of miles to help
strangers,'' she said. ``He would evacuate thousands of refugees
from the militia, and the refugees would look at him as God because
he was helping them. He gave up his life to help these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
