<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5428 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS &LR;      09-07 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;    Astronauts brush up on new skills to make orbital outpost a home &HT;    By MARK CARREAU
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Impressive resumes may qualify the
Atlantis astronauts as skilled pilots, engineers and medical
doctors, but their upcoming journey to the slowly developing
international space station will reveal whether they can also call
themselves movers, plumbers, electricians and cable installers.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Atlantis and its crew of five U.S. astronauts and
two Russian cosmonauts was scheduled to blast off from NASA's
Kennedy Space Center today (FRIDAY) at 7:45 a.m. CDT. But a chance
of showers or cloudy skies could force a delay, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   During an 11-day spaceflight, the shuttle astronauts plan to
dock with the yet-to-be inhabited orbital outpost to equip it with
an air-generating system, a toilet, fire extinguishers and exercise
equipment. During a spacewalk, two of the men will hook up
communications and computer cables and install an external
navigation device.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we've got a house up there that we're trying to get
ready for somebody else to move into,'' said astronaut Ed Lu, 37, a
physicist who dropped a career in solar astronomy six years ago to
join the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis flight is the first in a new flurry of missions
intended by NASA to hasten the long-delayed assembly of the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   If the efforts of its crew are successful, the fledgling outpost
will be ready for its first resident crew in early November, a
milestone that should initiate at least a decade of continuous
staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic problems forced a lengthy suspension in the
station's assembly soon after the first two components were joined
in orbit in late 1998. More than two years overdue, Russia's Zvezda
crew module was successfully orbited in July, adding a 43-foot-long
compartment designed to house three astronauts and cosmonauts at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing 42,000 pounds, Zvezda required Russia's most powerful
rocket for the ride into orbit. Even at that, it could not be
launched with all of its life support equipment in place because it
would have been too heavy even for Russia's Proton launcher.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the missing gear followed Zvezda into orbit aboard an
unmanned Russian Progress cargo capsule that docked with the
station in early August. Other gear is mixed with more than 2 tons
of new station equipment stowed aboard the shuttle, including
essential but bulky power storage batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The task of installing the life support equipment and unstowing
hundreds of pounds of other equipment from the Progress and the
shuttle was too much to leave until the November arrival of
American commander Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko and
Sergei Krikalev. The three men plan a four-month stay, most of it
preparing the outpost for the arrival of future components.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a tremendously important mission,'' said
Atlantis pilot Scott Altman, 41, a Navy test pilot. ``I feel a
heavy responsibility as far as making sure everything is ready when
they arrive so they can get right to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle skipper Terry Wilcutt, a Marine Corps test pilot, will
supervise a crew that also includes Lu; Rick Mastracchio, 40, an
electrical engineer and former NASA flight controller; Dan Burbank,
39, a former Coast Guard search and rescue pilot; Yuri Malenchenko,
38, a Russian Air Force colonel and former Mir space station
commander; and Boris Morukov, 49, a Russian medical doctor and
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great project for beginning the 21st century,'' said
Morukov, who has waited for 20 years for what will be his first
trip into space. He will supervise the unstowing of the Progress
capsule as well as serve as the shuttle crew's medical officer.
</P>
<P>
   NASA plans three shuttle flights to the station before year's
end, equaling all U.S. activity there since late 1998. A half-dozen
flights are planned in 2001, the most NASA has flown in a single
year since 1997. The upcoming missions will greatly expand the size
of the station, add the first of its science laboratories and equip
it with huge power generating solar arrays.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
