<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-PEACEKEEPING-BOS &LR;      09-07 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-PEACEKEEPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST TIMOR SLAYINGS CAST PALL OVER UN SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ First they gave a moment of silence for the
three dead men. Then the most powerful leaders in the world
Thursday asserted they would change the way the United Nations
protects people around the world from war, even with the tacit
acknowledgement it now wasn't protecting its own.
</P>
<P>
   In a historic gathering of 14 heads of state and a foreign
minister representing the nations of the UN Security Council, the
gulf between the official deliberations on peacekeeping and the
realities of keeping peace on the ground were laid bare in the
aftermath of the three UN aides, among them an American, brutally
murdered Wednesday in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, the lone leader to speak
without a prepared speech, called the murders an ``outrage,'' and
said the world must pay tribute to them and to all the ``brave
people'' who work on behalf of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   wircop But the most important reaction, he said, was for the
leaders to act. The Security Council did just that minutes later,
unanimously passing a draft resolution that called for
strengthening UN peacekeeping operations by improving training of
personnel and the caliber of weaponry, defining mandates much more
clearly and speeding the deployment of forces to areas of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   And it also called for ``effective measures for the security and
safety of United Nations personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks today are a lot tougher and more difficult than ever
before,'' Blair said. ``We're putting our people in far greater
difficult situations. At the same time, the need for peace has
never been greater. It can be determinative between anarchy and
stability for people around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council's focus was almost squarely on the
continent of Africa, where the UN has suffered a series of
peacekeeping failures. In Rwanda, it didn't act quickly enough to
stop the genocide that killed about 800,000 people in 1994. In
Angola, it pulled out peacekeepers after the rebel UNITA group shot
down two UN planes in 1998. And in Sierra Leone earlier this year,
rebel fighters captured more than 500 UN peacekeepers who had moved
close to their treasured diamond mines.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the deaths of UN workers on another continent, Asia,
that caused the outcry Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As the Security Council deliberated, halfway around the world an
airplane carried out the three caskets of the slain workers, the
caskets draped in blue UN flags and covered with tropical flowers.
Several dozen frightened UN relief workers also were evacuated from
West Timor Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The UN suspended its operations as Indonesia's military arrested
15 people after the militia-led mob destroyed a UN office in the
West Timor town of Atambua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking at the UN, urged Indonesia to
``bring those responsible to justice, to disarm and disband the
militias and to take all necessary steps to insure the safety of
those continuing to work on humanitarian goals there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid, humiliated before about
150 world leaders at the UN Millennium Summit, promised he would
work with the UN administration in East Timor on removing the
hostile militias from the border region. ``But to remove such a
number of people needs time,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The almost providential timing of the deaths coming on the eve
of the Security Council debate tragically reminded leaders about
the dangers of allowing the peacekeeping operations to continue
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   It underscored Secretary General Kofi Annan's push that the
United Nations must remake itself in the new century if it is to
remain relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he sadly commented, many nations see it as irrelevent.
</P>
<P>
   He called it a ``crisis of credibility facing this Council _ and
this organization _ in discharging its gravest responsibility: the
maintenance of peace and security. Too many vulnerable communities
in too many regions of the world now hesitate to look to the United
Nations to assist them in their hour of need. No amount of
resolutions or statements can change this reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only action can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Annan formed a commission to study the
failures of peacekeeping and its recommendations formed the basis
of the draft resolution. The matter will now face several months of
fine-tuning and planning in order to build upon the current forces.
</P>
<P>
   One necessary change, several leaders said Thursday, will be
paying of UN dues. The largest debtor is the United States, which
owes more than $1 billion, much of it for past peacekeeping
operations. The US has withheld money in a conflict over how much
it should pay.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, like several leaders, said that the Council needed to
address the root causes of conflict as well as broadening the
definition of security. No longer should war be seen as the only
cause of insecurity, he said. Now, the list should increase the
deadly spread of infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not just AIDS,'' he said, even though his
administration has only designated AIDS as the sole disease rising
to the level as a national security threat. ``It's malaria and TB,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The three diseases, he pointed out for the second consecutive
day at the UN, accounted for a quarter of all the world's deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we can break the iron link between deprivation, disease
and war we will never be able to create the feat the founders of
the United Nations'' had intended, to free the world from the
scourge of war.
</P>
<P>
   There was some disagreement among members on when the UN should
insert peacekeeping operations, including determining the factor of
sovereignty, namely whether the UN should respect a nation's right
to enforce the law within its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Russian President
Vladimir V. Putin, who have crushed opposition movements in Tibet
and Chechnya respectively, both argued that the UN should tread
very carefully when it came to sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the biggest concern Thursday was quickly putting together
an effective UN force.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders expressed embarrassment with the current state of
affairs. Some said they were shamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inadmissible for our organization to be held hostage in
conflicts,'' said French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations,'' said Jamaican Prime Minister P.J.
Patterson, ``is facing its most critical test.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
