<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTIC BLOOMS FOR A CITY PARK; A PICASSO GOES TO AUCTION; A
9,000-SQUARE-FOOT WORK OF ART; AN ARTS FESTIVAL IN DOWNTOWN
MANHATTAN; PHILLIPS APPOINTS A BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., London, Spain, Italy and Hong Kong)   By   CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Target Stores has given $1 million to a
contemporary-art program at Madison Square Park in Manhattan. The
initiative, part of a restoration of the park between 23rd and 26th
Streets from Madison to Fifth Avenues, will feature work by an
international group of artists including Tony Oursler, Ron Mueck,
Janet Cardiff and Yutaka Stone.
</P>
<P>
   The gift, announced this week by the City Parks Foundation and
the Parks and Recreation Department, is an effort by Target to
establish a presence in Manhattan, where it does not yet have
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give $1 million each week to communities across America,''
said John Remington, Target's vice president for special events and
publicity. ``We thought this was a way we could make Madison Square
Park an exciting cultural destination.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Landau, director of the City Parks Foundation, said the
foundation wanted the park to have a distinct identity. It asked
the Public Art Fund, a nonprofit organization that presents public
art projects around the city, to come up with a creative program.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the difficulties of a project of this scale is
fund-raising in order to be able to do a knock-your-socks-off kind
of program,'' said Susan K. Freedman, president of the Public Art
Fund. ``At the same time, we learned of Target's interest in
getting involved in a meaningful art project.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   A three-year plan for the park will begin with the installation
artist Tony Oursler's ``Influence Machine,'' in which the artist
will project ghostly images onto artificial smoke and the parks'
trees and paths. It will will be on view Oct. 19 to 31 from sunset
to 9 p.m. A group show is planned for late May. A PICASSO COMES UP
</P>
<P>
   Just as Christie's is packing up the highlights of its Nov. 8
sale of Impressionist and modern art for an international tour
beginning in London on Sept. 15, the auction house is approaching
important collectors about a rare painting from Picasso's Blue
Period. ``Woman With Crossed Arms,'' a portrait the artist painted
in Barcelona in 1902, is expected to sell for around $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The work, which shows a glum-looking woman seated against a
background of rich blues, has been owned by Mr. and Mrs. Chauncey
McCormick, Chicago collectors, since 1936. Besides being included
in many Picasso exhibitions (including in the first retrospective
of the artist's work, in Paris in 1932), it was on view at the Art
Institute of Chicago as part of ``Picasso in Chicago'' in 1968. The
painting remained there on loan until 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The last Blue Period Picasso to come up at auction was a
portrait of the artist Angel Fernandez de Soto, bought by the
composer Andrew Lloyd Webber for $29.1 million at Sotheby's in New
York in 1995. TRANSFORMING DIA
</P>
<P>
   As Chelsea continues to boom, so does the Dia Center for the
Arts. With the increased traffic of gallery-goers to the West 20s
every weekend, Dia is so packed that its ground-floor space at 548
West 22nd Street needed to be renovated to accommodate the crowds.
Rather than hire a traditional architect or designer, Dia turned
over the challenge to Jorge Pardo, the Los Angeles artist known for
his design-based creations.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of transforming Dia's 9,000-square-foot ground floor
into an artwork fits nicely with other artist-created portions of
the institution. Eighteen trees and stone columns that line the
block are by Joseph Beuys; Dan Flavin's fluorescent work lights up
the stairways; and Dan Graham created a rooftop park.
</P>
<P>
   Pardo has changed the facade, adding windows and enlarging
existing ones. He also reconfigured the lobby, moving the main
entrance and making the reception and ticketing areas more
accessible. Perhaps the most noticeable part of his design _ one
that extends from the lobby into the gallery space and enlarged
bookshop _ is the addition of tilework in bright lime, lemon,
yellow and mustard green covering the floors and the columns.
</P>
<P>
   Pardo is also creating murals that will be abstract, biomorphic,
brightly colored forms throughout the floor and has added large
glass dividers while at the same time visually connecting the
entire space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about tempting the edges between art, design and
architecture, said Michael Govan, the director of Dia. FESTIVAL,
DOWNTOWN
</P>
<P>
   The eighth annual Downtown Arts Festival begins Friday and runs
through Sept. 24, with more than 40 galleries and 10 performance
venues participating. This year the festival has added a
contemporary French art and performance series. It will also
continue to present tours by dealers of galleries in Chelsea and
SoHo along with talks by artists. The art walks begin on Saturday
in Chelsea. Information and schedules are available at the N.Y.C.
Lab School, 333 West 17th Street (691-6119). BOARD FOR PHILLIPS
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly a year since LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton
bought Phillips and only now is the company putting together a team
to oversee the auction house. This week it announced the formation
of a six-member board.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Powell of Bayswater, a former foreign affairs and defense
adviser to Prime Ministers Margaret Thatcher and John Major, was
named the company's chairman in April. The board also includes
Mario d'Urso, an Italian senator who lives in Rome; J. Carter
Brown, director emeritus of the National Gallery in Washington; Sir
Joseph Hotung, a Hong Kong real-estate developer; Gert-Rudolf
Flick, a London-based collector; Lord Camoys, lord-in-waiting to
Queen Elizabeth II and a former deputy chairman of Sotheby's; and
the Duke of Lugo, a manager director and senior adviser at Credit
Suisse First Boston in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has also appointed Thierry Millerand as its director of
French and Contintental furniture worldwide. Millerand, who began
his new job this week, left Sotheby's in February after 27 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
