<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5435 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TIRES-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      09-07 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRES-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD TIRE, BAD ADVICE LED TO FIRESTONE RECALL, SPECIALISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jacques Nasser, the chief executive at Ford Motor Co., told
a committee on Capitol Hill this week that the problem of shredding
Firestone tires on Ford SUVs was ``a tire problem, not a vehicle
problem'' he may have drawn too sharp a distinction.
</P>
<P>
   According to some tire specialists, what may have happened to
prompt the current tire recall is that a bad tire met with bad
recommendations for inflation, that Firetone's ``tire problem'' was
exacerbated by Ford's desire to make its SUVs more stable in turns
and to give them a softer ride.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve this, Ford recommended that its very popular Explorer
SUVs be driven on tires inflated to 26 pounds per square inch.
Chevrolet recommends that the tires on its comparable model, the
Blazer, which are supplied by other manufacturers, be inflated to
35 pounds per square inch. On its Ranger pickup truck, which is 300
pounds lighter than an Explorer but is equipped with the same
Firestone tires, Ford recommends inflation to 35 pounds per square
inch. Drivers expect a harsh, stiff ride in a truck; they are
asking for softer rides in their SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave owners of SUVs, those with Firestones
that they rightfully worry about, and those with other brands whose
concerns are more vague?
</P>
<P>
   Keep your tires inflated properly, say those in the tire
industry. Underinflation is the leading cause of tire failure.
</P>
<P>
   Take a heavy SUV with badly underinflated tires, said Marvin
Bozarth, executive director of the International Tire &AMP; Rubber
Association Inc., load it with people and gear, and run it for a
long period down the highway, and there's a good chance the tires
could come apart, faulty or not. Hot weather increases the
possibility of this. Of course, not every tire failure results in
tragedy; the highways are littered with the remnants of failed
truck tires, victims of weight, heat, and distance running.
</P>
<P>
   Tire failure is generally caused by overheating, Bozarth said.
This can be caused by underinflation, overloading, tire defects, or
a combination of all these things.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about an hour of steady running at high speed to
approach the heat limits of a tire _ usually about 200 degrees. The
heating is caused by flex, a normal bending motion in the sidewalls
of a tire that occurs as the car moves up and down, bouncing on its
suspension, and side to side in turns. The motion stresses the
tire's sides as the tread maintains grip on the road surface.
</P>
<P>
   If the sidewalls are stiff _ and higher inflation makes them
stiffer _ they do not flex as much. Phillip Zaroon, a member of the
Society of Automotive Engineers and owner of a company that is
developing tire inflation monitoring equipment, likens a bending
sidewall to a coathanger. Bend it slowly in a large arc, it heats
up, but not much. Bend it tightly and repeatedly and it overheats _
as a sidewall will do in an underinflated tire.
</P>
<P>
   Add hot ambient temperatures and long drives, and you can get
tire failure. Most Firestone failures have occurred in hotter
climates and in states where the roads are more wide open and the
distances routinely traveled greater than in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Steinberg, president and CEO of Watertown's Direct Tire
and Auto Services, said he has not heard of a shredded Firestone
tire in the Northeast. He has seen Firestone tires distorted or in
the early phases of separation, and, in fact, his stores have long
recommended that tires on Ford SUVs be inflated above the
recommended 26 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bozarth, of the tire and rubber association, said it is ``pretty
clear that the tire pressure (on Ford SUVs) was dropped for two
reasons:'' to answer customer complaints about a rough ride and to
address problems in passing rollover tests.
</P>
<P>
   SUVs are basically trucks and have long ridden like them. Also,
because they are high and heavy, they tip more easily than lower
vehicles. But people want to drive them like cars _ quickly,
zipping in and out of traffic _ and with their weight, height, and
stiff, heavy tires, they are unstable at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   What can SUV owners do if they are worried about their tires?
</P>
<P>
   Keep them properly inflated. Recommended inflation levels can be
found on the doorpost of your car, the glove compartment lid, or
the cover for the gas cap.
</P>
<P>
   Check the tire pressure at least every month. Tires lose 1-2
pounds of pressure per month in cool weather, more in warmer
weather.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, most people seldom check tire pressure. And
that, said Bozarth, may be where some customer fault can be found
in the Ford/Firestone controversy. Explorers delivered with 26
pounds per square inch in the tires could probably operate safely
at that level he said. But that is near the bottom limit.
</P>
<P>
   And after a few months of driver neglect, there probably were
Explorers on the roads with as little as 16 or 18 pounds of
pressure in their tires _ tires that may have already had inherent
faults.
</P>
<P>
   But bad tires or not, said Zaroon, ``the horrors of
underinflation are well-documented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
