<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSHPOLL0908-1STLEDE-     09-07 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHPOLL0908-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This version contains revision of first seven grafs.
 &HT;    Bush trailing Gore in national poll, but still strong in Texas
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It all looked so effortless just a few short weeks
ago. Now, Gov. George W. Bush _ down in the polls and plagued by
news reports of gaffes and missteps _ is taking very public
criticism from within his own party and promised Thursday to retool
a faltering campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring, ``I am the underdog,'' Bush promised to interact more
with real people.
</P>
<P>
   Four new polls, Three national, and one in Texas, show Vice
President Al Gore gaining momentum among voters and now locked in
an intense race with Bush less than a month after trailing Bush in
most polls.
</P>
<P>
   A Reuters/Zogby National poll of 1,001 likely voters had Gore
leading Bush 46 percent to 40 percent. Adjusted for the margin of
error of three percentage points, Zogby said the poll shows Gore
with a ``slight lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is running especially well among Independents, African
Americans, Hispanics and other key Democratic groups, the latest
evidence that he has secured his once-elusive base. He gained
startling ground among women, who traditionally vote Democratic in
large numbers but have, until now, eluded Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington Post-ABC News poll of 738 likely voters has Bush
with 49 percent and Gore with 47 percent with a margin of error of
four percentage points. The poll was conducted Sept. 4-6. In a four
way race, including Green Party nominee Ralph Nader and Reform
Party candidate Pat Buchanan, Bush and Gore are dead even at 47
percent each.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll taken over the same period put Gore
up 47 percent to 44 percent, just two weeks after Bush was up 46
percent to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And a new Texas Poll shows that although Bush, the Republican
nominee, still holds a formidable lead in his home state, it has
eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bush has had a dismal few weeks but has kept it
close because the swing groups are close,'' Zogby said. ``The swing
groups are independents, where Gore leads, parents and voters who
live in $25,000 to $50,000 households. No one's won the presidency
without winning that group, going back to '72. And the two are in a
dead heat among those two groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The Summer 2000 Texas Poll released today shows Bush still
enjoying a generous lead in the state _ 53 percent to 30 percent _
but Bush's standing is down from June, when he led 57 percent to 24
percent. The poll of 1,000 registered voters was conducted Aug.
7-30 and has a 3 percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials ignored the tightening Texas numbers,
voicing confidence despite the national polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whopping 23 point lead shows once again that Texas is
solid George W. Bush country,'' spokesman Ray Sullivan said. ``As
we saw in the race against Ann Richards in 1994 and in the
primaries this year, George W. Bush runs strongest as the
challenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly and privately, though, Republicans are expressing
concern. On Thursday, conservative columnist Robert D. Novak,
advising from the nation's op-ed pages, wrote, ``George W. Bush
needs to change the atmosphere to keep panicky backers from heading
for the high grass.'' He urged Bush to seek a, ``face-to-face
confrontation,'' with Gore before the Olympics steals away already
scant voter attention.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, one GOP adviser said the campaign has got to
marshal more forces to give Bush - who dubbed himself, ``the
underdog'' Thursday - much-needed support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole theme of the national convention was, 'Read the
polls. We're going to win,' `` the adviser said. `` There was no
serious discourse on the agenda and how to sell the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   He revived a familiar criticism, that Bush's tight-knit Austin
team _ strategist Karl Rove, campaign manager Joe Allbaugh and
communications director Karen Hughes _ must branch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are all the governors? Where's the calvary that's
supposed to be coming over the hill? Poor Bush is out there all
alone defending himself,'' he said. ``I think the campaign needs to
understand this is a big deal. You need 15 or 20 guys out there
every day pushing your message. Traditionally, campaigns expand the
tent after you win the nomination and you expand it again after
your party convention,'' he said. ``This Austin one's stayed a pup
tent.''
</P>
<P>
   A prominent GOP Bush supporter circulated a three-page e-mail
lambasting the campaign for ads attacking Gore, failing to reach
out effectively to black voters and muzzling running mate Dick
Cheney, whose Halliburton stock options presented public relations
problems for the campaign for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's a loser,'' the Republican said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's post- convention bounce has been more sustained than the
Bush team anticipated. Some insiders are wary of a Republican ad
poking fun at Gore for his appearance at a Buddhist temple and they
say Bush's use of a vulgarity to describe a New York Times reporter
_ picked up by microphone at a recent campaign appearance _ made
him look like an amateur at best.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush's efforts to keep his message front and center
have been eclipsed by his refusal to agree to all the debates set
by the Commission on Presidential Debates, the bipartisan group
established to avoid just such posturing. He has so far not
committed to all three scheduled metes, saying instead that he will
debate Gore on ``Larry King Live'' and on NBC's, ``Meet the
Press,'' and in one commission debate.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby called the debate over the debates, ``preposterous,'' and
added: ``Every day he's focusing on it he looks like a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Fowler, director of the Nelson A. Rockefeller Center for
the Social Sciences at Dartmouth College, said candidates
routinely, ``play games about format,'' but that Bush can ill
afford them now.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bush's case I think it's a little more problematic because
of perceptions among political elites that he's not going to be
good debater, that Al Gore is going to make hamburger out of him,
that it makes him look fearful,'' she said. ``That's kind of
insider baseball stuff. If, in the end he ends up debating, most
voters will forget how he got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Reed, campaign manager of former Sen. Bob Dole's 1996
White House bid, said there's plenty of time for Bush to recover.
He called Bush's Medicare and prescription drug plans steps in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a very substantive campaign on paper,'' Reed said.
``The convention speech was great. They just need to go back to the
basics of blocking and tackling when it comes to message delivery
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   You may reach Jena Heath at jenah(at)coxnews.com and Ken Herman
at kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
