<SLUG> BC-TV-EMMYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEST WING' THE CLEAR FRONT-RUNNER AT EMMYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let Al Gore and George W. Bush spend and debate and struggle;
it's already been a good presidential year for Josiah Bartlet.
</P>
<P>
   Played by Martin Sheen, Bartlet is the fictional chief executive
in ``The West Wing,'' the NBC drama favored to win the shiniest
statuette for outstanding drama Sunday night at the Prime Time Emmy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   After its first season, ``The West Wing'' has already won a
Peabody Award, three Television Critics Association Awards and, two
weeks ago, four Emmys in the technical categories.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, it's up for a batch of major Emmys _ outstanding
drama, lead actor (Sheen), supporting actor (John Spencer, Richard
Schiff), supporting actress (Allison Janney), writing (Aaron
Sorkin, Rick Cleveland) and direction (Thomas Schlamme).
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, ``The Practice'' was voted best drama, as half of
producer David E. Kelley's unprecedented drama-comedy (``The
Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal'') sweep. The ABC legal drama is
nominated again this year, but the HBO mob drama ``The Sopranos''
is believed to be the main competition for ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' would be favored in a perfect world. Emmy
historian Thomas O'Neil says its loss last year prompted a bout of
soul searching at the Academy of Television Arts &AMP; Sciences and was
partly responsible for a change in the Emmy voting procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the old blue-ribbon panels that met in strictly
monitored sessions to determine the major winners.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, videotapes were mailed this year to all qualifying
academy members, who pledged to watch the tapes at home. The
process is seemingly more democratic, but O'Neil is skeptical about
the voters' diligence. He fears that reputation and sentiment will
count for more than the demonstrated skills on the submitted tapes.
</P>
<P>
   So why won't ``The Sopranos'' win this year? O'Neil says the
fact that it's a serial drama is a liability. There could also be a
regional bias. Most Emmy voters are in California; ``The Sopranos''
is an East Coast production.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``The West Wing,'' ``The Sopranos'' and ``The
Practice,'' the outstanding-drama nominees are ``ER'' and ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' which won the Emmy in 1996 and 1997, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Other major categories and predictions:
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY SERIES: ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' ``Frasier,''
``Friends,'' ``Sex and the City'' and ``Will &AMP; Grace'' are
nominated. And the winner is ... ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' Nope,
maybe next year. There's no clear favorite. ``Friends'' has never
won, and this seems an unlikely time to start. ``Frasier'' won five
times and then got old. I like ``Will &AMP; Grace'' as the freshest
show in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  MINISERIES: ``Arabian Nights,'' ``The Beach Boys: An
American Family,'' ``The Corner,'' ``Jesus'' and ``P.T. Barnum''
are nominated.
</P>
<P>
   The balloting should be between CBS' ``Jesus'' and HBO's ``The
Corner.'' ``Jesus'' is just all right with me.
</P>
<P>
   TV MOVIE: ``Annie,'' ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,''
``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge,'' ``Tuesdays With Morrie'' and
``RKO 281'' are nominated.
</P>
<P>
   I'd vote for ``Annie''; I think ``Tuesdays With Morrie'' will
win. HBO's ``RKO 281,'' about the making of ``Citizen Kane,'' is a
not-so-dark horse.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD ACTOR IN A DRAMA SERIES: Dennis Franz (``NYPD Blue''),
James (``The Sopranos''), Jerry Orbach (``Law &AMP; Order''), Sheen
(``The West Wing'') and Sam Waterston (``Law &AMP; Order'') are
nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Franz, for a fifth time, or Gandolfini? O'Neil says Franz has
once again submitted a powerful episode. He seemed almost
embarrassed to win last year. But he'll probably cop another Emmy,
tying him with Ed Asner, Candice Bergen, Don Knotts and Art Carney
for most Emmy victories in a single role.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD ACTRESS IN A DRAMA SERIES: Lorraine Bracco (``The
Sopranos,'' Amy Brenneman (``Judging Amy''), Edie Falco (``The
Sopranos''), Julianna Margulies (``ER'') and Sela Ward (``Once and
Again'') are nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for Ward, in a minor upset over last year's winner, Falco.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD ACTOR IN A COMEDY SERIES: Michael J. Fox (``Spin City''),
Kelsey Grammer (``Frasier''), John Lithgow (``3rd Rock From the
Sun''), Eric McCormack (``Will &AMP; Grace'') and Ray Romano
(``Everybody Loves Raymond'') are nominated.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be nice to hear Fox's acceptance speech, and we probably
will. O'Neil says he submitted the season finale, in which Fox, who
has Parkinson's disease, took his leave from the show. The episode
was an hour long, an advantage for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD ACTRESS IN A COMEDY SERIES: Jenna Elfman (``Dharma &AMP;
Greg''), Patricia Heaton (``Everybody Loves Raymond''), Jane
Kaczmarek (``Malcolm in the Middle''), Debra Messing (``Will &AMP;
Grace'') and Sarah Jessica Parker (``Sex and the City'') are
nominated.
</P>
<P>
   If the voters actually watched the submitted tapes, O'Neil says,
Heaton should win for an episode about premenstrual syndrome. But
I'm thinking Kaczmarek.
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM LENGTH: It's not an award category, but executive
producer Don Mischer is expected to bring the Emmys in under the
four-hour, 10-minute record set six months ago by the marathon
Oscars show. This despite plans for several taped comedy bits
featuring Shandling.
</P>
<P>
   He (set ital)has(end ital) &LR;   &LR; to bring it in on time. We
reporters have deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
