<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-DAVIS-ANDERSON090     09-07 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DAVIS-ANDERSON0908-COx </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friendly rivals Anderson, Davis hope to meet on field Sunday
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flowery Branch, Ga. _ One week after blowing out his right knee
last season, Jamal Anderson got a call from a buddy. Terrell Davis
was complaining about how bad he had it the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve of that guy!
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at home (after the injury) that first weekend when (the
Falcons) were at St. Louis (losing 35-7), and (the Broncos) were at
Tampa Bay,'' Falcons running back Anderson said. ``He said, `Man,
did you see that game?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `Yeah, they were all over you, but look at it this
way: At least you're not hurting like me while sitting around.' He
said, `Oh yeah, right, right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One week later, Davis, the Broncos' running back, was out for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks apart, the NFL's two leading rushers in 1998 _ Davis
with 2,008 yards and Anderson with 1,846 _ tore the anterior
cruciate ligaments in their right knees.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also suffered a partial tear of the medial collateral
ligament and cartilage damage.
</P>
<P>
   The two men share other similarities. Although their teams had
met 10 months earlier in Super Bowl XXXIII, won 34-19 by Denver,
their teams started last season 0-4. Atlanta finished 5-11, Denver
6-10.
</P>
<P>
   But soon after their surgeries, they resumed competition with
each other. Unless Davis fails to cooperate, when the Falcons (1-0)
play the Broncos (0-1) Sunday at Mile High Stadium, it will qualify
as the battle of wounded knees.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to the badly sprained left ankle of Davis, who missed
practice Thursday for the second day in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the NFL released schedules last winter, Anderson, 27,
and Davis, 27, have been keeping tabs on each other's
rehabilitations and talking about playing this one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've kind of eyed this game for our returns,'' Anderson said.
``I hope he gets a chance to play, I really do. I hope we have the
showdown everybody anticipates.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a sixth-round choice of the Broncos in `95, got to know
Anderson, a seventh-round choice of the Falcons in `94, through a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   One of Davis' high school teammates at San Diego's Lincoln Prep,
Charlie Brown, was a teammate of Anderson at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would talk to him on the phone and we'd always talk about
Jamal,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Anderson, from Woodland Hills, Calif., and Davis became
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was one of those things where we kind of had a chip
on our shoulders being low-round picks,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   After his surgery in October, Anderson told Davis that if he
ever had to go through it again, he would retire. In so many words,
Davis said, ``Yeah, right.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davis got ready to go into surgery, Anderson tried to warn
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him when he was in the hospital to kind of give him a
heads up as far as what to expect,'' Anderson said. ``He kept
saying, `It ain't going to be like that; I'm not going to hurt so
much.' I said, `All right, Terrell.' ``
</P>
<P>
   It hurt a lot. But before long, the two of them were rehabbing,
doing many of the same things, and competing without putting pads
on or even seeing each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of cool, not cool, but interesting, when you have
another person in the same situation who's a running back,'' Davis
said. ``The one thing about Jamal I wish I had was that stiff
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the talk was in jest, as they occasionally called each
other by nicknames -- Davis ``The Dominator'' and Jamal ``The
Juggernaut.'' But much of it was serious.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, for example, knew that if he worked out on the field
before a Monday night game late in the season, chances were good
ABC would show footage of it on that night's telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me one time when Denver was going to be on Monday
night, and said, `Check me out. I'm going to be running,' ``
Anderson said. ``I hadn't been running like that yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking the next time we had a Monday night game,
I was going to run, too. There were competitive things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson drove Falcons' trainers nuts every week by telling them
what Davis was doing in his rehab. In Denver, for example, they
have a pool in which injured players rehab.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' old facility in Suwanee had no such pool, although
the team has one at the new facility in Flowery Branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell was somebody to push me in a competitive sense,''
Anderson said. ``Our rehabs were very, very similar, except for
some philosophical beliefs that were different among the
trainers.''
</P>
<P>
   They have a bet, although Anderson won't get specific about the
subject or the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The two have played telephone tag this week, but Anderson is
willing to make another bet: Davis won't be a spectator Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's going to play,'' Anderson said. ``The only way he
wouldn't play against us, and particularly me, would be if his
ankle was broken in several places, and then he'd try to tape it up
and play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect Mr. Davis to be in uniform, on the field, and
running like he never got hurt.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
