<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Qwest plans to cut 11,000 jobs
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Qwest Communications announced plans Thursday for
massive job cuts along with a major restructuring aimed at slashing
costs and focusing on growth.
</P>
<P>
   About 11,000 of the company's 70,000 jobs will be trimmed by the
end of next year, most in the 14 states served by US West, the
regional Bell company that Qwest bought in June after a short and
unpleasant bidding war with Global Crossing. The Denver-based
company also created a new digital media unit and named David
Woodrow _ who had retired a week ago as executive vice president of
Cox Communications _ to run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this because we need a streamlined company,''
Qwest Chairman and Chief Executive Joseph Nacchio told analysts.
``We want to create an entrepreneurial atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   That effort is a test _ not only of Nacchio's skill and vision _
but also of the notion that an upstart provider of high-speed
services can be melded with an old-time phone company. Like
BellSouth, US West was one of seven Baby Bells created in the 1984
break-up of AT&AMP;T. With US West's $35 billion acquisition, BellSouth
became the only Bell not part of a merger in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth did make a $3.5 billion investment in Qwest, a
stake now worth about 4 percent. Because Qwest offers long-distance
service and BellSouth has still not won entry into long-distance,
BellSouth can hold no more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, BellSouth and Qwest can market their services together,
and they have landed 150 contracts worth $310 million, said
BellSouth spokesman Jeff Battcher. For instance, the companies
recently won a $20 million contract to handle telecom services for
Winn-Dixie. ``That arrangement has been a success, especially with
corporations and big businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth is no longer the presumed senior partner, even
though its $26 billion-a-year in revenues best Qwest by nearly 50
percent. Qwest stock is now valued at $81 billion compared to $72
billion for the public shares of BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Qwest's expansive worth, it is still an enticing
takeover target for a foreign interloper looking for a foothold in
the United States. Most likely suitor is Deutsche Telekom, said
analyst Patrick Comak at Guzman &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest was lambasted for buying US West by some analysts who
argued that the slower growth rates of a Bell would be an albatross
for the high-flying company. But Nacchio indicated Thursday that he
means to juice expansion, especially in Internet and wireless
markets where demand is growing quickest.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest predicted it will finish this year with sales of more than
$18.8 billion to $19.1 billion _ higher than previous forecasts.
Company predictions for next year's revenues were also ratcheted
up. Qwest said it expects to generate $1 billion in cash by selling
its stake in 15 companies at the same time that it is creating new
units in high-growth markets.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the digital media unit will provide various
services using broadband _ the word given to describe any line
``wide'' enough to handle huge amounts of data needed for video and
other data-intensive transmissions. Those services can be delivered
either to television or computer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted with some distaste to the announcements,
dropping Qwest stock $2.56 to $48.94. Some analysts were apparently
disappointed that Qwest's announcement was not more of a
blockbuster. The company also announced plans to increase capital
spending to $9 billion this year and $9.5 billion next year to push
construction of high-speed lines, but some investors may fear it
will also drain earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Laboring to cut costs, the company is chopping overlapping jobs,
and most of those targeted jobs were in US West pre-merger, said
spokesman Tyler Gronbach. About 40 percent of Qwest's legal staff
has already been cut or moved to different places in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
