<HEADER>
A5449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-475&AMP;ADD-N     09-07 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE MOVES CLOSER TO DECISION ON TRADE WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate took an important step closer to a final
vote on President Clinton's major trade bill with China on
Thursday, as momentum built for final passage next week after
months of delay.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory for the White House and the business community,
senators voted 92-5 to end preliminary debate and proceed to final
consideration of a measure that would establish permanent trade
relations with China and end Congress' annual review of Beijing's
trade status.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate then rejected the first of several amendments that
threatened to undercut the bill. An amendment by Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., calling on China to increase religious freedom
was defeated, 69-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration is focused on trade, which it is
now promoting as its human rights policy,'' Wellstone said. ``But
trade alone will never guarantee change.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, chairman of
the Foreign Relations Committee and one of most conservative
senators, joined Wellstone, one of the chamber's leading liberals,
in support of the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in America still stand for something _ something other than
profit,'' Helms said. ``We don't believe China should be welcomed
into international organizations such as the World Trade
Organization while China continues to repress and to jail and to
murder and to torture their own citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Another amendment, this one by Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., to
support the export of non-polluting energy technology to China,
lost, 65-31.
</P>
<P>
   A third measure, by Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., to continue
Congress' annual review of China's trade status, was defeated,
81-13.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the contentious trade bill in May, 237-197,
and more than 70 senators are likely to support the measure in the
final vote.
</P>
<P>
   The only mystery left is whether senators will vote to link
passage of the trade measure to concerns over China's record on
human rights, religious freedom and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In any other context, many of the amendments would have broad
support. But if the Senate adopts any amendments, the bill would
have to be returned to the House, where supporters say there is not
enough time to reconcile differences before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the legislation is necessary for U.S. companies to
benefit fully from a deal reached last year by the United States
and China that paves China's way into the World Trade Organization,
the 135-member trade group that sets the rules for global commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how lawmakers vote, China will enter the WTO. But
without the blessing bestowed by Congress, Beijing could withhold
some trade benefits from the United States that it extends to other
members of the group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to passing a clean bill is a possible
amendment by Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert G.
Torricelli, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It would require the administration to monitor China's record on
the spread of nuclear, chemical, biological and missile technology,
and would impose sanctions if there is evidence of certain types of
prohibited weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's top aides oppose the measure, arguing that the
legislation would hamper the administration's efforts to combat
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Support for it as an amendment to the trade bill appeared to be
eroding on Thursday. Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader who backs
the idea, met with supporters and opponents on Thursday to try to
arrange a separate vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Torricelli and another sponsor of the original
legislation, Michael D. Crapo, R-Idaho, said the senators had
strong reservations about supporting it as an amendment to the
trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Thompson-Torricelli measure expressed optimism
that they had enough support to defeat it..
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that we've got the votes, and I'm reasonably
optimistic that we do,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
Democratic leader. ``But in any election or any vote, only the
paranoid survive, and I think we've got to be sufficiently
paranoid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will debate other potentially crippling amendments
through next week.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, for example, introduced six amendments on Thursday that
could come up in the next several days. They include measures
requiring the president to call on China to improve its human
rights record, to stop interfering with broadcasts of Radio Free
Asia or the Voice of America, and to condemn forced abortions in
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
