<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FEDEX0908-COX     09-07 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDEX0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS slams FedEx, postal plans
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service Corp. officials said Thursday
they will seek to block a proposed alliance between FedEx Corp and
the U.S. Postal Service on legal and public policy grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government can't favor one private company to the
exclusion of all others,'' said Tad Segal, a UPS spokesman in
Washington. ``There's going to be a lot of pressure to analyze
whether this is in the best interest of U.S. taxpayers. . .and
whether it's fair to government workers. It's far from certain that
the Postal Service is going to be able to pull this off.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Black, a UPS spokesman in Sandy Springs, said the company
also intends to fight any FedEx/Postal Service collaboration in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would anyone pay FedEx prices for postal service?'' he
asked. ``They have the worst reliability and package tracking in
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Postmaster General William Henderson said Thursday that he hopes
to reach an agreement by October that would allow FedEx cargo jets
to carry Postal Service next-day deliveries. In exchange, the
Postal Service would deliver some FedEx Ground packages. The Postal
Service also would allow FedEx to install retail drop boxes at
38,000 U.S. post offices.
</P>
<P>
   The planned ``strategic alliance'' is far more sweeping than any
previous agreement between the Postal Service and a private
delivery firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``FedEx is the most efficient air carrier, and we're interested
in having FedEx carry all our (Express Mail and Priority Mail)
shipments,'' Henderson said. ``In residential deliveries, we're the
most efficient. We could deliver, in some instances, (FedEx's)
ground packages.''
</P>
<P>
   FedEx is a leader in information technology and could give the
Postal Service package tracking, online ordering and billing, and
other electronic capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   An alliance requires approval from the Postal Service Board of
Governors, and Henderson expects to bring the panel a detailed
proposal in October. If it is approved, the organizations would
begin coordinating their operations early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no legal prohibition to our doing this,'' Henderson
said. ``The notion that we're seeking more efficient air
transportation shouldn't surprise anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the legal issue isn't clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot for FedEx and the Postal Service to gain,'' said
Paul Schlesinger, transportation analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette in New York. ``But the idea of an agency favoring one
private company in an industry where there's lots of competition
brings up some enormous public policy questions. In the end, it may
be illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   An alliance between private, entrepreneurial FedEx and the
quasi-governmental Postal Service would represent a sea change in
the delivery industry and a direct challenge to Sandy Springs-based
UPS. UPS is the world's largest transportation firm with $27
billion in annual revenue, and FedEx is second with $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service brings in $63 billion in annual revenue,
primarily through its monopoly on first-class mail. UPS and other
private delivery firms have long accused the Postal Service of
abusing its mail monopoly by subsidizing next-day deliveries and
other products that compete with private firms. The Postal Service
also enjoys structural advantages since it doesn't pay taxes,
license fees or even parking tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Postal Service has been under pressure from recent
declines in first-class mail and chronic losses in next-day and
international deliveries. This year, the Postal Service expects to
lose about $300 million, its first annual loss since 1994. The
Postal Service has struck limited deals in recent months with
Airborne Freight Corp. and DHL Worldwide Express _ but those
agreements aren't nearly as sweeping as the alliance being
discussed with FedEx.
</P>
<P>
   UPS officials say the Postal Rate Commission and Congress should
ultimately decide the public policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   A Postal Service/FedEx partnership seems an odd marriage. Some
of FedEx's national TV ads in the 1980s mocked Postal Service
employees, and two years ago the Postal Service launched its own
series of ads taking aim at FedEx and UPS. FedEx sued to halt the
ads, but the Postal Service campaign continued.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the acrimony, FedEx and the Postal Service have worked
together in the past.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx, founded in 1971 as Federal Express, was designed to speed
the delivery of canceled checks for the Federal Reserve Bank. The
idea never caught on, but Federal Express survived its lean years
by carrying U.S. mail at night on its small jet aircraft. Revenue
from the Postal Service kept the young company afloat as it
struggled through the mid-1970s to create a market for next-morning
shipments.
</P>
<P>
   When premium-priced, next-morning deliveries caught on, FedEx
dropped its mail routes.
</P>
<P>
   Emery Worldwide currently handles the bulk of the Postal
Service's air shipments. But the two organizations have been at
odds since April when Emery sued claiming breach of contract.
Postal Service officials said Thursday that a deal with FedEx would
replace the existing Emery contract.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
