<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-UNDERDOG-HNS &LR;      09-07 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERDOG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush declares himself the underdog in race against Gore
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By R.G. RATCLIFFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   YPSILANTI, Mich. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, once enveloped by
an aura of inevitability, officially went from presidential
front-runner Thursday to self-declared underdog and challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks after exiting the Republican National Convention with
a 16 percentage point lead over Democrat Al Gore, Bush suddenly
found himself either tied with or trailing the vice president in
three new national public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the underdog. Sure I am. But I was the underdog when I
first started and nothing's changed about underdog status,'' said
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised a record $90 million for his campaign and led in
almost all previous poll match-ups with Gore over the past year.
Gore went to a Halloween party last year dressed as the cartoon
character Underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a very tough opponent. He is the incumbent,'' Bush
said. ``And a challenger is somebody who generally comes from the
pack and wins, if you're going to win, and that's where I'm coming
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane alluded to Bush's successful
fund-raising in reacting to the governor's newly acknowledged
status. ``He's the first $100 million underdog I've ever seen,''
Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his campaign team promised to retool his effort, to
give his policy proposals more of a human face and to get more
aggressive with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may go more alpha male going down the stretch,'' Bush joked,
referring to Gore's hiring of a feminist consultant last year to
reshape his image from that of an underling of President Clinton to
that of a top dog _ an alpha male.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's statements were his first public admission that momentum
may have shifted from his campaign to Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Bush last week dismissed a Houston Chronicle report that his
advisers were privately concerned about trends in the campaign, but
Thursday he was confronted with a New York Times story that openly
quoted Washington Republicans as saying they were afraid Bush might
lose.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he always expected the race to tighten this
fall. He said Washington insiders who talked to the New York Times
should have more confidence in his campaign's ability to turn
things around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's people getting ready to jump out of the foxhole before
the first shell is fired in Washington, D.C.,'' Bush said. ``But
when you get out here in Michigan, Ohio and Pennsylvania and you
talk to the troops on the ground, they're excited and they want to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his battlefield analogies, Bush on Thursday
picked up formal endorsements from former Joint Chiefs of Staff
Chairman Colin Powell and retired Gen. Norman Schwartzkopf.
</P>
<P>
   In two new national polls, Bush and Gore are in a statistical
dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News poll found the pair tied at 47 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   In a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll, Gore led 47 percent to 44
percent over Bush, but that was a statistical tie because of the
poll's margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. The
poll of 777 likely voters was taken Monday through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore held a solid lead over Bush in a Reuters/Zogby
International poll. Gore led Bush 46 percent to 40 percent in a
survey that found 5 percent support for Green Party candidate Ralph
Nader and 2 percent support for Reform Party candidate Patrick
Buchanan. In a two-way race, Gore led 49 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby survey of 1,001 likely voters also found a tremendous
gender gap. Gore held a 21 percentage point lead among women and
Bush an 11 percentage point lead among men.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also held a major lead over Bush on issues such as
education, health care for children and campaign finance reform.
And he led Bush by 9 percentage points on prescription drugs issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed a system teaming Medicare, the federal health
program for seniors, with private insurers to provide prescription
drug insurance policies. Gore would directly subsidize
prescriptions through Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's advantage in the national polls, Zogby found a
virtual tie in the battleground states of the Midwest, with Bush
leading in the region 47 percent to 45 percent. A victory in key
states could deliver Bush an Electoral College win even if he
trailed in national popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very competitive race, especially among key swing
groups,'' said pollster John Zogby.
</P>
<P>
   Bush agreed. ``The vice president has run a strong race. But so
have I,'' Bush said. ``If people asked me a year ago if by Labor
Day would I be happy with a close race, if the economy was still
strong, I'd say sure. I'm under no illusions and neither should our
supporters be. It's going to be a tough contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush adviser Charlie Black of Washington said some of the
nervousness reflected in the New York Times story was caused by an
``artificially high'' lead Bush took out of his convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find more people nervous inside of the Beltway than
outside,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   But Black said Gore did a good job with his convention speech
and benefited from three weeks of positive media coverage that the
vice president had not previously obtained in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going to be hand-to-hand combat for a while,'' Black
said, saying things could change with the presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to give some ground Thursday in what had seemed an
impasse over debates, offering to begin negotiations. On Sunday,
Bush challenged Gore to meet him on NBC television next Tuesday,
but Gore refused until Bush agreed to all three events sponsored by
the bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates. Bush agreed to
only one of those, and had been unwilling to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I want to make it clear to you. I want there to be
debates,'' Bush said. ``I'm confident that there will be debates.
As to what they look like and where they are, it will be worked out
in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Methodist University political scientist Cal Jillson
said Bush lost his lead because Gore capitalized on his convention
and dominated the issues for three weeks, especially with his
prescription drug plan.
</P>
<P>
   Jillson said then Bush's verbal gaffes and inability to explain
his budget plan one day distracted from his campaign efforts to get
his own message out.
</P>
<P>
   Jillson said Bush's personality may make it difficult to come
from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is a much better front-runner than a candidate trying to
make up ground,'' Jillson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a front-runner he tends to be buoyant and amiable,''
Jillson said. ``He's much more tight when he's trying to come from
behind. His face is tight and his posture is drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush is used to this
position, having come from behind in 1994 to defeat Texas Gov. Ann
Richards and then having turned his Republican presidential primary
campaign around after losing New Hampshire to Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has recaptured some of the traditional
benefits of incumbency, but Governor Bush likes his position as a
challenger. He likes being the challenger. We're going to work very
hard. Every day is going to be a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the campaign will do more activities like visiting
the homes of taxpayers to show how Bush's proposed tax cut will
save them money. Bush said he may start doing town hall meetings
again and hold fewer news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he is not going to let one bad set of polls
bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been down in the polls before in this campaign, and I've
been up,'' Bush said. ``Every time I went up, a lot of folks in
Washington were right with me. And when the polls went down, they
started getting a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
