<SLUG> BC-BBA-TWINS-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX OVERCOME EARLY TWINS LEAD TO TRIUMPH, 11-6 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For one dark moment on a glorious September afternoon,
grand old Fenway Park Thursday felt like Bleak House.
</P>
<P>
   A game the struggling Sox sorely needed to win was slipping
away. Fans who had cashed in comp days to cheer the hometown team
were all but covering their eyes at the ugliness. And it was only
the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yet just when a crescendo of boos suggested all faith had been
hijacked, the Sox stormed back from the precipice, overcoming a 5-0
deficit to dump the Minnesota Twins, 11-6, and keep hope alive in
their quest for a place in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The win stopped the bleeding from a rough loss to Oakland the
night before and bolstered the Sox for Friday's opener of a
four-game showdown with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge,'' said third baseman Lou Merloni, whose three
hits and two RBIs were instrumental. ``Every game from now on is
big, but this one, it just seemed like we had to have this game.
There's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The crucial comeback was powered by a late-blooming power
hitter, Jose Offerman, and a supporting cast led by the
no-longer-dizzy Merloni, returning to full-time action from a mild
concussion, and the increasingly reliable newcomer Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   But it might have failed without a timely turnaround by Ramon
Martinez, who swiftly righted himself after the Twins shelled him
for the five first-inning runs. The game was a makeup of a July 26
rainout.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest blow in the first was a grand slam by David Ortiz,
which was the third first-inning slam Martinez has yielded in his
last five starts. Jay Buhner hit one against him in Seattle July 31
and Will Clark crushed one in Baltimore July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Corey Koskie followed Ortiz's shot with a solo homer
to make it 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out there and give up five runs, you don't have to
give up,'' Martinez said. ``You can never give up. You have to give
your team a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Which he did splendidly. After Koskie's bomb, Martinez retired
the next 10 batters and 16 of the next 17. He then yielded a bloop
single to Koskie and a run-scoring triple to Torii Hunter before
manager Jimy Williams inserted Jeff Fassero as the first of five
relievers who helped seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Martinez departed, the Sox were sitting on a 9-6
lead. And Williams credited Pedro's big brother for withstanding
the first-inning pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a sign of a guy who has been through the war, so to
speak,'' Williams said. ``He's a professional, to be able to
maintain his composure. He bent a little, but he didn't break.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez received a standing ovation when he left, not long
after many of the same patrons jeered him. And he can thank the Sox
hitters for giving him the lead that helped make it possible.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, power starved for much of the season, launched the
comeback by lacing a home run into the left-field screen in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   And Bichette, who doubled to open the second, scored on
Merloni's two-out single to make it 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing to do when you're down 5-0 is try to get all
five back right away,'' Merloni said. ``You just chip away.''
</P>
<P>
   They chipped plenty in the fourth. Bichette made the first dent
with a leadoff homer into the screen, his second homer in as many
games. He said he is trying to use the pressure of the pennant race
to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is at stake right now,'' Bichette said, ``so I'm
just trying to enjoy it and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the inning ended, the Sox batted around, chased starter
Eric Milton, and scored five runs on three more hits and two walks.
The big hit other than Bichette's homer was a two-out, two-run
double by Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Sox a 7-5 lead, which they increased to 9-5 in the
fifth on a single by Jason Varitek, an RBI double by Merloni, and
Mike Lansing's run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we've always had since I've been here, the
ability to come back,'' said Varitek, who joined the team in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After the Twins scored the run off Martinez in the sixth, the
Sox countered in their half of the inning. Offerman led off with a
double to the gap in left-center. A batter later, Garciaparra lined
a single that left fielder Matt Lawton let scoot past him for an
error, allowing Offerman to score, making it 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's second homer of the day, another screen job, made it
11-6 in the eighth. It was his third homer in two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in our offense,'' Williams said, ``and they did an
outstanding job on a day when he had to have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday brings a new test, as Roger Clemens goes against rookie
Tomo Ohka, who was in grade school in Kyoto, Japan, when Clemens
was winning 24 games and pitching the Sox into the 1986 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running out of games and we've got to make up some
ground, so every game is big,'' said Bryce Florie, who pitched a
scoreless ninth to preserve the victory. ``But if we can do
something against those guys, we can put ourselves right back in
the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing bleak about that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
