<HEADLINE>
ON WORKPLACE SLEEVES,   FEW POLITICAL HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ark., Fla., Calif., Colo.)   (For release Sunday, September 10)  
 By LINDA LIGOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention in Philadelphia last month,
Dean Dennis, an alternate delegate from Colorado, stood on the
convention floor shouting his lungs out for George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Back at work, though, Dennis keeps his mouth shut about the
election campaign. As the facilities manager for the Pueblo
Convention Center, he said, he tries to keep his work life and
political life separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the type to back somebody into the company water
cooler and fill them with rhetoric,'' said Dennis, whose wife,
Ginette, is a Republican state senator.
</P>
<P>
   With the fall political campaign season gathering speed, many
politically active workers in corporate America find themselves
downplaying their activism while on the job, or at least keeping
their politicking below the radar of frowning managers.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say overt political activism can cut both ways,
advancing some careers while retarding others, depending on the
circumstances. As a rule, though, both managers and workers seem to
prefer keeping it low-key, an approach made easier by the Internet
and e-mail communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political activism within the workplace is divisive,'' said
David Heller, chief executive of Internet Business Systems in
Campbell, Calif. ``If someone's got strong views, we don't want to
hear about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Formal bans are rare, but informal taboos are widespread. ``Most
companies operate on a `don't ask, don't tell' policy when it comes
to political involvement,'' said Eric J. Wallach, who heads the
employment practices group at Kasowitz, Benson, Torres &AMP; Friedman,
a law firm based in New York. ``They don't want to act like Big
Brother and tell people what to do outside of the workplace. But
they want employees to be discreet while they're on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   That describes the attitude of Dennis' boss. ``I don't care if
our employees are involved in politics, as long as they don't bring
their activities into the workplace,'' said Mich Sauers, chief
executive of Global Spectrum in Tampa, Fla., which manages the
Pueblo center and others.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Erives' involvement in the Democratic Party is hardly a
secret to her boss at Qwest, a telecommunications company in
Denver: She took time off to serve as a delegate for Al Gore at the
party's national convention in Los Angeles. But neither Erives, an
operations analyst, nor her co-workers talk politics on the job.
``It's kind of an unwritten rule that we stay apolitical,'' she
said; the furthest she goes is reminding colleagues to vote each
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Why do politically active workers keep such a low profile? Some
do so because companies insist. While most states have laws
forbidding discrimination against private-sector employees because
of political activity outside the workplace, they also allow
employers to restrict the use of company time and resources for
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Such policies do not deter some employees from engaging in
quiet, behind-the-scenes politicking beyond the boss' notice.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick A. Sweeney, an assistant public defender for Allegheny
County, Pa., which does not have such a policy, said he is quiet
around his mainly Republican superiors, but often discusses his
Democratic views with co-workers, and even recruited several
interns to attend a fund-raising luncheon for Representative
Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a group of us who hash out a lot of the issues,''
Sweeney said. ``Lately, the biggest debates have been about
national health care and HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   Company computer systems are often used by employees to quietly
send politically motivated e-mail messages or to surf political
sites on the Internet, often without management's consent. The
great majority of people who visit E-ThePeople.com, a nonpartisan
Web site that helps users sign petitions and send memos to elected
officials, do so from 9 to 5 weekdays in their time zones. ``People
are definitely using company time to get out their political
messages,'' said Alex Sheshunoff, the Web site's president.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all employers try to ban politics at work; some
welcome activism, while many more look the other way. Daniel Lysk,
an asset administrator in Little Rock, Ark., said he proudly
displays his activism in the animal-rights movement and other
causes. His cubicle is decorated with anti-fur posters and
photographs of him dressed as a cow for a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   He once had to tell his boss that he might not make it back to
work on time after a trip to Indianapolis because, while there, he
planned to throw animal feces into the crowd at the Pork Expo and
might be arrested as a result. (He wasn't.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've definitely influenced people at work to support animal
rights,'' Lysk said, adding that he also sends e-mail messages to
fellow activists elsewhere during the workday. ``I don't smoke, so
to me, these activities are my cigarette break,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many bosses might not appreciate such activities at work, but
Dave Dillon, who supervises Lysk, said he doesn't mind. ``He isn't
obnoxious about it,'' Dillon said. ``I let it pass.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw advantages in having politically active
employees. ``I find that people like Dan who are passionate about a
cause bring that same level of passion and caring to their jobs,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing his view, for a somewhat different reason, is Douglas S.
Stone, a law partner at King Hershey Coleman Coch &AMP; Stone in Kansas
City, Mo. Its lawyers are accustomed to working with city officials
in navigating real estate deals. They feel at home in political
circles and are encouraged to be politically active. Stone was a
Democratic convention delegate last month and ran for a seat in the
Kansas Legislature in 1998. One partner is a former councilman; two
others have run for other offices.
</P>
<P>
   In such a firm, unanimity helps: all the politically active
lawyers are Democrats. ``We all sit around and tell George Bush
jokes,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses in other fields encourage employee involvement
in politics as well, often because the chief executive is
politically active. Many create political action committees and
encourage employees to contribute, said Larry Makinson, executive
director of the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington: ``At
some companies, soliciting political donations has become part of
the corporate culture.''
</P>
<P>
   An example is Enron, the Houston energy conglomerate, which even
suggests how much employees should give. Kenneth L. Lay, the
chairman, recently sent top executives a memo on his stationery
asking them to contribute $1,000 each to the Bush campaign, said
Steven J. Kean, an executive vice president. This year, Enron and
its employees have contributed more than $615,000 to the Bush
campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are limits, even at companies like Enron. ``We might
tell employees to go out and vote, but nobody tells them who to
vote for or passes out brochures,'' Kean said. ``That kind of thing
is just not acceptable in today's workplace.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
