<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAMON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ GOES FROM GOAT TO HERO IN ONE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You might be able to count on one hand the number of
times a Red Sox starter has surrendered six runs and eight hits in
5 2/3 innings _ and left to a standing ovation. Maybe even one
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez saw and heard both sides of the Fenway fan
Thursday. He was booed in the first inning, when five of the first
six hitters he faced scored, two on home runs. He then was treated
to the standing O five innings later, having allowed only three
more hits and, by that time, one incidental additional run. The
early 5-0 hole was quickly erased in Boston's 11-6 win over
Minnesota and Martinez won for the ninth time this season and for
the first time since July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, about this early stuff, Ramon. It's becoming a habit. How
many pitchers can lay claim to surrendering three first-inning
grand slams in a single season? (Five others also have given up
three grand slams this season, but Martinez has the first-inning
distinction all to himself.)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but there are good signs for Boston when this happens. In
all three instances, the Red Sox rallied to win, so they are 3-0 in
games in which Martinez gives up a granny in the first. In two of
those three, Martinez himself picked up the W.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the first three Minnesota batters reached on singles,
and David Ortiz then deposited a 2-2 delivery into the right-field
stands. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan came out for a chat. Three
pitches later, Corey Koskie homered to right.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, much of Martinez's early troubles have been due to
wildness. In Seattle on July 31, he walked the bases loaded and
then gave up a granny to Jay Buhner. Eleven days earlier, he had
given up a first-inning slam to Will Clark in Baltimore. He has a
first-inning ERA of 11.35.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, Martinez had two strikes on each of the first
four hitters, so it wasn't control. What was it, then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Martinez said. ``It was a rough first inning,
that's for sure. It happened before. I missed a couple pitches and
they took advantage of that. But I didn't change anything. I kept
throwing strikes and everything was better after that.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a mild understatement. In a remarkable 180, Martinez
closed the first by striking out Torii Hunter and getting Jacque
Jones on a grounder to second. Thus began a stretch in which he
retired 10 in a row and 16 of 17, the only blemish being a two-out
single to center in the fourth by Jones.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Sox had caught and passed the Twins, thanks to
a five-run fourth which gave them a never-look-back 7-5 lead. It
was 9-5 after five.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the sixth, however, Martinez gave up a single to
Koskie. Manager Jimy Williams came to the mound. There was a chat.
Martinez remained in the game.
</P>
<P>
   What did Williams say?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's between a manager and his pitcher. Good question,
though,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Hunter, tripled off the center-field wall.
Williams came out again and Martinez departed after 5 2/3 innings,
five runs, eight hits, seven strikeouts, no walks, 96 pitches, 25
batters faced. His ERA rose from 5.83 to 6.02. He he has pitched
more than six innings only three times. He still got a big ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the sign of a guy who has been through the war, so to
speak,'' Williams said. ``A true professional. He kept his
composure and fought back. After that first inning, he was
outstanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
