<SLUG> BC-OIL-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE HIKES EXPECTED TO HIT OIL, GAS CONSUMERS THIS WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers of home heating oil should brace for stiff price
increases this winter after crude prices this week hit their
highest level in 10 years, speakers at an energy forum said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Supply is unlikely to be interrupted, panelists at the event
held at the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston agreed. But price is
another story, and hikes are expected to hit gas as well as oil.
</P>
<P>
   --Fearing recession, Clinton urges OPEC to boost output. C5.
</P>
<P>
   A US Department of Energy official cited projections of an 18
percent rise, to $900, in the cost of heating an average Northeast
household for the winter with oil, assuming ``normal'' weather.
Even though the gas supply to this area is now seen as more
reliable than oil, a larger price increase _ 25 percent _ was
forecast for a household using gas.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci opened the session with a stern warning
about the heating fuel challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average price for a gallon of heating oil already is
running well above last year's level and is expected to rise as the
weather turns colder,'' Cellucci said. ``And, unlike last year, the
price of natural gas also is on the rise, primarily because of
market conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   New England was hit last winter with its worst heating oil
crisis since the 1980s after OPEC cut the world supply of crude and
a January cold snap set in. Heating oil prices spiked as much as
150 percent, to $2 a gallon, and glitches in the supply line
reduced the region at one point to a 10-day supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been a disaster for elderly and low-income
people across New England,'' Cellucci said. Thursday's forum,
sponsored by the New England Governors' Conference and the New
England Council, was called in hopes of getting a jump in preparing
for another crunch this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities for doing much at the state level are limited.
Two of the biggest factors affecting supply and demand _ OPEC
production levels and the severity of this winter's weather _ are
outside state control.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci urged everyone from President Clinton to individual
consumers to take a variety of steps he said could help. He called
for Clinton to:
</P>
<P>
   --Increase the size of a planned Northeast heating-oil reserve
recently announced by the president. Federal officials have said
they would buy 2 million barrels and store them at two regional
sites.
</P>
<P>
   --Approve the early release of federal funds earmarked to help
low-income families in the Northeast buy heating fuel. Making the
funds available sooner would allow the states to better prepare for
a heating emergency and encourage distributors to set up larger
reserves, according to Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci advised consumers to winterize their homes at first
opportunity, buy heating fuel early before prices go up further,
and consider buying fuel at fixed rates. Distributors have stopped
writing fixed contracts, but probably only temporarily, according
to other speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter remains we are consuming just too
much,'' said Jack Sullivan of the New England Fuel Institute. ``If
there's one lesson that should be brought to every consumer, it's
conserve, conserve, conserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers noted that the price spike follows oil plunging
as low as $10 a barrel only two years ago. West Texas Intermediate
crude for October delivery closed Wednesday at $34.90 a barrel. It
closed Thursday at $34.39.
</P>
<P>
   Oil inventories were reported below normal, but industry
speakers said financial incentives to replenish them are lacking
with prices so volatile. Cellucci said the state will consider
offering to buy surplus oil after the winter so that suppliers
don't have to worry about being stuck with excess inventory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 1957EDT &QL; 
