Inc. over their handling of apparently defective Firestone tires
that were used on some Ford models. Meanwhile, Congress is weighing
legislation that would require companies to immediately report
recalls that occur in other countries. By JENNIFER HOYT.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-TRIBUTE (Washington) _ A political action committee
supporting House Republicans who led the impeachment case against
President Clinton has postponed a tribute to former Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr. With some of Clinton's House prosecutors
facing tough election battles this November, Republicans are
questioning the wisdom of placing an emphasis on what was a losing
issue for them in the polls. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX (Washington) _ The House fails to override President
Clinton's veto of the estate tax repeal, giving Republicans what
they say is a potent political issue for the campaign trail. By
JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UN-SUMMIT (United Nations) _ World leaders turn from the
ceremony of the Millennium Summit to problems facing the United
Nations, including peacekeeping operations and end to conflicts in
several regions of the globe. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING (Houston) _ Sen. Charles Hagel, R-Neb., a global
warming skeptic and chief critic of the Kyoto accords, addresses a
conference at Rice University's Baker Institute on Public Policy.
By TODD ACKERMAN and BILL DAWSON.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ Ground teams are back on
schedule, overcoming storm delays as they prepare the shuttle
Atlantis and a crew of seven for a mission to the international
space station. The shuttle is to lift off Friday morning. By MARK
CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Al Gore's vow to fight for a minimum
wage increase prompted big cheers at the Democratic National
Convention, second only to promises to protect abortion rights and
overhaul the health care system. The minimum wage issue is so
popular that congressional Republicans dare not oppose it outright.
Instead they are loading it up with tax breaks for business. George
W. Bush has his own zinger. He wants to give states the right to
ignore the minimum wage if they want. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-TRAINER (Washington) _ It was originally billed by the
Pentagon as a low-risk, relatively low-cost program to equip the
armed forces with a simple training aircraft for novice pilots. But
now the project is expected to significantly exceed cost estimates
_ by $753 million _ with taxpayers footing most of the bill. By
ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
