<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-07 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAKED MEN AND OTHER   SEASONAL PLEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   By   JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a long, somnolent summer, Broadway came alive
again this week. Just hours after Labor Day turned into that
terrible Tuesday, rehearsals began for ``The Full Monty,'' the
musical version of the hit 1997 movie and a show promising more
male nudity than any Broadway production since ``Love! Valour!
Compassion!''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also brought the first preview of ``The Best Man,'' Gore
Vidal's 1960 political satire. Earlier, at an dress rehearsal,
Vidal took to the stage to trumpet the quality of this revival. ``I
haven't changed a word,'' he said proudly. Whether that was wise
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday two more fall entries began their out-of-town
tryouts: ``The Search for Signs of Intelligent Life in the
Universe'' in Seattle and ``Seussical'' in Boston. (More on this
later.) Farther afield a pair of productions from the same
household but on opposite sides of the globe may also gather some
serious attention from New York producers.
</P>
<P>
   The first is ``The Late Henry Moss,'' Sam Shepard's new play,
which opens with an all-star cast (Nick Nolte, Cheech Marin, Sean
Penn and Woody Harrelson) at the Magic Theater in San Francisco on
Nov. 14. Less certain but equally intriguing is the possibility
that Jessica Lange, who lives with Shepard, may take on Mary
Tyrone, the ephemeral mother of despair in Eugene O'Neill's ``Long
Day's Journey Into Night,'' in a November production in London.
Nothing is confirmed, but if it comes together, expect some
jet-lagged audience members at that premiere.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, the big action was closer to home,
where a mix of the musical, the comical and the lyrical promised an
interesting Broadway season. At very least it won't put anyone to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSICALS
</P>
<P>
   The musical carrying with the heaviest burden of expectation is
the season's most lighthearted. On Nov. 9 ``Seussical'' is
scheduled to open at the Richard Rodgers Theater, having run the
gamut of gossip, from reports of early ecstasy to more recent
signals of concern.
</P>
<P>
   The costume designer was fired recently, and if the critics in
Boston can be trusted, the show still needs work. Writing Thursday
in The Boston Globe, Ed Siegel said the show was overearnest and
clunky, faulting its ``middle-of-the-road literal-mindedness.''
That said, he also predicted success on Broadway, thanks to a
catchy score.
</P>
<P>
   With the questions hanging over ``Seussical,'' ``The Full
Monty'' has emerged as a contender for the title of Big Musical.
The show finished a sold-out run at the Old Globe in San Diego in
July and, on the strength of supportive reviews, booked the Eugene
O'Neill. The show's advance buzz and advance sales have been
strong. It also has the jump on the competition; with a Oct. 26
opening it is the first musical offering of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The final new musical of the fall is ``Jane Eyre,'' which
bounced around the regional circuit for several years before a
successful run at La Jolla Playhouse in California over the summer.
In November it lands at the Brooks Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of dominance of revivals, the fall's only
return engagement is ``The Rocky Horror Show,'' and one would be
hard-pressed to categorize this 1975 camp favorite as standard
Broadway fare. (For those of you who missed the long-running
midnight movie, here's a synopsis: A couple gets lost and finds a
haunted castle. Freaks emerge.) The show, which opens on Nov. 14 at
Circle in the Square, has already won the award for the most
eclectic cast, luring a rocker (Joan Jett), a talker (Dick Cavett)
and a mocker (Lea DeLaria) into Frankenfurter Castle.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 new Broadway productions planned for the fall 6 are
plays. ``The Best Man'' will be the first, opening on Sept. 17.
</P>
<P>
   October will bring something of a modern rarity: two new plays
in a single week. The first is ``The Dinner Party'' from Neil
Simon, mounting his first new comedy on Broadway since
``Proposals'' in 1997. It opens on Oct. 19 at the Music Box.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 24 ``Proof,'' David Auburn's mathematically tinged drama
about a father and daughter, opens at the Walter Kerr. It is one of
two transfers from the Manhattan Theater Club; the second, the
comedy ``The Tale of the Allergist's Wife,'' opens on Nov. 2 at the
Barrymore. Its advance stands at about $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``The Best Man,'' and ``Search for Signs,'' the other
revival of the fall is the Roundabout Theater's ``Betrayal,''
Harold Pinter's time-bending dissection of infidelity. The cast was
set this week: Juliette Binoche, Liev Shrieber and John Slattery.
The director is David Leveaux, whose stewardship of another
adultery-laden classic, ``The Real Thing,'' was a high point of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   As usual Off Broadway offers far more new drama. One proven
Broadway talent, the French playwright Yazmina Reza (``Art''),
opens her newest work, ``The Unexpected Man,'' at a big small
house, the 399-seat Promenade, on Oct. 24. Eileen Atkins and Alan
Bates star as strangers on a train.
</P>
<P>
   Some A-list American writers also have new work in store,
including Wendy Wasserstein (``Old Money,'' at Lincoln Center),
Craig Lucas (``Stranger,'' at the Vineyard), Susan Sontag (``Alice
in Bed,'' at New York Theater Workshop) and Horton Foote (``The
Last of the Thorntons,'' at the Signature Theater). Let's not
forget Isaac Mizrahi, the fashion designer cum showman, who brings
his one-man show, ``Les Mizrahi,'' to the Drama Dept. in October.
Mizrahi promises to sing, dance and sew every night.
</P>
<P>
   For clowning, however, it is tough to compete with the master
vaudevillian Bill Irwin, who will return to familiar territory with
Samuel Beckett's ``Texts for Nothing,'' opening in October at the
Classic Stage Company.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, known for his near-silent clowning with David Shiner (the
Cat in the Hat in ``Seussical''), performed an adaptation of
``Texts,'' directed by Joseph Chaikin, to critical acclaim in 1992.
This time Irwin is directing himself and doing just 4 of the 13
short monologues in ``Texts.'' The process sounded appropriately
Beckettian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage manager and I are in here alone every day,'' Irwin
said. ``It's different. And every day I work on it, it gets more
different.''
</P>
<P>
   He added with a laugh, ``We shall see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
