<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: SYSTEM FAILS, BUT PLAYER PROSPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.C.)   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding a franchise player in the NFL draft is one of the great
challenges of our time, even more difficult than deciphering the
latest rap lyrics or discovering intelligent life on other planets.
A scout once compared the excitement of watching a top quarterback
prospect to the day that he got married. It is true the scout needs
to get a life, but his words explain just how desperate teams are
to select that special player.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Philadelphia Eagles running back Duce Staley,
a franchise player if there ever was one, and someone who
exemplifies what happens when professional football's anal,
fat-pinching, stopwatch-obsessed system completely misses the boat
on a prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Staley may prove to be one of the great runners of the next five
years, but when he was coming out of the University of South
Carolina in 1997, scouts called Staley too small and too slow.
Eight running backs were picked ahead of him in the draft that
year, none of whom have proven to be better than Staley.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's scouts try so hard. Each year they log tens of
thousands of miles going to various college campuses, staying at
hotels, motels or their brother-in-law's basement, just so they can
get up at 5 in the morning to time some college prospect in the
40-yard dash. Then, when the scouting process is done, teams design
computer graphs and flow charts that rival NASA's. They know what a
player ate last Thursday and if his children's children will prefer
boxers or briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Then someone like Staley sneaks through the cracks and makes the
system look ridiculous. Last week against Dallas it was Staley,
practically an invisible man to the NFL as a college prospect, who
rushed for 201 yards on 26 carries, the fifth-best opening-game
performance since 1933. He became the Eagles' first 200-yard runner
since Steve Van Buren in 1949 and gives the team hope of capturing
the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Staley, after rushing for 1,273 yards last season, is
probably one of the top five to seven runners in the game, a
younger version of the St. Louis superstar, Marshall Faulk. But
where did Staley come from? He emerged despite an NFL system that
sometimes relies too heavily on numbers and not enough on what
happens on the field, which should be the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Staley transferred from Itawamba Community College in Fulton,
Miss., to South Carolina, where he stunned coaches with his
quickness and toughness. Still, NFL scouts were not impressed. At
barely 5 feet 11 inches and just over 200 pounds, Staley simply did
not fit the NFL prototype for a featured running back. So he was
picked in only the third round of the draft by Philadelphia, not an
obscenely low selection, but too low for someone with his apparent
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick Dunn, Antowaine Smith, Tiki Barber, Byron Hanspard,
Corey Dillon, Sedrick Shaw, Troy Davis and Jay Graham were all
chosen before Staley. Dunn has been mediocre; Smith and Barber are
solid but not as durable as Staley; while Hanspard, Shaw, Davis and
Graham _ supposedly bigger or faster players who would fit better
in the professional ranks than Staley _ were all busts. Dillon has
exceptional talent but is a troublemaker off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Staley is cognizant he was an afterthought in the scouting
process, and it remains a source of motivation. ``Sometimes you
have to fight through things and be a man who makes it happen
yourself,'' Staley said. ``Especially in what I do for a living, no
one is going to hand you anything. You have to pick yourself up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the NFL does get it right, teams go against the
system, and pick that obscure player who fails to fit into the
picture-perfect frame. The Giants selected the Lambuth University
wide receiver Ron Dixon in the third round despite the fact he was
not from a football powerhouse. Dixon might be one of the best
picks of the entire 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   But too many teams stick to the numbers. One team's scout, when
rating Staley as an NFL prospect in 1997, was disappointed in his
speed _ he was timed at 4.65 seconds in the 40-yard sprint,
considered slow for a runner. A scout on a different team felt
Staley's smallish frame was too slight to accommodate his inside
running style in the pros. And yet another team's scout wrote the
following in a report, ``a backup at most.''
</P>
<P>
   The system hiccuped. It goofed, but Staley prospers. Now Staley
can only laugh, and his chuckle will grow louder as those
supposedly slow legs carry him to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
