 PERSONALS: Miss M Becomes More Divine 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Bette Midler &LR; , who started her career singing in gay bathhouses in
New York and now has a 13-year-old daughter and a new TV series,
has changed her mind about raunchy material. The morality of the
modern entertainment industry, she tells Good Housekeeping magazine
this month, is ``grotesque. I mean, `There's Something About Mary'
_ that stuff used to be private. What happened? There are some
things that are completely off the table: really terrible language.
And drugs. And behavior that is uncivilized. Violence. Sex before
you're ready for it. Violent sex. Grossness. There are other ways
to behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Midler's early material was created for her by  &UR; Bruce &LR; 
 &UR; Vilanch &LR; , the comedy writer who was in town this week promoting his
new book, ``Adventures in the Skin Trade.'' During an appearance on
BayTV's ``The Show,'' Vilanch seemed genuinely fond of Midler but
joked about having worked with her for 30 years and suddenly
realizing that on her new show she portrays herself as being merely
30ish.
</P>
<P>
   Old friends think Midler's new stance is ``ironic,'' said
Vilanch, but understand that it's a natural result of being the
mother of a teenager. Midler's husband,  &UR; Martin von Haselberg &LR; ,
used to do nude performance art.
</P>
<P>
   Vilanch laughed and remembered the old days when audiences would
shout, ``Gross us out, Miss M.'' And she would.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE BUZZ &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Al Gore &LR;  has made a personal apology, by telephone, to reporter
 &UR; Chad Swiatecki  &LR; of the Flint (Mich.) Journal, who was told by the
candidate's spokespeople that he couldn't cover a Gore campaign
appearance in Michigan because the campaign stop was inaccessible
to wheelchairs. Swiatecki, who has used a wheelchair since
childhood, was told that both the press entourage bus and General
Motors plant site of Gore's appearance could not accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   Swiatecki's first-person story about the denial of access
appeared in his newspaper on Tuesday, Sept. 5. ``They say the
squeaky wheel is the one that gets greased,'' he wrote. ``Well, Al,
I've got four of them. Can you hear them yet?''
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Christie Brinkley &LR;  told  &UR; Colin Powell &LR;  at a New York
luncheon sponsored by Redbook magazine this week, ``I'm really
scared of  &UR; George W &LR; . I mean really scared.'' Said Powell, who was
quoted in the New York Daily News, ``You don't have to be afraid of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Deauville Film Festival, director  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Altman &LR;  said that if Bush is elected, ``I'm leaving for France.''
To which Bush campaign spokesman  &UR; Ari Fleischer &LR;  said, ``The French
will be very lucky to have a man of his stature _ and we'll welcome
him back to America in 2009.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Linda Polley &LR;  of Fargo, N.D., told Wireless Flash News
Service that she is in contact with  &UR; John Lennon &LR; 's spirit and that
he has dictated a new song to her, entitled ``It's Heaven That
We're Dying For.'' But in Berkeley, Calif., &UR; Country Joe &LR; 
 &UR; McDonald &LR; , whose 1965 song ``I-Feel-Like-I'm-Fixin-to-Die Rag''
included the phrase ``It's heaven we're fighting for,'' says he
usually gets licensing fees for such usage.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting royalties from heaven would be difficult, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Paul McCartney &LR; , who paints on an easel that belonged to
 &UR; Rene &LR; 
 &UR; Magritte &LR; , told the Telegraph of London that his late wife,
 &UR; Linda &LR; , once asked him, ``Why do you want to exhibit?'' (which
doesn't seem like the most flattering question). His answer:
``People will wonder what I have been up to all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Screen Actors Guild is asking actors who support the SAG
strike to wear gold ribbons during Sunday night's Emmy ceremonies.
The cast of ``Frasier'' held a press conference Wednesday
announcing the ribbons and asking ABC to refrain from running
nonunion ads during the show.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The key to breaking the ice is making yourself stand out in &LR; 
 &UR; your target's mind. When you're surrounded by misery, that means &LR; 
 &UR; putting on a serene, happy face. According to Nanette Pope, a &LR; 
 &UR; Boston PR rep who met her beau at her great-uncle's last call, &LR; 
 &UR; it's the man who celebrates living who gets noticed.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ From How to Score at a Funeral, in Maxim magazine.
</P>
