A5469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CULT-BIRTH-BOS &LR;      09-07 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULT-BIRTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS CULT MEMBER CONFINED UNTIL HER BABY IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTLEBORO _ Saying he has heard the voice of a cult member's
fetus pleading from the womb, a judge ordered the woman to remain
confined and closely monitored to ensure the child is born healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol County assistant District Attorney Gerald Fitzgerald
told reporters that, towards the end of a day-long closed hearing,
District Judge Kenneth P. Nasif said that his role in protecting
Rebecca Corneau's fetus had enabled him to hear that unborn child's
voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it says `I want to live. I do not want to die. I do not
want to die like my brother Jeremiah did,' '' Fitzgerald said,
quoting Nasif's words from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said the judge also told the courtroom: ``I believe
that Jeremiah died by asphyxiating some contents of the birth
canal. And I believe that this baby could die like Jeremiah.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the religious cult have been jailed for almost a year
because they have refused to provide authorities with information
about Jeremiah and another baby who are missing and believed dead
but whose bodies have never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Corneau was ordered into custody by Nasif on Aug. 31 at
the request of prosecutors who feared for the welfare of her unborn
child.
</P>
<P>
   While Corneau still refuses a medical exam or even to answer
medical questions about her fetus, Judge Nasif ordered that a
medical `command post' be created using staff from Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center to stand by in case there's a medical
emergency during the birth.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the hearing, Judge Nasif confirmed his
quotes in a case which continues to draw national attention as
women's rights activists challenge Corneau's confinement as a
violation of her rights
</P>
<P>
   ``A case of this nature quite frankly for me is difficult from a
technical, legal, right-or-wrong point of view,'' the judge said.
``But in terms of the morality of my decision, it is not difficult
to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasif said that during the entire hearing, Rebecca Corneau never
asked to be allowed to go home, but she consistently and pleasantly
refused to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very polite,'' said John J. Rego, a Rhode Island
attorney appointed to represent Corneau's fetus. ``She doesn't show
any emotion. She just looks straight ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rego said the judge took under advisement a contempt of court
order against Corneau filed by him on behalf of the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Thursday's hearing, Corneau's husband, David,
sought legal counsel for the first time since he was jailed for
refusing to cooperate with a criminal investigation into the
disappearances of the two children.
</P>
<P>
   After attorney Jane Sullivan agreed to represent him, David
Corneau, 32, asked both she and the judge if arrangements could be
made for him to be notified in jail about the birth of his child.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Corneau, also 32, who is estimated to be about 8 1/2
months pregnant, was placed in a Roxbury facility for pregnant
women in state custody last week after repeatedly refusing a
court-ordered medical examination.
</P>
<P>
   Corneau and the group she belongs to have rejected conventional
medicine as blasphemy, believing instead in the power of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian sect, whose members reside in Attleboro and
Seekonk, came under scrutiny in November when they were suspected
of covering up the deaths of Jeremiah Corneau and 10-month-old
Samuel Robidoux, son of cult leader Jacques Robidoux.
</P>
<P>
   David Corneau has told police Jeremiah was stillborn and buried
by the group. Police believe Samuel starved to death when he
stopped breast feeding. But, according to court records, members of
the sect have refused to provide the whereabouts of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Searches throughout Massachusetts and Baxter State Park in Maine
have turned up nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the investigation a number of children from the
cult were taken into state custody and Rebecca Corneau was declared
an unfit mother.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Nasif extended the order keeping Rebecca Corneau in
custody for another 30 days or until her child is born, which was
expected to be soon.
</P>
<P>
   The fetus, known as `Unborn Child Corneau' in court papers, has
dropped, according to medical staff at the facility where Corneau
is being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not far away...from a childbirth here,'' said Bristol
County District Attorney Paul F. Walsh Jr.
</P>
<P>
   If a medical emergency does take place during birth, Walsh said
the judge would have to issue a court order allowing others to help
Corneau and the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Because Corneau has been declared an unfit mother, her newborn
would immediately be turned over to the custody of the state
Department of Social Services. At that point, Walsh said, Corneau
would be free to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Nasif's latest rulings come a day after Walsh defended his
office's actions in the face of a rare legal appeal before the
state's Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   In that petition, a Norfolk County woman identified in court
papers only as Barbara F. asked the state's highest court to throw
out Nasif's ruling against Rebecca Corneau, saying it imperils the
rights of all pregnant women. Thursday the American Civil Liberties
Union filed a friend of the court brief in support of Corneau's
release.
</P>
<P>
   An SJC decision is expected sometime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
