<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GM-LAWSUIT0908-COX     09-07 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-LAWSUIT0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit by ex-safety inspector attacks processes at GM
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General Motors Corp. has delivered possibly tens of
thousands of dangerous vehicles with loose fuel lines, missing
steering-gear bolts and other defects, alleges an Atlanta-area
employee with a whistle-blower lawsuit in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Richard Story will probably keep GM's
vehicle inspection data sealed under a protective order for the
time being, he said Thursday during his first hearing on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped to put this in front of the public,'' said William
McAleer, a former GM safety inspector who alleges that owners of
most of GM's millions of cars and trucks produced since the
mid-1990s are ``playing Russian roulette.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges that GM forced McAleer, 51, out of the
vehicle final inspection program he managed and helped develop
after he tried for years to get GM to fix production problems
causing life-threatening defects in one-quarter of 1 percent to 1
percent of the automakers' cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really have a job,'' said McAleer's Atlanta
attorney, Rose Goff. She said McAleer, still a GM employee who
lives in Woodstock, currently works with a supplier in Alabama
about once a week.
</P>
<P>
   GM denies the allegations. The automaker says McAleer
overestimated the number of quality problems and was told of his
new assignment before he raised the alleged defect issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reassignment had nothing to do with him raising quality
concerns, as evidenced by the fact that GM responded to issues he
raised in a positive fashion by enhancing our quality procedures,''
the company said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   McAleer originally filed suit in Fulton County Superior Court
last October after GM refused a settlement offer for ``$12 million
and to get the cars off the road,'' said Goff. The lawsuit was
later transferred to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Story said he will consolidate a related age
discrimination lawsuit, filed last week, with McAleer's
whistle-blower case.
</P>
<P>
   The two lawsuits ask for back pay and unspecified damages for
emotional distress, plus punitive damages against Detroit-based GM
under Michigan's whistle-blower law.
</P>
<P>
   ``His career at GM is effectively over,'' said Goff.
</P>
<P>
   McAleer alleges that GM forced him from the safety inspection
program in 1998 and tried to get him to retire early.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Goff asked the court to order GM to release its safety
inspection data as open court records. But Story instructed GM's
and McAleer's lawyers to draft a proposed confidentiality agreement
before he will order GM to produce the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Story also said his ``inclination'' is not to order GM President
G. Richard Wagoner Jr. and another top executive to testify in
depositions, as Goff requested. Story is expected to rule next week
on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   McAleer said he and other inspectors inspected about 30 vehicles
monthly from each of GM's North American plants. They found two to
eight ``catastrophic safety defects'' each month, he said, out of
the 1,000 vehicles they inspected and drove over a short test track
designed to reveal squeaks and rattles.
</P>
<P>
   The defects included loose or missing fasteners that secured
such critical components as steering gears, tie rods, gas tanks,
seats and other parts that might cause a driver to lose control of
the vehicle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM spokeswoman Kelly Cusinato said McAleer's small samples and
method of selecting test vehicles didn't produce a reliable
estimate of the number of defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any problem is too much of a problem,'' she said, ``(but) it's
our position that it's not appropriate to extrapolate from such
data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still responded to his issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said GM's quality audit process ``evolved'' as a result of
McAleer's complaints to include more inspections and follow-up at
assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   She said the company conducts multiple inspections, halts
shipping of any cars with defects and requires the affected auto
plant to go through more ``error-proofing'' steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not aware of any injuries or deaths related to matters
alleged by Mr. McAleer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Goff also said that McAleer doesn't know if the alleged defects
caused any accidents that resulted in fatalities or serious
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Courtland Kelley, the GM employee who replaced McAleer as
manager of the so-called Global Delivery Survey program, testified
in a June 1 deposition that he thought the problems ``would be
fixed in short order'' once GM was informed, but that they still
crop up in about one in every 200 to 400 cars tested. McAleer was
formerly Kelley's supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Goff said McAleer had already taken his complaints to National
Highway and Traffic Safety Administration officials last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told him ... that they could not investigate problems
across model lines,'' she said. ``
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
