<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS FAIL TO OVERTURN CLINTON'S ESTATE TAX VETO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Mo.)   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of a bill to repeal the federal tax on
large estates failed Thursday to overturn President Clinton's veto
of the measure, killing the issue for the year in legislative terms
but leaving it very much alive politically.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were eager to take the debate to the
campaign trail, where they said it would attract support from
small-business owners, farmers, entrepreneurs and other voters who
object to having a portion of their wealth taxed when they pass it
to their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, the majority of whom lined up with Clinton in
opposition to the bill, said they would continue to make their case
that while the estate tax should be reduced for family-owned farms
and businesses, the measure that was rejected Thursday would eat up
too much of the projected budget surplus and disproportionately
reward a tiny percentage of the richest families.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had passed both the House and the Senate earlier this
year, with nearly all Republicans and some Democrats voting in
favor. Clinton vetoed it last week.
</P>
<P>
   Overriding the veto would have required a two-thirds vote in
both chambers, and in the House Thursday supporters of the bill
fell well short.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 274 votes in favor of overturning the veto and 157
in favor of sustaining it. It would have taken 290 votes to
overturn the veto if all 435 House members had voted, or 288 of the
431 votes cast Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When the House passed the bill in June by a vote of 279-136, 65
Democrats voted in favor. Thursday, after pressure from party
leaders and phone calls to some of those 65 from Clinton, 53
Democrats bucked their party to support overriding the veto.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after the vote, Clinton commended those members
of the House who voted to uphold the veto and kept up his attack on
the bill and the overall Republican effort to push through a series
of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a misguided bill that provides a huge tax cut to the
most well-off Americans at the expense of working families,''
Clinton said. ``It is a key ingredient of a Republican tax plan
that would leave nothing for Social Security, Medicare, education
or a voluntary, affordable prescription drug benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week the Republican leadership in Congress is expected to
try to override the president's veto of its other main tax bill
this year, a tax cut for married couples. Republicans acknowledged
that they will probably fail, but said that again highlighting
Clinton's opposition to tax cuts would help them in their efforts
to retain control of the House and put Gov. George W. Bush in the
White House by motivating their core base of supporters to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore opposed the estate tax bill passed by
Congress, but he has supported a smaller plan to reduce the tax on
family-owned farms and businesses. Bush, who included repeal of the
estate tax in his $1.3 trillion tax cut proposal, said in a
statement Thursday that if he is elected president, ``there will be
no veto to override'' because he would ``sign the abolition of the
death tax into law.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would have phased out the federal estate and
gift tax over the next 10 years, with much of the tax disappearing
only at the end of that period.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the tax is levied only on estates valued at
$675,000 or more, an amount already scheduled to rise to $1 million
by 2006. Family owned businesses and farms have a special exemption
up to $1.3 million. Above those levels, estates are subject to a
graduated tax with a top rate of 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the exemptions, the tax actually affects relatively
few estates _ fewer than 48,000 this year, or about 2 percent of
all deaths _ but is of concern to interest groups with considerable
political clout, including the small-business and farm lobbies as
well as wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats renewed their call Thursday for a compromise measure
they offered earlier in the year. The Democratic alternative would
immediately raise the exemption for family-owned farms and
businesses to $2 million per individual, or $4 million per couple.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans rebuffed the Democratic plan again, saying it is
built around tax rules that are complicated and narrowly drawn and
that they would benefit only a tiny percentage of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one way to rid the code of this immoral, unfair
and economically unsound tax, and that's to eliminate it,'' said
Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that Congress should be concentrating on issues
that are of concern to all voters, not just the 2 percent who have
to worry about estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader in the
House, said that his constituents never mention the estate tax when
talking to him about their concerns. Instead, he said, they pressed
him for action on adding a prescription drug benefit to Medicare,
education, shoring up Social Security and keeping guns out of
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not want to spend the majority of this surplus on
tax cuts, and they sure don't want to spend it on tax cuts for the
wealthiest Americans,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
