<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREAMLINE-SALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE GROCER STREAMLINE SELLS OPERATIONS TO RIVAL PEAPOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Streamline.com Inc., an online grocer based in Westwood, averted
a looming financial crisis Thursday by selling its Washington,
D.C., and Chicago operations to rival Peapod Inc. for $12 million
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Following the sale, Streamline.com will operate only in northern
New Jersey and the Boston area, where it competes with Peapod. The
company had planned to expand to the Minneapolis area but now says
it has terminated a lease for a new facility in Shakopee, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a short time ago, rapid national expansion was the focus
and expectation for companies in our industry,'' said Timothy
DeMello, who founded Streamline.com in 1993. ``Now, you clearly
need to show that a (distribution) center that you put in a market
can be profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   By retreating to the Northeast, Streamline.com will be able to
drastically reduce its costs and move more rapidly toward
profitability, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capital provided by the divestiture of these markets will
allow us to prove the profitability of our business model, which we
plan to demonstrate by next year,'' said DeMello, the company's
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Streamline.com has made some progress, making a profit per
customer order in the Boston area despite competition from several
Web grocers, including Peapod, HomeRuns, and Shoplink. In addition,
growth in the New Jersey market has exceeded expectations, said
Edward Albertian, Streamline.com's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Like many dot-com executives, Albertian is hoping for a more
favorable climate on Wall Street. Over the last several months,
Streamline.com has struggled to interest investors. And though
Thursday's sale is a lifeline, executives will need to seek
additional funding in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For now, many financial analysts say they have lost interest in
virtual grocery retailers, citing low profit margins in the
supermarket business and high costs of delivering to consumers'
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an industry that doesn't look like it has a promising
future,'' said Jeffrey Siegel, an analyst with Innovative Research
Associates in New York. ``There are too many risks. There were too
many players in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel and other analysts are more optimistic about online
grocers backed by supermarket chains. Those include Peapod, an
ailing Internet retailer based in Chicago, rescued in June by Dutch
grocery conglomerate Royal Ahold NV.
</P>
<P>
   Ahold, which also owns Stop &AMP; Shop, has made it no secret that
it plans to use Peapod in its drive to become a major force on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Peapod said it would shed its Columbus, Ohio, and
Texas markets in favor of expanding into areas where Ahold's
supermarkets operate.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's market acquisitions, Peapod will strengthen its
presence in the Chicago market, gaining 4,000 new customers and a
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In the Washington area, where Peapod snaps up 2,000
Streamline.com customers and a distribution center, the company can
take advantage of Ahold's relationship with market leader Giant
Food.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition also gives Peapod a head start over Webvan Group
Inc., a California-based online grocer that plans to enter the
Washington market, according to Marc van Gelder, Peapod's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making a strategic move,'' van Gelder said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers in Streamline.com's old markets will likely see some
changes in their services. Van Gelder says Streamline.com caters
more to higher-end customers, while Peapod aims for more mainstream
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Peapod will continue stocking refrigerators that Streamline.com
installed in its customers' homes, van Gelder said. But new
shoppers will have their food delivered in totes _ Peapod's method
of delivery, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gelder declined to say whether Peapod will continue with
video rentals, dry cleaning, and other services that Streamline.com
now offers its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Streamline.com's stock price fell 15.625 cents to close at
84.375 cents Thursday on the Nasdaq Stock market. Shares of Peapod
rose 18.75 cents to close at $2.1875 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
