<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-SC-GA0918-COX     09-07 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SC-GA0918-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Losing streak behind them, Gamecocks ready for Georgia
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ South Carolina coach Lou Holtz says he had an
Internet Web site long before he knew how to turn on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Until last weekend, however, putting together three ``W's'' _ as
in www. _ seemed unlikely at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, in his second season with the Gamecocks, is trying to
keep his team's fans realistic. But he might be fighting a losing
battle. Fans in Columbia have renewed optimism after the Gamecocks
ended their 21-game losing streak with a 31-0 victory over New
Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a question on my Web site this week: 'Do you think
we can go to a bowl game this year?''' Holtz said. ``You make a
first down and the fans automatically think that you're a great
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gamecocks, who on Saturday host No. 9-ranked Georgia in the
Southeastern Conference opener for both teams, are by no means
great. But this year's edition is certainly better than last year's
0-11 squad, which ranked last in the nation in both scoring and
total offense.
</P>
<P>
   The offense showed dramatic improvement against the lowly Aggies
by gaining 353 yards in offense and scoring four touchdowns. Last
season, the Gamecocks gained 300 yards only once and didn't score
their fourth touchdown until the seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a football team that has really started to make
improvements,'' Holtz said. ``We're not a good football team by any
stretch of imagination, but I think we have the focus of just
trying to get better. Nobody mentions our losing streak now. . . .
Fortunately, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, the former Notre Dame coach who was lured out of
retirement in December 1998, said the biggest challenge was
convincing his players that they could win.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the offseason, we put the past behind us,'' he said. ``The
past is dead, and what's dead should be buried, so we buried that.
I thought everybody got fired up to play us when we were at Notre
Dame. But they really got fired up to play South Carolina once we
had that losing streak. Nobody wanted to be the team that lost to
South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia doesn't want to become the first SEC team to lose to the
Gamecocks in 19 games. South Carolina hasn't beat a conference
opponent since a 35-3 victory over Vanderbilt on Oct. 25, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Since that losing streak persists, South Carolina's players
aren't celebrating their first victory in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys aren't talking about New Mexico State too much,''
Gamecocks linebacker Andre Offing said. ``That was the past. We've
got more to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Snapping a three-game losing streak to Georgia would earn South
Carolina a lot of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a longer winning streak than half the teams in the
country,'' Holtz said, ``but nobody writes about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
