<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-REVIEW0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Nurse Betty' is all sweetness and bite
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ No doubt ``Nurse Betty'' is friendlier and more
accessible territory for Neil LaBute. The director secured his
notoriety with ``In the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' dark comedies that revel in emotional barbarity
between the sexes. Both hailed and hated for their brute candor,
the films are misanthropic masterpieces, cringing snapshots of bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than a jerk, the movies reveal LaBute as an A student
of our crueler impulses, and he shrewdly weaves these insights
through ``Nurse Betty's'' sunny fantasy. He flecks the comedy with
vulgarities and shocking eruptions of violence. This gives it teeth
and heft, and makes it the terrific movie it is.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's a wizard at wringing real and cracklingly alive
performances from his actors. Even the tentative Renee Zellweger,
whose face here is a dumpling rolled in flour, shines as naif Betty
Sizemore. Betty's a floaty waitress who moons over the hospital
soap ``A Reason to Love.'' She's infatuated with its glistening
hero, Dr. David Ravell (Greg Kinnear, master of bland irony), while
slogging through a bad marriage with a piggish used-car salesman
(superb LaBute regular Aaron Eckhart).
</P>
<P>
   In a pat narrative leap, Betty witnesses a murder that hurls her
into an amnesic fugue. Suddenly, she thinks she's the ex-fiancee of
Dr. Ravell and decides to leave Kansas (shades of ``Oz'') to rejoin
her true love in L.A. dressed as a nurse. But the killers, Chris
Rock and Morgan Freeman, are on their witness's trail. (Freeman and
the explosive Rock produce the film's funniest friction.)
</P>
<P>
   This is conventional stuff about chasing dreams, but LaBute and
his writers punch holes in the template. The plot curlicues,
hitting jolts of violence and poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' is a mix of bonhomie and bite that would have
fit in last year's crop of highly original, tonally volatile movies
(``Three Kings'' to ``American Beauty''). LaBute joggles tones like
a snow dome, and the result is a surprisingly textured oddity.
Usually less concerned with viewer amity, LaBute here meets us in
the middle, donning one boxing glove, one kid glove, and scores a
knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
