<HEADER>
A5487 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SAMSUNG0908-COX     09-07 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMSUNG0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Samsung plans to increase chip manufacturing capacity
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - South Korea's Samsung Electronics Co. plans to
spend heavily to increase its chip manufacturing capacity for at
least the next two years, a top company official says.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung, the largest maker of memory chips for computers and
other products, said it sees no signs of a softening in the market
for dynamic random access memory (DRAM) chips until 2003 at the
earliest. The company employs 1,100 people in Austin at its only
chip manufacturing plant outside South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Rising chip prices and strong demand have bolstered the
profitability of memory chip makers like Samsung, who were ravaged
by a three-year slump in the market from 1996 through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mercurial growth of the Internet and digital media
products will lead to a shortage of DRAMs until the year 2002,''
said Samsung President Lee Yoon Woo this week in story reported by
Bloomberg New Service.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's bullish comments were made in response to press questions
about the recent slide in the company's stock price. Samsung shares
dropped 33 percent from July 13 to early September, Bloomberg said.
Some financial analysts were concerned about reports of slowing
computer sales growth in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung projects that its chip sales will reach $13 billion this
year and $30 billion by 2005. Samsung's 1999 sales were estimated
at just over $7 billion, by IC Insights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samsung has been one of the earliest memory manufacturers to
start increasing its capital spending in response to the uptick in
the market,'' said analyst Jim Handy with the Dataquest market
research company in San Jose, Calif. ``Most of the other
manufacturers are waiting until they see hard profits. Most other
manufacturers are just on the verge of profitability right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said rising demand for memory chips in products like digital
cameras, videodisc players and television sets will offset slowing
growth of computer sales in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The largest portion of Samsung chip manufacturing investment is
going on in South Korea, where the company is bringing one new chip
factory into production and where it expects to start work this
month on a new, larger factory -- Line 11 -- that can process
silicon wafers that are 12-inches in diameter, compared with the
industry standard 8-inch wafers.
</P>
<P>
   The new factory will cost more to build -- an estimated $2
billion -- but its production costs are expected to be much lower
than costs for a conventional factory.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Samsung has expanded the employment of its chip
factory by 200 people over the last year, but top management has
not yet decided whether to build a second factory in Northeast
Austin. Samsung's first factory, which went into production in
1997, makes 64-megabit and 128-megabit chips and operates at close
to full capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Company management should make a decision on whether to build a
second factory in Austin sometime next year, said spokesman Bill
Cryer. When Samsung announced in 1996 that it would build a chip
factory in Austin, company officials said the Northeast Austin site
was large enough to handle from three to give chip factories.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Kirk Ladendorf at kladendorf(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
