A5489 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-IRISH-HUSKERS0908     09-07 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-HUSKERS0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A `Gipper Game' in store as Huskers come calling?
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Notre Dame scheduled a home-and-home series against
Nebraska several years ago, officials from both schools knew fans
would want tickets. The schools haven't met in the regular season
since 1948. Notre Dame is second in all-time college football
victories with 768, Nebraska third with 744.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing prepared the schools for the incredible demand to
get into Saturday's 2:30 p.m. NBC game between the No. 1
Cornhuskers (1-0) and the No. 23 Fighting Irish (1-0) in Notre Dame
Stadium
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you guys got any extra tickets?'' were the first words
out of the mouth of Notre Dame coach Bob Davie when he met with the
media early in the week. He wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Face value of the tickets is $36, but they were selling on eBay
for $200 and up. Some alumni told the school of offers of more than
$1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's remodeled stadium holds just over 80,000 fans, but
the school had only 32,000 tickets available to sell to alumni. The
school received more than 47,000 requests, its second-largest
demand for a regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   At Nebraska, the demand was even greater. The Cornhuskers, who
got only 4,000 tickets to the game, received 28,000 requests.
</P>
<P>
   The talk in Lincoln this week is that as many as 10,000 Nebraska
fans might show up in South Bend, Ind., without tickets because
they just want to be near the stadium when the game is played. They
will fill up the local bars so that years from now they can say
they were there.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd for Notre Dame's pep rally tonight is expected to be
so large that for only the third time in school history it is being
moved from the Joyce Center, which seats just over 11,000, to Notre
Dame Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is thinking that this could be a Notre Dame
moment,'' said Chuck Lennon, the executive director of the school's
alumni association.
</P>
<P>
   In Notre Dame lore, such contests are known as ``Gipper Games,''
in which the Irish summon the ghosts of their storied past _ George
Gipp and Knute Rockne _ to vanquish a seemingly unbeatable foe.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame has had some of those moments against the No. 1 team
in the nation. The Nebraska game will be the seventh time Notre
Dame has been home to face No. 1. They are 3-3 in the first six
games. Notre Dame is 8-13-1 when facing the nation's No. 1 team,
and the eight wins over No. 1 are more than by any other school.
One of those losses was to Georgia in the Jan. 1, 1981, Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska, which opened the season by thumping San Jose State
49-13, will be a heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, when Notre Dame was licking its wounds from a
5-7 season, Davie stood before a large copy of the schedule during
a team meeting. He drew a rectangle around the Sept. 9 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to raise the bar as a football team,'' Davie said,
``you raise that bar by comparing yourself to Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
