<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.N. VOTES TO BEEF UP PEACEKEEPING CAPABILITY
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Haunted by a string of recent failures in its
core mission of preserving peace and security, the United Nations
pledged Thursday to beef up its capacity to head off wars and
intervene in civil conflicts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Heads of state from the 15-member U.N. Security Council voted
unanimously to increase the funding and improve training and
equipment for U.N. peacekeeping forces.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to turn around what Secretary General Kofi Annan
called ``a crisis of confidence'' over the U.N.'s ability to
fulfill its central mission. The U.N.'s reputation has been damaged
in recent years by high-profile failings of its peacekeepers to
halt the killing of innocent civilians in places such as Bosnia,
Rwanda and East Timor, formerly part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many in the present generation are losing confidence in the
ability of the United Nations to make a difference between war and
peace,'' Annan said during the Security Council meeting. ``No
amount of resolutions or statements can change this reality; only
action can.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, one of 15 heads of state who endorsed Annan's
call for strengthening U.N. peacekeeping operations, said the body
must also become more effective at embracing the root causes of
conflict, including the abject poverty that afflicts much of the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we confront the iron link between deprivation, disease
and war,'' said Clinton, ``we will never be able to create the
peace that the founders of the United Nations dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is one of about 150 world leaders here this week
attending the U.N. Millennium Summit, the largest gathering of
heads of state in history.
</P>
<P>
   The club became a little too cozy for Clinton on Wednesday, when
Cuban leader Fidel Castro approached Clinton after a U.N. luncheon,
shook his hand and started a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the exchange was
cordial, but signaled no thaw in four decades of estrangement
between the United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance encounter that Mr. Castro initiated,''
Albright told reporters. ``They talked for a couple of minutes, and
there was no substance.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the enduring divide between the two countries,
Clinton pointedly left Castro off a list of 350 heads of state,
spouses and diplomats he hosted Thursday night at the Metropolitan
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   On the margins of the U.N. summit, but very much at the center
of his foreign policy agenda, Clinton continued to press for an
Israeli-Palestinian peace accord, though he said there was no clear
path forward on the difficult issues that divide the longtime foes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met into the night Wednesday with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and, separately, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Clinton was willing to meet again with the Mideast
leaders before the U.N. summit concludes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is obviously prepared to be engaged at any
time,'' she said. ``He's still here.''
</P>
<P>
   And, while the process is fluid, she said, diplomacy remains
very much under way on a number of levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a floating operation,'' she said, ``and we're working
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hosted Arafat and Barak for two weeks of summitry at
Camp David in July. That effort collapsed, though, over the
leaders' inability to agree on the future of Jerusalem, a city holy
to Christians, Muslims and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   With Barak facing a possible rebellion from the Israeli
parliament by the end of October, he told reporters that ``time is
running'' out on his own efforts to reach an accord with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that he was ready to reach an agreement with Arafat
that called for setting the Jerusalem question aside for some
period of time, but Arafat rejected that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``After quite painful hesitation, we were ready to say that we
are ready to contemplate it if the other side is ready to negotiate
it,'' said Barak. ``It happened that the idea was refused by the
Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   In yet another U.N.-related initiative, Clinton hosted roughly
200 African leaders and diplomats for a midday reception. There,
Clinton called for a multibillion-dollar global effort to rescue
the continent from the ravages of a devastating AIDS epidemic, the
legacy of generations of debt and poverty that prevents millions of
children from access to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed for the long run,'' said Clinton. ``I believe
America is moving inexorably to be a much better partner over the
long run for Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
