<HEADLINE>
TRUCKERS' STRIKE SPREADS IN FRANCE AS FUEL SHORTAGES GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS ``Friday'' to ``Thursday'' thruout.)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A strike begun three days ago by truckers who blockaded
fuel depots to protest spiraling fuel costs spread Thursday as
workers from other sectors of the economy joined the
demonstrations, disrupting transportation systems throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, airline workers, bus drivers, taxi drivers and even the
owners of river barges and sightseeing boats that cruise the Seine
have now joined in the protest. Their actions, along with the
truckers' blockade, have combined to produce the growing fuel
shortages and varying degrees of inconvenience for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In Bordeaux, for instance, farmers set fire to piles of tires on
train tracks, leading to havoc with train schedules in the area. In
the north, they blocked border posts between France and Belgium. In
other towns, private ambulance drivers used their vehicles to block
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Paris had largely been spared in the last few days. But Thursday
hundreds of taxis poured into the city in a slow-moving column that
created a traffic jam that lasted hours.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the truckers' blockade of the country's fuel depots
has begun to be felt the pumps. France's three major oil companies
said that up to 80 percent of their stations were reporting
shortages. Some drivers also found it difficult to get fuel because
police officers were patrolling gas stations to make sure that
police, hospital and emergency service vehicles got the first
chance to buy the gas that was available. In other towns, officials
sought only to limit hoarding by putting a cap on the amount of
fuel that could be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has quickly become a huge political problem for Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin, who on Wednesday broke off negotiations
with the truckers after two of the country's three major unions
refused to ratify an offer of a 15-cent reduction per liter in fuel
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Jospin did not comment on the strike. But his
transportation minister, Jean-Claude Gayssot, talked tough, saying,
``If we let things go on, that could break the process of growth
and development that's going on in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest began gathering steam on Sunday after a week in
which the government offered a series of financial measures to
fishermen, who had also blockaded the country's ports in August
because of rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the truckers believed that they would get relief in a
long-awaited package of tax cuts that Jospin's government unveiled
last week. But the government instead chose to use a budget surplus
from a booming economy in other ways. The plan included a cut in
the taxes on home heating oil, but not fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of fuel has been rising even faster in Europe than in
the United States because of the decline in the value of the euro.
On top of that, fuel carries a government surcharge of more than 70
percent in France.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of diesel fuel in France has risen about 40 percent in
the last year. A gallon of diesel fuel costs about $2.84 here.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Jospin's problem in negotiating with the truckers is
that even his latest offer has been sharply criticized by
environmentalists in his governing coalition. The Greens say his
concessions break earlier promises to continue to push France
toward use of rail traffic over more polluting trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to blocking various border posts, farmers scuffled
with the authorities at the Channel Tunnel as they tried to block
freight trucks from boarding trains to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, the European Union asked France to prove that it
was taking measures to ensure the free movement of goods and access
to its ports.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers' blockades, set up at some 80 depots throughout the
country, were beginning to take a heavy toll in some areas. One
French newspaper reported that school cafeterias in the Vosges
region, in eastern France, faced shortages because food suppliers
ran out of gas for their delivery trucks. Some school bus routes
were shut down in the central city of Lyon. In other areas, rental
car agencies said they had to turn away customers because they
could not give them any gas.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, leaders of the truckers union tried to blame
the government for backing out of the negotiations and urged that
they return to the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to reach a solution quickly,'' said Rene Petit, the
leader of the trucker's union. ``We simply must resume dialogue
with the authorities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
