<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: EU REPORT DUE
</P>
<P>
   A report commissioned by the European Union to help it decide
whether to continue sanctions against Austria is to be presented
Friday to the current holder of the rotating EU presidency,
President Jacques Chirac of France. The sanctions were imposed in
February after the far-right Freedom Party joined Austria's ruling
coalition. The report was to evaluate the ``respect'' of the
Austrian government for ``common European values'' as well as the
evolution of the Freedom Party, which has been accused of taking a
xenophobic stance.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: GREEK MEETS MILOSEVIC
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister George Papandreou of Greece met in Belgrade
with President Slobodan Milosevic, the first NATO foreign minister
to do so since the alliance bombed Yugoslavia last year. There was
speculation about what larger message from the West Papandreou
might be passing on to Milosevic, given the lavish pre-election
coverage his meeting with Milosevic, indicted for war crimes,
received on state television. Papandreou also met opposition
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: TERRORISM ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   Public Order Minister Michalis Chryssochoides will sign an
accord in Washington on Friday providing for cooperation with the
FBI in the fight against terrorism, organized crime, Internet
espionage and drug smuggling. The government had resisted signing
the accord for two years, but changed its position after a British
military attache was assassinated in Athens in June and Greece was
awarded the 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: GAY AMERICANS SEE SITES
</P>
<P>
   The police provided extra security in Istanbul for about 800 gay
Americans who toured historic sites without incident after being
refused access to other locations in Turkey. The group told the
State Department they were discriminated against after the police
in the Aegean port of Kusadasi refused to allow them to tour
Ephesus and other sites. When their ship arrived in Istanbul, the
group was welcomed by the American consul general, Frank Urbancic,
but he did not comment on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: DEFECTION TO RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   In the latest sign that Canada's new right-wing party is
emerging from its western base, the Canadian Alliance won the
loyalty of Jim Jones, the lone Tory member of Parliament from
Ontario. The defection came two days after Brian Mulroney, a former
Tory prime minister, described the dwindled state of his party as
``difficult and challenging'' and called Stockwell Day, leader of
the Alliance, a ``fine gentleman.'' Mulroney does not support the
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: AIDE COMMITS SUICIDE
</P>
<P>
   An undersecretary in the Commerce Department killed himself in a
growing controversy over the management of a national car registry,
senior officials said. The registry was run by a former Argentine
military officer, hired by the Commerce Department, who stands
accused by a Spanish judge of murder and torture under Argentina's
military junta two decades ago. Officials said the undersecretary,
Raul Ramos III, left behind six suicide notes denying culpability.
</P>
</TEXT>
