u a BC-GULFWAR-STUDY-SUB-BOS     09-07 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULFWAR-STUDY-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUSE OF GULF WAR SYNDROME A MYSTERY, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects name of researcher to Sox.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no conclusive evidence that nerve gas, uranium or
military vaccinations caused the Gulf War syndrome ailing thousands
of Desert Storm veterans, according to a massive study released
Thursday that strongly suggests the affliction's actual cause will
forever remain a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 118,000 Persian Gulf veterans suffer from the
chronic fatigue, headaches, muscles spasms, joint pain, and rashes
that characterize the syndrome, and the new results left many of
them yet again frustrated at the inability to properly diagnose
their decade-old problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most veterans expected this outcome. Most of them don't have
faith in government to resolve this,'' said Bill Frazure, a Gulf
War veteran from New London, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the Institute of Medicine in Washington, was
designed to help devise a way to compensate ailing Gulf War
veterans. Its immediate implication was that veterans petitioning
the government for financial compensation cannot cite exposure to
the chemicals and vaccines studied as proof they are sick.
</P>
<P>
   But the study's more sweeping suggestion was that the apparent
nonexistence of data on what each soldier was exposed to in the
Persian Gulf permanently cripples scientists' ability to diagnose
the syndrome's causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that crucial piece of information, we cannot draw
conclusions regarding whether the agents present in the Gulf War
theater are the cause of the health problems among veterans who
served there,'' said the study's chair, Dr. Harold C. Sox, a
medical professor at Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center at a news
conference Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sox's crew of researchers continue to examine 30 other possible
causes of the syndrome. But even if they eventually determine some
of the chemicals veterans were exposed to have long-term health
effects, they will not know which individual soldiers are ailing
from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really know who was actually exposed to what. The
Department of Defense really doesn't know who was where when,''
said Dr. Samuel Potolicchio, a professor of neurology at George
Washington Medical Center and one of the study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure data, he said, will ``probably never be available.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has spent an estimated $145 million
studying Gulf War Syndrome, and still classifies it as an
``undiagnosed illness.'' One-sixth of the 700,000 veterans who
helped wrest Kuwait from the Iraqi army in 1990-91 have filed
medical complaints since returning.
</P>
<P>
   Most have gotten treatment for each symptom, one by one, at
Veteran's Administration hospitals. But an underlying cause has
been frustratingly elusive. Initially, many thought the cause was
in veterans' heads, that war-time stress and hysteria provoked the
symptoms. The accusation irked many veterans, creating an
atmosphere of hostility and distrust of the government that
continues to linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're blaming it on the vets. They want to tell guys it's
all in their heads,'' said Frazure. ``We're so used to this, we're
just kind of at the point where we just shrug our shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the causes eliminated Thursday was the anthrax vaccine
injected in thousands of soldiers in the event Iraqi leader Saddam
Hussein unleashed the lethal virus. But that didn't convince Paul
Perrone, 35, of Methuen, who served as a military police officer at
the US-led coalition's base in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, during the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty convinced that the vaccines are the culprit. What
they say means nothing to me one way or another. They're either
stonewalling or just blind to the issue,'' he said Thursday, just
after returning from his neurologist's office where he is being
monitored for multiple sclerosis symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's study was an effort by the federal government to
corral a decade's worth of research to determine if the scientific
establishment had made any progress on Gulf War syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers reviewed thousands of studies on the chemicals
thought most likely to be the source behind the syndrome: sarin, a
deadly nerve gas that Iraq has deployed in the past; military
vaccines for anthrax and botulism given to many soldiers to guard
against chemical weapon attacks; pyriodostigmine bromide, a
compound taken by many soldiers to strengthen them against possible
chemical attacks; and depleted uranium, which many were exposed to
when military equipment was destroyed during combat.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers concluded there is not enough evidence to say these
substances cause any long-term health problems. However, with
sarin, they said further study is necessary because the evidence is
extremely limited, most of it comes from victim studies from a 1995
terrorist attack on a Tokyo subway by a Japanese cult.
</P>
<P>
   Many outside researchers criticized the study's approach in
examining the substances in isolation. They theorize that Gulf War
syndrome is a product exposure to multiple toxic substances that,
perhaps, make veterans more sensitive to everyday chemicals used
here. They worry the new evidence will lead to a new round of
skepticism about the veterans' claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors who treat vets are very much influenced by studies
like this,'' said Dr. Claudia Miller, associate professor of
environmental and occupational medicine at the University of Texas
Health Science Center in San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
