<HEADLINE>
(SPORTS), MIDEAST-PEACE TALKS; ELIMINATES GORE-RHETORIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, September 8, 2000  
 Eds: UPDATED BUDGET ADDS BBA-REDSOX-RAMON AND BBA-TWINS-RED SOX
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Jean Conley  &LR; at
the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
budgeted graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or
 &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UN-PEACEKEEPING (United Nations) _ As the UN debates the future
of its peacekeeping efforts, the deaths of three UN workers
murdered in West Timor give the discussion a sharp edge. By John
Donnelly. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   WORKER-CARCERAS (Miami) _ A closer look at the life of UN worker
Carlos Caceres, a Puerto Rican who was schooled in Florida and at
Cornell. By Richard Chacon. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE TALKS (New York) _ The first strong indication
that the Israel-Palestinian peace talks were in trouble in New York
came late Wednesday when Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
stormed out of a meeting with Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright. The talks are in limbo as the Palestinian Council decides
whether to declare a Palestinian state. By John Donnelly. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLL-BUSH (Dayton, Ohio) _ As new poll numbers come out, a
deeper look at the scuffling Bush campaign's voyage from
overconfidence to open worry. Also an attempt to put in some
perspective the dire-seeming numbers. By Anne Kornblut and Walter
V. Robinson. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   VETO-ESTATE _ House expected to fail in its attempt to override
Clinton's veto of the estate tax repeal. By Susan Milligan. 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GULFWAR-STUDY (Undated) _ A massive national study concludes
there is not enough evidence to link Gulf War Syndrome to the
chemicals or drugs most suspected of causing the mysterious chronic
conditon, which has affected thousands of Desert Storm veterans.
The study all but says the causes of the syndrome will likely never
be found, leaving veterans frustrated and puzzled. By Raja Mishra.
900 words.
</P>
<P>
   TIRES-ANALYSIS (Undated) _ When Jacques Nasser, the chief
executive at Ford Motor Co., told a committee on Capitol Hill that
the problem of shredding Firestone tires on Ford SUVs was ``a tire
problem, not a vehicle problem,'' he may have drawn too sharp a
distinction. By Royal Ford. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   CULT-BIRTH (Attleboro, Mass.) _ Saying he could hear the voice
of Rebecca Corneau's unborn baby pleading from the womb to let him
live, unlike his dead brother, the judge in the Attleboro cult case
orders Corneau to continue her confinement and close monitoring to
ensure her child is born healthy. By Mac Daniel. 650 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OIL-SUMMIT (Boston) _ ``Heating-fuel summit'' at Federal Reserve
discusses Northeast's concerns about rising costs of oil and
natural gas going into the winter. By Richard Kindleberger. 600
words.
</P>
<P>
   STREAMLINE-SALE (Undated) _ Streamline sells off all operations
save local ones to Royal Ahold, parent of Stop &AMP; Shop and rival
online delivery company Peapod, as it struggles for survival in a
tough market. By Stephanie Stoughton. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-TWINS-REDSOX (Boston) _ For one dark moment on a glorious
September afternoon, grand old Fenway Park Thursday felt like Bleak
House. A game the struggling Sox sorely needed to win was slipping
away. Yet the Sox stormed back from the precipice, dumping the
Minnesota Twins, 11-6. By Bob Hohler. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-RAMON (Boston) _ You might be able to count on one
hand the number of times a Red Sox starter has surrendered six runs
and eight hits in 5 2/3 innings _ and left to a standing ovation.
Maybe even one finger. Ramon Martinez saw and heard both sides of
the Fenway fan Thursday. By Peter May. 600 words
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
