<SLUG> BC-U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL CONTEMPLATES PEACE FOR A NEW AND UNRULY WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,2,33,34,35,38 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867; see UN-PHOTO-ADVISORY-NYT for
descriptions.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With President Clinton and other government
leaders filling seats usually occupied by their envoys, the
Security Council moved on Thursday toward a new role for itself in
a world where the rules have been rewritten by warlords, and the
poor kill the poor over dwindling natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual meeting, with 14 heads of government and a foreign
minister gathered around the council table, was intended to
concentrate on peacekeeping problems, with a special emphasis on
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But it very quickly turned to a far broader discussion about the
causes of war in an age when ethnic cleansing, rape and mutilation
have become the tactical hallmarks of pickup armies that terrorize
populations often already weakened by poverty or disease. The issue
was raised most prominently a year ago by Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, and was addressed vigorously on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing makes a big difference in the type of debate we will
have today versus what it might have been 15, 20, 30 years ago,''
said Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   He told the council that peacekeeping was often all that stood
``between anarchy and some form of stability.'' Sierra Leone, where
Britain has sent hundreds of peacekeepers, is an example, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is poverty or debt or aid and development, or
infectious diseases or governance and the rule of law, we need a
far broader concept of how we deal with these security issues for
today's world,'' Blair said. ``We cannot isolate conflict from the
root causes of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Security Council moved into new territory on
Thursday, other leaders addressing the summit meeting in the
General Assembly kept to familiar attacks against the deep
disparities between rich and poor nations. With passion and often
eloquence, they demanded that the industrialized world offer more
tangible aid to countries that have been left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Like Annan and Blair, Clinton argued that peacekeeping meant
thinking not only about weapons but also about water, schools,
health and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will listen to this discussion and say, well,
peacekeeping has something to do with security, but these other
issues don't have anything to do with security and don't belong in
the Security Council,'' he said. ``This is my last meeting _ I just
have to say I respectfully disagree. These issues will be more and
more in the Security Council. Until we confront the iron link
between deprivation, disease and war, we will never be able to
create the peace that the founders of the United Nations dreamed
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton soon discovered he was not alone. Except for President
Jiang Zemin of China, who argued stonily for the most restrictive
definition of the Security Council's role, and Vladimir Putin of
Russia, who in an unspoken reference to NATO was more preoccupied
with opposing the use of force outside the council's control, a
significant number of national leaders echoed Clinton's call.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   China and at times Russia argue that social issues should be
left to the Economic and Social Council, which was established by
the U.N. Charter to be a body parallel to the Security Council. It
was given wide authority in social issues, including human rights
and crime.
</P>
<P>
   But ECOSOC, as it is known, has proved unwieldy with 54 members,
ineffective and rarely innovative, despite the considerable efforts
of U.S. and European diplomats to reform it and give it greater
authority.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina of Bangladesh and President Jacques
Chirac of France spoke at the council on Thursday of large-scale
human rights abuses and disasters of other kinds affecting large
numbers of vulnerable people.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk moved the council to its first high-level debate, on
the thorny subject of when it has the right to intervene to save
citizens, even if that means intruding on national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the discussion, despite lingering differences of
opinion, the leaders unanimously adopted a resolution that called
for, among other things, the development within the United Nations
of ``comprehensive and integrated strategies to address the root
causes of conflicts, including their economic and social
dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, since Annan first raised this issue in the
General Assembly, it has been the fodder of academic and
policymaking debate. Prime Minister Jean Chretien of Canada on
Thursday told the council _ meeting at head-of-state level for the
first time since 1992 _ that it could not back away from the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if the Security Council is unable to adapt,'' Chretien
said, ``it will seriously undermine its credibility as a guarantor
of peace, credibility that is essential to maintaining the moral
authority of the U.N. as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a speech in the General Assembly, Chretien announced
that Canada would establish an international panel of legal and
political experts to study the issue of military intervention on
humanitarian grounds, taking a major step toward making the
discussion more concrete.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The credibility factor lurked behind much of what was said about
peacekeeping and how the United Nations has been stumbling
disastrously in trying to meet new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   In opening the council session, Annan laid bare the background
against which U.N. peacekeeping operations must work when he said,
``Many in the present generation are losing confidence in the
ability of the United Nations to make the difference between war
and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan, a former head of peacekeeping who moved into the top job
just as the United Nations was floundering over its role in the
post-Cold-War era, has ordered reviews of peacekeeping debacles in
Rwanda and Bosnia and of the overall functioning of the department.
The results have been very critical not only of the organization
but also of its leading members, especially the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many vulnerable communities in too many regions of the
world now hesitate to look to the United Nations to assist them in
their hour of need,'' Annan said on Thursday. ``No amount of
resolutions or statements can change this reality. Only action can
_ prompt, united and effective action, pursued with skill and
discipline to halt the conflict and restore the peace. Only such
determined action can restore the reputation of the United Nations
as a credible force for peace and justice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. peacekeeping department has 32 officers to provide
military planning and guidance for 27,000 troops. An additional
8,600 civilian police officers are supervised by only nine police
experts in New York. Fifteen political desk officers look after 16
operations. Only 1.25 percent of the peacekeeping budget goes to
headquarters administration, far too little, experts say, to allow
for adequate planning.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council itself _ or at least its leading members _
is often the problem, said Lakhdar Brahimi, a former Algerian
foreign minister who was chairman of the expert panel that studied
overall U.N. peacekeeping and issued a critical report last month.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Brahimi said interference from powerful nations
in the Department of Peacekeeping Operations _ known by the letters
DPKO _ should stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big boys on the Security Council come through the back
door and tell the DPKO and all of us here: `Don't say this; don't
say that. Don't ask for this, don't ask for that,''' he said.
``They really influence us into self-censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States put another brake on peacekeeping when the
Clinton administration agreed to give Congress 15 days' notice
before voting for a new operation. The agreement can stall any
action, even in a crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
