<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NC-GOV0908-COX     09-07 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-GOV0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. governor's race heating up
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C._ Richard Vinroot arrived in a dark suit, blue shirt
and necktie with gold stripes. A former Charlotte mayor running for
governor, he seemed out of uniform for the remarks he would soon
deliver to fellow Republicans in Durham.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up the three middle fingers of his right hand,
59-year-old Vinroot recited the Boy Scout oath, a gesture of
integrity that he says separates him from his Democratic rival,
Attorney General Mike Easley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need a full-grown governor as well,'' said Vinroot,
a lanky, 6-foot-7-inch former bench warmer for the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill basketball team. ``I tell them it is
clean living that does this.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinroot, an Eagle Scout as a teen who now stands about a foot
taller than Easley, is swinging hard at the gubernatorial
front-runner and what Vinroot calls Easley's misuse of public money
for thinly veiled campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   With a sizable lead in the polls and in fund-raising for the
Nov. 7 election, Easley says he's braced for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they said I did, I didn't do it,'' Easley said to
laughter Wednesday during a private fund-raiser in Cary packed by
Democratic dignitaries, including outgoing Gov. Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they want to do is win,'' Easley said after the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Easley and Vinroot will debate publicly for the first time next
week in Raleigh, following a forum Saturday in Greensboro where the
two candidates are scheduled to address state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Easley, 50, a two-term attorney general and former state
prosecutor, frequently attacks Vinroot as an enemy of public
education and rural North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care if they destroy my reputation or anybody
else's along the way,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby in Durham, Vinroot said his campaign will focus on
capping state spending and setting priorities to improve schools
and roads.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We are going to tell the truth about Mike Easley the
rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   UNC-Chapel Hill political scientist Thad Beyle said he believes
negative ads from the opposing campaigns will shape voters' views
of Easley and Vinroot.
</P>
<P>
   In this state with a well-deserved reputation for political
mudslinging, Vinroot ``hired the toughest gun he could,'' Beyle
said of political strategist Carter Wrenn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Wrenn created the television commercial for U.S. Sen.
Jesse Helms (R-N.C.) that showed the hands of a white man slowly
crumpling a rejection letter. The ad linked Helms' black opponent,
Harvey Gantt, another former Charlotte mayor, to racial hiring
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Wrenn couldn't be reached Wednesday or Thursday at Vinroot's
campaign headquarters in Charlotte. In Durham on Wednesday, Vinroot
bristled at the suggestion Wrenn was calling the shots, saying,
``This is Richard Vinroot's campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   An Easley supporter, retired state Sen. Jim Johnson (D-Concord)
said he believes Vinroot is ``one of the last Southern gentlemen''
and thus wouldn't resort to tactics such as the 1990 Helms
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   In what Easley calls ``silly stuff'' and his supporters decry as
negative campaigning, Vinroot has accused Easley of misusing as
much as $3 million in tax dollars since 1995 in a series of public
service ads.
</P>
<P>
   In the spots, Easley, as attorney general, warned of the dangers
of telephone fraud, predatory lending practices and other schemes
taking advantage of North Carolinians.
</P>
<P>
   Easley used, in part, proceeds from the settlement of lawsuits
by his office under a state justice department program set up by a
previous attorney general, Robert Morgan. During an audit earlier
this year, State Auditor Ralph Campbell found nothing illegal about
the ads.
</P>
<P>
   But Easley's opponent in last spring's Democratic primary, Lt.
Gov. Dennis Wicker, criticized the ads as thinly disguised
political ads for Easley's gubernatorial bid.
</P>
<P>
   Easley beat Wicker easily. Nonetheless, Vinroot's criticism of
the ads has been central to his portrayal of Democrats _ from
Easley to President Clinton _ as untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to do with character,'' Vinroot said. ``He had the
public trust and he abused it, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley's supporters say Vinroot's criticism of Easley will
backfire on voters tired of negative ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vinroot's people are making a major mistake,'' said Wayne
Troutman, chairman of the Democratic Party in Concord, where Easley
stumped at a poorly attended event Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a statewide poll and fund-raising records,
Easley is out front.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Mason-Dixon poll of 625 likely voters in July put
Easley 10 percentage points ahead of Vinroot, 47 percent to 37
percent. The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Vinroot said Wednesday his campaign's polling shows the gap is
now ``about 7 percentage points,'' putting him within striking
distance. , he said. , as his campaign raises ``$25,000 to $50,000
a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past month, Vinroot said his campaign raised $900,000,
with ``a lot of help from the National Republican Governors
Association.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Easley had a sizable advantage in fund-raising at the end
of June, the conclusion of the latest reporting period. Easley had
$850,000 on hand to spend, while Vinroot had $117,000 _ including
$100,000 of which he loaned himself in April.
</P>
<P>
   During the second quarter of this year, Easley raised $1.2
million while Vinroot raised $765,000, their campaign finance
statements show.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
