<HEADER>
A5513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-TEAMSTERS-NYT &LR;      09-07 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEAMSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS UNION ENDORSES AL GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long after most other unions had backed Vice President Al Gore,
the Teamsters executive board gave him its endorsement Thursday.
Despite the long wait, James P. Hoffa, the union's president, said
the decision was easy.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa said he pushed his board to make the endorsement after he
held extensive talks with Gore during the past few months and after
the vice president began speaking on issues important to working
families, something Hoffa said he had urged him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has come out of the Democratic convention speaking about
issues that are important to working families,'' said Hoffa, who
was in New York for a campaign rally with Hillary Rodham Clinton.
``He's talking about the middle class. He's talking about the fact
that we need help on health care, education, paying off the debt,
and I think what he says makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa denied suggestions by some political analysts that he was
a fair-weather friend who embraced Gore only after the vice
president became the front runner.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa insisted in an interview that he had planned all along to
put off an endorsement until after the conventions and after
Teamster members and leaders were polled.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor officials said Hoffa, as the new leader of the
Teamsters, also wanted to show that he is his own man and would not
automatically join the union leaders who heeded the AFL-CIO's
president, John Sweeney, and quickly endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After Gore lobbied for the China trade bill last May, Hoffa
sometimes sounded so angry with the vice president that there
appeared to be little chance the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters would back him. Hoffa attacked the China trade deal
because it did not provide protections for workers and because he
feared it would encourage American companies to transfer operations
to China.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffa said Thursday that Gore had given assurances on trade
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's said he's going to try to work on trade issues to make
sure there is input from labor and environmentalists with regard to
future trade deals,'' said Hoffa, who describes himself as a
progressive Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   While some labor leaders, like Gerald McEntee, president of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, seek
to endorse candidates early, believing that is the best way to
maximize influence, Hoffa's strategy has been to hold off in the
hope that candidates will make significant promises and commitments
to secure his endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gore had indicated that he was far more likely than Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas to pick judges and members of the National
Labor Relations Board favorable to labor. He added that Gore had
made no commitments on one of Hoffa's priorities: persuading the
federal government to end 11 years of intensive supervision aimed
at rooting out corruption in the Teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hoffa's aides said the Republican Party had vigorously
wooed Hoffa. The aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the Republicans promised to make Hoffa labor's main liaison with
the White House and give him a say in labor-related appointments if
he endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa declined to criticize Bush, saying the Teamsters wanted to
improve relations with Republican lawmakers. He said the Teamsters
have endorsed several Republican congressional incumbents who have
often sided with labor, including Peter King of New York and
Christopher Smith of New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
