<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-645&AMP;ADD-N     09-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS SHOW FIRESTONE KNEW OF RISING WARRANTY CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Vt.)  (With TIRE-VENEZUELA and TIRE-SAFETY) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Internal documents from Bridgestone/Firestone show
that officials of the company were concerned as early as February
about rising warranty costs for the tires that the company recalled
last month.
</P>
<P>
   At congressional hearings on Wednesday, Firestone executives
testified that the company's data on warranty claims did not show a
problem with the tires.
</P>
<P>
   But documents obtained by investigators working for Rep. Billy
Tauzin, R-La., who is the chairman of the House Commerce
Subcommittee on Consumer Protection, show that Firestone's sales
staff was aware of a growing problem with the company's light truck
tires even as Firestone, the U.S. unit of Bridgestone of Japan,
denied it to the Ford Motor Co. and regulators. The documents were
distributed to members of the subcommittee in preparation for its
hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Tauzin questioned how Firestone's
safety officials could not have known of a problem if the sales
staff was told. ``You can't have that much information floating
around not to have noticed a problem that should have been notified
to federal authorities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The documents include charts prepared for the sales staff's
annual meeting in February that repeatedly and prominently mention
the high cost of warranty claims for tread separation in light
truck tires.
</P>
<P>
   The label on one chart read ``Separations increasing'' in large,
underlined letters. The chart showed that the number of warranty
``adjustments,'' or claims, for tread separation had climbed to
4,694 in 1999 from 4,200 in 1998, an increase of 11.8 percent. The
chart also described how the tires were coming apart and the rates
at which each type of separation was increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Five more charts analyzed patterns in tread separations and
emphasized tires for light trucks, a category that includes the
Ford Explorer. One of these charts, labeled ``separations,'' showed
that the number of separations involving Wilderness tires had risen
194 percent in 1999 from the level a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A separate collection of charts, prepared for the same sales
meeting in February and labeled ``Critical Performance Issues,''
also singled out recreational light truck tires of the sort
installed on Explorers, with one chart stating in large letters:
``Wilderness AT needs improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Firestone recalled 6.5 million ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT
tires on Aug. 9 after Ford analyzed the tire maker's data on crash
claims and found a pattern of property damage and injury claims
dating back at least to 1997. Firestone officials said then, and
have said repeatedly since then, that they missed the trend of
crash claims because they were focusing on warranty data that did
not show a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Crigger, Firestone's executive vice president for business
planning, testified before a Senate subcommittee on Wednesday that
the company's safety program relied on warranty data, quality tests
at factories and field research into the performance of tires in
use. ``None of those indicators pointed to any kind of a problem
with the tire line that we are talking about here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wyant, Firestone's vice president for quality assurance,
said that the company's warranty data was the most reliable. ``You
can see trends, there is volume there and it is statistically
significant,'' he told the Senate subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone officials did not return telephone calls Thursday
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials expressed anger when told Thursday about the
Firestone documents, saying that they asked the tire maker
repeatedly to check whether the tires had a problem and had been
told every time that no problem existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flabbergasting,'' said Jason Vines, Ford's vice president
for public affairs. ``You'd think if they saw a pattern like that
they might tell us, as their largest customer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ken Johnson, a spokesman for Tauzin's subcommittee, said
Thursday evening that investigators would look next at how
Firestone and Ford went about testing the tires a decade ago,
before the Explorer was introduced in late 1990 as a 1991 model.
Tauzin accused Ford in an interview earlier this week of not having
tested the tires at 26 pounds per square inch, the pressure at
which Ford recommends that they be inflated. Firestone began
recommending at the time of the recall that the tires be inflated
to 30 pounds per square inch, which would increase their capacity
to carry weight.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin told Firestone's Wyant at the hearing on Wednesday night
that the subcommittee had been trying unsuccessfully for a week to
obtain from the tire maker the original test data for the tires.
Wyant said that Firestone had been engaged in an ``around-the-clock
search'' for the test results and that he did not know what had
become of the information.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of lawmakers have been calling for a criminal
investigation of Firestone and Ford. Attorney General Janet Reno
said Thursday morning that she was reviewing such a request from
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. But Justice Department officials said
that an investigation was not likely because the federal law
covering auto defects is fairly weak.
</P>
<P>
   The law provides for fines of no more than $925,000 on
manufacturers and does not authorize criminal penalties. Firestone
and Ford, and possibly their executives, could still face
prosecution by state or local authorities, however, if it is proven
that they knowingly sold products with deadly defects.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
