<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-GEORGIA0908-COX     09-07 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-GEORGIA0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fund-raising pace remains hot
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President AL Gore's fund-raising trip to Atlanta
today _ coming less than two months before the Nov. 7 general
election _ underscores the way the thirst for campaign money has
dominated the 2000 presidential race like never before.
</P>
<P>
   It also shows how post-Watergate reforms designed stop
fund-raising during the general election have all but evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when candidates ended their fund-raising
obligations with the party nominating conventions. Campaign 2000
will be a money dash into October. As with Gore's visit today, the
focus on money is often driving when and where candidates campaign,
cutting into their time to meet and greet average voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we are seeing this year is that
wherever the candidates are going along the trail, they are doing
fund-raising,'' said Anthony Corrado, a campaign finance expert at
Colby College in Waterville, Maine. ``That was most obvious at the
conventions, where an unprecedented amount of fund-raising was
done, and I think we are now going to see that carry right through
the month of September and into October, because the demand for
this money has become so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Including tonight's activities, Gore has attended eight
fund-raising events since the Democratic convention wrapped up
three weeks ago. That doesn't include events headlined by his wife,
Tipper, or his running mate Joe Lieberman, who the party is
beginning to cycle into the mix of scheduled fund-raisers. More
events are scheduled. Gore and Lieberman and the DNC can't say when
the candidates will participate in their last one before the Nov. 7
election.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the GOP nominee, also has kept up
the fund-raising pace, after shattering the record for the most
money raised by a candidate in a primary. Bush has done four
fund-raising events for the Republican National Committee since the
GOP convention and will continue to help state Republican parties
raise money. Former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, Bush's running
mate, also is pitching in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush and Secretary Cheney are occasionally helping''
the state and national parties raise money, said Ray Sullivan, a
Bush spokesman. ``It is certainly not a priority, when you compare
it to the importance of going to states and reaching voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fund-raising is a relatively new phenomenon. When Congress
passed the first campaign reform legislation in 1974, after the
Watergate scandal, it established a system of public financing for
presidential candidates in the general election, barring them from
raising money for their campaigns if they accepted public money.
This year, Gore and Bush each became eligible for $67.56 million in
public funds after their respective conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the 1974 legislation was to free candidates from
the burden of fund-raising and allow them to focus their general
election campaigns on communicating with voters. The law also was
meant to insulate candidates from the perception that raising large
sums obligated them to donors.
</P>
<P>
   But the goal of public financing began to unravel with the
advent of soft money, unregulated donations from corporations,
unions and wealthy individuals that parties could collect and spend
on generic ``party building'' activities like voter registration.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1988, the parties began expanding the definition of
what constituted a party building activity. The floodgates opened
in 1996, analysts say, when when President Clinton and the
Democrats used soft money to finance issue advertising, ads that
advocate positions but not candidates. The Republicans quickly
followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That created an insatiable demand for this money,'' Corrado
said. ``Because no matter how much you raise, you can spend (it) on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   So while presidential candidates can't raise money for their own
campaigns during the general election (except for legal and
administrative expenses), they are free to continue raising money
for their parties.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe the two major parties are on pace to raise
a record $500 million in unregulated, soft money this election
cycle _ twice the amount raised in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in 17 battleground states already are seeing what the
money is buying _ tens of millions of dollars worth of 30-second
commercials from the major parties.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, the two parties are spending more than $10
million a week on ads that prominently feature the two major
candidates. The latest Republican spot is an attack on Gore's
credibility; the Democrats responded with one that attacks Bush's
record on health care policy in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't had this large an air war this early in the
campaign,'' said Clifford May, a spokesman for the RNC. ``The
genteel era of taking breaks may be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Backus, a spokeswoman for the DNC, said the fund-raising
activities scheduled by the party since the Democratic convention
are serving a dual purpose as the election nears: raising money and
energizing supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC has scheduled two music concerts later this month, one
New York and one in Silicon Valley in California, as a way to raise
money and draw bigger crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fund-raising is designed to . . . gather a lot of folks
together, talk about the issues, and then get people to go forward
to knock on doors and bring us to victory,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the larger events, money is driving the process.
Federal election laws prohibit the parties from using only soft
money to pay for issue advertising; the parties must mix the soft
money with donations that are subject to limits _ $1,000 from an
individual and $5,000 from a political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are scrambling to raise enough of this regulated
hard money so that they can spend their soft money. All the
fund-raisers Gore has done since the convention, for example, have
been to raise hard money. Party officials have sought to broaden
the base of their hard money donations by scheduling concerts and
bigger events where ticket prices are lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether these events are more political or more fund-raising
is kind of a relative question right now,'' said Backus.
``Everything we are doing now is motivating people to bring them
out to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts caution that the candidates could face a
public backlash if they are perceived to be putting fund-raising
ahead of connecting with average voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters may begin to say, `What about us?' '' said Larry
Makinson, director of the Center for Responsive Politics. ``
`Enough with the fund-raising.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
