<SLUG> BC-CHAMBERS-GORE0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore stops in Atlanta today for two fund-raisers
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore attends two events in Atlanta
today, but only those willing to spend at least $1,000 will be able
to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will appear at a reception at the Hyatt Regency at 6 p.m.
and deliver remarks to ticketed guests and the media. Then, he's
off to a private dinner with 100 guests at the home of Anne Cox
Chambers, the media heiress who had backed former New Jersey Sen.
Bill Bradley in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hope to raise $1 million for the Democratic National
Committee at both events, said event co-chairman Michael Coles.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers is chairwoman of Atlanta Newspapers, which owns the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, and also a stakeholder in Cox
Enterprises, the fifth-largest cable operator in the country. Her
father, James M. Cox, was a Democratic governor of Ohio and was the
Democratic Party's presidential nominee in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, a former ambassador to Belgium under President Carter,
has come full circle in her support for Gore. She was a major
backer of Gore's failed presidential bid in 1988, but she fell out
with Gore in 1992 over cable rate regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, who could not be reached for comment, has in the past
declined to talk about her relationship with Gore, but Alexander
Netchvolodoff, Cox Enterprises' vice president of public policy,
and Gore aides previously said the rift occurred because Gore
supported legislation regulating cable rates while he was a U.S.
senator.
</P>
<P>
   The two also disagreed over provisions of the 1996
Telecommunications Act, said Greg Simon, who was then Gore's chief
domestic policy adviser. The act included a three-year phaseout of
cable rate regulations instead of an immediate phaseout that was
supported by Chambers and other cable operators. Last year,
Chambers contributed to Bradley's unsuccessful bid for the
Democratic nomination and hosted a fund-raiser at her home that
netted the New Jersey Democrat $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Coles approached Chambers about contributing to the
Democratic Party and its efforts to elect Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take any coaxing whatsoever to get her help,'' said
Coles, the cookie company executive who was the Democratic Party's
senate nominee against Paul Coverdell in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers donated $100,000 to the Democratic National Committee
in April, matching the largest individual contribution by any
Georgian to either political party. Coles has also donated $100,000
to the Democrats. Coles described Chambers' relationship to Gore as
one of mutual respect, despite their past disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between the vice president and Mrs. Chambers
goes back a very, very long time,'' Coles said. ``Any support she
may have given to Bill Bradley early on had to do with just sending
a message that maybe that she hadn't approved, or had some
disagreements with the vice president in the past. But I think the
loyalty to the vice president has always been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Farley, a spokesman for Cox Enterprises, said Chambers was
out of the country and would not attend the fund-raiser herself.
Gov. Roy Barnes, Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) and Sen. Zell Miller
(D-Ga.) are expected to be among the guests. The minimum donation
to attend the dinner was $5,000, said Keith Mason, Gore's state
co-chairman. The suggested donation for the reception beforehand
was $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
