<HEADER>
A5524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PEACETALKS-BO     09-07 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACETALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST PEACE TALKS AT UN HANG IN LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first strong indication that the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks weren't going anywhere this week in
New York came late Wednesday. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
stormed out of a meeting with Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright after Albright pressured him for concessions on Jerusalem,
US officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The highly pressured negotiations flew apart Thursday. Though
not finished, the negotiations remain in limbo until the
Palestinian Council decides this weekend whether to back the
unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state on Sept. 13, as
originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility remains unlikely, but if the lawmakers do so,
with the blessing and encouragement of Arafat, the peace talks
would end. If the lawmakers push back the date, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said Thursday that the two sides and President
Clinton would have only a few weeks to put together a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the best-case scenario, the odds are long for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next few weeks we have to find if we have a partner or
this is the end of the road of this part of the stage,'' Barak said
in Hebrew at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton directed his senior Middle East mediator, Dennis Ross,
to keep talking to Israeli and Palestinian negotiators. The US
president also is prepared to begin talks again, although no
meetings were set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is available and everyone is quite flexible,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   From interviews with US officials and the blunt comments made by
Barak Thursday, the crux of the remaining division between the
Israelis and Palestinians remained the holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The specific divisive issue has become the fate of the Temple
Mount, location of the ancient Jewish temples and the holiest site
in Judaism. The elevated compound, known in Arabic as Haram Sharif,
or Noble Sanctuary, is also site of the Dome of the Rock and
al-Aqsa Mosque, the third holiest shrine in Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and other members of the Palestinian delegation have
alleged that Israelis were digging underneath the Temple Mount, US
officials said, a charge that has recurred from time to time over
the years. Israeli officials denied the claim in negotiations, US
officials said. In 1996, Israel's opening of a tunnel near the holy
site sparked violent confrontations in Jerusalem and the West Bank,
killing nearly 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   According to US officials, Clinton has proposed awarding
sovereignty to the Palestinians over the mosques and recognize
Israeli sovereignty over the Western Wall, remnant of the perimeter
wall of the Jews' Second Temple, which was destroyed by the Romans.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the wall around the Temple Mount and the enclosed
area apart from the mosques would be placed under ``divine
sovereignty,'' the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that religious claims could destroy the negotiations,
US officials had tried to push old issues to the sidelines during
the Camp David talks, which broke up six weeks ago without
agreement but with substantial progress on addressing the core
issues for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But for Arafat, the suspicions about digging underneath the
Temple Mount have risen to foremost importance, according to US
officials, speaking on condition of anonymity. US government
lawyers, in response, have begun researching the legal boundaries
of the Temple Mount compound.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat Thursday indicated that religious issues dominated his
approach to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I . . . promised my people, my nation, my
religions _ Christian and Islam _ I am not going to betray them,''
Arafat said in an interview with CNN. ``You must remember with whom
you are speaking, you are speaking to Yasser Arafat. I will
continue to liberate all the Muslim and Christian holy places. It
is clear and obvious. If not, another one will come to liberate
it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Arafat walked out of the meeting with Albright, stunned US
officials briefed Clinton, who had just spent an hour talking with
Barak. Clinton, because of Arafat's anger, decided not to confront
him as Albright had on Jerusalem, said a US official who described
the 90-minute meeting between Clinton and Arafat as cordial.
</P>
<P>
   The president's hope, according the official, was that the talks
could continue in a week or so. The official said he didn't want to
risk the talks breaking down completely in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But among US officials there are disagreements about whether
Arafat's outburst was genuine or staged. If the anger was
calculated, it may have been done to delay tough negotiations until
after the meeting with Palestinian legislators, officials believe.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton and Barak have publicly accused Arafat of
intransigence in the talks, US officials also acknowledge that the
decision on Jerusalem is not Arafat's alone to make. They also say
that because discussions moved so quickly at Camp David, US
officials did not have enough time to brief leaders in the Arab
world about the potential scenarios of a final Israeli-Palestinian
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Clinton has spoken in person or on the telephone
with several Arab leaders, and Edward Walker, the assistant
secretary of state for Near Near Eastern Affairs, traveled from
Morroco to Oman to brief kings, sultans and prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak said Arafat was giving no ground. The Israeli prime
minister also disclosed details that revealed the Americans as
preparing specific proposals to break the logjam.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton raised several far-reaching ideas on the
core issues such as Jerusalem, refugees and borders and security,''
Barak said. ``I told President Clinton that some of the ideas he
raised were beyond the ideas we would accept. But if Arafat was
ready to take the ideas as a basis for negotiations, we would be
ready to enter the negotiations with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now,'' Barak said, ``Arafat has not been ready to use
that as a basis for negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak also specifically mentioned the need to win a large
monetary package from Congress as a cornerstone for the deal.
Israel has asked for at least $17 billion in new US aid for
security upgrades, including a request for state-of-the-art fighter
jets, according to US officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not lost hope that a solution could be found and would
be found,'' Barak said. ``But it's clear time is running out. In
October, Congress will adjourn and there is a clear need to
mobilize a major sum of money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Globe researcher Lisa Tuite contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
