<HEADER>
A5525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ELDERLY-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      09-07 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SWITCHES COURSE AND PLANS VOTE ON DRUG COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leading Senate Republicans, under intense pressure
from Democrats and some of their own members, changed course
Thursday and said they would try to pass legislation in the next
few weeks to help low-income elderly people buy prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Their comments guarantee that senators will soon be able to vote
on legislation similar to the competing proposals offered by Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After months of resisting Democratic efforts to offer drug
coverage to all Medicare beneficiaries, the Senate Republicans said
they would schedule a debate and a vote on the issue, which has
reverberated through the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said that Democrats, eager to highlight
differences between the parties, would seize every opportunity to
force votes on the issue before Congress adjourns next month. And
Sen. William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance
Committee, said that Republicans would try to push through
legislation to subsidize state programs that help low-income
elderly people buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Votes in the Senate do not mean that anything will become law
this year. But they would permit lawmakers to tell constituents
they had tried to address one of the most pressing concerns of many
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, who is in a tight race for re-election, introduced two
bills Thursday to provide federal money to the states for
pharmaceutical assistance programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This temporary legislation offers an assurance to low-income
seniors that they will be able to receive the help they need while
Congress completes the larger task of overhauling the Medicare
program,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's proposal resembles a major element of a plan unveiled by
Bush on Tuesday. Roth described his proposal as an interim measure
to provide drug coverage ``outside the Medicare program.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, has
opposed Democratic efforts to call up prescription drug
legislation. But he is no longer in a position to stop a debate and
a vote.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott, said Thursday night:
``Senator Lott strongly supports the effort to provide seniors in
need with prescription drugs now. That's why he is a co-sponsor of
the Roth bills. This is the first step in what Governor Bush has
outlined as a two-step process. Ultimately, we want to see
modernization of Medicare, with reforms to guarantee its long-term
solvency.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said his proposal, modeled on the Children's Health
Insurance Program, would offer $51 billion to the states over the
next four years to assist Medicare beneficiaries with annual
incomes up to 75 percent above the poverty level _ up to $14,600
for an individual or $19,700 for a couple.
</P>
<P>
   At least 22 states already have pharmaceutical assistance
programs. Roth's bill would encourage states to establish or expand
them, and the federal government would offer its own program in any
state that did not have one.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries, many
above the income limits specified in Roth's bill, do not have any
insurance for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth proposal fleshes out ideas he had been considering
before the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, where
many speakers declared their commitment to drug coverage for
Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats said Thursday that they would test that
commitment by forcing votes on the Senate floor. The votes could
occur this way: Democrats offer their proposal as an amendment to
some legislation pending on the Senate floor, and Republicans offer
their proposal as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight is going to be conducted at every opportunity for
the remainder of this session of Congress,'' Graham said. Graham is
one of the main architects of the Senate Democrats' proposal for
Medicare drug benefits, which closely resembles the plan developed
by Vice President Gore and the Clinton White House over the last 20
months.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate rejected the Democratic proposal by a vote of 53-44
on June 22. Two Republican senators, Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island
and Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois, voted for it; one Democrat, John
Breaux of Louisiana, voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Byron Dorgan of North Dakota, chairman of the Senate
Democratic Policy Committee, asked Thursday: ``What has changed
since the last vote? We now have a stack of speeches delivered in
Philadelphia. Let's see whether those who talk about prescription
drug benefits are willing to vote for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either there has been a genuine change of heart by Senate
Republicans, or the speeches in Philadelphia were not a true
reflection of what they really believe.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television commercial, the Republican Party of Rhode Island
boasts that Chafee ``voted against his own party for a real
patient's bill of rights and a prescription drug benefit that gives
seniors the drugs they need at a price they can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats said elderly people would, in many states, have
to go to welfare offices to qualify for pharmaceutical assistance
under state programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senior citizens want Medicare, not welfare,'' said Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Roth insisted that no stigma would be attached to drug coverage
under his bill.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services,
criticized Roth's proposal for other reasons. ``It doesn't cover
everyone, and it's not fair because the benefits would not be
consistent across the country,'' Shalala said. ``Where you live
would determine what benefits you get.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
