<HEADER>
A5530 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     09-07 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PRACTICE, READ THIS TOMORROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's T-minus 168 hours, give or take a time zone, before the
Autumn Games begin as spring arrives to a lingering winter-struck
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything.
</P>
<P>
   And the big minus, if you hadn't heard, hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Not some, not half, not even the bulk of, but all 441 hours of
what NBC will send back prepackaged and wrapped in preservatives to
the 13 colonies and its subsequent possessions will be about a day
ol So not only is it not live, or even ``plausibly live,'' it'll be
part of your kids' world-history class curriculum by the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, the network might reintroduce itself to the
technological advances that started with the Ben Franklin era of a
kite and Fortunately, much of the current population has heard of a
gizmo called the computer, which can tap into a netherworld called
the Internet, which _ get this _ provides nearly instantaneous
information.
</P>
<P>
   Which, as we have come to understand it, are what make sporting
events that much more enjoyable to experience.
</P>
<P>
   The network continues to stick with its story. The time
difference _ 18 hours between the place where kangaroos run wild
and where the L.A. Zoo has them caged _ is why tape-delay is the
only alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as NBC pooh-bah Dick Ebersol says: ``In order to bring the
competition to the greatest number of viewers, it will be all on
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay no attention to the fact that in 1992, the same network gave
Americans the option of !ital!three live pay channels to watch the
events from Barcelona, Spain. But that, as it turned out, did not
serve the greatest number of viewers. So that option isn't one any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what NBC has done with its $705 million investment in
these athletic events is basically say it's not sports, it's
entertainment, and you'd better get used to that concept now or
else you'll just be another confused passive consumer.
</P>
<P>
   At least NBC tried to deliver some live coverage during the '88
Games in Seoul. But it didn't get the ratings outpouring that it
expected. This time, it feels it has to protect itself. And the
chance that if it did carry stuff live overnight, we'd just tape
them anyway and watch the next morning, speeding through the
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   And since NBC announced Thursday that it has sold out its
advertising space to reach a record high $900 million in revenue _
which secures the network turning a profit _ this approach must
work.
</P>
<P>
   That's the American way, bub.
</P>
<P>
   But what NBC has done is condescending, as it condenses the
athletic achievements of the world's elite into viewer-friendly
tidbits, first with the prepackaged bio feature, then with the
result of an event.
</P>
<P>
   It's restrictive and it tricks you into thinking that if you
don't want to know the results, you can effectively tune out all
other TV, radio, newspapers, Internet and co-worker's bellowing. No
problem, right?
</P>
<P>
   It's insulting, insinuating that live results really aren't that
important.
</P>
<P>
   And it's demeaning. As well as plain mean.
</P>
<P>
   So on behalf of this newspaper, which will likely have stories,
pictures and expanded results on events from Sydney before you
actually have a chance to see them on TV, we're sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Just thought you'd like to know.
</P>
<P>
   __ In other words: Dick Enberg's essays were at least something
to look forward to during the Olympics telecast, but even that
won't be an option this time.
</P>
<P>
   Having jumped from NBC to CBS earlier this year, he'll be
covering the last few matches at the U.S. Open tennis tournament in
New York, then be off to his NFL assignments with partner Dan
Dierdorf, starting with the Bills-Jets game a week from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All of which will be carried live by that network.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe New York is a far cry from Australia, but he's not crying
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been so involved here that when someone mentioned it the
other day, asking if I didn't wish I was doing the Games, I said,
`Are they about to start?' '' Enberg said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His take on the non-live Olympic coverage:
</P>
<P>
   ``I know now that when I sit down to watch, anything I see will
only be the creme de la creme. I won't have to wade through an
event that's not so interesting or doesn't have a dramatic outcome.
They'll handpick all the best moments. The fact that I'll know some
of the results, they'll probably be a instance where I might say,
`There's something else instead I might do this hour.' But I
suspect there's a magnetism once you become drawn in that makes it
pretty tough to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The other games: ESPN's newest foray into the game-show
business starts Monday at 4 p.m. with ``ESPN's 2-Minute Drill,''
hosted by crossover ``SportsCenter'' deadpan anchor Kenny Mayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wardrobe is probably somewhere in between Dick Enberg on
`Sports Challenge' and Regis on `Millionaire,' '' admits Mayne.
``One benefit for this show is that we did not have a wardrobe
allowance and we got the suits at the same place where Regis went
to start his show. They are nice suits and I'm happy to be wearing
them, but we're not going to start any fashion trends.''
</P>
<P>
   No, just following trends seems to be a trend in itself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES __ ``One Day In September,'' which won the Academy
Award for this year's best documentary feature, has a one-time-only
play on HBO on Monday at 8 p.m. before it heads toward theater
distribution. Anything but a stuffy rehash of the events
surrounding the deaths of 11 Israeli athletes and coaches during
the '72 Olympics in Munich, West Germany, this 1-hour film narrated
by Michael Douglas includes remarkable recounting by the lone
surviving Palestinian terrorist, who has been hiding in Africa for
the last 25 years, contrasted with the story told by Ankie Spitzer,
the widow of Israeli fencing coach Andre Spitzer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Last time the same athlete simultaneously made the cover of
Time and Newsweek . . . heck, who keeps track of these things?
Anyway, Marion Jones won't go unnoticed when the Games begin next
week. Oh, and she's also on the cover of Sports Illustrated For
Women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Jim Rome's gloss for Dennis Miller: Carrot Top. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ The Kings' new radio spots for season tickets. This year,
they have soundbites from coach Andy Murray addressing the team in
the locker room and on the bench, which highlight not so much a
``Win One For the Gipper'' approach but a no-nonsense,
here's-what-it-takes mentality that the hockey fan really finds
intriguing. Here's a coach who not only won't shy away from wearing
a mike but turns out is good enough to sell tickets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES __ ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' Web site
(www.espn.go.com/abcsports/mnf/sights_sound s/dmiller.html) has a
new weekly feature: Dennis Miller's ``top lines of the week.'' Such
as, from the Rams-Broncos' opener, the No. 1 quip: ``Everyone's
worried about me using profanity _ the only f- word I might say a
lot this year is Faulk.'' Ah, the Disney family must be proud. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Taking things a step dumber, The Encyclopedia Britannica's
Web site (www.britannica.com) introduced an ``Annotated Dennis
Miller'' feature, breaking down his historical, literary and
sociological references. It details what he was referring to, tries
to explain what he meant and speculates on what he was implying.
Here's a rule of thumb: Anytime you need a joke explained to you,
or in this case translated, it kinda loses its effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS-ART-     09-07 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB TURNCOAT EAGER TO TALK ABOUT CONSTRUCTION RACKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a cold night last December, a white limousine
stopped near Il Boschetto restaurant in Yonkers. Two large men
stepped out and hurried through the restaurant's tinted front door.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were suspected of being mob racketeers. One, Joseph
Datello, was an inducted member of the Lucchese crime family. The
other, Sean J. Richard, was the son-in-law of John Riggi, the
imprisoned boss of the New Jersey-based DeCavalcantes. Richard had
recently been in a car accident. He wore a bandage on his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   In the restaurant, they met Steven L. Crea, the Luccheses'
acting boss, who greeted them from the first stool at the bar. For
about an hour, the three men talked about bribery and extortion,
the authorities say. Richard remembers that Crea was angry. He
speculated darkly about a man he thought might be a snitch.
</P>
<P>
   When the meeting ended, Richard dropped Datello off at his home
on Staten Island, as he had after many meetings before. Then he
broke from the routine.
</P>
<P>
   He directed his driver to a motel parking lot and switched cars,
taking a seat in a sedan with another group of men. Reaching into
his sweatsuit, he unrolled the bandage and removed a hidden
recording device.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Richard had just betrayed his Mafia boss. Crea had guessed
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was a fellow boss' son-in-law, worried that his
future held either jail time or a violent death, who had turned
against him. In the parlance of mobsters, Richard had become a rat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not the kind of circumstances you want to gain fame
and notoriety for,'' Richard said in a recent interview. ``But I
didn't have many options, and that's what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard, who while in hiding agreed to several interviews, is
the mob's latest embarrassing, tell-all turncoat. He is an eager
raconteur.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan district
attorney, unsealed racketeering indictments against Crea and 37
other defendants, accusing them of participating in a criminal
enterprise that drove up the prices of construction projects
throughout the city. The indictment identifies Crea as the acting
boss and Datello as a soldier in the Lucchese crime family.
</P>
<P>
   As the prosecutions go forward, they will rely on years of
investigation and wiretaps by the New York Police Department. And
they will rely on Richard, who agreed to plead guilty to attempted
enterprise corruption in exchange for a new identity and a sentence
of five years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   In return, he plans to testify with zeal about how the
Luccheses, through persistence and payoffs, maintained a grip on
construction projects at a time when the Mafia was supposedly in
decline. Dozens of contractors, union officials and mobsters are
said to be vulnerable to his testimony, which will recount, in
detail, bribes doled out in bars and restaurants, coercion at
construction sites and the Mafia's aggressive, if somewhat
bumbling, management of a sprawling criminal scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a godsend,'' said a lawyer who is familiar with the
case.
</P>
<P>
   It is a remarkable reversal. As Riggi's son-in-law and the
father of two of the boss' granddaughters, Richard, 35, is
literally married to the mob. And he is displaying an almost
gloating disrespect. In interviews, he went beyond discussing
details of labor corruption. He spoke with disdain for the mobsters
he once served.
</P>
<P>
   He described Emmanuel Riggi, one of his brothers-in-law and a
man prosecutors describe as a member of the DeCavalcante crime
family, as ``so fat he breaks chairs at every family function.'' He
said John Riggi, the feared crime boss, ``ought to thank me for
feeding his useless kids.'' He said Datello, his 6-foot-5 former
partner, was ``a big idiot, like Frankenstein.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say, `Hey, Joey, I've got to take you in to get the
bolts for your neck,''' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard is a gritty man and can emanate the blunt, coarse
demeanor of a thug. He is utterly unlettered. He says ``mob
fractions'' when he means ``mob factions.'' But he is also capable
of warmth and charm, and the people who know him say he is very
smart, a man who passed easily through many different roles until
arriving at his latest: witness for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a chameleon,'' said Tommy, a friend of nearly 20 years
who spoke only on the condition that his last name not be
published. ``He became a gangster better than one of them, and he
thought circles around them while he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first 30 years of his life, Richard was a virtual
nobody, a laborer from the Bronx who trained as a union apprentice
and, by his mid-20s, started a small subcontracting company in New
Jersey. His insider's tour of the mob did not begin until 1995,
when he began dating Sara M. Riggi, the daughter of the
DeCavalcantes' boss.
</P>
<P>
   The DeCavalcantes are the smallest of the region's Mafia
families, and considered by law enforcement to be the weakest,
often relying on cooperation with the five families in New York.
But they have long specialized in labor rackets: extorting
contractors in exchange for labor peace, or replacing unionized
employees with nonunion workers and then spiriting away savings on
wages or fringe benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Richard became fascinated with Riggi, whom he said he first
visited in the Federal Correctional Institution in Cumberland, Md.,
in 1996, when the boss was serving a sentence for extortion. Riggi,
75, appeared in prison khakis, yet somehow managed, Richard said,
``to have an almost presidential bearing.'' He sat briefly with
Richard and Riggi before sending his daughter to a vending machine,
Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as she left, he looked at me and said: ``Who you with?
Who you indentured to?'' Richard said. ``I said: ``Nobody. I don't
answer to nobody.' And after we talked for a while, we hit it
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Riggi married on Sept. 13, 1996. ``Friday the
13th,'' Richard now says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Riggi's three sons, who law enforcement officials say
were unable to run the rackets (Richard calls them ``goofballs,
three guys you wouldn't take miniature golfing''), his son-in-law
seemed smart and aggressive. Soon, Richard's legitimate business
was a sideline; labor rackets were his game.
</P>
<P>
   He and law enforcement officials said that in 1996 he began
circulating his father-in-law's instructions to corrupt New Jersey
locals and pursuing larger plans. ``Sean was a significant
player,'' said Robert T. Buccino, who retired last month as deputy
chief of New Jersey's Organized Crime Bureau. ``He was more trusted
than the sons were.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, Richard established a link with the Luccheses, working
for Datello, who prosecutors say also specialized in labor rackets.
In one of his first schemes, Richard and prosecutors assert, he and
an associate bribed Michael Forde, the president of Local 608 of
United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners, to help limit the
number of unionized carpenters at a Park Central Hotel renovation
project.
</P>
<P>
   He said the first payment _ $10,000 in cash _ was made over
afternoon beers at a Hooters on West 56th Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him the ten thousand, and he says, `You know, I really
shouldn't be drinking beers while I'm working; the union is
cracking down on that,''' Richard said. ``It was the funniest
thing. I said: `You're worried about the beers? What do you think
your guys would think about that ten thousand you just took?'''
</P>
<P>
   Forde was indicted this week; through his lawyer, he said the
meeting with Richard never took place.
</P>
<P>
   As he worked for Datello, Richard lived a high roller's life,
canvassing Manhattan and spending freely from wads of $100 bills.
He bought pedigreed Rottweilers. He leased a new luxury car every
few months. He bought a $320,000 home on two acres in Holmdel,
N.J., putting $145,000 down. The house had a sauna, a Jacuzzi, an
in-ground pool and separate yards: one for his two infant
daughters, the other for his menacing black dogs.
</P>
<P>
   By 1999, he had become a fixture at the Oak Room at the Plaza
Hotel, where the manager, Patrick Littlejohn, remembers he sat in a
corner booth and ordered heaping plates of chilled seafood and
seared prime rib, washing both down with 1982 Lafite-Rothschild.
Sometimes he stood by the piano, singing Frank Sinatra or Perry
Como. ``All the classics,'' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   He also passed long hours at the Paradise Club, an adult
nightclub near the Empire State Building, where he tipped the
raven-haired striptease dancer he fell in love with as much as
$1,000 a night, he and the dancer both say. ``If I dropped dead
tomorrow, I lived, baby, I lived,'' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   He and the authorities also say he attended the meetings of a
secret three-member construction panel that the Luccheses used to
plan rackets, mediate disputes and divide spoils. By his telling,
these meetings illustrated the paradox that the latter-day Mafia
has become.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the mob was resourceful enough to cheat the
construction industry of millions of dollars. On the other, many
members and associates were almost pathetic: grown men who groveled
to get jobs as flagmen at road crews, or who talked relentlessly on
cellular phones about secret meetings, all while the detectives
were listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was supposed to be a secret society, but we'd get 20, 25,
30 guys turning up, all asking for something,'' Richard said. ``It
was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled one panel meeting last year at Little Charlie's Clam
Bar on Kenmare Street in Manhattan, for which, he and investigators
say, two dozen mobsters and associates arrived in flashy cars,
lining the block with Cadillacs and Lincolns. Later, he learned
that police had watched the entire show. ``It was kind of
comical,'' Richard said. ``The detectives were right across the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard's life began to unravel last June, when police raided
several dozen homes and offices in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut, searching for records documenting the suspected
rackets. One of the targets was the Linden, N.J., office of S &AMP; S
Contracting, the business he had formed with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The raids filled him with dread. ``It was the beginning of the
end,'' he said. ``For them to get 40 warrants in three states? Come
on. That's real.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five months, he fell into a funk. He began to use
cocaine, marijuana and heroin, he said, and drank more heavily than
usual. He spent even more money, dipping into the weekly cash
tribute he said he was supposed to pay Datello as a member of his
crew.
</P>
<P>
   He also began to think about becoming the state's witness, in
part because friction within the Luccheses rose after the raids,
and he worried that Datello had been given orders to kill him. The
fear, he said, intensified late last fall when he was told to wait
outside the Tick Tock Diner in Clifton, N.J., to meet Dominic
Truscello, a Lucchese capo. Datello told him he would be picked up
in a van.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What do you guys need a van for?''' Richard recalled.
``A van is never a good sign in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   He was so spooked that he armed himself, he said, carrying a
pistol in his belt. The van ride passed without violence, but
during the meeting that followed, he said, Truscello stared icily
at him and said, ``What are your sins?'' Richard interpreted the
question as a sign that he was marked for execution. He defected
soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the case is public, some of Richard's former Mafia
associates seem astounded at the breadth and tone of his
confessions. A few, through lawyers or associates, declined to
comment, including John Riggi, his sons and Datello, who has eluded
arrest so far.
</P>
<P>
   Others, through associates or lawyers, said Richard is little
more than a wild exaggerator and a serial manipulator who drew
attention to the Luccheses through a foolishly flamboyant style.
``This guy was a wannabe, and he conducted business that was not
authorized by organized crime,'' said a person who is familiar with
the Lucchese family.
</P>
<P>
   They also said the state's star witness was a traitor on many
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Richard is now in hiding with his girlfriend, the stripper, who
performed under the name Lola. His wife, Sara Riggi, has not seen
him in months. She has been left in disarray, alone with their
daughters and facing foreclosure proceedings against their home.
She filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy protection in July and for
divorce in August. ``It's very upsetting,'' she said in a brief
interview, which she ended in tears.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Richard has the appearance of a man who has long
been resting. He has lost weight and added tattoos. He has a rich
tan. Now and then he talks about book or movie deals. He takes
precautions, of course, but they are almost comically half-hearted,
like his tendency when venturing away from police to wear a hat and
sunglasses, or his request to a reporter not to describe his
tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   The Luccheses' latest racketeering case, and his probation will
be over one day, he says. Then he will have a new life. ``The last
thing anybody wants to be is a rat,'' he said. ``But you know
something? I'll be a rat and I won't be in prison. I'll be a rat
and I'll be alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
