u a BC-LA-JUVENILE-PRISONS-3     09-07 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-JUVENILE-PRISONS-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA SETTLES LAWSUIT, ENDING TEST OF PRIVATE JUVENILE
PRISONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FOX BUTTERFIELD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The State of Louisiana agreed in federal district court in Baton
Rouge on Thursday to sweeping changes in the way it runs its
juvenile prisons, including steps to protect inmates from abusive
guards and promises to provide medical, dental and mental health
care.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was intended to settle several lawsuits against
the state, including one by the U.S. Department of Justice, which
charged that teen-age inmates were being deprived of food, clothing
and medical care and were routinely beaten by guards.
</P>
<P>
   While providing better treatment for inmates, the agreement
would effectively end Louisiana's experiment with privately run
juvenile prisons, where the worst abuses had occurred, said David
Utter, director of the Juvenile Justice Project of Louisiana, a
civil rights group that represented some inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Louisiana was prohibited from placing any
more young inmates in a prison at Jena, which had been run by the
Wackenhut Corrections Corp., a subsidiary of Wackenhut Corp. and
the world's largest operator of for-profit prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Utter said the state had also agreed to prohibit a company
operated by friends of former Gov. Edwin Edwards, which owned a
juvenile prison at Tallulah, from managing the prison. The state
took control of the Tallulah prison in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Stalder, the secretary of the department of public
safety and corrections, said in a news conference Thursday with
Gov. Mike Foster that the increase in youthful offenders had forced
Louisiana to expand its juvenile prisons but that ``the state's
efforts to provide some of these services through privately
operated facilities were a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of Louisiana's secure juvenile facilities now are operated
directly by our department,'' Stalder said. ``The state is
confident that difficulties experienced in the past will not recur.
We are pleased to be able to put this litigation behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana had tried to privatize its juvenile prisons as a way
to cut costs, but the effort raised questions about whether
for-profit corporations can operate prisons more efficiently than
state governments without skimping on essential services and
training.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As often in Louisiana, the plan was enmeshed in a political
scandal. Another friend and business partner of Edwards, Cecil
Brown, is awaiting trial in federal court in Baton Rouge in
January, along with the former mayor of Houston, Fred Hofheinz, on
charges of conspiracy, extortion and bribery for trying to obtain
the contract to operate the juvenile prison at Jena.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been accused of funneling $845,000 from Hofheinz to
Edwards to secure the Jena contract. Edwards was named an
unindicted co-conspirator, and was convicted in a separate bribery
trial last May involving the award of a riverboat casino license.
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut abandoned the Jena prison last spring after a juvenile
court judge in New Orleans and investigators hired by the Justice
Department found that the teen-age inmates there had been deprived
of underwear, sweaters, blankets and food and that a 17-year-old
boy had been forced to lie face down on the concrete floor, with a
guard's knee in his back, even though he had recently undergone
stomach surgery for a gunshot wound and was wearing a colostomy
bag. Wackenhut said it would convert Jena to an adult prison, but
it is now empty.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lann Lee, the assistant attorney general for civil rights,
said the agreement ``does not mean everything will be magically
solved.'' But, Lee said, ``It does mean that there are now over 100
pages of detailed obligations and responsibilities that the State
of Louisiana has agreed to, with timetables and mechanisms to make
sure they are taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly important, Lee said, was the role of medical
personnel from Louisiana State University.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, doctors from the university's School of
Medicine would provide medical, mental health and dental care at
the state's five juvenile prisons, and independent monitors would
have the right to inspect the facilities to make sure guards were
no longer beating inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Staff from the university would also help provide training to
guards in an effort to lessen the amount of physical force that has
been used, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Other independent monitors, chosen by the Justice Department,
Utter's group and lawyers for other juvenile inmates, would also
conduct annual inspections.
</P>
<P>
   If the problems continue, the agreement allows the Justice
Department and the others to file motions to reopen their lawsuits
with Judge Frank Polozola of federal district court in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Polozola, who has overseen prison conditions in
Louisiana since 1973, had played a crucial role in reaching the
agreement after he ordered all sides last spring to keep talking
until a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   But several lawyers who took part in the talks said that while
pressure from Polozola had been helpful, the troubles had taken
place during the very time he was supposed to be supervising the
juvenile prisons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
