u a BC-LEOFRANK-RABBI0908-CO     09-07 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEOFRANK-RABBI0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL censure sought on Falcons investor
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A rabbi has asked the National Football League to
censure a part-owner of the Atlanta Falcons for remarks concerning
the notorious 1915 lynching of Leo Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson Brown, whose great-grandfather was editorialist and
later U.S. Sen. Tom Watson, whose writings are blamed for whipping
up anti-Semitism before the lynching, owns 6 percent of the
Falcons. He says Frank, a Jew, was properly convicted of killing
13-year-old Mary Phagan, and he was lynched because Frank's
supporters in effect bought off the governor to get him to commute
his sentence. In a recent Atlanta Journal-Constitution article
Brown said, ``Maybe the Frank people should apologize for bribing
the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes Rabbi Steven Lebow of Temple Kol Emeth, in metro
Atlanta, fume. The words he says, perpetuate the stereotype of
``rich Jews'' controlling the system while most historians believe
the governor acted ethically. He wrote a letter asking the NFL to
rebuke Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Harvard-educated lawyer, Mr. Brown should be more careful
of what he says when he slanders people,'' said Lebow, who placed a
plaque in Frank's memory at the site of the lynching in Marietta.
``An NFL owner should not be making bigoted statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he plans to respond to Lebow, but he won't retract
his statements.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue will respond when he receives
Lebow's letter, said spokesman Greg Aiello. The Falcons aren't
commenting because the dispute involves a minority owner whose role
is as an investor, said spokesman Aaron Salkin.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, a Northern-born Atlanta factory manager, was sentenced to
death in the death of Phagan, whose family was from Marietta. Gov.
John M. Slaton, a law partner of Frank's lawyer, commuted his
sentence to life. A group of Mariettans kidnapped Frank from his
cell and hanged him near where the Big Chicken now stands.
</P>
<P>
   Brown argues the governor was bribed because as a partner in the
law firm he shared in its proceeds, including a promised bonus if
it won a commutation.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Oney, a writer who has spent 13 years researching and
writing a book on the case, said there is no evidence the governor
received a dime from the action that ruined his political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Slaton made a decision of conscience,'' he said.
``That said, there was a clear and troubling appearance of a
conflict of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
