<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTRO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HANDSHAKE AND SMALL TALK FOR CLINTON AND CASTRO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Bill Clinton and Fidel Castro were in
the same room, in October 1995 at a United Nations reception in New
York, the Secret Service deftly kept the two men apart. Not a word
or a handshake was exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   So anyone tracing the glacial progress in Cuban-American
relations _ always a sensitive political issue, especially in
Florida, New Jersey and New York, three key states in the coming
presidential election _ should note that the White House this week
quietly reversed its Cuban handshake policy. After changing its
story several times, the White House press office said Thursday
that Clinton and Castro actually shook hands on Wednesday, on the
edges of a luncheon for the summit meeting of world leaders at the
United Nations. It was apparently the first time Castro, 74, had
ever shaken hands with a sitting U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the president of the United States and the leader who
has bedeviled every occupant of the White House since the
Eisenhower administration apparently spoke to each other for the
first time. But on Thursday afternoon, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who usually describes all conversations between her boss
and other national leaders as deep and important, was quick to
caution that ``there was no substance'' to the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   But in relations with Cuba, even empty talk is brimming with
symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Vice President Al Gore talked Cuba policy _ about
the fate of Elian Gonzalez, the young boy who was ultimately
returned to his father in Cuba over the objections of his Miami
relatives _ it dominated campaign news for days. So even the
thought of Clinton and Castro making polite conversation is bound
to be viewed with suspicion by Cuban Americans already smarting
from the Elian affair. Perhaps that explains why the White House
spokesman, Joe Lockhart, when first asked about the encounter, said
reports of a handshake were ``not true.'' Later, other officials
said Lockhart had been insufficiently briefed. ``On background,''
one official said, ``I can confirm there was a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   With all this diplomatic sensitivity on display, Albright and
the White House went to some lengths Thursday to make the point
that Clinton did not seek out one of the world's last true
communist leaders. ``As I understand it,'' Albright said, ``it was
a chance encounter that Mr. Castro initiated, and they talked for a
couple of minutes, and there was no substance.'' Administration
officials were under strict orders not to detail the small talk.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time Castro has had a close encounter
with a top American leader.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after coming to power in 1959 after the Cuban revolution,
Castro flew to Washington and met the sitting vice president,
Richard M. Nixon. President Eisenhower had decided that it was not
appropriate for him to see Castro because of the unsettled
situation in Cuba. So Eisenhower's secretary of state, Christian
Herter, asked Nixon to meet the Cuban leader and give the president
his assessment of him.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, when the White House spokesman finally confirmed
that President Clinton and Castro had indeed shaken hands, he
pointed out that President Bush had also come close to Castro
several times, including at a conference in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil,
in June 1992. But the two apparently never spoke, and certainly
never shook hands, according to reports at the time, although Bush
applauded several times during a speech by Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is not about to repeat his handshake with Castro.
Almost all the world leaders attending the summit meeting here were
invited to a reception Thursday at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
But the White House made a point of keeping Castro's name off the
list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
