<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-BLAKE-LADN-(SLANG     09-07 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLAKE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE'S UNFINISHED BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ For Rob Blake, it was like any other summer
_ charity golf tournaments, volleyball in the sand near his home in
Manhattan Beach, even a couple of visits to the family farm outside
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, life is good for the Los Angeles Kings captain.
The team finished last season with 94 points, fourth-best in
franchise history. Blake was third to NHL MVP Chris Pronger in
voting for the league's top defenseman. In June, he and wife,
Brandy, celebrated their second wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the club opens training camp today at its swanky new
facility in here in preparation for its second season at the $400
million Staples Center, there's a sense of urgency in Blake's
voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the season ended last year is not something you easily
forget,'' Blake said. ``We went into the playoffs believing we had
a chance and we got wiped out. It's hard not to take that
personally. I can't remember a time when training camp seemed more
critical than now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Kings lose four straight to the Detroit Red
Wings last April in the first round of the postseason, they were 0
for 23 on the Blake-run power play.
</P>
<P>
   For an organization that made the playoffs for just the second
time in seven years, it appeared to shatter the momentum of the
regular season. And during the summer, the Kings did not add a big
name the way they had the year before when plucking Ziggy Palffy
from the lowly New York Islanders. They flirted with the thought of
acquiring injured superstar Eric Lindros, a restricted free agent
whose rights were retained by the Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, first-year players Steven Reinprecht, Lubomir
Visnovsky and Andreas Lilja are expected to make the club and play
prominent roles.
</P>
<P>
   All that, and the fact Blake is entering the final season of a
three-year, $15 million contract. Although Blake, 30, is the team's
top player, the Kings are not close to a new deal. The club's top
priority right now is re-signing first-line center Jozef Stumpel,
who is expected to miss at least part of training camp in a
contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is a lot to think about,'' said Mattias
Norstrom, Blake's defensemate last year, who missed all of the 1999
camp with a holdout. ``I talked to Rob a couple of times this
summer and we didn't talk at all about Detroit. I think he has
gotten past it, but he cares so much about this team so you never
know. He puts so much of what happens on himself. That's part of
being a leader, but the rest of us have to take some
responsibility, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings weren't expected to beat the Red Wings, a veteran team
that had won the Stanley Cup two of the previous three years. But
the failure of the Kings power play landed directly at Blake's
skates.
</P>
<P>
   He had missed the final week of the regular season with a
sprained left knee and returned out of sync. The knee is again
sound. The team's emotional condition is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   After playing their best game of the Detroit series, a 8-5 loss
in Game 2, the Kings returned to Los Angeles and were defeated 2-1
and 3-0. They now have dropped 12 consecutive playoff games dating
back to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Murray, entering his second year as Kings coach, was as
excited as anyone at the possibility of obtaining Lindros, whose
hockey future is clouded by six career concussions.
</P>
<P>
   When Philadelphia retained the right to Lindros, Murray the
motivator went a different direction. He started to sell Kelly
Buchberger and Nelson Emerson _ players acquired at last March's
trading deadline _ as leaders who could help take the pressure off
Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger was the captain in Edmonton and played on Stanley Cup
winners before going to Atlanta in last year's expansion draft.
Emerson has been a regular 20-goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the important messages of camp is getting the players
to take more ownership of this team,'' Murray said. ``It's
important that they feel they can influence the outcome of the
season, not just feel they are along for the ride. I think that
happened last year and it put an awful lot of pressure on Rob.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Blake is concerned the Kings are asking too much of
unproven players in a year they are hoping to raise the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Visnovsky and Lilja are defenseman. During the summer, the Kings
did not re-sign veteran Garry Galley and lost Sean O'Donnell to
Minnesota in the expansion draft. Galley and O'Donnell were the
Kings' second defensive unit and valuable members of the power
play. They also were alternate captains along with Luc Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings did sign free-agent defenseman Mathieu Schneider from
the New York Rangers at Blake's recommendation. Schneider and Blake
worked out together this summer at Gold's Gym in Venice Beach and
will be paired on the power play this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schneider is the only one who is a proven player,'' Blake
said. ``It would be great if the other guys all contributed, played
a full season and helped us get back to the playoffs. But that
could be a lot to ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you'd love to go out and get as many players as you can,
a (Jaromir) Jagr, a Lindros and Brian Leetch. But in this business
you don't always get what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the issues facing Blake, his contract future is not an
immediate concern. Just days before signing his last deal three
years ago, a frustrated Blake said that even though he loved L.A.,
he knew there was a chance he might finish his career elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the latest negotiations are on hold between Kings GM Dave
Taylor and Blake's agent Ron Salcer. Taylor said Wednesday he could
see getting it done after the season begins. Unlike Stumpel, who is
using the leverage of training camp to secure a new deal, Blake has
been skating, and participating in meetings with Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's out there,'' said Blake, acknowledging that
Pronger is seeking a five-year deal worth between $8-10 million per
season. ``But after last year, there is a lot unfinished. This is
an organization that needs to keep the momentum going. We did well
last year. But we need to do much more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
