<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5551 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NURSEBETTY-AZR &LR;      09-07 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSEBETTY-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NURSEBETTY-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SKIP APPOINTMENT WITH `NURSE BETTY' (a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nurse Betty seems as if it were patched together from parts of
other films.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is reminiscent of (beginitalic)True Romance(enditalic),
in which a spunky girl and her beau make off with a passel of drugs
and are chased down by vicious thugs. In this case, Betty (Renee
Zellweger) steals the drugs unknowingly, but the result is pretty
much the same.
</P>
<P>
   The movie even includes an interrogation scene similar to the
one in (beginitalic)True Romance(enditalic), except it's more
gruesome, less clever and lacks two vital elements: Dennis Hopper
and Christopher Walken.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the characters in (beginitalic)Nurse
Betty(enditalic), which all seem familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Freeman plays a philosophical hit man named Charlie, the
same character he has played in films such as (beginitalic)Seven
(enditalic)(philosophical cop) and (beginitalic)Hard Rain
(enditalic)(philosophical bank robber). Freeman does a nice job,
but he should. He's had plenty of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock is Wesley, a wisecracking sidekick, much as he was in
(beginitalic)Dogma(enditalic). This is hardly casting against type.
Besides that, Rock's performance is uneven, as if he's not sure
when to fly into his stand-up act.
</P>
<P>
   Betty is married to Del (Aaron Eckhart), a jerk ripped straight
out of (beginitalic)Thelma &AMP; Louise(enditalic). He fools around on
her, forgets her birthday and has poor table manners, the universal
movie shorthand for rotten husbands. The penalty, of course, is
death.
</P>
<P>
   All these familiar characters don't necessarily make the movie
unwatchable. It does, however, make it predictable.
(beginitalic)Nurse Betty (enditalic)also can't decide whether it's
a black comedy, a crime drama or a romance. It has elements of all
three. Sometimes they mesh, and sometimes they don't.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, Zellweger does an admirable job as Betty, a
waitress who suffers a psychotic break after seeing Del get
murdered by Charlie and Wesley, who are after stolen drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Betty is so traumatized, she plunges into a fantasy world where
she is engaged to her favorite soap-opera character, Dr. David
Ravell (Greg Kinnear), who is actually an actor named George
McCord. In a sort of trance, Betty writes a note to her dead
husband and heads off to California to locate and marry Dr. Ravell.
</P>
<P>
   While the soap fantasy deserves some points for creativity, much
of the story plays out conventionally. Betty has unwittingly taken
the drugs (hidden in the trunk of her car), forcing Charlie and
Wesley to track her across the country. As they flounder around,
she struggles to hook up with her fictional finance.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the energy of this movie hits a low ebb. There's
also some big gaps in internal logic.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Charlie keeps saying he can't believe Betty would
head to California because of a soap opera. But in the movie's
opening scene, Charlie watches Betty pour coffee while being
engrossed in the show. As a cagey master crook, you'd think it's
something he'd remember.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there's not much memorable about (beginitalic)Nurse
Betty(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
