<SLUG> BC-1ap0908a </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta council mulls naming street after Young
 &HT;    By Mae Gentry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who helped put Atlanta on the world map may get his own
International Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta City Council is considering changing downtown's
International Boulevard to Andrew Young International Boulevard in
honor of the globe-trotting former mayor and U.N. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking is that it's time that we give some recognition
to Andy,'' said Councilman C.T. Martin, who introduced the
legislation with Debi Starnes. Her council district includes the
downtown street.
</P>
<P>
   Martin cites Young's involvement in Atlanta's bid for the 1996
Olympic Games. ``We know that he provided, from his ambassadorship,
those relationships with those 17 African countries that helped put
the vote over the top,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Starnes anticipates council approval ``in the absence of any
objections or any reason why we shouldn't change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bond, one of eight council co-sponsors, favors lauding
the civil rights activist, ordained minister and former U.S. House
member and thinks International is a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a street that, in some respects, is the gateway into
Atlanta from I-75 and I-85,'' he said. ``And it leads right into
(Centennial) Olympic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a short street, so few businesses would need new
stationery.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hulata, a Czech immigrant who manages Pittypat's Porch
restaurant, remembers the last name change in 1977. ``It was kind
of messy a little bit, because it was Cain Street forever. For
major customers coming from the suburbs, it was messy. Mail
disappeared or was lost because of that. It was not pleasant for a
little while.'' As for the proposed name, Hulata said, ``If they're
going to leave it International Boulevard, just put a person's name
in front of it, I don't see any problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, a partner in the consulting firm Good Works
International, declined to comment. His assistant, Maggie Womack,
liked the idea. ``It should have been done a long time ago,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The council's City Utilities Committee will hold a public
hearing on the proposal at 9 a.m. Tuesday in Committee Room 2. The
council is expected to vote on it Sept. 18. If passed, it would
require Mayor Bill Campbell's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
