<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-E-LIVING08-COX     09-07 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-LIVING08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News about the net: 09.07.00
 &HT;    By John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Cartoon characters helping parents teach Net safety to kids
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An interactive ``Nash Bridges''? Up next on CBS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SoYouWanna know about a red-hot site?
</P>
<P>
   CYBER SAFETY: Donald Duck slays computer viruses with a pea
shooter. The Three CyberPigs uncover racism on the Web. And the
Idea Seekers urge children not to respond to ``strange, mean or
upsetting''
</P>
<P>
   e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the efforts helping parents teach kids about
safe Internet use in ways that will interest and entertain. The
reason: 25 million children are online in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples: Canadian Media Awareness Network has released
``Cybersense and Nonsense,'' in which children help three
skateboarding pigs learn that not all wolves blow houses down;
Circle 1's kidscom charged its safety word puzzles with cartoon
characters; and Disney Online established ``Surf Swell Island,''
where children guide characters through spooky scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   The kids are noticing. More than 75 percent of the nearly 1,000
kids surveyed (ages 8-12) say their parents restrict the sites they
can visit and more than half say their parents limit their time
online. Both figures are up sharply over the last five years, says
the survey by SpectraCom Inc. and Circle 1 Network.
</P>
<P>
   www.media-awareness.ca
</P>
<P>
   www.kidscom.com
</P>
<P>
   www.surfswellisland.com
</P>
<P>
   CBS' WEB: If you like the Web-enhanced Emmys this weekend on ABC
(abc.com.), then you'll love the latest media coupling: CBS and
WebTV. The network will soon offer interactivity on 500 hours of
programming, including comedy and drama series, an industry first
(unless you consider ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' a comedy).
Those with an eye on the Eye Network and a hand on the remote will
``experience'' enhanced content on demand (including sports and
cast bios), take part in live polling, have access to programming
updates and have e-commerce and chat options. The expanded service
will be available only via WebTV Networks and Microsoft's
interactive TV products: WebTV Plus or UltimateTV.
</P>
<P>
   STEALTH SITE: It's the 36th fastest-growing site on the Internet
and it's spent exactly zero dollars on marketing _ a highly unusual
feat in the publicity-charged dot-com marketplace. So what's making
SoYouWanna.com, a new how-to site offering factual advice on
everything from how to get a tattoo to how to pitch a TV show to
how to eat sushi, so hot? The high traffic may be because of the
hip, clever tone of its advice. But it probably has more to do with
the obvious target audience: the 18- to 29-year-old demographic,
which spends more than $200 billion annually. Since it went live in
March, it has grown from about 800,000 page views in June to 3.3
million in July, according to PC Data Online.
</P>
<P>
   www.soyouwanna.com
</P>
