   SITES
</P>
<P>
   For procrastinators,
</P>
<P>
   goof-offs, Web addicts
</P>
<P>
   Do the at-work numbers above surprise you? Perhaps, then, so
will this site for slackers (you know who you are: just coming off
a four-day week and dreading the looming 40/5 _ at least 40 hours
over five days _ or those with to-do list with nothing to do).
Visit I Should Be Working for a collection of games, contests,
sports pages, entertainment links, office humor links and more. The
creators say the site is dedicated to ``slackers, goof-offs,
procrastinators, loafers, long-lunchers and Web-addicted
employees.'' And this bonus: It comes equipped with a panic button
should the boss walk your way.
</P>
<P>
   ishouldbeworking.com
</P>
<P>
   If the grass is greener on the other side of the fence
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Tech and the Braves games Saturday are all at home and
on TV, starting with the Dogs at 3:30 p.m. on ESPN2. That still
leaves plenty of time for yard work. (Don't look to the skies for
any excuses: The weather looks good for outdoor chores, too.)
Before you start, check out AllAboutLawns. Included are tips on
mower maintenance (``Keep those blades sharp!''), weed control and
aerating. Also, learn how to pick the right sprinkler and, for
heaven's sake, observe proper mowing patterns!
</P>
<P>
   allaboutlawns.com
</P>
<P>
   Mega-reference site
</P>
<P>
   promises big results
</P>
<P>
   For years, WGST's ``news monster'' stalked the airwaves.
``Godzilla 2000'' was a recent monster at the movies. And then
there's that job-search site, monster.com. So what's the next
creature feature? Try the Factmonster. This mega-reference site for
elementary students combines a user-friendly format with flashy
graphics. Pages are packed with data on everything from dragons and
giants to the latest dinosaur discoveries. The Cool Stuff section
includes the Story of Popcorn and Scooter Mania.
</P>
<P>
   www.factmonster.com
