<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5558 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KEMPNER-GREENBERG08-C     09-07 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEMPNER-GREENBERG08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How baseball stirs the melting pot
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Filmmaker Aviva Kempner has a unique suggestion for people
turned off by Atlanta Braves closer John Rocker's racist comments:
``Throw him flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   No, she's not a Rocker fan, by any means. But having spent more
than 12 years putting together her documentary ``The Life and Times
of Hank Greenberg,'' she knows a little bit about the powers of
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is true in Rocker's case, but (hearing
insults) was a spur for Hank to do better,'' she says during a
recent stop in Atlanta. ``I'm sure Rocker feels that _ `I'm gonna
show you, I'm gonna strike you guys out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Born to immigrant parents in New York, Hank Greenberg was one of
many first-generation Americans who found a sense of national
identity through playing baseball. But he took it a lot further
than most kids, getting signed to the Detroit Tigers, nearly
beating Babe Ruth's single-season home-run record and being chosen
most valuable player twice at two positions. All the while he had
to deal with, on one hand, racist epithets from the crowd and
fellow ballplayers, and, on the other, the heightened expectations
of his fellow Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Detroit,'' Kempner says. ``My dad was an
immigrant Jew. He himself had come to America in the late '20s, and
part of the way he became American was to follow baseball.'' So did
Kempner, who arrived on U.S. shores at age 4. ``I also was an
immigrant who grew to love baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   She sees the same trend _ baseball viewed as a sign of
patriotism and assimilation _ working for different races: ``I've
met Dominicans in New York who follow Sammy Sosa, and the way they
talked about Sammy, they were bursting with pride,'' she says.
``That's the way fans talked about Hank, and still do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempner, a Washington film critic and lecturer, never met
Greenberg. The idea of making a film about his life came to her
when she heard of his death in September 1986, while she was in Los
Angeles presenting her first documentary, ``Partisans of Vilna,''
about Jewish resistance fighters during World War II. She compiled
her new movie by talking to the baseball star's family and friends,
and mixing them with pre-existing interview clips of Greenberg.
Vintage footage of his games and a nostalgic soundtrack of popular
songs of the '30s and '40s fuel the movie, which lacks a
traditional narration.
</P>
<P>
   ``His story is a dramatic story,'' Kempner says of her decision
to dispense with the disembodied voice found in many documentaries.
``You don't need narration.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Greenberg's story seems a natural for the movies, it took
Kempner, 53, more than 12 years to raise enough money to complete
the film. Maybe that's because another little project, Ken Burns'
TV series ``Baseball,'' was also in the running for funding at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   In traveling with her film and speaking to audiences, Kempner
has found ``Life and Times'' has had an especially strong effect on
men. ``A lot of men have come out with tears in their eyes,
crying,'' she says. ``So I decided to change my epitaph. I'm going
to have them put on my epitaph, `She Made Men Cry.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Times
</P>
<P>
   of Hank Greenberg''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   A documentary about baseball player Hank Greenberg. Directed by
Aviva Kempner. Not rated. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
