<SLUG> BC-LEFTEYE-MISSING08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lisa Lopes' vanishing act spurs frenzy
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Post reported Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes missing
Thursday, and a mini-media frenzy erupted, with the likes of TV's
``Inside Edition'' and Rolling Stone magazine trying to chase down
the story.
</P>
<P>
   But the singer's friends in Atlanta weren't worried.
</P>
<P>
   Business partner and longtime friend Ian Burke said he hadn't
seen Lopes _ one third of the Atlanta R&AMP;B trio TLC _ since the
start of Labor Day weekend. And he had no idea why she skipped a
news conference Tuesday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   But he said her ``disappearance'' sounded to him more like
``Lisa Lopes simply being Lisa Lopes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post quoted Lopes' publicist as ``pleading'' with his
client: ``Lisa, if you're reading this, please call us _ we're very
worried about you.'' On Thursday, though, he didn't seem so
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried,'' Matt Shelton told the Journal-Constitution.
``Since she was last seen with Sean (Newman, her boyfriend), I'm
sure the pair of them are somewhere safe and will turn up or make a
grand appearance soon _ as only Sean and Lisa can.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes, of Stone Mountain, Ga., has a reputation as the trio's
most unpredictable member _ she once torched the house of former
Atlanta Falcon Andre Rison _ which undoubtedly fueled the media
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   To her friends, however, this episode was hardly newsworthy.
``She takes these little `sabbaticals' all the time,'' Burke said.
``It's just that most of the time, no one does a story about it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
