<DOCNO> NYT20000907.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-CONFIDENCE09     09-07 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-CONFIDENCE0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumers give mixed signals
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Consumers may not be spending as freely, but their
confidence levels rebounded during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation concerns are easing, and interest rates have peaked
for the year,'' said Roger Tutterow, co-director of Kennesaw
State's Econometric Center, which released its latest metro Atlanta
consumer confidence survey Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of interest rate boosts, only 59 percent of the
survey's 400 respondents expect them to rise in the coming year.
That's a drop from the record level of 73 percent in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A record 87 percent of employed respondents are not worried
about job security. That's 10 percent higher than a year ago in the
same quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the signs are mixed, Tutterow said. Consumers have not
loosened the grip on their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen improvement in buying habits, especially in
big-ticket items,'' he said. ``I though we would see more of a pop
on the buying conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists, including Tutterow, monitor consumer confidence
because spending fuels two-thirds of the country's growth. When
consumers feel good about the economy, they are more likely to
splurge on luxury and big-ticket items, such as major appliances,
new homes and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday outlook is not bright. August retail sales were
stagnant. Federated Department Stores saw its sales rise only about
1.1 percent at stores open a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Retailing analyst Kurt Barnard, of Barnard Retail Trend Report,
said consumers have cut spending since the spring. He forecasts
same-store retail sales growth of 4 percent this holiday season,
down from about 6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers will spend more cautiously than they've spent in a
decade,'' Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer debt on credit cards is $630 billion, almost 10 percent
higher than a year ago, and that could restrain holiday spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennesaw State survey, co-sponsored by the Greater Atlanta
Home Builders Association, is modeled after a national survey by
the University of Michigan. That survey showed a slight decline in
consumer sentiment from the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
