<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5563 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-BETTY08-COX     09-07 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BETTY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waitress, soap opera and hitmen collide in `Nurse Betty's'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renee Zellweger may have the most chuckable chin in show biz.
Plus the most pinchable cheeks and the widest blue eyes. She's a
cherub with sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Her otherworldly sweetness is used to great effect in ``Nurse
Betty,'' a dark-farce fantasy that exists in some cinematic
collision course with ``Being There,'' ``The Wizard of Oz'' and
early Coen brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a long-winded way of saying you've seen bits of it
before, but you've never seen anything quite like it.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dorothy, Betty Sizemore (Zellweger) is a Kansas naif. A
waitress at the local coffee shop, she muddles through her mundane
life and loveless marriage to Del (Aaron Eckhart), a sleazoid car
salesman, by keeping her eye on, well, not the prize but her prized
favorite soap opera, ``A Reason to Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one night, she sees something that sends her over the
psycho-rainbow. She enters a fantasy life in which it is imperative
that she find her long-lost love, Dr. David Ravell. She hops in one
of Del's Buicks and heads for _ where else? _ La-La Land.
</P>
<P>
   Two not-so-small problems. First, the Buick is full of drugs,
and two hitmen _ Charlie (Morgan Freeman) and Wesley (Chris Rock) _
are soon hot on her trail. Second, there is no Dr. Ravell. He's a
character on her soap, played by a self-infatuated actor named
George McCord (Greg Kinnear).
</P>
<P>
   What ensues is a kind of fugue for romantic fantasists. Against
all odds, Betty meets McCord, who mistakes her madness for Method.
As in Method acting. He thinks her delusional behavior is an
extended audition for the show, and he's thrilled by her
commitment. ``I haven't felt this way since I was with Stella Adler
in New York,'' he rhapsodizes.
</P>
<P>
   Betty, naturally, has no problem incorporating McCord/Ravell
into her own private fantasy; she just can't understand why he
spends so little time at the hospital. Meanwhile, Charlie is
beginning to have fantasies of his own _ about Betty as his ideal
woman. Except, of course, that he has to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' is directed by Neil LaBute, best-known for his
corrosive brilliance as the writer-director of ``In the Company of
Men'' and the less successful ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors.'' This
time, LaBute has left the writing to John C. Richards and James
Flamberg, who shared the screenplay prize at Cannes. What he brings
to the table is a gift for character, which, underneath its
convoluted structure, is what ``Nurse Betty'' really is all about.
Who we are, who we think we are, who others think we are, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Zellweger's pixilated performance is the movie's Crazy Glue. If
you don't like her _ you first saw her in ``Jerry Maguire'' _ don't
bother going. She's our tragicomic touchstone, looking for a reason
to love and a reason to live.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the rich supporting cast that makes the movie special.
Rock is rock-solid in a role that asks for more than his bristling
attitude and razor-sharp wit. Kinnear gives shallow charm a
surprising depth. Allison Janney as the soap's producer channels
the acerbic ghost of Eve Arden.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all is Freeman, who brings a courtly elegance to his
killer in cowboy boots. His growing love for Betty is, in its own
demented way, as true as Heathcliffe's for Cathy, and his rapport
with Rock is a thing of beauty. Maybe this performance will be the
one that brings him his long overdue Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Renee Zellweger, Morgan Freeman, Chris Rock and Greg
Kinnear. Directed by Neil LaBute. Rated R for violence and
language. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   48 minutes. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   Good medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
