<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veto by Clinton Is Upheld On Repeal of Estate Tax
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a bill to repeal the federal tax on large estates
failed in an attempt to overturn President Clinton's veto of the
measure, killing the issue for the year in legislative terms but
leaving it very much alive politically. Republicans said they were
eager to take the debate to the campaign trail, where they said it
would attract support from small business owners, farmers and
entrepreneurs. Democrats said they would continue to make their
case that while the tax should be reduced for family-owned farms
and businesses, the measure that was rejected would eat up too much
of the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont Warns of Profit Shortfall
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, the nation's biggest chemical company, warned that
soaring costs for fuel and raw materials, the declining value of
the euro and potentially lower sales would push earnings for the
rest of the year 2 percent to 5 percent below Wall Street
expectations. Shares of DuPont fell $4.88, to $42.13, and other
chemical stocks declined, but many analysts said investors
overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest to Eliminate 13,000 Jobs
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Communications said that it would lay off nearly 13,000
employees, about 18 percent of its work force, and increase capital
spending in an effort to increase efficiency after its $44 billion
acquisition of U S West.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch Internet Company Is Sold
</P>
<P>
   In a race to become the America Online of Europe, Italy's
second-largest Internet service provider, Tiscali, agreed to buy
the Dutch company World Online for $5.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Rebounds After 2-Day Slide
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks rebounded after a two-day downturn while
blue-chip shares fell on earnings warnings. The Nasdaq composite
index rose 85.01 points, or 2.1 percent, to 4,098.35. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 50.77 points, or 0.5 percent, to
11,259.87, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 10.26
points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,502.51.
</P>
<P>
   Koppel Signs 5-Year ABC Contract
</P>
<P>
   Ted Koppel, the anchor of the ABC News ``Nightline'' program
since it made its debut in 1980, has agreed to stay with the
program for the next five years, though he will appear as the
anchor less frequently. Under a five-year contract, Koppel will be
the anchor three nights a week, starting in January. He has also
agreed to be the host of six special weeklong ``Nightline'' series
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler Touches Off Agency Battle
</P>
<P>
   Two giant agency companies _ the Omnicom Group and True North
Communications _ are squaring off in a huge review called by a
major client they share, the DaimlerChrysler Group. Shares of
Omnicom and True North fell, with True North dropping $6.50, or
14.8 percent, to $37.50, and Omnicom sliding $1.75, or 2.1 percent,
to $80.
</P>
<P>
   Post Office and FedEx Discuss Deal
</P>
<P>
   The United States Postal Service and FedEx are discussing a
partnership that would help the post office increase revenue while
giving FedEx a low-cost way to reach millions of residential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup to Miss Forecasts
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup said that its first-quarter profit would miss
estimates because of higher spending intended to increase demand.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream Deal Clears a Hurdle
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's proposed acquisition of VoiceStream Wireless
cleared its first regulatory hurdle, but lawmakers urged the White
House to do more to force the privatization of foreign phone
companies before they are allowed to buy American companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
