<SLUG> BC-BASS-ARASI0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exec quits, is replaced at Bass Hotels division
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thomas Arasi has resigned as president of Bass Hotels
&AMP; Resorts' Atlanta-based Americas division, effective Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Arasi, who was named to the post a year and a half ago, will be
succeeded by John Sweetwood, a veteran marketing executive.
Sweetwood is president of Bass' midscale hotel group for North
America, which includes Holiday Inn Express and Staybridge Suites
by Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will remain on the same path,'' said Sweetwood, who joined
the company five years ago as executive vice president and chief
marketing officer. He said he plans ``to increase the synergies
between the brands to the extent that we have not been able to
achieve to date.''
</P>
<P>
   The move, which surprised many, comes as London-based Bass PLC,
the parent company of Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts, puts greater emphasis
on its hotel business following the sale of its brewing operations.
Bass is eyeing Europe, Asia and Latin America for development.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say one of Sweetwood's strengths is his
marketing background. Prior to joining Bass, he held several
positions at Ralston Purina, including marketing for the Eveready
Battery Division. Under his leadership, Eveready launched the
``Energizer Bunny'' advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the more innovative changes that have occurred in the
lodging industry in recent years have come from nonindustry
people,'' said Mark Woodworth, executive managing director of PKF
Consulting's hospitality research group.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Lister, senior editor of Lodging magazine, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or 15 years ago, I would have said that operations was
probably the most important thing,'' he said. ``Now, marketing is
just as important as anything else. It's like the brand is the
thing now and building brand loyalty and awareness are the
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership of the Americas division is important because the
bulk of Bass hotels are in the region, which includes the United
States, Canada, Mexico and South America. Its flagship brand _
Holiday Inn _ has its greatest presence in the Americas,
particularly the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americas is the absolute crux,'' Lister said.
</P>
<P>
   Arasi is leaving to start his own business, but he will remain a
consultant for the company. Arasi plans to form a holding company,
based in Atlanta, that will be involved in hotel investment,
development, finance and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Arasi said he is leaving now ``because there is so much change
and volatility in the global hotel industry. I felt that this was
an opportunity for me to use my experience, to use my relationship,
my industry presence and capital to create opportunities for myself
and investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
