<HEADLINE>
ON THE STREETS OF BALTIMORE THE WORD ON MEDICARE IS `EXPAND' NOT
`OVERHAUL' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The shuffleboard players here at the John T. Booth
Senior Center all have a horror story or two about how they, a
friend or a relative has been saddled with crushing prescription
drug costs. And so they are thrilled that the issue has moved
center stage in the presidential contest between Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   They did not claim to understand the details of the two
candidates' competing plans to create prescription drug policies
through the Medicare system. But on one issue they were in
complete, clear agreement: They do not want the system
significantly changed. Expand it, make it more generous, but do not
overhaul it, they all said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they change it, they'll just foul it all up,'' said Helen
Mirabile, 80, a retired sewing machine operator, as her friends
nodded in ascent.
</P>
<P>
   If there was one political lesson to be gleaned from a 90-minute
conversation Thursday morning with 15 retirees in this
working-class neighborhood of modest row houses, it might be this:
Bush could have trouble selling his plan for redesigning the
Medicare system among the very people who depend on the system now.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Tuesday, Bush called for retooling the
35-year-old system to encourage the use of private insurance plans,
some of which would provide prescription drug coverage. By breeding
competition among private insurers for the Medicare market, Bush
contends, costs will be lowered and elderly people will have more
choices.. To help people with drug costs, he proposed subsidizing
the premiums of the low-income elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also vowed to modernize what he called a ``rigid and
sluggish and slow to change'' Medicare bureaucracy that he said
increasingly poses ``a hazard to your health.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the elderly gathered here Thursday, nary a bad word
about Medicare could be heard. A few people recalled a bureaucratic
error here or there. Others bemoaned cuts in services or rising
premiums. But all praised the system for providing services they
said they could never have afforded on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Medicare has been a godsend,'' said Florence Barnes,
81, a former city employee.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bush's proposal for prescription drugs sounded
appealing to members of the group, even though most of them already
have supplementary insurance plans that cover most of their
prescription drug costs. But his attacks on the bureaucracy did not
resonate with them. Only one woman could offer a complaint: She had
been improperly billed for an X-ray. But after several phone calls,
the matter was worked out to her satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   And most of them found his proposal to increase the role of
private insurance companies troubling. Though only a few of them
are enrolled in health maintenance organizations through Medicare,
almost all of them had viscerally negative reactions to the idea of
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's proposal would make participation in private health
plans voluntary, its goal would be to encourage more people to join
HMOs, which now cover 6.2 million, or 16 percent, of the 39 million
Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Rose D'Ambrosio, an 86-year-old retired federal employee,
offered the kind of story that many people in the room said they
had heard before. Her daughter's HMO, she said, took several months
to approve major treatment for cancer, creating all kinds of
anxieties for the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``She needs more operations,'' D'Ambrosio said. ``They have to
refer you to a doctor. And it takes a long time. A person who has
these types of decisions needs care right now, not six months from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other people said they did not like the idea that
managed care companies could tell them to use different doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not only a regular internist,'' said Syd Goldfield, 71,
``I have a urologist. I have a bone doctor. I have an eye doctor.
Etc., etc. I know who I am seeing, and I like them. And I don't
like to have a strange doctor working on me for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Hemmeter, 71, said, ``Some people have the same doctors
for like 15, 20, 30 years and they aren't going to switch and go to
another doctor after they've been with that doctor for that many
years.'' Several people also questioned whether Bush's plan for
greater competition was realistic, noting that several HMOs, some
in the Baltimore area, have pulled out of the Medicare system in
recent years, citing low reimbursement rates from the government.
</P>
<P>
   The group, most of whom said they were Democrats, seemed more
comfortable with Gore's plan, though it would cost more than
Bush's: $253 billion over 10 years compared with $198 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That plan would create a voluntary prescription drug benefit
inside the traditional Medicare program. Beneficiaries would pay
monthly premiums, but like Bush, Gore would subsidize coverage for
the low-income elderly. Unlike Bush, the vice president would offer
a uniform, standardized package with the same premiums for most
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   To many people in the group, having more choices among health
plans was not their major concern; reliability was. And to them, a
system run by the government rather than by private managed care
companies seemed like the better alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want the best, you have to pay,'' said Hemmeter,
referring to Gore's more expensive plan. ``And I want the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The group praised both candidates for focusing on high
prescription drug costs. All knew people who have struggled to get
by without prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmeter, for example, said her sister's insurance plan does not
cover the cost of drugs to control her cholesterol and blood
pressure, which run about $170 a month. Consequently, she said, her
sister takes only half the prescribed dosages.
</P>
<P>
   Several people in the group said Gore's populist attacks on
``big drug companies'' struck a chord with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other countries have price controls and get their drugs
cheaper,'' said Eulalia Pereira, 76, a retired federal employee.
``We should too.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Melton, 71, a retired nurse, said she often saw patients
who were ill because they could not afford prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are low-income families who have to make a decision
about whether they are going to eat or buy medication,'' she said.
``That's really sad. There should be some kind of prescription
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
