<HEADER>
A5569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DUPONT-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      09-07 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DuPONT SHARES DROP 10 PERCENT AS COMPANY WARNS ON PROFITS  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DuPont Co., the nation's biggest chemical company, warned
Thursday that soaring costs for fuel and raw materials, the
declining value of the euro and potentially lower sales would push
earnings for the rest of the year below Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent shares of DuPont and those of other big chemical
companies into a tailspin, but many analysts said investors
overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont said its earnings for the year were likely to come in 2
percent to 5 percent below expectations, at $2.85 to $2.95 a share
instead of the $3.01 that analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   But DuPont executives said that they still expected earnings for
the year to be 10 percent to 14 percent above results for the
previous year and that 2001 earnings were likely to increase at
least 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those projections, shares of DuPont fell $4.88, to
$42.13, their lowest point in four years as more than 17.5 million
shares changed hands compared with a daily average of 2.7 million.
Shares of Dow Chemical Co. fell $1.88, to $25.56, while Rohm &AMP; Hass
fell $2, to $29.38, and Eastman Chemical Co. dropped $1.19, to
$45.31. Shares of the European chemical companies BASF and Bayer
also fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market oversold the stock today,'' said Frank J.
Mitsch, a senior chemical industry analyst at Chase H&AMP;Q. ``I think
this is an excellent buying opportunity for long-term investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need to put this into perspective,'' he added, ``and
consider that at the beginning of the year, DuPont's expectation
for 2000 was $2.96. Then they saw some positive trends and adjusted
upwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander A. Hittle, a chemical industry analyst at A.G.
Edwards, said he, too, was ``a little surprised that the stock
pulled back as much as it did.''
</P>
<P>
   A.G. Edwards has recommended that investors maintain or hold
their positions in DuPont. But Hittle said: ``We're being a little
bit greedy. We'd like to pick it up in the high 30's.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the drop in DuPont's expectations, Hittle said: ``It's a
bunch of things that DuPont didn't really have control over. And
we've already seen the chemical companies pull back on exactly this
collection of concerns about high raw material prices and slowing
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitsch said investors, wary of a possible further slowing in the
economy and its effect on sales, clearly took the warning as ``a
signal for them to lighten up their portfolios.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``We're now seeing DuPont stock trading at levels
close to where it was trading in 1996 and, I can guarantee you,
it's a much better company today than it was in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have also been encouraged by DuPont's earlier
announcement that it planned to buy back up to 5 percent of its
outstanding stock, which would help to maintain share prices, if
not raise them.
</P>
<P>
   A.G. Edwards has a buy rating on Dow Chemical. ``Dow has been
more oversold than DuPont,'' Hittle said, ``and Dow pays a bit
better dividend. It's really the same bet as DuPont, that global
economics will stay strong and that oil prices will cool off.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call, Gary M. Pfeiffer, DuPont's chief financial
officer, said the company expected to achieve its new goal of more
than 10 percent in earnings growth this year by increasing prices,
cutting operating costs and being ``more prudent and selective in
use of capital.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as July, DuPont increased its earnings expectations
as cost cutting appeared to be running ahead of schedule and sales
were up. But oil prices have jumped 20 percent since then, the
company said, while United States natural gas costs have leaped 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont makes products like auto paints and lacquers, fabrics and
health care products. Crude oil and natural gas make up 40 percent
of the company's raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsch estimated that 30 percent of the company's sales were in
Europe, making it particularly vulnerable to the euro's recent
slide against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   In the conference call, DuPont executives said they saw some
weakening in volume from customers in the clothing business. They
also said sales would be hurt by the shutdown of some Ford truck
plants, which were closed for two weeks to make more tires
available to replace those recalled by Bridgestone/Firestone last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Hittle said DuPont had been trying to put itself on a path of
steady growth and to step away from the traditional volatility of
the chemical industry, partly by diversifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``DuPont has made a substantial effort to recast itself and move
into the life sciences and away from the commodity chemical
business,'' Hittle said. ``This announcement today reminds us that
the life science vision of the company isn't mature and that for
the time being this is still a chemical company, subject to the
kinds of macroeconomic factors that make chemicals a difficult
business.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
