<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.08.00
</P>
<P>
   AmEx debuts card numbers just for Web sales
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Steel hits Web as Atlantic Station
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's gets bragging rights over Home Depot
</P>
<P>
   Grocer Peapod leaves 4 cities, buys into 2 more
</P>
<P>
   Priceline adds wireless phone service, term life
</P>
<P>
   CYBER CREDIT CARDS: Still nervous about blasting your credit
card number through cyberspace? Through a new American Express
program, you'll be able to buy online without transmitting your
actual account number. The company's ``Private Payments'' program
assigns a random number to each online purchase, then the number
expires after the transaction. The service begins next month.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTIC STEEL ONLINE: The Atlantic Steel redevelopment team has
given its monster mixed-use project in Midtown a name, Atlantic
Station, and launched a Web site. Developers Jim Jacoby and Charles
Brown say the name ``suggests not only our design focused on
transit but on our intent to provide a station in life for the
businesses, families and consumers who will enjoy the community of
services offered at the site.'' The site was launched to inform
Atlantans on the progress of the $2 billion, 10-year project.
</P>
<P>
   _ Melissa Turner
</P>
<P>
   www.atlanticstation.com
</P>
<P>
   LOWE'S GETS FORBES PICK: Lowe's Cos., the No. 2 home improvement
retailer behind you-know-who, got a nod from the Web surfers at
Forbes.com. In a new ``Best of the Web'' issue, reviewers picked
www.lowes.com over rival Home Depot's site. ``We may like shopping
at Home Depot better, but we found Lowe's Web site a better source
of reference,'' Forbes said. Both Lowe's and Home Depot
(www.homedepot.com) have a warehouse full of how-to info on their
sites but have only scratched the surface of online product sales.
(Home Depot is testing an online store for Las Vegas customers
right now.)
</P>
<P>
   www.forbesbest.com/index.asp
</P>
<P>
   CHECKING OUT, PAYING UP: Online grocer Peapod Inc., still
consolidating after rapid expansion nearly forced it into
bankruptcy, said Thursday it's ending service in Houston, Dallas,
Austin, Texas, and Columbus, Ohio. It also announced the $12
million purchase of Streamline.com's operations in greater Chicago
and Washington. The Skokie, Ill.-based cybergrocer said Thursday
the moves will speed its entry into the Baltimore-Washington
market.
</P>
<P>
   MORE FROM PRICELINE: Priceline.com Inc., the bidding service for
items such as airline tickets and hotel rooms, said it will add
wireless-telephone service and term life insurance to build sales.
The items will become available in three to six months,
Priceline.com Chief Executive Daniel Schulman said.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide study on the Web
</P>
<P>
   Europeans are getting more plugged into the Net, according to a
study by Nielsen/NetRatings. Nielsen studied 20 countries in
Europe, Asia and North America. Not surprisingly, the largest
Internet populations reside in the United States and Japan. About
82 million Europeans have access to the Internet from a home
computer. That's about one household in five. In Europe, the
British bought the most online _ about 64 percent of consumers who
researched products made a purchase in the past six months.
</P>
