u i BC-U.N.-MIDEAST-1STLD-WR     09-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-MIDEAST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST PEACE MAY NOT COME DURING CLINTON'S TENURE, U.S. OFFICIALS
FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS lede to refine language; 4th graf to add `Christians'; adds
new 6th graf; deletes 9th graf in orig., bgng `Since they
arrived...,' to delete info now in 6th graf; in graf bgng `During
the eight...' adds background info on Clinton and Mideast peace
talks)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT42 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a sustained effort to seal a Middle East peace accord, the
White House has begun to sense that a solution is slipping away,
and senior administration officials say they are preparing
themselves for the likelihood that a deal will not come during
President Clinton's time in office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not about to abruptly give up what has been one of
his most cherished and hard-fought foreign policy goals, but senior
administration officials said that the momentum created at the Camp
David summit meeting in July had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met this week with both Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak as well as with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, while
the men were in New York for the U.N. Millennium Summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But senior administration officials said that Arafat had failed
to give sufficient assurances that he would agree to a solution on
Jerusalem and, in particular, on sovereignty over the sites there
that are sacred to Muslims, Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   In public statements on Thursday, Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright kept open the possibility of future meetings.
But Clinton suggested that he would not meet again this week with
Arafat or Barak. And in private, assessments were even gloomier.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Barak nor Arafat have threatened to walk away. They have
both pledged to keep going, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration is not prepared to keep talks between
Israel and the Palestinians going for the sake of talking, a senior
official said. ``It's not our job to give it life support if it's
not breathing,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand we heard some movement, but not sufficient and
not with the kind of precision that we need to hear that looks
anything like a process that goes to closure,'' the official added.
</P>
<P>
   During the eight years of his presidency, Clinton has spent more
time than any other president talking and negotiating with the
Israelis and the Palestinians in search of a final peace agreement.
He oversaw the momentous signing ceremony for the Oslo peace
accords in 1993 at the White House, where he extended his arms to
ensure a handshake between Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin. And the president also helped broker the accords
reached after great pain at Wye Plantation in 1998. But on
Thursday, even Clinton sounded uncertain about future steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there will be any more meetings while we are
here,'' Clinton said before meeting Thursday morning with the South
Korean president, Kim Dae-jung. ``We'll see where we are and
whether anything else can be done while we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said at a news conference, ``The truth is, just look at
the calendar, and there is not a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Clinton's senior advisers are beginning to
talk about their achievements at Camp David as possibly being
material for another administration to build on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Camp David there was a huge iceberg, we sent an
icebreaker through it, and we cracked it open 100 different ways _
refugees, Jerusalem, security, borders,'' said Clinton's national
security adviser, Sandy Berger. ``The good news is that this is no
longer just an iceberg, it's 100 pieces of ice. Can this be
reassembled into something like a bridge _ I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official put a best-face on a deteriorating situation
that came after so much work. ``It's not entirely pass-fail,'' he
said of Clinton's Middle East negotiations. ``The best thing is to
get an agreement. But we are not going back to where we were.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Albright's emphasis on the shortage of time was prompted by
several factors.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is the belief within the administration that the
longer the two sides remain apart, the harder it becomes to put the
pieces back together.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official said that confidence was being lost,
not unlike the drift that occurred after talks between Israel and
Syria ended in Shephardstown, Va., earlier this year and were never
reconvened.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, Barak must start to remedy his weak political
situation at home by early next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli parliament returns to session at the end of October,
and if a peace agreement looks impossible, Barak wants to spend
most of October reconfiguring his government by joining with the
rightist Likud Party and others.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Clinton made conceptual breakthroughs at Camp David,
there was not enough time to delve into the finer details of issues
like religion and national identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis, this issue may have too far to go _
from 2000 years of history and 52 years of not really coming to
grips with shared aspirations,'' one senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   The main obstacle remained the Temple Mount, known to Arabs as
Haram al-Sharif, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has been saying since the Camp David talks in July, when
the question of sovereignty over the site was raised, that the
temple does not exist, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   By insisting that what the Jews consider to be the most sacred
of their holy sites was not even a Jewish place, Arafat was denying
a basic respect to his main negotiating partner, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can't be solved by denying the beliefs of one of the
great religions,'' said the official.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, the Temple Mount is the most sacred of all places, the
site, according to Jewish beliefs, of the First and Second Temples
destroyed by the Babylonians and the Romans. Among the Muslims, the
site and its two Muslim shrines, the Dome of the Rock and Al Aksa,
are among the holiest of all Islamic sites.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, Barak tentatively agreed to the notion that the
Palestinians could be granted religious sovereignty over the mount,
with the Israelis retaining political sovereignty. But after
leaving Camp David, Barak made clear that nothing was agreed to
until every aspect of the peace deal was in place.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at the United Nations on Thursday, Barak,
who has come under fire at home for conceding too much at Camp
David, reiterated that Jerusalem and the Temple Mount ``are the
cornerstone of Jewish identity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No Israeli prime minister will ever be able to sign a document
that gives up sovereignty to the Temple Mount to the
Palestinians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak then went on to chide Arafat for his attitude toward the
Temple Mount and toward the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the time, the prime minister said, for Arafat ``to
rewrite the history of the three monotheistic religions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The very word of Temple Mount tells the real story of Temple
Mount,'' Barak said. When Jesus Christ walked in Jerusalem, Barak
said, he did not see Christian churches or Islamic mosques. ``What
he could see is the Jewish Temple.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Barak went on to criticize the Palestinian for
inflexibility, saying he was not willing ``to take Clinton's ideas
as the basis of negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The fairly harsh words about Arafat appeared to reflect the
Israeli leader's increasing frustration with what he considers the
Palestinian's refusal to seriously negotiate. In private meetings
with American Jews since he has been in the United States, Barak
has said that he cannot give more in negotiations. He has also been
pessimistic about the chances for a peace deal, describing them as
well under 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, the administration will keep working at
the issues, senior U.S. officials said. They will try to encourage
Arab leaders to take more initiative in moving Arafat toward a
solution on Jerusalem and the Temple Mount, they added.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptians have been helpful in recent weeks in devising some
ideas, including the notion of ``divine sovereignty'' for the
Temple Mount, meaning that the site belonged to God. But a senior
U.S. official said that the Egyptians and other Arab countries have
only said that they will support Arafat in whatever he chooses to
do. They stopped short of recommending solutions to him, the
official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
