<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-INTERNET-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN-DUTCH DEAL WILL CREATE INTERNET GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a race to become the America Online of Europe,
Italy's second-largest Internet service provider, Tiscali SpA, said
Thursday that it had agreed to acquire the troubled Dutch Internet
company World Online NV for $5.1 billion in stock. The move
catapults the combined concern into the second-largest Internet
service provider in Europe behind T-Online, a unit of Deutsche
Telekom of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the United States, where the Internet access business
has been mainly dominated by one company, America Online, the
Internet service provider business in Europe is much more
fractured. And for most Internet service providers in Europe,
making money off of providing Internet access has so far proved to
be a difficult task. Most access providers rely on e-commerce and
advertising from their home pages, or portals, to provide the real
revenues, not access charges.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement that Tiscali would acquire World Online
marks the end of protracted negotiations between the two companies
that have lasted for more than two months. World Online had been
seeking a partner since the beginning of the summer as its stock
price has continued to suffer, hovering around 15 euros, or about
one-third of the price of the company's initial public offering in
March. Tiscali's offer of about .44 of its shares for every World
online share, values the acquisition target at about 20 euros, or
about a 27 percent premium over the companys current stock price.
</P>
<P>
   While the combined company will have 3.5 million subscribers, it
remains substantially smaller than T-Online, which has more than 6
million Internet users. Nonetheless, the deal will give the
enlarged Tiscali 1.6 billion euros in cash and a market value of
about 12.5 billion, allowing it to make further acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   For World Online, the deal begins a new chapter in the life of
the Dutch online business that was seemingly scarred back in March
when regulators said they would launch an investigation into the
company's controversial initial public offering. A group of
shareholders plan to sue the company, alleging that World Online's
chairwoman at the time, Nina Brink, acted improperly by not fully
disclosing that she sold her stock before the offering. The value
of the company fell to 3.8 billion euros, down from 12 billion
euros when shares of World Online were first offered to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Brink resigned from World Online on April 14, about a month
after the company went public.
</P>
<P>
   Renato Soru, Tiscali's founder, will be chairman of the combined
company. Jim Kinsella, a former chief executive of MSNBC.com, who
took over World Online when Brink resigned, will be chief executive
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Tiscali was advised by UBS Warburg, NM Rothschild &AMP; Sons Ltd.,
Rothschild Italia SpA and Schroder Salomon Smith Barney. Goldman
Sachs International, which helped manage World Online's IPO, and
Merrill Lynch International advised World Online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
