<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI &LR;      09-07 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES PIPELINE SAFETY BILL, BUT CRITICS REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beating the clock but not every critic, the Senate
Thursday night approved sweeping legislation designed to make
pipelines safer and their corporate parents more accountable to
regulators and the public.
</P>
<P>
   The approval, by unanimous consent, gave Washington state
lawmakers a victory on one of their highest priorities. Even so,
the issue is far from settled. The bill now goes to the House which
has shown less zeal in passing a pipeline safety bill and where
opposition remains strong. That could create a difficult mix in a
Congress that has only 21 working days left.
</P>
<P>
   Industry spokesmen complained the bill is too harsh, while
consumer advocates say it doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``we are obviously extremely pleased the Senate has taken
some action,'' said Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., who is supporting
tougher safety standards than those approved by the Senate. ``They
have moved the ball in the Senate and that's extremely important to
put pressure on the House.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill had been the subject of furious
behind-the-scenes negotiations for weeks by supporters who were
mindful that if it did not pass this week it would likely get
buried under more pressing legislation. The bill came to the floor
after Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., promised Majority Leader Trent
Lott that it would pass quickly, without debate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill stemmed from the 1999 gasoline pipeline leak and
explosion in Bellingham, Wash., that killed two 10-year-old boys
and an 18-year man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really pleased. This is a significant step forward,''
said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash. ``Did we get everything we wanted?
No. You never do in the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill brings much needed reform,'' Gorton said from the
Senate floor. ``It is a marked improvement from the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the bill would require more frequent and
thorough pipeline inspections, better training for operators and
more timely and detailed information about the location and
condition of pipelines to be given to the public. It also allows
regulators and the courts to impose bigger fines for violations and
calls for more money to be spent developing technology to better
inspect pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   It would give the transportation secretary authority to shut
down a pipeline indefinitely in the event of an ``imminent hazard''
and it lowers the threshold for reporting a pipeline spill from
2,100 gallons to five gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state lawmakers sought those steps in the wake of
last year's accident in Bellingham when a pipeline owned by Olympic
Pipe Line Co. ruptured, dumping 229,000 gallons of gasoline into
Whatcom Creek. A spark touched off a firestorm that killed Wade
King and Stephen Tsiorvas, both 10, and Liam Wood, 18.
</P>
<P>
   The accident stunned the community and prompted Congress to look
seriously at weaknesses in how pipelines are inspected, operated
and regulated. That concern was underscored last month when a
natural gas pipeline in New Mexico exploded, killing 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   Murray reminded her colleagues of that ``much darker day'' in
Bellingham in a speech just before the bill passed. ``For too long,
communities across the country in tragedy after tragedy have felt
the impact of our nation's inadequate pipeline safety standards.
Today, the Senate has responded with a strong bill that will help
make pipelines safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the step forward, critics remain. Industry lobbyists
argue that the bill goes too far and the cost of complying with the
new requirements will be high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate bill is a tough bill and there's a lot of stuff in
there we're not fond of,'' said Gay Friedman, senior vice president
for legislative affairs for the Interstate Natural Gas Association
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest objections is a whistle-blower provision and
another that calls for the creation of a citizen advisory committee
similar to the one Washington Gov. Gary Locke is assembling.
</P>
<P>
   Such committees, said Benjamin Cooper, executive director of the
Association of Oil Pipelines, a trade group, will require the
industry to spend considerable time educating the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have do a lot more to explain ourselves to a
lot more people'' he said. ``We're not going to get away with
simply putting out a glossy press release.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never been a fan of these citizen advisory
committees,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   One the other hand, some safety advocates said the bill wasn't
tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is vitally important we pass a bill with teeth. We would be
doing a grave disservice to the men, women and children who have
lost their lives in pipeline accidents if all that came out of
their deaths was a weak piece of political posturing,'' said Rep.
Jack Metcalf, R-Wash., whose district includes Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Dalen, the mother of Stephen Tsiorvas, said she would
have liked a stronger bill, likening negotiations to a parent who
has to deal with an ``errant'' child.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't ask the child, what do you want?'' she said in an
interview. ``You put your foot down. We need to put our foot down
because, like an errant child, the oil and natural gas industry is
going to try to pull in as many dollars as they can with as little
legislation as possible tying their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all hoping the House strengthens the bill, pays
attention to what I believe is a rising consciousness among their
constituents. I don't understand what the hangup is. Obviously,
something powerful must be done or more will die.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank King, whose son, Wade, was killing in the Bellingham
fireball, was more emphatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing I would like better than to have my quiet,
happy, rather apathetic life back,'' he said. ``I don't have that.
Right now, to the Senate, my son is a statistic. I'm not going to
allow Wade King, Stephen Tsiorvas and Liam Wood to be just a
statistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely disappointed in the bill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
