<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-AD-CO     09-07 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GIANTS VIE AS DAIMLERCHRYSLER CONDUCTS ASSIGNMENT
REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The battle lines are already being drawn in one of
the biggest confrontations in Madison Avenue history.
</P>
<P>
   Two giant agency companies _ Omnicom Group and True North
Communications _ are squaring off in a huge review unexpectedly
called by a major client they share, the DaimlerChrysler Group unit
of DaimlerChrysler AG. The company is undertaking a review for
assignments with spending estimated at $1.3 billion, out of a total
spent last year of $1.5 billion. The work is now divided between
the Southfield, Mich., offices of BBDO Worldwide, part of Omnicom,
and FCB Worldwide, part of True North.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives representing both sides of what is already being
called the shootout in Southfield have taken the unusual step of
issuing statements that aggressively welcomed the review; each
confidently predicted his side would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of us will be right,'' said Allen Rosenshine, chairman and
chief executive at BBDO Worldwide in New York. Asked in what his
optimism about BBDO's chances was rooted, he replied, ``In
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   His competitor, David Bell, chairman and chief executive at True
North in Chicago, said: ``This is an opportunity for us to take
them out, and that's exactly how we're approaching it. What we will
be doing is what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The review, which is likely to end with the DaimlerChrysler
Group assignments for creative and media duties consolidated at a
single shop, is indicative of the ferment roiling agencies as
restless clients seek more efficient and effective campaigns.
Indeed, Omnicom and True North figured in other big decisions
yesterday involving another blue-chip advertiser, the Kraft Foods
unit of Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a merger of the magnitude of the one that created
DaimlerChrysler takes place,'' Rosenshine said, referring to the
acquisition by Daimler-Benz of Chrysler Corp., which now operates
under the DaimlerChrysler Group name, ``it is not a shock to us''
that the merged company would intensify efforts ``to provide cost
savings.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Rosenshine and Bell did not prevent a decline in
the prices of shares of Omnicom and True North traded Thursday on
the New York Stock Exchange. True North's tumble was steeper, down
14.8 percent, or $6.50, to $37.50 versus 2.1 percent, or $1.75, to
$80, for Omnicom. Analysts who follow agency industry stocks
attributed that disparate performance to the fact that almost all
the True North DaimlerChrysler accounts are part of the review,
compared with fewer of Omnicom's.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts lowered their ratings of True North stock as a
result of the review. They said a larger percentage of total True
North revenue compared with Omnicom comes from the assignments in
review, about 9 percent versus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If True North lost the $140 million in annual revenue from the
automaker, it ``could wipe out most of the company's organic growth
for one year,'' said Michael J. Russell Jr., an analyst at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter in New York who reduced his rating of True
North to neutral from strong buy. (He maintained a strong buy on
Omnicom.)
</P>
<P>
   Rosenshine said ``it's fair to say'' on a total percentage basis
that ``True North has `more to lose.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would classify the stock market reaction as unusually
rational,'' he added, chuckling. ``Not exuberant, but rational.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, for his part, said: ``We are very confident. We think we
bring an enormous amount of weight to tilt the scale in our favor
before the shootout.'' A decision is expected in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The battle began late Wednesday afternoon when the
DaimlerChrysler Group announced the review, which involves the
assignments to create national and regional-dealer general market
campaigns for the cars, trucks, minivans and sport utility vehicles
sold under the Chrysler, Dodge and Jeep brand names as well as the
DaimlerChrysler Group corporate image account.
</P>
<P>
   The BBDO Southfield office handles the Dodge work, with spending
last year of $651.9 million, according to Competitive Media
Reporting in New York, a unit of Taylor Nelson Sofres. The FCB
Southfield office handles the rest of the assignments, which
include Chrysler, $251.9 million; Jeep, $277.2 million; and
corporate, $67.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the review are the media planning and buying
duties now consolidated at a BBDO sibling, PentaCom in Troy, Mich.
If FCB was to best BBDO, those duties would presumably be shifted
to an FCB operation now dedicated to international media buying for
DaimlerChrysler, called the DaimlerChrysler Media Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Media Alliance could take over PentaCom, just as in 1993
a FCB predecessor, Bozell Worldwide, took over the Jeep creative
assignment from the Southfield office of Campbell Mithun.
</P>
<P>
   Excluded from the review are assignments handled by Omnicom
agencies like the creative duties for Mercedes-Benz, at Merkley
Newman Harty in New York, with spending estimated at $115.1
million, and so-called customer relationship management programs,
at InterOne Marketing in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting spirits at True North as the shootout began was word
that Kraft had shifted the creative duties for Jell-O gelatin,
pudding and snacks to the New York office of FCB from the New York
office of Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising. Spending last year was
estimated at $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   FCB adds Jell-O to Kraft creative assignments that include Cool
Whip, DiGiorno Pizza and Kraft macaroni and cheese dinners. Y&AMP;R
Advertising, which keeps Kraft creative tasks for brands like
Crystal Light soft drink mix and Toblerone chocolate, had created
Jell-O campaigns since 1926. The agency developed Jell-O's
sponsorships of radio and television series like ``The Jack Benny
Program'' and ``The Aldrich Family,'' hired endorsers like Bill
Cosby and created the familiar ``J-E-L-L-O'' jingle and slogans
like ``There's always room for Jell-O.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no more room for Jell-O at Y&AMP;R Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Kraft confirmed reports in Advertising Age and
Adweek that it would review its media planning and buying
assignments in the United States and Canada, to consolidate those
tasks for brands with spending estimated at $800 million. Those
assignments are now divided among the media agencies allied with
the Kraft creative agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Knuth, a Kraft spokeswoman in Northfield, Ill., identified
the participants as: MindShare, part of the WPP Group; Optimum
Media Direction, part of Omnicom; the Starcom MediaVest Group, part
of the B Com3 Group; and TN Media, part of True North.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve its goals of ``operational efficiencies'' and ``a
quicker, more nimble response to marketplace opportunities,'' she
said, Kraft may consolidate the duties at one shop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
