<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GLOBAL-WARMING-HNS &LR;      09-07 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-WARMING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Critics of global warming treaty see hopeless battle for
ratification
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BILL DAWSON and TODD ACKERMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A day after President Clinton's top science adviser
expressed hope that a political consensus might be achievable on
global warming, two prominent critics threw cold water on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Nebraska, and former U.S. diplomat
Richard R. Burt told a Rice University audience Thursday that a
worldwide treaty to reduce pollutants blamed for global warming
still faces an insurmountable battle in the Senate. Hagel had been
one of the treaty's most vocal critics when the world's nations
signed it in Kyoto, Japan nearly three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and vice president have refused to send (the
treaty) to the Senate for ratification because they know it has
little support and would be overwhelmingly rejected,'' Hagel said
via teleconference at Rice's James A. Baker III Institute for
Public Policy. ``There are not now, nor do I anticipate there
being, 67 votes in the U.S. Senate to approve the ratification of
the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Burt, who was ambassador to Germany in the Reagan
administration, earlier in the day also said the treaty, the Kyoto
Accord, remains too flawed to win ratification. A worldwide
conference to finalize the accord is scheduled for November in the
Netherlands, but even if the world's nations there agree on a plan,
it would still have to be adopted by individual governments.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Lane, director of the Clinton administration's Office of
Science and Technology Policy, said Wednesday at Rice that he has
detected ``real movement'' among previously skeptical congressmen
that global warming poses a ``real threat'' to the future. Still,
Lane said he knew of no plans by the administration to submit the
plan for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The accord would require the United States to reduce greenhouse
gas emissions 7 percent below 1990 levels by 2008-2012, a reduction
that Hagel said would cause catastrophic consequences to the U.S.
economy. Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush opposes
the treaty for that reason; Democratic presidential candidate Al
Gore traveled to Kyoto in 1997 to help negotiate the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   If Hagel and Burt remained skeptical about global warming, some
others at the Baker Institute conference did not. During a panel
discussion, a Texas A&AMP;M University researcher said his recent study
of temperature changes during the past 1,000 years has convinced
him that human-caused global warming is already occurring.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Crowley, an oceanography professor who specializes in
research on climate conditions of the past, said he was surprised
by the result of this study, which was published in July in the
journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Crowley said, his analysis of temperature changes
in the Northern Hemisphere during the last millennium provides ``a
compelling indication'' that natural variation accounts for only a
small part of the warming trend observed in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   This recent warming can only be explained as a result of
humanity's increasing introduction of ``greenhouse gases'' to the
atmosphere, he said. The principal gas is carbon dioxide, which is
emitted during the burning of fossil fuels and also increases as a
result of deforestation.
</P>
<P>
   Using evidence from indicators of past climate conditions,
including ice cores and tree rings, Crowley reached two basic
conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   First, the warming of the past century was unprecedented in the
past 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a climate model featuring two natural climate influences
_ fluctuations in volcanic activity and solar radiation _ explains
much of the temperature variation between the years 1000 and 1850,
but only about 25 percent of the temperature increase of the last
100 years.
</P>
<P>
   If the same temperature increase continues with a
``business-as-usual'' introduction of more ``greenhouse gases'' to
the atmosphere, the earth will be as warm by the late 21st century
as it was at any time in the last 400,000 years, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Burt said the Kyoto treaty has numerous problems,
including the absence of mechanisms to ensure compliance. A chief
negotiator in strategic arms reductions talks with the former
Soviet Union, Burt said a similar lack of mechanism would be
regarded as ``fatal'' to an arms-control pact.
</P>
<P>
   International agencies don't have the ability to carry out the
climate accord effectively, he said. Even if they could do so, he
charged, many in the United States would resent giving up national
authority to these world organizations.
</P>
<P>
   According to a conference biography, Burt has been ``involved in
several diverse, international business corporations'' for the past
10 years, including steel manufacturing, newspapers and information
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the Rice conference include two utility companies,
Carolina Power and Light Service and Southern Company Services, and
ExxonMobil. Before merging to become the world's largest oil
company, both Exxon and Mobil challenged scientific findings
underlying concerns about global warming and disputed the need for
mandates like those in the Kyoto treaty to reduce greenhouse
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
