u k BC-DEATH0908-COX     09-07 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death and dying draws media attention
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Adventure lover Roxann Starr of Austin is
planning her next trip. When she gets there, she'll be doing back
flips and cartwheels. She'll dance and sing. Her body, she says,
will soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be totally amazing and incredible,''
Starr said. ``It's going to be a hundred times better than the best
sex I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, 41, laughs with no trace of irony. Her friends guffaw.
She is talking about her death, and she is doing it with the same
irreverent humor that has defined her life. Starr is looking
forward to leaving a body imprisoned by ALS _ amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Since her terminal diagnosis in 1997, she has had the time to
plan a death that matches the way she has lived: joyful, fearless,
surrounded by the people she loves. How we die in America _ a topic
most people avoid _ is starting to get attention. It will be
explored in a public TV series that starts Sunday. The program
already has triggered elaborate plans to hold death and dying
discussions in communities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is expected to die with little or no pain because she is
in hospice, a program that treats the terminally ill with narcotics
and provides nurses to keep patients in their homes. Hospice may
not be for everyone, but more people are choosing it, and more
people will hear about it soon.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization reports
that hospice programs served at least 700,000 patients last year,
up from 540,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Starr will have ``a good death,'' a term gaining currency as
more people question whether they want to spend their last days in
a hospital, tethered to machines, using technology to the utmost.
</P>
<P>
   When surveyed, most Americans say they don't want a high-tech
death; they want to die at home with loved ones nearby. But the
vast majority die in a hospital, often unconscious and alone, said
Chuck Meyer, chaplain and vice president for operations at St.
David's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and others think the country is ready for a dialogue on
death and dying. Broadcast journalist Bill Moyers is launching the
discussion with a four-part PBS series that starts Sunday, ``On Our
Own Terms: Moyers on Dying.''
</P>
<P>
   In Central Texas, the Capital Area Partnership for End-of-Life
Care is among the hundreds of groups that have formed to continue
the discussion. The local coalition, which includes medical
professionals, state agency personnel and public television
representatives, has published a resource guide on end-of-life care
and and has organized panel discussions, broadcast programs and a
public forum on death and dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really hungry to talk,'' Meyer said. ``Scratch
anyone within five feet of you, and they are dealing with somebody
who has a terminal or irreversible condition.''
</P>
<P>
   No one should have to call on a Dr. Jack Kervorkian to help them
die, said Meyer, author of ``A Good Death: Challenges, Choices and
Care Options.''
</P>
<P>
   But even doctors are uncomfortable talking about death, and many
resist referring patients to a hospice, said Dr. Leigh Fredholm,
medical director of Hospice Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an artificial perception that when you admit your
patient to a hospice that's it. You can't do anything else,''
Fredholm said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Parkinson, 79, of Georgetown, Texas, said he is at peace
staying at home with his oxygen bottle and wheelchair. Tended by
his wife, Ann, and Hospice Austin nurses, Parkinson is dying of
heart disease but says he is ``very content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The love, care and consideration of these Hospice people is
absolutely incredible,'' he said. ``I dearly love all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   What can he do to pay them back? he asked an agency
representative visiting his home last week.
</P>
<P>
   Like Starr, Parkinson _ a retired textbook publisher and a jazz
trumpet player who won a contest in high school to play with Tommy
Dorsey _ is spiritual and has maintained his sense of humor. He is
not afraid of dying, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my grandkids. I know my own kids, and they love me,''
he said. ``What more do I want?''
</P>
<P>
   But like many who face death, he is worried about his family. He
suspects his wife of 55 years, three children and four
grandchildren ``won't much like it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No I won't,'' Ann said, her dark blue eyes shining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss her,'' he said, turning toward Ann. ``I'll
think of you all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had a choice, he'd be well and dining at a favorite New
York-style deli that never closes. But he is old now, he said, and
everyone has to die.
</P>
<P>
   Like Starr, he believes in an afterlife and imagines a reunion
with loved ones, including a brother who died years ago. He wants
to hang out with jazz musician Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep having fantasies that I'm going to room with the
pope,'' said Parkinson, who is a Presbyterian. ``Then he could get
rid of all those idiotic people standing around in knight's
uniforms. He's a man. He's a humble human being, and I'd like to
chat with him. He's inspired me.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkinson said he hopes to be around for his 80th birthday in
November ``for bragging purposes,'' but no one knows how much time
he has. Hospice patients are admitted to the program when their
prognosis is six months.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been living at Hospice Austin's Christopher House for
two months _ ever since she needed care 24 hours a day. ALS has
taken over her body. It attacks the motor neurons and leaves people
unable to move, and ultimately, unable to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Starr doesn't leave her bed anymore. She couldn't without being
lifted. With her hair dyed a maroon-red and her limbs limp, Starr
has nicknamed herself ``Raggedy Ann with an attitude.'' She
entertains a parade of friends, and their laughter brightens the
halls of Christopher House.
</P>
<P>
   Her close friend Robbie Billig, a nurse, always comes on
Wednesdays. She banters with Starr non-stop and talks about the
good times they've shared.
</P>
<P>
   Starr recounts hiking and beach trips to Mexico. In college, she
studied geology, but didn't graduate. She worked a variety of jobs,
from waiting tables to cleaning houses to proofreading legislation.
She'd save her money and then travel some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disease certainly changes the way I live my life,'' Starr
said, unable to speak as fast as she would like. ``But I'm not my
disease . . . I decided I needed to keep living as I've been living
_ sucking all the joy and fun out of life as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   She had a hard time surrendering her independence and asking
others for help. But she has accepted that, too, she said, with
help from the Christopher House staff who are ``so open, easy going
and loving.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Billig recounted a trip they took in February to the
Grand Canyon _ one of Starr's favorite places _ with Starr's
wheelchair and bedside commode in tow. The van broke down, though,
and they only made it as far as Santa Fe. They shopped and feasted
for nine days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the last trip,'' Billig said.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr isn't quite done. She's got plans for one more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
