<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-OPEN-STODA0908-CO     09-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-STODA0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle rages on between Hingis and Williams
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What if they were friends?
</P>
<P>
   What if this Gucci girl and that girl whose favorite places to
visit are anywhere that accepts credit cards were shopping buddies?
</P>
<P>
   What if the white woman from Switzerland and the black woman
from California discovered a bond transcending race?
</P>
<P>
   What if these two young women, separated by birth 20 years ago
by little more than a hundred days, found a common ground instead
of professional tennis' killing ground?
</P>
<P>
   What if today's women's U.S. Open semifinal match between
top-seeded Martina Hingis and third-seeded Venus Williams at the
National Tennis Center was rooted in admiration instead of
loathing?
</P>
<P>
   What if?
</P>
<P>
   A thousand what-ifs wouldn't matter now, because the animosity
between Hingis and Williams _ also involving Williams' younger
sister, Serena _ has escalated to the point that the heads of state
gathered nearby at the U.N. likely couldn't broker a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The competitve history between Hingis and VWilliams going into
today's match is remarkable for its depth considering the age of
the players. Williams turned 20 three months ago; Hingis will
celebrate her 20th birthday in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But already they have played against each other 15 times with
Hingis holding a 9-6 edge. The first of those meetings was early in
the 1997 Lipton, which Hingis won. The most recent was Williams'
victory in the Wimbledon quarterfinals earlier this summer on the
way to her first Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has five Grand Slam championships, but none since winning
the Australian Open to start 1999. The emergence of the Williams
sisters as viable contenders for Grand Slam titles (Serena won last
year's U.S. Open) is regarded as more than coincidence in
consideration of Hingis' fade.
</P>
<P>
   Which goes a long way toward explaining what Hingis said to
second-seeded Lindsay Davenport before Davenport's quarterfinal
match Wednesday night against Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started last year (at the U.S. Open),'' Davenport said,
``because I played the first semifinal against Serena and she
played Venus. She's like, 'Well, you better, you know, win.' I
lost. I saw her in the locker room and she was shaking her head at
me right before she played.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis then beat Venus in the other semifinal before losing in
the championship to Serena.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Hingis and Davenport _ with Hingis already through
to today's showdown semifinal with Venus and Davenport preparing
for Wednesday night's quarterfinal with Serena _ talked about
stopping the Williamses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' Davenport said, ``she said, 'You're first again.'
I think she feels like she sides with me against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should just tag-team wrestle.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the backdrop for the third Hingis vs. Venus meeting at a
U.S. Open in the past four years. Hingis won in straight sets in
the 1997 final and in three sets last year in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   A bit more intrigue was added Thursday when Serena, scheduled to
play a women's doubles semifinal with her sister, withdrew with an
inflammation of the small sesmoid bone at the joint of the big toe
on her left foot. It has been a long-term problem, but not one that
appeared to bother her Wednesday night. Nor is it likely to keep
her from representing the U.S. in the upcoming Olympics in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists, of course, suggest the reason for the
withdrawal was to benefit Venus by keeping her from having to play
on a day off from singles.
</P>
<P>
   Williams professes to be unaware of the madness surrounding the
encounter. She chooses only to ``believe in my game'' instead of
creating a ``real problem'' worrying about someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best competitor will win,'' she said. ``If you start
taking it too seriously, that's when it gets to be pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Richard, allowed how he actually thought it ``a good
idea'' for Hingis and Davenport _ sisters in arms, if not blood _
to consort with each other and even strategize against his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis is obviously weary of the attention given the Williamses
_ ``Nothing surprises me anymore,'' she said _ and would like
nothing better than to beat Venus, who has won three times in their
past four encounters, to end her rival's current 24-match winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   What if that happens?
</P>
<P>
   What if it doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
