u s BC-FBC-HUSKIES0908-COX     09-07 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'The Throwin' Samoan' continues family tradition
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Marques Tuiasosopo has never set foot in
American Samoa, the small South Pacific island 6,000 miles from
Seattle where his family name is royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to,'' said the senior quarterback for the University of
Washington, which plays Miami on Saturday at Husky Stadium. ``It's
pretty expensive. I'll have to save up some money.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't have to wait long, probably after he signs an NFL
contract.
</P>
<P>
   When he does arrive, he may get a reception fit for a king _ and
not just because of his grandfather, one of 200 Tuiasosopos on the
island but one of six living men to hold the rank of High Talking
Chief.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 15 family members to play collegiate and professional
sports, Marques might rank as the best. That's because of
versatility that enabled him to pass and run his way to a
school-record 2,723 yards last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marques is an inspiration for young Samoan kids,'' said Jack
Thompson, one of the first quarterbacks to come from the
77-square-mile island known for producing linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``The Throwin' Samoan,'' Thompson, a Washington State
standout in the late '70s, remembers the hits he took from Marques'
father, Manu Tuiasosopo, a UCLA defensive lineman who played for
the Seahawks and 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   When Thompson watches Marques _ who at 6-feet-2 and 220 pounds
is considered small for a Samoan football product _ he knows, ``I
won't have to sue him for copyright infringement. He's going to
have several names because he can run, he can throw, he can
scramble.''
</P>
<P>
   His showcase game came against Stanford last year when he rushed
for 207 yards and passed for 302, becoming the first quarterback in
NCAA history to eclipse 200 yards rushing and 300 yards passing in
a single game.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an injury, Marques will become the Huskies' all-time
total offense leader this season, eclipsing names like Damon Huard
and Mark Brunell and Warren Moon in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   No. 15 Washington is expected to dominate the Pac-10 using an
option-based offense led by Marques, a former baseball prospect
from Woodinville, Wash., who was drafted by the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so multi-dimensional,'' said Washington quarterbacks
coach Steve Axman, who coached Troy Aikman at UCLA. ``Most option
quarterbacks can't throw the ball very well. But he can throw the
ball and run the option.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said one of Marques' strength is his ability to read
the defense during a play and quickly adapt Washington's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a Hurricanes fan, I would watch how he is,''
Thompson said. ``As Marques goes, the team will go. He is the heart
and soul of that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Marques credits his prowess to his father, who instilled an
athletic work ethic that mirrors the values of Samoan culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad played the game for 20 years. Football was something I
was raised with. It's the ultimate team sport. You get a chance to
play with the 49ers in the Super Bowl, that's where he learned a
lot of about his principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Manu's principles include the family of five children he raised
with wife Tina, who is white and of Polish and German descent.
That's why Marques said his father, who could not be reached for
this story, will not return to Samoa to abide by Chief Asovalu
Tuiasosopo's wishes to assume the family title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably slim to none,'' Marques said. ``He's pretty set
over here. He was born here and lived his whole life here.''
</P>
<P>
   While Marques embraces both sides of his heritage, he is
especially proud of his Samoan roots. ``He always says to me, 'If I
go over there, I'll find 300 Tuiasosopos in our village,' '' Axman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuiasosopos' football legacy dates back to the 1950s with
uncle Johnny Olszewski, a running back who played 10 years in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's part of me,'' Marques said. ``I take a
lot of pride when I go out and play and work hard. It's passed down
from generation to generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The current generation includes younger brother Zach, a Husky
teammate, sister Leslie, who played volleyball at UW, and cousin
Naomi Mulitauaopele, who plays for the WNBA's Utah Starzz.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the best athlete in the family, Marques said
without hesitation: ``My little brother Matt. He's as tall as I am
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Tuiasosopo, 14, plays baseball, basketball and football. In
1998, he led the Woodinville baseball team to within one out of
advancing to the Little League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Matt plays shortstop and pitcher, which is why Thompson says the
14-year-old Tuiasosopo might be the next Throwin' Samoan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to umpire one his games behind the plate,'' Thompson
said with a laugh. ``I was telling the catcher, 'Son, you better
catch every ball. I don't want any missed balls.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
