<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT &LR;      09-07 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GETS POWERFUL HELP FROM CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT13,17,18,26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARBONDALE, Pa. _ Vice President Al Gore may be trying to
distance himself from President Clinton, but he is making no
attempt to escape from the Clinton Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the vice president is relying more and more these days
on the expertise, advice and support of a gallery of members and
former members of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was this more evident than in Cleveland on Wednesday,
when Gore delivered a major speech laying out his vision of the
economy for the next decade. At his side was Robert Rubin, who, as
Clinton's former Treasury secretary and one of the people who is
felt to have madea significant contribution toward the current
prosperity, is regarded as the administration's economic superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin provided not only his presence and reputation to vouch for
Gore's ability to keep the economy sound. He helped put in place
the fundamental principles _ chiefly, paying down the debt and
heeding the bond market _ that underpin Gore's own economic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was not the only Clinton appointee helping Gore with his
economic blueprint. The list of brainstormers reads like a who's
who of the Clinton administration's economic elite _ Lawrence
Summers, the current Treasury secretary, Erskine Bowles, Clinton's
former chief of staff, Laura D'Andrea Tyson, former chairwoman of
Clinton's Council of Economic Advisers, and Gene Sperling, the
president's top in-house economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The degree to which Clinton appointees are campaigning on behalf
of the vice president is unusual and reflects the confluence of
several factors: Clinton's serious investment in getting Gore
elected; Gore's need to have people with policy expertise and
marquee names vouching for his participation in important decisions
within the Clinton administration; the desire by the Cabinet
members themselves to use to the fullest their waning months in the
limelight and, perhaps for some, a desire to improve their chances
of appointments in a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing illegal about Cabinet officers electioneering.
The Hatch Act prevents government employees from spending official
time on political work, but presidential appointees are exempt from
that restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Having Cabinet-level experts at a candidate's disposal is an
enormous advantage of incumbency, and Gore has not been shy about
using it.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore is deeply familiar with policy details, his ability
to call forth the armies of the administration to speak on his
behalf has bolstered one of the central tenets of his candidacy _
that he is, as Clinton has often argued, the most qualified person
in history to run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Simon, a senior Gore adviser, said the campaign was
thrilled to be able to showcase the Cabinet. ``We've had the most
stable Cabinet of any recent administration, so these are people
who have become authorities,'' he said. ``There's no substitute for
having Bob Rubin talk about economic prosperity or Donna Shalala
talk about health or Andrew Cuomo talk about inner cities. Each of
these people is a shining star.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the strong support of so many Cabinet officers
was a benefit of Gore's having been so involved in the
administration. ``This isn't a situation where you have a vice
president and Cabinet warring among itself, the way Johnson and
Kennedy did, or an office kept in the dark, the way Quayle was,''
he said. ``You have a vice presidential staff that was fully
integrated into all the Cabinet agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Wittmann, a conservative policy analyst at the Hudson
Institute, said that the extent to which current and former members
of the administration were working for Gore appeared
``unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of a single former official who has come back and
worked so prominently for a vice president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that such action showed both an extraordinary
degree of loyalty within the administration as well as the degree
of determination in helping Clinton establish a political legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, Gore's election would provide some
``vindication'' of Clinton's mixed tenure.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tricky area for Gore to navigate. On the one hand, he
says he is not running for a third Clinton term, and he has sought
to close the Clinton chapter of his career.
</P>
<P>
   He often says, as he did here Thursday at a high-tech company,
that he is not running on the ``past performance'' of the economy
but on his own plan for a stronger economy in the future.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Gore has routinely relied on Clinton's political
appointees to advance his cause. Rubin even stumped with him in New
Hampshire last winter. Many have been with the Clinton
administration for years and are seen not so much as auditioning
for a Gore administration but as making themselves more marketable
for the private sector as the end of the Clinton era nears.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Virtually the entire Cabinet has participated in one form or
another in the Gore campaign. Most commonly, they are hosts for
conference calls with reporters. Shalala, the secretary of health
and human services, conducted a conference call on Tuesday to
critique Gov. George W. Bush's plan for prescription drug coverage.
A few days before, Dr. David Kessler, former head of the Food and
Drug Administration and now dean of the Yale School of Medicine,
took part in a conference call to preview a week of Gore speeches
on health-care issues. A few days later, Tyson, who had served on
the 1999 Medicare Commission, conducted a conference call to
discuss Gore's plan to save Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis Herman, Clinton's secretary of labor, has been among the
Cabinet officers most visibly involved in Gore's campaign,
particularly in his efforts to reach out to black voters. She and
Rodney Slater, the transportation secretary, who is also black,
were on hand to brief reporters when Gore addressed the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People last month in
Baltimore. Herman also played an advisory role in Gore's
vice-presidential screening committee and is part of the team
working out the debate schedule.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the most striking examples of Gore's reliance on the
Clinton Cabinet was his selection earlier this summer of William M.
Daley, Clinton's commerce secretary, as his campaign chairman to
replace the ailing Tony Coelho.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala, the health secretary, is one of the Cabinet members
most actively campaigning for Gore. She said she has been doing so
because of her belief in Gore's proposals and her admiration for
his wife. ``It's both a personal commitment to them and a real
commitment on my part to the programs,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had made it clear that she was not interested in a
job in a Gore administration. Moreover, she said, she just flat-out
loves politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the rough and tumble,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she has closely followed the rules about having
the campaign, not the taxpayers, pay for her political trips. But
she noted that Cabinet secretaries are on duty 24 hours a day and
get no vacation, and that part of their jobs are political.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who seemed to be trying openly to parlay his
position into a Gore administration post was Bill Richardson,
Clinton's energy secretary. He was widely considered a possible
vice-presidential running mate for Gore until problems within his
department's purview derailed him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
