<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians hanging tough in doubles, junior events
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's Day 11 of 14 at the U.S. Open, and the USTA
National Tennis Center is still teeming with Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   Vinings resident Ellis Ferreira and Rick Leach are in today's
men's doubles final after beating Yevgeny Kafelnikov and Wayne
Ferreira 6-4, 5-7, 6-3 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira and Leach, the Australian Open champions, will play
Lleyton Hewitt and Max Mirnyi today at 11 a.m. This is the retiring
Leach's last U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played three years together, and I'd love to win it for
him,'' Ferreira said of Leach. ``We were emotionally overwhelmed in
Australia because of that fact. Not that you need much more
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the junior tournament, Robby Ginepri of Marietta, Ga., and
Ashley Harkleroad of Flintstone, Ga., are through to the singles
quarterfinals as unseeded players.
</P>
<P>
   Ginepri defeated Hiroki Kondo of Japan 7-6 (7-5), 3-6, 6-1
Thursday in the boys draw, impressing Tom Gullikson, USTA director
of coaching for player development.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from down 5-2 and two breaks in the first set to
dominating in the third,'' Gullikson said. ``I think he was
physically overpowering that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginepri also reached the doubles semifinals with partner Tres
Davis of Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Harkleroad, who left her northwest Georgia roots last summer to
train at the Saddlebrook Resort in Tampa, beat Annette Kolb of
Germany when Kolb retired trailing 6-2, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I should be considered one of the players who can win
it,'' said Harkleroad, 15, who turned pro earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   A third Georgia native, Jamea Jackson, had two match points
against 13th-seed Matea Mezak of Croatia on Thursday but began
cramping due to the heat. Jackson lost six straight games and
retired trailing 6-7 (6-3), 7-5, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 Americans in the 64-player girls draw, four were from
Georgia, and Harkleroad is now the only American left. Tanner
Cochran of Dublin beat Erin Burdette of Jackson in the first round,
then lost to Jamea Jackson in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Atlanta U.S. Open,'' said Randy Walker, USTA
communications manager. ``It seems like from the start, Georgia's
top tennis players have been front and center.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
