<SLUG> BC-U.N.-RICH-POOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SPEAKERS URGE INCREASE IN CHARITY TO THE POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A succession of leaders speaking on the second
day of the United Nations' Millennium Summit on Thursday demanded,
with passion and often eloquence, that the industrialized world
show more tangible charity toward the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billions among the living struggle to survive in conditions of
poverty, deprivation and underdevelopment as offensive to
everything humane as anything we decry about the second
millennium,'' President Thabo Mbeki of South Africa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor of the world stand at the gates of the comfortable
mansions occupied by each and every king and queen, president,
prime minister and minister privileged to attend this unique
meeting,'' Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, relatively few speakers of the 70 leaders who were
scheduled to speak Thursday offered specific remedies beyond debt
forgiveness, leaving it to some Western countries, like Canada and
Italy, to endorse additional, if less dramatic, measures.
</P>
<P>
   A declaration to be signed on Friday when the summit meeting
ends has set ambitious benchmarks for resolving the global ills of
war, disease, poverty and environmental degradation. One such goal
proposes to reduce by half over the next 15 years the number of
people earning less than a dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that, President Hugo Chavez of Venezuela reckoned,
``we should increase that income to levels of fairness and dignity
for 140,000 persons each day of each month and of each year from
the present until Dec. 31, 2015.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian prime minister, Giuliano Amato, agreed that radical
efforts were required. ``Debt cancellation is important,
indispensable even, but not enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed opening markets to developing countries by
abolishing quotas and tariffs and allocating fresh resources for
education.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the misgivings expressed about the impact of
globalization on poor countries, Prime Minister Jean Chretien of
Canada said: ``We must share the benefits of globalization. We must
give it a human purpose and a human face. The poorest countries
require access for their goods to export markets. Faster, deeper
and broader debt relief should be pursued vigorously.'' And
Chretien added: ``We must ensure that the benefits or the
information revolution are shared by all.''
</P>
<P>
   King Herald V of Norway observed that poverty is inextricably
linked to problems like environmental deterioration. ``For we shall
never be able to cooperate effectively on how to husband the scarce
resources of our planet, how to prevent the degradation of the
environment, as long as so many are trapped in hopeless poverty,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   President J.J. Rawlings of Ghana blamed Western corporations for
``thrusting'' corruption on Africa, which, he contended, ``has
drained some of our countries of resources which should have been
used to improve the quality of life of the poor and
disadvantaged.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be less corruption in Africa,'' he said, ``if there
is no place to hide the proceeds of corruption or if the proceeds
of corruption, once uncovered, are returned to their real owners,
the people of Africa,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
