<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    U.N. council pledges better training, faster deployment of
peace-keepers
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Acknowledging that traditional U.N. security
operations are too limited, members of the U.N. Security Council
Thursday pledged better training and faster deployment of
peace-keepers, as well as more stable funding for their work.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, issued by the council's five permanent members _
China, France, Russia, Great Britain and the United States _ came
shortly after President Clinton urged members at the U.N.
Millennium Summit to pay closer attention to problems in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The president also pleaded with the leaders to broaden their
approach to preventing war throughout the world by attacking the
poverty, disease and environmental hazards that breed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we confront the iron link between deprivation, disease
and war, we will never be able to create the peace that the
founders of the United Nations dreamed of,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that a quarter of all deaths on the planet are now caused
by infectious diseases such as AIDS, malaria and tuberculosis,
Clinton said the U.N. must invest in the basics of clean water,
safe food, sanitation and health education. If it doesn't, he
warned, the AIDS epidemic that has caused life expectancy in some
African nations to plummet by as much as 30 years will spread to
Asia in the next decade, causing more panic and instability.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also predicted that if nations fail to address global
climate changes, environmental problems in the next decade will
become ``as big an obstacle to the development of poor nations as
disease is today.``
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the three-day summit, Clinton and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan have warned that the AIDS crisis and
environmental problems in the world's hot spots would lead to
increased instability in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   In brief speeches before the Security Council and before a
gathering of African leaders attending the summit, the president
said the United States ``strongly supports'' Annan's goals to
significantly reduce poverty, disease and environmental destruction
in the next 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has begun to work toward those goals, he said,
citing his administration's efforts to encourage U.S. investment in
Africa, connect African countries to the Internet and write off the
debts of as many as 27 developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Already, debt write-offs in Uganda have allowed that country to
use the savings to double its primary school enrollment, Clinton
said. He added that Senegal has used its savings to hire 2,000 new
teachers and Mozambique has put the savings toward purchasing
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the U.S. Congress to approve $435 million this
year to fully fund the debt-relief program, and asked other world
leaders to join the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said the United States has launched a $300
million initiative to help African countries provide free meals to
encourage parents to send their children to school. If other
countries would contribute, he said, $4 billion worldwide would
provide nutritious meals in school to every child in every
developing country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pledged continued investment in medical research to
develop a vaccine for AIDS and other diseases, pointing out that
the United States currently invests $2 billion a year in AIDS
research alone. The president has asked Congress to provide a $1
billion tax credit for pharmaceutical companies to speed up
research and development of vaccines against AIDS, malaria and TB.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed for the long run,'' Clinton told the African
leaders. ``We want to take on the great human challenges; we want
to take on the great political challenges. There are some things
that you will have to do, but I believe America is moving
inexorably to be a much better partner over the long run for
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Thursday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
that she and Clinton's Middle East envoy, Dennis Ross, were
continuing peace meetings with Israeli and Palestinian officials.
She said both sides realize they may have only a few weeks to reach
an agreement. She added that there has been ``an intensification of
effort'' with many ideas being discussed, including more detailed
discussions on the fate of Jerusalem, a major sticking point in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a floating operation and we're working hard,'' Albright
said, adding that she and Ross were keeping the president informed.
She said Clinton is ready to step in to help mediate an agreement
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian Chairman
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said during a news conference Thursday that he is
committed to leaving ``no stone unturned'' in his search for peace,
but he complained that Arafat remains inflexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped to find a partner'' in Arafat, he said. ``We
didn't find a responsive partner on the other side, but the door is
open and we hope we will find it in the near future.``
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he told Clinton that several far-reaching ideas put
on the table by the president ``are beyond what we believe we can
accept.'' He added, however, that if Arafat would agree to take
Clinton's ideas as a basis for re-entering negotiations, ``we are
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was unsure whether there would be further
meetings while he's in New York, but he said he's confident there
will be ``a serious effort'' to work toward a peace agreement in
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
