<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-AMERICANS0908-COX     09-07 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-AMERICANS0908-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foreign athletes melt into U.S. team
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seven years ago, Anna Kozlova was unaware of bagels
and after-school jobs. For all she knew, the lyrics to ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' could have been from Eminem's ``The Real
Slim Shady.'' She did not grasp the concept of paying interest on
credit-card charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they just gave you money,'' Kozlova says.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has found a new favorite breakfast food and
part-time work. She knows the meaning of annual percentage rates
and billing cycles. And she can recite the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. ``I can, but don't ask me to say it,'' she pleads
to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlova is from Russia, for decades the mortal Olympic enemy of
the United States. Today, she is the leading lady on the U.S.
synchronized swimming roster.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your grandfather's, or old Uncle Sam's, Olympic
team. As the walls separating nations come tumbling down, the plane
to Sydney is buzzing with accents from far and wide. The United
States will be represented by about two dozen athletes born beyond
its borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Olympic team is a mirror of the country,'' USOC
spokesman Mike Moran says.
</P>
<P>
   The Statue of Liberty might say, ``Give me your tired, your
poor, your huddled masses _ and, while you're at it, throw in a
good distance runner, kayaker and cyclist.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants are scattered among several sports and clumped in
one, table tennis. One natural-born citizen with paddle in hand is
joined by three from China, two from Vietnam and one from
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC says it does not accelerate the citizenship process,
but athletes can tap congressmen and lawyers on their own to cut
through red tape so they can break the finish-line tape wearing
red, white and blue. Marathon champion Khalid Khannouchi of Morocco
was fast-tracked this year, only to decide before the U.S. Trials
that he was too leg-weary to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the original nation's Olympic committee must sign off
before an athlete is transferred officially. China refused to
release racewalker Yueling Chen, a 1992 Olympian, then relented
last month. Cuba still has not let loose paddler Angel Perez, much
to the frustration of USA Canoe/Kayak.
</P>
<P>
   No immigrant has taken American shores by storm more than
swimmer Lenny Krayzelburg. A world-record holder in two backstroke
events, he stands to become the male counterpart to Marion Jones _
a multiple gold-medalist, a hit on Madison Avenue, an icon to
youth.
</P>
<P>
   HOPING TO ESCAPE PREJUDICE
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism drove the Krayzelburgs from the Ukraine in 1989.
Young Lenny had gotten a taste of it, hearing ``bad words (from
kids), insulting words in Russian that would be, like, 'Jew.'''
</P>
<P>
   They landed in California, for no particular reason. His parents
``were going into pretty much nothingness,'' Krayzelburg said. ``I
mean, they didn't know what was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first new home was West Hollywood, where movie makers with
vast imaginations tell stories more credible than Lenny's.
</P>
<P>
   His father had first placed him in a swim program largely to
pass the time until soccer. He swam at a junior college. He missed
out on the Atlanta Games one year after obtaining citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Now Krayzelburg, 24, can parlay almost certain Olympic success
with his cheery disposition and blond, blue-eyed features into
regular gigs on ``Entertainment Tonight.'' Even before the Games,
he has seven endorsement contracts. His handsome mug is on a cereal
box. His degree in finance from Southern Cal is about to come in
handy.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg resorts to his native language at home. He envisions
marrying a Russian someday. Yet when his ingredients _ the faintest
of accents, westernized lingo, look and interests _ are stirred
together, out pops an American-as-apple-pie.
</P>
<P>
   BECOMING AN AMERICAN
</P>
<P>
   Kozlova, who got a later introduction to capitalist ways,
retains an accent thicker than Krayzelburg's. Her image of America
had been shaped by cinema classics such as _ Freddie Krueger
slasher flicks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the bad parts,'' Kozlova, 27, says. ``Just how people
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, Kozlova had been struck by the sight of visiting
Americans in their bright clothes _ and with their brighter moods.
She sojourned to California in 1992 to train, returned home and
came back a year later for good, half the world away from her
parents and two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment has not been all bagels and cream cheese. When
Kozlova's new friends and roommates _ including the male syncro
swimmer, Bill May _ would depart for overseas competition, she was
left behind, awaiting her citizenship. ``That was very, very
hard,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlanta Games, she watched from the stands, forbidden
even from associating with the team. ``I wanted to jump in the
pool,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Oct. 9, Kozlova became an American. She was so overcome
with emotion that she barely was able to recite the oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my father came over, the first words out of his mouth
were, 'I'm glad you stayed here,' `` she says.
</P>
<P>
   While the former kid Soviets probably will add to the U.S. medal
count, their move was mutually beneficial. Krayzelburg journeyed
home once to see his old pool filled with garbage. Kozlova's
ex-teammates scattered to Australia or Greece or Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, good riddance, Kozlova says about the Soviet system that
has crumbled along with those walls dividing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you are through, you are thrown out,'' she recalls of the
program that tied up an athlete's entire day. ``Sports takes up so
much (time) you cannot prepare for anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, in the land of the free, an array of life's options stand
before them.
</P>
<P>
   His name is on the Lakers' season ticket list. She drives a
Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   You can't get much more thoroughly American than that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
