<SLUG> BC-ADULTWEB-BILLSCAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORN SITE VISIT FEES A SCAM, JUDGE RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Malibu-based Web site operator must pay
defrauded credit card holders $37.5 million after charging them for
visits to Internet pornography sites even though some victims
didn't own computers, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Audrey B. Collins found that more than
90 percent of the charges the company made were fake, made simply
by taking account numbers off a list supplied by an Agoura Hills
bank. Between 1997 and 1999, it changed names four times to stay
one step ahead of credit card issuers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew something was seriously wrong when we got complaints
from people saying I got a bill for Internet pornography and I
don't even own a computer,'' said Federal Trade Commission attorney
Douglas Wolfe. ``What we proved was that they took numbers from
that database and billed them as if they used their services.''
</P>
<P>
   Lead defendant Kenneth Taves faces additional criminal charges
because he allegedly disobeyed a court demand to reveal the
whereabouts of money and records. During the trial, he was on
parole for an unrelated check kiting conviction. His wife Teresa
Taves and co-defendant Dennis Rappaport can only conduct business
in the future under court-imposed restrictions. Only the Taveses
are liable for paying the fine.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the couple did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, the FTC filed its case against the Taveses and
Rappaport, whose business operated variously under the names J.K.
Publications, Discreet Bill, MJD Service Corp. and Herbal Care Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The operation had the account numbers of 3 million credit card
holders who had purchased goods or services from companies with
accounts at Agoura Hills, Calif., -based Charter Pacific Bank.
Several times, Visa came close to putting the Taves' company on its
active monitoring list for merchants with excessive numbers of
disputed charges. Each time, the operation would apply with Visa
for a new merchant account with a new name, the FTC said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge found that in as many as half the cases, complaining
card holders did not have computers and hadn't given their card
numbers out to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Charter Pacific, which will not face regulatory action, provided
the list of credit card numbers to the Taves' outfit in a practice
known as ``fraud scrubbing'' meant to alert legitimate merchants to
card holders attempting to use such cards fraudulently. As an
example, cards with high percentages of credit refunds known as
``chargebacks'' could appear on such lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that the service the bank was providing was meant
to prevent fraud, not cause fraud,'' said bank spokesman Steven
Fink, who said Charter Pacific chose to stop offering the service
after the FTC filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC has found some $20 million of the fraudulent companies'
assets but could not say how much of the $37.5 million settlement
would be available to victims. The agency said consumers wishing to
file claims to recoup money lost to the Taveses can call
court-appointed receiver Robb Evans and Associates at (818)
768-8869 or by visiting the FTC Web site at ftc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
