<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5606 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-07 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPRENTICE HOPING TO FINISH IN BAZE OF GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyler Baze doesn't let himself worry about the future. At age
17, he'd have a lot of future to worry about if he did.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't wonder if he'll be able to keep riding winners after
his apprenticeship and five-pound weight allowance expire in
December. He shrugs off speculation his 5-foot-5, 110-pound frame
will grow for the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Baze is putting all his thoughts and energy into the next three
months. Is he ever.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the dark day before Del Mar's finale, will be the last
day off for quite a while for the youngest member of the Baze
family of jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to take advantage of the weight break, to pile up as
many victories as he can, and to earn the Eclipse Award as the nati
outstanding apprentice jockey of 2000, Baze plans to ride every day
this fall. That's !ital!every day.
</P>
<P>
   After clocking in for the 18 consecutive days of the Los Angeles
County Fair meet that opens Thursday in Pomona, he'll ride
Wednesday through Sunday at Santa Anita's Oak Tree meet and
Hollywood Park's fall meet _ and round out each week by riding at
Turf Paradise in Phoenix on Mondays and Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough, sticking it out seven days a week for
the rest of the year, but you've got to do what you've got to do,''
Baze said on the phone from Del Mar. ``I just want to ride as many
horses as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Baze has given his Eclipse Award campaign a boost during the
six-week Del Mar season, riding 22 winners in 37 days (at an
average payoff of $15.60), fifth in the San Diego-area track's
star-studded jock standings.
</P>
<P>
   He has moved up the list since the Hollywood Park meet, where he
was ninth with 31 victories in 65 days.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Baze's 156 victories this year put him first among
apprentices, with New York-based Norberto Arroyo Jr. second with
139. But Baze's $2.2 million in purses are a distant second to
Arroyo's $4.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because Arroyo's 12-month apprenticeship has run out, Baze and
agent Ivan Puhich see a chance to sway Eclipse voters by increasing
their advantage in the wins column.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now if I can win 50 to 60 races more than him
(Arroyo), I'll win,'' Puhich said in classic agent-speak, in which
``I'' means ``my jockey.'' The last Southern California-based
apprentice to win the Eclipse was Steve Valdez in 1973, and the
last to remain a fixture on this highly competitive circuit was
Corey Nakatani, who came along in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But Baze has impressed Southern Californians more than the
average newcomer. Hall of Fame jockey Gary Stevens, on a racing
radio show last weekend, praised Baze as the headiest apprentice he
has seen in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Baze is, you might say, bred for it. He grew up on a
Washington-state farm as the son of Earl Baze and the former Cammie
Hunt, both riders. He's the nephew of Gary Baze, currently riding
at Emerald Downs near Seattle. And he's the second cousin of Hall
of Famer Russell Baze, the dominant rider at the San Francisco Bay
Area tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Baze name has opened some doors. But Tyler started at the
bottom like any jockey. He was 15 when he got his first racetrack
job grooming horses for trainer Mike Puhich _ Ivan's nephew _ at
Emerald Downs. Ivan went to see the boy with the riding genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked him and saw he was pretty athletic,'' the agent said.
He brought Baze to Santa Anita and got him ready to race.
</P>
<P>
   Puhich estimates Baze galloped 500 horses, breaking 50 from the
starting gate, before his first competitive rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason he's become so good so young is the
preparation we've made,'' Puhich said.
</P>
<P>
   It took Baze five tries before he rode his first winner, a horse
ominously named Fleeting Wonder, on Oct. 31, 1999 at Santa Anita.
His fifth victory, signaling the beginning of his apprenticeship,
came on Dec. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Baze spent most of the winter at Turf Paradise and finished
fourth in the standings with 109 winners (20 percent). Oh, and he
finished his senior year in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never disappointed me,'' said Puhich, with whom Baze is
living in Monrovia until he turns 18 on Oct. 19. ``He still asks me
for permission to go to the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Baze's success at Del Mar has surprised nobody more than
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me. It's like a dream come true, riding with
the best riders in the world,'' he said. ``I didn't expect (to do
this well) in Southern California. I mean, geez Louise, I'm
surprised they even allow me on the grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Baze admits he doesn't know if he'll be able to compete with the
older jockeys here after Dec. 12, when his horses will no longer be
allowed to carry five pounds less.
</P>
<P>
   As for questions about his own weight, Baze responds that he
thinks he is full-grown and will top out at 112 or 113 pounds,
light enough for a jockey on any circuit.
</P>
<P>
   His technique has room to improve. ``I need to get better at
staying still on a horse,'' he said. He is winless in 24 starts on
the turf course at Del Mar. But apprentices rarely are given strong
horses to ride in the trickier grass races.
</P>
<P>
   Puhich, 74, said Baze will be ``my last jock . . . I'm going to
work about three more years, then turn him over to (fellow agent)
Tony Matos, and Tony will get him to the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   But let's not get ahead of ourselves. The next three months
figure to be enough of a challenge for now. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DEL MAR LEADERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Through Wednesday) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys: Victor Espinoza, 43 wins; Laffit Pincay, 29; Kent
Desormeaux and David Flores, 28; Tyler Baze, 23; Eddie
Delahoussaye, 20. Trainers: Bob Baffert, 25; Bill Spawr, 14; Bobby
Frankel, 12; Mike Mitchell, 11; Bob Hess Jr., 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PINCAY UPDATE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laffit Pincay underwent surgery on an eyelid Tuesday and was
expected to return to competition next Wednesday to ride Squirtle
Squirt in the closing-day Del Mar Futurity. Pincay, the career
record holder, is 23 wins from 9,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON THE STAKES SCHEDULE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ At Del Mar: today, $75,000 El Cajon Stakes, 3-year-olds, 1
mile; Saturday, $400,000 Ramona Handicap, fillies and mares 3 and
up, 1 miles on turf; Sunday, $300,000 Del Mar Derby, 3-year-olds, 1
miles on turf; Monday, $100,000 I'm Smokin, California-bred
2-year-olds, 6 furlongs; Wednesday, $250,000 Del Mar Futurity,
2-year-olds, 7 furlongs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ At Belmont Park: Saturday, $500,000 Man O'War, 3-year-olds
and up, 1 miles on turf, and $200,000 Gazelle Handicap, 3-year-old
fillies, 1 miles; Sunday, $250,000 Garden City Handicap, 3-year-old
fillies, 1 miles on turf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ At Woodbine: Sunday, $1 million Atto Mile, 3-year-olds and
up, 1 mile on turf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Ramona and Wednesday's Futurity are the remaining
attractions at Del Mar. Palomar Handicap winner Tranquility Lake is
out of the Ramona because of the effects of an insect bite. But
2-3-4 finishers Tout Charmant, Miss of Wales and Spanish Fern are
in the race, along with Alexine, Cafe Latte, Bordelaise, Keemoon
and Sweet Life. . . . Ladies Din, coming off a win in Del Mar's
Eddie Read, is expected to join a large field for Sunday's Atto
Mile at Woodbine racetrack near Toronto. Honest Lady, Riviera and
Kahal are the other Californians. . . . Del Mar stewards on
Thursday handed trainer Craig Dollase a 15-day suspension starting
Dec. 13 and $2,500 fine because Abby Girl tested positive for an
illegal level of albuterol following a May 20 victory at Hollywood
Park. Dollase indicated he'll consider appealing. He said the drug
was administered to treat an allergy. . . . Jerry Bailey and Bill
Mott were the leading rider and trainer at the Saratoga meet that
ended Monday. Bailey set a track record with 50 wins, the last
aboard Perfect Sting in the Diana Handicap. The New York horses
return to Belmont Park for a 33-day season opening today. . . .
City Zip, who deadheated with Yonaguska in Saturday's Hopeful
Stakes, became the fourth horse to sweep Saratoga's three big
2-year-old stakes. Dehere, in 1993, had been the most recent to do
it. . . . Weekend stakes wins by El Corredor and Saudi Poetry put
Bob Baffert back atop the national trainer standings with $7.4
million in earnings, about $100,000 more than Bobby Frankel. . . .
Frankel's Chester House, who scored his biggest victory last month
in the Arlington Million, has been retired because of a shoulder
injury. . . . Silic, Julio Canani's 1999 Breeders' Cup Mile winner,
has been retired after a bone chip was found in a foreleg. . . .
Trainer Ron McAnally ended his extraordinary Del Mar losing streak
at 50 races when Jimmy Z won Sunday. . . . LemonDrop Kid remained
No. 1, with 16 of the 19 first-place votes, in the NTRA media poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
