r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG)     09-07 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO TEAM LOOKS FAMILIAR TO USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After months of recruiting, linebacker Zeke Moreno
finally made his college decision, so one of the first things he
did was call his friend, fellow San Diego prep star Lonnie Ford. It
makes perfect sense today, since Moreno and Ford ended up at USC
and are crucial players on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't talking about USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Lonnie I was going to commit to Colorado,'' Moreno
said. ``because we just wanted to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford knew the pair would end up at either USC or Colorado but
urged Moreno to wait until his campus visit with the Trojans. That
trip convinced both to commit to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have easily been in this same spot this week where we
would be playing against USC,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an unusual position. USC plays Colorado on Saturday for
the first time in 36 years, but the two schools have spent most of
the mid-`90s battling for the top players in Southern California,
and in some cases, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   They are probably more familiar with each other than some of
their own conference rivals.
</P>
<P>
   There's a long list of players whose final two school choices
were Colorado and USC, and each school has its share of victories.
While the Trojans got Moreno and Ford, the Buffaloes grabbed
linebacker Jashon Sykes and tailback Marcus Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven players on the Colorado roster are from California,
and this week's game will be a homecoming with many players
scrambling for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes this game so different is a lot of guys from
Colorado are finally getting a chance to come home to their family
and friends, and they want to put on a show,'' USC cornerback Kris
Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   The connections even extend off the field. Colorado chancellor
Richard Byyny earned his bachelor's and doctorate degrees from USC.
</P>
<P>
   Even the coaches have mixed emotions. USC running backs coach
Kennedy Pola was an assistant at Colorado for two seasons
(1997-98). Linebackers coach A.J. Christoff was a Buffalo from
1995-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recruited a lot of those players and I want them to do
well,'' Christoff said. ``And I want us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Christoff remembers recruiting Ford, along with current Trojans
Markus Steele, Bernard Riley and Omar Nazel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recruited Southern California like it was in-state,''
Christoff said.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason was that former Colorado coach Rick Neuheisel
had close ties to the area, having played and coached at UCLA.
Former USC coach John Robinson used to say that Colorado was a
bigger rival for players than UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neuheisel was here every chance he had,'' Pola said. ``We put
a lot of coaches down here. Those guys that USC didn't want, we
stayed on top of, and those that didn't want to stay in the area,
we welcomed with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pola believes that era is fading and attributes it to some
of the changes on USC's current coaching staff, which includes
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt I could come in here and battle. At Colorado and
San Diego State, I always thought we had a shot,'' Pola said.
``Now, we have a young and enthusiastic staff of recruiters at USC.
I believe this staff is a recruiting staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest battle last season occurred over a Colorado
native. Houston, who gained 98 yards last week in his college debut
against Colorado State, was considered one of the top tailbacks in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, USC was trying to snatch a player from the
Buffaloes' backyard, although Houston eventually decided to stay
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me it was between us and Colorado,'' said USC wide
receiver Marcell Allmond, who hosted Houston on his recruiting
trip. ``I thought it was a 50-50 chance, but I guess he wanted to
be with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Another player who kept both schools on edge was Sykes. USC
feverishly attempted to sign him after Paul Hackett was hired but
couldn't convince him to stay in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was torn between the two places,'' said Richard, a high
school teammate at Serra High in Gardena. ``But he was wary that we
had depth. I told him that you have to come here and compete, but I
guess he didn't take my word.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with Sykes' decision. He is considered one of
the premier linebackers in the country and a strong candidate for
the Butkus Award.
</P>
<P>
   But his situation might be one of the last major competitions
between USC and Colorado since Gary Barnett replaced Neuheisel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis now is the state of Colorado,'' Christoff said.
``Gary Barnett was a high school coach in Colorado and said he
wanted all the Colorado kids he could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Pola: ``I don't think that staff has that much of a
relationship in Southern California.''
</P>
<P>
   But that won't affect Saturday's contest, when players from both
sides imagine themselves wearing the uniform of the team across the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to play the school that recruited you,'' Moreno
said. ``I think it'll be good seeing some of the coaches that
recruited me. They tried to get me to change my mind when I
committed to USC, but I think I made the right decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
