<SLUG> BC-CALPINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY FIRM GENERATES CONTROVERSY ON ITS WAY TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY YAMANOUCHI  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; Calpine moved swiftly more than two years ago
to take advantage of a window of opportunity when California
deregulated its energy markets.
</P>
<P>
   The small San Jose, Calif., independent power producer acquired
gas-fired power plants as well as many of the geothermal plants and
steam fields in Lake County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious acquisitions strategy paid off, helping it become
the nation's largest geothermal producer. Today, the company shows
no signs of slowing down in its relentless drive to become the
country's largest independent energy producer.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of its second quarter this year, Calpine's assets had
grown to $5.6 billion, up from $2.5 billion a year ago. At the same
time, it has seen its net income steadily increase to $95.1 million
in 1999 from $7.4 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The state's energy shortage ``created real opportunities for
us,'' said Peter Cartwright, Calpine's president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   But the soaring profits of Calpine and other independent power
producers have sparked investigations by the state Public Utilities
Commission, state attorney general's office and federal agents of
possible price gouging.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright denied that prices have been manipulated. He said his
company is attempting to lower prices by building new power plants,
not to profit from price spikes in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, 70, started the company in 1984 after spending 19
years helping General Electric build nuclear power plants and five
years at an engineering firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Calpine started out providing management
services for independent power producers. After a few years, the
company got into the the power producing business itself. In 1989,
Calpine bought its first megawatt, enough power to serve 1,000
households, from an existing power plant at the Geysers, a
geothermal power facility in Lake County.
</P>
<P>
   It has been during the past few years, though, that the company
has grown the most. It has 45 existing and proposed plants in 27
states in the U.S. and Alberta, Canada. In California, it has
plants in San Jose, Gilroy, Yuba City, King City, Pittsburg and
Watsonville, as well as Sonoma and Lake counties.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine's growth accelerated in large part because the state
deregulated the energy market in 1998, forcing utilities to sell
off most of their generating capacity based on fossil fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deregulated power market has really opened up and
expanded,'' Cartwright said. ``We've been building up for this for
a long time, building up the capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the electricity industry shifted as the growing
demand for juice required companies with the wherewithal to build
larger, more-efficient power plants. Each megawatt placed online
can require an investment of as much as $500,000, according to Ron
Walter, Calpine's senior vice president of business development and
head of the firm's mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of decades ago, power companies were building
50-megawatt plants. Today, power producing giants are building
1,000-megawatt behemoths that generate enough power for 1 million
homes.
</P>
<P>
   During Calpine's early growth period, Walter sought small
generators that lack the capital to continue building plants.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Calpine's aggressive plant acquisition strategy helped
the company grow from 141 megawatts in 1994 to 3,355 megawatts in
1999 _ enough to light 3.3 million households.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with larger power companies like Enron, which operates
16,000 megawatts worldwide, Cartwright's company is a small-fry.
</P>
<P>
   But Cartwright said Calpine has big plans to get up to 30,000
megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   In its Sept. 4 issue, Fortune magazine ranked Calpine 25th among
its 100 fastest-growing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine ranked 34th in the country in megawatt sales during the
third quarter of 1999, according to the Power Marketing
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Energy analysts, though, say Calpine is on track to become the
largest independent power plant company in the country. According
to industry sources, the company has the most generating capacity
under construction and in development in North America.
</P>
<P>
   To finance its acquisition and development program, Calpine has
raised $5.6 billion in financing since November 1999, according to
Neil Stein, an independent-power analyst with Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this industry, they have unprecedented access to capital,''
Stein said. ``Their credit ratings have steadily improved over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with fewer and fewer plants left to acquire, Calpine
has had to shift its strategy, focusing instead on building plants
from the ground up. The idea is to employ the latest technology to
produce efficient generating plants that will phase out older
plants.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that distinguishes Calpine from many other power
plant companies is its focus on the domestic market. When the
company went public in 1996, the conventional wisdom was to invest
in emerging markets such as Southeast Asia, while the United States
was seen as a dead market, noted Stein.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've discovered is that this is the one market you
really want to be invested in,'' he said. ``All the price spikes
that we've seen in California and the threat of blackouts are
really a testament to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The specter of rolling brownouts this summer in California in
particular has underscored the need for the state to shore up its
power-generating capacity. The need was so acute that California
had to go out of state to fill 20 percent of its energy needs.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine has three plants already under construction in the state
_ two in Pittsburg are scheduled to come online, one in July 2001
and the other in June 2002, according to the California Energy
Commission. Another in Yuba City is scheduled to begin operations
in September 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these will add 1,880 megawatts to meet the
California's thirst for power, which currently runs as high as
45,000 megawatts during peak periods.
</P>
<P>
   But some energy companies are unhappy about the wholesale prices
they are getting for the power they provide, and have threatened to
stop building any power plants in California.
</P>
<P>
   The California Independent System Operator, which runs most of
the state's electricity grid, lowered the wholesale price cap twice
to its present $250, from $750 in June.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright dismissed the threats of leaving as posturing and has
pledged to continue to build plants here. ``Price caps don't hurt
us. We know that California needs the power,`' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Highlander, a Calpine spokesman, said the company's plans
to build plants in California have not changed since the ISO
lowered price caps, nor since state lawmakers placed a $65 cap on
San Diego consumer electricity bills last week.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who has a ``strong buy rating'' for Calpine, projects
that during the next five years, the company's market share in the
fragmented industry will grow from 1.5 percent to 5 percent and
earnings will grow 40 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's rapid growth could also be a liability. Jeff
Wolinsky, an analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's, said that the 40
percent of the company's current cash flow this year insulated from
market price volatility could drop to only 20 percent by 2004, due
to Calpine's rapid acquisition and development strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Wolinsky added that the company could be at a disadvantage due
to its small market share in each region it serves. In California,
for example, Calpine operates 1,300 megawatts of 55,000 megawatts
of in-state generation, according to the company and the California
Energy Commission. By contrast, PG&AMP;E operates 8,500 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   In this regard, Mike Florio of The Utility Reform Network said
Calpine doesn't have the buying power of large energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   Florio also said Calpine plans to build some plants in urban
areas where power is most needed but sometimes more difficult to
get approved. Such is the case in south San Jose, where
neighborhood groups, politicians and the mayor have rallied against
Calpine's proposal to build a 600-megawatt plant on a 14-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the proposed Metcalf plant will be an eyesore and
increase pollution. They also say it is unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright said that the plant would not create more pollution,
noting the facility is nowhere near as close to residential areas
as a similar plant Calpine recently built in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose resident Elizabeth Cord, who is heading up efforts
by the Santa Teresa Consumer Action Group against Metcalf, said the
plant would be the worst-polluting business in the city. Cisco,
which is also proposing to set up operations in South San Jose, has
opposed the plant, saying it is not necessary and would interfere
with its own expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   Cord said that ``there's absolutely no community outreach
anywhere'' by Calpine and the California Energy Commission's review
process.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Haber, associate director of the air division at the
federal Environment Protection Agency, said the Metcalf plant does
meet regulatory standards and is a ``pretty good plant'' compared
to other possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at kyamanouchi(at)sfchronicle.com
</P>
