<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore's momentum: What a difference some time, a convention and a
popular veep make
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCRANTON. Pa. _ When Al Gore last visited northeast Pennsylvania
in June his campaign appeared on the verge of a nervous breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the polls, the Democratic candidate generated even more
negative headlines here when he was forced to scramble for a new
site for a health care event after the local Bishop, angry over the
vice president's support of abortion rights, nixed his scheduled
visit to a Catholic hospital.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a few months, a successful convention and a
well received vice-presidential choice make. Gore returned to this
hilly industrial pocket of an important swing state Thursday having
turned around, at least for now, what had been a struggling
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A telling sign of the changing tide occurred when Gore stopped
by Shooky's Deli Restaurant shortly before lunchtime. He was
greeted by Scranton Mayor Jim Connors who announced he was
switching from Republican to Democrat. The mayor cited Gore as his
reason for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll win northeast Pennsylvania and all of
Pennsylvania,'' said Connors, a flamboyant character who has feuded
with the state's Republican governor, Tom Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Other indicators point to a Gore rebound. A fresh batch of
post-Labor Day polls show that Gore, bolstered by strong support
from women, has retained his post-convention bounce.
</P>
<P>
   He also solidified labor support Thursday when the last major
union hold-out, the Teamsters, voted to endorse him. The Teamsters'
backing should give Gore's campaign a lift in Midwest battleground
states, where unions are strong.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's lead is narrow and he has lost momentum before,
particularly last spring when he failed to capitalize on his
primary sweep.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, buoyed by the change in fortune, the often-formal
candidate appears to be enjoying himself. He is looser on the
campaign trail, joshing with voters in diners, sports bars and
sports stadiums. On Wednesday he even stepped in as a temporary
pitcher for the Detroit Tigers during the team's batting practice
at its new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After months of watching Bush set the agenda, Gore recently has
kept his Republican opponent on the defensive on a range of issues
from health care to Social Security to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing workers at a Gentex plant in nearby Carbondale, Gore
pressed Bush to explain how he would pay the trillion-dollar cost
to phase in his Social Security plan, which would allow workers to
invest a portion of their payroll taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's an important specific, that trillion dollar
hole. Don't you think you want to know the answer before the
election?'' Gore asked the workers, who make lenses.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Gore unveiled his economic blueprint, his campaign
took out an ad in the New York Times that contrasts the candidates'
plans. Entitled ``Does it matter if the numbers add up?'' the ad
claims that Bush's tax cut proposals and spending plans ``would
bust the budget surplus and plunge the nation back into deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has countered that the surplus will be
sufficient to pay for the candidate's $1.3 trillion tax cut and
spending programs. Bush campaign officials accuse Gore of
underestimating the cost of his programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was trailing in Pennsylvania for much of the spring
and summer, Gore now enjoys increasing momentum in the state, said
Terry Madonna, a pollster at Millersville University.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna said that Gore's populist message is appealing to the
blue collar, socially conservative Democrats who populate this part
of the state and who are essential to any presidential candidate
who wants to carry Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bringing them home,'' said Madonna of a group of voters
who have swung back and forth between the parties in the last two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was targeting these workers at Gentex when he told them
that he advocates a prescription drug benefit for the elderly that
benefits ``not just the poor but the middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
