<SLUG> BC-FED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARINGS HIGHLIGHT HOME LOAN ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM ZUCKERMAN  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; For some consumers, a home equity loan is a
great source of cash to fix up the house or put kids through
college.
</P>
<P>
   But for others _ especially those with small incomes and little
financial savvy _ borrowing against the home can be a nightmare
ride on a merry-go-round they can't get off.
</P>
<P>
   Omaga McGlothin, a 51-year-old east Oakland, Calif., resident,
found that out the hard way. After she lost her nurse's assistant
job six years ago, she refinanced her mortgage, collecting about
$10,000 in cash to pay for living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, she owed about $11,000 on the three-bedroom stucco
house she bought in 1969. Today, after several more refinancings,
her debt has ballooned to $113,000. And her monthly mortgage
payment is up to $920 per month, more than three times the $250 she
paid before she refinanced.
</P>
<P>
   With less than $2,000 coming in each month from the foster care
services she provides, McGlothin hasn't able to keep up. She is
trying to negotiate a new payment schedule with the current lender,
Pennsylvania's Advanta Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a struggle,'' said McGlothin. ``But I will find a way to
keep my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Cases like McGlothin's were the subject of Federal Reserve
hearings yesterday in San Francisco. Officials of the central bank
are considering how to enforce a 1994 law that set rules governing
high-fee, high-rate loans to low-income homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups at the hearing said that high-pressure marketing
of rip-off home loans _ so-called predatory lending _ has put
thousands of poor people on the edge of financial ruin. Such
lenders prey on the most vulnerable, they said, seeking out
customers with tarnished credit and job histories, and few other
places to turn for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous problem of people losing their houses,''
said Consumers Union attorney Norma Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, lenders stress that not all loans to borrowers
with low incomes or less-than-prime credit records are predatory.
And, indeed, government officials and consumer groups are eager to
boost the flow of credit to low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because poor borrowers often are easy marks, the business
is rife with abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Some lenders, for example, charge low interest rates for short
periods before switching to sky-high permanent rates. Others charge
huge up-front fees. Still others set payment schedules in which
principal balances don't get paid down, but rise instead, putting
the borrower deeper in debt.
</P>
<P>
   That apparently is what has happened to McGlothin. ``When I make
a payment, it doesn't take anything off the principal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McGlothin has borrowed from several lenders, and it's not clear
which ones were responsible for the worst abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Advanta, her current lender, said it couldn't comment on her
case, but that it treats customers fairly. ``There may be some
unfortunate situations out there created by less-than-credible
lenders,'' spokeswoman Catherine Reid said. ``Advanta is not one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups at yesterday's Fed hearing said regulators
aren't doing enough to rein in rip-off lenders. But, they noted,
borrowers must take responsibility, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think nothing of shopping in six stores for a
toaster,'' said Consumer Union's Garcia. ``They should so the same
thing for a loan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail sam zuckerman at szuckerman(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
