<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO'S STOCK PRICE FALLS FOR NO REASON 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHLEEN PENDER  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When it comes to Internet stocks, no news is bad
news.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Tim Koogle, chief executive officer of Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Koogle was the luncheon attraction at the Robertson Stephens
Internet conference in San Francisco on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After he delivered a news-free speech that seemed to confirm
what analysts and the media have been saying for months, Yahoo
stock plummeted 10 percent in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question about a slowdown in Internet
advertising, Koogle admitted that the online market has been in a
consolidation phase for nine or 10 months. ``It takes a little bit
of the upside away in the near term,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long the consolidation would last, he said it would be
``most visible for a couple quarters,'' but that long-term, Yahoo
would benefit as the number of competitors decreased.
</P>
<P>
   Koogle finished his speech around the same time the markets
closed. Within the next hour or so, Yahoo's stock plummeted from
$112 to a low of $103.
</P>
<P>
   While the stock was tanking, I asked several money managers who
heard the speech whether Koogle had sprung any surprises.
</P>
<P>
   No one could come up with a thing.
</P>
<P>
   The best explanation came from Dave Karraker, a spokesman for
BlueLight.com, the Kmart-affiliated Web operation that has several
partnerships with Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Koogle didn't appear to say anything new, and that was the
problem. This was his first real speaking engagement since the
whole online advertising thing blew up on Yahoo. I guess investors
expected him to say more.
</P>
<P>
   ``His comments didn't seem to do anything to calm anyone's
nerves. With how volatile the Internet sector is right now, you
almost have to say something really decisive, even controversial,
to get people back into the frame of mind that your company is a
fighter that will make things work no matter what. Just laying low
will get you battered.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo blamed the stock drop on the media, saying that news
services misinterpreted Koogle's comments. At least one news
service, Dow Jones, did ``clarify'' a headline, saying that Koogle
``did not explicitly state that the company expects a near-term
decrease in advertising spending.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yahoo spokeswoman said Koogle's comments referred to
consolidation in the online market in general, not to consolidation
in online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like hair splitting to me, but it was enough to turn
Yahoo's stock around. It recovered most of its after-hours loss
Wednesday, but reversed course again yesterday, closing at $106.94,
down $5.13.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Blue Light Special
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned BlueLight.com made a presentation at the
conference just before Koogle's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Koogle, BlueLight CEO Mark Goldstein did break some news.
</P>
<P>
   Of most interest to San Franciscans is the new store BlueLight
is creating on the ground floor of its new headquarters building on
Jefferson Street in Fisherman's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   When it opens in November or December, the 8,500-square-foot
store will feature an Internet kiosk like those being installed in
Kmart stores, a Jamba Juice outlet and a Kodak one-hour photo
processing center.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, it may add Kmart-branded products like the new
BlueLight PC.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart initially wanted to sell the computer for $399. But Intel,
``in classic Intel'' fashion, wouldn't provide the chip that
Kmart's manufacturer, LG Electronics, wanted to use, Goldstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   So Kmart had to substitute a more-expensive Intel processor,
which brought the retail price to $449, including free Internet
service, which BlueLight provides to anyone who wants it.
</P>
<P>
   BlueLight will call attention to its new store with a huge
flashy sign modeled after the classic blinking blue light that used
to attract Kmart shoppers to temporary specials like four sub
sandwiches for a dollar. Kmart is bringing back the blue light in
its stores and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said the sign hasn't received final approval from the
city, but it probably will because the only restriction on signs in
Fisherman's Wharf is a 25-foot height limit.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Goldstein, it's clear that Kmart is not going
``upscale'' in its stores or Web site.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, BlueLight will expand its Web site to include a
photo-processing deal with Kodak, a gift registry, sweepstakes
offers and a free gossip newsletter from National Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart is the No.1 outlet for National Enquirer, which Goldstein
called ``the Kmart shopper's Reuters.''
</P>
<P>
   People who sign up for the newsletter will get an HTML page
e-mailed to them. The page will contain National Enquirer content
in the middle and Kmart ads and offers around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter is a ``prospecting tool,'' Goldstein said. ``We
have 6 or 7 million e-mail addresses now.'' By the end of 2001, the
company hopes to have 20 million e-mail addresses, at least $100
million in sales and be turning a profit.
</P>
<P>
   It also plans to do an initial public offering next year. In the
meantime, it can live off $80 million in second-round financing it
recently secured from Kmart and Softbank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Drawing a Crowd
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's not public yet, BlueLight is one of the few
pure B2C (business-to-consumer) Internet companies that drew an
overflow crowd at the conference, which concludes today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies that are struggling are the B2C providers, the
e-tailers, that are really trying to deal with gaining brand
identity in a market that's crowded,'' said John Rohal, director of
research for Robertson Stephens. ``People have shifted from the
idea that new brands are going to be created on the Web, to the
idea that established brands (like Kmart) are going to extend to
the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Rohall said the biggest audiences were for Internet
infrastructure companies, mainly in network equipment, fiber optics
and communications chips.
</P>
<P>
   Presentations by B2B (business-to-business) companies like Ariba
and Commerce One were also ``really packed in really big rooms'' at
the Ritz-Carlton hotel, Rohall said.
</P>
<P>
   Rohall said that Phone.com, which makes software for getting
wireless applications onto cellular phones, and Lifeminders.com,
which will be delivering breaking Olympics news to mobile devices,
were also big attractions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Full Disclosure
</P>
<P>
   The Robertson Stephens conference is the first big investment
confab since the Securities and Exchange Commission passed the Fair
Disclosure Regulation. Reg FD is supposed to ensure that big
investors like those who attend these conferences don't get
material information before the little guys.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the investment banks that host these get-togethers
only invite their big clients. Some allow the media, but exclude
reporters from ``breakout sessions,'' where analysts get to ask
CEOs questions. The answers often move a stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Reg FD hasn't taken effect yet, and Robertson Stephens excluded
the press from breakout sessions this week. Rohall said his firm
hasn't decided what it will do in the future. ``We're still trying
to understand Reg FD. Our legal guys are looking hard at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
