ancient city called Cancuen, meaning ``place of serpents,''
archaeologists have uncovered one of the largest and most splendid
palaces of Maya kings ever discovered. The palace has more than 170
high-ceiling rooms which were built around 11 courtyards and spread
over an area greater than two football fields. A burial vase frrom
the Mayan site. (Christopher Talbot/National Geographic Society/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CLEVELAND -- Sept. 7, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President Al
Gore may be trying to shed himself of President Clinton, but he is
making no attempt to shed himself of the Clinton Cabinet. In fact,
the vice president is relying more and more these days on the
expertise, advice and support of a gallery of members and former
members of the Clinton Cabinet. Gore with former Secretary of the
Treasury Robert Rubin before a speech unveiling Gore's economic
plans, Wednesday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 7, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-1 -- Marat Safin
showed off his many-splendored talents -- 135-mph serves, crushing
groundstrokes, a wall-climbing retrieval of an overhead -- to reach
the U.S. Open semifinals Thursday in a performance reminiscent of
Pete Sampras at age 19. Infamous already for breaking more rackets
than anyone else, the 20-year-old Russian kept his temper in check
and his errors down as he beat Germany's Nicolas Kiefer 7-5, 4-6,
7-6 (5), 6-3. Safin in action, Thursday. (G. Paul Burnett/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LATRUN, Israel -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT.
10 -- ISRAEL-U.S.-AID-COX -- Wednesday is the deadline for a peace
agreement between the Palestinians and Israel -- and the
Palestinians have threatened to declare a state with, or without
Israel's approval. With a country smaller than Vermont, Israelis
say they can only offer land for peace if their army is stronger.
Israel already draws one-fifth of all U.S. foreign aid, and will
likely be getting more. A young boy runs past two Sherman tanks at
Israel's Armored Corps Museum in Latrun, Israel, displayed among
the weapons that Israel has relied on for survival during it's
52-year history. (Evelyn Hockstein/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MEXICO CITY -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 10
-- MEXICO-HUMANRIGHTS-COX -- Rosario Ibarra, 73, looks at photos of
her son Jesus on the walls of her Mexico City home. After her son
was kidnapped by security forces in Monterrey in 1975, Ibarra began
a quest to find him and started an support group, the Eureka Group,
to fight for the disappeared and torture victims. The group has
forced the release of about 1,500 political prisoners in the 1980s,
some of whom had vanished for as long as nine years. (Luis J.
Jimenez/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
