   (NYT50) BALTIMORE -- Sept. 7, 2000 -- CAMPAIGN-HEALTH -- If
there was one political lesson to be gleaned from a conversation
with 15 retirees at the John T. Booth Senior Center in Baltimore,
Md., it might be this: Gov. George W. Bush could have trouble
selling his plan for redesigning the Medicare system among the very
people who depend on the system now. Syd Goldfield, 71, left, and
Rose Rose D'Ambrosio, 86, right, complained about the policies and
practices of managed care companies. Maggie Melton, 71, center,
said she knew people who had to decide between buying food and
buying their prescription drugs. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
