<P>
   (NYT30) CANCUEN, Guatemala -- Sept. 7, 2000 -- EMBARGOED UNTIL
11:30 P.M., EDT, THURSDAY, SEPT. 7 -- SCI-MAYAN-PALACE-4-B&AMP;W -- In
a remote jungle of Guatemala, among the remains of a little-known
ancient city called Cancuen, meaning ``place of serpents,''
archaeologists have uncovered one of the largest and most splendid
palaces of Maya kings ever discovered. The palace has more than 170
high-ceiling rooms which were built around 11 courtyards and spread
over an area greater than two football fields. An artist's
rendering of what the site might have looked like. (Luis Fernando
Luin/ National Geographic Society/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) CANCUEN, Guatemala -- Sept. 7, 2000 -- EMBARGOED UNTIL
11:30 P.M., EDT, THURSDAY, SEPT. 7 -- SCI-MAYAN-PALACE-3 -- In a
remote jungle of Guatemala, among the remains of a little-known
ancient city called Cancuen, meaning ``place of serpents,''
archaeologists have uncovered one of the largest and most splendid
palaces of Maya kings ever discovered. The palace has more than 170
high-ceiling rooms which were built around 11 courtyards and spread
over an area greater than two football fields. An excavation of a
room at the royal palace. (Christopher Talbot/National Geographic
Society/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) CANCUEN, Guatemala -- Sept. 7, 2000 -- EMBARGOED UNTIL
11:30 P.M., EDT, THURSDAY, SEPT. 7 -- SCI-MAYAN-PALACE-2 -- In a
remote jungle of Guatemala, among the remains of a little-known
ancient city called Cancuen, meaning ``place of serpents,''
archaeologists have uncovered one of the largest and most splendid
palaces of Maya kings ever discovered. The palace has more than 170
high-ceiling rooms which were built around 11 courtyards and spread
over an area greater than two football fields. Arthur Demarest,
right, from Vanderbilt University, stands near a piece of an altar
and a stela, or marker, exposed at the site of the dig.
(Christopher Talbot/National Geographic Society/The New York Times)
</P>
