<SLUG> BC-GLF-CANADIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS FINDS THE GOING TOUGH IN CANADA, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKVILLE, Ontario _ For some reason, when Tiger Woods has
traveled north to Canada, his performance has headed south.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Woods missed the cut at the Bell Canadian Open,
the only time in 86 career starts on the PGA Tour as a professional
that Woods has missed a cut. Thursday, Woods returned to the
Canadian Open for the first time since 1997, trying to accomplish a
rare triple crown. Lee Trevino is the only player to win the U.S.
Open, the British Open and the Canadian Open in the same year
(1971), and after waltzing to victories at both the U.S. and
British Opens, Woods arrived in the suburbs of Toronto this week
hoping to add even more luster to his history-making season.
</P>
<P>
   But after Thursday's opening round at Glen Abbey Golf Club,
winning the Canadian Open will be no easy task for the world's No.
1 player. Spraying shots all over the back nine, and making a
costly double-bogey at No. 11, Woods finished at even par 72, tied
for 45th place, seven strokes off the lead, and well off his game.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Sutherland, who has never won on tour, was the surprise
first-round leader, shooting a 65. Cameron Beckman (66) was alone
in second place, while Sergio Garcia, J.L. Lewis, Jesper Parnevik
and Brian Watts were tied for third place at 67.
</P>
<P>
   Does Woods still have plenty of time to come back? Of course he
does. Would he have to play much better to win? Of course he would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of ugly,'' Woods said, describing his play over
the final 10 holes. ``I hit it left, I hit it right, I hit it
short, I hit it long, I hit a lot of bunkers. Golf is a fickle
game. It was just one of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods coughed occasionally as he spoke, still feeling lingering
symptoms from a flu he caught last month. Many were surprised that
Woods played this week, instead of taking more time off. After this
week, Woods will not play again until the Presidents Cup in
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken antibiotics, but I haven't had enough time to get
it totally out of my system,'' Woods said of the flu. ``If I don't
play this week, I'd take seven weeks off in a row. That's way too
long. Five weeks in a row is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods started well, reaching three under par through eight
holes, but then things fell apart. He made a three-putt bogey at
No. 9, missing badly from just 3 feet away on his putt for par.
Then at the par-4 No. 11, Woods pulled his tee shot left into deep
rough, leaving himself with a difficult approach shot, over a tree
and over water, just to reach the green. Woods could not pull it
off. The ball sailed high over the tree, but it dropped well short
of the green and into the water. After a drop and a penalty stroke,
Woods hit his fourth shot onto the green, but it landed 15 feet
past the cup. Woods missed his putt attempt for bogey, and the
double-bogey dropped him to even par. Woods made another bogey at
No. 14, but he birdied the final hole, and barely extended his
streak of consecutive rounds of par or better to 32.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even struggling, Woods remained the focal point of the
tournament, and the Toronto area has gone wild for him. When Woods
confirmed last week that he would play, the remaining tickets sold
out within hours. And Thursday, many in his huge gallery yelled,
``Thanks for coming, Tiger,'' as he walked by, treatment that Woods
clearly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people scream a lot of other things before,
especially after they've had their favorite beverage,'' said Woods
smiling. ``This was nice. That's one reason why I've always enjoyed
playing in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are friendly,'' he said. ``I'm still not out of the
tournament. I have an early tee time, hopefully the wind won't
blow, and I can get back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods will have to catch Sutherland, who birdied six of his
first nine holes during a splendid round. Meanwhile, Garcia
continued to play well, bolstered by his recent performance at the
Battle of Bighorn, the made-for-television match against Woods, won
by Garcia, 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to beat Tiger was probably the best thing that
could happen to me,'' Garcia said. ``It gave me a lot of
confidence, of course. Hopefully, I'll be able to continue playing
well this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
