u p BC-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-07 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AS BUSH HITS BUMPS, A RIFT OVER STEERING 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The political troubles facing Gov. George W. Bush
have exposed a serious rift between the Bush organization and the
Republican National Committee over how best to conduct the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-ranking officials at party headquarters here say
they were furious that the campaign had shut them out and rejected
their advice on things like television commercials and how Bush
negotiates a schedule of debates with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking party official official complained that the
view from Austin, Texas, where Bush has his headquarters, has been
that the party has nothing to add.
</P>
<P>
   ``They acted like they were the smartest people in the world _
and that no one here in Washington had anything to contribute,'' he
said. ``Their view was: `We really understand the American people.
You people in Washington don't.'''
</P>
<P>
   Officials on both sides said that there had been some friction
for months between officials in Austin and at the party but that it
escalated two weeks ago when Bush himself ordered the party to
shelve a 30-second commercial questioning Gore's ethics by using
misleading information.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican officials said the party had been unfairly
blamed for championing the commercial, even though several Bush
aides had pushed for it, as well. Some Bush aides, in turn,
complained that the party did not have a better chain-of-command
for reviewing and distributing advertisements _ and that it had
already delivered the commercial to some television stations when
the decision was made to pull it.
</P>
<P>
   After the controversy surrounding the pulled commercial, Bush
campaign officials removed David Israelite, the party's political
director, as coordinator of its advertising campaign. The campaign
replaced him with Maria Cino, who was the Bush organization's
political director during the primaries and who moved to the party
in the spring as a deputy chairman.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush lieutenant said Israelite had been ``the center of the
universe as far as the spots go,'' but that campaign officials
prefer ``a broader group of people considering the options.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest complaints among party officials is that for
months they were rebuffed in their efforts to keep Gore on the
defensive by starting an early advertising campaign, as the
Democrats did against Bush. Throughout the summer, Democrats spent
$35 million on commercials promoting Gore or pounding Bush, while
Republicans spent roughly $25 million. Some party officials said
they had pressed for the campaign to approve a much more aggressive
television blitz against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush officials said there was no need for Bush to begin
attacking when he was enjoying a solid lead in the polls and when
he was vowing to keep the tone of the campaign positive.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials also complained that members of the campaign
high-command in Texas instructed them earlier in the year to stop
staging events and putting out news releases intended to knock Gore
off stride. Such efforts, these officials said, could have
prevented the vice president from gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin wants to control everything,'' said one strategist who
works closely with officials at the campaign and at the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   One party official said he had suggested that the party put on
an anti-Gore event to help Bush regain momentum and capture
attention in the press immediately after the Democratic convention.
But, he said, the idea was dismissed by Bush aides in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   As is common for a presidential campaign, the Bush organization
effectively seized control of the party after the primary season
ended and installed some of its loyalists _ including Cino and Fred
Meyer, the chief coordinator between the party and the Bush
campaign _ at party headquarters. It left the chairman, Jim
Nicholson, in place.
</P>
<P>
   Several people described Nicholson as a loyal partisan, and one
of the few top party officials who has not complained about the
Bush campaign. ``I'm not aware that there's very much concern,''
Nicholson said in an interview. ``In any campaign there are always
certain personality conflicts. But there's even very little of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many party stalwarts who work closely with Nicholson went as
far as to say that members of the tight-knit Bush high command in
Austin were overly confident, even arrogant. A mocking phrase
making the rounds among party officials here is ``Austin Knows
Best.''
</P>
<P>
   Several well-placed Republicans said the confusion over the
advertising campaign _ and who is running things _ has frustrated
many top officials, including the party's chief of staff, Tom Cole,
and Alex Castellanos, the media consultant who is producing the
Republican commercials. Neither agreed to be interviewed for this
article.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for such tensions to arise at a time when a
candidate is watching his poll numbers sag, as Bush is. But many
officials on both sides said the strains are deeper han usual,
prompting one party official to say that Bush aides would likely
investigate sources for this article. ``There will be witch
hunts,'' he said. ``There will be victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The tensions stand in marked contrast to the relationship
between the Gore campaign and the the Democratic National
Committee, which have worked closely together to mount a drive to
discredit Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DNC has been a lot more coordinated with the campaign,''
added one strategist with close ties to the Republican Party, ``and
has been complimenting the campaign on a message standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   It should not be a surprise, perhaps, that Bush camp has not
devoted more attention to party officials here. Bush has cast
himself as an outsider and built his campaign in part on his
disdain for Wasington and politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Some people involved in the Bush operation and at the party
cautioned that it was simplistic to characterize the rift as one
between Austin and Washington. They noted, for instance, that there
have been debates among officials in both places about how and when
the party should begin broadcasting commercials attacking Gore _
and that those debates are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of frayed egos, bad relationships and
strong-willed beliefs on difference sides,'' said one Republican
consultant who is close to officials in both camps. ``It's not the
kind of climate you want at this point in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a Bush campaign spokesman, brushed of suggestions
of disputes, saying, ``We're all working together to win in
November.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, said
some of the finger-pointing may be from Washington insiders who
feel left out of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a low of squawking, a lot of complaining _ there are
some babies involved in this stuff,'' he said. ```All of the people
who live inside Washington are resentful that they're not running
the campaign.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
