<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   GORE RIDES HIGH
</P>
<P>
   In the first spate of post-Labor Day national polls,
traditionally considered among the most important of the campaign
season, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas are
locked in a tight race, with Gore holding onto the momentum he
gained after his convention, having made great strides among women,
Democrats and independents. Gore also appears to have made
considerable headway in turning around negative views of his
personality and demeanor. He continues to hold an advantage over
Bush on the issues. A poll of 810 likely voters by ABC News and the
Washington Post shows Gore and Bush tied, at 47 percent each. A
Gallup Organization poll of 750 likely voters for CNN and USA Today
has Gore leading Bush by a margin of 47 to 40. And a Zogby poll of
1,001 likely voters shows a six-point lead for Gore. All three
polls have margins of sampling error of plus or minus four
percentage points and were taken Monday through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   THE RUNNING MATES: LIEBERMAN IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut ventured deep into Bush
country Thursday, showing up in Houston, and he plans to return
Monday, signaling the Democrats' new-found confidence and boldness
to campaign in a state they have almost no hope of carrying.
Lieberman, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, plans to hold
a campaign forum in Houston on Friday on children's health care, an
event that will no doubt include a few digs at George W. Bush's
record on the subject as governor of Texas. On Monday, Lieberman
will be the draw at a Democratic National Committee fund-raising
luncheon at the home of Thomas Meredith, the former chief financial
officer of Dell Computer and now the managing director of Dell's
venture capital unit. The DNC expects to raise $500,000 at the
lunch. Vice President Al Gore's campaign aides concede that he has
no chance of winning Texas, but they note that an opponent's home
state can be a useful forum for attacks, as Michael Dukakis learned
in 1988, when Bush's father showed up in Massachusetts to lament
water pollution in Boston harbor.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY DUCKS A BULLET
</P>
<P>
   The suspense was palpable. When Dick Cheney took a tour Thursday
through a Londonderry, N.H., optics firm to emphasize his ticket's
commitment to building a higher tech military, all eyes fell on an
outsized gray helmet festooned with the latest in panoramic night
vision goggles that was sitting on a table in the middle of the
factory floor. Visions of one of the most-ridiculed images of the
1988 campaign, Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts donning an
unbecoming helmet during an ill-fated photo opportunity aboard a
63-ton tank, danced through cameramen's heads. As Cheney handled
the helmet at Insight Technology Inc., an eager photographer called
out, ``Do you think it's the right size?'' Alas, the minefield was
avoided. ``Come on, guys, you don't think I'm going to try it on,
do you?'' Cheney replied, before walking over to a table of laser
devices.
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES: FISTICUFFS IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican Florida legislators from feuding families traded
punches early Wednesday morning after one legislator's father
reportedly insulted the other legislator's father on live radio.
According to The Miami Herald, State Rep. Renier Diaz de la
Portilla and Rep. Carlos Lacasa of duked it out in the parking lot
of Radio Mambi, a popular talk radio station, after Lacasa's father
insulted Diaz de la Portilla's father during a talk show on
election night. After the comments, Diaz de la Portilla went to the
station and demanded to be let in to defend his family's honor,
frightening Martha Flores, the radio host, who exclaimed into the
microphone, ``Hail Mary Mother of God, the Diaz de la Portilla's
are out there.'' Miguel Diaz de la Portilla, Renier's brother, had
just been badly beaten in his race for mayor of Miami-Dade County,
and had complained that the radio was unfair to him in favor of his
rival, incumbent Alex Penelas. Renier Diaz de la Potrilla and
Carlos Lacasa met in the parking lot and fought, although each man
says that the other started it. Flores begged her listeners to call
the police, and so many listeners responded that the flood of calls
caused the 911 system to crash.
</P>
<P>
   HAYDEN SEEKS CITY COUNCIL SEAT
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hayden has spent close to 40 years rocking the political
boat, first as a college student and later as a California
assemblyman and senator. The state's term limits law is forcing him
out of the Senate this year, but he is not giving up on public
life. He announced Thursday that he would run for Los Angeles City
Council next year, for a seat covering the Westside and parts of
the San Fernando Valley that is being vacated by Mike Feuer.
Hayden, a Democrat who unsuccessfully challenged Mayor Richard
Riordan in 1997, joins a crowded field in the nonpartisan race. He
has been a sharp critic of police corruption and school
construction problems, has promoted gang truces and has complained
that Angelenos feel unconnected to their government.
</P>
<P>
   THE CONVENTIONS:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA'S RED SCARE More than a month after the Republican
convention ended, Philadelphia residents learned Thursday of the
police department's rationale for a raid that resulted in 75
arrests at a warehouse where demonstrations were being planned. In
a newly unsealed warrant, the police said some of the protesters
had ``communist and leftist'' sponsors and others were sympathetic
to ``the former Soviet-allied World Federation of Trade Unions.''
Stefan Presser, legal director of the state American Civil
Liberties Union, called the warrant an outrage today. ``That
document could have been written by Hoover's FBI in the '40s and
'50s,'' he said, complaining that it failed to justify the raid and
served as a pretext for one of the largest instances of preventive
detention in modern American history. Some of those arrested were
kept in jail for more than two weeks after the convention and more
than 300 cases are pending against demonstrators. The warrant also
disclosed that the city police, who had been under court order not
to infiltrate protest groups, used state troopers as infiltrators.
Presser complained that the use of the troopers was ``an end run''
around basic civil liberties. The police declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES:
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Pittsburgh and Springfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD CHENEY _ Burlington, Vt.; Shelton and Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ New Orleans and Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH LIEBERMAN _ Houston and Miami
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER _ Denver
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
