u f BC-CMGI-INVEST-NYT &LR;      09-07 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN REVAMPING, CMGI TRIES TO LIFT SAGGING SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI, one of the earliest and savviest investors in the
Internet, announced a sweeping restructuring Thursday meant to
reassure disenchanted investors that it was moving toward becoming
profitable and is picking the winners among the plethora of
companies it owns.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Andover, Mass., has backed companies
including GeoCities, Lycos and Alta Vista. At the beginning of the
year, it had a market value of nearly $50 billion. But since then
its shares have plunged by 69 percent, more even than many other
big Internet companies. Its shares closed Thursday at $43.19, up
$3.50.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the company said it would reduce its 17 majority-owned
businesses to between 5 and 10, organized around 5 business lines.
It will merge three venture capital funds into a single fund. It
will also abandon plans for a fund meant to invest in Internet
companies overseas with Hicks, Muse Tate &AMP; Furst, the buyout firm,
and Pacific Century CyberWorks, an Internet company, because of
differences among the partners over the structure of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improving our path to profitability is the single driving
force here,'' said David Wetherell, CMGI's chairman, in a
conference call.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI identified five broad business categories in which it would
concentrate: search and portals; infrastructure and enabling
technologies; professional services; interactive marketing; and
electronic business. It hopes to wind up the revamping with one or
two companies in each of these areas that it will ultimately take
public. A few of its companies, like Engage, a database advertising
company, already have public shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   As for the weaker companies in each area, it will decide whether
to merge them into the stronger ones, sell them, or close them. It
also hopes to acquire new companies, especially profitable ones, to
shore up its businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell refused to name the businesses he considered weak or
to say how many people would be laid off, but he said the company
had routinely pared positions even as it had grown rapidly. CMGI
acquired 33 companies in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, CMGI did not create a business line for Internet
content or community, two areas in which it had many early
investments. Indeed some companies like Icast, an music and
entertainment service, fit awkwardly into the new structure.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it hoped that the new organization would
reassure investors who, looking past the dazzle of CMGI's
investment success, found the company a jumble of largely unrelated
businesses. Starting with CMGI's fiscal fourth quarter earnings to
be released on Sept. 21, the company will report revenue and
operating earnings separately for each of these segments.
</P>
<P>
   Paul L. Merenbloom, an analyst for Prudential Securities, said
CMGI's move reflected strength rather than the desperation seen at
so many Internet companies these days. With CMGI burning through
$50 million in cash each month and investing another $25 million
through its venture arm, the company's $1.7 billion in cash will
last nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an eternity on the Internet,'' Merenbloom said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
