<HEADLINE>
POWER RELIABILITY SERVICES SURGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two local stocks revved like overtaxed air
conditioners in the long, hot summer nearing its end.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, part of the red-hot industry providing reliable
power services to communications companies, have seen their shares
skyrocket since June. That's when Chatsworth's Capstone Turbine
held an initial public offering and Camarillo's Power-One split
shares 3-for-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cutting-edge companies in a universe that is just
starting to develop,'' said Masroor Siddiqui, an analyst who covers
both for Goldman Sachs and Co.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, Capstone's stock had risen from its June IPO
price of $16 to $83.375. Power-One's stock closed at $71.50 after
its June 5 split. Now it is at $172. The company will complete
another 2-for-1 split next week.
</P>
<P>
   The service the two provide is steady power supply almost
impervious to surges or blackouts. The industry calls it ``high
nines'' power in reference to the 99.9999 percent reliability
devices can achieve. In comparison, utility power grids provide
99.9 percent reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Capstone's turbines, installed in city buses, at landfills or at
businesses as small as convenience stores, can give customers an
independent electricity supply. Power-One's products come in
further down the supply line. The company makes power systems for
Internet service providers and telecommunications companies, making
devices like DC/DC converters that send the right voltage to
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Capstone especially benefited from the hot summer, which showed
the shortcomings of the power grid and deregulation. Southern
California spent much of August in energy conservation mode as the
system reached its breaking point and consumers lamented the new
era of electricity deregulation they once demanded.
</P>
<P>
   The summer ``shed more light on distributed generation,'' said
Capstone spokesman Keith Field. ``There are growing needs not only
for more power but for power reliability and power quality.''
</P>
<P>
   But more important to the future of both companies is the huge
need of the telecommunications industry for the services of both,
brownouts or not, Siddiqui said. Brokerage Needham and Co. noted
that power fluctuations cause more than 17,000 computer disruptions
per second around the world. In households, that could be no more
than being bumped offline. In industry, such disruptions could
bring computer controlled operations to a halt with disastrous
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has less to do with deregulation than with the digital
economy because that's an industry that needs high-quality power,''
Siddiqui said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts like the fundamentals of both companies. Power-One is
responsible for $10 billion of an $18 billion market for power
supply products.
</P>
<P>
   J. Keith Dunne, an analyst with Robertson Stephens, dates the
surge of the power industry less to the beginning of summer than to
a July conference when analysts christened power as The Next
Investor Sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then you've seen all these companies perform remarkably
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
