<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON PROPOSES GRANTS FOR SCHOOL PRINCIPALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Turning the nationwide shortage of school principals
into a campaign issue, Hillary Rodham Clinton proposed a plan
Thursday to help schools recruit and train 10,000 principals over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a speech at Queens College in her campaign for the
Senate, Clinton said the federal government should award a total of
$60 million a year to school districts that sorely need principals
and assistant principals. Schools could use the money, which would
come in the form of matching grants, to hire outstanding teachers
or people from other professions as principals.
</P>
<P>
   School districts could also use the grants to provide stipends
to ``master principals,'' who would train and provide support to
new principals, ideally with the help of nonprofit groups and
universities, Clinton said. Her proposal comes as an increasing
number of schools in New York City and across the nation are
struggling to replace principals who have retired or quit in the
face of mounting job pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``No school can reach its potential without a firm leader,''
Clinton said, addressing several hundred students and community
members. ``If we don't put an emphasis at the national level on
recruiting and training and placing more principals we are going to
fall further and further behind in the leadership gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that school districts should be required to
provide parents with statistics about violent incidents and
discipline problems in their children's schools. The information,
which would be posted on the Internet as part of a school's annual
report card, would include the number of students who were caught
with weapons and the number of violent incidents against teachers.
</P>
<P>
   She also introduced a plan to break some of the nation's largest
high schools into smaller schools, an idea that has already taken
off in many urban school districts, especially in New York City.
The proposal, which would cost $100 million a year in federal
funds, would focus primarily on high schools with several thousand
students.
</P>
<P>
   The new, smaller schools would remain in the same building and
use the same teachers, but most would need to hire new
administrators and support staff. School districts would receive
matching grants to cover hiring costs, Clinton's aides said.
Proponents of small high schools say they have fewer discipline
problems and higher graduation rates than large schools, which they
say breed violence and academic failure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In New York City, hundreds of small public schools have been
created over the last decade, many in buildings that once housed
enormous high schools. The schools often have a theme, like science
or the arts. Some are at the top of city achievement lists,
although others _ typically those that have been set up to serve
children who failed in traditional settings _ rank at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said money for the principal recruitment program
and the small schools program would come out of the federal budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do for children today what my parents and their
generation did for me and my classmates,'' she said. ``That means
we take this surplus, this moment of great prosperity, and we do
the responsible things with it. We don't give trillion-dollar tax
cuts, most of which go to people who are already doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also reiterated many of her other education proposals,
some of which address the nationwide teacher shortage with promises
of scholarships and signing bonuses to people who agree to teach in
hard-to-staff schools. Her campaign also released a television
commercial Thursday that highlights her education proposals and
paints her as a longtime crusader for public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Her Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island,
released a statement saying that Clinton's efforts to improve
education in Arkansas when her husband was that state's governor
were ``a dismal failure whereby taxpayers spent more money and got
worse results.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton ended her speech at Queens College, two audience
members stood and shouted, ``Hillary hates Israel!'' and ``Jew
hater!'' But they were practically drowned out by applause for
Clinton, and they quietly left the room. In a question-and-answer
session that followed, Clinton, who has had difficulty swaying
Jewish voters, outlined her views on the Middle East and said that
``a Palestinian state would make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that she was ``absolutely opposed to any
unilateral declaration of statehood'' by the Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
