<HEADLINE>
AIRLINER IS FORCED TO EVADE STEALTH JET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A United Airlines passenger plane leaving Los
Angeles for Boston on Thursday was forced to take evasive action
when it came too close to an Air Force stealth fighter shortly
after takeoff, airline and federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at 8:43 a.m. Pacific Daylight Time as the
passenger plane, United Airlines Flight 174, was climbing to 15,000
feet from Los Angeles International Airport. The anti-collision
device in the plane's cockpit detected an approaching aircraft and
issued an alert, said Chris Brathwaite, an airline spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The United pilot, who saw the F117 stealth fighter jet,
responded by dropping to 10,800 feet, Brathwaite said. There were
166 passengers and seven crew members aboard the Boeing 757, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force jet passed overhead, and our flight continued to
Boston without incident,'' Brathwaite said.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot B. Brenner, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said the aircraft came within 500 feet vertically
of each other but were about two-thirds of a mile apart
horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collision avoidance system worked as designed and the two
aircraft were never in serious conflict,'' Brenner said. The FAA is
investigating the incident, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Johnny Whitaker, the deputy director of Air Force public
affairs, said the incident involved an F-117 stealth fighter
operating from the flight test center at Edwards Air Force Base,
which is about 100 miles from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at Edwards said the Air Force was still gathering
information about the incident and had no additional information
immediately available. The F-117 is considered the most
sophisticated jet in the U.S. arsenal. It can evade most radar, but
is generally visible to anti-collision devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
