<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE UNION BACKS LAZIO OVER MRS. CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 27,000-member New York City Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association endorsed Rep. Rick Lazio for the Senate on
Thursday. Patrick Lynch, the president of the association, said
that Lazio ``does not jump on the bandwagon of criticism
unreasonably at a time when it's difficult to be a New York City
police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch was referring to a statement made in January by Lazio's
opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who referred to the ``murder of
Amadou Diallo'' shortly before the trial of the four police
officers who shot Diallo. The four officers were subsequently
acquitted. Although Clinton has said she misspoke and has
apologized for the remark, Lynch has not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went so far, although apologizing, to call us murderers,''
Lynch said during a news conference with Lazio on the steps of City
Hall, the site of near-constant political endorsements for local
candidates these days. A New York City police officer, Lynch added,
``takes offense to that.'' Lynch added that Clinton's statement was
``one of many'' she has made against the police.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch praised Lazio for supporting higher pay for New York City
police officers and for opposing federal oversight of the
department. The possibility of such oversight is now being
negotiated between City Hall and the U.S. attorney's office in the
Eastern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although the endorsement by the city's police officers was not
unexpected, it was a boost for Lazio, whose relatively lax campaign
pace has worried state Republicans in recent weeks. ``This
endorsement means a great deal to me,'' Lazio said at the news
conference, adding that ``as a former prosecutor and as the
son-in-law of a former New York City detective, I know very well
how difficult this job is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign pointed out that Lazio voted in 1995 with
other Republicans against a Clinton administration program that
eventually put 100,000 more police officers on the nation's
streets, including more than 11,000 in New York state. Lazio
countered that his vote was based on his desire to see local
control of decisions about policing. ``The question is whether
Washington is going to dictate how that money's going to be spent
or whether we're going to spend it on our own priorities,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 New York Senate race, the PBA supported the
Republican incumbent, Alfonse D'Amato over then-Rep. Charles
Schumer, who won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
