<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOENEWEIS WAS DUE TO CATCH A BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Scott Schoeneweis has stood at his locker in
clubhouses throughout the American League this season, shaking his
head.
</P>
<P>
   In countless games this season, Schoeneweis pitched well enough
to win for the Anaheim Angels, only to have some freak play or bad
bounce end up costing him and the team. He also endured a six-week
stay on the disabled list with a pulled muscle in his rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday against the Tigers, he got the breaks, made the plays
and won the game with eight scoreless innings in a 1-0 victory. It
was only his seventh win of the season despite his ability to pitch
deep into games.
</P>
<P>
   In his 23 starts, he has pitched into the sixth inning 21 times
and into the seventh inning 18 times.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Schoeneweis has maintained a good frame of mind
and not let it affect his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the same game plan every game,'' said Schoeneweis, who
is 7-7 with a 4.89 ERA. ``I make little adjustments to get better,
but basically I'm trying to do the same things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think about those things (bad breaks), or say, 'Why
me? I should have more wins.' I just have to go out and keep doing
my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott has probably been the toughest-luck pitcher on the
staff,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``But he's pitched deep into
games and has a great attitude about it. In a 1-0 game like
(Wednesday) night, he's pitching on a tightrope. There is no margin
for error.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Staff absences: Three starting pitchers who were key to the
team's success earlier in the season _ Jarrod Washburn, Brian
Cooper and Seth Etherton _ are probably through for the season.
Washburn, who is recovering from a stress fracture in his left
shoulder, is the only one who has even a slight chance to return
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The club transferred Etherton (shoulder tendinitis) from the
15-day DL to the 60-day DL, meaning he wouldn't be eligible to
pitch again until the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes a little pressure off Seth in his mind to come back
before the season's over,'' Scioscia said. ``It's the same with
Jarrod. The chances of him pitching again this year are remote.''
</P>
<P>
   Etherton and Washburn are a combined 12-3 this season.
Meanwhile, Cooper (4-8, 5.90 ERA) is healthy but needs time to
`regroup,' according to Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we can get him back to being the
effective pitcher we know he can be,'' Scioscia said. ``Coop's been
trying for the past two months and he's just beating his head
against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Records: All the big swings and big home runs the Angels are
producing are making it a record-breaking season in many
categories. Including strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn struck out once Thursday, his 154th of the season,
which leads the American League. And unless he suddenly turns into
Joe DiMaggio, he'll break the club record of 156, set in 1982 by
Reggie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was the DH for the second night in a row Thursday, giving
Scott Spiezio another start in the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
