A5780 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-07 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORING OUTPUT DATA POINT TO EXCITING PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the best economic news of this year is unfortunately the
sort many Americans probably find the most boring.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wednesday's update of second-quarter productivity data
no doubt made many eyes glaze over, it not only was exciting stuff
but also a reassuring harbinger of continuing prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation that productivity's April-June spurt was even
better than preliminary estimates indicated means Federal Reserve
policy-makers will be increasingly likely to put interest rate
hikes on the back burner for the time being. The higher the rate of
productivity growth, the greater the potential for noninflationary
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity-inflation link is mostly related to labor
costs. Rises in productivity, which measures worker output, mean
employers can increase wages without a pressing need to try to pass
on increased labor costs to consumers in the form of higher prices.
It also means companies are more likely to be able to maintain
profit margins without the need to hike prices.
</P>
<P>
   The question most on the minds of economists during this
productivity surge has been whether it's a cyclical or long-term
run. The pertinent numbers seem to foretell more of the same for a
long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter productivity was up at an annual rate of 5.7
percent instead of the 5.3 percent estimated earlier. This put the
April-June growth pace at triple the first quarter's rate. Year
over year, productivity soared 5.2 percent, which was the best
showing since 1983's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This is phenomenal when considered in the context of an economic
expansion nearing its 10th birthday. Productivity is supposed to
slow as expansions mature. Moreover, viewed over a generation's
worth of productivity performance, it's exceedingly impressive.
Over the last four years, productivity has increased an average of
2.5 percent a year, compared with a 1.6 percent annual growth rate
over the previous 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   What's behind this productivity resurgence? Nothing less than
the technology boom and continuing corporate enthusiasm for capital
investment in high-tech equipment. While overall capital spending
soared at a 20 percent-plus rate in the second quarter, tech
spending was up at a 30 percent-plus pace. Meanwhile, new orders
for tech equipment in June were up more than 40 percent from a year
ago, according to a recent Merrill Lynch report.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis by Merrill Lynch's research team also shows that
productivity gains lag tech spending by about 2 1/2 years and that
tech spending has risen at a 25 percent annual rate over the last
two years. This means recent tech outlays promise to sustain the
current level of productivity gains through 2002, at the very
least.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, labor costs, which might be considered the
flip side of the productivity picture, are showing give. They
declined at a 0.4 percent annual rate, which was the third such
drop over the last year. This doesn't necessarily mean workers are
making less, as some may infer, but only that worker output is
climbing faster than compensation. This is a win-win situation for
employees and employers, because rising worker value enhances both
company performance and job security. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
