A5781 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DUMB-KAN &LR;      09-07 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUMB-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERK'S ALLEGED SCHEME TO STEAL CASH OVERLOOKS SIGNIFICANT DETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A night clerk's plan to steal cash from a
Shawnee, Kan., convenience store was elegantly simple, as far as
these things go:
</P>
<P>
   Police say he blocked the store's two security cameras by
putting tape over their lenses, stashed the money in a trash bin
and then called officers to report an armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   He made his biggest mistake when he selected the tape to mask
the cameras, police said. It was transparent tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things where (the videotape) looks a little
fuzzy, but I don't see any robbery in there,'' said Shawnee Police
Lt. Mitch Brim.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old clerk at the Texaco Starmart, 5501 Hedge Lane
Terrace, first told police early Thursday that a man had called the
store and ordered him to tape over the camera lenses. Then the man
walked in, pointed a pistol at the clerk and demanded money, the
clerk told police.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 a.m., police changed gears and were writing a report
describing how the clerk had staged the crime himself. They
released the clerk and planned to send a report to the district
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in recent years that an overlooked detail
had foiled a theft from a Shawnee business. In January 1999, police
arrested two men after they allegedly locked restaurant employees
in a freezer, then forgot where they had parked their getaway car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
