<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS TO SIMULCAST OCT. 2 GAME AT KAUFFMAN STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM TEICHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Lamar Hunt has always had big dreams, and the
founder of the Chiefs and the American Football League has hatched
another one.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt announced Thursday the Chiefs would try to break the NFL
regular-season record for paid attendance in their Oct. 2 game at
Arrowhead Stadium by selling about 12,300 tickets to watch a
simulcast on the video board at neighboring Kauffman Stadium.
Tickets for the Monday night game, in which the Chiefs play the
Seattle Seahawks, will cost $10.
</P>
<P>
   All Arrowhead Stadium tickets for the game, about 78,600 of
them, are sold. If the Chiefs can sell the full allotment at
Kauffman, the combined on-site total would surpass the NFL's
regular-season paid attendance of 90,833, set in 1958 when the
Chicago Bears played the Rams at Los Angeles Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   League records show an attendance of 102,368 for a
regular-season game between the San Francisco 49ers and Rams in Los
Angeles in 1957. But that total, according to the Chiefs, is a body
count, not paid attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league has told us that any record we set will have to
have an asterisk by it. That's OK. I remember a baseball player
named Roger Maris, and he had a record with an asterisk by it,''
Hunt said of the former single-season home run champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could get the record, that would be a great achievement.
If not, it's not the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Shaw, the Chiefs' manager of public information and media
services, said the fans at Kauffman would be seated in the lower
level between the first- and third-base sides of the infield. That
area holds about 12,300.
</P>
<P>
   A parking lot is under construction at the Truman Sports
Complex, and the Chiefs think it will be ready by Oct. 2 to handle
the extra vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said the Chiefs asked the NFL three years ago for
permission to simulcast at Kauffman. The league refused, saying it
would take away too many local TV viewers and reduce the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the league asked teams for help in promoting Monday
night telecasts. The Chiefs again offered their simulcast idea, and
this time the NFL agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Concessions will be available at Kauffman Stadium. Hunt said the
Royals would receive all concession revenue from the extra fans.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are available in the usual ways _ at Ticketmaster
outlets, by phone at (816) 931-3330, or over the Internet at
www.ticketmaster.com. They also can be purchased at the Arrowhead
box office. Parking will cost $15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always believe new ideas are worth trying,'' Hunt said.``I'm
a little bit fearful that when this is done, it'll be known as
`Hunt's Folly.' &UR; '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
