<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5783 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOLOCAUST-LAWYER-ABRI     09-07 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-LAWYER-ABRIDGED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-FLYING LAWYER IN HOLOCAUST SUIT OFTEN NEGLECTED MANY CLIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: a full-length version of this special report,
HOLOCAUST-LAWYER, is also moving tonight.)  
(SUBS graf beginning ``Fagan called Warshaw'' to note that he spent
much of his time traveling) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than four years ago, a little-known personal-injury lawyer
named Edward D. Fagan stood next to an Auschwitz survivor at a news
conference in New York and announced an audacious lawsuit, accusing
Swiss banks of stealing money 50 years ago from those who died in
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Fagan has a new and glamorous career and is likely soon
to earn millions of dollars in legal fees. He has since filed
lawsuits against banks, insurers and other companies in Austria,
Germany and elsewhere, charging that they too profited from Nazi
ties or exploited victims. Settlements of actions against Swiss
banks and German industry worth over $6.2 billion were recently
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of lawyers got involved in the Holocaust claims. But the
47-year-old Fagan cast himself apart as a media-savvy street
fighter who became the public point man in the cases. This July, he
hopscotched in a few days from Berlin to Vienna to Warsaw on behalf
of tens of thousands of people that he and lawyers associated with
him represent.
</P>
<P>
   They have also opened a second front, charging Japanese
companies in lawsuits with using thousands of Asians and others as
forced labor during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a posse,'' the tall, curly-haired and engaging
lawyer said. ``There are all these bad guys all over the world and
we have to track them down one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   His mission, he said, is to reach back into history and force a
reckoning with those who profited from evil. But an investigation
by The New York Times and the ABC News program ``20/20'' has found
that Fagan is facing his own reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   As he recast himself as a ``human rights'' lawyer, Fagan left
neglected personal-injury clients in his wake, abandoning their
claims or not returning their phone calls for years, according to
court papers and interviews. One former client recently won a
malpractice judgment against Fagan and ethics officials in New
Jersey filed a misconduct complaint against him last month on
behalf of another client.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, so at ease with using the emotional force of the
Holocaust as a weapon, also ignored for months scores of plaintive
calls and letters from aging Nazi-era survivors anxious about
whether their claims had been received, according to a paralegal
who worked last year for him and his partner at the time. Fagan
conceded he may have failed some clients by taking on too much
work. But he insisted that he did his best to represent his
personal-injury clients and that he labored ceaselessly in the
Holocaust cases without financial guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was remarkable to be a lawyer and to be able to use your
profession to do good,'' he said. ``To change history. To stand up
for people's human rights is incredible, and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan's conduct does not appear to have jeopardized the
financial claims of his Holocaust clients, but several survivors he
represented say that his failure to return calls for months, even
years, took an emotional toll.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that Fagan played a leading role in
promoting the Holocaust claims, cases whose moral charge made them
a public cause. He specialized in shaming companies and
governments, orchestrating demonstrations and prayer vigils. Some
Holocaust survivors and advocates view him as their champion.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made it his business, while other lawyers were
painstakingly developing legal claims, to be first at the
courthouse, gaining leverage with a hasty filing. A news conference
with an aged survivor would soon follow, drawing in a flood of
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers in the Holocaust cases say Fagan's ambitions
vastly outstripped his resources to deal with the vast numbers of
clients he took on and added that he was often absent for the
grinding legal work. Burt Neuborne, who had worked with Fagan
before breaking with him, said Fagan's filing in the Swiss banks
case was so inadequate that a judge asked him to rewrite it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an ordinary man who got swept up in issues that were
bigger than he was,'' said Neuborne, a law professor at New York
University. ``He didn't understand and eventually didn't really
know how to behave and just got swept away in the current of his
own ego and his own ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Harlingen, Texas, Fagan grew up in nearby San Antonio
with two brothers and a sister. He once wanted to be a rabbi, and
studied in Israel. After his religious ardor waned, Fagan returned
to the United States and enrolled in Cardozo Law School in New
York, a part of Yeshiva University, graduating in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   As Fagan began his claim against the Swiss banks in late 1996,
the claims of some of his personal-injury clients were apparently
abandoned or forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   One was Hector Ortiz. In 1992, Ortiz, a truck driver, smashed
into the back of a slow-moving crane, shattering bones and
sustaining head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Fagan filed a $35 million lawsuit on his behalf in
federal court in Brooklyn and brought a similar action in state
Supreme Court there. He aggressively pursued the federal claim
until late 1996, court papers and interviews indicate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, however, U.S. District Court Judge Sterling Johnson Jr.
dismissed Ortiz's federal lawsuit, noting, among other things, that
Fagan had ``failed to prosecute'' it for three years and had
ignored court orders. Ortiz's claim in Brooklyn state court has
lain dormant for three years.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a former client, Offer Salmoni, won a $167,000
malpractice judgment against Fagan, which the lawyer did not
contest. Fagan had filed a lawsuit on Salmoni's behalf in 1993 to
contest an eviction. Salmoni charged in a 1998 lawsuit that Fagan
had allowed that claim to be thrown out by repeatedly failing to
make court appearances and had let the statute of limitations
expire without refiling. Fagan, who is licensed to practice in New
York and New Jersey, said he planned to settle with Salmoni.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, New Jersey ethics officials, after a preliminary
inquiry, filed a misconduct complaint before a grievance committee
against Fagan on behalf of another former client, Diane Gibbons.
Gibbons had complained to the ethics board that Fagan's failure to
file required papers in her personal-injury action led to its
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, a legal-ethics expert at New York University
who is not involved in the Holocaust litigation, said that lawyers
face sanctions if they ignore existing claims when the prospects of
bigger awards beckon. ``Your loyalty to your original client is
undiluted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some personal-injury clients, whose names were provided to The
Times by Fagan, said he fought difficult cases on their behalf,
adding that they would use him again. But Fagan acknowledged that
he failed to withdraw _ as lawyers are required to _ from suits he
did not pursue.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1999, with the Holocaust cases on the way to settlement,
Fagan had established his place on the world stage. When Jane
Warshaw, a paralegal, came to work for him that fall, she was
thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were doing God's work,'' said the paralegal,
57.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Fagan's partner at the time, Carey R. D'Avino,
asked her to check the office's telephone answering system. On it,
she found more than 100 unanswered messages from Holocaust
survivors as well as personal-injury clients, including Ortiz. It
sounded like many had been desperately calling for a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Stacks of unopened letters from Holocaust survivors or their
heirs were scattered around and stuffed in a drawer, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by what she viewed as client neglect, Warshaw in
January sent a recording of those calls and correspondence to U.S.
District Court Judge Edward R. Korman of Brooklyn, who is
overseeing the Swiss banks case. She also provided that material to
The Times and ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   The picture that emerges from the documents and recordings is
chaotic. New York disciplinary officials were investigating
complaints by three of Fagan's clients. Calls from Holocaust
claimants were bounced from one answering machine to another.
</P>
<P>
   One caller, Bella Ross, said that her parents, concentration
camp survivors, were ecstatic when Fagan first took their case in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought, you know, they had this savior,'' said Ross in a
recent interview. ``I mean, this is the man. You saw him on TV. You
heard about him on the radio. You see him in print. He is
everywhere. It was like finally they were blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   By last year, however, the family was so concerned about Fagan's
lack of response to dozens of messages and faxes that she filed a
complaint against him with New York disciplinary officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, Mr. Fagan has done nothing to update my parents on
the status of their case and is literally unreachable,'' Ross wrote
in December.
</P>
<P>
   Hal R. Lieberman, a lawyer who represented Fagan in the matter,
told investigators in a March letter responding to Ross' complaint
that Fagan could not possibly deal with each of his tens of
thousands of clients.
</P>
<P>
   Other Holocaust lawyers, though, were devoting more extensive
resources to client communication. While some used paralegals to
handle calls, Neubourne, the New York University professor, said he
set aside four hours a week to deal directly with survivors,
including many of Fagan's clients who called him out of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who lived with these memories for so long,''
Neubourne said. ``The memories were then opened up, somebody told
them something was going to happen. And then they just got cut
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan called Warshaw a ``disgruntled former employee,'' though
he conceded that some of her concerns were legitimate. He said he
spent much of his time in recent years traveling and that only a
few clients had complained.
</P>
<P>
   Korman referred Warshaw's complaint to court officials and
D'Avino said that a court investigator contacted him. Fagan said an
assistant was hired in June to answer calls and he believed the
matter was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Fagan arrived in Berlin as part of a victory lap in two
of the most significant cases. To settle slave-labor claims against
German industry, the government and companies there had approved a
$5 billion fund to compensate Nazi-era survivors. Not long after,
Korman in Brooklyn approved the $1.25 billion settlement of the
Swiss banks case.
</P>
<P>
   During the signing of the settlement, though, Fagan dickered by
cell phone with Stuart Eizenstat, the U.S. deputy treasury
secretary, about lawyers' fees and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Under the German plan, two arbitrators are to decide how to
award legal fees. Fagan argued with Eizenstat, who led negotiations
in the case for the U.S. government, that he understood that the
arbitrators had up to $75 million to award, not the $62.5 million
to which some other plaintiffs' lawyers had agreed.
</P>
<P>
   After the call, Fagan telephoned a partner and said, ``I got the
legal fees up.'' But his excitement was premature; documents show
that the lower figure became the final one.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said that Fagan, after failing to get higher fees,
then asked for a letter testifying about his efforts in the German
case because he feared that lawyers critical of his conduct would
seek to reduce his payout. Eizenstat said he agreed to write such a
letter because he felt Fagan had played a constructive role.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan's fears are well-founded. He is seeking $4 million in the
Swiss banks case, twice as much as any other lawyer. In that case,
as in other class actions, a judge or court-appointed expert will
determine fees. Lawyers like Fagan argue in such proceedings that
they deserve the fees they seek because they took great financial
risks and played a central role in a case's resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But Neuborne and others said in interviews they would argue
before Korman for a far lower sum for Fagan in the Swiss banks
case, contending that his contribution was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``His only gift was for publicity,'' said Martin Mendelsohn, a
lawyer in Washington who worked on the Holocaust claims. ``But this
was a lawsuit. It was not theater.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
