r w BC-RIVER-KAN &LR;      09-07 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO PREVENT RAISING LEVEL OF MISSOURI RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a vote cast under threat of a presidential veto,
the U.S. Senate on Thursday decided that the level of the Missouri
River should not be raised in the spring to improve wildlife
habitats.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 52-45 to prevent the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers from releasing extra water from the Gavins Point Dam near
Yankton, S.D., at least once every three springs.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the river would enhance the breeding of two rare species
of birds, the piping plover and interior least tern, as well as one
rare fish, the bottom-dwelling pallid sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Kit Bond and John Ashcroft, Missouri Republicans, argued
against the river plan, contained in a $22.5 billion bill financing
energy and water projects. They said it could cause flooding of
downstream farms and towns without guaranteeing the protection of
the birds and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Further, they said, the spring releases would cut the amount of
water available to release in the summer, inhibiting barge traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, Missouri won big today,'' said Bond, who
wrote the provision against the river plan. ``We were able to
protect Missourians from a federally backed flooding scheme that
would have endangered countless Missourians along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he would veto the $22.5 billion
appropriations bill unless it protects the birds and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat running to unseat
Ashcroft, sided with the two Republicans and wrote to Clinton last
month.
</P>
<P>
   A veto could be unpopular with Missouri farmers and the state
overall, and Missouri is considered a swing state in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, a South Dakota Democrat who wanted to raise
the river level, said he was heartened the Bond provision didn't
win enough support to overturn a veto, which takes a two-thirds
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote today gives us more than enough Senate support to
make long-overdue changes that will lead to better management and
improved recreational opportunities along the river,'' said
Daschle, the Senate minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   He said outdated river management policies favor the $7 million
barge industry downstream but threaten a $90 million recreation
industry upstream, as well as the wildlife species.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle agrees with the Missourians that releasing extra water
in the spring would mean releasing less in the summer. But, he
argues, that would leave more water during the summer in four South
Dakota reservoirs upstream from Gavins Point for boating, fishing
and other recreation.
</P>
<P>
   While Daschle stressed the recreational benefits, the official
reason for pushing the change was a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
discovery that the Endangered Species Act would be violated if the
birds and fish weren't protected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited that act and the need for a more balanced use of
the river for commerce and recreation in threatening the veto.
</P>
<P>
   After the Senate vote a Clinton spokesman, Jason Schechter,
said: ``We have no intention of letting this language become law.
If it takes a veto, that's what we will do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has backed a similar Bond provision for four years.
This year, however, the wildlife service determined that higher
levels would cleanse sandbars of vegetation that can serve as
hiding places for predators of the plover and tern. More water
would help sturgeon breed.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Smith, director of the Missouri River field office of
American Rivers, a conservation group, agreed: ``Without changes in
the flow of the Missouri River, these three species will disappear.
That is crystal clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Natural Resources disagrees that
raising the river would help, saying it may even inundate nesting
sites while also increasing the risk of floods.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concern over endangered species, much of the Senate
debate concerned flooding and barge traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said a veto would send a clear message to Missouri:
``The Clinton-Gore administration is willing to flood downstream
communities as part of an unscientific, risky scheme that will hurt
not help the endangered species it was designed to protect. If
that's the message, I wouldn't want to be the messenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said voters in key election states would take note of a
veto and the risk of higher water levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does that, it's a disaster for all those states and I'm
sure going to talk about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schechter, the White House spokesman, said presidential politics
will not play a part. ``We will address this on its merits,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   An Ashcroft aide chided Carnahan for not swaying Democrats to
vote against Daschle. The only Democrat to do so was Sen. Blanche
Lambert Lincoln of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan spokesman Tony Wyche said it was illogical to think the
governor would hold sway with senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should take note of the willingness of the Ashcroft
campaign to partisanize and politicize everything for their own
gain, even when they agree with us on a subject,'' Wyche said.
``It's absolutely ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle disagreed with Bond about the risk of flooding, saying
no extra water would be released if water levels are already high.
``Let no one be misled,'' he said. ``This has nothing do to with
flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the barge industry accounts for only three
tenths of 1 percent of the transportation of farm products.
</P>
<P>
   Bond argued that hampering barge traffic would shift business to
higher-priced rail and highway shippers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the flood risk, Bond said water takes 11 days to get from
Gavins Point to St. Louis and that no one could predict how much
rain might fall over that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that people, property and fish can all be protected
at the same time without increased risk of flooding,'' he said. &QL; 
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
