<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-07 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOLOCAUST-LAWYER-ART-     09-07 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-LAWYER-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: been denied.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Rubinton, the fund's president, though, said in an
interview that its records showed that such a claim had not been
pursued and that the statute of limitations on making such a claim
had long expired.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a former client, Offer Salmoni, won a $167,000
malpractice judgment against Fagan, which the lawyer did not
contest. Fagan had filed a lawsuit on Salmoni's behalf in 1993 to
contest an eviction. Salmoni charged in a 1998 lawsuit that Fagan
had allowed that claim to be thrown out by repeatedly failing to
make court appearances and had let the statute of limitations
expire without refiling. Fagan, who is licensed to practice in New
York and New Jersey, said he planned to settle with Salmoni.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, New Jersey ethics officials, after a preliminary
inquiry, filed a misconduct complaint before a grievance committee
against Fagan on behalf of another former client, Diane Gibbons.
Gibbons had complained to the ethics board that Fagan's failure to
file required papers in her personal-injury action led to its
dismissal. Fagan said he could not comment on the matter because it
was pending.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, a legal-ethics expert at New York University
who is not involved in the Holocaust litigation, said that lawyers
face sanctions if they ignore existing claims when the prospects of
bigger awards beckon. ``Your loyalty to your original client is
undiluted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some personal-injury clients, whose names were provided to The
Times by Fagan, said that the lawyer fought difficult cases on
their behalf, adding that they would not hesitate to use him again.
But Fagan acknowledged that he failed to withdraw _ as lawyers are
required to _ from suits that he did not pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in over my head a lot of the time,'' he said. ``But now
I'm digging out, for me and for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unanswered Calls, New Inquiries
</P>
<P>
   By late 1999, with the Holocaust cases on the way to settlement,
Fagan had established his place on the world stage. When Jane
Warshaw, a paralegal, was sent by a temporary-help agency to work
that fall for him and his then-partner at the World Trade Center,
she was deeply thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were doing God's work,'' said the paralegal,
who at 57 is spunky with reddish hair.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Fagan's partner at the time, Carey R. D'Avino,
asked her to check the office's telephone answering system. On it,
she found more than 100 unanswered messages from Holocaust
survivors as well as personal-injury clients, including Ortiz. It
sounded like many had been desperately calling for a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Stacks of unopened letters from Holocaust survivors or their
heirs were scattered around and stuffed in a drawer, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must have gotten their hopes up and then, there again,
they were told that they just didn't matter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw said she suggested to D'Avino that she prepare a
newsletter to keep clients updated, an accepted practice in
class-action suits. The lawyer said he told her that their clients
were already getting periodic newsletters. He described her as
``well-meaning'' but ``out of the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, troubled by what she viewed as a pattern of client
neglect, the paralegal sent a tape recording of those calls and
office correspondence to U.S. District Court Judge Edward R. Korman
of Brooklyn, who is overseeing the Swiss banks case. She also
provided that material to The Times and ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   The picture that emerges from the documents and recordings is
chaotic. New York disciplinary officials were investigating
complaints by three of Fagan's clients. Calls from Holocaust
claimants were bounced from one answering machine to another.
</P>
<P>
   One caller, Bella Ross, said that her parents, concentration
camp survivors, were ecstatic when Fagan first took their case in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought, you know, they had this savior,'' said Ross in a
recent interview. ``I mean, this is the man. You saw him on TV. You
heard about him on the radio. You see him in print. He is
everywhere. It was like finally they were blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   By last year, however, the family was so concerned about Fagan's
lack of response to dozens of messages and faxes that she filed a
complaint against him with New York disciplinary officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, Mr. Fagan has done nothing to update my parents on
the status of their case and is literally unreachable,'' Ross wrote
in December.
</P>
<P>
   Hal R. Lieberman, a lawyer who represented Fagan in the matter,
told investigators in a March letter responding to Ross' complaint
that Fagan could not possibly deal with each of his tens of
thousands of clients. Both D'Avino and Fagan said in interviews
that they had fulfilled their ethical obligations to their clients;
to date, there have been no findings against them.
</P>
<P>
   Other Holocaust lawyers, though, were devoting more extensive
resources to client communication. While some used paralegals to
handle calls, Neubourne, the New York University professor, said he
set aside four hours a week to deal directly with survivors,
including many of Fagan's clients who called him out of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who lived with these memories for so long,''
Neubourne said. ``The memories were then opened up, somebody told
them something was going to happen. And then they just got cut
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Some clients said Fagan returned phone calls promptly and others
involved in Holocaust-related issues said they also had had far
happier experiences with Fagan. They described him as a passionate
advocate who took up a fight that traditional Jewish groups had
allowed to languish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed was the only true source of light,'' said Dr. Thomas Weiss,
an ophthamologist in Miami Beach who has been active in Nazi-era
claims against insurers. ``He saw himself as picked by Providence
to lead this charge.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-07-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
