<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-1ST     09-07 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DAYTON, Ohio: in chief.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush also hinted at stops across the day that he would name
Powell to his administration. ``The general talked about being
retired from public service,'' he said here, then glanced at Powell
and added puckishly, ``If all goes well. ...'' The crowd erupted in
cheers and applause.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pledged that he would push for modernization of the
military to meet the new threats in the world.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that the nation had the chance to ``redefine how war
is fought and won in the future, and therefore we have the
opportunity to redefine how the peace is kept.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that if elected he would assemble a task force of
military leaders to come up with a ``strategic plan'' for what the
military of the future should look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's not going to look like the great American moment
of Desert Storm and Desert Shield,'' Bush said. ``A military of the
future is not going to be that heavy, and it's not going to be that
hard to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's events were designed to put the gulf war leaders at
center stage in order to endorse the son of the man they served
under. Schwarzkopf called himself proud to ``stand up and endorse''
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Powell lambasted the Clinton administration for hurting military
readiness, a theme that Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney,
have been hitting hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and frankly deeply disappointed the other day
when the president's spokesman attacked Dick Cheney because he
dared to tell the truth about the state of readiness, and said he
was attacking the military,'' Powell said. ``Dick Cheney has never
attacked the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney pressed the same theme in appearances at military
contractors in New England. He recalled a telephone call he had
made to former President Ronald Reagan after the gulf war, saying
he had thanked Reagan the money his administration had spent on the
military. ``I ask myself,'' he said, ``is anybody going to call
Bill Clinton or Al Gore in the future to thank them for what they
did to the U.S. military? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, challenged several
of the assertions Bush made in his speeches Thursday. Bacon said
that the administration, along with Congress, had increased defense
spending by $150 billion over the next several years. That included
an increase in spending on weapons and other equipment _ an area
where Bush was sharply critical _ from $43 billion in 1998 to $60
billion today, as well as three straight years of pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also noted that the number of troops qualifying for food
stamps _ which Bush has often cited as evidence that the Clinton
administration had neglected men and women in uniform _ had
declined significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that 19,400 service members, 0.9 percent of the
total, collected food stamps in 1991, when Bush's father was
president and Cheney Cheney was secretary of defense. Today, Bacon
said, 5,100 are on food stamps, or 0.4 percent of a smaller force.
</P>
</TEXT>
