<SLUG> BC-CT-HMO-SUIT-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ind., Calif., Texas)  
 CONNECTICUT SUES 4 BIG HMOs OVER DENIAL OF CLAIMS  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Connecticut's attorney general filed a federal
lawsuit Thursday against four of the state's largest HMOs, charging
them with improperly denying medical claims, obstructing access to
prescription drugs, delaying payments to doctors and misinforming
patients about their rights to appeal decisions about their health
care.
</P>
<P>
   The civil lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Hartford,
seeks to represent thousands of clients who, according to Attorney
General Richard Blumenthal, have suffered physically and
financially from the organizations' practice of putting profits
ahead of patient care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have engaged in a pattern of conduct that has denied
essential medical treatment to patients,'' Blumenthal said at a
news conference in his office Thursday morning. ``They have forced
people to accept less-effective care simply so the company can
increase its profits.''
</P>
<P>
   All four companies named in the suit issued statements Thursday
stressing their commitment to high-quality patient care. Two
offered to meet with Blumenthal to discuss the charges. Oxford
Health Plans, based in Norwalk, went further, contesting many of
the lawsuit's allegations and chiding the attorney general for not
having met with company officials to discuss the allegations
against them.
</P>
<P>
   The three other HMOs and their Connecticut subsidiaries named in
the suit are Cigna Health Plans, based in Bloomfield, and its
subsidiary, CIGNA HealthCare of Connecticut; Foundation Health
Systems of Los Angeles, and its subsidiary, Physicians Health
Services of Connecticut; and Anthem Health Plans, in Indianapolis,
and its subsidiary, Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the four national HMOs provide medical services to
more than 800,000 Connecticut residents, as well as hundreds of
thousands of others in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court judge must determine whether the lawsuit
meets the legal requirements for the class-action status Blumenthal
is seeking. If it does, Connecticut would become the first state to
file such a suit against HMOs and the first to do so on behalf of
consumers, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Texas filed a suit against Aetna U.S. Healthcare
accusing it of providing improper financial incentives to doctors
to limit patient care. The two sides settled the suit earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed Thursday seeks no money award; instead,
Blumenthal said he intended to provoke the four HMOs into
reconsidering what he called ``misguided management'' that put
patients in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the suit contends that the HMOs illegally deny
hospitalization costs beyond a set number of days, regardless of a
patient's medical needs. It also charges the companies with so
strictly limiting the list of prescription drugs they will
subsidize that they effectively deny patients necessary medicines,
without denial notices or notifying clients of their rights to
appeal. The HMOs also intentionally ignore inquiries from their
clients, the lawsuit claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for fundamental, far-reaching changes to the way
they do business,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Internal documents outlining the policies of HMOs, he added,
will provide powerful evidence that they have consistently violated
federal guidelines that require them to administer health plans
solely in the interest of their patients.
</P>
<P>
   The suit does not charge Physicians Health Services with denying
prescription drugs to clients, a charge Blumenthal brought against
the company in a previous lawsuit. Dismissed by a federal court
judge, that suit is now being considered by a federal appeals
court.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message, a spokeswoman for Oxford Health Plans said
that Thursday's broad allegations were misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxford pays clean claims on average within seven days
(significantly faster than industry norms), Oxford answers member
inquiries in a timely manner, Oxford has all but eliminated
retrospective denials through a concurrent review program we
introduced over a year ago and Oxford offers drug benefits approved
by the Connecticut Department of Insurance which are clearly
described to members in their policy certificates,'' said the
spokeswoman, Maria Gordon Shydlo.
</P>
<P>
   David Olson, a spokesman for Foundation Health Systems, called
today's suit ``old news'' because it repeated allegations in
lawsuits filed by private plaintiffs against his HMO and many
others. ``The only thing that's new is that the attorney general
has decided to join the fray,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes as the shortcomings of managed care,
specifically the affordability of prescription drugs, have become a
central issue in the presidential campaigns of Vice President Al
Gore and Gov. George W. Bush. Three weeks ago, Gore attacked HMOs
as callous profiteers during his speech to the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, a prominent Democrat, said the timing of his suit
had nothing to do with presidential politics. ``The abuses of HMOs
have been a fact of life for years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also predicted that other states would join Connecticut's
lawsuit against the four companies, perhaps in the next several
weeks. Later this month, Blumenthal plans to present the details of
the suit to a gathering of attorneys general from several other
Northeastern states, including New York and New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
