<HEADLINE>
TAKING A NEW COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former UCLA safety Lovell Houston, after
undergoing surgery last week to strengthen his right-shoulder
socket, has enrolled at Colorado and began taking classes this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, a former Parade All-American at Denver Jefferson High,
battled a series of injury problems in his two years at UCLA that
rarely allowed him to fulfill his promise as one of the
cornerstones of the Bruins nationally top-ranked recruiting class
of 1998. Among the other highly touted members of that class were
DeShaun Foster, Robert Thomas, Mike Saffer and Ken Kocher _ all of
whom have started for at least two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Houston redshirted his first season after a quadriceps injury in
training camp slowed his progress. The shoulder surgery was the
third he's had since coming to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a chance to play and be Lovell Houston,'' said
Houston, who started three games last year at strong safety and
returned a kickoff for 95 yards against Stanford the first time he
touched the ball as a Bruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a good year last year, but I didn't meet my
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston said his decision to return closer to home had nothing
to do with UCLA and everything to do with his surgery. He had
arthroscopic surgery on the shoulder in the offseason, but it never
healed sufficiently for him to do the necessary work in the weight
room this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed UCLA very much and I appreciated all of my teammates
and coaches,'' said Houston, whom the UCLA coaches were hoping to
start at free safety. ``After the last surgery, I lost 20 pounds.
It was hard to go eat as much as I wanted to. This is where my
support system is (in Denver).
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, DeShaun, Julius (Williams) and Bryan Fletcher lived
together and it would be difficult for them to cook for me and
wrong for me to expect that. It's difficult when I have to put on
clothes and socks, and I write right-handed so it's hard to take
notes. There are a lot of things I needed to have a lot of help
with and between my parents, both my brothers and little sister,
I've got a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston says he might require surgery on his left shoulder _ it
was examined while he was under anesthesia _ but that he hopes to
be healthy for spring practice. Then he'll join his brother,
Marcus, a freshman running back who will start for Colorado against
USC on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, Houston will have a reunion with some of his
former teammates on Sept. 21, 2002, when Colorado plays UCLA at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but good things to say about my coaches and
teammates at UCLA,'' Houston said. ``Sometimes fate just bends a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Raisin' hell: Oregon has gone to Fresno before and Cal is
visiting this season. Next year is Texas Tech. And then Oregon
State. In five years, Wisconsin will be there.
</P>
<P>
   But schools like Ohio State, whom Fresno State played last week,
Colorado, Auburn and UCLA won't go there. The Bruins have played
Fresno State three times in the past six years _ all in the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to play UCLA in Fresno, but they won't play it,''
said Fresno State coach Pat Hill, who played center for UCLA coach
Bob Toledo when he was the head coach at UC Riverside. ``I can't
get Arizona or Arizona State to play (anywhere). I'm glad Bob
Toledo and UCLA will give us the opportunity to play them, but I
just wish they'd play us here. They go to San Diego State (in
2002), but they won't drive up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Toledo: ``We like our big crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: Receiver Brian Poli-Dixon (hamstring) and
defensive tackle Ken Kocher (ankle sprain) will not play, Toledo
said. Jon Dubravac, who has a strained left hip, will replace
Poli-Dixon in the lineup. Pass rushing end Steve Sua (concussion)
is doubtful.
</P>
</TEXT>
