<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GIULIANI, MUCH CLINTON, AT BELATED PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Organizers of this year's Labor Day parade, to be
held Saturday, are planning to turn the march into a major platform
for Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To highlight the first lady, whom they have endorsed, the
parade's organizers have taken the unusual step of not inviting
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who was briefly Clinton's opponent. Nor
have they invited the Republican who is running, Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The parade up Fifth Avenue, which will begin at 11 a.m. at 44th
Street and end at 72nd Street, is expected to give Clinton a giant
audience _ labor leaders predict at least 250,000 marchers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the parade has been scheduled for the Saturday
after Labor Day, because many union members did not want their
three-day holiday weekends cut short for the march. Union leaders
also wanted to hold it on a day when more people would be in
Manhattan to see it.
</P>
<P>
   The march comes during a difficult year for the city's unions.
Workers at the Museum of Modern Art remain on strike after four
months, more than 200 workers at Domino Sugar in Brooklyn have been
on strike for more than a year and a campaign to unionize
restaurant workers at the Metropolitan Opera remains stalled after
a year. In addition, the city's 300,000 municipal workers do not
appear close to getting a contract with the city _ another major
subject of the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Brian M. McLaughlin, president of the New York City Central
Labor Council, the parade's sponsor and an affiliate of the
AFL-CIO, said Clinton would give separate speeches to some unions
that plan to turn out thousands of members: the teachers,
electrical workers, building trades' unions and District Council
37. ``We want to showcase her meeting with working people,''
McLaughlin said. He said the labor council also wanted the parade
to showcase two endorsed incumbents in Congress who face tough
challenges in Tuesday's Democratic primary: Major Owens and
Edolphus Towns.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lazio was not invited, labor leaders said that two
unions that have endorsed him, the police and the corrections
officers, might carry pro-Lazio signs. Michael Marr, a spokesman
for Lazio, said the Republican would be campaigning in Queens and
Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mayor, if he shows up uninvited, McLaughlin said, he
will be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for the mayor said he would not attend.
Giuliani was invited to march each year for the last five years and
accepted every year except for 1999, when he had a scheduling
conflict, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
