<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MARIJUANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES CALIFORNIA DOCTORS AND PATIENTS MAY DISCUSS MARIJUANA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Ariz., Hawaii, Maine, Nev., Ore., Wash.)   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A federal judge in San Francisco ruled Thursday
that federal officials may not interfere with the freedom of
California doctors and patients to discuss the potential medical
benefits of marijuana, or of doctors to recommend its therapeutic
use, under the terms of a state ballot initiative approved by
voters in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge William Alsup came in a
class-action lawsuit filed against top Clinton administration
officials, including Attorney General Janet Reno, in 1997, seeking
to block them from prosecuting or removing the prescription
licenses of any doctors who endorsed marijuana's potential benefits
in treating patients with illnesses like AIDS and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relevant federal statute does not authorize the government
to revoke a physician's license to dispense controlled substances
merely because a physician ``recommends'' marijuana as a therapy to
a patient,'' Alsup wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any contrary holding would raise severe First Amendment
doubts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar measure have been passed in Alaska, Arizona, Hawaii,
Maine, Nevada, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The California ballot measure, like the one in Arizona, did not
remove the longstanding federal prohibition against doctors
prescribing drugs like marijuana and heroin, in which the
government recognizes no medical value. It simply gave patients
found with small amounts of marijuana a defense if they could show
that a doctor had recommended it orally or in writing. But almost
since the law's passage, doctors have been fearful of the threat of
federal sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This finally signals that doctors and patients can once again
openly discuss marijuana as medicine without fear of draconian
federal punishment,'' said Graham Boyd, a lawyer with the American
Civil Liberties Union who filed the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Weiner, a spokesman for Barry McCaffrey, the White House
drug czar who was also a named defendant in the case, said his
office had just learned of the decision and that together with the
Justice Department, the main agency handling the case, ``We will
study and analyze the decision closely, and that's all I can tell
you right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The government can appeal the decision to the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
