<SLUG> BC-GAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS GASOLINE PRICES RISE, WORRIES MOUNT ABOUT HIGHER HEATING FUEL
COST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Gasoline prices have surged again this week
amid increasingly gloomy predictions that the cost of fuels used to
heat homes and businesses will remain high.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for unleaded gasoline in the Kansas City area have gone
up as much as 15 cents per gallon, to $1.55, at most service
stations _ a reaction in part to oil prices that are posting
10-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the costs of heating oil, propane and natural
gas are climbing. Analysts worry that the price of these fuels
could rise even further unless there is a warm winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the risk of (price) spikes has gotten bigger,'' said
David Costello, an analyst for the federal Energy Information
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The price of natural gas, for example, has remained unusually
high throughout the summer. Already those prices have moved higher.
On Aug. 1, the wholesale cost of 1,000 cubic feet was about $3.80,
nearly double the price at the same time last year. On Thursday,
the average wholesale price for 1,000 cubic feet of gas in the
Midwest was $4.90.
</P>
<P>
   At those prices, an average household would see its heating
bills increase $300. The average household uses 120,000 cubic feet
of gas in a year, most of that in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Traders in the futures and wholesale markets have been worried
about supplies of natural gas. Prices have been volatile, partly on
reports of increased use of natural gas by electric utilities. Now
concerns about a cold winter are fueling some of the surge.
</P>
<P>
   As for gasoline, Costello said there had been some tight
supplies in some parts of the country, including the Midwest. But
much of the upward price push has come from rising crude oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   A barrel of West Texas crude oil _ a frequently used reference
price _ cost $28 on Aug. 1. Thursday's price was $35 a barrel. A
barrel makes 42 gallons of gasoline and other products.
</P>
<P>
   But Costello said he held out hope of some relief for motorists.
Now that summer driving is over, demand should slacken, although
more oil will be needed to rebuild stockpiles of heating oil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
